<HEADLINE>
BAVASI SAYS SON IS DOING GOOD JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; DENVER _ Anaheim Angels general manager Bill Bavasi finds
himself in the final year of his contract with the Angels, and it
so happens it's been his most difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi has seen his team decimated by an inordinate number of
injuries -- even by the Angels' standards. And there was the
dissension in the clubhouse over manager Terry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   The team has been in last place since May 4, and Bavasi has been
tempted to make trades. But at what cost? Bavasi is careful not to
trash all he and the organization have built for a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   So how does Bavasi's performance rate? Bavasi's bosses at Disney
won't tell and Bavasi himself won't talk about his contract
situation, but there is a pretty good judge down south near San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi's father, Buzzie, the former general manager of the
Brooklyn and Los Angeles Dodgers, the Angels and president of the
Padres, says Bill is doing just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never went through anything like he's gone through, the
elder Bavasi said. ``I thought he handled the Collins situation
well. Somebody has to be boss. Who would he rather have unhappy --
the players or (Disney chairman and CEO) Michael Eisner? I know
what my answer would be.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi related a story from his days in Brooklyn when Jackie
Robinson had a problem with manager Walter Alston in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie, as he would do, popped off about Walter not having any
(major league) background, Bavasi said. ``So he called Jackie into
his office and closed and locked the door. He said `Jackie, I heard
what you we're saying. And unless you apologize, only one of us is
leaving this room.' Jackie apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Walter was 230 pounds, and Terry is 160 pounds. But
I think Billy had it right. I told him I wasn't interested in happy
players, I'm interested in good players.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bavasi's immediate goals is to help the offense, but the
Angels hitters have shown signs lately they are breaking out of
their season-long slump. And with outfielders Tim Salmon and Jim
Edmonds beginning to make significant progress in their recoveries
from injuries, a deal for offense might not happen.
</P>
<P>
   In the six games since the Angels were swept by the Rangers, the
Angels are hitting .316 (67 for 212) and are averaging 6.7 per runs
per game. It's a noticeable improvement from their season average
of .259 and 4.3 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happening for us now, said Mo Vaughn, who has a
team-leading 17 homers and 55 RBIs. ``We're taking a solid approach
up there and putting together good at-bats. The team is showing we
can hit the ball where it's pitched, and that's what he have to do.
I've said it a thousand times.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Greene, optioned to triple-A Edmonton on Tuesday, did not
join the club in Oklahoma City on Thursday as planned. He missed
his flight.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, though, will join the Trappers in an effort to correct
his flawed stroke. He's hitting .197 with runners in scoring
position and has looked ugly at the plate recently, swinging at
pitches out of the strikezone with regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be there very long, Greene promised.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels resume interleague play with a three-game series
against the Colorado Rockies in Denver beginning tonight. Pitching
matchups for the series: Tonight (6:05) -- Chuck Finley (4-9, 5.52
ERA) vs. Darryl Kile (5-6, 5.57); Saturday (5:05) -- Omar Olivares
(7-6, 3.26) vs. Pedro Astacio (8-7, 5.30); Sunday (12:05) -- Mike
Fyhrie (0-0, 2.57) vs. Bobby Jones (4-7, 5.85).
</P>
</TEXT>
