<HEADLINE>
&HT;    AMTRAK TRAIN DERAILS AFTER HITTING TRUCK WEST OF HOUSTON; 18
HURT
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 WRECK-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
1st-Lede-writethru (eliminates material at end of story) &HT;     &HT;    By PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    and T.J. MILLING
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGLE LAKE, Texas _ An Amtrak train carrying 234 passengers hit
a tanker truck at a rural crossing Thursday and derailed, injuring
18 people, including the engineer and his assistant.
</P>
<P>
   The truck, which was hauling a saltwater disposal tank, crossed
the tracks in front of the eastbound Sunset Limited just before
noon near Eagle Lake, about 65 miles west of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Two locomotives and seven of the train's 10 cars jumped the
tracks, with the engine landing on its side perpendicular to the
tracks. The train, en route from Los Angeles to Orlando, Fla., had
stopped in San Antonio and was heading toward its next stop in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There were no warning lights or crossing gates at the crossing,
which was on a short dirt road leading from a rice field onto U.S.
90A.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, Jason David Bubela, 21, of El Campo, was not
seriously injured, police said. Police said they are considering
possible charges against the driver. The truck, which police say
may have had bad brakes, is owned by Key Energy Services of
Bryan-College Station, which is conducting its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, these crossing accidents happen all too
often,'' Amtrak spokesman Derrick James said. ``People just don't
seem to want to wait.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Mark Davis, a spokesman for Union Pacific, owners of the track,
said an accident occurred at the same crossing three weeks ago when
an empty freight train clipped the back of a grain truck. The
wreck, however, was termed minor. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Vernon Stevenson, 32, of Eagle Lake, was using a portable
restroom near the tracks when the accident happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was coming out, and I heard all this commotion,'' said
Stevenson, who works at Rice Industries, behind the Colorado County
Rice Mill. ``The train just went up and went to flipping like. It
was like an explosion. It scared me so bad. I took off running.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking that engine was coming into my car,'' said
Tommy Stewart, the train's head conductor, who was two cars behind
the engine. ``Nobody in my car was bleeding, and everybody could
walk, so I jumped out and saw my engineer on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the assistant engineer was trapped ``and he had a big
gash in his head. He was talking to me, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew members and rescuers used a sledgehammer to break a window
and pulled out the assistant engineer, Ed Guidon. He and engineer
J.D. Wood were in stable condition Thursday evening at Rice Medical
Center in Eagle Lake. &UR;  &LR; Their hometowns were not immediately known &UR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Sixteen other passengers and crew members were treated for
bruises, cuts and heat exhaustion from standing in the 90-degree
heat awaiting transportation into Eagle Lake, about five miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who spent the afternoon at the wreck site after a short
trip to the hospital to get his elbow X-rayed, said he planned to
check on his passengers at a makeshift shelter at the local
community center before heading home to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' he said, ``I might go buy a bottle of whiskey. We were
very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the passengers were Cindy and Jack McCain, the wife and
13-year-old son of presidential candidate and Arizona Sen. John
McCain, who were on their way to Florida on vacation. Authorities
said neither was hurt. They took a private plane to Florida a few
hours after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Other passengers were taken in school buses to the Eagle Lake
Community Center, where volunteers set up a first-aid station and
served barbecue and pizza donated by local restaurants. The
passengers later were bused to Houston, where Amtrak officials
planned to reunite them with their luggage and arrange other
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
