<HEADLINE>
NEW NBA RULES TO GET TESTED AT PYRAMID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LONG BEACH, Calif. _ If you embrace only one rule change in pro
basketball this summer, it should be the guarantee that no lockout
will arise to estrange the NBA from its offseason home in Long
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The other rules aren't bad, though.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring Long Beach State's Pyramid as a lockout-free zone
allows great optimism to accompany today's tipoff of the Fila
Summer Pro League. Now in its fifth run at LBSU, this summer of
slam offers 115 games over the next 24 days, framed by sightings of
NBA players in various stages of enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   Without NBA-sanctioned participation last year, the league was
obliged to grind through its 29th season.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with 12 NBA teams enrolled in summer school, any ol'
lottery pick or sneaker-commercial hotshot might roll in to do a
little crowd-pleasing maintenance on his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had a tough summer,'' said Washington Wizard and
ex-UCLA star Tracy Murray, who stopped by the Pyramid to pay his
respects at Thursday's press conference. ``A lot of guys were
afraid of getting hurt during the lockout. But this league is very
important; it helps gives you an idea of what to expect when it's
time to go to training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA rules changes include:
</P>
<P>
   __ A five-second limit for a dribbler who's being defended below
the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   __ Small-but-crucial alteration of the complex and unpopular
illegal- defense guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   __ A less-than-generous reset of the 24-second clock if a foul
occurs with less than 14 ticks remaining. In that instance, the
clock will be turned back to 14, rather than the original,
action-strangling 24 of the old days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
