<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL DELIVERY: BABY IS BORN OUTSIDE CONVENIENCE STORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- As a QuikTrip cashier, Rusty Suhr is used to
helping people -- but not like this.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the 22-year-old Suhr helped a woman deliver her
baby in the front seat of a truck in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was definitely beyond the call of duty,'' said the woman,
Wendy Levy of Odessa. ``Not everyone would step right in like that
and help.''
</P>
<P>
   Suhr visited Levy, 31, and her daughter, Sheridan Micheala Levy,
Thursday at Truman Medical Center. Levy and Sheridan, who weighs 7
pounds, 2 ounces, were doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   The family reminisced about Wednesday's early arrival for
Sheridan, who wasn't due until July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Levy said she had driven to Kansas City on Wednesday for a
doctor appointment and met her boyfriend, Russell Rowlett, at his
job at 12th Street and Hardesty Avenue for lunch. They sat in the
parking lot and Levy said she began having abdominal pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just figured they were false labor pains,'' said Levy, who
also has a 5-year-old daughter. ``But then they started getting
worse and I said to Russell, `You're going to have to take me to
the hospital now!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rowlett, 27, drove toward Truman Medical Center East, where
Levy's doctor is, but her water broke. He turned in the QuikTrip
parking lot at Truman Road and Ewing Avenue, parked his car and ran
inside, leaving his truck door open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone call 911!'' he yelled at Suhr, the first clerk he saw.
</P>
<P>
   Suhr tossed the cordless telephone to his manager, who called
911, and Suhr ran outside to the 1977 Chevrolet truck. Levy lay
across the seat and could feel the baby's head coming out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a nervous wreck,'' Rowlett said. ``Rusty said he had
just had a baby six months ago so I said, `OK, here you go. You
have more recent experience.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Suhr said he didn't have time to think about what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just telling her everything was going to be OK,'' Suhr
said.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the baby was out.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hoek, an ambulance dispatcher, talked to Suhr on the
telephone and advised him to tie the umbilical cord off with a
shoestring. Suhr said he also cleared out the baby's mouth with his
little finger and wrapped her in a QuikTrip towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the situation, everything went perfectly,'' Suhr said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoek said it was the fourth time in his 8-year dispatch career
at Metropolitan Ambulance Services Trust that he had helped in a
baby delivery over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely unusual,'' he said. ``Most of the time we get
the calls from home, but the parking lot at a QuikTrip? That is
strange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
