A3944 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUPSUN-LADN-(SLAN     07-09 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUPSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN ALWAYS SHINES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ In China, a nation of 1.2 billion, it's
estimated that only 10,000 women play soccer.
</P>
<P>
   And though the immense soccer potential of the country has yet
to be fully unleashed, China already has a huge head start on most
of the rest of the world when it comes to success.
</P>
<P>
   China will play the United States on Saturday at the Rose Bowl
in the 1999 Women's World Cup final, and leading the way will be a
player who doesn't seem to fit the typical image many have of life
in that country. Sun Wen is a pioneer in many ways, but the
26-year-old forward was one of soccer's elite players in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   This year's tournament has done nothing to dispel that notion.
Sun is tied with Brazil's Sissi for the lead in goals scored with
seven, including two in the 5-0 semifinal victory over Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Sun certainly has her admirers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen her over the last decade and she's playing the best
soccer of her life,'' said U.S. assistant coach Lauren Gregg. ``We
have tremendous respect for her.''
</P>
<P>
   And respect doesn't come from only Sun's opponents but also
teammates, fans and most others who come into contact with her
jovial personality and humble nature. Sound familiar, Mia Hamm
fans?
</P>
<P>
   But Sun is far from being the marketing icon Hamm has become. At
this point, her only exposure has been as part of an Adidas
campaign that focuses on a number of World Cup players.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said Hamm and Sun are different players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mia's a bit faster and a bit better with the dribble,''
DiCicco said. ``Sun Wen is an artist, finding space for herself and
creating space. They're both outstanding passers; they're both
excellent goal scorers. They're two of the best players in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   To place Sun in that category might seem like a stretch on the
surface, considering the numerous obstacles she faced in
cultivating her game in her homeland. But the statement couldn't be
truer.
</P>
<P>
   As rigid as the Chinese seem to be, even when it comes to
training sessions and preparation for Saturday's game, Sun seems
relaxed _ almost at peace, if you will. She prefers to treat the
moment with the wide-eyed exuberance it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   But her life isn't only soccer. Some of her poetry has been
published in newspapers, she studies Chinese literature at Shanghai
University and she loves to sing karaoke. She even belted out a
rendition of Elton John's ``Candle in the Wind'' for a group of
reporters earlier this week at Pomona College.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sun remembers what it has been like for most young girls
in China who dream of playing soccer at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most fathers cannot accept girls playing soccer,'' Sun said.
``It's the culture. Girls are supposed to be shy and studious and
not so active.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sun said she was lucky to have a father who did not feel
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a real soccer fan, a former player, and he
encouraged me to play,'' Sun said. ``I started to play when I was
10 and started regular training when I was 13. My father is very
proud now.''
</P>
<P>
   He and an entire nation have good reason to be, with China on
the doorstep of an historic game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   China has been angling for revenge since losing to the U.S. 2-1
in the gold- medal game at the '96 Summer Olympics. Sun scored the
lone Chinese goal that day. She also scored a goal in each of
China's two victories against the U.S. earlier this year, including
one in the Algarve Cup final in Portugal, further signifying her
status as a prime-time player.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an incredible forward and she's very good in every
aspect of her game,'' said U.S. defender Kate Sobrero, who likely
will draw the assignment of marking the 5-foot-4, 128-pound Sun.
``She's a complete forward. And that says a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway assistant coach Jarl Torske shakes his head when asked
about how a team should deal with Sun. His team certainly couldn't
in the semifinals. But Torske does have his own impressions of what
makes Sun shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``One on one, she's a very good player,'' Torske said. ``She's
able to turn away from her opponent and she seems to have a huge
repertoire. She's hard to mark because she's always moving. She's
as close to a complete player as I've seen, and I don't think she
has ever been as good as this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun would prefer not to hear such talk, focusing instead on what
her team is trying to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very, very important that we win now,'' she said, ``for
ourselves and for China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
