<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM OF PROPOSED MEDICARE DRUG BENEFIT IS OFF THE MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most criticism of the push for Medicare prescription drug
coverage is valid but misses the point of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drugs are the biggest medical expense for many
senior citizens. The heart-bypass surgeries Medicare underwrites
may be godsends for those relative few needing such heroic
procedures, but it's the unreimbursed, out-of-pocket drain of drug
purchases that relatively more senior citizens have the most
difficulty dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   For every ailing senior for whom Medicare-covered surgery is
indicated, there are many more whose physician visits end with the
simple writing of a prescription whose cost isn't covered by
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But, say opponents of adding the drug benefit, many
beneficiaries already have private supplemental insurance to cover
drug therapy expenses. This means the proposed benefit isn't needed
and will only encourage those paying their own way to become
Medicare free riders.
</P>
<P>
   This argument is a good example of how critics miss the point.
Any national health insurance program worthy of the name should
cover the most pressing expense faced by most of the program's
beneficiaries. To do otherwise is not only morally indefensible,
but also nonsensical given the wherewithal of drugs to make
riskier, more expensive treatments unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many seniors can't afford supplemental private-policy
coverage for prescriptions. Should their needs be dismissed simply
because many others are able to afford private coverage? Besides,
Medicare isn't supposed to differentiate on the basis of economic
status. Like Social Security, it was set up as a universal benefit
to avoid the welfare stigma.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say that even as defensible as drug coverage may
be, morally and economically, it's beyond the scope of a program
already sliding into insolvency. This is a point well taken,
because Medicare's widely publicized financial problems are indeed
critical. But this argument also misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   If Medicare is going broke, it's because it's badly
administered. Mismanagement is no excuse for the program not to
assume its rightful responsibilities, of which drug coverage should
be one. If Medicare's broke, which it is, it should be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The first step toward fixing it would be to remove it from
government control. A blue-ribbon panel recommended a move in this
direction recently but was rebuffed by the administration. A key
recommendation was to issue vouchers with which seniors could buy
their own health insurance tailored to their specific needs.
</P>
<P>
   Having rejected such sensible advice, the administration chose
to push a plan to increase Medicare's outgo despite its inadequate
income, while ignoring the program's anachronistic flaws.
</P>
<P>
   The White House says its plan will ensure that drug coverage
will mostly finance itself, but no reasonable person can believe
this. The history of government entitlements is lowball cost
estimates going in and budget-busting outlays after the program is
running full steam.
</P>
<P>
   If the drug benefit is approved and Medicare's bankruptcy is
accelerated, however, this may not be an entirely bad thing. A
crisis would force the reforms crucial to Medicare's long-term
survival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
