<SLUG> BC-TRACK-SUITES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMAND IS HIGH FOR SUITES AT STILL-UNFINISHED RACETRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM PEDLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Construction isn't even to the point where Kansas Speedway looks
like a speedway, but plans are already being made for the
facility's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Speedway Corp. President Grant Lynch said Thursday that
because of demand for hospitality suites at the track,
consideration is being given to increasing the number of suites
that will be available in phase 1 of construction.
</P>
<P>
   The interest ``is even greater than we anticipated,'' Lynch
said. ``We are overwhelmed by the excitement that folks around the
region have shown.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Zucker, director of business development for Kansas
Speedway Corp., said if the plan for expansion is approved by the
board of directors of International Speedway Corp. -- the parent
company of Kansas Speedway Corp. -- it will more than double the
number of suites -- from 32 to 68 -- that will be built for phase
1.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term lease agreements have been secured for all of the
original 32 suites. Speedway developers have received hundreds of
requests for additional suites.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker declined to reveal names of companies that have committed
to purchase suites, but she said the companies offer ``a neat mix.
Some are national, some are regional, some are local. Some are
companies you have never heard of.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of building the new suites is uncertain, but it would
be added to the project's overall price tag that now stands at $224
million for phase 1. The speedway is being funded by a combination
of revenue bonds, developer equity and state and local incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Speedway Corp. may also consider increasing the
grandstand capacity for phase 1. The reason, again, is the level of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   More than 15,000 people who have contacted speedway offices in
search of tickets have been placed on a mailing list. Speedway
officials project that each person on the list will buy
approximately four tickets to Winston Cup events.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (the number of people who are on the mailing list) is
totally unsolicited,'' Zucker said. ``That's important. We have
been very cautious about putting our number out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Phase 1 plans currently call for grandstand seating of 75,000.
Phase 2 calls for increasing that to 150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker said that phase 1 plans have been updated to increase the
number of parking spaces from 25,000 to 65,000.
</P>
<P>
   The speedway, now under construction near the intersection of
Interstates 70 and 435, was originally scheduled to open in 2000.
But delays in construction caused by poor weather and since-settled
lawsuits have in all probability pushed that date back to 2001.
</P>
<P>
   A Winston Cup race will be the crown jewel of the 1.5-mile,
tri-oval track's race offering. The Indy Racing League also is
planning to hold a race at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Those wanting to get on the mailing list are asked to do so by
accessing the track's Web site at www.kansasspeedwaycorp.com, or
call (913) 328-3300.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
