<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROLIFERATION-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES PLAN TO CURB PROLIFERATION OF WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government's efforts to fight the spread of
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons are disorganized and
overlapping, says an independent commission that calls for a new
White House czar to direct a streamlined defense against ``a grave
threat to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report to be sent to Congress next week, the bipartisan
panel implicitly criticizes President Clinton and recommends that a
national coordinator head a council of senior officials from the
departments of State, Defense, Commerce and Energy and from the CIA
and FBI.
</P>
<P>
   This new organization would coordinate policy making and
budgeting among as many as 96 often-competing federal agencies that
are now involved in preventing or responding to the spread of
biological, chemical and nuclear weapons, and the means to deliver
them.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not address domestic threats like terrorist
attacks, but instead focused on ways to create more effective
responses to matters like detecting foreign germ warfare programs
and reducing the risk of nuclear material being lost or stolen from
the Russian stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. government is not effectively organized to combat
proliferation,'' the report says. ``With no one specifically in
charge of all proliferation-related efforts, no one is ultimately
accountable to the president and to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's recommendations come as North Korea is threatening
to launch another long-range missile, perhaps capable of reaching
the West Coast, and the world's two newest declared nuclear powers,
India and Pakistan, are waging war along their border in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   In light of a House investigation that concluded that China has
been systematically stealing information about American nuclear
warheads and missiles since the 1970s, many lawmakers want to move
nuclear weapons work from the Energy Department to the Defense
Department to increase security over the nation's atomic secrets.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, John M. Deutch, a former director of
Central Intelligence who headed the panel, said, ``The government
must reorganize itself if it's going to meet the more dangerous
proliferation threats we now face.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress set up the panel, the Commission to Assess the
Organization of the Federal Government to Combat the Proliferation
of Weapons of Mass Destruction, in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   An advance copy of the 178-page report was obtained by The New
York Times. The commission's findings were first reported this week
in The Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's recommendations touch virtually every federal
agency with a role in combating the proliferation of weapons of
mass destruction, and Deutch predicted that many federal officials
would balk at reorganizing their efforts and perhaps relinquishing
some of their bureaucratic authority.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reacted cautiously Thursday to the report's
findings and recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious and thoughtful report that we're going to
study very carefully,'' said a senior administration official who
has read the report.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Deputy Defense Secretary John J. Hamre told
reporters that the United States was well prepared to stop the use
of nuclear weapons, but less prepared to combat other threats.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member panel declared, ``The president must lead
efforts'' to combat the threat and to direct a more cohesive,
effective counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   While the threats from biological, chemical and nuclear weapons
that the panel described are not new, the ominous world backdrop
against which the report is being made public gives new urgency to
the findings, panel members said.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the continuing economic turmoil in Russia, the
panel reported at least seven instances since 1992 when
weapons-grade fissionable material was stolen from Russian plants
or storage sites. ``Russia has no reliable inventory of its fissile
material,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, countries like Iran, Iraq, North Korea and
Syria either have or are seeking biological, chemical or nuclear
weapons, and China has sold missiles or missile technology to Iran
and Pakistan, it said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a many-headed monster out there,'' said Sen. Arlen
Specter, a R-Penn., who is vice chairman of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many federal agencies have been slow to respond to the
threat, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   The Persian Gulf War, for example, exposed shortcomings in the
military's ability to detect biological or chemical agents. Eight
years and billions of dollars in research later, the commission
said the military had made little progress in developing more
advanced technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
