r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-COACH-LADN-(SLANG     07-09 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COACH-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICICCO HAS LEARNED ON THE JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ Tony DiCicco was not the most popular choice
to succeed former U.S. women's soccer coach Anson Dorrance in the
summer of 1994. In fact, the choice seemed destined for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did DiCicco have no professional, college or head
coaching experience, his four children are boys.
</P>
<P>
   He had served as the U.S. women's assistant since 1991, working
with the goalkeepers during Team USA's inaugural Women's World Cup
championship in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He was a graduate of Springfield College in Massachusetts and
played five years of professional soccer in the American Soccer
League. But what did he stand to gain by accepting the women's job?
</P>
<P>
   He had to follow Dorrance, not only the coach of Team USA's
Women's World Cup champions but the winningest women's college
coach ever at North Carolina, where he worked with such standouts
as Mia Hamm, Kristine Lilly and Carla Overbeck.
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco, who leads the United States against China in Saturday's
Women's World Cup final at the Rose Bowl, looked at it two ways: He
had nothing to lose. And nothing to gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``One part of me was excited about the challenge,'' said DiCicco
in 1994. ``The other was terrified and knew that even winning would
simply be what was expected.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew there were naysayers, but he simply went about his
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reminded them (the critics) that the players had no
experience when they started, either,'' DiCicco said. ``This is
something you have to learn by doing, by getting into the game and
making it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   So he did what any smart, green coach would do. He went to his
star player _ in this case, obviously, Hamm _ and asked for advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Coach us like men but treat us like women,' '' said
DiCicco, whose only coaching failure was losing the 1994 Women's
World Cup to Norway in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took that to mean, `Be demanding of us on the field and push
us to our best possible level, but treat us with respect and don't
be an in-your-face coach.' And I'll tell you what. I've utilized it
to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco has become the most successful coach in the history of
international soccer, winning the 1996 Olympic gold medal, and has
compiled a remarkable 96-8-7 record along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international games force you to grow, and that's one
thing I really admire about Tony,'' assistant coach Lauren Gregg
said. ``Every opportunity he has to get better, he takes advantage
of. He's a student of the game. No one spends more time watching
tapes, analyzing and discussing them, than Tony does. He's learned
how to lead women, how to lead teams and brought an incredible
tactical sophistication on both sides of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco also learned the difference between coaching women and
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very subtle changes, but overall, when you're
speaking to men, you have to speak to them individually,'' DiCicco
said. ``When I speak to the women, I can speak to them collectively
because they internalize everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I say, `Work on your fitness,' the women will know I'm
speaking to the whole group. If I say that to the guys, they just
say, `I'm the only one fit on this damn team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's more to coaching women than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching 20 females and trying to keep 20 females happy isn't
always the easiest task,'' striker Cindy Parlow said. ``But he's
unique in that he's willing to listen to the players and willing to
take their opinions on different things. We're never afraid to
voice our opinions to him and he has adopted what we've said to
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   And for a man with four sons, he certainly learned a few things
about females.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has 20 daughters here,'' midfielder Lorrie Fair
said. ``He's the perfect fit for this team because he's fatherly.
But he's a coach first, which we all respect.''
</P>
<P>
   And who better to receive the credit for constructing Team USA's
wonderful reputation than DiCicco?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the manager of these 20 players; it starts with him and
ends with him,'' striker Tiffeny Milbrett said. ``I credit him a
lot for learning how to keep his players in check and knowing what
to do. He's had to manage this team and keep winning, and he's done
both for a long time now.''
</P>
<P>
   The bumpy five-year ride has all been worth it for DiCicco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel very fortunate,'' he said. ``I was in the right
place at the right time to even be given this job. It's been a joy
to work with this team over the past five years. We've developed
some great relationships with the team, and it's been an honor to
watch them mature.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco isn't looking past Saturday but admits his future is
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how long I'll keep going,'' he said. ``I've spent
a lot of time away from my family and I'm just looking forward to
winning Saturday and getting home to my wife and children.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg, at least, thinks he'll stick around a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been such a tough road for him,'' Gregg said. ``People on
the outside have no idea what it takes to succeed at this level and
he's given so much of his time. I know he wants to get back with
his family, but hopefully, he'll stay through the 2000 Olympic
Games in Sydney.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
