<HEADLINE>
BOGGS REFUSES TO ACT HIS AGE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-DEVIL RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The difference between the third basemen
is two decades and 2,970 hits.
</P>
<P>
   The kid, 21-year-old Red Sox rookie Wilton Veras, will have his
nights. He's shown that already in the week he's been filling in
for John Valentin, who is back home having his head examined.
</P>
<P>
   The old man, 41-year-old Wade Boggs, knows his nights are
numbered, but that doesn't mean he can't still have his moments
before they place his bust in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   One such moment will come when he collects his 3,000th hit,
sometime next month. That will be a career highlight, assuring him
a place among baseball's immortals.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's highlight won't be remembered past next week.
But Boggs's diving stop of Veras's bid for a hit with runners on
second and third with two out in the eighth inning helped assure
Tampa Bay of another win over the Red Sox, who were 3-2 losers for
the second night in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was unbelievable, man,'' said Devil Rays pitcher Bobby
Witt, the Canton, Mass., native who outdueled another
south-of-Boston pitcher, Dartmouth's Brian Rose, the Red Sox rookie
saddled with his second straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one thing about Wade,'' Witt said, ``he never ceases to
amaze you. I don't know how old he is, but he's still out there,
diving on the turf, the first one running on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's passion has never been lost. He still plays the way
I saw him when he played for the Red Sox. That's why you have to
enjoy him when you watch his act, to see how he performs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox also were hurt by former Red Sox Jose Canseco, whose
31st home run accounted for Tampa Bay's second run. Boston lost its
third straight to the second-year Devil Rays and is four games
behind the Yankees in the American League East. It's the first time
in a month the Sox have lost as many as three games in a row. They
lost five straight from June 5 to June 9.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is best, in terms of October planning, that the Sox
won't have to see Tampa Bay again this season. The Devil Rays, who
took two straight last week in Fenway Park before taking three of
four here, won the season series, 9-4. It's the first time the
Devil Rays have beaten anyone as many as nine times in a season,
and it's the first time the Sox have lost nine times to one
opponent since 1996, when both the Royals and Indians did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rose really pitched a good game, and so did (Derek) Lowe,''
manager Jimy Williams said, alluding to the 2 1/3 scoreless innings
turned in by the Sox reliever. ``We turned some double plays (two),
and we hit the ball good. With that in mind, I feel like we're
going to win games if we play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who were 1 for 7 with runners in scoring position, are
clearly showing the effects of missing Nomar Garciaparra, who sat
out his sixth straight game since aggravating his strained left
groin, and Valentin, who is eligible to come off the disabled list
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who won the opener here, 4-2, managed to score just
a dozen runs in four games against the Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great player, that kid,'' Witt said of Garciaparra.
``Without him in the lineup, they're obviously a lot different. You
get him out of there, and John Valentin, that's the left side of
their infield. And they're both good clutch hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox scored a run in the third when Jose Offerman walked,
took third on Reggie Jefferson's double, and scored on Damon
Buford's infield out.
</P>
<P>
   They scored again in the sixth on Buford's one-out walk, a
stolen base, and a single by Troy O'Leary. That was it, as they
left seven men on base in the last four innings, including the
eighth, when Boggs flashed leather at a time of night when he
usually is on the bench for a defensive replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch runner Chad Fonville, who entered the game after pinch
hitter Mike Stanley drew a leadoff walk from reliever Norm
Charlton, sped to third when Jason Varitek grounded a two-out
double down the third-base line past Boggs, who ostensibly was
guarding the line.
</P>
<P>
   Veras, who already had one single, then slapped a ball toward
the shortstop hole. But Boggs, leaving his feet, stabbed the ball,
scrambled to his feet, and threw out the disbelieving Veras.
</P>
<P>
   That left the hit totals:
</P>
<P>
   Boggs, 2,978.
</P>
<P>
   Veras, 8.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson singled with two out in the ninth off Devil Rays
closer Roberto Hernandez, but Hernandez retired Buford on a tapper
to second to put away the Sox for his fifth save in eight
appearances against Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays took a 1-0 lead against Rose in the first when
Miguel Cairo tripled and scored when he beat Daubach's throw home
on Aaron Ledesma's ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   After the Sox tied it in the third, Canseco, who had been 0 for
12 with six strikeouts in the series, lost a hanger from Rose (3
runs, 5 hits in 5 2/3 innings) into the left-field seats for his
31st home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slider right over the middle of the plate,'' Canseco
said. ``Even as bad as I've been slumping, I couldn't have missed
it. I'm glad I didn't foul it off or miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Canseco walked, took second on an infield out when
Offerman elected to get the out at first instead of the force, and
scored on a single by yet another former Red Sox, catcher John
Flaherty. The throw from right fielder Trot Nixon, for the second
straight night, was just enough off line to allow the run to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rose had good stuff,'' said Witt, who walked four and gave up
seven hits in his 6 2/3 innings but held the Sox to two runs. ``We
were fortunate to get a couple of breaks, and Jose hit that ball,
but I think the kid has great stuff. This was the first time I've
seen him live, and I was really impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   But not impressed enough to lose to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
