<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-09 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IF the message hadn't penetrated, then it is unavoidable even for
the most pig-headed chauvinist: Women's sports are no longer the
distant next wave in this country but are crashing ashore with the
force of a tsunami.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that a crowd of more than 70,000 has filled Giants
Stadium this summer to see the U.S. national team in the Women's
World Cup soccer tournament. They sold out Soldier Field in
Chicago, drew more than 50,000 to Foxboro, Mass., and probably will
exceed the 90,000 barrier for Saturday's final at the Rose Bowl in
Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Houston, in the third season of the WNBA, the Comets
draw an average of 11,143 for their home dates, a figure that is
roughly matched throughout the league as the popularity of the
women's game has spread with the speed and heat of a grease fire.
</P>
<P>
   What is significant about the inroads of the late 20th century
is they are not coming only in the so-called ``traditional''
women's sports of tennis, golf, figure skating and gymnastics,
where it is the individual name that has marquee value.
</P>
<P>
   For while Venus and Serena Williams, Juli Inkster, Tara Lipinski
and Kerri Strug are merely the latest in a line of women's sports
stars, what is changing the landscape most is the area of team
sports.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The number of young girls participating in
basketball and soccer is in the millions nationwide, and it only
makes sense the majority gender eventually would develop its own
idols to emulate or athletes in the hometown or national colors to
cheer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a capitalist society, this is the tip of the iceberg for
gender equity,'' says Donna Lopiano, director of the Women's Sports
Foundation. ``Corporations finally understand that the men's market
is oversaturated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were ignoring a prolific market _ women _ who buy
products disproportionate to their own participation. For sponsors,
this is like finding candy in a candy store.''
</P>
<P>
   For many male sports fans, it has been like hitting a secret
button on the remote control and finding a new ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   For others, women's sports have grown in appeal because they are
more fun to watch than a collection of pampered, grumpy,
no-autograph-signing, paternity-suit-fleeing, I-get-no-respect men
going through the motions for $5 million to $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Because they're relatively underpaid and struggling for
attention, the female pros consistently play harder and also
perform with equal flair, fire and emotion.
</P>
<P>
   They carry around less off-the-field baggage than their male
counterparts, and because they are not as physically powerful, they
usually employ better teamwork and technique and seem to have more
fun.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the NBA, not the WNBA, convened a special committee to
inject more life into its games. Just watch Sheryl Swoopes, Cynthia
Cooper, Tina Thompson and the rest of the Comets push the ball up
and down the floor if you're a basketball fan and have forgotten
what a fast break looks like.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA women also have taken a quantum leap in the style and
quality of the game. Just from the early '90s, the difference in
women's basketball is similar to the change in the men's game from
the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Air Jordan, but there is athleticism to which the
next generation of young girls can aspire.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of popularity, there is nothing that has exploded onto
the radar screen this year like the U.S. women's soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   As the pithy slogan goes on Late Night with David Letterman:
Soccer moms; Soccer mamas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them have kids. Some of them have posed provocatively
for magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm, the prolific goal scorer, was not only named one of
the 50 Most Beautiful by People magazine but also gained the
ultimate tribute in marketing and sports iconism by co-starring
with Michael Jordan in the ``Anything you can do, I can do better''
TV spot.
</P>
<P>
   Together they have shown it is possible to become the most
formidable team on the planet, playing an aggressive, attacking,
relentless brand of soccer, while at the same time remaining down
to earth and accessible to the thousands in the stadiums and the
millions of others watching their march to the World Cup title and
wave-ride of acceptance into the sports mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   For half the population, surf's up, finally, for the new
millennium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
