<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARDLY ANY HAM IN HAMM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ Somebody on Thursday showed Mia Hamm the
1999 Women's World Cup All-Star selections. The U.S. striker
scanned the 16-player list. She saw U.S. goalkeeper Briana Scurry's
name and Brazilian midfielder Sissi's and Chinese striker Sun
Wen's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players there definitely deserve to be on it,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   Then her eyes locked on the last name on the list. Pointing to
it, she said, smirking, ``Oh, I don't know about that one.''
</P>
<P>
   The name she was fingering was her own.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's gesture drew guffaws from the news gatherers in her
midst.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez renouncing his All-Star berth after failing to
beat Tampa Bay despite fanning 14 would be worth a headline. Ditto
cyclist Lance Armstrong turning down the yellow shirt in the Tour
de France or Shaquille O'Neal repudiating any 50 Greatest Players
list with his name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's humility, however, didn't raise an eyebrow, much less a
pen. She has a reputation, well-earned, for being as modest as a
nun's habit. So people naturally read nothing into her
self-deprecating remark.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in this instance Hamm wasn't being humble, just honest.
</P>
<P>
   She might carry the torch as the world's best female soccer
player, but Tiffeny Milbrett has been the one carrying the U.S.
team during the past three weeks. Milbrett, 26, is tied for fourth
in World Cup scoring, with three goals on four shots in five games.
Hamm, 27, is tied for 13th with two goals, both of them
game-winners (she also has two assists).
</P>
<P>
   The real strength of the U.S. squad has turned out to be its
depth, not its demure diva. Every starter but two has scored and
six players have at least two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Its balance is reminiscent of France's World Cup-winning men's
team of a year ago, when Zinedine Zidane and his fellow hosts
blasted Brazil 3-0 in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm is less like Zidane than Brazil's Ronaldo. Right down to
her sponsor's swoosh. Ronaldo, you might remember, was roundly
ripped for failing to live up to his pre-World Cup press clippings.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pallid performance'' is how one scribe summarized Ronaldo's
turn on the world stage. This review he earned by scoring ``only''
four goals in six games leading up to the final, which France won
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm, the game's all-time leading goal scorer, isn't under siege
by the press. She has been hemmed in by reporters but by no means
hammered.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene U.S. co-captain Carla Overbeck termed ``hilarious,''
scribes scampered the length of the soggy field, elbowing one
another for position around Hamm, as soon as the U.S. team finished
practice Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm diligently answered questions while sitting in a folding
chair. Sometimes she made eye contact with her inquisitor but more
often she looked down and picked at the cellophane ice bag wrapped
around her tender left hamstring while giving measured responses.
</P>
<P>
   There were kids by the minivan full at the practice and more
than a few of them infiltrated the interview session afterward,
armed with indelible markers. One turned to another halfway through
Hamm's Q and A with the media and whispered, ``She's really shy.''
</P>
<P>
   The little girl got that right. If there's one thing Hamm skirts
more deftly than defenders, it's the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   A national news magazine recently wanted to run a shot of Hamm
on its cover. She pleaded with her interrogators not to do that and
they ended up running a head shot of presidential hopeful George W.
Bush instead.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. team bus pulled up to Pomona-Pitzer college,
hundreds of people were there with signs and smiles to greet them.
Hamm disembarked on the heels of the team's tallest player, Cindy
Parlow, and followed her up the path as though she were hoping to
hide behind Parlow's 5-foot-11-inch frame.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the U.S. practice got under way in earnest, a couple
thousand people were framing the field. Mia wannabes on this day
looked to be much more outgoing than the original, mugging for the
television cameras and breaking out into chants of ``Mee-ahh'' at
the drop of a hint from a microphone-wielding reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to keep all the attention in a humorous light,''
Hamm said. ``The most important thing is to not let it change you
as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   In her teammates' eyes, Hamm is a star in street clothes, too.
</P>
<P>
   Said Overbeck, ``Mia is as good or better of a person than she
is a soccer player.''
</P>
<P>
   If it annoys Hamm that people who didn't know a free kick from a
penalty kick three weeks ago are picking apart her World Cup
performance, she doesn't show it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person can't carry a team. I never thought I could,'' Hamm
said. ``If people want to (define) success as whether you're
scoring or not, that's their prerogative. What I focus on is, do I
have an impact on this team?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, she made two great passes that led to goals in the second
game against Nigeria, drew a penalty kick in the second half of the
U.S.s semifinal against Brazil that Michelle Akers converted. And
then there are her two goals.
</P>
<P>
   You hear people critically dissect Hamm's performance and you're
reminded of another unselfish scorer whose Hall of Fame bust seemed
to be sprouting cracks under the white-hot spotlight. During the
1993 Stanley Cup playoffs, the so-called experts excoriated Wayne
Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   So who scored the overtime winner in Game 7 against Toronto to
send the Kings into the Finals against Montreal? Gretzky, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't shock us if Hamm has a similar answer for her
critics on Saturday against China. As teammate Tisha Venturini
observed, ``Good things always happen to her in big games.''
</P>
<P>
   That would explain why she's the best. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0017 </DOCNO>
