<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABLED-CHARGES-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA FOOTBALL PLAYERS CHARGED WITH OBTAINING HANDICAPPED PLACARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE   AND JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tripped up by a sharp-eyed police officer, 14
current and former UCLA football players were criminally charged
Thursday with falsely claiming physical disabilities to get
handicapped parking placards.
</P>
<P>
   The players used the placards to park in handicapped-only spots
on and off campus and to avoid paying the $225 per-semester parking
fees, according to Deputy City Attorney Brian Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme began to unravel when a school police officer noticed
a placard was misplaced on a car and questioned the driver, leading
him to football players, according to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The players, including five from the San Fernando Valley area,
face up to six months in jail and $1,000 fines each if convicted of
the misdemeanor charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am embarrassed and disappointed for the young men who were
involved in this problem,'' head football coach Bob Toledo said in
the statement released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spoken to the team as a whole and to the individuals
involved, and those individuals will be disciplined by me. This is
not how I expect players in my program to act _ that has been made
very clear to these young men.''
</P>
<P>
   With the season set to begin Sept. 4, the charges rocked team
members, who held an informal practice Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toledo was very, very angry,'' said one player who asked not
to be identified. ``The penalties are going to be severe. He talked
about how bad we would feel if we knew people who were
handicapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletic Director Peter Dalis said the Athletics Department has
cooperated fully with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly do not condone the actions of the individuals
involved,'' Dalis said in a statement. ``No one in the Athletic
Department was aware of the situation until it was brought to our
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the handicapped said the misuse of placards is
outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating when you're driving around and all the
handicapped spots are taken,'' said Rose Farzaneh, director of
Farzaneh Social Services. ``If you sit and watch, many people come
back to their cars and they are not disabled after all. We don't
like this kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA sports spokesman Steve Rourke said team members have known
for a few weeks that they might be charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``But right now they are only accused. Let's not convict them
yet,'' Rourke said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Collegiate Athletic Association does not have
jurisdiction over athletes involved in criminal charges. Rather,
the organization leaves penalties up to the schools.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Motor Vehicles officials said UCLA has been the
source of frequent complaints about handicapped parking violations
and the target for undercover investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done stings at UCLA before. A lot of complaints come
from there,'' said Evan Nossoff, a DMV spokesman. ``Illegally
taking a handicapped space is right up there with stealing a blind
man's cane.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, the DMV ran a sting at a Beverly Hills restaurant
where valets were stealing placards and either selling them or
using them for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a lot of heat for that,'' Nossoff said. ``Almost
everyone wants preferential parking in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the UCLA scheme involved players listing false
ailments and disabilities on applications for the placards. They
also are accused of signing the names of physicians who do not
exist and then submitting the applications to the DMV, Williams
alleged.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, initiated by UCLA police, began Jan. 16 when
a patrolman spotted a car in the Sunset Village parking structure
on De Neve Drive with a placard improperly placed on the rear-view
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   The officer questioned the driver, who said he was visiting
Robert Wayne Thomas and had borrowed the placard from him, said
City Attorney spokesman Mike Qualls.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA detectives questioned Thomas, then teammate Abdul Azziz,
and got copies of their DMV applications for the placards.
</P>
<P>
   Those applications reportedly contained false information about
physical handicaps, the signature of a nonexistent doctor, a fake
medical license number and an address at the Los Angeles Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, suspicion grew that other players might have
done the same thing,'' Qualls said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators then used DMV records to eventually match the
names of 12 other team members with current or recently expired
handicapped placards, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the players, 21-year-old Deatra Clinton of West Covina,
obtained two placards and faces two misdemeanor counts of illegally
obtaining a placard and giving false information to the DMV.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
