<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GRAHAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RONNY GRAHAM, 79, ACTOR AND MEL BROOKS' WRITING COLLABORATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ronny Graham, an actor and writer who worked in theater and
films and who was known for his frenetic pacing and ear-to-ear
leer, died on Sunday at Century City Hospital in Los Angeles. He
was 79 and lived in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from liver disease, his son Ronald
Stringer said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was a longtime associate of the writer and director Mel
Brooks, whom he met while performing in Leonard Sillman's Broadway
musical-comedy revue ``New Faces of 1952,'' for which they both
wrote sketches.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which earned Graham a Tony Award, was adapted for the
screen with much of its stellar cast in tow, among them Robert
Clary, Paul Lynde, Alice Ghostley, Eartha Kitt and June Carroll.
Graham later collaborated on several of Brooks' films, including
``The Inquisition'' and ``History of the World, Part I,'' as well
as ``Spaceballs'' and ``To Be or Not to Be.''
</P>
<P>
   Born Ronald Montcrief Stringer in Philadelphia, Graham learned
his craft by accompanying his parents, Florence Sweeney and Thomas
Stringer, on the vaudeville circuit, where they played as the
comedy team Steve and Flo. As a boy, he developed an interest in
jazz by listening to Fats Waller records, and by the time he left
high school he had picked up enough piano by ear to play in several
nonunion bands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947 he began performing as a comedian in nightclubs in the
Philadelphia area, using original material rich with innuendo and
double-entendre. He made his New York debut two years later at Cafe
Society Downtown in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, with saucer-shaped eyes, curly black hair and a
gravel-edged voice, Graham preferred his humor pointed and topical.
His act parodied subjects ranging from the titles of 1950s movies
(``Quo Vadis/That's what I said the night we met/Quo Vadis/Means
whither goest thou, my pet?'') to Freudian psychoanalysis to Truman
Capote.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954 he appeared on Broadway in ``The Tender Trap,'' with Kim
Hunter and Robert Preston. He later turned to directing for the
stage, including ``Grin and Bare It,'' a 1969 Broadway comedy about
a family of nudists.
</P>
<P>
   Graham wrote episodes of the television series ``MASH,'' in
which he sometimes appeared, and was a consulting writer on ``The
Mary Tyler Moore Show.'' In the 1970s he was a guest on the
``Tonight'' show more than 60 times, usually performing updated
renditions of his original routines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Stringer, of Los Angeles, he is survived by his
wife, Pamela Gill; two other sons, Julian Graham of Bridgewater,
Conn., and Hilmer Graham of Manhattan; two daughters, Nora Graham
of East Norwalk, Conn., and Timothi Graham of Manhattan; two
sisters, Edna Pastman of Burlington, N.J., and Annabelle McKenna of
Philadelphia, and a granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3989 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELMONT-FIASCO-LADN     07-09 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-FIASCO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEISMIC ACTIVITY COULD MAKE FLAW UNFIXABLE AT BELMONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TERRI HARDY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Constant seismic activity underneath the Belmont
Learning Center makes it impossible to create a fail-safe system
that would vent the explosive methane gas that plagues the site, an
environmental expert told a state commission Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Independent petroleum engineer Bernard Endres told the state's
Seismic Safety Commission that unique environmental problems and
location on top of a blind-thrust earthquake fault create a
dangerous situation that cannot be fixed at the $200 million
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any seismic activity impairs the integrity of methane barrier
seals,'' Endres said after he testified. He was the lead
investigator into the infamous methane gas explosion in the Fairfax
District in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to his comments, Barry Groveman, an outside
environmental attorney and member of the Los Angeles Unified School
District's safety team, said the seismic effects on any proposed
system would need to be thoroughly evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Questions like that deserve legitimate answers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education, with advice from the safety team, is
expected to decide as soon as next week whether to halt
construction at Belmont, at least temporarily. The board plans an
early decision on whether to abandon the project or finish what
would be the nation's costliest school.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Seismic Safety Commission cannot control the LAUSD
board's actions. After hearing the presentation on Belmont,
however, the commission agreed to study state laws and regulations
and determine whether there are holes in the system identifying
seismic problems at potential school sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to examine what the strengths and weaknesses in the
system are,'' said Richard McCarthy, executive director of the
Seismic Safety Commission.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy expects a draft report to be ready in September, but
noted that the commission might not be able to meet then. Gov. Gray
Davis has yet to appoint nine new members to the 17-member
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the system failed at Belmont, state Sens. Tom Hayden,
D-Los Angeles, and Richard Alarcon, D-Van Nuys, said there could be
other toxic problems in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The LAUSD alone is building 100 schools in the next five
years, and schools are going to be built throughout the state with
Proposition 1A bond money,'' Alarcon said. ``We need to learn from
the Belmont experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Endres and Hayden said concerns about seismic hazards at Belmont
were swept aside in the limited environmental reports done for the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said the school was in an earthquake-prone area, as is
all of downtown, and it wasn't a problem,'' Hayden said. ``Here's a
school that's already a danger because it's on top of an active oil
field, but under that is an earthquake problem that will accelerate
the release of methane gas to the surface. Everyone turned a blind
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Endres said the Belmont site is unique because it sits squarely
atop a blind-thrust fault, and there is a source of oil and methane
gas at the surface of the land. Conditions are different from those
at downtown sites such as the city library's, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of whether seismic activity could force oil and gas to
the surface is one of the first that should have been studied
before school officials decided whether the former oil field should
become a school site, Endres said.
</P>
<P>
   Commission members were astonished when Hayden said one of the
recommendations of the safety team in an initial report was not to
use the first floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd have to warn people never to smoke on the first floor
because they'd kill everyone,'' Hayden said. ``This is a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said there was a clear regulatory lapse that allowed the
land to be approved for a school site.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News reported in October 1998 that state safeguards
failed at several sites, including those for Belmont and Jefferson
New Middle School, before construction started.
</P>
<P>
   Groveman said the Los Angeles safety team, attempting to
determine why crucial environmental work wasn't done, repeatedly
heard from representatives of agencies saying it was not their job.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just unacceptable,'' he said. ``There are a number of
places where (Belmont) could have been stopped, but it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Groveman applauded the Seismic Safety Commission's decision to
look into the state's role in approving school sites. If the
systemic problems are not solved, ``there will be a repeat of this
somewhere else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
