<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-NEWS-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA'S LUIS GIUSTI: UNFINISHED BUSINESS 
 CORRUPTION: NORTH OF THE BORDER
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By CLAIRE POOLE 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A CONVERSATION WITH VENEZUELA'S LUIS GIUSTI
 &HT;    Luis Giusti, former CEO of state-owned Petroleos de Venezuela
(PDVSA), has a lot of free time since resigning his post following
President Hugo Chavez's landslide victory last year. Giusti spoke
recently with LATIN TRADE Contributing Editor Claire Poole at a
meeting of the InterAmerican Chamber of Commerce in Houston. They
talked about his tenure at PDVSA, his falling-out with Venezuela's
president and his future plans. The following is an excerpt of the
interview:
 &HT;    
 &HT;    LT: How did you get off on such a wrong foot with Hugo Chavez?
 &HT;    GIUSTI: In politics, especially during campaigns, people take
unilateral positions.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Did you try to repair the relationship?
 &HT;    No. I simply acted in a very cordial and open manner. But I got
the message very clearly that if (Chavez) won, he would want other
people to run the show.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    What do you see as your legacy at Petroleos de Venezuela?
 &HT;    I would like to be remembered for three major things. One,
Petroleos de Venezuela management opened the oil sector and made
clear the difference between sovereignty issues and state control.
Second, we undertook a major corporate transformation to prepare
the company for competition in modern times. Finally, by creating a
competitive playing field, we're bringing Venezuelans closer to oil
and oil closer to Venezuelans.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    What's left that needs to be done?
 &HT;    Hydrocarbon retail sales have not been adequately reformed.
Measures in Congress fell short of our expectations and some work
is still needed to create a free market in distribution and in
retail. We also wanted wider private-sector participation in the
petrochemical sector. We didn't get that, either.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    How are Latin America's big state-owned oil companies, such as
PDVSA, Petrobras and Pemex, working together?
 &HT;    We've been working (with Petrobras) for a while. There was a
protocol signed at the highest level, but we haven't been able to
agree on the basic terms. We have a very close relationship with
Pemex to coordinate U.S. marketing activities. The possibility of
doing more in the future is not out of the question.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    So what are you doing these days?
 &HT;    I'm going to be spending some time with CSIS (Center for
Strategic and International Studies, a think tank) in Washington.
I'll be spending two days every month at Babson College
(Massachusetts) conducting seminars on public policy reforms in
Latin America. I'll be traveling frequently to New York to work
with a couple of institutions.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Do you hope to be president of Venezuela someday?
 &HT;    It's too early to think about that. But I will maintain a heavy,
intense presence in Venezuela. I will be writing in the newspaper
and doing television commentary once a month. And I will be in
close contact with PDVSA. I'm not leaving the country.
 &HT;    --------------------- 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CORRUPTION: NORTH OF THE BORDER
 &HT;    HOUSTON _ Think the Mexican police and other government
officials are the only ones corrupted by Mexico's drug lords? Think
again. The U.S. Customs Service and the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service have not done enough to prevent the
infiltration of Mexico's drug cartel's into their ranks along the
1,962-mile U.S.-Mexico border, says a recent U.S. General
Accounting Office report.
 &HT;    The GAO reviewed 28 cases involving INS and Customs employees
convicted of drug-related crimes between 1992 and 1997. Among the
more notable: Waving drug loads through ports of entry,
coordinating the movement of drugs across the border (using cell
phones and beepers to tell drug traffickers which lanes to use and
when), transporting drugs past border patrol checkpoints (sometimes
in government vehicles), selling drugs and disclosing drug
intelligence information.
 &HT;    ``Given the enormous sums of money being generated by drug
trafficking, the corruption of some INS and Customs employees along
the Southwest border is a serious and a continuing threat,''
concluded the report.
 &HT;    Coming to the defense of the agencies were Assistant Attorney
General Stephen Colgate and William Riley, Customs director of
planning. ``Twenty-eight instances of corruption out of 9,600
agents over about a six-year period is a commendable demonstration
of the integrity of ours and (Customs) personnel,'' said Colgate in
his letter to the GAO.
 &HT;    Still, the GAO is recommending that the two agencies institute
advanced integrity training, much like the U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation, the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration and the
U.S. Secret Service. The GAO also is suggesting the agencies
conduct ``reinvestigations'' of existing employees every five years
(most were overdue by three years and the agencies had a combined
backlog of 934 as of March 1998). Such reinvestigations can raise
red flags about personnel who might be tempted to accept bribes
from drug smugglers to pay down debts or appear to be living well
beyond their means.
 &HT;    Indeed, the GAO cited one border patrol agent who owned a
$200,000 house with an Olympic-sized swimming pool, five cars, one
van, two boats, 100 weapons, $45,000 in U.S. Treasury bills and 40
acres of land _ and carried no debt. Nice work if you can get away
with it.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
