<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELAXED AND READY, WORLD CUP PLAYERS `EMBRACING THE MOMENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ Motorcycles. Uniformed cops on big, shiny
motorcycles revved down the soccer field toward the U.S. Women's
World Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a strange sight.
</P>
<P>
   After practice Thursday, the Claremont police were on hand just
to make sure no one messed around with Mia Hamm, Julie Foudy,
Brandi Chastain or any of the other U.S. team members who have come
like a twister off the sports horizon, sweeping the nation in their
appealing fury.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of shrinking away from this official show of force, you
know what these U.S. players did?
</P>
<P>
   They climbed on the cycles like little kids at Jolly Rogers
Theme Park.
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Kristine Lilly and a few other players put on
motorcycle helmets and went for little spin. Reserve Tiffany
Roberts hit the siren button, sending a ``whoop, whoop'' screech
through the air.
</P>
<P>
   Then the team called over some photographers so they could get
their pictures taken with the motorcycles and the police officers.
They giggled and waved.
</P>
<P>
   In such a loose, relaxed mood, who would guess the Women's World
Cup final was just two days away and that this U.S. team was
gunning to do nothing less than beat China for the coveted title?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Colleen Hacker, the U.S. team's full-time sports
psychologist, would tell you this is exactly the right mood for
this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to embrace the moment. We're not looking behind us.
We're not looking ahead. That's how these guys are. We have this
moment and this time and we want to embrace it,'' Hacker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And rather than seeing them as acting loose and relaxed, I
would say you're seeing them embracing the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hacker, a professor and assistant dean at Pacific Lutheran
University, has been working with the U.S. Women since 1995 _ the
year the U.S. lost in the semifinals during the last World Cup and
something, someone was needed to come in and help these elite
soccer players achieve their potential.
</P>
<P>
   Hacker was hired by U.S. coach Tony DiCicco after he begged U.S.
Soccer to fund the sports psychologist position. And with Hacker in
place, available for one-on-ones and group exercises, the U.S.
women went on to win 25 of 28 matches in 1996, including the
Olympic gold medal match.
</P>
<P>
   Hacker was a soccer coach at PLU for 17 years, winning three
NAIA national titles, in 1988, '89 and '91. But she resigned as PLU
coach in '95 when she was asked to work with the U.S. National
Team.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has worked with U.S. Rowing and the U.S. Tennis
Association and been wooed by NFL teams to come work with them,
Hacker said she is deeply committed to this team and is providing
some serious techniques (imagery, stress management, self-talk,
goal-setting and relaxation) to help make them winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask the elite athletes _ and I'm talking Olympic,
world-class athletes _ what are the 10 qualities that separate
success from failure, the top five were all psychological skills.
In sixth place was physical ability, Hacker said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Hacker _ who has a sports psychology degree from the
University of Arizona and a doctorate from the University of Oregon
_ talked about the ability of this U.S. team to handle the world
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say this is unprecedented, how will they handle this,
but it was unprecedented during the '96 Olympics, so we have been
here before. They're not going around counting what papers are
here, what cameras. We've had papers around. We've had cameras.
We've had the largest crowds in history. We've been here. We draw
on our experience,'' Hacker said.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to deny that these U.S. women have some sort of
special, strong, psychological composure. That much was evident
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the reason soccer officials picked Pomona College as
the training site for the Women's World Cup finals was because its
campus is small, pretty, quiet and _ since it is 30 miles east of
downtown Los Angeles _ out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   At least it used to be out of the way. Thursday, quiet little
Pomona was the center of the universe, or at least it felt that
way.
</P>
<P>
   The Beatles were in town _ at least that's what this U.S. team
seems like, attracting Tom Brokaw, Newsweek and a crowd to
Thursday's practice that swelled to more than 3,500 cheering
spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, even actor Karl Malden came out and watched at the edge of
the soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever practice in front of Karl Malden before?'' someone asked
Mia Hamm.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm simply smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever think this team would inspire this sort of
interest?'' someone else asked wise-cracking midfielder Foudy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, because we have always felt this team was the best-kept
secret,'' Foudy said. ``Not because of how well we play soccer but
because of the people who are on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same group of athletes who demanded they be coached
like men but treated like women, since team and feelings are
important.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the face of all this World Cup hype and attention, this
very special team is demonstrating remarkable focus, poise and
spontaneity, as well as _ pardon the expression, but it fits _
athletic cockiness.
</P>
<P>
   They manage all of this while also extending a generous
graciousness to anyone who comes into their orbit. Try asking that
of some NBA, NFL or major league baseball teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them, `Your attitude is like a paintbrush. You can
color any situation. So what is the spirit? What is the attitude
you bring to this?''' Hacker said.
</P>
<P>
   Their spirit and attitude are inspiring, quite frankly. And it
is this team's chemistry, karma and sense of destiny that very well
could help them overcome a dangerous opponent in China on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, their psychology coach has already made them
winners within.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
