<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARAK'S-BIG-CHANCE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EHUD BARAK'S BIG _ REALLY BIG _ OPPORTUNITY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 625-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 10 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He took office this week promising to end ``the 100-year
conflict'' in the Middle East. If he goes for it, Ehud Barak has a
better hope than any previous Israeli prime minister of bringing
this off.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected with a resounding personal vote of confidence, he
is backed by a comfortable majority in parliament, no section of
which is in a position to block the way to peace, and his choice of
ministers signals that he will be running things in the way he
wants.
</P>
<P>
   He faces Arab leaders whose relief at the departure of the
previous Israeli government makes them receptive to the new one.
</P>
<P>
   The chance of peace, at least at this initial stage, is Barak's
to squander. First impressions are good. The prime minister is to
pay a quick call on his neighbors _ Egypt's Hosni Mubarak, the
Palestinians' Yasser Arafat and Jordan's King Abdullah _ before he
goes off to see Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   His first speech to the Knesset, in which he made a plea for ``a
peace of the brave,'' was in stirring contrast to Benjamin
Netanyahu's deep-freezing of the process.
</P>
<P>
   No less important, he tried to reassure Palestinians and others
who doubt his priorities: the pursuit of a permanent Palestinian
settlement was as ``vital and urgent'' to him as winning peace with
Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   His commitment to get Israeli soldiers out of Lebanon within a
year, and his own instincts as a former chief of staff, had
suggested that he might pour his energies into the Syrian pot.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by an interviewer from Israel's Haaretz newspaper whether
he agreed with the late Yitzhak Rabin that the Palestinian problem
was at the heart of the Jewish-Arab conflict, Barak replied with an
inventory of Syria's arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, said Barak, the Palestinians ``are the weakest of
all our adversaries. As a military threat they are ludicrous.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Barak acknowledged, the Palestinians give legitimacy to
the Arabs' continuing grievance against Israel. Put another way,
until the Palestinian problem is solved, Israel's existence will
continue to Arabs to seem illegitimate.
</P>
<P>
   No arrangement that Israel makes with an Arab state will be
normal while the Palestinians' status remains indeterminate: the
20-year-old cold peace with Egypt provides a convincing example of
that. However important peace with Syria, regional stability still
depends on an Israeli-Palestinian settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Like Netanyahu, Barak would have liked to skip the unfinished
business left over from the interim agreement, including the
withdrawal prescribed at the Wye summit in Maryland last October,
and go straight to negotiating a final settlement with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   There is a case for that: Barak, unlike Netanyahu, would be
negotiating in good faith, and experience shows that a drawn-out
process invites trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Why waste time and goodwill when there is a chance of achieving
a decent and lasting solution? The answer is that the Palestinians,
as weak as Barak described them, are fearful of being exploited.
</P>
<P>
   They agree that talks on a final deal should not be further
delayed, but they want to enter them in control of the one-third or
so of the West Bank they have so far been allotted.
</P>
<P>
   With good cause to be distrustful, they need the reassurance of
seeing an Israeli government honestly implementing signed
agreements. That first step needs to be taken swiftly, without the
prevarications of the Netanyahu government, while preparing for the
all-important final talks.
</P>
<P>
   The target date for a deal is next May, a year later than
originally scheduled. This is tight, but it could be met if the
opportunity were grasped.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has shown decisively that he is his own man. Now he has to
show that he is the man who can make peace. &QL; 
