<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HATE-CRIMES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWW.KILL-MINORITIES.COM  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Chicago and Peoria, Ill. and Ind.)   (This excellent 925-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 10 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ America's melting pot can sometimes boil over, and
violently.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, Benjamin Smith, a 21-year-old university student and
avowed white supremacist, apparently began a three-day, two-state
shooting spree in which he killed a black and a Korean and injured
nine Jews, blacks and Asians.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of July 2, according to the police and the FBI,
Smith fired shots from his blue Ford Taurus at six Orthodox Jews as
they walked home from Sabbath prayers in a Chicago suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Less than half an hour later, in Skokie, he apparently shot and
killed Ricky Byrdsong, a black man who was the former basketball
coach of Northwestern University; Byrdsong was jogging with his
children when he was shot in the back.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later and several towns away, an Asian man and
woman were shot at while they were driving.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, as police struggled to connect the shootings,
Smith turned up in central Illinois where, in separate incidents,
he seems to have fired shots at several black men, a black
minister, and a Taiwanese man standing on a street corner with a
group of Asian men.
</P>
<P>
   Smith then crossed the state line to Bloomington, Ind. On July
4, Won Joon Yoon, an Indiana University graduate student, was shot
and killed outside a Korean church.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 48 hours after the shooting spree began, the police
responded to a carjacking and gave chase to a van Smith had stolen
after ditching his car, which was now widely recognized. Before the
police could take him into custody, he shot himself and later died.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest clue to this rampage may be Smith's involvement in
the World Church of the Creator, a white-supremacist, anti-Semitic,
anti-Christian organization founded in Florida in the early 1970s
and now based in East Peoria, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The World Church has declared a ``racial holy war'' against
non-whites, who are deemed to be inferior ``mud races'' that
jeopardize the prosperity and integrity of whites.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old leader of the group, Matthew Hale, recruited
Smith while he was a student at the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blacks and non-whites are taking this country right from
under us,'' Hale told a National Public Radio interviewer after the
shootings. ``We are becoming a niggerfied, Jewified, Mongolfied
country, and it's disgusting. We have to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hale insists his organization does not embrace violence, yet he
has refused to express remorse over the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Harlan Loeb, the region's counsel for the Anti-Defamation
League, a Jewish civil-rights organization, reckons that the World
Church of the Creator is one of the fastest-growing white supremacy
groups in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The membership figures are notoriously unreliable, but the
organization claims to have 7,000 members in nearly 40 chapters
spread around the country. And the World Church is not unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web has been an absolute boon for hate groups,'' says
Loeb.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago the Simon Wiesenthal Institute, an international
human-rights organization, identified a single hate website; a
study finished this month found over 1,800 such sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet reaches into places where hate groups have never
gone before: homes, offices, schools. Attractive websites can drape
fringe ideas with a certain respectability.
</P>
<P>
   The medium is particularly well suited for reaching angry social
outcasts, who find comfort in the Web's anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Some websites cleverly ensnare schoolchildren. A student doing a
report on Martin Luther King, for example, might stumble upon the
site mlking.org, offering ``complete facts and documentation'' of
his life. The site is not sponsored by a museum or library; it was
created by a white supremacist who has his own views about King's
place in history.
</P>
<P>
   In Smith's case, his racism seemed to grow slowly. At the
University of Illinois he studied environmental sciences, but
later, after he had met Hale, he went to the University of Indiana
in Bloomington and switched to criminal justice in a department
specializing in crimes against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   His apparent rampage flies in the face of two common notions
about racism: first, that it thrives best during tough economic
times, when hard-up workers see minorities snapping up precious
jobs; and, second, that it is whites at the bottom of the economic
barrel who find the racist message most alluring.
</P>
<P>
   The American economy could hardly be in better shape, and Smith
was far from the bottom of the ladder. He was brought up in one of
Chicago's most affluent suburbs, where his father was a doctor and
his mother was a real-estate agent and member of the town council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely nobody is immune,'' says the Anti-Defamation
League's Loeb, who compares the psychology of racial hatred to drug
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals with low self-esteem, he believes, seize upon racist
doctrine to overcome feelings of inadequacy. And, as with drugs, it
can be a powerfully self-destructive urge.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Abraham Cooper, associate dean of the Simon Wiesenthal
Institute, thinks the problem will not correct itself, and would
like to see more social responsibility on the part of Internet
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government must sort out the messy compromises
that balance free speech on the Web against the violence it may
inspire, as it has with every other kind of expression.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there is the prodigious task of influencing
the growing number of people who find the messages of hate so
attractive in the first place. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
