<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPERPHECT-DAN-QUAYLE-325&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE SHOOTING: WHY IT'S ALWAYS OPEN SEASON ON DAN  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article _ with two helpful
optional trims _ is from the current (week beginning 10 July 1999)
ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO USER-FRIENDLY OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 275 WORDS, AT 325
AND 750. TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,025 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Name-recognition is an asset craved by all politicians. Some,
like George W. Bush, inherit it or, like Elizabeth Dole, gain it by
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Others buy it: witness the current television commercials of
Steve Forbes, crafted in a grainy black-and-white to make the
billionaire publisher look more like a leader than an oddball.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, with neither inheritance nor a personal fortune,
uses his popularity as a pugnacious TV pundit. John McCain relies
on his past as a war hero.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, among these and other contenders in the contest for the
Republicans' presidential nomination, surely none has a name quite
as recognizable as Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Quayle has gained recognition through ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   He was the American vice-president (a heartbeat away from the
position held by the father of George W.) who on a classroom visit
in New Jersey chalked up a misspelled ``potatoe'' in front of the
television cameras; who declared that he ``didn't live in this
century''; who is derisively caricatured in the Doonesbury comic
strip as a feather.
</P>
<P>
   The cruelty of journalism is that no profile of Quayle, not even
by Economist's gentle pundit, Lexington, is complete without a list
of Quayle gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   But does the vice-president (the title may be out-of-date, but
it has its uses) object? Hasn't the press been pretty mean to him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredibly mean,'' comes the answer _ but with a sparkle in
the blue eyes and a genuine grin on a sun-burnished face that is 52
years old but remains incongruously boyish.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Quayle is not a man to bear grudges, and, even if he
were, he would be clever enough to hide them. After all,
recognition, however gained, is still an asset: it may just
possibly keep Quayle in the battle for the nomination when other
warriors, their reputations bruised and bank accounts emptied, have
no choice but to leave early. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 175 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 325) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How early is a function of two things: the preeminence of George
W. and the electoral calendar.
</P>
<P>
   In just six months Bush has raised an astonishing $36.3 million
_ double the amount collected by Al Gore, the Democrats'
front-runner, and almost nine times more than any other Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, even though he has spent the past six years preparing
for the 2000 nomination, has managed a mere $3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the nomination will be sewn up in March, when big
states such as California, New York, Florida and Texas all hold
their primaries, how can any candidates other than Bush, with his
war chest, and Forbes, with his deep pockets, survive beyond
spring?
</P>
<P>
   The immediate answer for Quayle is to do well in Iowa, first in
the straw poll on Aug. 14 in Ames (candidates will give voters a
$25 entrance ticket, a free bus ride to Ames and free food once
they are there), and then in the caucus on Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well'' is a measure left undefined, but what it clearly
involves is that in the Ames straw poll Bush should fall short of
his hubristic target of more than 50 percent, and that Quayle
should do better than fellow conservatives such as Gary Bauer or
John Kasich.
</P>
<P>
   As Quayle's clever campaign director puts it, the money may not
be good but with matching funds there is more than enough for the
Iowa caucus and the New Hampshire primary the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question that looms is electability. For us the straw poll
is a shakedown. Some candidates are betting the ranch on the straw
poll.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, if they drop out, does Quayle really become more electable
simply because he is still standing?
</P>
<P>
   Before a crowd of friendly Iowans gathered in a room at the
Washington County Hospital, he draws a ripple of laughter by
recalling his brave but disastrous 1992 criticism of the TV
character Murphy Brown's decision to become an unmarried mother:
``It was like I'd launched a nuke. I'm proud to say that I'm still
here fighting for the American family, and Murphy Brown is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the good humor and the passing of time will make the
ridicule (``the cost of doing business,'' says the campaign
director) fade into insignificance. After all, Quayle has become a
master of staying ``on message,'' whether talking to Larry King on
CNN or chatting to small-town Iowans. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 750) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A stronger family; a ban on late-term abortions; restrictions on
judicial ``activism'' (by liberal-minded judges, that is); more
discipline in schools; lower taxes (by 30 percent across the board,
and with deductions reserved for mortgages, charitable
contributions, health care, retirement, education and state and
local taxes); better-equipped armed forces _ it is the message of
bedrock conservatism, bolstered by references to the long-term
danger of China and the folly of American involvement in Kosovo
(``the wrong war in the wrong place''). &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he discards the onions from his lunchtime salad _ politicians
need to be careful _ Quayle praises the Midwestern characteristics
of Iowa: ``This is real America, with real people and real
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed: and by implication the Midwestern Quayle, elected to the
House of Representatives from Indiana at the age of 29, to the
Senate at 33 and to the vice-presidency at 41, would be the perfect
defender of those values in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   So why do so few Americans, even in his own party, believe in
the concept of President Quayle?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is clearly the George W. Effect, which amazes Quayle
and the pundits alike. Another is perhaps that a lot of Americans
think his ``Midwestern values'' are a mite simplistic (though
Quayle bristles at the notion that he is more comfortable in rural
than inner-city America).
</P>
<P>
   But, ironically, the third has to do with George Bush senior.
All politicians commit gaffes: Al Gore, for example, was supposedly
the inspiration for ``Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that Bill Clinton has treated his
vice-president with a respect and seriousness that President Bush
withheld from Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Gore's gaffes evoke amused smiles and Quayle's only
condescending sneers. And it is why Quayle, like a small boy
playing basketball with people very much taller, will surely end up
looking brave rather than triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   As he puts it: ``I don't think about losing _ and I have a lot
of love for my country, win or lose.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
