<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-GERMAN-CLOUT-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY EMERGES FROM ITS POSTWAR SHELL  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,075-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 10 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONN _ The timing, though accidental, could hardly be more
striking. Ten years after the collapse of communism, and just as
the government in sleepy little Bonn starts its long trek east to
the old-new capital of Berlin, united Germany is at last starting
to punch its full political weight in the world.
</P>
<P>
   This is partly the work of Gerhard Schroder, a nifty pugilist
(some would say bruiser) of a chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Partly it is because Germany has this year been both president
of the European Union and chairman of the Group of Seven rich
countries, and has therefore had to show leadership on all sorts of
matters from European budget reform to debt relief for the world's
poorest states.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, it is because of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It is remarkable enough that German forces, with the backing of
most Germans at home, went abroad to fight for the first time since
1945 (they now make up the second-biggest contingent, after the
British, in the Kosovo peace force).
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago most Germans still shunned even a
non-combat role for the Bundeswehr in international peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Still more surprising, on the face of it, is that this leap was
made by the country's first government coalition of sometimes
strongly NATO-critical Social Democrats and broadly pacifist
Greens.
</P>
<P>
   But it may have been precisely the switch from a center-right
government to a red-Green one that gave Germany its unexpected
chance to increase its clout abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Had the parties of the left lost September's election, it is
argued, they would almost certainly have damned NATO's bombing of
Serbia, encouraged public opposition to the war and made it far
harder to send Germans into action and keep them there.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the new coalition under Schroder and his Green
foreign minister, Joschka Fischer, had willy-nilly to take a crash
course in foreign-policy realism. It turned out to be a painful
exercise. Just how painful is emerging bit by bit.
</P>
<P>
   At the start, it is true, the Germans were happily surprised by
American back-slapping and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Washington last October, after their election
victory but nearly three weeks before taking office, Schroder and
Fischer sought _ and thought they had received _ a promise that
they would not be pressed into backing a ``military option'' in
Kosovo, at least until they had been sworn into office.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, back in Bonn, a surprise call from Washington
demanded that they should give it their support more or less within
the hour.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden change? No one in Bonn seems to know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, the Germans had other Kosovo-induced differences
with America _ for instance, over the American bombing of the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade (embarrassingly just before Schroder
was due to visit Beijing) and over how best to handle the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Fischer notes, America is ``the only heavyweight''
around. Harder for the Germans to take was their treatment by the
British and French over the Rambouillet conference, which began
work in February to try to find a political solution for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   German officials who arrived in London in late January to
discuss setting up just such a gathering say they were
``dumbfounded'' to find that their partners had already settled the
matter and decided to appoint themselves co-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were left on the doorstep,'' says one official, though not
quite accurately, since the Germans did indeed get inside
Rambouillet's hallowed halls, albeit as little more than house
guests.
</P>
<P>
   When the big three flew to Belgrade in a last-ditch bid to avoid
war, Germany got no place aboard the aircraft. ``That won't happen
to us again,'' vows one senior official, glowering over the
Rambouillet debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Sour grapes? In part, no doubt. But it is understandable that a
brand-new red-Green government should have been treated with
circumspection by its partners in such a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The coalition's leaders reckon that in Kosovo they
have clearly proved Germany's reliability as an ally. They had to
fight off sturdy opposition in their parties' ranks and they
(especially Fischer) put their jobs on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they want an equal say at the West's top table. Strictly
speaking, Germany has been part of the West's big four since at
least 1979, when Chancellor Helmut Schmidt joined America, Britain
and France for a summit conference in Guadeloupe to discuss how to
counter the Soviet Union's nuclear plans in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades after that, though, Germany has remained less
equal than the other three _ partly because it was divided until
1990, partly because, under pressure from the left, it balked at an
active role in peacekeeping abroad.
</P>
<P>
   That is now past. This does not have to mean that Germany,
conscious of its muscle and new status, will now seek to go it
alone. On the contrary, Fischer's people chant that Kosovo
underlines the EU's crying need for a common foreign and security
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany demands ``a leading role'' (any ears cocked in Paris
and London?) in formulating that policy. And it will be no less
forceful than its partners in promoting its own people for top
international posts.
</P>
<P>
   Note how Schroder boxed through his right-hand man, Bodo
Hombach, for the big economic-aid job in the Balkans; also how he
has played tough with Romano Prodi, the European commission's new
president, over which two Germans should become commissioners in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Nor may it be coincidence that Germany has decided to boycott
informal EU meetings because Finland, which took over from Germany
at the beginning of this month to hold the Union's six-month
presidency, refuses to include German at them as a working
language.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a danger that Germans may now be forgetting the
grimmest aspects of their past?
</P>
<P>
   No. On June 25, after more than a decade of anguished debate,
the German parliament at last agreed to the building of a huge
memorial to Jewish victims of the Holocaust in the middle of
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though Germany is not turning its back on the past, it is
less disposed to be constrained by it.
</P>
<P>
   As Schroder put it on taking office, it is a country ``neither
better nor worse'' than others. Quite so. Just a bit bigger than
its neighbors, and bang in the center of Europe. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 1,075-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4036 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-GERMAN-CLOUT-ECON     07-09 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-GERMAN-CLOUT-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY EMERGES FROM ITS POSTWAR SHELL  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,075-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 10 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
