war, Germany got no place aboard the aircraft. ``That won't happen
to us again,'' vows one senior official, glowering over the
Rambouillet debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Sour grapes? In part, no doubt. But it is understandable that a
brand-new red-Green government should have been treated with
circumspection by its partners in such a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The coalition's leaders reckon that in Kosovo they
have clearly proved Germany's reliability as an ally. They had to
fight off sturdy opposition in their parties' ranks and they
(especially Fischer) put their jobs on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they want an equal say at the West's top table. Strictly
speaking, Germany has been part of the West's big four since at
least 1979, when Chancellor Helmut Schmidt joined America, Britain
and France for a summit conference in Guadeloupe to discuss how to
counter the Soviet Union's nuclear plans in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades after that, though, Germany has remained less
equal than the other three _ partly because it was divided until
1990, partly because, under pressure from the left, it balked at an
active role in peacekeeping abroad.
</P>
<P>
   That is now past. This does not have to mean that Germany,
conscious of its muscle and new status, will now seek to go it
alone. On the contrary, Fischer's people chant that Kosovo
underlines the EU's crying need for a common foreign and security
policy.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany demands ``a leading role'' (any ears cocked in Paris
and London?) in formulating that policy. And it will be no less
forceful than its partners in promoting its own people for top
international posts.
</P>
<P>
   Note how Schroder boxed through his right-hand man, Bodo
Hombach, for the big economic-aid job in the Balkans; also how he
has played tough with Romano Prodi, the European commission's new
president, over which two Germans should become commissioners in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Nor may it be coincidence that Germany has decided to boycott
informal EU meetings because Finland, which took over from Germany
at the beginning of this month to hold the Union's six-month
presidency, refuses to include German at them as a working
language.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a danger that Germans may now be forgetting the
grimmest aspects of their past?
</P>
<P>
   No. On June 25, after more than a decade of anguished debate,
the German parliament at last agreed to the building of a huge
memorial to Jewish victims of the Holocaust in the middle of
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though Germany is not turning its back on the past, it is
less disposed to be constrained by it.
</P>
<P>
   As Schroder put it on taking office, it is a country ``neither
better nor worse'' than others. Quite so. Just a bit bigger than
its neighbors, and bang in the center of Europe. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
