<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMWORKS-COMPETITION-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMWORKS' STUDIO SEARCH ANIMATES CITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff Writers Jim Skeen, Patricia Farrell Aidem and Angela M.
Lemire contributed to this story. 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Welcome to the home of DreamWorks SKG _ the star
studio and pride of Burbank, or is it Glendale, Palmdale,
Lancaster, Santa Clarita or North Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   A week after DreamWorks abandoned its plans to build a $250
million studio complex at Playa Vista near the beach, a long line
of communities is trying to woo the glamorous production company
run by Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen.
</P>
<P>
   The company, responsible for ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``The
Prince of Egypt,'' has yet to show any interest in reviving its
plans for constructing a major studio at a single site. Operations
now are scattered at Glendale, Universal City and Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Mayors, city managers and development officers from throughout
the San Fernando Valley region _ home to Warner Bros., Disney and
Universal _ hope to become home to Hollywood's newest studio, a
move that would boost tax and tourism revenues, bring good-paying
jobs _ and add star power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to champion their bad news, but this is an opportunity,''
said Derrill Quaschnick, assistant director of the Glendale
Redevelopment Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clarita Mayor Jo Anne Darcy is drafting a letter asking
DreamWorks to consider her city.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank City Manager Robert ``Bud'' Ovrom already has sent not
one but three letters, including aerial photos of the sites he
likes best.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Lancaster is willing to give DreamWorks 47 acres _
free.
</P>
<P>
   And what is DreamWorks doing about all this newfound attention?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking at anything at this point,'' said spokesman
Andy Spahn. ``We've been getting calls, but we hadn't had
discussions with anyone yet.''
</P>
<P>
   That hang-back approach might only fuel the competition among
suitors even though the early forecasts give the edge to Universal
City, where DreamWorks has offices, and Glendale, where its
animation shop is housed.
</P>
<P>
   That won't stop Burbank's Ovrom from pulling out all the stops.
The city's No. 1 promoter has shamelessly attempted to entice other
studios to locate new facilities in Burbank, going so far as taking
out ads in the Hollywood trades.
</P>
<P>
   After their ordeal in Playa Vista, where financing fell through
and environmentalists raised substantial community opposition,
Ovrom said DreamWorks might be ready for a pitch from a
studio-friendly city like Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every site we'll show them is ready to go. All you have to do
is come over to our counter and pull the building permit,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   While DreamWorks had planned to create a huge complex at Playa
Vista, complete with soundstages and office buildings, Ovrom said
it might make more sense for the company just to build a
``signature'' headquarters building and then to lease soundstage
space from other studios, like Warner Bros. and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're perfect for that,'' Ovrom said. ``We're ground zero for
the entertainment industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich weighed in
on behalf of Lancaster's offer of land near Fox Field, writing
letters to Spielberg and Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike the city of Los Angeles, Lancaster is business-friendly
and would work to help you locate your studio in its
jurisdiction,'' Antonovich wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Margolis, a spokesman for Mayor Richard Riordan's office of
economic development, said DreamWorks is a priority for Los
Angeles, which had offered more than $70 million in incentives for
the Playa Vista site.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with other potential major developments, the city will
continue to present DreamWorks with other sites. A number of sites
are being considered,'' he said, adding that it was too soon to
consider what types of incentives might be offered to the studio to
locate in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The L.A. site most often talked about is the North Hollywood
Studio Project, where developer J. Allen Radford has been cleared
to build 10 soundstages, two 20-story towers and a business campus.
</P>
<P>
   Radford said his site provides a convenient location for
DreamWorks because it is located near both the company's offices on
the Universal campus and its 12-acre animation complex in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always took the position that if they weren't successful in
Playa Vista that we are a viable alternative within the city of Los
Angeles,'' Radford said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Allen, president of the Economic Alliance of San Fernando
Valley, said Los Angeles needs to be aggressive to win the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Los Angeles should be scrambling to keep this deal
because they have a good chance of losing it to Glendale and
Burbank. It could be embarrassing for L.A. to lose this deal,''
Allen said. ``L.A. needs to take this competition seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
