<HEADER>
A4043 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-MONARCHS-H     07-09 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MONARCHS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ For the long-suffering Sacramento Monarchs,
respect has been hard to come by.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That should no longer be a problem, after the way they took
apart the Comets 74-63 on Thursday night at Arco Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Kedra Holland-Corn, a Houston native, had six steals to key a
stifling defense that held Cynthia Cooper and Sheryl Swoopes in
check. The Comets (11-2) shot a season-low 32.8 percent from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shoot 32 percent, you're not going to beat a good
basketball team that played well,'' said Comets coach Van
Chancellor. ``And (Monarchs coach Sonny Allen) said he thought that
was as well as they could play. They had a great plan; they
deserved it. They really executed well.''
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, Chancellor thought about drafting
Holland-Corn but changed his mind. Thursday night, she got under
the Comets' skin with 16 points and six steals.
</P>
<P>
   But she also threw a net over Cooper, holding her to a single
field goal and four points through the first 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time we've ever played for 40 minutes solid,
and tonight we just focused on Cooper, Swoopes and (Tina) Thompson
and tried to mess their game up a little bit,'' Holland-Corn said.
``I thought we got in Cooper's head and got in Swoopes' head just a
little bit, but Thompson wasn't affected in the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson scored 10 of her 17 points in the first half. But
Cooper didn't reach double figures until midway through the second
half and Swoopes was sporadic throughout as she tried to counter
the defense of Ruthie Bolton-Holifield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we had to shut them down defensively, and our kids just
did a great effort,'' said Allen, in his first year as Monarchs
coach. ``That's probably the best defensive game the Monarchs have
ever played for 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been getting respect, but you have to earn it. You have
to beat good teams, and this is the first real good team we've
beaten this year. I'm not worried about respect, if we keep playing
well. That'll come.''
</P>
<P>
   Though defense was the name of the Monarchs' game, offensive
rebounds and the perimeter shooting of Bolton-Holifield were
contributing factors for Sacramento (9-4).
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see Cynthia Cooper making the moves tonight?''
Monarchs point guard Ticha Penicheiro playfully asked the crowd of
9,505 afterward. ``I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the game we wanted to see where we are. We won, but we
still have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs are at the top of the WNBA class this season in
offensive rebounding. Thursday night, they worked over the Comets
for 16 offensive rebounds (35 total) and used that advantage to
help score 34 points in the paint compared to 12 for the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Griffith pulled down a game-high 13 rebounds (four
offensive) to go with 15 points, and Latasha Byears had 10 rebounds
(six offensive).
</P>
<P>
   After spotting the Comets a 3-0 lead, thanks to a 3-pointer by
Swoopes, the Monarchs took the lead for good on a fast-break layup
by Penicheiro, one of Sacramento's three All-Stars, at 16:25 of the
opening period.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets trailed 37-32 at the half. Cooper was 0-for-5 from
the field and had only four points, and the Comets had shot a
dismal 29.4 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the first few minutes of the second half are a time for
the Comets to regroup, adjust and come out firing.
</P>
<P>
   It was not to be Thursday. Instead, the futility of the opening
20 minutes only worsened. The dismal shooting continued with
Holland-Corn harassing Cooper and Bolton-Holifield making life
miserable for Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   And when Thompson picked up her fourth foul with 13:19 to play,
it gave Griffith a chance to make one of two free throws and put
the Comets in a 12-point hole (51-39), matching their largest
deficit this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper finally got her second field goal of the night and first
3-pointer with 8:04 to go, but it served only to rescue the Comets
from a 56-43 deficit. Griffith's offensive rebound and basket gave
Sacramento a commanding 60-46 lead a minute later.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-0 run by the Comets with Sonja Henning and Thompson getting
back-to-back buckets and Swoopes hitting a pair of free throws cut
the margin to 60-52.
</P>
<P>
   But the rally was short-lived. A basket by Bolton-Holifield with
5:06 left boosted the lead to 62-52.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of free throws by Penicheiro made it 74-60 with 32.1
seconds left. Thompson's 3-pointer with 14.1 seconds to go provided
the final margin.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper finished with 13 points, her third straight game reaching
that figure, which is 10 points below her average, and Swoopes
added 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
