<HEADER>
A4044 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOUCHNER-KOSOVO-ECONO     07-09 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOUCHNER-KOSOVO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. BERNARD KOUCHNER: EGO SANS FRONTIERES, OR KOSOVO'S ANTIDOTE?  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,050-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 10 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.N.'s secretary-general said he was looking for someone
``with a political sense, a leader and manager, who is also a good
negotiator'' to be the civilian proconsul for the new protectorate
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Those are certainly not the qualities usually associated with
Bernard Kouchner, France's junior health minister, whom Kofi Annan
has picked for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kouchner, however, has always been full of talents _ and
surprises. Under his direction, the administration of Kosovo will
certainly be neither dull nor lacking in idealistic spirit. Whether
it will be effective is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Impulsive, provocative, frenetically energetic, teeming with
ideas, articulate, generous and courageous, Dr. Kouchner is also
blunt, abrasive, impatient, disorganized, opinionated and
quick-tempered.
</P>
<P>
   Now nearly 60, he still cultivates the cavalier manner of the
1960s rebel he once was. Many have found him hard to work with,
poor at delegating and short on political nous. He failed abysmally
both times he stood for a seat in France's National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   He can appear vain and media-obsessed. Still, whatever the
carpers say, he is regularly judged France's most popular
politician.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point as far as Kosovo goes, he knows the
international aid scene backwards. And for all the chaos he creates
around him, he has a knack of getting things done.
</P>
<P>
   It was he, in 1971, who blazed a trail in the provision of
humanitarian aid when he jointly founded Medecins sans Frontieres,
an organization that got volunteer doctors, most of them French, to
help people devastated by war and disaster in the most remote and
bloody parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   As a young gastroenterologist, he had gone with the
International Committee of the Red Cross to treat victims of
Nigeria's civil war. Appalled by what he saw, he determined on his
return to break the Red Cross volunteers' vow of silence that was
often the price paid to nasty governments to let them operate.
</P>
<P>
   If atrocities were to be stopped, it was as important to
dispense information as medicine, he insisted. So Medecins sans
Frontieres's aims were ``temoigner et soigner'' _ to ``bear
witness'' as well as to ``care for'' the sick and wounded.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three decades of brave action by the ``French
doctors,'' as they are often simply known, it is easy to forget
that it was only in 1988 that the U.N.'s General Assembly resolved
to give neutral organizations a right to ``free access to the
victims of natural catastrophes.'' And only in 1990 did it bless
the idea of ``emergency humanitarian corridors.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kouchner was the driving force behind both resolutions. And
he helped push through another, in the Security Council, after the
Gulf war, calling on Iraq to give international humanitarian groups
``immediate access to all those in need.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw the ensuing joint relief operation by France, Britain and
the United States in the Kurdish part of Iraq as a crucial step
towards the acceptance of an even more ambitious and controversial
notion for which he had long campaigned: where disasters are
imminent, there must be a universally accepted droit d'ingerence,
variously translated as a right of ``intervention'' or of
``interference.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kouchner reckons the phrase embraces a bit of both. He
proudly quotes what Nelson Mandela once told him: ``Thank you for
interfering in things that do not concern you.''
</P>
<P>
   With the aim of preventing mass suffering before it happens, he
also envisaged the creation under U.N. auspices of a multinational
``army without frontiers,'' empowered to intervene without the host
government's approval whenever a people was in imminent danger of
famine, civil war, or suchlike.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, he reckons, has prompted another stride towards
achieving that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Born of a Jewish father just after the Second World War began,
Dr. Kouchner dreams of a world where another Holocaust could never
happen.
</P>
<P>
   But his critics say his zeal for a droit d'ingerence (or, as he
prefers it, an obligation d'ingerence) is just another means to
slake his thirst for publicity: witness the film of him, back in
1992, as France's minister for health and humanitarian affairs,
lugging a sack of rice for starving Somalis up a beach.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kouchner would not deny that he plays to the gallery; nor is
it his fault that he is handsome and dashing; nor that his wife,
Christine Ockrent, is a famously glamorous former TV newscaster,
now magazine editor. He would argue simply that he needs the media
to help him do good.
</P>
<P>
   Handling Kosovo _ and the news about it _ is so far proving
easier for soldiers than for civilians. The lessons of Bosnia,
where buck-passing between the two groups often degenerated into
ugly transatlantic squabbles, are already being recalled.
</P>
<P>
   British, French and Swedish peacemakers in Bosnia ground their
teeth as politicians in Washington praised the American-led
soldiers policing Bosnia's internal partition lines _ contrasting
them with supposedly slothful European bureaucrats building a new
country where such lines were no longer meant to matter.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, too, the peacekeepers in uniform are getting going
far faster than the U.N.'s dawdling civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly five weeks after western forces marched in, their
commander _ General Sir Mike Jackson, a British paratrooper _ is
the only person exercising any real authority on behalf of the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
   What about the 3,000 policemen the U.N. is supposed to run? So
far, less than 100 have arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kouchner, who has already (rightly) trashed the idea that
the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) should serve as the core of a new
police force, will soon be chafing at the bit.
</P>
<P>
   Once he gets his various people in place, he will have to
coordinate the work of umpteen other agencies _ the EU, the World
Bank, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, the
democracy-builders of the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe _ in building a brave new province, while General Jackson
does his best to put the KLA under control.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of things, Dr. Bernard and General Mike look an odd
pair. But the success of Kosovo's rehabilitation will depend
largely on how they get along _ and how dexterously the doctor
manages a myriad of competing civilian agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Keep your fingers crossed. &QL; 
