 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, July 9.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RALLIES (Prokuplje, Yugoslavia) _ Protesters against
President Slobodan Milosevic gathered in the main square of this
small southern town Thursday night, while the government, which had
planned to stage a rally of its own in response, failed to do so.
By Carlotta Gall. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Leskovac, Yugoslavia) _ Voices of discontent:
Leskovac, a hotbed of anti-Milosevic sentiment, sent 25,000
reservists to Kosovo. They're back now, furious with the way the
government has treated them (little pay) and their families (little
food). By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-WORKERS-ALCOHOL (Wellington, South Africa) _ The
tradition of keeping workers drunk with free alcohol _ a way of
keeping them working for next to nothing _ has been illegal for
decades, although it continues on some farms. But even where the
system is ending heavy drinking goes on and new hardships emerge.
By Suzanne Daley. With map.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ASSESS (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ News analysis: If the
warring sides in the Congo's 11-month-old war sign a cease-fire
that won preliminary approval on Wednesday, it will be the first
time that they try to bring closure to the single event that has
destabilized all of Central Africa in the last half decade: the
genocide in Rwanda. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ As Ehud Barak, Israel's new prime
minister, prepares to fly off to Egypt on the first leg of an
ambitious mission to make regional peace, he is facing down
political squabbles on the home front. By Deborah Sontag.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Anaheim, Calif.) _ President Clinton wrapped up
his four-day tour of poverty in America with a visit to a
job-training program at a high school in the heart of the Watts
section of Los Angeles, then challenged corporate executives to
provide more support for preparing disadvantaged students for jobs
in the booming information economy. By Todd S. Purdum. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY-IMPACT (Washington) _ Amid the river of
dismissive reaction to President Clinton's travels this week to
highlight the limits of American prosperity, it is worth mulling
over an unconventional thought: It is possible that historians will
find more to praise in the Clinton anti-poverty record _ perhaps
even in this mad-dash trip itself _ than meets the eye. By Jason
DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-PANEL (Undated) _ After protests from Jewish
organizations, the House minority leader, Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.,
decided late Thursday to withdraw his appointment of an American
Muslim leader to a congressional counterterrorism commission, an
aide said. Salam Al-Marayati, executive director of the Muslim
Public Affairs Council in Los Angeles, had been named by Gephardt
in June to serve on the National Commission on Terrorism, a
10-member group charged with reviewing national policy on
preventing and punishing terrorism. By Laurie Goodstein. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BLACKOUT-POWER (New York) _ The blackout that stilled upper
Manhattan for nearly a day was a sort of distress call, a warning
that the electric power system in New York City and Long Island _
and, to a lesser degree, in other parts of the country _ is bumping
up against its physical limits, experts in the field cautioned. By
Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LUNG-SCANS (Undated) _ Death rates from lung cancer could be
greatly reduced if smokers and former smokers were routinely given
CT scans of their lungs, doctors report. The scans use a new
technique that is far more sensitive than conventional chest X-rays
and can detect tumors when they are small enough to be cured. By
Denise Grady. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ACCESS (Washington) _ A new federal survey shows that
while minority groups are increasingly gaining access to computers
and the Internet, the racial divide remains stark, with blacks and
Hispanics less than half as likely as whites to explore the net
from home, work or school. By David E. Sanger. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ Bob Squier has worked as a
consultant for Al Gore since the early '80s and is among the vice
president's half-dozen closest friends and advisers. So it looked
like a sure sign of panic last week when the Gore presidential
campaign hired Carter Eskew, Squier's former business partner and
protege, to whom he has not spoken in seven years, since their
bitter and public breakup. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-TAX (Undated) _ In a stunning defeat for the IRS' efforts
to restrict tax-avoidance strategies of foreign corporations, a
federal judge Thursday ruled in favor of Britain's National
Westminster Bank in its demand for a $180 million tax refund. By
David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS-OUTLOOK (Toulouse, France) _ In the giant hangers where
Airbus Industrie's single-aisle jetliners are assembled, only a
handful of workers can be found. Compared with the busy assembly
line in Renton, Wash., where Boeing Co. makes its narrow-body jets,
the atmosphere is almost ghostlike. But appearances are misleading.
By Laurence Zuckerman. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   COMMODITIES-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The prices of key
commodities, whose decline helped to restrain inflation the past
few years, are climbing again. By Jonathan Fuerbringer. With
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FRAUD-INDICT (New York) _ The Manhattan district attorney
announced an indictment Thursday of A.S. Goldmen &AMP; Co., a small New
Jersey brokerage firm, and 26 of its employees on charges that the
firm had orchestrated a securities fraud that cost thousands of
investors $100 million in losses. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ A cry for self-determination is
again sending shudders through world capitals. This time it's in
Kashmir, a lovely land coveted by autocratic Pakistan, most of it
occupied by 600,000 troops of democratic India. Commentary by
William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN (New York) _ If you were thinking about
going to see the Yankees and the Mets at Shea Stadium Friday night,
Saturday afternoon or Sunday afternoon, you'd better have a ticket
by now. If not, fuhgeddaboutit. All three games are sold out.
That's the bottom-line rebuttal to anyone who wondered, as both Joe
Torre and Bobby Valentine did for different reasons, if this
season's six Met-Yankee games, up from three in each of the
previous two seasons, were three too many. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WOMEN-HAMM (Los Angeles) _ As much as Mia Hamm continues to
protest, ``This World Cup is not about me,'' the more it becomes
apparent that, yes, it is about her. She is the name and face that
everyone knows. It is her jersey that the little girls wear. It is
her lack of scoring in the last three games that has everyone
wondering whether the Americans are capable of beating the surging
Chinese on Saturday in the World Cup final before 90,000 fans at
the Rose Bowl. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-ART-AUCTION (London) _ Sales records were broken one after
another for Old Master paintings, medieval manuscripts and antiques
of every variety here at Christie's on Thursday as more than
three-and-a-half hours of feverish bidding erupted over a trove of
treasures looted by the Nazis and returned to the Rothschild family
this year by the Austrian government. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   PEONY-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ The peony is a hardy flower. Its
theatrical counterpart has survived 400 years in China and now a
trip across the Pacific. It has been thwarted by bureaucrats at
home, shortened and modernized abroad. Now, as ``The Peony
Pavilion,'' it faces another test: maximization. Placed at the
center of Lincoln Center Festival '99, Tang Xianzu's wandering epic
of love, death and the supernatural is testing the endurance of
both its players and its audience: 6 episodes, 20 hours, the cycle
to be repeated three times this month. By Bernard Holland. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
