<HEADER>
A4062 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-DBACKS-HNS     07-09 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DBACKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pitching help is Astros' trade target: Page 7B.
</P>
<P>
   Astros
</P>
<P>
   Associated PressThe Astros' Scott Elarton, who struggled in his
second start of the season, adjusts his cap after issuing a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Astros tumble to D-Backs in 11th
</P>
<P>
   Late attack not enough in 8-7 loss
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ Extra-inning games are a battle of the bullpens, and
that's usually bad news for the Arizona Diamondbacks, who have
blown 15 save opportunities this season.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday they were outdone by the Astros' relievers, who
surrendered two extra-inning leads en route to a demoralizing 8-7
loss at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams' 11th-inning RBI single off Brian Williams put the
Astros out of their misery four hours and 16 minutes after the
first pitch. It also wiped out a huge performance by Derek Bell,
who twice delivered clutch hits in the late innings.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's two-out single to center chased home Craig Biggio with
what might have been the winning run in the top of the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio keyed that rally with a hustling, two-out double off
embattled reliever Gregg Olson. Biggio's line drive to left had
single written all over it when it left the bat, but Biggio never
slowed down as he rounded first and dived into second base.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of many big hits for the Astros on a night that began
miserably for the offense and ended terribly for the bullpen. The
Astros scored in each of the last six innings, tying the game with
two outs in the ninth and taking one-run leads in the 10th and
11th.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had two hits through the first five innings, and they
stranded runners in scoring position with less than two outs in the
sixth, seventh and eighth innings. But their hit-or-miss attack
turned dangerously efficient in the late innings, when they had
their way with the Diamondbacks' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   After Bell's two-out double in the ninth tied the game, capping
a rally from deficits of 3-0 and 5-2, Carl Everett led off the 10th
inning with a triple to right field and scored on Bill Spiers'
sacrifice fly for a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks also had their moments in extra innings,
scoring off Astros closer Billy Wagner on Damian Miller's two-out
RBI double in the bottom of the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first run Wagner had allowed since May 20 _ a string
of 20 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Elarton was allowed a more liberal pitch count in his
second start of the season, but he didn't last any longer than in
his previous four-inning stint. The Diamondbacks managed three runs
in four innings against Elarton, who surrendered seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton had good movement on his fastball, as evidenced by his
five strikeouts, but he didn't have the command he regularly
displayed as a reliever. The Diamondbacks put runners on base in
each of Elarton's four innings and scored in the third on Matt
Williams' two-out double to center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks loaded the bases with two walks and single to
lead off the fourth, and the damage was done by a familiar foe. Jay
Bell, who was 9-for-14 with four RBIs in the three-game series,
drove home a pair of runs with his fifth double of the series.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jay Bell's double in the 11th that tied the game and set
the stage for Matt Williams' game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, who was scheduled to throw between 75 and 80 pitches,
finished the fourth inning at 87 pitches and surrendered the mound
to reliever Joe Slusarski with the Astros trailing by three runs.
Elarton has a 5.63 ERA in two starts after 27 consecutive relief
outings to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks starter Armando Reynoso retired 15 of the first 18
batters he faced and worked around leadoff doubles in the first and
second before the Astros finally broke through in the sixth on
Biggio's eighth home run _ a solo shot to left field. Biggio is
hitting .325 over his last 33 games, raising his season average
from .267 to .289 during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell followed Biggio's home run with a double off the top
of the left-field fence, but was stranded at second base after Jeff
Bagwell and Everett grounded out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored a run, but couldn't force a tie in a
close-but-no-cigar kind of seventh inning. After Spiers reached on
a walk, Richard Hidalgo hit two balls into the left field seats
that were within inches of being game-tying home runs. Instead,
Hidalgo settled for a broken-bat RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks right fielder Tony Womack stole a hit _ and
possibly an RBI _ away from Ricky Gutierrez with a diving catch of
looping liner. After relief pitcher Greg Swindell walked pinch
hitter Tim Bogar to give the Astros runners at first and second
with two out, rookie Byung-Hyun Kim got Biggio to foul out to end
the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
