<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANAGED-CARE-$ADV11-C     07-09 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-CARE-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE OPENING BATTLE OVER 'PATIENTS' BILL OF RIGHTS'
 &HT;    550&AMP;add. With MANAGED-DATA. For release Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With control over the delivery of medical care at
stake, Congress this week takes up legislation aimed at curtailing
the power of the health insurance industry and managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over a ``patients' bill of rights'' pits some of the
most influential special interest groups against each another, and
both political parties are mindful of how the issue could play in
the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are doctors and consumers. They want to see the
managed care industry reined in, with doctors gaining more control
over treating patients and patients gaining more access to care.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are insurers, health maintenance
organizations, and business interests. The insurers and HMOs worry
they'll lose control of managed care, causing medical costs to
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups worry that more federal regulation will increase
premiums and mean more Americans without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   When debate starts this week in the Senate, the biggest fights
are likely to be over:
</P>
<P>
   _ Who is covered by the bill.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether it will guarantee access to physicians outside of
managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   _ To what extent patients will be able to appeal decisions
regarding their coverage, such as whether to pay for a specific
procedure or whether to be treated in or out of a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether patients will be able to sue if such decisions result
in injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican position, basically, is to limit the number of
people covered by the bill, curb the use of physicians outside of
managed care organizations, make it difficult for patients to
appeal if they're denied coverage or specific treatments, and
prohibit patients from suing over medical decisions _ whether those
decisions are made by an insurance company, an HMO or a business
which is self-insured.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic position is just the opposite: broaden the bill
to include all 160 million people covered by private insurance;
give patients and doctors wide latitude over medical treatment; and
allow patients to sue if a coverage decision causes harm.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Democrats see themselves as benefitting most from
the issue. With polls showing public unease with HMOs, Democrats
have given passage of a patients' bill of rights top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have sought to avoid a showdown. One reason is that
they know whatever position they take will offend at least one of
their usual constituencies: doctors, insurers or the business
community.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, the first chamber to take up the issue, plans a
final vote on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the battleground was expected to be a series of
Democratic amendments aimed at strengthening a Republican bill
adopted on a party-line vote in March by the Senate Health,
Education and Labor Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But in a surprise move, GOP leaders decided last week to use a
Democratic bill as a starting point, with the final amendment being
offered by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Senate could adopt all of the Democratic
provisions early in the week, and then sweep them away by adopting
the weaker GOP version of the bill as a final substitute amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that final vote that counts,'' said Dr. Nancy W. Dickey,
immediate past president of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The AMA last week launched a $200,000-plus advertising and
lobbying campaign targeting key senators.
</P>
<P>
   Substituting the GOP version of the bill for the stronger bill
``falls short'' of what the doctors' want, Dickey said. ``We would
not consider that an acceptable bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, AMA officials said they are concerned that the GOP
tactic may confuse the public by allowing senators to vote for
popular patient protections, but then tell their constituents that
those provisions just weren't included in the final bill.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers, who also have a series of targeted ads circulating the
country, are mounting their strongest effort to defeat legislation
since they defeated President Clinton's health reform proposal in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Their message is that the Democratic bill is another
big-government power play whose winners would be bureaucrats and
trial lawyers. The losers, they say, would be businesses and
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These so-called 'patients rights' would add new federal
government regulations costing billions of dollars that would be
passed on to families and businesses who simply can't afford it,''
said David Lack, president of the Council for Affordable Health
Insurance, an insurance industry group.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Kahn, president of the Health Insurance Association of
America, pointed to an April study by the Congressional Budget
Office that predicted that the Democratic bill would increase
insurance premiums about 6.1 percent when fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Each percentage point increase could mean another 200,000
Americans would be uninsured, the CBO estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens in the Senate, the House also is
gearing up for a battle over a patients' bill of rights. The
political landscape there is even more complicated, because three
sets of bills are competing.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership is backing a series of eight bills,
which together resemble the GOP Senate version, that have passed a
labor subcommittee. But competition for GOP support is coming from
a tougher bipartisan proposal sponsored by Rep. Charles Norwood, a
Georgia Republican. A key provision of the Norwood bill would be
the right of patients to sue insurers over treatment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Democratic alternative _ a companion to the
Democratic Senate version _ has been offered by Rep. John Dingell
of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the House Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has indicated he hopes the
House will consider a bill before the August recess.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
