A4187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANAGED-DATA-$ADV11-C     07-09 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-DATA-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With MANAGED-CARE. For release Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here are some of the major areas of disagreement
between Democrats and Republicans regarding the ``patients' bill of
rights'' being voted on this week in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   WHO IS COVERED?
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill limits coverage to about 48 million people
in self-funded employer-sponsored health plans. It would not cover
most people in managed care plans such as health maintenance
organizations. The Democratic bill would cover about 160 million
people, virtually everyone covered by a private health insurance or
managed care plan.
</P>
<P>
   HOW ARE APPEALS HANDLED?
</P>
<P>
   Republicans allow limited external reviews in cases alleging
that treatment was denied even though it was considered a medical
necessity. However, the definition of ``medical necessity'' would
be determined by the insurance plan. Reviews could take up to 65
days. Democrats want a broader external review by an independent
panel that would be required to report in a few days depending on
the severity of the case.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ABOUT SUING FOR DAMAGES?
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans have fought against allowing patients to sue
their insurer or HMO for decisions that cause medical injury.
Democrats view such damage liability as one of the key provisions
in their bill.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ABOUT ACCESS TO SPECIALISTS?
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan would allow limited access to specialists
who are not in a managed care plan if patients pay an extra fee and
get approval from the plan each time. Denials could not be
appealed. The Democratic bill would allow patients with specialty
care needs direct access to specialists after an initial referral
from the plan. It would allow referral denials to be appealed to an
independent reviewer.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
