<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suit seeks Southwestern Bell refunds
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. allegedly owes
its customers millions of dollars in refunds because since 1991 it
improperly collected a surcharge on monthly bills to pay its
municipal franchise fees, according to a Cameron County lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell spokesman Bill Maddox said, ``We strongly deny
the allegations in this case, and, since it is continuing
litigation, that should be the extent of our comment at this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on whether the plaintiffs should be granted
class-action status is scheduled to begin July 29 in Brownsville.
If granted, it would bring in most of the company's Texas
customers, including those in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges breach of contract, fraud, unjust enrichment
and violations of the state's Deceptive Trade Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   The suit does not say how much money would be refunded if the
plaintiffs win, nor does it ask for specific damages. But a lawyer
for the plaintiffs, Mike Lynn of Dallas, said the amount involved
is ``well over $100 million.''
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Southwestern Bell collects 94 cents a month per
residential line for municipal franchise fee payments and $2.84 a
month per business line, a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the Public Utility Commission last year showed that
telephone utilities pay cities about $150 million a year. Most of
that comes from Southwestern Bell, which has about three-fourths of
the telephone lines in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The same survey reported that Southwestern Bell paid Austin
about $8 million a year; Houston, $35.8 million; Dallas, $20.6
million; San Antonio, $11.4 million; and El Paso, $4.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
