<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My dad enjoys a day watching the ponies run
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSSIER CITY, La. _ My brother and I brought my dad here to
watch the ponies run, a belated Father's Day present for a man who
doesn't get out much anymore, since a botched medical procedure
nine years ago left him disabled far too young.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to my dad is a tragedy. He was smart and talented,
making his living as a commercial artist and gathering a following
in Deep East Texas for his Western art _ pen-and-ink drawings of
cowboys and horses, acrylic paintings of Indians and old barns. He
was a fine artist who dreamed of giving up his day job painting
signs. That is, until he came down with a benign tumor on his
pituitary gland at the age of 58. The tumor threatened his
eyesight, so it had to be removed. Surgery couldn't get it all, so
radiation therapy was advised.
</P>
<P>
   He was overdosed by radiation, and his temporal lobe was
destroyed. Another brain surgery was necessary to save his life.
Before it was over, he was completely disabled, dependent on
medication and my mother. This happened to a man who hadn't spent a
night in the hospital since losing his tonsils as a child, who just
a few months earlier had spent a weekend in the summer heat helping
me build a shed, his endurance outlasting mine with ease.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors responsible for the mistake settled out of court for
enough money to allow my parents to live comfortably but not
lavishly. It's a poor trade. My dad takes a host of medicines each
day, everything from blood-thinning drugs to stop the clots in his
legs to anti-seizure medicine to keep his brain in check. He walks
with a cane and has trouble remembering things that happened an
hour or a day ago, though he can still recount incidents from three
decades past.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, he is happy most days, though his skin is on fire
from constant itching, a reaction to the drugs that doctors can't
seem to alleviate. He still spends much of his day drawing
caricatures, Western scenes and cartoons, some of which make it
into print from time to time. He still has talent, certainly more
than the average person, but nothing like what he had before all
this happened.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't complain much to his three sons and is thrilled when
we visit. He reads the newspaper faithfully and brags on me and my
brothers far too often. His tragedy and courage in the face of it
inspires me at times, though it also angers me, too. I have little
sympathy for those who would stop or greatly restrict people from
recovering damages when injured by negligence, because medical
negligence is what disabled my father, ended his career and nearly
put my parents under financially. Put a price on that if you will.
I can't.
</P>
<P>
   It was my idea to come to the races. The first plan was for my
brother, who came up to give my mother a break and a chance to go
home and visit her mother and siblings, to bring him down here to
see me. Then I realized the ponies had started running at Louisiana
Downs. My dad loves horses, has spent decades drawing and painting
them. Let's go see the ponies, I suggested.
</P>
<P>
   They watched while I gambled and largely lost. My dad sat
quietly, asking which horse I had placed my $3 on and then rooting
for my nag to win. Most times my horses finished out of the money,
but it didn't matter. He reveled in being out of the house and in
watching these fine animals fly through the mud. He reminded me
that he used to ride horses in Wyoming and Missouri. I knew that,
of course. I'm prejudiced, but in his prime, nobody could draw a
pen-and-ink sketch of a horse as well as he could.
</P>
<P>
   A fight broke out about halfway through the afternoon, outside
on the bleachers where it was steamy. We were inside in the air
conditioning, raptly watching the scuffle as if it was on TV. Two
guys went at it for about a minute, swinging wild roundhouse
punches that rarely connected while their girlfriends/wives watched
and contemplated joining in. My dad made some remark about how he
always enjoyed boxing, but I couldn't get him to lay down a bet
with me on who would win. Finally, security guards ambled up and
escorted the miscreants out of the facility. The horse races seemed
a bit tame after that.
</P>
<P>
   We left early and ate seafood at one of my favorite spots, Ralph
and Kakoos. My dad insisted on paying, and I let him. I left to
head back home, wondering if he would take up his drawing tablet
and try to capture what he saw on that hot, steamy Saturday
afternoon. I figure it's even money if he'll try to draw the horses
or the amateur boxers.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
