<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing tennis just another way for me to court disaster
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I played tennis last night and, of course, the
results were predictable: I had to be carried off the court.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as if I have been carried off every playing field but
the ones at Eton and only because I've never been there.
</P>
<P>
   So it really wasn't surprising when, after making a particularly
remarkable serve _ remarkable for how far out of bounds it flew _ a
cramp in my calf sent me to the court in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   For my own part, I would have stayed there forever in my pain
until buzzards began circling, but progress and tennis must go on.
</P>
<P>
   The four septuagenarians in the next court who had been playing
tennis in the sun for, oh, six or seven hours and who were almost
about to break a sweat _ maybe, drug me off the court as they might
had a dying water buffalo suddenly expired at the midcourt line.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of my doubles foursome were appropriately
somber and concerned. Frank Dias said he would have been willing to
help me stretch my leg out if not for the fact that doing so might
have entailed looking up my shorts. Actually, I don't blame him a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't really want help, anyway. I was more into feeling
pitiful.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling pitiful, you see, because I had just come to a horrible
realization. Other than Frank, I really didn't know the other
players in our group. I got paired with a man (poor guy) I'd never
met before. He introduced himself as Jimmy Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   I would have sworn Frank told me that Jimmy was 38 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly he played like he was 38. Being a few years younger
than me he was quicker, could hit the ball a bit harder and
certainly his serve was far better than mine.
</P>
<P>
   Still and all, while I couldn't quite keep up with the snappy
38-year-old _ he was younger, after all _ I didn't do too badly
considering his younger age. If I had been just a few years younger
_ OK, maybe 10 or 12 years younger _ I could have been a good
match.
</P>
<P>
   I kept telling myself that I was glad this young guy was playing
with me instead of against me.
</P>
<P>
   And then I found out I had made a small mistake. Somehow in my
mind I had transposed the numbers. Jimmy Nolan isn't 38 years old,
he is 83.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-three?
</P>
<P>
   Prostrate on the court, trying to hide the pain, that number
kept coming up in my mind.
</P>
<P>
   All Jimmy said was: ``A leg cramp? I've never had one of those.
Does it hurt?''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy is 83 and he has been playing tennis at least twice a week
since he was nine. That is almost three-quarters of a century of
volleys, serves and running to the net. And not one leg cramp in
all that time.
</P>
<P>
   There is a God, and he favors Jimmy.
</P>
<P>
   This morning I am quite sure that Jimmy doesn't have a single
pain in his body after our match. I can barely walk, I have a
couple of nasty bruises on my hand from falling on the court and my
ego has been damaged beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   I hope I am still playing tennis when I am 83 and, if I can make
it, I have no doubts that Jimmy will be in the foursome, running a
bit faster, hitting the ball a bit harder and not worrying a bit
about getting a leg cramp.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
