<HEADER>
A4202 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN10-COX     07-09 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is government powerless to stop hate-filled Web pages?
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Vice President Al Gore claimed he invented the
Internet before Americans attacked the Internet for inspiring the
killers in Littleton, Colo., and last weekend's hate-crime spree in
Illinois and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   This was unfortunate timing on Gore's part. But his invention
should not be linked to these tragedies for two reasons. One, he
did not invent the Internet. Two, there is no controlling authority
over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   There were calls to ``do something'' about the Internet after it
was revealed that the two teens who killed their fellow Columbine
High School students were Internet users who had a Web site with
links to sites that espoused violence and racism.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is learned that Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, a 21-year-old
college student who went on a three-day hate-inspired killing spree
in Illinois and Indiana, also had Internet ties.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had been a devoted advocate of the World Church of the
Creator, an Internet-based white supremacist group that is said to
be one of the fastest-growing hate groups in America.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that the World Church of the Creator has expanded so
rapidly has to be because of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The World Church of the Creator apparently is the creation of
Matthew F. Hale, 27, who lives in the pleasant suburban Illinois
home of his retired-policeman father.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever demons infect the brain of Pontifex Maximus Hale are
open to inspection to one and all on his Internet Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Hale's message of hatred for Jews and people of color _ mud
people, he calls them _ struck a chord with Smith, who joined
Hale's Web church.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Hale is upfront about his hatred for Jews and
nonwhites. But he is careful to say that his church really stands
for love _ love of white people. Hale concludes that his church
must hate Jews and nonwhites because they hate white people.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith, a good student and the privileged son of a doctor,
was named as the gunman who killed two and wounded nine others over
three days, Hale claimed Smith was no longer a member of his church
even though Smith had been named ``1998 Creator of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   Frighteningly, Hale's message of hatred and his call for RAHOWA
_ Racial Holy War _ has attracted enough followers to establish 41
World Church of the Creator outposts in 17 states.
</P>
<P>
   An oddball hate-filled supremacist operating out of a room in
his father's house could never attract such a large following of
like-minded sickos so quickly without the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Government censorship of Internet material is not the solution
to the shootings in Colorado, Indiana and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, government censorship of what Americans say,
write and publish _ even on the Internet _ is fraught with
constitutional hazards. How much different is it, if at all, from
government censorship of speech or of the press? It's hard to tell.
</P>
<P>
   More practically, the government can't stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's claims, scientists at the Rand Corporation more
than 30 years ago came up with the concept for a communication
system that would withstand a nuclear attack. With no central
authority, it would be be decentralized down to the level of each
individual anywhere in the world attempting to communicate. Even
with the nation smoldering in ruins, the Internet would keep on
sending information.
</P>
<P>
   Education and the constant exposure of Internet filth peddlers
to the sunshine of public scrutiny offer the highest likelihood of
public protection.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, however, should never be considered a safe haven
for law-breakers. Crimes committed on the Internet should be
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Education, public outrage and new forms of law enforcement are
needed to curb Internet rot.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
