<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD10-COX     07-09 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good equipment costs big bucks
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I have found no way to get around the fact that
building furniture is an expensive hobby.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly if you're going to create a houseful of it, you'll
save money in the long run. But setting up a reasonably
well-equipped shop is a very expensive proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The only way I know to make it cheaper would be to eschew
machinery and use nothing but hand tools. You will certainly get
into good physical shape that way, and if you are quite young and
working wood only in your spare time, you might get the houseful of
furniture built before you're too old to lift a No. 22 plane.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks don't seem to be able to grasp the concept that good
equipment is expensive. For instance, this query from a woodworker
in San Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   ``I need some help locating and evaluating a used table saw,''
he writes. ``I can't spend more than a couple of hundred dollars,
but I want something good and usable, perhaps something I can add
to (extensions, fences, etc.).''
</P>
<P>
   Right, and when you solve that problem, see if you can find the
descendants of those Indians who sold Manhattan Island for $25 or
so and see if they'll take a couple of hundred for it, too. But let
the gentleman continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can any of you give me some guidance on what brands to look
for, what brands to stay away from, what problems to watch out for,
how to tell a good table saw from a bad one, what kind of problems
are not worth trying to fix and what are?''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly.
</P>
<P>
   1. You can't buy a usable table saw for $200. Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   2. The leading brands of home-shop table saws are Delta,
Powermatic and Jet.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stay away from brands that offer a new table saw for less
than $750.
</P>
<P>
   4. To tell a good table saw from a bad one: First, kick it. If
it doesn't wiggle and your toe hurts, continue. If it jumps and
your toe doesn't hurt, forget it. Second: Set up the saw for a
crosscut. Check the blade for squareness to the table. Take a small
piece of scrap wood in the neighborhood of a foot long and two
inches wide and draw a line from one end to the other to identify
the face side. Now cut it more or less in half. Turn one half
upside down (so that the line doesn't show) and put the cut edges
back together. If it's a snug fit, the saw is well-aligned. If
there's a gap at one edge of the mating, the saw blade and the
miter slot are out of alignment. They can be realigned, but the
question is whether they will stay that way. If it's a Delta,
Powermatic or Jet, they probably will.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that all other brands of table saws are poor.
Most Taiwanese saws, which will be the bulk of the other brands
priced comparably to these, suffer chiefly from relatively lax
quality control. Some will be fine, some not so fine. There are a
lot of really great European saws, but they tend to be considerably
more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Our correspondent continues:
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance: there is an ad in the local paper for a 10'' saw
with a 52'' jet fence for $750. It's a 5-year-old, Craftsman
contractor saw which has been modified by the owner. He added the
fence, extensions and a pedestal. How can I tell if he did a decent
job making the modifications, or should I stay away from this
one?''
</P>
<P>
   Stay far away.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the used table saws you see advertised are Craftsman
models. If you can find one that's 30 years old or so and in good
condition, it might be a good buy. The newer they are the poorer
they are. In my experience they are cheaply made, woefully
underpowered, and incapable of staying in alignment.
</P>
<P>
   This is why there are so many on the used market. They are
relatively inexpensive and people who think they will be adequate
buy one, find out they have made a mistake, and try to unload it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
