<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-TURBULENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURBULENCE INJURES 63, PROMPTING NEWARK JET TO LAND IN BERMUDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixty-three people, including four flight attendants, were
slightly injured yesterday when a Continental Air Lines jet flying
from Newark, N.Y., to Puerto Rico encountered severe turbulence
just south of Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   The jet made an unscheduled landing in Bermuda, where the
passengers and crew members were treated at a hospital for head and
neck injuries. Only one passenger, a middle-aged woman whose name
was not immediately released, was hospitalized. She had complained
of chest pains.
</P>
<P>
   Karla Villalon, a spokeswoman for Continental Air Lines, said
Flight 743 took off from Newark at 12:20 p.m. EDT and encountered
heavy turbulence in midflight at 29,000 feet, about 180 miles south
of Bermuda. She said she did not know whether all the passengers
were wearing seat belts during the turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities in Bermuda said they received a distress call
from the plane shortly before 3 p.m. and the plane landed at 4
p.m.at the Bermuda airport.
</P>
<P>
   The injured passengers were taken by three ambulances, a bus and
taxis to King Edward VII Memorial Hospital, the island's 220-bed
acute-care hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passengers are mainly complaining of neck pains, cuts and
bruises, but we see nothing immediately life threatening,'' said
Sheila G. Manderson, the executive director of the hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
