<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      07-09 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION GIVES HEADACHES TO BRAZILIAN PHONE CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Like many people who tried to place
telephone calls as competition in Brazil's long-distance market
gradually opened this week, Antonio Carlos do Amaral Maia felt like
slamming down the receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried Brasilia, Rio Preto and Aracatuba without success,''
said Amaral, listing cities he could not reach. Amaral, 34, a
bankruptcy lawyer with a small practice here added, ``I'll bet this
chaos will result in these new phone companies being nationalized
within a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Amaral's lament was echoed by other Brazilian customers of phone
companies including MCI Worldcom and Telefonica SA of Spain, which
have bought pieces of Brazil's national phone system. After
competition was allowed in several regions of Brazil last weekend,
the long-distance network nearly collapsed in confusion and
technical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 25-30 percent of long-distance calls have been
completed successfully since companies began vying for clients,
about half the call-completion rate under the old system, according
to Anatel, the government's telecommunications regulatory agency.
During some peak hours, only a fifth of long-distance calls were
completed.
</P>
<P>
   As individual consumers and corporate clients became
increasingly angry this week, the companies involved in the
tumultuous transfer to a competitive system scrambled to repair the
glitches. But the service breakdown has raised questions about how
the government has handled privatization in general.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso told the
telephone companies that they had 72 hours, or through Saturday
night, to fix the service. The companies said they would meet the
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In Sao Paulo, where 40 percent of Brazil's phone calls are made,
the criticism has been especially acute. Residents had been fuming
for months anyway because of problems with the local phone system,
which was taken over last year by Telefonica. As Telefonica rushed
to install more than two million phone lines this year, adding to
the city's five million lines, the pressure on the system resulted
in phones going mute for days, misaddressed bills and crossed lines
with several discussions taking place.
</P>
<P>
   The government responded by fining Telefonica, together with the
company responsible for service in Rio de Janeiro, three million
reais, or $1.7 million. Now, because of the latest difficulties,
authorities have said the penalties may grow larger, with
Telefonica and other companies facing fines up to 40 million reais,
or $23 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilians expected more from privatization. ``There were
promises of services worthy of the First World,'' said CassiaMaria
Candido, 30, a primary school teacher who complained this week of
troubles when calling her mother, who lives in the interior of the
state of Mato Grosso do Sul. ``We now pay First World prices for
Third World service.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's response has been marked by differences within
Cardoso's Cabinet over who should administer the fines. The
communications minister, Joao Pimenta da Veiga, said the regulatory
agency should be responsible for fining the companies. But Renan
Calheiros, the justice minister, contended it was his
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the companies have blamed each other for the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within our region we tested our networks, prepared for the
changes and everything is close to normal,'' said Stael Prata Silva
Filho, the vice president responsible for residential service at
Telefonica's Brazilian unit. ``The problems are originating mostly
at Embratel,'' Prata said, referring to the Brazilian long-distance
carrier operated by MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a massive change into competition never before seen on
this scale,'' said Purificacion Carpinteyro, an Embratel
spokeswoman. ``We are all part of the network and were all
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carpinteyro said Brazil's decision to switch into a system
of long-distance competition, in which the consumer chooses the
carrier with each call, through a code system, is more wide
reaching than similar systems in countries like Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the difficulties have been traced to switches, a
technical term used to describe a computer program that routes
calls to other computers. Because some switches were not prepared
for the new system and others were overloaded by heavy traffic,
confusion ensued, Ms. Carpinteyro said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the difficulties, deregulation has brought benefits to
the telecommunications system that would have been unthinkable a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The scarcity of phone lines under the old state-run system led
to the creation of a secondary market in telephone lines that were
bought and sold depending on demand. Before the privatization of
Telebras, the state company, some 10 million Brazilians were on a
waiting list for a phone. Now, a telephone line can be purchased
for about $500 on the secondary market, compared with as much as
$5,000 three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, the number of lines is expected to rise to 33 for every
100 people, up from about 13 lines for every 100 today, according
to Marcos Silveira, head of the telecommunications practice at the
Sao Paulo office of KPMG, the consulting and accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brazilians are learning that such expansion does not
happen flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   One prominent critic, Elio Gaspari, a newspaper columnist,
nominated Jar Jar Binks, the lanky Star Wars character, to head the
telecommunications regulatory agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the best intentions, but as he himself admits, he's
clumsy,'' Gaspari wrote in the Folha de Sao Paulo. ``At least that
makes him agreeable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
