<SLUG> BC-BBO-TV-ALLSTAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS WILL ALL BE STEPPING UP TO THE PLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- No shortage of All-Star coverage this weekend. Anytime
a television producer can legitimately claim a game is not really a
game but rather a ``show,'' then get ready for a veritable bonanza
of programming.
</P>
<P>
   Fox airs the game Tuesday night. ESPN has the Home Run Derby
Monday night. And given the fact that the last All-Star Game this
millennium will be played right here at Fenway, our hometown
stations are stepping up to the plate with live updates, special
guests, and the usual assortment of feature stories. Remember, it's
not all about quality; it's about quantity as well.
</P>
<P>
   Take Fox. The network plans to triple everything. Instead of
eight cameras, Fox plans to use at least 24, including cameras
attached atop The Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of two announcers in the broadcast booth, Fox plans to
use six. And not just any six. Joe Buck, the boy wonder of baseball
play-by-play, is calling the game with Tim McCarver, arguably the
best color commentator in the game. Bob Brenly is also in the
booth, while Steve Lyons works the American League dugout, Keith
Olbermann covers the National League dugout, and Thom Brennaman is
in the star-studded stands.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Michael Weisman justifies the increases in staff and
equipment. ``This will be one of the greatest assemblages of
baseball talents at one time in the history of the All-Star Game,''
Weisman said. ``There will never be a moment like this again. Think
about it. There will be 50 of the greatest legends walking to home
plate from center field. Then there will be the current All-Stars.
They will be followed by Ted Williams throwing out the first pitch
to none other than Carlton Fisk. We're talking goose bumps here. It
will the field of dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Weisman is right. The game will be one of those dream
assignments for producers; anywhere they assign a camera, there's a
story. The players, the legends, the game, and, of course, Fenway.
``This is not a game,'' Weisman said. ``It's a show.''
</P>
<P>
   Weisman is not the only producer licking his chops. ESPN airs
the Home Run Derby live at 8 p.m. Monday night. Chris Berman calls
the show, along with Joe Morgan and New York Mets catcher Mike
Piazza. Stuart Scott and Rich Eisen work as on-field reporters.
Charley Steiner calls the Derby for ESPN radio.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN2 airs the first-ever All-Star Futures game, featuring top
minor league prospects, Sunday at 5 p.m. Dave Ryan, Ray Knight, and
Peter Gammons call the action.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, ESPN's ``Baseball Tonight'' airs at 7:30 p.m., and
after the Home Run Derby, the station will air taped coverage of
the celebrity hitting challenge, beginning at 10. The one-hour show
will feature actors such as Kevin Costner and Matt Damon, and
retired All-Stars Fred Lynn, Rico Petrocelli, Jim Rice, Dwight
Evans, George Brett, and Andre Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   CNN/SI airs an All-Star special throughout the day of the game,
starting at 12:30 p.m., hosted by Bob Lorenz and former St. Louis
Cardinals shortstop Ozzie Smith. The show features an interview by
Smith with Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra. CNN/SI's ``Page One''
features an essay by Jim Huber on Fenway Park Saturday at 1:30 p.m.
CNN/SI's ``Sports Sunday'' airs live from Fenway at 10:30 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1217EDT &QL; 
