<SLUG> BC-NOSTRADAMUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NOT ENDING YET, NOSTRADAMUS DEFENDER ASSURES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Rest easy. Predictions, circulated worldwide
and attributed to the 16th-century seer Nostradamus, that the world
will end this month are off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   By 1,700 years.
</P>
<P>
   That assurance comes from the head of the Nostradamus Society of
America, who happens to be a Fort Worth blues drummer and part-time
property title researcher named Vaughn Bean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset because Nostradamus never said the world was going
to end in July,'' said Bean, who launched the ``society'' on the
Internet's World Wide Web after spending years researching a
self-published (at Kinko's) tome on the French astrologer,
``Remember the Future: The Prophecies of Nostradamus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the world was going to end in 3797.''
</P>
<P>
   The fuss has been stirred up by a bestselling book in France by
fashion designer Paco Rabanne and numerous articles in the British
news media that cite a Nostradamus prediction that a ``King of
Terror'' will materialize from the sky in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bean's calming words have been picked up and broadcast in
interviews from Sydney to London. Hours after discussing the matter
in a late late radio talk show, syndicated nationally here, he
appeared eager to take advantage of any notoriety that comes his
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anything wrong in trying to make something of
myself,'' said Bean, 42, who became a drummer in a succession of
rock and blues bands after graduating from Texas Christian
University with a degree in business and marketing. ``I'm like a
surfer. I'm going to ride this wave as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   A fellow musician friend crafted the Web site,
www.nostradamususa.com, which has attracted ``less than 100
members'' but launched the unknown, ``self-appointed'' director of
a made-up society as some kind of authority on the ever-popular
French clairvoyant. Call it the magic of cyberspace. The BBC has
rung him up three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two and a half years ago, I realized there were Edgar Cayce
Society Web sites and George Washington Society Web sites but not a
Nostradamus Society Web site,'' Bean said. ``So I decided to fill
the void.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a historical society _ not a cult with a ranch house full
of young women somewhere,'' he quickly added with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   A lanky 6-foot-2 with wavy brown hair, Bean came dressed in
black shirt, black jeans and cowboy boots. He sipped a cold drink
at a west side coffeehouse, paused and then qualified his passion
for Nostradamus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not some whacked-out, obsessive person,'' he explained.
``I was the guy who stayed up all night for years and years
(studying) because I knew this was going to be big. Now that it's
hot, I've got to stay on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's staying on top of are four-line verses, known as
quatrains, barely fathomable in French, let alone in English
translation, that since their first publication four centuries ago
have never gone out of print. Their evergreen appeal, skeptics
assert, stems from the fact that they are so vague they can be
related to virtually any case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often what is taken as prophetic is only due to coincidence,''
wrote one would-be debunker, Paul Kurtz, a professor emeritus at
State University of New York at Buffalo. ``His quatrains have been
adapted to all sorts of circumstances in every time period.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Kurtz's views, Bean leaned back and responded with
the mild rejoinder: ``I would call that person a skeptic.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the world is not facing an immediate apocalypse, Bean
tells interviewers that the July 1999 prediction seems to refer to
the current conflict between India and Pakistan, as well as the
tension between North and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Of Nostradamus' 942 prophecies, only seven come with dates. Of
these, just one falls in the 20th century, which makes the ``King
of Terror'' quatrain all the more significant, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Eastern Hills High grad doesn't know old French, let alone
the modern tongue, relying instead on a variety of translations to
base his interpretation of Nostradamus' murky forecasts. In fact,
knowing the language could be a handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, the French authors do the worst job,'' Bean
said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
