<HEADLINE>
TEXTURES COULD MAKE THE WEB MORE FUN  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JULY 12, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By CATHERINE ZANDONELLA  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble with shopping on the Internet is that you can't
touch anything. Fortunately, that may be about to change with a
motorized computer mouse that can give Web surfers the sensation of
texture _ or other physical attributes _ of items pictured on the
Net.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to last week's Web99 convention in San Francisco were
able to test out the ''Feel It'' mouse: running the cursor over a
picture of a tennis racket let a user feel the tautness of the
strings. You could also feel the texture of a pair of corduroy
jeans or test-drive a car, feeling how it handles the curves and
accelerates on the straight. And the mouse even simulates an
attempt to move through a heavy wind.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the technology to create such a mouse was only
available in consoles and joysticks for computer games. Originally
developed by Stanford University and NASA, force-feedback
technology was first used for flight simulation.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Immersion Corporation in San Jose, Calif., managed to
achieve the fast data exchange rates needed to provide realistic
tactile sensations when someone is shopping on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse is attached to a pad that contains two motors in a
small housing at the top, one to move the mouse right to left, and
the other to move it up and down. As you move your cursor over an
image on a Web page, embedded motion commands are sent to a
microprocessor in the mouse, telling it how to move to produce the
desired sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Internet shopping sprees aside, one of the best applications for
this technology is in schools, says Robert Tinker, a physicist who
runs a nonprofit-making company dedicated to using emerging
technologies in education. Tinker plans to use the force-feedback
mouse to teach children about the forces of nature, especially the
atomic level forces they cannot see. ''With this technology, kids
can feel their way around a molecule,'' Tinker says.
</P>
<P>
   The $99 mouse goes on sale in the United States in the autumn.
For the technology to proliferate, Web designers need only download
free software from www.FEELtheWEB.com to embed the relevant Feel It
commands in images, says Ramon Alarcon of Immersion.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
