<HEADER>
A4331 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUICIDAL-BACTERIA-(NE     07-09 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDAL-BACTERIA-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUICIDAL BACTERIA STOP VIRUSES FROM SPREADING  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JULY 12, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By ANDY COGHLAN  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suicidal bacteria that sacrifice themselves to save their
neighbors from viral infections are triggering a dormant
self-destruct button. If the same type of mechanism exists in
harmful bacteria, it might be possible to develop drugs that
persuade whole colonies to commit mass suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Snyder and his colleagues at Michigan State University in
East Lansing first observed the suicide effect in a harmless strain
of Escherichia coli called K-12.
</P>
<P>
   When viruses called T4 bacteriophages invaded the bacteria,
infected cells died before the viruses could make multiple copies
of themselves. If the cells had survived, the copies would have
burst out and infected adjacent bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder showed that the bacteria self-destruct thanks to an
enzyme called Lit, standing for ''Late Inhibitor of T4''. Last
year, he and his colleagues discovered two other molecules that
react with Lit to thwart the virus. One is a bacterial protein
called elongation factor Tu (EF-Tu), which orchestrates the
production of all other proteins by the bacterial cell. The other
key ingredient, they found, is a region of the bacteriophage
protein coat called Gol.
</P>
<P>
   Now Colin Kleanthous and Ryan Bingham at the University of East
Anglia in Norwich, working with Snyder, have discovered how the
threesome sabotages the virus. They found that the key to success
is the stage when the Gol viral coat protein clings to EF-Tu,
changing its shape in some subtle way.
</P>
<P>
   Shape-changing somehow turns the bacterial protein into a target
for the Lit enzyme. ''It's to do with the protein being dressed up
properly for destruction,'' says Kleanthous. Once Lit has destroyed
EF-Tu, protein production in the bacterial cell shuts down
completely, denying the bacteriophage the chance to copy itself. So
the rest of the bacterial colony is saved.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lit is almost like a primitive immune system,'' Kleanthous
says .
</P>
<P>
   But the origin of the system is a mystery. Why should a protein
from a bacteriophage be the architect of its own destruction?
Kleanthous suspects that the bacteriophage initially needed Gol to
stick to EF-Tu so it could survive. But the bacteria somehow
''sussed this out'' and evolved the Lit enzyme as a sentinel to
counter the threat.
</P>
<P>
   If similar suicide mechanisms exist in bacteria that cause
disease, they might lead to new drugs. Patients could be given
injections of a substance which mimics the effects of Gol-like
proteins, causing the bugs to self-destruct.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
