<HEADER>
A4337 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-09 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MORE STRIKE AGAINST BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It never fails. Whenever I start to lose interest in my
long-standing boycott of major-league baseball, I can always count
on one of these overpaid, self-indulgent ballplayers to deliver a
reality check.
</P>
<P>
   The wakeup call this time came from Juan Gonzalez of the Texas
Rangers, who declared himself unavailable for next Tuesday's
All-Star Game after the baseball fans of America failed to vote him
into the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez racked up the fifth highest vote total among American
League outfielders, finishing behind Mr. Baseball, Ken Griffey Jr.
of the Seattle Mariners, and three members of the Cleveland Indians
who benefited from what might be described as unusually high voter
turnout in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In political circles, this sort of electoral aggressiveness is
known as ``stuffing the ballot box'' and practitioners of the art
are subject to prosecution. But in the strange universe of All-Star
electioneering, the real-world crime of voting early and voting
often is considered a legitimate element of baseball's fanocracy.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Gonzalez doesn't like it _ and he's willing to
sacrifice a $50,000 All-Star selection bonus in exchange for the
sheer exhilaration of thumbing his nose at the fans. Gonzalez makes
millions, so he can well afford to forego such pocket change to
snub those who snubbed him.
</P>
<P>
   Juan's apologists keep saying that he is acting out of
principle, that he is lodging a protest against a flawed selection
process that punishes true All-Stars and rewards lesser lights who
are lucky enough to play in a town where residents are willing to
wallow in shameless partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   I say this: Gonzalez isn't acting out of principle. He's acting
out of shameless brattiness, which is far more obnoxious than
shameless partisanship. The Rangers' Rafael Palmeiro was a victim
of Cleveland's election fixing, finishing second to the Indians'
Jim Thome in the voting for first basemen _ but Palmeiro's idea of
a principled act was to graciously accept an invitation to serve as
Thome's backup.
</P>
<P>
   No one should be surprised by Gonzalez' petulance. Two years
ago, I shared with readers an anecdote from a fellow boycotter
whose desertion of the onetime pastime was a direct result of
Juan's disregard for the just plain folks who have made him rich
and famous.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-fan recalled an incident during spring training way back
in 1991 when a young boy pleaded with Gonzalez for an autograph.
Here's the story:
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this kid with a broken arm hanging around the
clubhouse with his mom. He was probably 10 years old. He had his
book of baseball cards and as soon as he saw a player coming toward
the clubhouse from the parking lot, he'd have that player's card
out of the book ... his Sharpie open at the ready, and he'd
politely ask the player, by name, for his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``A van pulls up on the back side of the building and from the
sliding door emerges none other than THE GREAT JUAN GONZALEZ,
hobbling on crutches (knee surgery). This kid about has a coronary
waving to his mom to `get the jersey!' She goes over to this duffel
bag and pulls out this jersey and gives it to the kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GREAT JUAN GONZALEZ can't walk up the sidewalk to the main
door of the clubhouse, but walks around to a back entry. The whole
time this kid is walking behind him saying, `Please, Mr. Gonzalez,
could I get your autograph, please?' and THE GREAT JUAN GONZALEZ
acts like he's deaf. Even the mother pleaded, `You're his favorite
player _ he's followed your career since the minors.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The steel door opens. THE GREAT JUAN GONZALEZ goes in, the
steel door closes and the kid is standing there in total disbelief.
The mother announced to the crowd that the jersey was one that THE
GREAT JUAN GONZALEZ wore in the minor leagues and they had come to
spring training hoping to get it autographed. ...''
</P>
<P>
   When I first related this tale, the pro-Juan crowd assured me
that he had changed, that he was working very hard to establish a
good relationship with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
