<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4338 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     07-09 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP GO THE ADS, POP GOES THE USER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Is there any way to disable those annoying
pop-up windows on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   _2 Close 2 Insanity
</P>
<P>
   DEAR 2: You're not the only one getting cheesed off. I'm really
tired of going to my favorite sites only to be greeted by pop-ups
telling me where I can find hot pix of bikers marrying farm
animals..MDNM/ Sure, I went through that experimental phase like we
all did, but that was before I mistakenly took the animal husbandry
course at the local junior college.
</P>
<P>
   You see, the problem is that nobody has figured out how to make
a buck off the Internet except for those guys who start up
electronic widget businesses five minutes after graduation, go
public and retire as billionaires later that week. Advertisers, in
particular, don't have a clue. What they do in print and on the air
just doesn't work on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   So they hijack you.
</P>
<P>
   Banner ads, those nasty little animated commercials littering
Web sites everywhere and slowing everything down while they load,
were bad enough. They're easy enough to ignore, and if you don't
click on them, maybe they'll go away one day when the advertiser
figures out he's funneling his money into a black hole.
</P>
<P>
   More obnoxious by far are advertisers' attempts to carry you off
to their own cruddy little sites. They figure that if somebody
visits, say, a site specializing in exciting new things to do with
ordinary kitchen implements, he'd be grabbing for his Visa as soon
as he's magically transported to a fun-with-cooking-spray pay site.
</P>
<P>
   Insidious Web designers can put code in their pages that
launches new browser sessions when you visit or try to leave a
site. The new sessions invariably call up pages you never wanted to
see, which is exactly what the advertising guys want.
</P>
<P>
   But don't cash your paycheck yet, ad-boy. There are so many
people out there tired of seeing your stuff that you finally ticked
off the wrong ones: the programmers. There are at least a
half-dozen programs out there now that intercept banners and
pop-ups. Once they're loaded, they look for known advertiser
addresses, common graphic names (like Ad.gif) and the code that
pops up stuff you don't want to see. Off the top of my head I can
name AtGuard, InterMute, WebMask and InterQuick. Just do a Yahoo!
search for them (if you don't mind looking at a few more banners).
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the flip side, those ads do pay the freight for a lot of
Web sites. They have a right to be there. You, however, have the
right to ignore them the same way you do a new Pepsi commercial
during the Super Bowl. At least that little girl with Joe Pesci's
voice isn't quite as irritating as a banner screaming ``Click
me!!!'' Well, maybe. Web advertisers need to find a way to be less
annoying, and until they do, they're going to have to expect
countermeasures at every step.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: As an active member of a Mac user group and
one-half of the club's ``newbie'' class teaching staff, I want to
say that I share your opinion about Apple's advertising slogan
about ``Just plug it in.'' I couldn't agree more about the
time-consuming, often frustrating problems that face 90 percent of
all newbies. Just changing modems can be a real pain.
</P>
<P>
   _Realist
</P>
<P>
   DEAR REALIST: A Mac user agreeing with me? I must have been
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay actually used a
Macintosh once. Just once. He says that was enough. Steve Jobs can
mail-bomb him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com or vent via
snail-mail at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. Fax: 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst,
editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
