   &UR; TEXTURES COULD MAKE THE WEB MORE FUN &LR;  _ Shoppers on the
Internet will soon be able to experience the ability to `touch'
items pictured on the Net. A Californian company has created a
motorised computer mouse that enables the computer user to feel the
texture of a pair of corduroy jeans or feel what it's like to
test-drive a car. By Catherine Zandonella. 450 words. Slugged:
BC-WEB-TEXTURES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GENETICALLY MODIFIED CROPS DON'T FULFILL PROMISE &LR;  _ New figures
reveal that genetically engineered crops may not be bringing about
the revolution in agricuture expected. American farmers who have
turned to modified crops seem to be getting yields no better than
farmers who grow traditional varieties and are using similar
quantities of pesticides. By Kurt Kleiner. 400 words. Slugged
BC-MODIFIED-CROPS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENTISTS TIE BRAIN CHEMICALS TO IQ &LR;  _ Neuroscientists in New
Mexico have found a link between variations in the levels of two
brain chemicals and the results of IQ tests. If the link holds up,
they say it might be possible to boost your intelligence by
changing the balance of these chemicals with dietary supplements.
By Philip Cohen. 650 words. Slugged
BC-EARTH-SLOWING-DOWN-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUICIDAL BACTERIAL STOP VIRUSES FROM SPREADING &LR;  _ Researchers
from Michigan State University have found suicidal bacteria that
sacrifice themselves to save their neighbours from viral
infections. If similar suicide mechanisms exist in bacteria that
cause disease, it might be possible to develop drugs that persuade
whole colonies to commit mass suicide. By Andy Coghlan. 500 words.
Slugged BC-SUICIDAL-BACTERIAL-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
