A4352 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-09 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE LAW, NUMBER OF DISABLED WITH NO JOB RISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine years after the enactment of the Americans with
Disabilities Act, the news from the trenches is not nearly as good
as people had hoped when the ADA became law.
</P>
<P>
   True, the act has had a significant impact on many of the
nation's 54 million disabled Americans, and on employers. It has
prompted the installation of ramps, rails, curb cuts, handicapped
parking, special computer equipment, and other devices that
accommodate people with disabilities. It has educated the public
and helped battle stigma and stereotypes in a nation in which youth
and physical beauty are revered. It also has paved the way to
employment for millions of people who, by and large, were
considered unemployable in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Given all that, there should be a lot to shout about as we
approach the 10th anniversary of the ADA. But if a survey by Louis
Harris and Associates in New York is any indication, there is a lot
more work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   The pollster has found that 71 percent of people with
disabilities who are of working age were unemployed in 1998, five
percentage points higher than in 1986, when the study was first
conducted. Three out of four of those not working said they would
like to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employment continues to be the area with the widest gulf
between people with disabilities and the rest of the population,''
according to the survey of 1,000 people with disabilities aged 16
and older between April and May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, this low rate of employment has led to an income
gap that shows no signs of narrowing. As a result, reports Louis
Harris, one in three adults with disabilities lives in low-wage
households with annual incomes of less than $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, talk of a booming economy increasing job opportunities
for people with disabilities doesn't jibe with the study's findings
_ or with advocates' expectations for the ADA, given its mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Were the expectations too high? Chai Feldblum, a Georgetown
University Law professor who wrote the ADA, says she never thought
the law would lead to big changes right away, especially in
employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that it was already hard to prove that a person was not
hired because of a particular characteristic,'' said Feldblum.
``What has happened, though, is that a message has been sent out
that a person can have a disability and still be able to work. The
intent was to have that message, over time, penetrate our
consciousness so that the law becomes a mechanism for changing
attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldblum may have gotten her wish. While the statistics are
grim, many people polled believed there had been significant
changes in public transportation, access, and the public's image of
people with disabilities. Presumably, their optimism stemmed from
their own belief in the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question remains: Why aren't more people working?
Feldblum maintains that employers can still screen people out at
the hiring stage. And, she says, some people might suspect they
have been discriminated against, but most cannot prove it.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another problem. If a person with a disability
works full time or puts in too many part-time hours, he or she
risks losing federal and state-supported benefits and medical
insurance. Fear of being cut off is a strong disincentive to work
in a marketplace in which the cost of private insurance is
prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many parents are so afraid that there is a medical problem
right around the corner, they would rather have a son or a daughter
stay home than work,'' said Hank Cheney, president of Work Inc. in
Quincy, Mass. a nonprofit organization that trains people with
disabilities and helps them find jobs.
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot in all the gloom is a bill cosponsored by
Massachusetts Senator Edward M. Kennedy, a Democrat, and James
Jeffords, a Republican from Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is called The Work Incentives Improvement Act, and
it would revamp laws so workers with disabilities could continue to
receive Medicaid and Medicare benefits, even if they work full
time. It also allows them to choose between state-funded vocational
rehabilitation and private programs that link them to jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, those who earn $75,000 or more would be required
to pay a full Medicaid premium. Those who earn under $75,000 could
buy coverage at sliding scale rates. People earning $25,000 to
about $40,000 per year would not pay more than 7.5 percent of their
earned income for Medicaid benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, once a disabled person is accepted into the Social
Security Disability or Supplemental Security Income program, he
also becomes eligible for Medicare or Medicaid. He can work but can
earn only up to $700 per month or he risks having his insurance and
cash payments cut off. The Catch 22: To collect basic benefits, he
must live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Garner, a disability and policy adviser in Kennedy's
officer, says the bill was designed to fix what many now consider a
stumbling block. ``This bill is for people who are born with a
disability and the person who becomes disabled later in life,''
Garner said. The former ``is born into poverty; the rest wind up in
poverty after becoming disabled.''
</P>
<P>
   At 47, Martha Winship is well aware of the problem. A bakery
assistant at Roche Brothers supermarket in Quincy, she'd like to
work more than the eight hours she logs in each week, but worries
about losing Supplemental Disability Insurance, Medicare, and
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Winship is legally blind in one eye, totally blind in the other,
and developed a mental illness in her 30s. She earns $6.25 per
hour. ``Right now, I only work two days a week,'' she said. ``If
the bill passes, it will be a good incentive for people like me,
the part timers, to work more hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, whose Work Inc. also trains people with disabilities,
says passage of the measure would go a long way toward lowering the
unemployment rate among the nation's disabled. ``Many people with
disabilities feel they have been left out,'' he said. ``We've
bypassed them, and they've become discouraged. . . The real break
is that when they finally do get a job, it's like watching a flower
starting to blossom.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Contact Diane E. Lewis at work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
