<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4357 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-ECONOMY-HNS &LR;      07-09 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW NOT TO HELP THE BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDRZEJ LUBOWSKI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOSTER CITY, Calif. _ When President Clinton visited Slovenia
last month, he told people of other Balkan nations that they too
can be like Slovenians: living in peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But while peace is within reach, prosperity will have to wait.
Slovenia, bordering Austria and Italy, enjoys a per capita gross
domestic product of more than $10,000 _ three times that of Turkey,
a NATO-member, at least six times that of Yugoslavia, and more than
10 times greater than Albania's. It will take generations for
Kosovars and Serbs to get to where Slovenians are today.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming high is healthy. Aiming too high and promising too much
leads only to painful disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens of several nations of the former Soviet bloc have had
their share of disappointments, confusion and self-doubt. In few
countries, however, did the fall of communism bring such
disillusionment as in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dismal story of transformation gone astray. Not only are
most Russians worse off today than 10 years ago, they will not
become better off unless things change dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some of the former Soviet satellites, Poland
being the prime example, are legitimate success stories.
</P>
<P>
   While not every Pole is today better off than 10 years ago, few
would welcome a return to Communist days. For the average Russian,
who sees his country ridden by crime and corruption, the old,
fairly even distribution of misery under Soviet rule looks pretty
appealing _ and may even elicit nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Some time ago, Harvard University's Samuel Huntington wrote that
``drinking Coca-Cola does not make Russians think any more like
Americans than eating sushi makes Americans think like Japanese.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the freedom to travel, to worship, to speak out and to
use the Internet doesn't make Russia a democracy. The presence of
the stock exchange does not make it a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Russia has abandoned central planning. But it has never
embraced the market, which, for many tired and impoverished people,
has now become a dirty word. Russia ended halfway. Halfway between
central planning and the market lies chaos.
</P>
<P>
   True, Russia had a much steeper hill to climb than Poland,
Hungary or the Czech Republic, where the damage to the work ethic
was less severe and memories of democracy and a market economy were
not totally extinct. And, unlike Russia, these nations were getting
rid of a system imposed on them by force from outside.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia never tried to transform fully its economic
institutions, despite what we in the United States, and our
leaders, desperately wanted to believe. To say that the market
reforms in Russia failed misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   Genuine reforms were never given a chance, and for that, part of
the blame can be placed on the West in general, and on Washington
in particular. On the other hand, Polish reform was radical.
</P>
<P>
   This was not only because the country's new leaders believed
that the economic benefits of such shock therapy outweighed the
costs. They also recognized that any historical breakthrough, such
as the fall of an oppressive system, creates a period of
extraordinary politics, when people are more likely to endure pain
for the sake of the common good.
</P>
<P>
   Such a period, however, seldom lasts long. It is usually quickly
replaced by the mundane, ``normal'' politics of contending interest
groups and parties. Poland, unlike Russia, had a credible and
highly competent opposition, ready to step in and act quickly and
decisively.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing hardships in Russia now threaten both economic
reforms and a still fragile political democracy. The longer it
takes for living standards to improve, the greater the risk of
political disarray. The longer it takes to deliver the goods under
democracy, the more attractive the authoritarian alternative will
become. So what has the United States been doing to help?
</P>
<P>
   We're forgiving Russia's debts and lending more _ despite clear
incompetence and rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
   We've been convincing ourselves that progress is just around the
corner. We don't like what we are seeing, but we are afraid that
the alternative may be worse. We want to be pragmatic. We've become
hypocritical. We never held those in power in Russia accountable _
not even for what happens to the money provided by the America
taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   We must not repeat these mistakes in the Balkans. There are, we
hope, some lessons learned:
</P>
<P>
   Our understanding of other nations and cultures is deficient,
which leads to frequent surprises. (We were surprised by the
persistence of Slobodan Milosevic and by Russian insecurity that
resulted in their capture of the Pristina airport.)
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to be a superpower on the cheap. There are
serious risks when well-justified moral outrage becomes the top
political motivation. To build democracy and have a shot at
prosperity, both Russia and the Balkans will need our support. But
this support cannot be unconditional, as happened too often with
Russia in the last eight years. If the pattern continues, we will
further damage our credibility and hurt the people we want to help.
</P>
<P>
   Moral capital, a shortage of which we often lament domestically,
is much easier to squander than to rebuild. If the outcome of the
Balkan crisis does not live up to the high standards that we set,
our credibility will suffer. We should be careful what, when and
whom we promise, unless we are certain that we can deliver.
Credibility is fragile.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Andrzej Lubowski, an economist and journalist in Poland and a
senior Fulbright Fellow at Stanford University, is now a banker.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
