A4359 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-09 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY'S NOT-SO-SECRET ADMIRER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The current issue of the New Yorker has a brief article about
Hillary Clinton's not-so-secret ambition to become the nation's
first woman president. Various scenarios have Senator Clinton
(D-N.Y.) running for vice-president in 2004, after an Al Gore loss
in 2000, or running for the tob job in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Well then, a wealthy Beverly Hills immigrant named Max Rhodes
proves to be even more clued in than the incomparably clued-in New
Yorker, because he has been pushing his Hillary for President 2000
campaign since the end of last year. Rhodes loves Hill, thinks Gore
has the scarlet (crimson?) L-for-Loser written all over him. ``He
appears weak, his voice speaks without conviction, and he lacks the
appeal that we need in a leader. . . . Al Gore himself does not
believe in his candidacy,'' according to Rhodes's campaign
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes has everything _ a pile of dough, a Web site
(www.hillary4prez2000.com), T-shirts, bumper stickers, a cheer and
even a fight song:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She's got the smarts. . .and she's humane
</P>
<P>
   She can even outwit Saddam Hussein!
</P>
<P>
   Hill's already a White House resident
</P>
<P>
   Let's save 'em a move and make her President.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also has Democratic Party mailing lists, and some big cheese
donors have been surprised to see his solicitations showing up in
their mailboxes. Rhodes lacks only one thing: Hillary's blessing.
``She does not support us, but we are in the process of changing
her mind,'' Rhodes says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bulger-ama
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's all very nice that Billy Bulger is pumping University
of Massachusetts budget dollars into flashy ads hyping his ``new''
UMass. But several ongoing projects will report on a different side
of the Bulger family legend, to wit, the former Senate president's
famous fugitive brother, Whitey. Robert Redford has supposedly
optioned a Bulger family movie script from Mike Barnicle and Peter
Maas. Next year, Globe Spotlight Team editors Gerry O'Neill and
Dick Lehr plan to publish ``Ties that Blind,'' a book describing
the complicated relations among the Bulgers, the Irish Mob, and law
enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   And just a few weeks from now, Beacon Press will publish Michael
MacDonald's much-anticipated Southie memoir, which may begin the
process of burying Whitey's reputation as a modern-day
Irish-American Robin Hood. Here's the author on Whitey, on page
183: ``I thought it was pretty smart of him to position his liquor
and drug business right on the edge of our project, where more and
more kids were doing whatever they could to get drug money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sports Talk
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Okay, now that my Lady Paper Clips (Norway) are no longer in the
Women's World Cup, will I root for the Lady Prison Camps (China) in
Saturday's final? No, my heart is with the Northern California,
sorry, the US team, but my head tells me it's going to be tough
sledding for the Lady Gatorades. The Chinese are playing like they
invented the game. . . Because the New England Revolution is a
comparatively successful franchise, it isn't widely known here that
Major League (Men's) Soccer is on the verge of collapse,
nationally. Any bump that the 1994 US-hosted World Cup provided for
MLS has dissipated now, and several big-city franchises are sucking
wind. The long knives are out for commissioner Doug Logan, and some
speculation in Internet chat rooms has focused on Steve Gans as a
possible successor. Gans is a former professional player who
studied law at the World's Greatest University. He helped run the
successful Baltimore Blast franchise, and he has represented some
players in contract negotiations. . .A friend of mine whose company
has several hundred thousand dollars invested in the upcoming
All-Star idiocy, e.g. Matt Damon and Kevin Costner hitting
baseballs at Sunday's Celebrity Hitting Challenge, calls next
week's All-Star game ``the most elitist, blacked-out event in
Boston sports history. A normal Joe never had a chance to get near
a ticket.'' True enough. The Red Sox sold about two-thirds of the
park to season ticket holders and then turned the rest of the
tickets over to what is euphemistically called ``the baseball
family'' _ the fat cats who run Major League Baseball. Helpful TGIF
explanation: Ted Turner gets seats. You don't.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
