<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FEMININE SOCCER MYSTIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a typical Bud-swilling American male, I
didn't think any woman could get me to put down our culture's
sacred phallic symbol, the TV remote control.
</P>
<P>
   It took 11 women to get me to stop pushing those buttons, but
they did it, and it'll happen again on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the TV audience for women's World Cup soccer has
been men, and the reason is simple, but not as simple as bouncing
ponytails and shapely legs, no matter how much you hear about
``soccer mamas'' and ``soccer babes.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, women's soccer is a great sport, and translates
well to TV. The couch criterion is the ultimate male test for any
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm, Briana Scurry and company have given average American
males soccer we can stand watching. In fact, during the
quarter-final game against Germany, I couldn't take my eyes off the
TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   During men's World Cup soccer you can take a nap for an hour and
not miss anything but hooligans getting drunker in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Men's soccer is a reflection of the modern male psyche. It's
defensive and insecure. Men keep diddling with the ball the way
they do with the TV remote. The object of the male game is to keep
opponents from scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Men are funny that way. They don't want to win as much as not
lose.
</P>
<P>
   The object of the female game is to score. Women want to win,
and how often do they get a level playing field? Women's soccer is
a reflection of the modern female psyche. The women are constantly
on the move, attacking, subtly tripping each other, and shooting
for the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Male soccer players, at least in my limited World Cup watching,
are big whiners and fakers. They're always falling down, holding
their poor little shins and pleading with referees.
</P>
<P>
   Women soccer players, at least in the two games I watched, went
down on the turf after being firmly planted there. The only blatant
fake injury was when a Brazilian player was carried off the field
on a stretcher and then leaped up and tried to get back in the game
again.
</P>
<P>
   Women have a long way to go before they become as skillful at
malingering as men.
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer is by far a greater sport than women's
basketball, particularly for guys who are forced to comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   After initial statements from men about the wonderful team
spirit, the sentence you always hear about women's basketball is:
``It's like men's basketball the way it used to be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, wasn't basketball something when it was played by short
white guys? In other words, ``pretty good for girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the worst male chauvinist doesn't want to be caught saying
anything like that, especially about women who can slam-dunk him
through the parquet.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we now have a women's soccer craze, and you won't
find a male American saying it's ``pretty good for girls.''
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty good for men. And here's why.
</P>
<P>
   Men can enjoy women's World Cup soccer without having to nod
while their wives say it's good for their daughters' self-esteem
and personal development. It's just good.
</P>
<P>
   In women's basketball, there are always clumsy, embarrassing
interludes when confusion reigns under the basket and the game goes
to pot. When things get confusing in front of the goal in soccer,
the game gets more exciting, just like hockey with a loose puck in
the crease.
</P>
<P>
   American men can enjoy women's soccer without having to say,
``It's like men's soccer the way it used to be played.''
</P>
<P>
   We have no idea how it used to be played. Instead we say it's
like hockey without the sticks and pads, and no need to put a silly
glowing halo around the ball so the nearsighted can follow the game
from the couch.
</P>
<P>
   There also is no need for fights that clear the benches, because
the women soccer players are brutal enough just doing it with their
Nikes.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if women soccer players are role models for our
daughters. Our daughters will do fine. Women are better than men,
especially at things that don't involve brute strength, like
soccer, school and being sensible.
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer is good for men's personal development. One day
women will be at least half-running the world. We can prepare for
that day by watching women tear up a literally level playing field,
skillfully kicking inflated leather spheres.
</P>
<P>
   Get used to the management style. Men are doomed, and women's
soccer tells us why.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SUMMER-BOS &LR;      07-09 1548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SUMMER OF '99 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given our culture's current obsession with the '70s, it's no
surprise that Donna Summer, perhaps the quintessential voice of the
disco era, has resurfaced. Ever-savvy VH-1 picked this moment to
produce a ``Behind The Scenes'' episode about Summer, a televised
concert special, ``Donna Summer: Live &AMP; More _ Encore!'' The
network and Epic Records have also released a live album with the
same title that was recorded at the concert. The CD, a compilation
of greatest hits and three new tracks, was released last week, and
entered the Billboard charts at No. 43. That's no small feat for an
artist who hasn't been in the collective pop-culture consciousness
for a good 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   This week Summer began a 35-city tour that stops in Boston, her
hometown, Wednesday at BankBoston Pavilion. She'll also sing the
national anthem at the All-Star game at Fenway Park the night
before. Summer's soprano is as smooth and booming as it was in her
heyday, a remarkable feat that the 50-year-old grandmother
attributes to the grace of God. But song and spirit weren't always
in harmony for Summer. On the contrary, a painful ambiguity of
faith and ambition, which evolved into a wrenching identity crisis,
nearly destroyed Donna Summer at the peak of her success.
</P>
<P>
   One could trace the genesis of Summer's conflict to 1968, when
she left Newton, Mass. and a strict religious family for the wilds
of New York, where she was quickly recruited for the German touring
company of the musical ``Hair.'' But Summer fingers that first,
now-infamous hit single of 1975: ``Love To Love You Baby.'' It was
a 16 minute and 50 second moanfest that tranformed dance floors
into erotic playgrounds and Summer into a sex goddess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never comfortable doing that song,'' Summer says on the
phone from Atlantic City, the first stop on her tour. And yet her
delivery managed to sound so . . . persuasive. ``Those `oohs' and
`aahs' came out because I hadn't written all the words,'' she
explains matter-of-factly. ``I didn't know what to sing. We were
goofing around. I wanted to give `Love To Love You Baby' to someone
else. I never, never wanted to do that song.''
</P>
<P>
   But Summer was a newly divorced mother of a baby girl (Mimi, now
26), when she met producer Giorgio Moroder in Munich in the early
'70s and recorded the demo tape of ``Love To Love You Baby.'' When
the late Casablanca Records chief Neil Bogart stumbled upon it, he
immediately licensed the song and signed the fledgling singer to
his label, and his wife, Joyce, became her manager. ``At that
point, I was under the guidance of people who I thought knew what
they were doing. They said, `Do this till we get from point A to
point B.' But inside I kind of fought it all along. It didn't fit
with my spiritual background.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer was born Donna Gaines, the third of seven children born
to Mary Ellen Gaines, a teacher's assistant who died in 1995, and
her husband, Andrew, a now-retired electrician. Growing up,
Summer's musical idol was gospel singer Mahalia Jackson. ``I
sounded like Alfalfa on `The Little Rascals,' '' recalls Summer.
``And Mahalia had such a big voice.'' Her love of singing, as well
as her deep religious faith, was nurtured Sunday mornings at the
Grant African Methodist Episcopal church, ``at 1906 Washington
Street'' Summer announces proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Summer characterizes her childhood as a constant struggle for
attention, a state of mind that would feed the troubles she
encountered down the line. ``I had such low self-esteem. There were
a lot of kids and the focus was not on me. But I always talked to
God, from the time I was a little kid. When I was about 8, I was
singing in church, and I heard a voice. I knew it was God. And he
said that this was my power, and that I would be famous.''
</P>
<P>
   How ironic, then, that it was a gift from God that would unravel
Summer's spirituality almost to the point of no return. As her
powerful soprano and pulsing dance tracks became the defining sound
of the disco craze in the late '70s, Summer strayed further and
further from her faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, that was a low point in my spiritual life,''
says Summer, whose image as an icon of hedonism and sensuality
included performing that song with a machine blowing steam between
her legs. Summer struggled to reconcile her public persona with the
religious belief system she had always relied on to sustain her. At
the same time, she began to suffer the fallout of massive fame. A
rapid succession of hits _ ``Bad Girls,'' ``Hot Stuff,'' ``Last
Dance,'' ``MacArthur Park'' _ followed Summer's 1975 debut. And so
did the pressure. ``It's like if you woke up tomorrow morning and
you were president of the United States. Everyone's calling you,
wanting you. You go to the ladies' room and you can't get out. That
success, and all that goes with it, it was beyond my human ability
to deal with it,'' Summer remembers. ``There was no room for me in
this thing anymore, there was only room for the image. Yeah, I was
depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms became increasingly severe as the decade wore on, and
Summer was finally hospitalized in 1979. ``I started to feel
fragmented, everyone scared me,'' Summer says. ``I was insomniac.
The doctors put me on drugs for the depression, and they put me on
drugs to help me sleep. That's when I started getting suicidal. And
I thought, `God, if you don't help me, I won't make it.' I know I
wouldn't have made it another week and a half.'' What happened next
is something, Summer says, that many people still have a hard time
accepting. ``It was very simple, though. God delivered me. That's
it. In a moment. I can pinpoint the moment. My doctor, who was
administering these heavy drugs, said I couldn't get off drugs that
fast. But I did, and I was healthy. I was different.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer's next album,``The Wanderer,'' was released in 1980; it
included the song ``I Believe in Jesus'' and a special thanks in
the liner notes to ``the Supreme Being, the Creator, without Whom
there would be no beginning or no end.'' She continued to have
hits, most memorably 1983's ``She Works Hard for the Money,'' a
song that has since gone on to make Summer a fortune in advertising
royalties. But as disco waned, so did Summer's star.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the good news. Feeling ``complete'' for the first
time in years, she dedicated herself to family life: Summer,
songwriter Bruce Sudano, her husband of 19 years, and their two
daughters, Brooklyn and Amanda, now 18 and 16, relocated in 1991
from Los Angeles to Tennessee. They split their time between a
house in Nashville and a 104-acre farm outside the city. Summer
began painting in earnest and has released a series of gospel
albums.
</P>
<P>
   While planning her greatest hits album, ``Endless Summer,'' in
1993, Summer began working on an autobiographical musical called
``Ordinary Girl.'' The process has been cathartic, marking a return
not only to musical theater _ Summer's first love _ but to the
singer's tumultuous past. ``I had gotten some Broadway offers, but
I turned them down. I really felt I needed to establish myself in a
role no one else had done. So I started thinking about my life.
Mistakes. Good moves. Actions and reactions. Difficult times,''
says Summer, who has written all the songs and fleshed out
characters and a story line. Alfred Uhry, who wrote ``Driving Miss
Daisy,'' is currently working on the book. While the title doesn't
exactly seem to reflect Summer's experiences, she points out, ``I
got married, had a baby, got divorced. I think a lot of people can
identify with those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer thinks a great deal these days about the stage. In recent
years she's learned to draw more on her early acting experience for
her live shows and cites Judy Garland as her model for performance.
In her concert, ``each song is like an acting piece, and I sing
each one as a different woman,'' says Summer, who is touring with
an eight-piece band and two dancers. ``I want you to go home
feeling like you've heard songs, but that you've also learned
something about me. My goal isn't to make you understand I can
sing. It's to make you understand this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   One musical memory Summer won't be revisiting, however, is that
infamous first single. Summer hasn't performed ``Love To Love You
Baby'' since the early '80s, and says she never will. ``It's just
not where I am in my life. And it brings out a real weirdness in
people.'' Pressed to elaborate, Summer says only ``trust me.
Weirder than you can imagine.'' Audience members, she confirms,
have been known to become quite inspired by the song, leading to
overzealous public displays of affection.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, however, is that Summer's audience is still out
there, and it's a devoted one. Despite the fact that interest in
her is fueled largely by nostalgia, Summer is grateful. ``I don't
think they even knew they were devoted. I think they woke up one
day and said, `Hey, I remember that.' People say to me that I was
the soundtrack to their lives. It makes you feel really good to
feel you're a part of someone's life you don't even know. That
something you've done has affected someone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
