<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODE-ISLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIT TO TINY RHODE ISLAND IS HUGELY REWARDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KAREN NELIS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISQUAMICUT, R.I. _ Rhode Island may be the smallest state in
the union, but its breathtaking ocean views, vast stretches of
sandy beaches, elegant mansions and world-class music festivals
make it a big vacation destination.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island offers history and art in its capital city of
Providence, music and excitement in Newport, spectacular and
pristine scenery on Block Island, and quiet, family-oriented beach
communities along the South County shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Newport, a major port city in the late 1700s, rivaling Boston
and New York, became a summer getaway in the 19th century for the
richest families in America, who built elaborate ``cottages''
overlooking the Atlantic Ocean. Newport today is known for those
mansions, as well as its jazz, blues, folk and classical music
festivals.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gilded Age of the 19th century, those seeking to avoid
the hustle and bustle of the Newport summer social scene and
pursuing a less ostentatious display of wealth headed down to the
South County coastline, including the area around Misquamicut and
Watch Hill. Today too, the South County region is the quieter, less
crowded vacation destination of those wanting sun and sand but who
can do without the scores of chic restaurants and boutiques of
Newport.
</P>
<P>
   It was this quieter beach region that my family, traveling with
a not-quite 3-year-old, opted to visit on a week-long vacation last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Misquamicut, where we stayed, where large malls and
tract-housing developments are simply nonexistent, is clearly
geared to a relaxed, low-key pace. The miles of sandy beaches along
the South County shore were crowded on weekends, but emptied out
come Monday. Even the small amusement park located on the main
section of the beach was nearly deserted on that warm Monday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen small strip motels lie near the beach; only a couple
are located right on the beach. We chose to stay about a mile away
at a resort hotel offering better accommodations and amenities,
including an outdoor pool, shuffleboard, daily continental
breakfast and twice-weekly barbecues by the pool. Our large room
also featured a private balcony, refrigerator and microwave oven.
Hundreds of rental cottages and condos are available throughout the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The shoreline was divided into private beach areas for residents
or those with passes issued by various hotels, including ours, and
the public section at Atlantic Beach Park. Parking at the beach
ranges from $5 to $8 a day for those without a pass.
</P>
<P>
   The beach was beautiful, the water temperature comfortably cool.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for any diversions off the beach, however,
you'll have to look hard or be willing to take some short
side-trips as we did out of the immediate area.
</P>
<P>
   We made two separate excursions to Mystic, Conn., which is only
about 15 miles, or a 25-minute drive, from Misquamicut. We spent
one overcast morning at the Mystic Aquarium, which has many indoor
exhibits and shows, and we spent a half-day at historic Mystic
Seaport.
</P>
<P>
   We also explored some of the other beach communities surrounding
Misquamicut in Rhode Island. Take Route 1 north about 25 miles to
Narragansett, a quiet little town that also was once a resort for
the very wealthy at the turn of the last century. The town once
featured the Narragansett Pier Casino, which offered bowling,
billiards, tennis, a rifle gallery, a theater and a ballroom. The
casino burned down in 1900; only the towers that marked its
entrance remain. The beach at Narragansett is lovely and you can
stroll along a boardwalk for views of the ocean and several large
hotels near the beach.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to Narragansett, we stopped at the South County
Museum for a picnic lunch on the museum grounds and a tour of
reconstructions of several typical New England buildings, including
a cooper's shop and blacksmith's shop. A museum building houses
such exhibits as a general store and children's nursery. The museum
is small and isn't much different from other such historic
reconstructions (it pales greatly in comparison to Mystic Seaport
and the Farmers Museum in Cooperstown, N.Y.), but it's enough to
offer some diversion to small children.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back to Misquamicut, we drove down Route 1A through
Galilee to check out the beaches there. Roger W. Wheeler State
Beach had a children's playground. Galilee is a busy, working
fishing port and the site of the only year-round ferry to Block
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to our home base in Misquamicut, we went several times to
the village of Watch Hill, just 4 miles away, for a small taste of
Newport.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Hill has a beautiful marina, gracious mansions, a lovely
beach (where the waves seemed to be calmer than at Misquamicut) and
several blocks of shops and restaurants. There wasn't much to do in
Misquamicut in the evenings other than take in the Atlantic Beach
Park amusement center with its handful of rides and nearby
miniature golf course, but, in Watch Hill, you could buy an ice
cream cone and stroll along the marina, check out the shops
offering clothes, crafts, jewelry and used books, and watch the
sunset from a gazebo.
</P>
<P>
   Near the beach, you won't want to miss the Flying Horse
Carousel, the oldest carousel in the United States, built in 1867.
Each horse, which will swing out when the carousel is in motion, is
hand carved from a single piece of wood and has a real horsehair
mane and leather saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Rides, which cost $1 each, are for children only.
</P>
<P>
   There are a just a few small hotels in Watch Hill, plus a grand
old Victorian hotel, the Ocean House, on a bluff overlooking the
ocean and a private beach. There are many condos for rent along the
waterfront, as well as numerous summer cottages.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the whole South County region seemed more geared toward
vacationers staying in rented cottages and seeking quiet and
solitude than toward those who selected a hotel or motel.
Misquamicut, in particular, seems to be a resort that didn't plan
on being a resort.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a handful of restaurants including a McDonald's,
Burger King and a Friendly's within a few miles driving distance.
Finer dining was even harder to seek out.
</P>
<P>
   We did have an excellent seafood dinner at a fine restaurant a
few miles away on Route 1 in Charlestown and we found a wonderful
neighborhood Italian restaurant in Misquamicut that was recommended
by the owner of our hotel.
</P>
<P>
   We also enjoyed dinner one evening in Watch Hill's Olympia Tea
Room, an old-fashioned restaurant with wooden booths, ceiling fans,
and an early 1900s soda fountain counter.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, we packed picnic lunches with food bought at a nearby
grocery store and enjoyed the two barbecue dinners poolside at our
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   While our hotel was very nice and I would highly recommend it,
we would be more likely to look into rental cottages for any return
to Misquamicut or check out a more romantic stay at the majestic
Ocean House in Watch Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
