<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCENROE'S ACT GETS A CURTAIN CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ When he famously baptized a Wimbledon umpire as
``the pits of the world!'' was John Patrick McEnroe Jr. making a
geological classification? Or was it just another tempestuous
statement in his fashion of disapproving the judiciary while also
unnerving those who disapproved of his conduct?
</P>
<P>
   Many were they who fumed about his fuming, the tactless,
tasteless _ sometimes tactical _ tirades. Yet who could resist his
artistry and competitive verve with a tennis racket? All was
forgiven this lefthander because his distinctive sinister style,
the whirling dervish volleying and balletic footwork, was
mesmerizing. You cannot be serious if you believe McEnroe is
undeserving of canonization and a place among the greats Saturday
at the International Tennis Hall of Fame. Saints have had flaws,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying McEnroe in the Class of '99 at Newport's Casino,
the cradle of the American tournament game, is Ken McGregor, a
husky Australian of similar serve-and-volley persuasion, but
entirely dissimilar temperament. As the Aussie-US Davis Cup
collision looms next weekend at Longwood, it seems appropriate that
two such mainstays of the most compelling Cup rivalry should enter
the Hall together.
</P>
<P>
   McGregor, 70, who comes from Adelaide, was a vital cog in the
Australian Cup renaissance of 1950, alongside Frank Sedgman, his
predecessor to the Hall in 1979. They won three straight, breaking
a US stranglehold and launching their country's reign of terror: 15
Cups in 18 years. McEnroe, 40, also led a revival, sparking five
winners between 1978 and 1992, and bagged seven major singles: four
US, three Wimbledons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I acted up, and was out of line many times, no question,''
McEnroe says. ``But I don't think I was any worse than Ilie Nastase
or Jimmy Connors. It was a time for acting up _ but we could back
it up with solid playing. I hope I'm remembered more for my
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be. Mac did it all, racking up a professional record of
154 career titles, a 77-77 singles-doubles split. He doesn't
understand why today's top guys don't play doubles _ ``it's great
fun.'' Nor does McGregor, who, with Sedgman, crafted the only men's
doubles Grand Slam in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   During one of his monster seasons, 1979, Mac won 27 titles, 10
in singles, plus all nine matches as the US took the Davis Cup.
``My mother made me promise I'd play Davis Cup if I was invited,''
he says, unsympathetic to decliners, as Pete Sampras has been.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduling sometimes made it tougher. In 1979 McEnroe won a
Monday night indoor singles final in San Francisco, rushed to the
airport with a police escort to make the midnight flight to Sydney
for a Cup semifinal. Jet lagged but jumping, he had one day's
practice on grass, then beat both Aussie foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm best remembered for a match I lost,'' he laughs.
``People are always saying to me they remember my Wimbledon final
against Bjorn Borg. I know what they mean, but I say, `You mean '81
when I beat him?'
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. They mean '80 and the long tiebreaker'' _ Borg's last
of five straight championships, the colossal 1-6, 7-5, 6-3, 6-7
(16-18), 8-6, decision. ``That was a lesson for me. I always
thought winning was so important but I came to realize that match,
just being part of such a wonderful match, elevated my stature,
enhanced my career more than winning. It made me a little humble _
not that I'm very humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bjorn quit, only 25, I lost something. I was in shock. It
bothered me for a long time. We had a great rivalry.'' Even though
it was probably his ascent past Borg to No. 1 that drove the Swede
away, McEnroe says, ``I was affected negatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first major, the US in 1979, was bittersweet. I beat my
buddy Vitas Gerulaitis. There we were, two New York kids who grew
up 15 minutes from Flushing in the final. When would that ever
happen again? We were thrilled, but people booed us because the
final they wanted was Borg and Connors. I'd beaten Jimmy and Vitas
beat Roscoe Tanner, who beat Borg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant a lot to me to repeat in 1980, to show that my title
the year before wasn't a fluke _ and also what I had to do to win.
I beat Ivan Lendl in the quarters, four sets. The next day, Friday,
Peter (Fleming) and I lost the doubles final to Stan Smith and Bob
Lutz in five. Saturday a tiebreaker in the fifth to beat Connors at
night, four hours-plus. The next day five more sets and four more
hours to beat Borg for the title.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago Mac swooped and swatted across the Casino lawn
in spearheading a Davis Cup victory over Spain. But Saturday he'll
be out of action, standing still to accept the induction encomiums
draped on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm forcing all my kids to be here,'' he grins. ``Maybe
they'll remember it. Ava will enjoy it the most, sleeping. She's 3
months old.''
</P>
<P>
   The favored Americans thought Aussie captain Harry Hopman was
asleep when he selected rookie McGregor to start against them in
the 1950 final at Forest Hills in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see them smiling when my name was announced at the
draw,'' says McGregor. ``Their happiness was understandable. Who
was I? But Sedgman gave us a 1-0 lead over Tom Brown, and I started
fast to beat Ted Schroeder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That did us in,'' US captain Alrick Man said at the time.
``Ted had never lost a Cup match, and we needed him to win.''
</P>
<P>
   McGregor last appeared at Newport in 1952, losing the final to
Sedgman, whom he'd defeated for the Australian title. ``We were
amateurs then, playing for a few shillings expenses a day,'' he
recalls. ``Sedgman and I turned pro after winning the 1952 Cup. He
got a $75,000 guarantee. I got $25,000. We thought we were rich.''
They were. You couldn't buy the experiences that line the path to
the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Rich, too, is McEnroe, the volcanic virtuoso at the crest of
many peaks, but not always avoiding the pits of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The latest pitfall was being stood up by Steffi Graf at
Wimbledon, where they were in the semis of the mixed with a good
shot at winning it. A last major title 20 years after the first
(the French mixed of 1977 with Mary Carillo), would have been a
sweet full-circle closer of his days at the Big W.
</P>
<P>
   But the fraulein said ``nein'' to playing more than the singles
final, which she lost to Lindsay Davenport. ``She promised me she
wouldn't pull out, but she did,'' says McEnroe, who may have
pleaded, ``You cannot be serious!''
</P>
<P>
   He's not the first guy to be jilted, but perhaps the Hall of
Fame is some consolation for being stiffed by Steffi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
