r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-HAMPSHIRE-2TAKES-     07-09 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-HAMPSHIRE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DRIVE ALONG THE `KANC' LEADS TO A LAND OF DISCOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED STETSON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONWAY, N.H. _ With a whir of wings, a partridge explodes from
waist-deep snow and flies on a line through evergreens and
hardwoods. Seconds later, another lifts off and darts up the gully,
passing gray boulders half as tall as the trees. One partridge
leaves meandering tracks in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   But, the prints stop where the frightened bird took flight. This
moment occurred in the New Hampshire woods, a short walk from a
34-mile scenic highway that twists and turns through the White
Mountain National Forest. From the east, the two-lane road climbs
to almost 3,000 feet, then descends past swift, clear rivers, and
cuts through deep forests and jagged cliffs. Finally, it stops near
a tourist-driven town plastered with hokum.
</P>
<P>
   This is the ``Kanc.'' The east-west highway carries the name of
Kancamagus (Fearless One), who assumed leadership of the Penacook
(Native-American) Confederacy in 1681. Defeated in bloody wars,
Kancamagus and his followers retreated to northern New Hampshire
and Canada in 1691. They left behind a mountainous region filled
with history and lore. Since the early 1800s, such eminent artists
as Thomas Cole and Alfred Bierstadt have celebrated the White
Mountains. Visiting writers included Henry Thoreau, Ralph Waldo
Emerson and Nathaniel Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until 1959 that highway crews finally blasted
through the rocky terrain and completed the Kanc, linking Lincoln
and Conway, 34 miles to the east. Today, the Kancamagus Highway is
part of a 123-mile New Hampshire ``Scenic and Cultural Byway.''
</P>
<P>
   This loop connects several routes and passes through thousands
of acres of forests, by scenic rivers and waterfalls, between
Crawford and Franconia Notches and by historic homes, inns and
villages. The byway even leads to the grand old Mount Washington
Hotel and the coal-fired Cog Railway locomotive that belches black
smoke as it chugs up the mountain. From many vantage points,
Washington's broad 6,288-foot summit slumbers on the far horizon.
</P>
<P>
   On warm, hazy afternoons, the mountain becomes faint and
mysterious, assuming a beauty found in landscape scenes from
ancient Japan. Most years, snow crowns the summit in late September
and lasts until May or June. Weather changes in a flash. In late
winter, skies above the Mount Washington Valley turned, in 72
hours, from cobalt blue, to hazy white, to battleship gray and then
coal black. At dusk, wind-driven clouds spun off nearby hills.
Sunlight, adding the drama of a Renaissance painting, beamed
through a pastel-blue hole in the overcast. Edges of gray clouds
turned sulfur yellow and soft pink, the color of the inside of a
conch shell.
</P>
<P>
   We began our trip at Woodsville, N.H. A mile east of Woodsville,
is New Hampshire Route 112, which, about 15 miles farther east in
Lincoln, becomes the Kancamagus Highway.
</P>
<P>
   Before turning onto Route 112, though, go a mile farther to the
pleasant town of Bath. In the village, beside a 400-foot-long
covered bridge, is the rustic and handsome Brick Store (1824), the
nation's ``oldest continuously operating general store.'' Dozens of
old Life magazines hang from upper walls, penny candy fills counter
jars, pastries and fudge sit under glass. Floors gleam with polish,
and porch floor boards, painted gray, have a comforting mix of wear
and grit. Another mile to the east is the so-called Upper Village
(located on a flood plain of the Ammonoosuc River), where Jeremiah
Hutchins and other pioneer settlers built a cluster of brick
Colonial homes.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the settlement looks as though someone moved a
neighborhood from Boston's Beacon Hill or Washington's Georgetown
to northern rural New Hampshire. The distinctive, Federal-style Ira
Goodhall House (1816) has a rare rounded brick wall facing the
street. After returning to Route 112, motorists begin a slight
climb, while winding along the Wild Ammonoosuc River.
</P>
<P>
   One of many Native-American names in the region, Ammonoosuc
means ``fish place.'' (The U.S. Forest Service says there are 750
miles of fishing streams and 50 ponds in the 800,000-acre White
Mountain National Forest.) While driving more than 50 feet from the
banks, car passengers can see the river bottom. Clear, shallow
water refracts the sand and rock.
</P>
<P>
   Once through Swiftwater, which has its own 150-year-old,
174-foot-long covered bridge, the highway climbs eight miles to
Beaver Pond. En route, sharp curves and frost heaves may toss a car
about, especially one with worn shocks. About 35 to 45 mph is a
comfortable speed. Overhead, trees such as hemlocks, pines and
birches create tunnels of shade.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, cool, evergreen-scented air spills down slope a
fresh, aromatic tonic. Before long, the trees give way to the
Beaver Pond overlook with 180-degree southerly views. Mount Blue,
Mount Moosilauke (``bald place'') and Mount Jim all more than 4,000
feet rise in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, brisk winds swirl down from the mountain ridges and
churn up small, but powerful cyclones of snow or spray. Like
imaginary tops, these spin across the pond. The Appalachian Trail,
a 2,000-mile trek from Georgia to Maine, passes nearby. Also, just
to the east of the Beaver Pond, are Lost River, a self-guided tour
through a scenic gorge at Kinsman Notch, and the ``Monkey Ledges,''
a series of outcroppings with pale-brown profiles similar to rhesus
monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   From the pond, Route 112 descends into North Woodstock. On the
south side of the road, immediately east of I-93, is the White
Mountain Visitors Information Center. Here, Dick Hamilton, a
multitalented booster known locally as ``Mr. White Mountains,'' has
an office filled with memorabilia watercolor and oil landscape
paintings, hotel post cards and dinnerware, historic books,
pamphlets and posters, and eclectic items such as an intricate,
hand-carved walking stick.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
