<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV11     07-09 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITIONAL INVESTMENT MIX SHOULD PRODUCE FOR LONG-TERM INVESTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 11, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a 59-year-old male with no outstanding debts other than
a mortgage which will be paid off in four and a half years. I have
$350,000 in a SEP-IRA with $300,000 invested with Vanguard and the
remainder in MFS Total Return fund. At age 62 I plan to access
Social Security as well as to earn approximately $9,500 a year. My
wife is 10 years younger than me and has her own retirement plan. I
would like to withdraw 7 percent a year from the SEP, figuring that
if I have $400,000 in the account by age 62 it will produce
$28,000. With $12,000 from Social Security and $9,500 from my
earnings, this will give me $49,500 annual income. Do you have any
suggestions on the mix of my investments, considering inflation and
the possibility of need until age 90?
</P>
<P>
   E. R., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm not enthusiastic about this plan, but I do think you can
get within striking distance of your objective. Basically, what
you're proposing to do it establish a withdrawal plan that calls in
part upon stock market gains to support the income stream. I
calculate that the portfolio works out to about one third stocks,
with the balance in conservative fixed-income holdings such as
Vanguard GNMA, Short-Term Bond Index, Admiral Treasury Money
Market, and Intermediate-Term Treasury funds. This is a fairly
traditional mix for a person of your age, albeit a bit conservative
for my taste. The idea behind such a traditional portfolio is that
the fixed-income holdings will provide an income stream and the
stock portfolio will be left alone to produce growth of principal,
which will be called upon later in your retirement to offset the
effects of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   That all works out neatly enough, but when you set a withdrawal
schedule that exceeds the predictable yields of the fixed-income
side of the portfolio, you're doing two things I don't like. One is
that by pulling down some of the capital gains from the stock side,
you are hindering the ability of that part of the portfolio to do
its inflation-protecting job. Second, when you rely on growth of
stocks to support your plan, you put yourself in a position where
it's possible that a few bad market years could seriously upset
your apple cart.
</P>
<P>
   On the more positive side, it seems to me that you've made some
very moderate projections of portfolio growth from now until your
retirement age. Growth if the account from $350,000 to $400,000
over three years would represent a total return of only 4.55
percent a year; if you achieved average returns of 7 percent, the
pool would reach $428,765. And if you were to make one portfolio
more I am going to suggest _ swapping the money market fund for
shares of Vanguard High-Yield Corporate Bond fund _ the chances are
that returns and the accumulation would be even higher still.
</P>
<P>
   Besides swapping the money market fund for the junk bond fund, I
suggest that you do everything you can to build the fixed-income
side of the portfolio previous to your retirement. If you not only
reinvested all distributions from the bond funds on the
fixed-income side, but also thus invested the yield (but not
capital gains distributions) from the stock funds in one of your
middle-of-the-road bond funds, such as the GNMA offering, you might
anticipate that you would have nearly $290,000 in fixed-income
investments by the time you retire. (That calculation presumes a
6.5 percent average yield from your fixed-income portfolio side and
income distributions of 1.5 percent from your stock funds.) The
projected $290,000 pool could then be counted on to bring you an
$18,500 annual income stream, which puts you $9,500 a year under
your income projection.
</P>
<P>
   What's the answer? The only things I can suggest are probably
both going to look fairly painful to you. One is to save like mad
during your final working years, doing everything you can to build
that fixed-income portfolio as close as you can to the $400,000
that will fulfill your income stream while leaving the stock
portfolio aside for pure growth. The second, probably still more
unpleasant, is to re-budget for your retirement, cutting back on
your anticipated expenses to the point that they match the
anticipated yield from your fixed-income portfolio and your other
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 45-year-old woman who just came to this country two
months ago because of economic needs. I really don't know where I
can start with my savings. I will earn approximately $12,000 a
year. I already know this is no money, but I want to invest at
least $50 monthly in a fund _ but how?
</P>
<P>
   A.M., Downey, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. I applaud your resolution to get off to a good start, but I
think you may be preparing to move too quickly. Before you begin
investing in the kind of mutual funds which have the prospect for
strong long-term growth, you want to establish a sizable pool of
liquid savings.
</P>
<P>
   So my suggestion is to begin at your local bank with a simple
savings account, plugging away for the next 38 months until you
have amassed $2,000. At that point, I would suggest that you split
the pool, leaving half of it in the bank and putting the other half
in a fund which simply seeks to duplicate the results of the
nation's 1000 largest publicly-owned companies. Such a fund is
Schwab 1000 Investor Shares. You can get information on the fund by
simply calling one of Schwab's almost omnipresent brokerage
outlets, or by calling the firm at 1-800-435-4000. After you've
established the initial position, I suggest you then continue to
divide your ongoing savings evenly between the bank and the mutual
fund.
</P>
<P>
   During the rather long delay before you get to experience the
fun and satisfaction of investing proper, there are two things to
do _ one is to mail for information about the fund, including a
prospectus and an annual report, and study these carefully until
you're fully satisfied that you understand what you would be buying
and the risks that go with the investment. Equally important is my
second suggestion. Take a few sheets of notepaper and note down the
share price of your intended fund, obtaining the figures once a
week from the mutual fund reports in the newspapers. Then play a
little game, based on your weekly salary.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you spent all of one week's earnings on Schwab
1000 shares at current prices, you could buy about six fund shares.
So when you begin this game, multiply the share figure from the
paper times six and watch how the account would grow (or shrink) as
the market changes. If you follow this discipline for many months,
it should give you a pretty realistic idea of what to expect from
such an investment, and it will also teach you the effect that
capital gains and income distributions has on a fund portfolio. And
by the time that the 38 months of saving is up, it will also give
you a pretty good idea whether you are willing to commit your
hard-earned money to the uncertainties of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have accumulated a stock portfolio over the years and would
like to give some of it to my children. They intend to hold the
stock for their children's education. What is the cost basis of the
receiver of annual gifts of stock worth $10,000? I have been
receiving different advice about this.
</P>
<P>
   H.B., Bethlehem , Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. According to my favorite tax guide, the one pout out by J. K.
Lasser each year and now resembling the Manhattan telephone
directory, if the fair market value of the property equaled or
exceeded the donor's adjusted base cost at the time you received
the gift, your basis for figuring the gain or loss is the donor's
adjusted basis. If on the date of the gift the fair market value
was less than the donor's adjusted basis, your basis for figuring
gain is the donor's adjusted basis, and your basis for figuring
loss is the fair market value. There are additional provisions
which relate to gift taxes, but since you plan to keep your gifts
at $10,000 or less, they won't apply to the transaction you
propose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
