<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4375 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-HAMPSHIRE-2NDTAKE     07-09 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-HAMPSHIRE-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 CONWAY, N.H.: x x x walking stick.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once past North Woodstock, the highway continues through
Lincoln, then becomes the Kancamagus and begins a gradual easterly
climb beside the East Branch of the Pemigewasset (``swift
current'') River. Years ago, this part of the route served as
bedding for railroads that carried millions of feet of timber from
the forests.
</P>
<P>
   Near Loon Mountain in Lincoln sits an old black locomotive once
owned by the region's notorious lumber baron, J.E. Henry. Some of
his critics called him a ``butcher.'' But nowadays, 50 years after
the trains shut down, few signs remain along the Kanc of past
forest devastation. Sparkling streams, roadside trees and yellow
``moose crossing'' signs suggest that nature is reclaiming the
woods.
</P>
<P>
   From higher ground, though, for example, from atop 2,530-foot
Hedgehog Mountain, scars of past clear cutting become visible. Only
five miles east of Lincoln, with its ski slopes and acres of
apartment-like condominiums, the Kanc crosses a beautiful, scenic
stretch of the Pemigewasset's East Branch. A few hundred yards
north of the highway bridge, a graceful, narrow footbridge also
crosses this 160-foot-wide expanse. White-barked paper birches with
branches like filigrees line both sides of the highway. Hidden in
the nearby woods are parking lots, hiking trails to Franconia
Falls, and the Forest Service's Lincoln Woods Center, a sturdy,
rustic log cabin.
</P>
<P>
   This center, along with the Saco Ranger Station 30 miles to the
east in Conway, provides information and rules on camping, fishing,
swimming and hiking in the White Mountain National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   If you stop for extended periods along the Kanc, you must pay a
$5 parking fee. Also, don't feed the bears. Lincoln Woods hikers
may encounter abandoned campsites or other signs of past logging
and railroad activities. These include logging roads, ice ponds,
bridge abutments, old dumps, abandoned rails, railroad ties and
ironware. ``Removing any artifact,'' the Forest Service warns, ``is
strictly prohibited.''
</P>
<P>
   Trails continue past Franconia Falls and go deep into the
Pemigewasset Wilderness, all the way to The Cliffs and Mount Bond.
This is a long hike about 20 miles round trip. But, at least half
the en route terrain is near-level railroad bed.
</P>
<P>
   From Lincoln Woods, the Kanc climbs east-southeast for about
four miles, then reaches two sharp, hair-pin turns and three
overlooks. To the south, Mount Osceola (a Seminole chief's name,
``black drink''), Mount Kancamagus and other peaks form a back-lit,
3,000- to 4,000-foot-high mountain curtain. A nearby trail leads to
Lower and Upper Greeley Ponds. The latter, surrounded by tall
cliffs and old-growth timber, has an aqua-green color. Both offer
trout fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Doan, author of ``Fifty Hikes in the White Mountains,''
recommends Upper Greeley Pond as a summer picnic site. ``Spruces
and pointed firs rise toward the cliff and reflect in the still
water,'' he writes. ``Speckled trout break the surface to suck down
hatchling flies. Juncos and white-throated sparrows call from the
trees. Cedar waxwings flutter over the pond to catch bugs, then
return to a branch alongshore and preen their glossy feathers.
...''
</P>
<P>
   Not far from Greeley Ponds parking lot, the highway reaches its
highest point, 2,855 feet, and cuts through a beige-colored
outcropping at Kancamagus Pass. Again, the high terrain offers
magnificent, unobstructed views, this time looking east to carpets
of trees in the valley below.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the Kanc descends beside the Swift River, another
clear, sand-bottom stream, strewn with rocks and boulders and lined
with trees. Historic covered bridges cross the river in Albany and
Conway. About five miles east of the pass is Sabbaday Falls picnic
area and an easy 30- to 40-minute walk to the falls. A gentle,
introductory hike inclines along a small stream and arrives at a
shaded pool, perhaps 40 to 50 feet across, with a sheer
30-foot-high wall or cliff at the south end. Hemlock trees, with
drooping green branches and cinnamon-brown bark and cones, line the
pathway.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared steps and wooden railings allow safe walking inches
from the flumes.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is the Russell-Colbath House, a 167-year-old home that
carries one of the most poignant tales of the White Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   One night, in 1891, Ruth Priscilla Colbath's husband told her
he'd be back ``in a little while.'' Taking him at his word, she
left a lantern in the window, thinking he'd come around the bend
any time and the light would guide him home. With the faith of an
apostle, Mrs. Colbath lighted her lamp night after night, year
after year. Finally, after gallivanting about Cuba, Panama,
California and other warm-weather locales while his wife shivered
in New Hampshire, Tom Colbath returned to the small cape in
Passaconaway.
</P>
<P>
   As the headline in the Sept. 29, 1932, Boston Herald said, he
was a bit late: ``Man Returns After 42 Years to Find Home Empty;
Wife Who Lighted Window Every Night Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Colbath, after celebrating her 80th birthday alone, had
died three years earlier. Thinking her husband had died long
before, her relatives had divided up and distributed his estate. In
summer months, travelers can stop and visit the classic old cape
with its center chimney, shingled roof and small-pane windows that
overlook the wild and woolly Kanc.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Fred Stetson is a free-lance writer living in Burlington, Vt.)
</P>
</TEXT>
