<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDWEST-EXPRESS-BOS &LR;      07-09 1491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDWEST-EXPRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGING THE PRAISES OF MIDWEST HOSPITALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Airports are crowded; seats in coach are cramped; airline
food, if you get any at all, is terrible. Things are so bad that
Congress and passengers forced the air line industry last month to
acknowledge that passengers should be treated with more respect.
</P>
<P>
   What's an angry, frustrated traveler to do?
</P>
<P>
   For some, the answer is simple: Fly Midwest Express.
</P>
<P>
   In an era in which airlines are trying to eke out every dollar
they can, Milwaukee-based Midwest Express puts all of its
passengers into first-class-size leather seats aboard its DC-9s and
MD-80s at coach prices, and spends almost $10 per passenger, or
twice the industry average, on meals that are served on china with
linen napkins. In doing so, it has consistently turned a tidy
profit _ $36 million in earnings in 1998 on operating revenues of
$389 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Midwest Express difference was readily apparent on Flight
202 from Boston to Milwaukee last Saturday morning. The choices for
breakfast were a stunning fruit plate with fresh stawberries and
pineapple and cereal, or, for the bigger appetites, a cheese
omelette with sausage plus a fruit cup, yogurt and granola, and a
corn muffin. And complimentary champagne flowed as freely as the
coffee. On lunch and dinner flights, red or white wine also is
free.
</P>
<P>
   The flight was an hour late taking off _ but the ticket agent
gave a detailed reason why, without even being asked: a lightning
strike that knocked out air traffic control computers had meant
delays into Logan the night before. As a result, the flight crew
could not fly as soon as scheduled because of mandated rest
periods.
</P>
<P>
   While Midwest Express's regular and advance-purchase discounted
fares are competitive, the airline does not offer the range of
destinations major airlines do. So if passengers want to fly from
Boston to Seattle or Honolulu, they can't do it on Midwest Express.
And if they want to fly nonstop anywhere but Milwaukee or Kansas
City from Boston, they also have to pick another airline. But by
changing planes at Milwaukee's uncrowded airport, they can go on to
cities such as Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, or Orlando. Other
connections to San Francisco, Tamp, Ft. Lauderdale, and Ft. Myers
are seasonal.
</P>
<P>
   Although it flew only 1.9 million passengers last year _ a
minuscule number compared with US Airways' 58 million passengers _
Midwest Express has developed a loyal following.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Morris, a production director for Atlantic Monthly, says she
``rejoiced'' when a Wisconsin printing company won a contract with
her magazine, because it meant she would end up flying Midwest
Express frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seats are wide; they are always very polite to you; and
the food is so different,'' said Morris on a recent flight into
Boston. ``It is such a different and pleasant experience.''
</P>
<P>
   On most flights, the cabin takes on the aroma of a bakery as
chocolate chip cookies _ still warm from an on-board oven _ are
passed out for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite simply,'' said Morris, as a flight attendant passed out
some gooey cookies as the DC-9 flew 32,000 feet above Michigan
farmland, ``this is the best domestic airline experience there
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is not alone in crying Midwest's praises in the wild blue
yonder.
</P>
<P>
   For the past seven years Consumer Reports has rated the airline
tops in customer satisfaction. The Zagat Airline Survey recently
ranked Midwest Express the best domestic airline and the fourth
best in the world _ the first time a US airline has cracked the top
10.
</P>
<P>
   Midwest Express was born in the era of deregulation, an offshoot
of the corporate airline of Kimberly-Clark Corp., the tissue paper
and personal care products giant.
</P>
<P>
   Starting out as corporate aviation service, to carrry
Kimberly-Clark employees to far-flung paper mills, enabled Midwest
Express to focus on service, said Timothy E. Hoeksema, Midwest's
chairman and once the chief pilot for Kimberly-Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Kimberly-Clark, we were very frustrated after airline
deregulation (in 1978),'' said Hoeksema in a telephone interview.
``In the early 1980s, it proved very difficult to get around. We
thought if we were frustrated, other business people must be
frustrated too. . . . We had a chance to learn what business
travelers really want.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the airline did was focus on cities that bigger
airlines ignored. It avoided routes already crowded by several
airlines. For example, Midwest Express's hubs are in Milwaukee and
Omaha, not the top tier of American cities. Nor can you fly on
Midwest along the East Coast Boston-New York-Washington corridor _
one of the busiest air markets in the world _ unless you fly
through Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Midwest Express fares and discounts are competitive with those
of most major carriers. And if you are paying full fare for your
coach ticket, the airline seems like a bargain because of the size
of its seats and the quality of the service.
</P>
<P>
   Unrestricted round-trip coach fares from Boston to Milwaukee are
$861 on Midwest and $990 on Delta. Advanced purchase with a
Saturday night stay is $279 on Midwest and $297 on Delta. An
unrestricted roundtrip coach ticket from Boston to Los Angeles
costs $2,070 on United, which flies nonstop. On Midwest, which
requires a change of flights, the unrestricted fare is $1,258.50.
The cheapest Boston-Los Angeles roundtrip fare on United is $528.
On Midwest it is $685.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, you get what you pay for in life, and customers
aren't willing to pay much more for service. But if all things are
equal, you will take the airline that has better service,'' said
Glenn D. Engel, an airline analyst with Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. ``If
everyone tried to improve their service, they would have some
trouble, but (Midwest is) doing something different, by offering
great service and matching the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Midwest began operations in June 1984 and Boston-Milwaukee was
one of its first routes. The airline has been profitable since its
second year; even during the disastrous early 1990s, when the
airline industry collectively lost $13 billion, Midwest continued
to make money.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other airline was profitable during that time as well _
no-frills Southwest Airlines. But while Midwest Express spent an
average of $9.87 on each passenger's food and beverages last year,
Southwest Airlines, spent an average of 20 cents, according to
AVITAS, an aviation consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Solomon, 21, flies Midwest Express four or five times a
year because he is a senior at the University of Wisconsin. Two
years ago, he bought some Midwest stock. ``You are supposed to buy
what you know and all my friends fly it and we love it. They just
made you feel like you were in their home,'' said Solomon. ``I
didn't want to get off, and now I look forward to flying rather
than dreading it.''
</P>
<P>
   The value of Solomon's stock has doubled. And since the company
went public nearly four years ago, the stock price has quadrupled.
Goldman Sachs analyst Engel thinks the run up is not over. Last
month he issued a ``buy'' recommendation on Midwest Express stock,
in part because business travel is expected to increase. Midwest
Express shares closed Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange at 31
7/8, down 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   About 55 percent of all Midwest Express passengers are business
travelers, while the ratio for the rest of the industry is less
than 50 percent. By attracting a larger percentage of business
travelers than other carriers, even at competitively priced fares,
the airline says its revenue yields are 30 percent to 40 percent
higher than the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   Midwest plans to expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had 20 percent compounded annual growth and we are
committed to double digit _ 12 to 16 percent _ capacity growth, but
I am not smart enough to grow at 50 percent a year and maintain our
culture,'' said Hoeksema. ``If we brought too many new people on at
once it would hurt our culture. . . . We try to treat every
customer as if they were a guest in our home.''
</P>
<P>
   To maintain its service-oriented culture, Midwest Express fills
anywhere from 30 percent to 50 percent of positions on new routes
with employees experienced with the airline. ``It is a very
important formula to transfer the culture there,'' said Hoeksema.
The airline is looking to develop a third hub somewhere in the US
by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   One cost Midwest Express tries to keep down is aircraft
acquisition. Indeed, by buying only used planes, it has one of the
oldest fleets in the industry. But the planes it buys have
relatively few takeoff-and-landing cycles on them. Manufacturer
recommendations call for DC-9s to be retired after 110,000 cycles.
Midwest's fleet has an average of 50,000 cycles per plane, and its
schedule adds only 2,000 more per year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
