<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4381 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      07-09 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME STANDS STILL ON THE COAST OF MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With: MAINE-IF-GO.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DONNA MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Me. _ On a summer morning at the first light of dawn
in Portland, you can stand at harbor's edge and watch fishing boats
unload fresh catch onto docks, some to be distributed throughout
New England, some to be sold right in the town's own market.
</P>
<P>
   From its biggest cities like Portland, to its smallest villages,
like Bailey's Island, life in midcoast Maine hasn't changed all
that much over the years. Since the mid-1800s, when ``rusticators''
began coming north to enjoy Maine's bucolic summers, the state has
been a place to take refuge from the stress of everyday life. And
so, today, the fishing fleet in Portland's harbor shares its waters
with cruise ships, as many eastern seaboard cruise lines add
Portland to their ports of call.
</P>
<P>
   A convenient gateway to many Maine points, Portland is rapidly
becoming a destination of its own. It has been likened to San
Francisco and Seattle due to its urban blend of elegant
architecture, cultural offerings, gourmet restaurants and ethnic
pockets. The new Portland Public Market (modeled after Seattle's
Pike Place Market), a huge post-and-beam indoor farmer's market
with fish vendors, wine merchants, organic produce and coffee bars,
adds a further sheen of sophistication and livability to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jewel by the sea,'' poet Henry Wadsworth Longfellow called his
boyhood home of Portland. The city rises up on a hill overlooking
the shimmering water and islands of Casco Bay. Several fires
claimed many of Portland's early buildings, the last and most
devastating being the fire of July 4, 1866, when an Independence
Day firecracker severely damaged the city. But with wealth and
prosperity on its side, the city was rebuilt during the Victorian
era. Today, its well-preserved historic buildings reflect the
opulent, gracious style of the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The city's primarily brick edifices are complemented by
shingle-style homes designed by John Calvin Stevens, a prominent
architect and painter famous for his Mount Desert Island
millionaires' ``cottages.'' More grandiose is the Italianate-style
Victoria Mansion, on Danford Street at the corner of Park. The
palatial brownstone, commissioned by entrepreneur Ruggles Sylvester
Morse in the 1850s, features frescoed walls and ceilings, a flying
staircase, and other ornate embellishments.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Port Exchange is the city's gift to tourists and
residents alike. Although this district has been gentrified, it
hasn't been gussied up past the point of authenticity. The historic
buildings have been renovated, brick and cobblestone streets have
been preserved, and gas-lit lamps were added along several of the
sloping sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   This is where you'll find the lion's share of specialty shops,
gourmet restaurants, endless variations of coffee bars, and a dozen
or so galleries and fine craft shops. It is purported that Portland
has the highest number of restaurant seats per capita in the
country; the truth of that statement is supported by almost
overwhelming dining choices facing visitors.
</P>
<P>
   There are microbreweries with stylish restaurants (some even
offer tours of their brewing facilities), traditional mainstays
like the Seaman's Club and DeMillo's Floating Restaurant, and
upmarket trendy spots. The bulk of all these are located in the Old
Port Exchange area (some 100), but you can easily get a good meal
in almost every corner of town.
</P>
<P>
   Within walking distance of the Old Port, the I.M. Pei-designed
Portland Museum of Art is noted for its impressive Winslow Homer
collection, and for its broad collection of American and
Impressionistic masters. Heading up the list of the city's cultural
institutions, the Merrill Auditorium is a huge draw. The principle
venue for the Portland Symphony as well as guest performers and
entertainers from around the world, the hall was renovated in 1997
to the tune of nearly $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   While Portland can easily fill a two-day visit, eventually the
mythic Maine coast will beg to be explored. From Portland, the
midcoast towns of Brunswick, Bath and Wiscasset are within a short
drive and supply all the charm of coastal New England villages and
a bounty of cultural enjoyments as well.
</P>
<P>
   Brunswick is the quintessential New England college town. The
main street, Maine Street, is said to be the widest in the state
(nine rods, if that helps!). Driving east down Maine Street _ which
is home to several of the town's better restaurants, cafes, a
natural-food store, boutiques and art galleries _ you come to the
town green, or the ``mall'' as it's called, a rectangle of lawn
that in the winter serves as a skating rink and in the summer hosts
a twice-weekly farmers market that draws locals from miles around.
</P>
<P>
   One block farther and you are on the grounds of gracious Bowdoin
College. Among Bowdoin alumni, Nathaniel Hawthorne and Henry
Wadsworth Longfellow are two of its more noted. Another graduate,
Robert Edwin Peary, was the first to reach the North Pole during
his Arctic expeditions with fellow Bowdoin alum Donald Baxter
MacMillan.
</P>
<P>
   Mementos from his expeditions, and a collection of other arctic
and Inuit artifacts, are well exhibited at the Peary-MacMillan
Arctic Museum in Hubbard Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, the Bowdoin College Museum of Art in the Walker Building
is considered to house one of New England's finest art collections.
During summer months, Brunswick's claim to fame is the Maine State
Music Theatre, an annual summer series showcasing big-name talent
in Bowdoin College's historic Pickard Theatre. Musical offerings
take place all summer long in Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   There are weekly organ recitals at the historic First Parish
Church, an annual week-long jazz festival at Thomas Point Beach,
and a repertoire of musicians performing at the outdoor bandstand.
In addition to a well-endowed local historical museum, and a
substantial collection of well-preserved historic houses (one of
which, the Stowe House, now an inn, is where Harriett Beecher Stowe
lived while she penned ``Uncle Tom's Cabin''), Brunswick is well
steeped in New England history.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
