<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-RESEARCH-BOS &LR;      07-09 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RESEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US NUCLEAR SCIENTISTS FEAR CURBS ON INTERNATIONAL COOPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When India set off a nuclear test last year, the
State Department responded by blocking certain US physicists from
attending a conference in Bombay. Indian scientists were removed
from a project at Fermilab, the national physics lab near Chicago.
The Department of Energy even asked the lab to remove the Indian
flag from a multinational display at its main building.
</P>
<P>
   For the scientists involved, those were inconveniences. But now,
researchers are worried that international cooperation will suffer
even greater setbacks as Congress reacts to reports of alleged
nuclear spying by China.
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Sciences recently issued a statement of
``deep concern'' over the prospect of new legal restrictions on US
nuclear scientists working with their researchers overseas. The
academy plans a conference in August to highlight the benefits of
allowing certain types of joint research.
</P>
<P>
   When the board of the American Physical Society met last month
at Tanglewood, the discussion focused on whether Congress, in
trying to make US weapons labs more secure, would also hamper the
work of US scientists. ``We're busy worrying about it,'' said ob
Park of the physicists' group, who urged Congress not ``to
interfere with the very culture of openness that has given the US
the lead'' in sciences.
</P>
<P>
   And from the classrooms of Boston to universities on the West
Coast, scientists report a pervasive fear that Congress will limit
their contact with foreigners or otherwise damage the climate for
international projects. At Northeastern University, for example,
physicists worry that the frosty US-China relations will undermine
support for a multimillion-dollar particle accelerator that China
had shown tentative interest in building.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a massive contribution to world science, and it
worries me that it would die because of some political problem,''
said Stephen Reucroft, a physics professor at Northeastern.
</P>
<P>
   The fears underscore the way science is changing in the era of
the Internet and big-money projects. Increasingly, cutting-edge
research brings together top scientists from several nations _
partly because foreign science programs have improved and partly
because large projects, such as studying a global environmental
trend or building a large telescope, involve great cost and
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   The global cooperation shows up in the large increase in
scientific papers with authors from different nations. The number
of internationally co-authored articles jumped 200 percent between
1981 and 1995, the National Science Foundation reports, while the
total number of papers rose only 20 percent. Nearly one-third of
all US scientific papers included foreign co-authors in 1995, up
from 18 percent in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Longtime debate
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, debate has ebbed and flowed over the past 20
years on how much access foreigners should have to US universities
and labs. But the nation has generally supported the idea of
building ``high fences around narrow areas'' of sensitive research,
and of allowing broad access to the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Congress is considering new restrictions as it
sorts out how to respond to two reports on security problems at US
weapons and physics labs that are supervised by the Department of
Energy.
</P>
<P>
   The first report, from a panel led by Representative Christopher
Cox, Republican of California, alleged that the Chinese government
had stolen nuclear secrets from US weapons labs. The Cox report
also pointed to a problem in corporate work overseas, saying that
US satellite companies gave the Chinese information that allowed
them to improve their ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The second panel, created by President Clinton and led by former
US senator Warren Rudman, charged that the Energy Department is so
``dysfunctional'' that it cannot be trusted to improve security at
national labs. It urged Congress to restructure the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government reacted angrily to the Cox report and
denied any espionage. Relations deteriorated further after NATO
bombed the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia, and China allowed unruly
protests at the US Embassy in Beijing. In Congress, some lawmakers
called for new restrictions on scientists not only from China, but
from Russia and other ``sensitive'' nations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Little impact yet
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, the actual impact on scientists from the dust-up with
China seems to be little more than fear and injured morale. Some
foreign-born graduate students offered positions at Department of
Energy research labs have turned them down out of fear that their
ability to work will soon be restricted, said E. William
Colglazier, executive officer of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as lawmakers continue to debate new restrictions,
scientists say they are uneasy. So are some foreign scientists
working on projects with US researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have received e-mails from three Chinese organizations in
high-energy physics or other fields of physics, where the Chinese
are questioning whether the collaboration is still on,'' said
Wolfgang Panofsky, former director of the Stanford Linear
Accelerator Center in California.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists' fears turns on several developments in Congress:
</P>
<P>
   --Lawmakers in both the House and Senate have proposed a
moratorium on visits to the American nuclear research labs, or to
parts of those labs, by scientists from ``sensitive'' countries
such as China or Russia. One version of the idea has passed a House
committee and is attached to a major bill that will soon reach the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists fear that this and similar restrictions would limit
scientific exchanges, which even some intelligence experts say is a
crucial element of cutting-edge science. ``In high-stakes research,
like nuclear weaponry, you have to have your guys not only develop
new concepts but get out and see what the top 100 or so people in
the world in the same area are doing,'' said Paul Moore, former
chief China counterintelligence analyst at the FBI. ``If you don't,
you are guaranteeing yourself a second-rate development program.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some security specialists say that China and Russia
would retaliate if the United States put its nuclear labs
off-limits to their researchers. And that, they say, would hamper
US efforts to counsel foreign scientists on converting weapons labs
to civilian research and on protecting weapons-grade material so
that it cannot be stolen and sold on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inevitable that there will be damage to these
forms of cooperation, and it's too bad, because they are very much
in the US's security interests,'' said John Holdren, a Harvard
University professor who leads the National Academy of Sciences
panel on international security and arms control.
</P>
<P>
   --The Rudman report recommended that Congress bring new security
oversight to nuclear research labs, either by creating a new,
independent security agency or a unit within the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists fear that an independent weapons agency would
make it harder for weapons scientists to cross back and forth to
the world of civilian research. ``You're not going to get top
weapons scientists to work in a pure weapons environment,'' said
Park of the American Physical Society. Scientists who work on
classified research cannot publish their work and advance their
reputations, he said, so they would leave the weapons labs.
</P>
<P>
   --Among its 38 recommendations, the Cox report called for the
inspectors general at five agencies, including the departments of
State, Defense, and Energy, to study scientific exchange programs
at the US national laboratories for their risk to national
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that absolutely outrageous recommendation,'' said
Panofsky. ``First, inspectors general are not particularly
qualified to review scientific exchange programs. And second,
whenever you want to find the correct course of action, you have to
look at benefits as well as risks.''
</P>
<P>
   For Boston, the ultimate fear is that lawmakers will revive an
effort, last considered during the Reagan administration, to limit
the type of scientific training that US universities may provide to
students from certain foreign nations. US universities award 40
percent of their doctorates in science and engineering fields to
foreign nationals. They included 16,500 from China between 1988 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a valid concern, and I think it's something
people should be thinking about and worrying about as they spin out
the possibilities of the direction in which this could escalate,''
said Holdren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's not an unrealistic fear to have, and I'm worried
about it,'' Colglazier said.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the fears are overblown. To begin with, China has
sent signals that it wants to repair relations with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Rudman report said it is possible to allow an open
exchange of most information while protecting the most sensitive
secrets. And Congress, after careful consideration, will come to
the same conclusion, said Michael Lubell, chairman of the physics
department at City College of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooler heads will prevail,'' said Lubell, who is also public
affairs chief for the American Physical Society. ``The issue won't
be as much the isolation of scientists as it will be whether the
Department of Energy can take action (to protect nuclear secrets)
when the need arises.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4386 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-2NDTAKE-HNS &LR;      07-09 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 PORTLAND, Me.: x x x New England history.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A historical walking-tour map can be picked up at the Pejepscot
Historical Society on Park Row. Brunswick is also the starting
point for a drive along the ``fingers'' that reach deep into Casco
Bay and bring you to nearby rustic fishing villages and seaside
summer colonies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shortly into the drive along Route 123 south past Bowdoin
College you might be surprised to see water on both sides; in
Brunswick it is easy to forget that you are in a coastal Maine
town, but now you're squarely in ``lobstah country.''
</P>
<P>
   Here you'll see lobster pots, lobster buoys, lobster boats and
yes, lobsters, too. You can buy them directly from the fishermen on
any number of docks. The ways and places to eat lobster are
seemingly endless here; The Dolphin Marina in South Harpswell is
one of the best (but don't miss out on its excellent fish chowder).
</P>
<P>
   Continue to drive along the coast through West Harpswell and
you'll wind up at Potts Point, a quaint resort community whose
summer residents inhabit colorful 19th-century cottages. It's also
worthwhile to stop and visit the studios of the islands' many
artists, most of which are attached to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Harpswell Craft Guild publishes a map to help visitors
locate their members; look for it at convenience stores and
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Backtrack down Route 123 and in a couple of miles you'll see the
sign for Mountain Road, on your right. This road connects two
``fingers'' of the peninsula via a bridge. Follow signs on Route 24
for Bailey Island. This peninsula is distinguished by a unique
rustic granite block bridge connecting Bailey Island to Orr's
Island.
</P>
<P>
   The famous Cribstone Bridge is the only remaining one like it in
the world. Crossing the bridge, the view of Merriconeag Sound is
breathtaking, and the other bonus: You're in the midst of excellent
restaurants such as Cook's Lobster House, which you'll see just
across a boat-filled bay on the right. At the very end of this
peninsula, there's a small parking area adjacent to a gift shop and
a cluster of rocks known as Land's End. Explore the shore; it's
classic Maine.
</P>
<P>
   In less than an hour, you can drive from the snail's pace of
small island living to the hustle and bustle of an active seafaring
town that also owes its existence to its direct proximity to the
water. Once the cradle of a boisterous seafaring economy, Bath is
now considered the cradle of culture in the midcoast region, with
shipbuilding continuing to provide for a thriving economy thanks to
The Bath Iron Works, an active naval shipyard whose giant cranes
rise high over the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Like a typical seaport city, Bath's prosperity is reflected in
the impressive homes of its sea captains and merchants, who in the
mid-19th century erected grand Italianate, Georgian Revival and
Greek Revival mansions. Washington Street and North Street frame
the once well-to-do neighborhoods that hug the Kennebec River. Some
of the grand homes have remained private residences; others have
been converted to inns and lodging establishments.
</P>
<P>
   The town boasts some of the midcoast's nicest B&AMP;Bs. Along the
banks of the Kennebec River, the Maine Maritime Museum is an
extensive complex encompassing several museum buildings and the
Percy &AMP; Small Shipyard, the country's only surviving yard that
builds wooden ships.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1870 and 1890, Down Easters were the schooner of choice
for moving coal and other heavy loads by water. These schooners
were built in Bath, and the museum has a considerable collection of
artifacts and a research library. During the summer, the museum
offers river tours and boat rides, and several special-themed
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Bath has actively fostered a reputation for being an arts center
over the years. In addition to a denizen of art galleries,
throughout the summer art shows are frequently held in the park in
front of the elegant town library. The centerpiece of the Bath arts
scene is the Chocolate Church, a converted Congregational Church,
where year-round plays, concerts and guest artists perform, most
often to sell-out crowds.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a gallery inside the brown board-and-batten
structure, named after its deep chocolate color.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the Carlton Bridge over the Kennebec, Route 1 continues
on to a town that bills itself modestly as ``the prettiest village
in Maine'' _ Wiscasset. There is no argument that this quiet town
offers some of the prettiest houses, prettiest views and prettiest
stores you will ever see. Just before it reaches the Sheepscot
River, Route 1 passes through a picture-perfect village center.
</P>
<P>
   On one side, an upscale gourmet cheese and wine shop is tucked
in a narrow, country weathered storefront; and on the other a fine
antiques dealer caters to out-of-town visitors. Down the hill,
Red's Eats is practically a summertime institution. At lunch hour
there are lines for the fried clams and lobster rolls at this
bright-red take-out stand.
</P>
<P>
   Don't leave town without stopping at Castle Tucker, built in
1807 by a local judge for his wife. As if its stunning views of the
Sheepscot River weren't enough, the judge had the house built in
the elegant style of an aristocrat. The Victorian furnishings and
much of the wallpaper are original, but its free-standing
elliptical staircase gets most of the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Wiscasset like almost every sizable Maine village is ultimately
best explored on foot, or by bike. The ebb and flow of a Maine
seaside village is in the details that are too easily missed in a
drive-through visit. It is the fragrance of an untamed flower box,
the fog as it lifts off the shore at sunrise, or an impromptu
conversation with a Down Easterner, that create the memories you'll
take home with you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Donna Marshall is a free-lance writer in Brunswick, Maine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
