<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYCLISTS USE NET TO PROTEST   ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As BankBoston Corp. and ad agency Hill Holliday Connors
Cosmopulos have just found out, e-mail and on-line chat rooms can
make it easier for even a handful of folks to orchestrate protests
about ads they deem objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a BankBoston TV ad that included footage of a
pregnant pedestrian dodging a bicycle messenger incited a mini flap
of sorts among some bike commuters who felt their preferred mode of
travel had been gratuitously maligned.
</P>
<P>
   Because the ad was near the end of a six-week run when
complaints surfaced last week, there was no need to make a decision
on whether to pull it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never intended to offend anyone, and we apologize if anyone
took it that way,'' said Jane Post, director of the BankBoston
department that oversees advertising. ``That's true of everything
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad in question was part of a campaign that featured the
theme ``This is your time. Spend it wisely.'' As a voiceover noted
how BankBoston offers time-saving solutions that empower consumers
to take control of their finances, the video offered up vignettes
of city dwellers coping with urban life.
</P>
<P>
   One ad's imagery is open to different interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   According to BankBoston, the ad showed a pregnant woman on her
way to work, dodging other pedestrians and car traffic. In a brief
scene, she jumped back to avoid a bicycle messenger, who says
something to her. Viewers didn't hear what the cyclist said.
</P>
<P>
   In the opinion of Jim Merrick, a 46-year-old librarian who
regularly commutes by bike, the ad portrays bicycle riders as
ruffians on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was rather appalled,'' he said. ``It was offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrick didn't get mad or even. Instead, he got on the Internet
to seek out like-minded souls. In one e-mail, he described the ad
as ``Snarling cyclist nearly wipes out pregnant-woman pedestrian.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon e-mails were proliferating, and some said cyclists should
think about closing their BankBoston accounts in protest.
</P>
<P>
   One of those contacted was Luc Levensohn, an information
technology manager who commutes by bike several times a week
between his Boston office and his home north of the city.
</P>
<P>
   According to Levensohn, Boston is a most inhospitable city for
bicyling, and the BankBoston ad reinforces local attitudes that
cyclists should be held in low regard.
</P>
<P>
   Levensohn estimated that nearly 100 cyclists were recruited to
contact BankBoston and ask that the ad be pulled.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston said it received seven complaints about the ad. For
the bank, a key question was whether these complaints represented a
spontaneous outpouring of dissatisfaction with the ad or the work
of a few well-wired individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven people who complained, BankBoston concluded that
only one had actually seen the ad and the rest were responding to
on-line ``networking,'' Post suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Hill Holliday spokesman Eric Fehrnstrom offered the agency's
view of the ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not the intention of the ad to show bicyclists in a
negative light,'' he said, adding, ``We could just as easily shown
a taxi or motorcycle roaring past, but then I suppose we would have
risked offending cab drivers and motorcyclists.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the ad was insensitive or whether cyclists were being
too touchy is open to debate. But one thing is clear: The Internet
makes it easier for individual consumers upset by ads to
orchestrate protests and make advertisers uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting to see how this unfolds,'' said
Post of BankBoston. ``You may see more and more of this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom and Ray Magliozzi, a.k.a. Click and Clack, have hosted ``Car
Talk'' on National Public Radio for more than 20 years. Now they
have their first ad campaign. Print ads are about to break, and TV
ads are in the works from Mullen, a Wenham, Mass. ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   NPR stations ``asked us'' for an ad campaign that would talk up
Tom and Ray, said Doug Berman, ``Car Talk'' producer.
</P>
<P>
   Many folks are a bit intimidated by NPR's highbrow repuation.
But if they can be persuaded to try ``Car Talk,'' they might change
their minds _ and stick around for other NPR shows.
</P>
<P>
   Created by the Mullen tag team of Stephen Mietelski and Michael
Ancevic, the first print ads feature the theme ``A Survivalist's
Guide for Listening to Car Talk.'' Ads suggest ``Car Talk'' is such
a showcase of hilarity that listeners who don't take proper
precautions might be hurt by the convulsions of laughter that Tom
and Ray induce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
