<SLUG> BC-CONNECTICUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A TASTE OF CONNECTICUT, GO BEYOND THE SUBURBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEANNE LeBLANC and DON STACOM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Connecticut has a contradictory public image,
seen as a bland suburb of New York yet regarded as a backwater of
traditional Yankee stodginess.
</P>
<P>
   There is truth in both views, but neither is even close to the
whole story. The part of Fairfield County known as the Gold Coast
is truly oriented toward New York. From stately Westport (home of
Paul Newman) to trendy New Canaan (home of David Letterman) to
wealthy Greenwich, most everybody works, or at least shops, in
Manhattan. It's even considered part of the New York television
market.
</P>
<P>
   This area is also a convenient gateway to New York for visitors.
Guests can stay at the Sheraton or Marriott hotels in Stamford for
a third of the price of a comparable room in midtown Manhattan,
take a 45-minute train ride to Grand Central Terminal for $10 and
enjoy a day in the big town without risking their cars in the
maddening traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But the true flavor of Connecticut does not start to come
through until you move away from the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   Heading east along the shoreline, about 45 minutes from Stamford
on Interstate 95, is New Haven, home of stately Yale University and
its many museums, including the Yale University Art Gallery, the
Yale Center for British Art and the Peabody Museum of Natural
History. The leafy area around Yale has a college-town atmosphere,
with trendy shops and ethnic restaurants. New Haven is also
renowned for its thin-crust pizza; try Frank Pepe's Pizzeria
Napoletana on Wooster Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Yale Repertory Theater produces performances by Yale drama
students, professional actors and guest troupes. The Schubert
Performing Arts Center and the Long Wharf Theater are both known
for staging Broadway-bound shows.
</P>
<P>
   To the east of New Haven, out in the woods near the Rhode Island
border, are two of the newest, largest casinos in the world:
Foxwoods Resort Casino and the Mohegan Sun. They have all the
polish of the big Vegas casinos with none of the glitz, creating a
more subdued and somewhat more elegant atmosphere, even in the
grim-faced, chain-smoking slot-machine sections.
</P>
<P>
   Foxwoods, owned by the Mashantucket Pequot tribe, rises out of
the woods of the reservation near Ledyard like a medieval city. It
is the largest, most profitable casino on the planet. Ten miles
away, the Mohegan Sun casino, nationally recognized for the
striking blend of traditional and modern elements in its
architecture, is an up-and-coming competitor.
</P>
<P>
   The tribal rivalry is in at least its fourth century. When the
Pequots opened a critically acclaimed museum near their casino, the
Mohegans protested the museum's account of a massacre of the
Pequots in 1637 by English colonists. The Mohegans' ancestors are
portrayed as collaborators with the English.
</P>
<P>
   Just south of the casinos is Mystic Seaport, the nation's
largest maritime museum (think Sturbridge Village by the sea) with
a working shipyard producing replicas of vintage sailing vessels.
The nearby Mystic Marinelife Aquarium has whales, dolphins, seals
and all manner of other ocean creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Two nearby restaurants are worth keeping in mind, if you feel
like a splurge: Randall's Ordinary in North Stonington serves
18th-century hearth-cooked meals in rustic fire-lit dining rooms
(there is a pleasant small inn on the premises), and Abbott's
Lobster in the Rough in Noank (open during the summer only) has
spectacular seafood in a casual ocean-view setting.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour inland, in the center of the state, is Hartford,
the capital city. It is so closely identified with the insurance
industry, its dominant business, that an annoyed Boston Globe
columnist last year called it ``America's file cabinet.'' The
columnist was annoyed because Hartford, as part of a nascent urban
renaissance, was trying to lure away the New England Patriots with
promises of a new riverfront stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Hartford has some remarkable gems.
</P>
<P>
   The Wadsworth Atheneum, the first public art museum in the
United States, has a large collection of European and American art
and houses the Amistad Foundation African-American Collection. The
Mark Twain House, where the author wrote ``Tom Sawyer,''
``Huckleberry Finn'' and other novels, stands next to the Harriet
Beecher Stowe House, home of the abolitionist author of ``Uncle
Tom's Cabin.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Park, on the West Hartford border, has extensive rose
gardens that peak late in June. Expect to see brides there on sunny
Saturdays, being photographed among the flowering shrubs and
arbors. There are many noteworthy museums within 20 minutes of
downtown Hartford, including the Hill-Stead Museum in Farmington,
which features a fine collection of French impressionist paintings;
the New Britain Museum of American Art, with a collection of more
than 4,000 American artworks and a growing reputation for
innovative exhibits; and Dinosaur State Park, where an enclosure
protects a slew of 200-million-year-old dinosaur footprints.
</P>
<P>
   From Hartford, it's another hour's drive to the Litchfield Hills
in the northwestern part of the state, a favorite destination of
well-to-do New Yorkers in search of a respite. In some towns the
summer population nearly equals the year-round population. This is
where Connecticut looks most like a part of New England, with
church spires poking above the trees of traditional town greens
that once served as communal pastures. Antiques shopping is among
the more vigorous pursuits for visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Litchfield Hills attractions are more aesthetic than active,
more about seeing than doing. Gardeners may want to make a
pilgrimage to White Flower Farm in the town of Litchfield, one of
the pre-eminent plant nurseries in the country with 10 acres of
display gardens. The Glebe House Museum in Woodbury, site of the
only garden in the United States planned by the British garden
designer Gertrude Jekyll, is also worth a visit.
</P>
<P>
   In autumn the roads in the Litchfield Hills are full of
leaf-peepers, in search of that quintessential photo of flaming
trees and New England countryside. One place with a good chance of
providing it is the picturesque village of West Cornwall, where a
135-year-old covered wooden bridge spans the Housatonic River.
</P>
<P>
   The view of Connecticut from that bridge is tranquil, timeless
and very Yankee. Maybe it's a stereotype, or else just part of a
much bigger picture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jeanne Leblanc and Don Stacom are free-lance writers in
Burlington, Conn.)
</P>
</TEXT>
