<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS BETTER AT COMMUNITY LENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Birds gotta fly. Advocates gotta advocate.
</P>
<P>
   That explains why advocates for a long list of community groups
crowded into an auditorium at the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston
this week to complain about the pending merger between Fleet
Financial Group and BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   The activists, including the Rev. Al Sharpton, argued that the
$14.6 billion the two banks plan to set aside for small business
and low-income lending is inadequate. Because this is the perfect
time to exert pressure, at least some of the activists laid it on
pretty thick.
</P>
<P>
   They staged demonstrations. They shouted ``shame on you'' when
bank executives explained the benefits of the deal. They warned of
hard times ahead for minorities in the city unless the banks agreed
to do more.
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame the advocates. Their job is to make things sound
as bad as possible so they can get the maximum amount of dollars
for their cause. But in the interest of the truth, it's worth
bringing a little perspective to the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, things have gotten an awful lot better in Boston
when it comes to banks and the money they make available to the
city's low-income and minority residents.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago banks were as rare as roof decks in the city's poor
neighborhoods. But beginning in 1989, prodded by the government,
community activists, and a landmark Federal Reserve study on
mortgage lending to minorities, the banks changed their ways.
</P>
<P>
   They put up branches in low-income neighborhoods. They installed
dozens of automated teller machines in those same neighborhoods.
And perhaps most importantly, they turned on the lending spigot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, banks and other lenders made 287 mortgage loans to
blacks in Boston. By 1996 that number was up to 900. Over the same
time mortgages to Hispanics climbed from 96 to nearly 400,
according to statistics gathered by Jim Campen, an associate
profesor of economics at the University of Massachusetts at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   With a slight lag, the same thing started to happen all around
the country. In a recent report, the Joint Center for Housing
Studies at Harvard University pointed out that minorities now
account for more than 30 percent of all first-time home buyers, up
from less than 20 percent in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, banks made a remarkable discovery: You could do
business in central cities and make a profit. Citizens Bank, which
has 25 percent of its Massachusetts branches in areas the US Census
Bureau calls low- and moderate-income tracts, has done well in
those branches, even selling mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My customers there aren't being bombarded by Chase and
Fidelity every night,'' Citizens vice chairman Robert Mahoney once
explained.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, competition for urban business has heated up. Citizens
says applications for the small business loans it sees these days
typically are shopped to several other banks. There is also
increased competition for mortgage business.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Between 1995 and 1997, Fleet's mortgage loans to local
minorities dropped sharply, according to Campen's tally. The bank
doesn't dispute the finding, but says the drop-off was the result
of problems in its mortgage unit, not any deliberate pullback from
low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Yet over that same two-year period, loans to blacks and
Hispanics in the city stayed roughly flat. In other words, the void
left by Fleet was filled by other competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The message here is not that all the problems of the central
city have been solved. Far from it. Robert Fichter, an executive
with the Massachusetts Bankers Association, points out a relatively
new one: affordability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a modest home in a city neighborhood now costs $200,000,
that's a problem,'' says Fichter. Call it one of the perils of
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe this week reported on growing fears of
gentrification in Roxbury. Professionals, both white and black, are
buying up houses in the neighborhood, paying prices that sound more
appropriate for Lexington than Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   Under those circumstances, even banks willing to make mortgage
loans are not going to be able to put low- and middle-income people
into houses. The numbers just won't work.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates may yet have their way. The banks could
conceivably decide to boost their community lending. In today's
booming economy they could probably afford it without much
sacrifice to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, don't believe it when someone tells you
that we're not going back to the bad old days. The world has
changed too much for that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock Funds, the mutual fund arm of the big insurance
company, Thursday said chief executive Edward J. Boudreau Jr. will
retire at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Ford, president of Hancock's broker/dealer distribution
network, will replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau, 54, has been with Hancock for 32 years, the last 11 as
head of the mutual fund complex. Over that time the firm's assets
under management grew from $3 billion to $34 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, Hancock's funds have had their
problems. ``They have a good brand name but they have been under
pressure,'' said Chris J. Brown, an analyst with Financial Research
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   After years of great performance, Hancock's best-known fund, its
Regional Bank fund, has struggled over the past year, which has
prompted investors to pull their money out, said Brown. As a
medium-sized player in the fund business, Hancock has also had
difficulty building the critical mass it needs for success, Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
