<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUTTERS ARE NOT ALWAYS NECESSARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 11, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I bought a 100-year-old house with a fieldstone foundation
and no gutters. It would be hard to install gutters, but the ground
is eroding away from the house where water constantly cascades. The
roof overhang is about 12 inches. Do I really have to put in
gutters? I have plenty of space to regrade, even allowing the
ground to slope down from the house, but how can I keep the ground
from eroding further? There is a sump and a sump pump in the
basement, but I have gotten no leaks so far.
</P>
<P>
   MARK GENDREAU, Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The handyman is not popular with gutter people when he says
gutters are not always necessary, but I think in some cases gutters
are, indeed, not needed. Yours is one of them. Your roof overhang
is more than adequate to allow cascading water to clear the house
wall. Regrading will allow that water to run down, away from the
house. To prevent further erosion, build a concrete apron about 6
inches deep and 18 inches wide, on the earth along each side of the
house, right up against the foundation. Slope it very slightly.
This will help prevent splashing water from bouncing back to the
house and also slow down the flow away from the house.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman's colonial house has a six-inch overhang on all
four sides of the house, and a concrete apron. It has worked well
for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have to replace my outdoor wood steps. Would you recommend
cedar as opposed to pressure-treated wood? I understand
pressure-treated wood cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ED LETIC, Leominster, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Cedar is acceptable for steps; it resists decay. I suggest
that you use pressure-treated for the stringers and cedar for the
treads; there is no need for risers (the board that sets just below
the treads). Space the tread boards to allow drainage. You could
leave the cedar as is, apply a sealer, or treat it with a
semitransparent stain. If the treads drain properly, and do not
stay wet but dry out between wettings, the treads will last
inedefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure-treated wood may crack. It may spall, it may splinter,
and it may do other things that wood does outdoors. That is because
it dries out after installation and shrinks. And it may not.
Treating it with a wood preservative or sealer may help prevent
this.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What kind of a waterproofing paint can I use on a window in
the bathroom. It is right in the bath/shower area, so it gets a lot
of water.
</P>
<P>
   ANNE MARTIN, Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I'll bet that windows were installed over the bathtub in old
houses long before Americans got into the daily shower habit.
</P>
<P>
   Interior paints are water resistant; some may stand up to wear
and tear and water better than others. Try this to paint the
window. Zinsser makes an acrylic interior paint called Perma-White,
which not only resists moisture if applied properly but also is
mildew-resistant. If there is mildew present, treat the wood with
one part household bleach and three parts water, to kill the
mildew. Rinse. Wear skin and eye protection when working with
bleach. Apply a latex enamel undercoater and one coat, possibly
two, of the Perma-White, which can be tinted.
</P>
<P>
   To get around this, cover the window with a shower-type curtain.
This is what Arlys Sakata of Wichita, Kan., suggested. Be sure to
open the curtain when done showering so you don't trap moisture
between it and the window.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Walden of Harwich said she uses plastic blinds with narrow
slats. Install them on the full casing, close the slats when
showering, open them to dry out, then raise the blind out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am having my bathroom redone. The clawfoot tub is
unsightly. What can I do about it? I also plan to put big ceramic
tile (12 inches square) on the floor. The contractor said such big
tiles break easily when installed. How can I keep them from
breaking?
</P>
<P>
   MARY LOU COVENEY, Jamaica Plain, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you can find a buyer, you can make a bundle on a clawfoot
tub. New ones in catalogs sell for $700 and up, way up, beyond
$1,000. You can try advertising in the Want Advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   But you might be able to spruce it up. If the inside is dirty,
try this: Wet it with hydrogen peroxide, apply cream of tartar, and
leave for an hour or so. Scrub and rinse. If the tub is still bad,
you could have it resurfaced. Then paint the outside a contrasting
color, and still another color for the clawfeet.
</P>
<P>
   And, you can buy a surround-type shower rod, one that lets the
curtain cover all four sides of the tub. Home Goods and other
specialty shops sell such rods and curtains.
</P>
<P>
   As for the big tiles, they won't break if installed on an even
surface with thin-set mortar. Breakage usually occurs when the
surface is uneven or rises a little; the tile then rocks when
stepped on and breaks.
</P>
<P>
   To get around this, on an uneven surfaces, use small tiles; six
inches square will do. Small tiles will look better in a small
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
