<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RIP-ROARING ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Approaching a 100th birthday, a human of the species barely gets
around, dwells on Thursdays instead of an extremely finite number
of tomorrows, and is petrified of taking a nasty fall.
</P>
<P>
   But as the US economy roars into its 100th consecutive month of
continued expansion, the old girl is exceedingly spry, jacked up on
a steady diet of low interest rates. Even the one-notch
quarter-percent belt-tightening telegraphed in advance and eased
down with some of old Doc Greenspan's castor oil had the opposite
effect he intended. That goosed the Dow Jones average to a new
high, instead of taking some of the hot air out of the economic
balloon.
</P>
<P>
   The bears, the contrarians, the short-sellers, the
gloom-and-doomers, the dusty academics who periodically break forth
with ``you'll be sorr-eeeeee'' if you don't hunker down in advance
of the coming crash, have omelette all over their long faces.
</P>
<P>
   Because this here epidemic of economic optimism eclipses the
JFK-LBJ war-fueled expansion of the '60s. There's never been an
economic expansion as long and as lusty as this one.
</P>
<P>
   Even our new treasury secretary, Lawrence Summers, quaffed some
of the feel-good moonshine in his very first week on the job: ``If
we can keep our fundamentals strong and continue the terrific
productivity improvement, I think we have got room to give people
wage increases that run ahead of price increases and represent
really higher standards of living,'' Summers told NBC.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred months and climbing. We keep spending to beat the
bend, both as consumers, and as public officials. Twenty-five years
ago, Americans saved almost 10 percent of the weekly paycheck. In
May, the savings level was minus 1.2 percent. And that spending
spree is what is boosting retail sales, home construction, and new
vehicles flying off dealer lots.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary dent in government spending that was arrived at
only after vast verbiage and much deal-making makes the deficit
picture uncharacteristically rosier than it has been since the
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   It is conceivable, President Clinton said with reasonable
grounds for contending such, that in 15 years, every debt owed by
Uncle Sam to anyone anywhere will be paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The red ink total is currently $5.6 trillion. But with the
economy going gangbusters, and tax revenue falling from the sky
into the treasury's coffers, the debt can be halved within five
years, and even more money saved by not having to pay interest to
government bond-holders. Of course, that scenario will be blown to
smithereens by a sharp recession, a war, the precipitate collapse
of some important financial institution, or an asteroid hitting
Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Such a deliriously ambitious goal _ paying off all the debt
accumulated over two and a half centuries _ would also probably
require the repeal of a substantial portion of human nature. I
refer to that part of the politician's DNA which propels the
politician to say ``yes'' when ``no'' is the right answer.
</P>
<P>
   You get elected by saying ``yes;'' you also go into debt when
saying ``yes.'' And the Klown Kollege that is our Krazy Kongress
kannot say ``no'' when the simple negative is what is required. The
rosy projections made possible by the zooming economy presume and
imply that fiscal discipline will be exerted.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Democrats can't go bananas devising new social
spending schemes, and the Republicans can't get their jollies
handing out tax cuts to fat cats. Don't bet on either side not
taking the easy way out. President Clinton this week bravely toured
some of the nation's poverty spots, trying to persuade the rich to
remember the poor.
</P>
<P>
   With his uncanny knack for not seeming to promise any more than
he might possibly deliver, Clinton stressed private-sector
solutions and government tax breaks for targeted investments in
run-down areas. But with their penchant for crashing through the
guardrail every time their bus rounds a curve near a precipice, the
Republicans sprang their tax-cut-for-them-that's-already-made-it.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where the Republicans take their polls. It must be
at the country club bar, the board room picnic, or wherever
plutocrats prevail. Because passing a tax cut at the moment is the
most pressing government need to only one American in 11, according
to The Wall Street Journal/NBC poll, while one in four say it is
building up public schools, one in five say it is fixing Social
Security, and one in six say it is improving morality.
</P>
<P>
   But slice a Republican, and out bleeds a tax cut. It's in the
bloodstream, apparently. So the solons of the majority party,
joined by the more opportunistic of their Democratic benchmates,
trot out the old 
let's-make-it-easier-on-the-rich-but-pretend-we're-doing-it-for-the-
middle-class schemes. If there's one thing the hotter-than-hot
stock market does not need at this point, it's a chunk out of the
capital-gains tax, which is now down to 20 percent and would go to
15 under the GOP plan.
</P>
<P>
   So Democrats want to spend on new social programs which they
deem worthy uses of public dough, and Republicans want to spend the
surplus on tax cuts for the folks who vote for the GOP. Inside
every dieted-down congressman is a big fat spender aching to get
loose. The next election, presidency and the House, will go to the
party that most assures voters in the middle that it will look out
for their economic interests. They'll promise you all sorts of
cholesterol-drenched porky plans. You can't count on the pols to
say ``no'' for you; you've got to say ``no'' for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
