<HEADER>
A4414 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ELECTRONICA-BOS     07-09 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ELECTRONICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEAT HITS THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can call it techno or call it electronica, but you may just
want to call it heaven when the triple-bill ``Community Service''
tour sets up shop at the Palladium in Worcester Saturday night. And
quite a shop it should be. On tap: the pioneering English duo
Orbital, consisting of brothers Paul and Phil Hartnoll, English
electronica/dance/rockers Lo Fidelity All-Stars, and the
California-based instigators Scott Kirkland and Ken Jordan of
Crystal Method. More than this, you'll get a full-blown
bells-and-whistles production _ four large, revolving projection
screens and a state-of-the-art sound system imported by Orbital.
</P>
<P>
   What it should not be is faceless, a charge often accurately
leveled at the electronica genre. The groups may use samplers and
synthesizers _ the tools of the digital age _ but all three main
acts are serious about live performance and the performer-audience
bond, about the seamless (and potentially ecstatic) blending of
dance and rock crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what we like to do, all stitched together,'' says Paul
Hartnoll, speaking both of the crowd and the bands' sounds. ``If we
combine sources, hopefully, people will turn it on like they do
dance music . . . although I don't think we make dance music.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they do _ sort of. Orbital's sound is more cerebral, more
free-floating and less rhythmically based, than it was a decade ago
when it formed, but it will make you move. Crystal Method, as
evidenced by their current hit ``Busy Child'' (with its relentless
``I guess I didn't know'' refrain), is a body-shaking band of the
first order. As to the trippy funk-rock 'n ravers Lo Fidelity
All-Stars, we'll turn it over to DJ-singer Phil Ward, a.k.a. The
Albino Priest: ``Someone described us as a rock 'n' roll band that
just happens to make dance music. We're rock 'n' roll in attitude _
we believe in full-on distortion and nosie _ but dance music and
hip-hop is what we grew up listening to. To take the rock 'n' roll
attitude, it doesn't mean you have to stand there with a spread
stance, making a big guitar sound.'' He likens the to-and-fro
nature of the Lo Fi's dance/rock sound to that of Primal Scream and
Stone Roses, just coming from the other direction.
</P>
<P>
   At their shows, Ward says, ``you see kids wearing Limp Bizkit
and Rancid t-shirts, and not seeing any difference in terms of
energy and ideas. With the Chemical Brothers and Prodigy (doing
what they're doing now) there's not a massive divide.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward credits the members of Orbital with being godheads of the
genre. ``We don't really know about Crystal Method,'' he says,
``but to play on the same bill as Orbital, well, growing up in
England and lsitening to dance music, Orbital were musical
geniuses, with (the songs) `Belfast' and `Chime.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the ``Community Service'' tour, which is about a
third through its three-week, 18-city sortie, was hatched by
booking agent Sam Kirby and Crystal Method. They intend it to be an
annual event with different bands playing out under its rubric _ a
small scale Lollapalooza, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the obvious musical differences, these groups differ
from the Lollapalooza ilk in their relationship to stardom. ``I
never set out to be a celebrity or a pop star,'' says Hartnoll. ``I
set out to make music and to start a `career,' a word I use in a
funny sense. I just want to make music and make all my money from
making music, so I don't have to do any other work. That's what I
wanted to do and I achieved it. Now, I get to travel around the
world playing really loudly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartnoll notes he and his brother are adamant about not
plastering their own mugs on their CD covers and even when they're
on magazine covers or newspaper pages, ``they get thrown away, so
people forget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fans of free beer and meeting celebrities,'' admits
Ward, of fame's perks. ``But we're music fans. It's got to be about
the music. We went out and bought 300 records since we'' came to
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In concert, the Lo-Fi's use traditional rock instruments plus
electronic gear. They are very much a ``live'' band.
</P>
<P>
   This, says Hartnoll, is how Orbital works on stage: ``I do the
arranging and Phil does the mixing. The only thing you have planned
is the order of the songs, so you will discuss that five minutes
before you go on, but there is no plan. We improvise. We have about
48 channels of mixing going on. We take most of what we need from
the studio with us. (What we play) isn't live _ I would not even
pretend that _ but what we do is improvise with the structure. It
can be very hit or miss. You always think you're prepared for the
unexpected, but the unexpected is a part of nature. Your lead line
could drop out and you only have the bass line _ you cannot panic,
which I tend to do, you move on in a different direction. I have to
condition myself to enjoy yourself, to turn to a different tangent
and incorporate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Method, which brings a somewhat sardonic edge to the
genre, is presently working on a new album and plans to incorporate
a number of new songs into their set. It is a relentlessly busy
band, one of the first electronica groups to push its image as live
entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   The Lo Fi's are still working material from their debut album,
``How to Operate With a Blown Mind,'' which has been out for a long
time in England _ and thus is at risk to become overly familiar for
the band. ``The crowds have been unbelievable and it breathes new
life into old songs,'' says Ward, who took over main vocals when
the group's former singer, the Wrekked Train, jumped the track last
year. (The Lo Fi's have been recording in a home-studio in San
Francisco, expect to release a new single in England in October and
an album in February.)
</P>
<P>
   DJ John Kelley is accompanying the tour and will spin between
sets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
