<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SEVENTEEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EDGE OF SEVENTEEN' TAKES TEEN-AGE ROMANCE SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
EDGE OF SEVENTEEN 
Written by: Todd Stephens 
Directed by: David Moreton 
Starring: Chris Stafford, Tina Holmes, Anderson Gabrych, Stephanie
McVay, Lea DeLaria 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rating: Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Edge of Seventeen'' is a film about teen-agers and sex, but
that's where any comparisons between Todd Stephens and David
Moreton's feature debut, and such hormonally charged movies like
``Cruel Intentions'' or the just-in-theaters, ``American Pie''
should end. This is a poignant, touching story of the longing for
first love, viewed through the life of a suburban high school boy,
played winningly by Chris Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   What also makes ``Edge of Seventeen,'' directed by Moreton, and
written by Stephens, different is that Stafford's Eric is attracted
to men. This is fairly new realization for Eric, but the film isn't
a standard coming-out, coming-of-age drama. More than any other
teen movie of recent memory, ``Edge of Seventeen'' captures the
uncertainty, awkwardness, and pains of adolescence, further
complicated when grappling with questions of sexual identity.
</P>
<P>
   As the film begins, it is the summer of 1984. Eric has completed
his junior year of high school and taken a summer job as a food
server at Crystal Shores, an amusement-park restaurant near his
Sandusky, Ohio, home. Joining him is Maggie (Tina Holmes), his
sweet, pretty best friend, who wants to be more than just Eric's
friend. Of course, Eric, an aspiring musician, would rather spend
time noodling his Moog synthesizer than romancing the indefatigable
Maggie.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Eric doesn't really seem attracted to anyone until he
meets Rod (Anderson Gabrych), an Ohio State University student also
working at Crystal Shores. With his blond hair, and ready,
seductive smile, Rod is openly gay, and openly flirts with Eric who
is all atwitter with the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Most films would make Eric and Rod's inevitable connection
dreamy and mutual _ which it is, for a while. But Eric learns a
hard lesson after spending a romantic evening with Rod, who returns
to school and won't even return Eric's phone calls. His second
encounter with a man he meets at a gay club is no more successful,
leading Eric into a painful and disastrous attempt at lovemaking
with poor, poor Maggie. It's such an emotionally shattering scene,
I defy any audience member not to wince while watching it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edge of Seventeen'' is worthwhile because it dares to show
adolescent sexual discovery as something other than a laugh-riot of
bodily fluids. It presents the matter seriously without becoming
maudlin. The film is also noteworthy for its portrayal of Eric's
parents as compassionate and understanding _ unlike the clueless
adult dunderheads who usually populate teen movies. Especially
noteworthy is the addictively watchable Lea DeLaria as Eric's
godmother and lesbian ``auntie,'' who takes him under her wing.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens and Moreton only falter with the film's conclusion
which ties the story up too neatly. But that's a small quibble,
with a film that mostly nails just about everything else. And
something must also be said about the film's memory-tugging
soundtrack. From Toni Basil's pounding ``Mickey'' to Eurythmics'
soulful ``Right by Your Side'' to Bronski Beat's anthemic ``Why'' _
Jimmy Somerville's falsetto wail is still a mad, startling thing _
the songs are the perfect seasoning for this memorable first film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
