<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ARLINGTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SURPRISING TWISTS OF `ARLINGTON ROAD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ARLINGTON ROAD 
Directed by: Mark Pellington 
Screenplay by: Ehren Kruger 
Starring: Jeff Bridges, Tim Robbins, Joan Cusack, Hope Davis 
Running time: 117 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and some language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How's your paranoia? Now that the Oklahoma City and World Trade
Center bombings have become part of our collective nightmarevision,
conspiracy thrillers like ``Arlington Road'' don't seem quite so
preposterous as they once did. Although you never lose sight of the
manipulations it performs on you, it's a more intelligent and
realistic thriller than most, sober in tone yet laced with
insidiousness and hysteria. Although its build is erratic, it'll
grab and hold you with its take on a married couple in a suburb of
Washington, D.C., the Langs. They have heartland roots written all
over them, but they just may be the terrorists next door, playing
their own deadly version of ``Honey, I Blew Up the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   The acting is boldly contoured and Ehren Kruger's script aims
the dialogue away from the usual comic strip balloons and toward
the everyday. Yet it tilts the film into the increasing dislocation
of the guy finding himself increasingly isolated in a stonewalling
climate of denial. One big reason the film works as well as it does
is its casting against type of Tim Robbins and Joan Cusack as the
couple in question. Robbins, especially, is synonymous with
liberalism and its causes, except when he's consciously playing
against type, as he did in his own satiric ``Bob Roberts.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbins will creep you out with the calculating look in his eye
as he lobs chitchat at Jeff Bridges' single dad, a history prof
named Michael Faraday, alongside the Little League batting cage
that brings their respective young sons together. His line of chat,
ranging from the innocuous to the insinuating, is just skewed
enough to induce you to share the prof's gnawing suspicion that his
neighbor just might be the next big-time mad bomber? As for Cusack,
nobody more consistently or more superbly embodies scattered charm.
She's spent more than a decade amusing us while seeming to be
waiting around for somebody to reinvent screwball comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet their all-American veneer skews disquietingly when they test
Faraday with pointed remarks about nobody in government assuming
responsibility. Have they targeted him for some devious recruitment
scheme, knowing that he's been a mess, and a resentful mess at
that, ever since his FBI agent wife was killed during a botched
raid constructed to echo the Ruby Ridge siege? Are they sinister?
Or is Bridges's character, icon of maladroit decency that he is,
overreacting? The prof's loose-cannon behavior means that nobody
takes him seriously. When he goes to his late wife's FBI partner
and asks him to run a background check on the Langs, the agent
flat-out refuses.
</P>
<P>
   When he then starts playing amateur detective, the Langs grow
chilly, then chilling. Even the new woman in the prof's life (a
satisfyingly edgy Hope Davis) gets nervous and wonders if the prof
isn't going off the deep end. If he isn't, if he's right about his
deepening suspicions, it's obvious that his increasingly extreme
behavior has scared off any potential allies. As he persists,
things darken. When you think you know where the film is headed,
you tell yourself it can't actually be going there. You'll stick to
see if you're right, or if the film is going to somehow trump you.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bridges's embattled but possibly unbalanced idealism
keeps us engaged even when his character is pushed into hysteria.
Such is his charm and the weight of decency attached to his
persona. And such is the information that we get from the faces of
Robbins and Cusack that we cling to the belief that the film is not
really headed where it seems headed. In fact, the film makes its
point about denial by nudging us into it, then jolting us with our
realization of our own complacency. The button-pushing is pretty
blatant in ``Arlington Road.'' But thanks mostly to the actors'
ability to bring dimension to their work, you'll keep traveling
down ``Arlington Road'' to what you know will be an explosive
finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
