<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX, COMEDY THE MAIN INGREDIENTS IN `AMERICAN PIE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
AMERICAN PIE 
Directed by Paul Weitz, produced by Chris Weitz, starring Jason
Biggs, Shannon Elizabeth, Tara Reid, Natasha Lyonne, Mena Suvari,
Chris Klein and Allison Hedagax. 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rating: R (Partial nudity, sexual situations, profanity) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not the ``American Pie'' you might remember from way
back. No Don McLean, no Chevys to the levee, no good ol' boys
drinkin' whiskey and rye.
</P>
<P>
   This ``American Pie'' is a raunchy, horny-teen movie directed by
Paul Weitz and produced by brother Chris (both of them
screenwriters for ``Antz'') and starring a bunch of no-names. The
title comes from the apple pie one teen's mom lovingly bakes. Jim
has heard from a ``worldly'' friend that the innards of an apple
pie are supposed to feel like a part of a woman where our boy has
never been but yearns to be. So he uses the pie they way young
Portnoy used raw liver in ``Portnoy's Complaint.'' This, by the
way, is a step up from where he is when the movie begins, which is
on his bed doing lewd things with a sock when his father walks in.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' is gross and tasteless, but so were early John
Waters movies. Waters, though, was an acerbic observer of society;
this high-school romp mixes the gross and tasteless with
sentimental mush. Its makers are aiming straight for the low
budget/high return territory of last summer's ``There's Something
About Mary. The difference is that ``Mary'' was (if overrated)
mostly funny and charming. It even had characters you cared about.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie,'' set in a suburban town in Michigan, suffers
from a humor deficit, a character-development problem, and a Simple
Simon plotline. Four virgin guys try to have sex with actual women
before or after their high school prom. An older woman is involved,
which allows the filmmakers to nod to ``The Graduate'' by playing
``Mrs. Robinson'' during the seduction scenes. The Internet is
involved, when a Web-cam inadvertently captures a female
foreign-exchange student (Shannon Elizabeth) in what she thinks is
very private enjoyment of the pornography in a boy's bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   There are premature-ejaculation jokes and bodily-fluid jokes and
potty jokes and immature boys playing with toys. There is a
quasi-serious subplot about the ambivalent Oz (Chris Klein), who
must choose choir (and the choir girl, Heather, played by Mena
Suvari) over lacrosse (and his dumb jock friends).
</P>
<P>
   There are actually a couple of raw, funny moments, none of which
can be described here. They are rare nuggets of intelligence that
draw bursts of subversive yuks the way the old National Lampoon
used to.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an irony for you: The only people this movie might really
appeal to are flesh-and-profanity starved youths who are supposedly
forbidden by the rating code from seeing the darn thing _ at least
until it comes out on video, which should be any week now.
</P>
<P>
   Unless it's a big hit, of course. It just might be: No one
predicted ``There's Something About Mary'' would do boffo box
office, and it's always risky to overestimate the public's taste.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
