<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4423 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-STARS-BOS &LR;      07-09 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOVIE STARS' HAS FUN WITH THE SHOW-BIZ LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. _ Litigation and laughter go together like . .
. well, they don't really go together, which may explain why it's
hard to remember Harry Hamlin cracking a smile during his five
years on ``L.A. Law.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hamlin insists that behind the scenes, he was constantly
trying ``to inject as much humor as I could'' into the somewhat
dour character of attorney Michael Kuzak.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they were always `Down, boy. Down,' ' he recalled
ruefully. ``They didn't want that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin's inner jokester is presumably free to roam in the WB
network's new sitcom, ``Movie Stars,'' a family comedy with a
showbiz twist that premieres Sunday at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movie Stars'' revolves around the home life of two actors,
rugged action star Reese Hardin (think Schwarzenegger) and
award-winning Jacey Wyatt (think Streep) who must balance their
Hollywood careers with the demands of raising two children and
coping with Reese's career-challenged brother.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Grant, who plays Jacey, has never starred in a
broadcast network series before, but it could be said she has been
preparing for this role her whole life: She is the daughter of Cary
Grant and Dyan Cannon. (Ironically enough, Hamlin appeared with
Cannon in a TV movie in the 1980s).
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Movie Stars'' is not guaranteed a spot on the WB's
fall schedule, Hamlin and Grant believe the public fascination with
celebrities, and curiosity about their private lives, will draw
viewers to the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects our lives are very banal, and yet to the
outside world, it appears as though they must be very glamorous,
and there must be a lot of fun and excitement going on all the
time,'' said Hamlin. ``What this show does is it kind of pops the
bubble for an audience that might perceive us as people who don't
put their pants on one leg at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has never starred in a sitcom before, Hamlin's
breakthrough part was in a comedy, ``Movie Movie,'' Stanley Donen's
hilarious 1978 parody of old boxing films. ``I consider comedy to
be my roots,'' he said. ``In fact, I've been just itching to get
back and do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he left ``L.A. Law'' in 1991, Hamlin has been largely
invisible on television except for a recurring role in the
short-lived ``Ink'' and a handful of movies-of-the-week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had wanted to do something in television after `L.A. Law,'
and have been looking for something for a number of years,'' he
said. ``But because `L.A. Law' was so special, it's a real hard act
to follow, in terms of a drama, unless I were to find something
that David E. Kelley was writing. Something like `Ally McBeal' or
whatever. But I think David's had quite enough of me, so I don't
think that's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Grant's impressive bloodlines, she arrived late to
acting. She spent her 20s working as a cook and attending Stanford,
eyeing a career in law.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life, I was expected to act,'' said Grant. ``And I was
so afraid of following in their footsteps. Besides the fact that
they had natural ideas of what they wanted me to be, and a lawyer
was the biggest one.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I tried to play out their stuff, and then I tried lots of
other things, and finally I just, at the insistence of a
girlfriend, took an acting class for fun. And I just loved it, and
I finally felt my whole body kind of settle, and thought: This is
what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Movie Stars'' has traveled a long and winding road to the WB
schedule. It was originally slated to air in April _ Hamlin and
Grant spoke to television critics in January _ but did not make it
into the schedule. The WB line is that the network believed a
summer launch would be more advantageous for a new show, since it
wouldn't get lost in the shuffle. Sources also say, however, that
the network was unwilling to bump the successful ``Rescue 77'' to
clear a time slot for ``Movie Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's finally going to be on the air, chances are that
WB executives are rooting hard for ``Movie Stars'' to succeed, if
only so the network can broaden its identity. Known for teen-angst
dramas like ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' and
``Felicity,'' the WB has had far less success developing hit
sitcoms, and would rather not be seen as a one-trick pony. In the
current issue of Broadcasting &AMP; Cable magazine, WB entertainment
president Susanne Daniels says that ``comedy is a major priority.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another reason that ``Movie Stars'' will stand out on
the WB schedule: At 48 and 33, respectively, Hamlin and Grant are
twice the age of most WB stars. ``Well, I guess somebody has to be
out there to sell those disposable diapers,'' joked Hamlin. ``The
denture cream and all that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
