<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4424 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERKSHIRES-SUMMER-BOS     07-09 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERKSHIRES-SUMMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE SEASON OF THE RICH IN THE BERKSHIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT BARRINGTON, Mass. _ This is the moment when the Berkshires
shrug off their bucolic irrelevance and seize the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The tribes are all here for the season once again. They wear
their colors on the great lawn at Tanglewood, the back roads of New
Marlborough, and the eateries of this once moribund town.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the weekend when the tribes reach critical mass:
From James Taylor to the Boston Pops, Jacob's Pillow, the
Williamstown Theater Festival, and countless smaller venues, it is
showtime for an aggregation of performing arts unmatched anywhere
else in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But before the arts came the same immutable tides of social
migration that hit the likes of Telluride and Sante Fe. George
Wislocki, president of the Berkshire Natural Resources Council,
delineates them as follows: ``First come the hippies, then the
cunning, the shrewd, the sun-tanned, and finally, the money.''
</P>
<P>
   And new species are appearing on the scene that create an even
richer food chain. Divisions of culture and geography, as well as
persistent rural poverty, still hamstring the region from realizing
its potential. But the Berkshires, as always, are very fine in high
summer.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, what saves this area from nightmarish excess is
space. Lots of it. The huge swath of green reduces the effect of
the mansions that metastacize throughout the county. This is not
the case in Nantucket and Martha's Vineyard. ``On Martha's
Vineyard, you can't move without treading on Kay Graham,'' says
conductor Andre Previn, who owns a house on the island but adores
Tanglewood, where he has come to conduct and teach for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   There is no excuse for feeling hemmed in in the Berkshires. The
entire population of Berkshire County is less than 140,000 people.
It still has the same area code that it started with. Granted,
there's a monster of a house on Prospect Hill in Stockbridge that
reportedly cost more than $12 million. But drive 10 miles in almost
any direction and you can get lost fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not out every night attacking some new subdivision,''
Wislocki says about his role as guardian of open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Along with open spaces, the Berkshires have always been defined
by an exotic tribal mix worthy of the Ottoman Empire: artists of
all stripes in Housatonic, acupuncturists in West Stockbridge,
trust fund hippies in Monterey, uber-financiers in Williamstown,
old Yankees in madras at the Lenox Club, hill people in the wilds
of Otis and Becket, musicians everywhere. The rural poor, invisible
from the window of a Lexus, are out here, too.
</P>
<P>
   The newest tribe on the scene are the young Internet swains,
many still in their 20s, who have hatched companies primarily
around Williamstown. These hormonal entrepreneurs add energy and
jobs to a culture still grieving over the seismic departures a
decade ago of General Electric in Pittsfield and Sprague Electric
in North Adams. If the long-term economic effect of this group is
debatable, their injection of moxie and resourcefulness into an
area steeped in self-doubt is not. They represent a healthy
antidote to the passivity of what locals call the ``GE mentality,''
in which a person went seamlessly from high school to the shop
floor for the rest of his or her life.
</P>
<P>
   The glue among them is an impossibly young Matthew Harris, who
at 26 runs Berkshires Capital Investors, a venture fund that
invests only in companies in the Berkshires. Harris works with a
secretary out of a two-room suite above McClelland's Stationery
store in Williamstown and is counseled by a trio of men retired
from very successful careers. His first investment two years ago
was in Tripod, an Internet company cofounded by a Williams
roommate, Bo Peabody, who sold it last year to Lycos for $58
million.
</P>
<P>
   There is also in Great Barrington a group of immigrants from the
Sheffield shop of Hollywood special effects wizard Douglas
Trumbull. Now in their own micro offices here, they are part of
Great Barrington's revival. A decade ago, the main street of the
town looked like Dresden after the firebombing. Today, it is a
vibrant community that hums all year.
</P>
<P>
   Lenox, in contrast, is more of a Potemkin village whose febrile
summer shoppers are nowhere to be found in February. The main
street of Stockbridge suffers from a plague of scented candle and
potpourri shops. The town was in danger of losing the Elm Street
Market, one of its last remaining real stores, until the
Fitzpatrick family, owners of the Red Lion Inn and Country
Curtains, bought it last year in an act of public service.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's opening in North Adams of MASS MoCA, the gigantic
museum of contemporary art, represents a breathtaking
700,000-square-foot roll of the dice for director Joseph Thompson.
But more important, it has changed the social fabric of the ``north
county,'' centered in Williamstown. The new museum has broken what
Thompson calls ``the Maginot line'' that existed for decades
between affluent Williamstown and its blue-collar neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   One of the top curators at Williamstown's superb Clark Museum
recently bought a house in North Adams, as have half a dozen
Williams faculty members. ``This would have been inconceivable a
few years ago,'' says Thompson. North Adams now sports two bed and
breakfasts where there was none two years ago. It even has a hotel
_ a Holiday Inn with the charm of a German pillbox _ but a hotel
nonetheless that does good business.
</P>
<P>
   Such progress is lost, though, on most folks from ``south
county,'' the area below the county's ailing hub of Pittsfield.
This disconnect is due neither to emnity nor to rivalry, at least
for now. Quite simply, it's hard to get from there to here. One
need trail a truck on Route 7, the two-lane spine, only once to
understand why.
</P>
<P>
   But cross-pollination between north and south is also minimal
because the Berkshires remain culturally balkanized. Take the
Tanglewood crowd, the most powerful tribe in the region. ``The
people at Tanglewood have no idea what's going on in the
Berkshires,'' says Nancy Fitzpatrick, a generous patron of the
Boston Symphony and the heir apparent to the family empire.
</P>
<P>
   That's beside the point, counters Previn. ``The Vienna
Philharmonic doesn't care what goes on in Austria.''
</P>
<P>
   And many in the Berkshires have no idea what's going on at
Tanglewood. Susan Sellew, who has made her estimable Monterey
Chevre goat cheese for the likes of Zabar's and Bread &AMP; Circus
since the early '80s on her farm in Monterey, likens the Berkshires
to a city. Put simply, it has its neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Her tiny community, which swells from 920 to 4,000 in the
summer, boasts a general store where a gold BMW might sit next to
an aging pickup. Its bulletin board includes a plea from the
Rosenthals for any news about Sugar, their lost cat, directly
beneath an ad offering screenwriting lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinetmakers mingle easily with arbitrageurs who buy big, quiet
houses. For folks such as Sellew, Tanglewood might as well be in
Wyoming: She milks her goats and listens to concerts on the radio.
(And once, while at her art class in Lee, she helped her daughter
deliver a kid over the phone.)
</P>
<P>
   Sellew's goat gang is a classic Berkshire melange. Her assistant
was a colorist for Marvel comics for 25 years. A Manhattan
therapist used to milk goats for free twice a week for two years.
(Now we know what shrinks do for help.) An ex-magazine editor
cleans the barn.
</P>
<P>
   Even further removed is the Dream Away Lodge in the hill country
of Becket. ``You'll never find this place unless someone takes
you,'' says its new owner, Daniel Osman. Yup. Reputed to have been
a bordello in the '40s, the Dream Away became the stuff of legend
in 1975 when photographer Ken Regan took Bob Dylan's Rolling
Thunder tour there. Mama Frasca, the owner at the time, so
entranced Dylan with her unprompted Italian singing that he
arranged for her to open for him one night at Boston Garden, Regan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Dream Away is appropriately shabby. It sports some
nifty neon, pictures of Pope John XXIII, Liberace, and the odd
bowling trophy. It is, hands down, the campiest place in the
Berkshires. Perhaps 15 miles from Bisto Zinc, the hottest new
watering hole in Lenox, the Dream Away might as well be on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   One tribe that is lost in the brilliance of the summer season is
the rural poor. Most of the adults among them will never gain the
savvy and confidence to start their own businesses. They are
victims of what economist Joseph Schumpeter once called ``creative
destruction'' as different industries rise and fall. Linda Small,
who runs the Children's Health Program, a Great Barrington
nonprofit, says the focus is on how to prepare the next generation
for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get the parents comfortable with the process of
letting their children go, to be as smart as I know they are. It's
a huge struggle,'' she says. ``I love that those smart young things
are starting businesses here. They can help the Berkshires go
through this transition. I hope they're here for our kids. That's
where I'm focusing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
