<SLUG> BC-REFORM-STRUGGLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURA GRAPPLES WITH PEROT TO LEAD REFORM PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This does not seem like a fair fight: Jesse ``The
Body'' Ventura against Ross ``I'm all ears'' Perot. But in the
lively political contest for leadership of the Reform Party that
Perot founded and to which Ventura gave fame, it is hard to tell
which one is the professional wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Governor Ventura, the first candidate elected
statewide on the Reform Party ticket, appears to have won round
one. Perot's handpicked party chairman, Russell Verney, announced
on Wednesday that he would not seek reelection at the party's
national convention July 23 through 25 in Dearborn, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe now is the right time for me to step aside and let
new leadership blossom, and to let those who have been working hard
move up and take over,'' Verney said Thursday in his office at
Perot's headquarters in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Verney insists his decision to resign was made long before June
28, when Ventura sent hundreds of convention delegates an e-mail
endorsing another candidate for chairman _ Jack Gargan of Cedar
Key, Fla. _ and threatening to pack up his star power and stay away
from the national Reform Party if Gargan was not elected.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Verney persuaded to leave, he said, by Ventura's latest
power play: His very public recruiting of Lowell Weicker, a former
Connecticut governor and senator, to be a Reform Party presidential
candidate in 2000. Weicker, who did not support Perot in his 1992
and 1996 campaigns for the White House, said he ``has no idea'' if
the Texas billionaire would run again, but hoped he would not. ``A
third time and people will just make fun of the Reform Party,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura has been more blunt. In interviews and in his new book,
``I Ain't Got Time to Bleed,'' Ventura has said that for the Reform
Party to survive, the time has come for Perot to go and the guard
to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing personal against Perot _ I think he's commendable,''
Ventura wrote in his autobiography, adding that he voted for the
maverick independent twice. ``But for whatever reason, he wants to
remain out front. He's fallen a great distance from the first time
he ran, and he fell again the second time. He had better step aside
in this next election, or the party won't exist anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Schier, chairman of the political science department at
Carleton College and a commentator on Minnesota politics, said
Ventura is using his position as the reigning king of Reform Party
candidates to lead the first serious attempt to wrest control of
the party from Perot and push him out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perot is entrenched and stubborn, so Jesse, who is about as
subtle as a Mack truck, is hitting the mule over the head with a
board,'' Schier said. ``But this could turn into a free-for-all at
the convention. These are uncharted waters, and it is hard to
believe Perot will go quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Perot has been very quiet about the whole matter. He did
not answer requests for an interview, and Verney said his boss is
keeping a low profile because ``the future of the Reform Party
depends on tens of thousands of great, hard-working activists, not
on one person's celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot, who received almost 20 percent of the presidential vote
in 1992 and 8.5 percent in 1996, has not disclosed his intentions
for 2000. Ventura says he will serve out his four-year term in
Minnesota and not run for president next year. Because of Perot's
vote in 1996, the Reform Party's presidential candidate next year
will be eligible for $12.6 million in federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Perot will be at the national convention, giving the keynote
speech on July 24 and energizing his followers before they vote the
next day on the slate of party officers. Ventura has been offered a
speaking slot on July 23, before many of the delegates arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Gargan, who sought Ventura's endorsement for chairman, says the
schedule of speeches is just one example of how the party
leadership has manipulated rules and procedures to quash anti-Perot
dissent and minimize the governor's role in the national party.
Gargan also is rankled that Perot did not help finance Ventura's
campaign last year, though Verney said the large loan Ventura
sought from Perot would have been illegal under campaign-finance
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse Ventura is the greatest public relations piece the
Reform Party has _ he talks the party talk and walks the walk,''
said Gargan, a Reform Party veteran who has run unsuccessfully for
governor and the US House in Florida. ``But instead of playing him
up to the hilt, our national committee pretends he is not one of
us. What is wrong with this picture?''
</P>
<P>
   Verney says Perot feels ``no rivalry'' with Ventura. ``Ross has
stepped back and taken the focus off himself and let Jesse run with
no interference,'' said Verney, who was born in Brighton and at one
time was executive director of the New Hampshire Democratic Party.
``Ventura tells Perot to `get out of the way.' Well, who has stood
in Jesse's way, who has impeded him in the least?''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say the Reform Party, which was born as a vanity
plate for Perot and then grew on good-government issues such as
campaign finance reform and term limits, is at a crossroads. Will
it become a functional third party, fielding candidates at all
levels of government, or will it remain a vessel for the
presidential ambitions of outsiders like Ventura and Perot?
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, will the Reform Party become a real third
party with some potential, or does it continue to be Ross Perot's
toy,'' said Sandy Maisel, a government professor at Colby College.
``The significance of Ventura's victory is that it gives the party
an opportunity to become something other than one person's vehicle
for salving an ego.''
</P>
</TEXT>
