<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-WOES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PICTURE-PERFECT WEDDING AND THEN DISASTER _ AND HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank and Suzanne Chandler had a beautiful wedding _ a wedding
that went off so perfectly, it was impossible to imagine the
disasters that would follow.
</P>
<P>
   But follow they did. The wedding from heaven spawned the
aftermath from hell. Photographs went missing. Presents were
destroyed. A precious ring was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Such a string of disasters might be looked back on with sadness
and regret, or provide entertaining tales at dinner parties. But
this Boston couple decided to fight the fates.
</P>
<P>
   And they did it with some snap-happy friends, two floods (one
with sewage), a man willing to comb the bottom of a muddy lake for
a wedding ring, and a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandlers were married on Sunday, May 24, 1998, in a
200-year-old synagogue on St. Thomas. The sun hung low in an orange
sky. The ocean sparkled. Afterward, a private boat took the
newlyweds and their 50 guests to the island of St. John for the
reception. Later, they went to Duffy's Love Shack for drinks and
cigars, where Frank Chandler bought a baseball cap as a souvenir.
The honeymoon on St. Maarten? Also perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful,'' said Chandler. ``Everything about it was
beautiful. We should never have left.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until the Chandlers were switching planes in Puerto Rico did
things begin to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   They had put all the professional photographs from the wedding,
including negatives and the only video, with their cameras in their
hand luggage. ``I wanted to keep it all in my hands,'' Chandler
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was little time and much confusion between planes.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler put his carry-on on a conveyor belt, thinking it was
going to be X-rayed. But the bag was actually headed for oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing I know the bag is going into the bowels of Puerto
Rico,'' Chandler said. The plane was leaving, and attendants urged
him to board.
</P>
<P>
   He admits he caused a scene. ``Everything I hold dear is in that
bag,'' he told American Airlines officials. ``I'm going to be very
uncomfortable without that bag.'' They persuaded him to board
anyway. They arrived at Logan Airport, but the bag _ and all the
photographs _ didn't. The airline was unable to locate it.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Chandler cried for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, their one-bedroom basement apartment, in which
all the wedding presents had been piled on the floor, flooded when
sewers backed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a foot of water in the apartment,'' Chandler said.
``Except I wish it were only water.'' Most of the presents were
ruined. And because the water had come up from the sewer, instead
of down from the sky, insurance covered none of it.
</P>
<P>
   On July Fourth of last year, Frank Chandler's parents threw a
wedding party for them in Maine. Before the party, the couple took
a Jet Ski out on Salmon Lake, in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out this was not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's Duffy's Love Shack cap blew off. He turned around to
get it, and flipped the Jet Ski. He and Suzanne fell, fully
clothed, into the middle of the lake. The Jet Ski, still running,
hummed in slow circles around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going round and round and round,'' Chandler said. ``I'm
pushing my wife away so she doesn't get sucked into the engine, and
with my right hand, I'm trying to reach under the Jet Ski to get
the key out.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, his wedding ring, a specially designed ring made of
platinum and yellow gold and engraved with their wedding date, a
ring Suzanne had persuaded him to splurge on because it was
forever, slipped off. It fell to the bottom of a lake which is 57
feet deep in parts. That wasn't covered by insurance either.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' Chandler said, ``we sit back and evaluate our
world. We are living under a black cloud. We have to take steps to
change these bad things, one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the breaks started to go their way.
</P>
<P>
   They had friends send them all the snapshots they could find of
the wedding, and ended up with 400 pictures.
</P>
<P>
   There was another flood a couple of months after the first one.
But this time, because a boiler broke, the new damage was covered
by insurance. The wedding presents were long gone, but the money
was a victory of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Two down. The ring was more of a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where it is,'' Chandler, a certified diver, said he
told friends. ``It's in that lake. There's no current, nobody's
going to take it, it's just going to sit there in the mud till we
find it.''
</P>
<P>
   At first he wanted to dive with a metal detector himself, but
local dive shops all pointed him to Richard Carney, known locally
as The Man Who Can Find Anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me make this clear,'' Chandler said. ``At this point,
people think I am insane. We're at a point where Frank the fool who
lost his wedding band is now Frank the bigger fool who's gonna go
and find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carney, unlike the many friends and family members who ribbed
Chandler mercilessly for months, never doubted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the gift,'' Carney said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, he fixes faxes and copy machines. But in real
life, Carney, whose boat is called Finders Keepers, finds long-lost
jewels and other treasures, not just in water, but in dumps and
houses, too.
</P>
<P>
   He went down into Salmon Lake last October, without success. The
weeds were too thick. And the Chandlers couldn't agree on where the
Jet Ski had dropped them.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Chandler, not the kind of man who gives up, and
Carney, whose reputation was on the line, went back to the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's dive brought no joy, except to the many friends and
strangers who had gathered on shore to laugh at the quixotic search
for the tiny ring in the huge 666-acre lake.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, they tried again, in a different spot.
</P>
<P>
   Down Carney went. In less than 10 minutes, he surfaced,
triumphant, with ring _ a full year after it was lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Carney is the greatest guy that ever lived,'' Chandler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Chandler doesn't have his wedding ring right now. It is at
the jeweler, being buffed, and sized so it doesn't slip off again.
And engraved with another date: July 4th, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the date my ring was reborn,'' Chandler said. ``And
that's the date my wife and I start our lives again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
