<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKER T AND THE MG'S LAY ON THE FUNK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For hired guns, there are none better than Booker T &AMP; the MG's.
They were the house band for the famous Stax/Volt label in Memphis,
backing Otis Redding, Wilson Pickett, and Sam &AMP; Dave. They were the
house band for Bob Dylan's 30th anniversary concert. They've been
the house band for the Rock Hall of Fame concerts _ and they backed
Neil Young on a world tour six years ago. Along the way, they've
backed Eric Clapton and John Fogerty.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Booker T &AMP; the MG's rarely tour, which makes it even
more special that they're coming to the Winter Island Blues
Festival in Salem, Mass. Saturday. They're on a richly enticing
bill with the Derek Trucks Band, Jazz is Dead, Entrain, the Miracle
Orchestra, Another Planet, and Mr. Airplane Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get up in your area too much. We've been mainly on
the West Coast,'' says MG's rhythm guitarist Steve Cropper, who is
also in the Blues Brothers Band. ``But really, in the whole life of
Booker T &AMP; the MG's, we never toured much, except on a small basis.
The biggest tour we ever did was with Neil Young when we played
with him six weeks in Europe and six weeks here.''
</P>
<P>
   On their own, Booker T &AMP; the MG's are an instrumental band known
for such hits as ``Green Onions,'' ``Hip Hug-Her,'' and ``Soul
Dressing.'' They were the backbone of funky '60s and '70s R&AMP;B,
before disco swept a lot of that away.
</P>
<P>
   As Cropper notes sardonically, ``R&AMP;B didn't die. Radio killed
it. But thank God today for oldies-but-goodies stations.''
</P>
<P>
   The classic MG's sound can be appreciated in the three-CD box
set ``Time is Tight,'' released last year on the Stax/Fantasy
label.
</P>
<P>
   Cropper, who has co-written such tunes as ``(Sitting On) the
Dock of the Bay'' with Otis Redding, ``Knock on Wood'' with Eddie
Floyd, and ``In the Midnight Hour'' (with Wilson Pickett), has
remastered some of those hits and reissued them on a solo album,
``Play It Again, Steve!'' It's available through his web site at
www.playitagainsteve.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to get Booker T &AMP; the MG's to do something similar
and put that out through the Internet,'' says Cropper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More on Mark Sandman: ``It was a beautiful night. We were
rocking and felt back in the groove,'' says Morphine saxophonist
Dana Colley, recalling last Saturday's gig at a festival outside of
Rome, where singer Mark Sandman died of a heart attack on stage.
``Mark crouched and stopped playing for a couple of minutes, and I
thought he was waiting for the groove to happen,'' says Colley.
Sandman then fell and knocked over a vase of flowers that drummer
Billy Conway always keeps on his drum riser. ``Mark's butt was on
his amp, his guitar was around his shoulders, and he had flowers
all around him,'' says Carrie Svingen, a longtime aide to the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two nights before in Portugal, it was 100 degrees at sound
check and Mark said, `I almost fainted,' '' recalls Colley. ``So,
in Italy, I didn't think much of it at first. I thought he just
fainted, because it was kind of warm.'' Sandman died during the
band's second song, not long after he had recited in Italian the
lyrics to his song, ``Mona's Sister.'' Says Colley: ``Mark spent
all day translating them and you could see that the crowd really
appreciated that he made the attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   A cardiac specialist was on the scene immediately, says Colley.
So was the police. They searched the band's belongings and later
searched Sandman's room looking for drugs, as if they could have
been the cause of death. ``It added insult to injury,'' says
Colley. ``But I guess they were just doing their police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ultimately impossible to put into a sound bite what I
feel about Mark,'' Colley adds. ``I owe everything to him, and
we're just going to try to see Mark's vision through.'' A new
Morphine live album will be released in October, followed by a
just-completed studio album next year. ``Mark had just sequenced
the songs for it,'' Colley says.
</P>
</TEXT>
