<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4435 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FOOD-SHOWS-HNS &LR;      07-09 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOOD-SHOWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY COOKING SHOWS SPOIL TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEN ALEXANDER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAFAYETTE, Calif. _ There are scads of things to get irritated
about these days. I'm the irritable type, so selecting one is no
problem, be it the government, school shootings, pollution, ethnic
cleansing, the plight of the poor or any of dozens of festering
situations.
</P>
<P>
   These are major enigmas, studied and analyzed and quarreled over
by savants and seers and navel observers and numbers-crunchers and
politicians who blanket the Sunday interview shows.
</P>
<P>
   I am, however, to quote Uriah Heep, ``an 'umble person,'' so I
select a quite minor, unimportant topic on which to vent my 'umble
rage: TV cooking shows.
</P>
<P>
   First, the proliferation. It's the American way to overdo
anything that seems to catch the public attention.
</P>
<P>
   I believe Julia Child started it all, probably during the Civil
War. Next came Jeff Smith, ``The Frugal Gourmet,'' whose shtick was
simple fare, low cost and whimsical commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Success changed the formula to international excursions, a huge
staff, books and famous guests. It also brought legal entanglements
over dicey morals charges; Smith seems to have disappeared from the
kitchen. Julia, bless her heart, still props herself on the counter
while guest chefs bake toothsome tarts and cakes and breads.
</P>
<P>
   But the floodgates had been opened. In a five-day period picked
at random, newspaper listings showed 23 different food shows on TV
(42 in all because some appear more than once.) Our TV pot runneth
over.
</P>
<P>
   Now if every one of these offered useful tips on good stuff I
can cook, or better ways to cook what I now serve, I'd say go for
it. (Yes, I am the cook in my house; my sainted wife cooked for
four hungry men for more than 30 years and gladly relinquished the
stove to me.)
</P>
<P>
   But the show-biz virus has infected the entire system, the end
result being culinary razzle-dazzle signifying little besides how
complicated and artsy-crafty a noble profession can get.
</P>
<P>
   Take the personnel. Julia can be excused her use of an aide;
she's 87 and can't handle the physical effort. But most of the
shows have deemed it necessary to have one or more so-called
assistants, most of them total klutzes, I suppose to demonstrate
the skill of the headliner.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Pepin is a kitchen magician with great ideas, simple
recipes and fabulous technique. As a solo he was everybody's idol,
but for some reason his daughter Claudine was added to the cast.
</P>
<P>
   She's inept, clumsy, generally without a clue but, in somebody's
twisted view, gives the show variety.
</P>
<P>
   Another show has an attractive, knowledgeable British woman,
trying to give recipes but drowned out by a lanky, clueless,
blabbermouthed kid with stupid questions and stupider gags. There
are a few solo chefs but they're increasingly in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   Let's consider the food. Certainly food should be pleasingly
presented, but on most TV shows contrived constructions on the
plate tend to mask what's to be eaten.
</P>
<P>
   Altitude is paramount. If a dish has some veggies with the
entree, they are mounded in the middle, then the meat or fish
elements are carefully stacked on end atop the mound, as high as
possible. Usually a cap of shredded, deep- fried something is
precariously balanced at the pinnacle as the camera moves in. They
don't dare move the plate or it'll collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Sauces are hardly ever put on the food; they're squirted around
the edges in little blobs. Same goes for desserts; the sauces (at
least three of different colors) are dribbled in random patterns
over the plate, the dessert plopped in the middle, and the same
balancing act done with cookies or mint sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   As for ingredients, there is a list of essentials in all TV
cookery: kosher or sea salt, arugula, cilantro, mango chutney,
heavy cream, a dozen egg yolks, goat cheese and a blow torch for
caramelizing sugar on top of whatever dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Settings range from a small kitchen, where a sincere young woman
expresses enthusiasm over heaps of coarsely chopped, meatless items
for gigantic vegetarian dinners, to the huge amphitheater of the
Culinary Institute of America. There platoons of would-be chefs,
all in starched smocks and tall chef's hats, sit high above the
demonstration table, for all the world like the operating room of a
major hospital, watching an instructor (read doctor) ponderously
process a partridge Provencal (read coronary transplant).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I overcavil. There are a few good tips to be gleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Have sharp knives. Fold in your whipped cream or beaten egg
whites gently. Don't test the temperature of hot oil with your
finger. Don't cook with wine you wouldn't drink.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one I learned just the other day, really helpful. If you
want to separate the leaves of iceberg lettuce (an abomination to
the heavy breathers, but I love it), hold the head in both hands
and bang the core end violently on your cutting board or sink.
</P>
<P>
   The core will pop loose from the leaves and can be pulled out
easily, the leaves flapping freely and ready for use in whatever
manner. Try it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Alexander, now retired, was for many years editorial
cartoonist for the San Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
