for gigantic vegetarian dinners, to the huge amphitheater of the
Culinary Institute of America. There platoons of would-be chefs,
all in starched smocks and tall chef's hats, sit high above the
demonstration table, for all the world like the operating room of a
major hospital, watching an instructor (read doctor) ponderously
process a partridge Provencal (read coronary transplant).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps I overcavil. There are a few good tips to be gleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Have sharp knives. Fold in your whipped cream or beaten egg
whites gently. Don't test the temperature of hot oil with your
finger. Don't cook with wine you wouldn't drink.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one I learned just the other day, really helpful. If you
want to separate the leaves of iceberg lettuce (an abomination to
the heavy breathers, but I love it), hold the head in both hands
and bang the core end violently on your cutting board or sink.
</P>
<P>
   The core will pop loose from the leaves and can be pulled out
easily, the leaves flapping freely and ready for use in whatever
manner. Try it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Alexander, now retired, was for many years editorial
cartoonist for the San Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
