<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, July 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-EGYPT (Alexandria, Egypt) _ Israel's Ehud Barak meets
Egypt's Hosni Mubarak and vows ``to turn every stone'' to find a
way to Mideast peace. Mubarak says ``give the man some time.'' By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina) _ Developments in the troubled Yugoslav
province. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MILITARY (Moscow) _ The Russian defense minister talks
about his country's recent military exercise and how Russian
reliance on nuclear weapons is much greater now because of its
deteriorating conventional forces. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-COMMISSION (Paris) _ The new president of the European
Union's executive commission in Brussels announced the appointment
of 19 commissioners on Friday, promising ``a new era of change''
after the forced resignation of the entire previous commission last
spring. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ The ``vast right-wing
conspiracy'' is already mobilizing against Hillary Rodham Clinton's
New York Senate bid as Republican and conservative groups, from
Alabama to New Hampshire, use her candidacy to raise millions of
dollars. By Don Van Natta.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (See also NY-MRSCLINTON, under NATIONAL-GENERAL)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PATIENT-RIGHTS (Los Angeles) _ President Clinton
concludes his trip with an appeal for passage of a patients bill of
rights. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-TAX (Washington) _ Senate Republicans unveil their tax
cut proposal, including broad reductions in personal income taxes.
By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   INCOME-REPORT (Washington) _ The Census Bureau releases new
income data, showing that one in five households had trouble paying
essential bills like rent or utilities at some point during the
year. And other statistics showing further disinclination toward
saving. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-DRUGS (Philadelphia) _ Not just paying for all their
medications, which Clinton wants Medicare to help with, but keeping
all the pills straight, defines the lives of many older people. We
talk to them. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-CONTRACTS (Undated) _ Sandra Feldman, president of the
American Federation of Teachers, proposes to revamp the way
contracts are negotiated for the nation's 17,000 school districts.
She would give far more flexibility on staffing and curriculum to
the individual school level and let schools, instead of districts,
do things like determine class size. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRSCLINTON (Dateline to kum, N.Y.) _ Hillary Clinton's
senatorial campaign tour continues. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly Religion Column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIZDAY &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPICE-TRADE (Singapore) _ To know the spice trade is to know a
good deal about Indonesia. Traders have been carrying spices from
these islands for many centuries, and spices have played a huge
part in shaping the nation's history. Amid recent financial storms,
small traders have had to employ modern economics to stick with
this ancient trade. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-FEE (Washington) _ Commerce Department orders Icann,
which oversees Internet domain name registration, to drop plans to
impose a $1 a year fee. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 11 a.m., stocks were slightly higher. The
Dow Jones industrial average were up 0.3 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 up
0.24 percent and Nasdaq virtually flat. The 30-year bond was
yielding 5.98 percent. Crude oil was at $19.74 a barrel, gold at
$258.2. European markets were little changed, with London down 0.13
percent and Frankfurt up 0.57 percent. In Asia, Tokyo's Nikkei
closed down 0.17 percent; the Hang Seng, in Hong Kong, down 0.03
percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-JAPAN-TRADE (Beijing) _ Japan and China reach an agreement
on Beijing's bid to join the World Trade Organization. But China
says it is still not ready to resume WTO talks with the United
States. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   No staff-written Op-Ed columns for Saturday's paper.
</P>
