<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4479 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-FERRIES-HNS &LR;      07-09 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-FERRIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS JETTISON SUPPORT FOR FERRY FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANITA WADHWANI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Environmentalists are withdrawing their support
for an extensive ferry system to operate in the San Francisco Bay
because a study concluded that the fleet would cause more pollution
than the car and bus traffic it was designed to replace.
</P>
<P>
   Diesel-powered ferries emit 10 times more air pollution per
passenger-mile than automobiles and 23 times more than transit
buses, according to the preliminary report released Thursday by the
San Francisco environmental group Bluewater Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Are Bay Area residents willing to increase
air pollution to decrease congestion?'' said Russell Long,
executive director of the Bluewater Network. ``We can't afford to
take a romantic view of ferries anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Audubon Society, Save the Bay and Clean Water Action are
joining the Bluewater Network in calling on state Sen. Don Perata,
D-Alameda, to reconsider his bill that would get the ball rolling
on a massive expansion in ferry commuter services.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of ferry expansion and Perata's bill say that the
environmental concerns are premature, narrowly focused and based on
worst-case scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement comes at a time when ferry services are
increasingly seen as a traffic-busting alternative for commuters in
the Bay area. Last week, Gov. Gray Davis announced $6 million in
state funds toward the purchase of a new ferry for the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's odd to be criticized for work that has yet to be done,''
said Russell Hancock of the Bay Area Council, a nonprofit public
policy organization. Hancock managed an 18-month task force of city
representatives, transportation officials and environmentalists
that proposed a $2 billion, 120-ferry plan.
</P>
<P>
   The plan envisions an extensive network of ferries and terminals
connecting far-flung points around the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock also called into question the report's focus on
diesel-engine ferries, adding that the Bluewater Network was making
assumptions about what types of boats would be used.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said the Perata bill would be a first step by
establishing a new water transit authority that would take on
detailed planning responsibilities, including environmental
assessments.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental critics of the ferry plan said a new authority was
unneeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the environmental impacts are as significant as we think
they will be, then it raises serious questions about whether we
should have the water transit authority,'' said David Lewis of Save
the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The group was part of the task force and initially supported the
ferry expansion plan as an environmentally friendly alternative to
vehicle commutes. Save the Bay withdrew its support because of the
findings in the Bluewater Network report.
</P>
<P>
   None of the environmental groups; representatives raised
questions about air quality while on the task force, Lewis said.
``I think everyone on the task force shares responsibility for not
asking that question,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1414EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
