<HEADER>
A4541 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTING-HNS &LR;      07-09 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TAKING PORTABLES INTO NEW TERRITORY &HT;    (For release July 9, 1999) &HT;    By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) In my never-ending search for the perfect portable
computer, I am torn between two types.
</P>
<P>
   I openly lust for the big-screen, high performance,
top-of-the-line behemoths favored by those who must do slick
presentations on the road. However, my passion dies quickly when I
try to use one of these on an airplane, or when I am trudging
across a trade show floor, building muscles as I go.
</P>
<P>
   Then, I long for the light, thin models that come with smaller
screens but are still full-featured. I enjoy using one until I have
to type a lengthy story on the tiny keyboard _ and must finish it
before the anemic battery dies.
</P>
<P>
   Here are two notebook computers that perfectly illustrate the
agony and the ecstasy at both ends of the size spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Portg 3020CT _ $1,899, Toshiba. &UR;  &LR; The Portg 3020CT is a
frustrating small notebook. It's an excellent example of what great
thin-and-light systems can be _ and an example of the classic
mistakes too often made by their designers.
</P>
<P>
   This portable virtually defines the thin-and-light category.
It's just under 3 pounds and only three-fourths of an inch thick.
It has a 10.4-inch active matrix screen, a 300-megahertz mobile
Pentium MMX chip, 32 megabytes of memory, a 6.4-gigabyte hard drive
and the touch-point, eraserhead-style pointing device.
</P>
<P>
   Many thin-and-light ultraportables come with only a few ports
built in, relying on an external port replicator to handle the
rest. The 3020CT actually has a decent number of built-in ports,
including two Type II PC-card slots, one on each side of the base.
There are infrared and USB ports, a connection for the included
external floppy drive and headphone and microphone jacks.
Traditional serial and parallel ports, as well as a connection for
a monitor, come on an external module.
</P>
<P>
   The modem is not built-in, but Toshiba includes a PC-card-based
56K modem made by 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   This computer is excellent for road work. If you need to access
the corporate network, log on to the Internet, work with e-mail and
even give a presentation, it's wonderfully useful. It certainly
won't weigh down your shoulders as you dash through airports.
</P>
<P>
   But the very thing that makes it attractive also makes it
difficult to use, and that's its small size.
</P>
<P>
   I found typing on the keyboard for any length of time quite
irritating. One of the main problems is the positioning of the
cursor keys in a design that's common to too many small notebooks.
The up-arrow key is positioned next to the undersized right-shift
key. When I went to hit that shift key, I too often hit the
up-arrow key, sending my cursor into the line of text above.
</P>
<P>
   The small size also means the 3020CT must have a small battery,
which has a short life. The best I could do was just over two
hours. While the system is peppy when plugged in, running the
3020CT in battery mode made it relatively sluggish.
</P>
<P>
   The screen is relatively bright, but again, when powered down to
save battery life it became hard to see under bright-light
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Portg 3020CT does not come with a CD-ROM drive.
You'll have to purchase that separate for about $250, or connect to
a network to install new software.
</P>
<P>
   Presario 1825 _ $3,549, Compaq Computer Corp. &UR;  &LR; At the other end
of the scale is the Presario 1825, a monster of a notebook computer
that can effectively replace a desktop PC. Aimed at home and
home-office users, it's big on glitzy, state-of-the-art features _
and just plain big!
</P>
<P>
   The 1825's biggest feature is its display. At 15 inches, it's
the largest you can buy on a portable system, and about the
equivalent of the viewable area on older 17-inch monitors. The
active-matrix screen is bright and crisp, and is the best 15-inch
portable display I've seen yet.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried comes with a 400-megahertz Pentium II chip,
192 megabytes of memory, a 10-gigabyte hard drive, a 4X DVD-ROM
drive, combination floppy/LS-120 (120-megabyte) drive, a built-in
Ethernet connection, a 56K modem and a port for connecting this
computer to a standard TV.
</P>
<P>
   That latter feature is being found on more and more notebook
computers that come with DVD. This essentially turns your portable
PC into a DVD movie player that can be connected to a home
entertainment system. Now, if only some smart manufacturer would
add a remote control that works with the DVD software on the
computer...
</P>
<P>
   It comes with a spacious keyboard (the cursor keys are placed
below the right-shift key, out of the way) and a responsive
touchpad pointing device. Oversized mouse buttons make it easy to
point-and-click.
</P>
<P>
   As I mentioned, the display is gorgeous. It's also relatively
fast, using an ATI Rage Pro graphics adapter, the same type found
in many consumer desktop systems. It has excellent sound to go with
its great visuals, and has a feature that lets you play music CDs
while the PC is off.
</P>
<P>
   But there should be no illusions about the size and weight of
this system. While it's not quite as heavy as Dell's monstrous
Latitude 7000, it still weighs in at a hefty 8 pounds. It's also
thinner than the Dell, at about 1.6 inches thick. Still, it's so
large, I had to struggle to make it fit the notebook case I
regularly use.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with a huge battery, but with a 400-megahertz Pentium
II chip and the 15-inch screen draining it quickly, it doesn't have
much staying power. I got a little over two hours on it.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, this machine will be sold on Compaq's Web site,
as well as at retail. It is likely to dwarf anything else on the
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to dwight.silverman(a)chron.com, or call
713-220-2000, access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
