<SLUG> BC-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
HOW TO REMOVE SOME ICONS CLUTTERING UP WINDOWS 98 DESKTOP &HT;    (For release July 9, 1999) &HT;    By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Q. By When I first upgraded to Windows 98, I wanted to
have icons for the things I use all the time on my desktop. Since
then, though, things have gotten very cluttered. I want to move
some of these icons back into the folders on the Start menu. How do
I do that?
</P>
<P>
   A. One of the interesting things about the way Windows 95/98 is
designed is that almost everything on the system has to do with
folders. For example, the desktop itself is actually a folder. If
you go into My Computer and find your Windows folder on your main
hard drive, you'll find inside it a subfolder called Desktop. Click
on that, and you'll see all the icons on your Desktop.
</P>
<P>
   The Start menu is also a subfolder found in the Windows folder _
it's called, appropriately enough, Start Menu. From here you can
also get to the Programs folder, and all the program groups that it
holds.
</P>
<P>
   There's a nifty trick you can use to get there quickly, rather
than going through My Computer. Right-click on the Start menu, and
choose Explore from the menu that appears. Now you'll have a
two-pane window that shows the contents of the Start menu on the
right, and a tree-based view of the folder structure on the left.
</P>
<P>
   Use either side to get to the folder that originally held the
icon now on your desktop. Then, just drag the icon into that folder
and drop it there. If you use the right mouse button to do this,
you'll have a choice of moving, copying or creating a shortcut.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it possible to check and read my e-mail from someone
else's computer?
</P>
<P>
   A. If your Internet service provider uses a standard form of
e-mail known as POP3 (for Post Office Protocol), then there are
several services that will let you access your e-mail from any Web
browser.
</P>
<P>
   The one I like to use is MailStart at www.mailstart.com. This
lets you do almost anything a basic e-mail program will do,
including delete messages in batches. It runs a bit slowly _ the
speed also can vary depending on your provider's mail server _ but
works well.
</P>
<P>
   Another is ReadMail at www.readmail.com. It's a little faster,
but does not have as many capabilities as MailStart. (It also
offers a daily national weather map to study while you wait for
your mail!)
</P>
<P>
   Both services require that you put your e-mail password into
their system so it can be passed on to your provider's mail server.
This is a necessity if you want to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Note that these will not work with America Online's mail system,
which does not use POP3. America Online has its own Web-based
e-mail at netmail.web.aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Some other major Internet providers have their own Web e-mail
service. Check with your provider before hitting the road.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I got a new joystick that will work with either a Universal
Serial Bus or a joystick port. I've tried it in both, and really
can't tell the difference. Which is better to use?
</P>
<P>
   A. Use the USB port. It transfers information between the
computer and the joystick much faster than through the gameport.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't notice the difference, chances are the game you
were playing was not that demanding. You might not notice it with,
say, Microsoft Flight Simulator. But you'd definitely see the
difference playing a jet combat simulator such as Falcon 4.0.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for a good Web site that lists new drivers and
patches for the Macintosh. You run some Mac items in Update. Where
do you get them?
</P>
<P>
   A. Try MacFixIt, at www.macfixit.com, which is an excellent site
devoted to troubleshooting and maintaining Macintosh computers. It
not only has driver and patch info, but also includes articles on
issues involving Mac hardware and software.
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(a)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter access
code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
