<HEADLINE>
`MOVIE STARS' DOESN'T SHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
MOVIE STARS 
Starring: Harry Hamlin, Jennifer Grant, Mark Benninghofen, Marnette
Patterson, Zack Hopkins, Rachel David, Anne Haney 
On: The WB 
Time: Sunday and Monday, 9-9:30 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a good time for a mainstream sitcom that trades on insider
knowledge of Hollywood. Because we're all insiders these days, and
ready and willing to get one-liners about Tina Turner's wigs and
Sean Penn's temper and Mel Gibson's many, many children. And we've
all learned not to take Hollywood at face value, to cultivate a
healthy sense of humor about actors and their plastic surgery and
their big bright green publicity machines.
</P>
<P>
   But it's never a good time for a grating sitcom like ``Movie
Stars,'' which squanders its potential on unbelievably stale
entertainment jokes that feel like they've been plucked from last
year's Jay Leno monologues. Someone should tell the writers of this
new WB series that goofs on Kevin Costner's political correctness
and Calista Flockhart's weight issues are very over, to say the
least. They do not constitute sharp Hollywood satire. While
comedies like HBO's ``The Larry Sanders Show'' and ABC's ``It's
like, you know . . .'' have managed to take an original point of
view on the cotton candy that is Lalaland, ``Movie Stars'' is about
as fresh and timely as a crinkled old People magazine in a doctor's
waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not only the lazy entertainment gags that make ``Movie
Stars'' so banal. All the tired references to Dweezil Zappa and
Roseanne and Robin Williams are put in the mouths of a family of
family-sitcom stereotypes who make for very annoying company
indeed. Mom and Dad are major stars: Jacey's an Oscar-nominated
actress and critical fave, while Reese is an action hero who makes
dumb blockbusters about giant insects. But they are meant to be
seen as just plain old ordinary TV parents, who must deal with all
the expected blended-family sitcom issues. The source of most of
their parental angst is Reese's rebellious daughter from a previous
marriage, 16-year-old Lori, who of course doesn't like her stepmom
very much. Meanwhile, Reese and Jacey's kids, ages 13 and 6, do
their precocious-Hollywood-kids bit on the sidelines. Even if the
jokes had vitality, this family would still be deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movie Stars,'' which premieres Sunday at 9 p.m. on Ch. 56,
tries to be clever by giving Reese a demoralized, wannabe brother
named Todd, who works as Reese's assistant. Todd attends a weekly
poker game with other famous brothers _ Joey Travolta, Don Swayze,
Frank Stallone _ each of whom appears as himself. We're supposed to
laugh as the four sit around commiserating on the struggles of
living in the shadows of famous men, but their scenes have an
awkward, desperate undercurrent. Like Swayze, Travolta, and
Stallone, Jennifer Grey plays herself on ``It's like, you know . .
. ,'' but the pathos of her self-ridicule is tempered by the fact
that she is well known for her own work, and not that of her
sibling. She doesn't seem quite as downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   The lead actors are all fine, but not quite natural in the
show's milieu. As Reese and Jacey, Harry Hamlin and Jennifer Grant
behave too much like ordinary Middle Americans to be rich and
famous and living in a gorgeous Malibu beach house. A few more
affectations and a bit more ego might be in order _ and might
provide a few laughs. ``Movie Stars,'' which will air on Sundays
and Mondays at 9 through the summer, fails to offer refreshment
amid the desert of network reruns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
