<HEADLINE>
THE NEW WYNONNA: SINGLE, WORKING MOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wynonna is back on the road with what she proudly calls ``The
Working Mama Tour.'' It's a blend of the musical and the domestic _
and it's working out just fine, thank you, the singer says during a
brief stop at her Nashville home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, I'm a mama by day and a red-headed singer by
night. I'm living the best of both worlds,'' she says. ``It's kind
of like we're on a family vacation and, `Oh, by the way, mama has a
show tonight.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Wynonna's mother, Naomi Judd, jumps on the line to
describe her daughter as ``Xena with an electric guitar.'' That's
an apt phrase, because these days Wynonna is having fun and kicking
butt at the same time with her adrenalized mix of
rhythm-and-blues-spiced country and rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 35 _ and I feel like I'm moving on to the next part of my
life. . . . I believe all things are possible right now,'' says
Wynonna, alias ``Hurricane Wynonna,'' who swoops into the South
Shore Music Circus in Cohasset on Wednesday and the North Shore
Music Theatre in Beverly on July 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a working single parent raising two children _ and mama
wants to work,'' says Wynonna, who has two children, Elijah, 5, and
Grace, 3, by Arch Kelly 3d, whom she recently divorced.
</P>
<P>
   While on the topic of all things being possible, she says she's
making a new album with the help of the Tower of Power horn section
and is about to call Joni Mitchell to ask her to sing backup on a
cover of Mitchell's ``Help Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's one of my heroes,'' Wynonna says of Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   In big news for country fans, Wynonna also will join Naomi to
resurrect the Judds _ the mother-and-daughter duo that ruled the
country airwaves during the '80s. They're planning a one-time-only
New Year's Eve show in Phoenix, though speculation is rife that
more dates may lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not planning anything beyond this show,'' says Wynonna,
countering the rumors. ``And I really want to do it right. It's
like planning a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also very clear that this will celebrate her healing,''
adds Wynonna, referring to how Naomi, who quit the road in 1991
because of Hepatitis C, has since conquered the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi, who has had a TV show, a radio show, and written an
autobiography and a children's book in the intervening years, jumps
on the phone again to mention how excited, but also how nervous,
she is to rejoin her daughter for the concert. But when Wynonna
exclaims that ``Mom, I want my own bus!,'' Naomi fires back, ``I
want my own bus because yours looks like a day-care center!''
</P>
<P>
   Wynonna went solo in 1992 with the album ``Wynonna,'' which sold
5 million copies to become the top-selling female country album
ever at that point. The record has since been broken by LeAnn Rimes
and Shania Twain, but Wynonna is not fazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To thine own self be true,'' she says. ``I want to be true to
myself and what I believe. I don't have to worry about being No. 1
anymore. What I have to do is just keep singing my butt off.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' Wynonna is also very accepting of her legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tammy Wynette paved the road for me _ and I paved it for LeAnn
and Shania. They're the next generation,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As for the widespread success of women in country music, Wynonna
adds, ``God's timing is always right on time. And my philosophy is
that a rising tide lifts all boats. . . . It's a really good time
for women, and if I can jump in line, I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   And, while some artists have taken chippy potshots at Shania's
success, Wynonna says, ``I like her,'' though she admits that
``women either love or hate her, and men covet her success.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynonna is not about to envy anyone, because as she gets older,
she feels more empowered about her own abilities. She just
finished, for example, a confidence-boosting, six-day, 60-mile hike
at the Ashram, a spiritual center, in Calabassus, Calif. (where
Oprah Winfrey has been) and was pleased to lose 13 pounds in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed my perspective on life,'' says Wynonna, who
attended at the suggestion of her sister, actress Ashley Judd. ``I
would get halfway through the hike each day and start crying. I was
the last one on the hike every day, but I still did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynonna says she's also learned to be alone _ another vital step
on what she perceives as her ongoing spiritual journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I'm a hurricane blast, but I'm also realizing how
introverted I am,'' says Wynonna. ``I'm just learning more and more
about myself. And I feel sorry for the next guy who comes along,
because I'll be so aware!''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true working mama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
