<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRGIN-SYNAGOGUE-$ADV     07-09 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGIN-SYNAGOGUE-$ADV10-1STLD- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in first sentence,13th graf, deletes 'continually used' and
adds 'to have never missed Sabbath services.'
 &HT;    VIRGIN ISLANDS' HISTORIC SYNAGOGUE TO GET MUCH-NEEDED FACELIFT
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., July 10 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands _ Imagine it's the late
1600s.
</P>
<P>
   The island of St. Thomas is populated by runaway slaves,
shipwrecked sailors, and soldiers who spend much of their time in a
fog from drinking a witches' brew called Kill Devil Rum.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of this patchwork of personalities is a smattering
of European Jews seeking to eke out a living as shopkeepers and
small landowners after fleeing the Spanish Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The Jews of St. Thomas flourish, bolstered by other Jews from
Brazil and Portugal also seeking refuge from persecution.
</P>
<P>
   By 1796, they raise an astounding $3,476 to build their first
synagogue, a Spanish Moorish structure that is eventually replaced
by something more spacious. But that synagogue -- and then another
-- are destroyed by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1833, the Jews build the ``Holy Congregation of
Blessing and Peace and Loving Deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   It's this synagogue that still stands, appropriately atop the
steep Synagogue Hill, as a testament to the Caribbean's stature as
a tolerant haven for Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But the synagogue, like the congregation it supports, has
suffered with age.
</P>
<P>
   The number of families that belong to the Hebrew congregation
has fallen from 200 in 1993 to about 120 today. Young people have
gone away to college in the United States and never come back;
other people have fled St. Thomas since Hurricane Marilyn
devastated much of the island in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   This week, though, a massive project to restore the synagogue's
original beauty got underway, a restoration that's part of an
ongoing effort by Jewish families here to preserve their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the synagogue to look the way it used to . . . we want
to restore the synagogue's original integrity,'' said architect
Bill Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The $350,000 makeover is expected to be completed by December.
</P>
<P>
   The structure is the oldest synagogue under the American flag to
have never missed Sabbath services. It is the third-oldest
synagogue in the Western Hemisphere after a temple built in 1732 on
the Dutch Caribbean island of Curacao and a 1763 synagogue in
Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation also boasts that its synagogue held the first
confirmation ceremony for Jewish youth in the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   The historical significance of the building, with its arched
window frames and original mahogany pews, has smitten visitors for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The menorah behind the bima, or pulpit, is of Spanish origin and
dates from the 11th century. And the ark contains six Torah
scrolls, three of them Sephardic, the others Ashkenazic. Two of
them are more than 200 years old.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a Czech memorial scroll, one of the few to survive
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   All are part of a Jewish legacy little-known to many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Historians believe that Jews first settled on St. Thomas as
early as 1665, with many reaching the Caribbean -- including such
islands as Curacao -- via Holland, which had opened its doors to
Jews after winning its 80-year battle with Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Holland urged the Jews to settle in the deserted West Indian
islands Holland hoped to control. Those who did soon found work as
shop owners or participants in the region's rum, sugar, and
molasses businesses.
</P>
<P>
   A real influx of Jews to St. Thomas occurred in the 1780s, when
Jews on the Dutch island of St. Eustatius fled here after the
British attacked that island in reprisal for the islanders' aid to
the American forces during the Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   The painter Camille Pissarro was born on St. Thomas in 1830 and
worshipped at the synagogue with his parents before moving to
Europe where he became a leader in the Impressionist movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of Jews in North America begins in the Caribbean,
although not a lot of people know about this,'' said Leon
Weissberg, executive director of the Jewish Education Commission, a
division of the Jewish Federation of South Palm Beach County in
Delray Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He said Jews from the Caribbean first reached Florida in the
1700s, settling both in Key West and Pensacola in Florida's
Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, Pensacola's was the largest Jewish community in
the South outside of Savannah (Ga.),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weissberg added that the renovation of the synagogue on St.
Thomas is vital to preserving an important testament to the faith
of the early Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly time -- as well as a string of hurricanes -- have
taken their toll on the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   It stands in the heart of Charlotte Amalie, known for its narrow
winding streets and the European ambiance of its colonial
buildings. Just a short walk away is a Jewish cemetery, which
includes tombstones dating from 1792.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, the building's walls were stripped of their crumbling
plaster, leaving worshippers to gather within exposed brick and
stone walls. Over the years, salt trapped under layers of sealant
have begun corroding these walls, which were constructed from local
rock and European brick that ships brought to the island as
ballast.
</P>
<P>
   The cement that holds the bricks together is a mortar made from
sand, limestone, and molasses. It is said that, in earlier years,
children used to lick the walls of the synagogue to taste the sweet
molasses.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the renovation, the walls will -- again -- be covered
in plaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exposed brick just didn't work too well,'' said office
manager Roy McMaster. ``Now the walls will be entirely white
again.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the walls, the restoration also will include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The cleaning of four pillars, handmade in Denmark from rounded
bricks, that support the entrance;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  restoration of European chandeliers, a few of which are still
lit by candles on special holidays;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and replacing of the synagogue's ark, constructed with plaster
and a finish of faux wood and marble, with one fashioned from real
marble and real mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   But the structure's sand-covered floor, perhaps its
most-striking feature, will not be touched.
</P>
<P>
   The floor's meaning can be traced to the Sephardic Jews of
Spain. Those Jews had been given a horrific choice: either convert
to Catholicism or face a torturous death at the hands of the
Inquisition. Those who chose to stay -- and stay Jewish -- used
sand on the floor to muffle the sounds of their movements during
prayer so as not to be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to pay tribute to those who came before,''
McMaster said. ``We don't want to do anything that would change
that.''
</P>
<P>
   For your information: To contribute money to the restoration
project, send checks to the Hebrew Congregation, P.O. Box 266, St.
Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands, 00804.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
