<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4570 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx14;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-WATCH-$ADV11-     07-09 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-WATCH-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S GNAWING AT YOUR FUND, AND NOW IT HAS A NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITORS: Originally skedded as MUTFUND-IMPACT-COSTS) 
(For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something is eating into mutual fund returns. It is called
market impact cost _ in essence, the impact that buy or sell orders
can have on stock prices. And Barra Inc., a research and consulting
firm in Berkeley, Calif., has developed a program to let investors
see how much those costs are affecting a portfolio's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like expense ratios, market impact creates a cost that funds
have to overcome before they can add any value,'' said Nicolo
Torre, Barra's managing director for research. ``The lower the
hurdle, the more likely that they will be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barra, which began selling market impact data to institutional
investors about a year ago, has picked up two mutual fund clients,
American Century and Fidelity Investments, that are known to pay
plenty of attention to such costs. Barra has talked to Morningstar
Inc., the Chicago financial publisher, about including market
impact data in its fund ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barra has taken on a large and important issue that until now
people had simply thrown up their hands at,'' said John
Rekenthaler, research director for Morningstar, which is weighing
whether to include the data along with the annual expenses and
sales loads that it reports for funds.
</P>
<P>
   Market impact flows from the idea that stock prices are based on
supply and demand. The more shares available for sale at a given
time, the lower the price buyers will pay. Money managers who place
large orders drive up the demand, and with it the shares' cost _ to
their own detriment. The larger the transaction, the more
significant the market impact.
</P>
<P>
   Market impact costs are more likely to result from trades in
small- and mid-capitalization stocks, because their smaller numbers
of shares provide a less-liquid market and make them more
vulnerable to price swings. Still, a big-enough trade can create
market impact costs in large-cap stocks, too.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose that a manager who expects a company's stock price to
increase 10 percent places a large order for shares priced at $20
each, and that the market responds by pushing up the price by $1.
That is a 5 percent increase, cutting by half the potential profit
in the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokers send bills to cover their transaction costs, but the
market doesn't send you a bill,'' Torre said. He figures that in a
fairly typical case, a small- or mid-cap stock fund with $500
million in assets and an annual turnover rate of 80 to 100 percent
could lose three to five percentage points a year in returns
because of market impact costs _ considerably more than the annual
expenses of the average mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Barra recently analyzed 150 domestic equity mutual funds _ all
with more than $100 million in assets and a track record of least
five years _ for 1996, 1997 and 1998. Among small-cap growth funds,
PBHG Emerging Growth had the highest market impact cost, at 5.73
percent; among mid-cap growth funds, Dresdner RCM Growth Equity was
on top, at 5.23 percent. The figures are estimates based on the
fund's operating style, using a mix of current and historical data.
</P>
<P>
   Some large-cap funds also had high market impact costs. American
Century Equity Growth led the list of large-cap value funds, at
3.29 percent. And another large-cap fund, Phoenix Engemann
Aggressive Growth, had the highest of all, at 8.13 percent. (A
spokeswoman for the fund said that different management was in
charge for most of the period and that the figure did not reflect
the current manager's style.)
</P>
<P>
   To calculate market impact, Barra created a computer model that
weighs more than 20 factors, including trading volume, volatility
and price elasticity for individual stocks. The model covers the
10,000 publicly traded American stockshopes to expand its data base
next year to include international issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rekenthaler offered a caution, though, about the model's
assumptions. For instance, the model might understate market impact
when a fund is run by a big company where many funds trade the same
stocks simultaneously. The figure would also be off if a fund
manager traded stocks significantly more or less often than in the
past. Over all, though, he concluded, ``In most cases, it should
give you a good ball-park figure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
