<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, July 11, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   GYM-TALES (New York) _ The less you spend on your health, the
healthier you become. This is why Kenyans, training barefoot on the
savanna, routinely obliterate America's best runners, despite
millions spent on college training programs. And if the logic here
is flawed, I don't want to hear about it. By Doug Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN-WEDDINGS (Sintra, Portugal) _ The newest place for
destination weddings is Europe: Portugal, Paris, Istanbul. By
Monique Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-IN-THE-CITY (Undated) _ The success of Sex and the City, now
midway through its second season, has taken even some of HBO's
executives by surprise. Last year, when the pilot was being edited,
some at the pay channel wondered if the racy, profane, decidedly
insidery look at the dating scene in New York would fly in other
markets. But Sex and the City, which is based loosely on a New York
Observer column by Candace Bushnell and created by Darren Starr of
``Melrose Place'' fame, has gained the stirring of a cult
following, not only in New York and big cities like Los Angeles and
San Francisco, but, according to HBO, in places like Cleveland,
Providence and Baton Rouge. By Nancy Hass.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-CHEAPDATE-RICHARDS (New York) _ On the town with Marlon
Richards of Cheap Date magazine. By Dana Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ How to care for sunflowers indoors. By
Cass Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   COWIE-ELEGANCE (New York) _ For whatever reason, I recently
accepted an invitation to dine at a new restaurant called City
Hall, for a taping of ``Everyday Elegance With Colin Cowie,'' a
cable television series about ``life as it should be,'' shown on
the Romance Classics and American Movie Classics networks. Life as
it should be, of course, isn't what it used to be. By Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Weekdays, Arceanious Felton (e-mail, arfelton(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
