<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4602 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-09 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOW SOME RESTRAINT WHEN DRIVING WITH YOUR DOG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will common training commands such as ``Sit!'' and ``Stay!''
soon be joined by ``Buckle up?''
</P>
<P>
   The accident injuring horror novelist Stephen King last month
seems to have touched off a great buzz about safety belts for pets.
In the accident, a van driver in Maine was distracted by his unruly
Rottweiler and swerved into King as he was out for a stroll. King
is now recuperating.
</P>
<P>
   Press releases have since poured in. ``Cujo's Revenge: Steven
(sic) King Accident Highlights Need For Pet Travel Safety'' reads
one.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls to leading veterinary hospitals reveal that several
major TV newsmagazines are dogging the issue.
</P>
<P>
   And on top of it all, Saab has just announced it is the first
car company to offer ``a full line of vehicle accessories
specifically designed for pets who travel,'' including the
trademarked ``Batzi Belt,'' a pet restraint system that attaches to
a safety belt.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marty Smith, a veterinarian and one of the founders of the
Doctors Foster &AMP; Smith pet catalog, says the company sells
thousands of these kinds of devices each year. After all, there are
38 million of us dog owners in the United States, and, according to
the Humane Society, half of owners report traveling frequently with
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has seen the consequences. He recounts an incident in
1980, when a woman driving up to his clinic lost control of her car
because her golden retriever pup had jumped down at the pedals. Her
car plowed right through the clinic's outer wall, coming to rest at
the far side of the waiting room. (Both doctors were away, and no
one was in the waiting room at the time.)
</P>
<P>
   Smith says this incident made a few things clear to him. He
reminds how loose animals in cars can cause accidents; they also
might become airborne during an accident and injure themselves or
people; furthermore, he suspects they may distract us even when
they are stationary.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown, Smith says, that because dogs don't talk, we
make more eye contact with them than with humans in order to
communicate. He thinks we probably do a lot more of that while
driving than we realize. We may turn our gaze away from the road
for a few seconds at a time to check on our napping companions.
(Maybe those dash-mounted rear-view mirrors for parents would
help).
</P>
<P>
   Smith says he has treated dogs with broken jaws and legs who
have been tossed about or slammed into dashboards during accidents.
He says that seat restraints, steel mesh buffers and grills, and
crates or carriers help prevent or minimize some accidents.
</P>
<P>
   That makes sense, but the subject gets murkier.
</P>
<P>
   The strange thing is that, with no statistics available on the
issue, two of the biggest animal hospitals in the country _ Angell
Memorial here in Boston, and the Animal Medical Center in New York
_ are hard-pressed to come up with even a couple of examples of
dogs treated for injuries sustained in car accidents. That's dogs
traveling inside cars as opposed to dogs hit by cars.
</P>
<P>
   The TV newsmagazines, always seeking a fresh angle, have been
calling, spokeswomen from both organizations report, but vets at
both places had to wrack their brains to come up with just one or
two examples from the last decade. This from doctors who deal with
thousands of pet injuries each year.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Paul Maloney, spokesman for the Massachusetts State Police,
says that in his 29 years on the force, he has never had an
incident in which he had to find medical attention for a dog
injured inside a car during an accident. A quick survey of his
colleagues available in the office confirmed his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few cases in which healthy pets have been
brought back to the station when an owner was injured. But there is
no protocol for dealing with injured pets, and there just doesn't
seem to be a great need for one, he says.
</P>
<P>
   That's all pretty surprising. But regardless, Saab points out,
logically, that pets in the car are subject to the same hazards as
the human occupants. You may not want to rely on statistical
evidence in deciding to restrain four-legged Rover in your
four-wheeled Land Rover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
