<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-MILITARY-NY     07-09 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA MILITARY SORTS OUT ITS ROLE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Every morning, marine guards prop their
plastic riot shields in menacing rows outside the Parliament
building. Then, shirts off, they jog around the seat of Indonesia's
government as if they own the place, chanting aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a confident army _ its morale and its public
image have been battered by the country's recent turmoil _ and it
no longer knows just what role it is to play inside the Parliament
building, where it has dominated the work of the government for a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Painfully, hesitantly, Indonesia's influential military has
begun to re-define itself, giving away power and privileges in an
attempt to become more professional and less overtly political.
</P>
<P>
   The process of official introspection began well before
President Suharto was forced to resign in May 1998. It has
intensified under the pressure of the reform movement that has been
driving Indonesia toward greater democratic openness in the year
since then.
</P>
<P>
   But in the midst of this retrenchment, the 300,000-man military
suddenly finds itself thrown back into the political spotlight by a
new surge in its own influence.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that in the coming months, the military will be in a
position to play its most overt political role since Suharto took
office 33 years ago and turned it into his personal enforcement
machine. In the past, the power it wielded was Suharto's, not its
own.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the results of a parliamentary election held on June 7
heading for an apparent deadlock between the two leading party
coalitions, more and more political analysts predict that a small,
unified military voting bloc may be in a position to determine who
will become Indonesia's next president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military may actually be put in the position of being
kingmaker, in other words, dictating the winner,'' said Adam
Schwarz, an expert on Indonesia who is the author of ``A Nation in
Waiting'' (Westview Press, 1994).
</P>
<P>
   This would be a remarkable outcome for an election that was
widely described as Indonesia's first democratic vote in four
decades.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear what effect the military's influence would
have. It does not appear bent on seizing power for itself, it does
not appear to wish to halt its process of depoliticization and it
does not appear to have a clear favorite among the leading
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, it is not necessarily an antidemocratic force.
Juwono Sudarsono, an expert on the military who is now minister of
education, noted that the armed forces, under its commander, Gen.
Wiranto, upheld a constitutional change of power last year rather
than trying to seize control for itself when Suharto stepped down.
</P>
<P>
   ``One tends to forget that Wiranto, for all his faults and
failings, put the emphasis on civilian supremacy on that day, May
21,'' Jusono said. ``One could say he laid the foundation for
civilian supremacy.''
</P>
<P>
   With Suharto's departure, the military finds itself reviled more
openly than ever for its past behavior _ the kidnapping, torture
and killings of his critics, the bullying of the official
opposition, including Megawati Sukarnoputri, the corruption and
brutality of its local commanders and its heavy-handed crackdowns
on dissidents and separatists, particularly in East Timor and the
province of Aceh.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its retreat from power, the military accepted a
crucial step this year in reducing its political involvement,
agreeing to a cut in its allotted parliamentary seats, to 38 from
75.
</P>
<P>
   But political analysts say the number of seats it effectively
controls could rise in the current election to 45 or even 55 with
the addition of other officers appointed by regional parliaments.
``On that basis, it could be the third or fourth major force in the
MPR,'' a Western diplomat said, referring to the 700-member
electoral assembly by its initials. ``This could give it the
crucial balance of power.''
</P>
<P>
   But what would the military do with this power?
</P>
<P>
   It does not appear to have a clear agenda, the military analysts
say, apart from making sure it is on the winning side and from
assuring that it can keep control over its own reform.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the vigor of the election process and the turning point
it represents in Indonesia's shift toward a more democratic
society, there do not at the moment appear to be significant issues
that divide the main contenders for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   And with their growing awareness of the potential decisiveness
of the military's role, both blocs appear to be ready to
accommodate its needs.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is Golkar, the governing party, whose presidential
candidate _ for the moment at least _ is the incumbent, B.J.
Habibie, who succeeded Suharto from his post as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto has worked loyally and professionally with Habibie, but
it is not clear how deep their personal or political relationship
goes.
</P>
<P>
   Both men share the political liability of their close
association with Suharto. Some analysts say the military's poor
public image would be further weakened if the military were seen as
taking the decisive step to keep in power a government beholden to
Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side is the party of Mrs. Megawati, which is the
focus of the hopes of many reformers and which appears to have won
a clear plurality in the June vote, which is still being counted.
</P>
<P>
   But with one-third of the seats in a presidential assembly
appointed rather than elected, and with coalition-building becoming
increasingly complex, a victory for Mrs. Megawati is far from
assured.
</P>
<P>
   On issues of importance to the military, some analysts say, she
might be more compatible than Habibie, and she has made what seem
to be gestures toward pleasing the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   She has voiced caution over changing the constitution that has
allowed the military to exercise power.
</P>
<P>
   She is a strong supporter of a unified state and a skeptic about
independence for the disputed territory of East Timor. And she has
suggested that she would not vigorously pursue past abuses, which
notably include the corruption of Suharto and the killings and
brutality of the military.
</P>
<P>
   Salim Said, a political analyst who is an expert on the
military, said the armed forces would prefer not to have to make
the choice at all and are pressing the two blocs to find their own
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Politics just has not worked for the military, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see themselves as moving away from day-to-day politics,
partisan politics,'' he said, ``because their experience of
overreach in politics in the Suharto era was a disaster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
