<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BROTHERS CHALLENGED ON ABORTION ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
 (bl)  
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush and Jeb Bush have something in
common besides sibling ties and serving as governors of large
Sunbelt states. A top abortion-rights group says the duo also
oversaw active anti-abortion legislative agendas in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   As the positioning begins over the divisive issue in advance of
the 2000 elections, the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League put Texas and Florida among its top five states for
most new abortion restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, where GOP presidential front-runner George W. Bush is
governor, enacted seven new laws limiting abortion access, placing
it No. 1 on NARAL's hit list.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, led by younger brother Jeb, earned the fifth spot by
adopting two laws: one requiring that a doctor seek parental
consent before performing an abortion on a minor and another
authorizing a new pro-life license plate.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL officials said the legislative activity flies in the face
of attempts by the Bush brothers to portray themselves as relative
moderates on the abortion issue _ anti-abortion themselves but not
committed to pursuing a hard-line stance. Jeb Bush softened his
rhetoric during his 1998 campaign and George W. Bush indicated he
would not require a vice presidential choice or Supreme Court
nominee to share his views on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the record now shows, Bush and the Texas Legislature are
indeed leaders when it comes to restricting the reproductive rights
of women,'' said NARAL president Kate Michelman.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bushes say they are only endorsing common-sense
approaches such as giving a parent some say in an important medical
decision involving a child. And they have drawn strong support from
women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in general have toned down their talk on abortion,
recognizing it as a subject that has cost them votes in the past.
The new GOP strategy has been to pursue legislation that can
attract centrist support, proposals such as the partial-birth
abortion ban and consent requirements for minors.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING HEADS
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., isn't often confused with Tom
Brokaw or Peter Jennings, but he has been on television almost as
much as the network stars.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby scored the second most Sunday talk show appearances by a
senator this year on a list compiled by Roll Call, the Capitol Hill
newspaper. The lawmaker appeared 14 times so far in 1999, second
only to Joseph Lieberman, D- Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby was a big draw during the impeachment proceedings,
standing out among Republicans for his reservations about the House
case against President Clinton. And as chairman of the Intelligence
Committee, he has been sought after for his views on espionage at
nuclear weapons facilities as well as the war in Kosovo and the
bombing of the Chinese embassy.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only Southerner to regularly face the likes of Tim
Russert and Cokie Roberts. Sen. John Breaux, D-La., a congressional
expert on Medicare known for his colorful sound bites, was also
among the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   POWER STRUGGLE
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Valley Authority continues to serve as a whipping
boy for congressional critics.
</P>
<P>
   With some lawmakers determined to cut any federal subsidies for
the utility, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., is attacking the TVA on a
new front _ electric rates.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell this month introduced a measure that would subject the
TVA to the same scrutiny other utilities get, forcing the agency to
justify its consumer rates and other charges. McConnell complained
that TVA's heavy debt has driven its rates upward while other
utilities have cut charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a self-regulated monopoly, TVA has not been accountable to
its captive ratepayers,'' said McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   VETERANS BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to shake-up the way the Department of Veterans Affairs
delivers health care to thousands of vets have reverberated through
the top ranks of the agency. Both VA Secretary Togo West and agency
health care chief Kenneth Kizer are on their way out.
</P>
<P>
   Kizer, who has shifted resources from the Northeast and Midwest
to the South with the migration of veterans, angered federal
employee advocates and other interest groups with his aggressive
push to move the agency away from hospital care to more reliance on
outpatient clinics. The physician chose not to seek reconfirmation
rather than endure a Senate battle.
</P>
<P>
   West came under fire for his personal conduct, drawing criticism
for his frequent travel and a decision to order a new luxury car
for his official use when his agency was facing a budget crisis.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers. This article was
distributed by the New York Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
