<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-STYLE-2NDTAKE-     07-09 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-STYLE-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
(Refiling for those needing)
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) ... one good handbag.``
</P>
<P>
   A key ingredient that observers of French style mention
frequently is presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A $5 item is wrapped like it cost $50,'' said Rives, ``and
that extends to their clothing style.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for outsiders, it is often difficult to penetrate the
French faade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French are wonderful people,'' said Rives, ``but until you
get to know them, they are a little reserved, especially compared
to Italians, who are sort of like the Texans of the
Mediterranean.''
</P>
<P>
   The French like to do a lot of entertaining at home, but only
for people they know well. Rives describes their homes as a mixture
of old French with modern _ ``old velvet curtains with a
contemporary suede couch.''
</P>
<P>
   In fashion, the concept of professional business dress for women
does not exist in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wear dark clothes and never wear white sneakers,'' said
Georgene Brandon, head of community relations and special events
for PricewaterhouseCoopers, a business advisory firm with offices
in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's how the women put their clothes together _ so chic, and
it looks so uncomplicated,'' she said. ``They have less in their
wardrobes but better quality. They can wear a black skirt and a
white blouse, and it looks so sharp but important and
professional.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon also believes that it is possible to absorb French
style, especially by spending as much time there as possible
``eating, watching and wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After I visited our Paris office, it made me take a new look
at how we do things,'' she said. ``When I told them we had
breakfast meetings at 7 a.m., they were horrified. They start a
breakfast meeting at 9, at the civilized hour, and it's not `grab a
danish and a Slurpee.' They really have tables, are seated and have
a lighter breakfast than we do, with fruit, croissants and
prserves. They don't cram in as many meetings as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentley credits some of the French sophistication to geography.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are well-traveled because of where they live. It gives
them more attitude and more cultural knowledge. More people know
more languages and so appear more sophisticated. And, too, they
take monthlong holidays every summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Bearden is another Texan who has come to love the French
lifestyle. Bearden has visited France three times in the last two
years and admires the French imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are daring and try things other people wouldn't even
think to try. When you first see some of these things, you think,
`Oh, I wouldn't do that.' But when you try it on ... ''
</P>
<P>
   She most recently fell for a long, sheer skirt worn over a
short, opaque mini, and she bought a black Thierry Mugler skirted
cocktail suit with red velvet cuffs. Now she wears the suit jacket
with a pair of black Gap pants.
</P>
<P>
   But Bearden said she doesn't credit the French woman for style
as much as she credits the French designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes me when I travel over there and everyone is dressed
in drab black, summer and winter. But their love of flowers amazes
me. There is a stand on every corner, and they take time out to buy
flowers and appreciate them.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
