<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4615 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-STYLE-2TAKES-W     07-09 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-STYLE-2TAKES-W/ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
(Refiling for those needing) &HT;    FRENCH STYLE: WHAT IS IT, AND HOW DO YOU GET IT? &HT;    By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN
 &HT;    c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Ask most Americans who embodies style, and they almost
invariably point to the French.
</P>
<P>
   Coco Chanel. Catherine Deneuve. Even Brigitte Bardot, who for a
few moments in history epitomized everything some viewed as French,
mainly sizzle and skin.
</P>
<P>
   As first lady, Jacqueline Kennedy had French style, and among
the British, both Princesses Diana and Fergie coveted it.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Americans what constitutes French style, and they have a
hard time putting their fingers on it. The women look put together,
they'll say, not overdone. And they always know what to do with a
scarf.
</P>
<P>
   While Paris is indeed considered the cradle of fashion, French
style is more than that. There is a certain je ne sais quoi, as the
Gauls themselves would put it, about the way a French woman puts
herself together.
</P>
<P>
   For another thing, men dig it.
</P>
<P>
   Skirts in the States tend to fall straight from the hips, but in
France they are tighter, cupping the buttocks, and are often worn
with high heels that tighten and shape the legs.
</P>
<P>
   Men dig the way French women wear fresh, white men's shirts with
their jeans and even men's jackets, all elements of sportswear but
worn with femininity. Maybe the shirt collar's worn up, and for
sure the hair is shiny and clean, and the skin flawless.
</P>
<P>
   And men dig the way French women wear boots with skirts and
suits, exposing leg between the hem and boot tops. And at night,
they go for everything from simplest black to no-holds-barred
glamour.
</P>
<P>
   American women like it that their French counterparts wear hats
that are truly confections to weddings _ and without a speck of
self-consciousness. Basically, a casual approach to fashion that
comes off as trs, trs chic to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But French style goes much deeper than wearing a cartwheel hat
or casually tying on a scarf that costs as much as a month's
groceries. It involves not only fashion but beauty, attitude and
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   French style is in the home, the furniture they choose, the
tables they set, the flowers they arrange, the shopping bags they
tote to market and the sunglasses they wear for driving. French
style is in the food _ not only snails, sauces and mystery meats
but pt, souffls, steak frites (steak and French fries, to you) and
those long, crusty loaves of French bread called baguettes.
</P>
<P>
   The French have an ability unique among cultures, write Suzanne
Slesin and Stafford Cliff, authors of ``French Style'' (Potter,
$35), ``to be perceived as a more cultured, more elegant, more
stylish people, and to make others feel at some disadvantage in not
being born French themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Slesin and Cliff wrote of interior design and the
essentially Gallic way of arranging objects to best advantage, the
statement also applies to French everything, especially fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The French have almost institutionalized their style. So
confident are they that names such as Coco Chanel, Christian Dior,
Givenchy, Herms and Louis Vuitton can exist almost in perpetuity
that those houses now have designers who are German, British,
Belgian or American.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what constitutes French style is the element of
surprise. Yet the surprise is that the French themselves have
trouble pinning down what that element of shock is or how it is
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``French style is good champagne, costly perfume and a great
haircut,'' said Vronique Vienne in ``French Style: How to Think,
Shop and Dress Like a French Woman'' (Express, $20).
</P>
<P>
   When Vienne, born and raised in Paris, moved to the United
States, she found everyone expected her to live up to his or her
ideal of a typical Parisian woman _ ``with a beret, red lipstick
... and a baguette under my arm. Men were disappointed because I
did not wear fishnet stockings. Their wives assumed I was going to
be an outrageous flirt.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Vienne, a French woman does not flaunt her
Frenchness but never lets one forget she is a woman, although she
can't define what a woman is.
</P>
<P>
   Vienne describes the French fashion style as a mixed metaphor _
white socks with black lace, menswear with ruffles. Those surprises
again. But is it instinct or a learned art?
</P>
<P>
   Houstonian June Rives believes that French style is absorbed as
a child.
</P>
<P>
   As president and owner of June Rives Public Relations, she
represents Air France and travels to France frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French overall, especially French women, have a certain
basic, natural, inbred style. It's obvious when you walk down the
street: They accessorize beautifully, wear very fine shoes, the
finest fabrics,'' Rives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the simplest, most modest-income Parisian woman is taught
how to put accessories together _ to look simply chic. It's almost
done without thought. I've never seen a French woman that looked
unkempt,'' she said, ``compared to British men, who look like
unmade beds. The French men and women are always well-dressed, hair
well-groomed. Even if they don't have a lot of money, they'll spend
money to buy one Herms scarf, one good handbag.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
