<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-PARTNERSHIPS-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 50-50 SPLIT MEANS FEWER WORRIES FOR GROWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CALIF-NAPA-WINE and CALIF-GALLO-PROFILE)  
 (For release Sun., July 11)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ALICE FEIRING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The ballroom was jumping with Chilean music, and
plates of hors d'oeuvres were circulating. But the wine very nearly
missed its own party.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the New York introduction of Sena, the product
of a high-visibility joint venture between the Robert Mondavi
Winery and Vina Errazuriz of Chile. What stands out about the
arrangement is its ownership structure, one that until recently
most winemakers shied away from: a 50-50 partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Vintners consider their business more art than science, and the
field is thickly populated with headstrong entrepreneurs and family
scions. In such an environment, partnerships where neither side has
the final say might appear doomed to deadlock and collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Mondavi, president and chief executive of Mondavi,
says the only impasse in the Sena venture was a minor one, just
before the New York debut: Mondavi wanted a blue label on the
bottles, while Eduardo Chadwick, head of the prominent Chilean
winemaking family that owns Errazuriz, preferred red.
</P>
<P>
   ``If either of the two partners had full authority over the
design, the decision would have taken half the time,'' Mondavi
said. ``But in the end, I feel it has a positive effect on
business.'' (Then again, he prevailed; they went with blue.)
</P>
<P>
   Mondavi's successful equal partnerships have helped propel an
industry trend. In the last few months, Chateau Mouton-Rothschild
of France and Concha y Toro of Chile announced a 50-50 joint
venture called Almaviva; Chateau Ste. Michelle, a winery in
Washington State, and Antinori of Italy formed one called Col
Solare. California's Wente Vineyards has similar ventures with
winemakers from Mexico, India and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Mondavi's first equal partnership began two decades ago, and it
long remained one of a kind. Mondavi's father, Robert, was
approached by Baron Philippe de Rothschild several times in the
1970s about producing a California wine together, so the two
``could finally agree on what was a great wine,'' the younger
Mondavi recounted. Begun in 1978, the venture proceeded slowly but
eventually yielded a celebrated wine, Opus One, that fetches $100 a
bottle and sells out rapidly each year.
</P>
<P>
   His father treated Opus as a singular labor of friendship, but
Michael Mondavi saw it as a prototype for globalizing the company.
As he took over Mondavi's reins in the early 1990s, he started
similar ventures with the Frescobaldi family of Italy and the
Chadwicks in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   The six products from the three joint ventures account for only
3.5 percent of Mondavi's $325 million in sales, but they are
central to its plans to sell more wine overseas. Mondavi now
exports 9 percent of its output, high by American standards but far
below the 80 percent figure for the Frescobaldi wineries.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-50 nature of Opus was born in the rapport between two
patriarchs, but Mondavi said its practical advantages over majority
ownership by his winery soon became clear: the accounting is
simpler, and so are the local politics of land use and permits in
countries where Americans can be seen as interlopers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, partners tend to contribute resources more
unstintingly when they do not feel ``junior,'' Mondavi said. By
teaming up with partners who know the local soil, climate and
people, ``we are able to jump-start the process,'' he said. ``We
produce a better wine in less time and for a lower initial
investment'' than Mondavi could on its own.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the Italian venture, Luce. Charged with creating a wine
to appeal to both American and Italian tastes, the two winemakers _
Mondavi's brother Tim and Lamberto Frescobaldi, whose father,
Vittorio, is president of Marchesi de'Frescobaldi _ tried a
so-called super-Tuscan, a sangiovese-cabernet blend. But they
struggled to produce anything mutually satisfactory until Tim had
the idea of adding merlot grapes from a nearby Frescobaldi
vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Lamberto made that wine alone, he would never have
considered merlot,'' Michael Mondavi said. ``If we went there
alone, we wouldn't have had those grapes available to us. This is
the beauty of a 50-50.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar dynamics propel newer ventures by other wineries.
Antinori, for example, may want access to super-premium grapes
grown outside Italy because of shortages at home, while its
American partner, Chateau Ste. Michelle, says the venture helps it
move into a higher-priced market segment.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced of the merits of 50-50 arrangements.
``We've done 50-50 domestically,'' said Phil Woodward, chairman of
Chalone Wine Group of Napa, Calif., ``and though there are
advantages to this kind of partnership, one of the two partners
clearly has to be the final decision maker.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lewis Perdue, editor of Wine Investment News, likened the
ventures, most of which garner headlines in the wine press but
involve small volumes of wine, to publicity stunts. ``These kinds
of partnerships are less of a trend and more of a PR stink that may
get clobbered by the coming global wine glut,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mondavi is sold on the idea and is open to more
opportunities, perhaps in France, Hungary or even China. ``Anything
is possible,'' Mondavi said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
