<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS HIGHER USE OF DRUGS AMONG BORDER STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Secondary school students along the Texas-Mexico
border are more likely to have tried cocaine than their peers in
the rest of the state, according to statewide survey.
</P>
<P>
   Cocaine use among all Texas secondary school students increased
by 40 percent between 1988 and 1998, the Texas Commission on
Alcohol and Drug Abuse said this week.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were based on a survey of more than 150,000
students statewide in grades seven through 12. There was no
breakdown available of district-by-district results.
</P>
<P>
   One researchers called the findings ``outrageous'' and said the
spike in cocaine usage can be traced to a combination of the drug's
widespread availability and the strong attention law enforcement
agencies have given crack cocaine, a highly potent and addictive
form of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so concerned about crack, we kind of lost sight of
powder cocaine,'' said Jane Maxwell, chief researcher for the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Among 60,000 students surveyed in school districts along the
border, 13.8 percent reported using cocaine at least once, while
nearly 6 percent reported using the illicit drug during the
preceding month.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas of the state, 9.3 percent of students reported
using cocaine once, and 3.5 percent admitted using cocaine in the
preceding 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is outrageous,'' Maxwell said. ``We shouldn't have to see
one in 10, or one in eight, of our children using cocaine.''
</P>
<P>
   Although cocaine usage is higher along the border, Maxwell said,
the trend doesn't hold true for other drugs. For example, students
in other areas of the state reported greater use of marijuana and
hallucinogens, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't paint the border as a drug haven,'' Maxwell said.
``The truth is that there are things in the Hispanic culture that
we should be trying to duplicate all over the state. There is some
real strength in that culture that helps kids stay away from
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell said Hispanic children are more likely to come from
two-parent households and many times are surrounded by various
members of the extended family as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
