A4668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ROCKET-NYT &LR;      07-09 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ROCKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAZAKHSTAN BLOCKS A MISSILE LAUNCHING BY RUSSIA  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMATY, Kazakhstan _ Three days after a Russian rocket
disintegrated over a grain-growing region of this Central Asian
republic, the government barred Russia from carrying out a
scheduled launching on Thursday from Baikonur Cosmodrome.
</P>
<P>
   After the launching was halted, government officials said they
found toxic fuel from the launching on Monday of a Proton rocket in
Karkaralinsk, 435 miles north of here, where a large piece of the
spacecraft crashed into a shepherd's yard, and other wreckage set
many acres of steppe on fire. No injuries were reported, but the
accident quickly revived long-held local resentment of vast
environmental and health damage, including chronic birth defects,
left behind from decades of nuclear tests and space launchings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the accident comes at a time of increased bilateral
tension between the two former Soviet neighbors. Since 1994, Moscow
has ostensibly leased Baikonur from Kazakhstan for commercial
launchings and missions to its Mir space station, but it has yet to
pay any of the $115 million annual rent.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan officials said no more launchings will be permitted
until the environmental consequences of Monday's accident are
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan officials said a scientific commission was examining
the environmental consequences of the accident. ``All launches from
Baikonur Cosmodrome will be forbidden until the commission
investigation gives a conclusion to the reason for the
catastrophe,'' said Rasul Jumaliev, a spokesman for the Kazakhstan
Foreign Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Kazakhstani political activists on Thursday night
delivered a letter to the Russian Embassy here, blaming Moscow for
the republic's ecological problems, and demanding ``the payment of
all possible expenses for the liquidation of the past
catastrophes.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Itar-Tass reported that a Russian Foreign Ministry
spokesman, Vladimir Rakhmanin, had apologized for the crash and
agreed that Proton launches should be suspended until the reason
for the crash is known.
</P>
<P>
   Yet other comments from Moscow suggested that Russian officials
were losing patience on the issue. Sergei Gorbunov, a spokesman for
Russia's space agency, dismissed Kazakhstan's ban on all launches
as ``an emotional outburst,'' adding that ``the accident was not an
ecological catastrophe, the population did not suffer. It is not a
technical problem, but a political decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Russian officials tested Kazakhstan's resolve by
proceeding with preparations for Thursday's scheduled launch -- a
Ukrainian exploratory satellite aboard a Zenith booster -- almost
until its midday launch time and the word that the ban would indeed
be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian officials hope to proceed Friday or Monday with the
launching that had been scheduled for Thursday, and to send up a
computerized navigation system to Mir on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow considers the Mir mission particularly vital because its
last crew will conclude its mission next month, and the new
navigation system will prevent the unmanned spacecraft from
hurtling to Earth before Moscow can raise the money to send up a
fresh mission.
</P>
<P>
   Rakhmanin appealed for Kazakhstan to lift the ban for spacecraft
not using the Proton-K heavy booster rocket ``so as not to disrupt
both bilateral and international commitments relying on the use of
the Baikonur Cosmodrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Kazakhstan obtained yet another promise from Russia:
to finally begin paying rent on Baikonur this month; the current
dispute could be used as a lever to initiate the much-needed cash
flow.
</P>
<P>
   The accident could be a setback for the Proton, Russia's
workhorse booster and the spearhead of an effort, with Lockheed
Martin Corp., to commercialize Russia's space industry in the face
of failure in virtually every other part of its economy. The
Proton's last crash was in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Proton is scheduled to launch a Russian-made
living quarters for the $60-billion International Space Station, a
joint venture of 16 nations including the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
