<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS-DECLARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTY CHEATERS BEWARE! THE CUSTOMS SERVICE IS READY FOR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 11)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JANE WOLFE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, like Florida's first lady, you have been known to skirt the
rules when bringing back merchandise from abroad, you may want to
mend your ways.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Customs Service estimates that each year, hundreds of
thousands of travelers break the rules, often saying either that
they forgot to pay duties or that they didn't know about them. But
Customs is making it more difficult to use ignorance as an excuse
for cheating.
</P>
<P>
   Airline passengers are about to be hit with a barrage of
warnings about Customs rules and the penalties for breaking them.
Signs and kiosks will greet travelers at the airport; Customs
employees will approach some of them in international departure
lounges to talk about the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties can be as much as eight times the amount of duty that
should have been paid, and the merchandise is sometimes
confiscated. In some cases, the violation can be a criminal
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity about the $4,100 civil fine recently paid by Columba
Bush, the wife of Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida, after she failed to
declare all the clothes and jewelry she brought home from a Paris
shopping spree has caught the attention of travelers everywhere.
Mrs. Bush paid fines that amounted to about three times the duty
she would have paid on the items, which cost her $19,000 and had a
domestic value of $25,000. The cost to her husband _ in reputation
and future votes _ is harder to tally.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials say that while stories like Mrs. Bush's will
make people think twice about improper declarations, amateur
smugglers have become emboldened in recent years because fewer
people are searched than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1980, inspectors questioned every passenger and usually
searched bags. In 1975, Betsy Bloomingdale _ wife of Alfred
Bloomingdale, an heir to the New York department store fortune _
was caught failing to report full value of two Christian Dior
dresses. Because duties are intended to protect stores and
manufacturers against foreign competition, that was big news.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous increase in international travelers, though, has
made such comprehensive searching impossible. Some 71 million
passengers cleared customs last year, almost four times the 18
million in 1980, while the number of Customs employees held steady
at 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't used to being questioned, so they wonder, `Why
me?''' said Susan Mitchell, assistant Customs director for
passenger operations at Kennedy International Airport in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A traveler pulled aside for more than cursory questioning may be
suspected of breaking the law or may just have been the unlucky
person at the front of the line when a selection timer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   At Kennedy Airport between October 1998 and May 1999, $330,000
in penalties were paid on $2.1 million in improperly declared
merchandise brought in by 460 travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers are allowed to bring in $400 in merchandise
duty-free. A 10 percent duty is levied on the next $1,000, and
further duties at various levels, depending on the items. If
travelers bring in a substantial amount of merchandise they intend
to sell, a violation can even mean jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers caught failing to declare items or underestimating
their value usually end up paying between two and eight times the
duty. But even when they are caught, violators might not be fined
if they cooperate with inspectors, said Don Simpson a Customs
supervisor at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should say, `I'm sorry,' and you should not withhold
information,'' he said. ``If there's an invoice we want, show it to
us. More than likely we'll find it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, thousands of people each year try to outwit Customs
officials. And even when inspectors who suspect lawbreaking give
people a last chance to amend their declarations, many choose not
to.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors go to school to learn how to spot smugglers. Nervous
hands and averted eyes are easy first clues. ``We don't do
profiling, but we target based on certain countries,'' Ms. Mitchell
said. ``Every flight has its own threat. Flights from Paris have
the fashion goods threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Marie Spiess, the Customs director for passenger operations
at Dallas-Fort Worth, knows the usual ploys. ``Jewelry is usually
hidden on the person or worn out in the open, and the inspector may
be hard-pressed to prove the person bought it on the trip,'' she
said. ``If we believe this person is smuggling, we can detain the
item and have them prove it was purchased previously.''
</P>
<P>
   Suitcase linings and toiletry bags are popular hiding places.
``People think we don't want to go digging in the toiletry bag
because it's all mushy in there, but they're wrong,'' Ms. Spiess
said.
</P>
<P>
   Removing clothing labels is an old trick, but inspectors often
find receipts. And bands removed from Cuban cigars, which are
normally not permitted to enter this country, are often found
hidden elsewhere. The items that are most often declared improperly
are expensive clothing, jewelry, laptop computers and perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Many travelers do not realize that some items, such as art and
antiques, are not subject to duty but nevertheless must be
declared. ``Our mantra is declare, declare, declare,'' an inspector
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
