<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-CHEAPDATE-RICHARDS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH MARLON RICHARDS: THRIFTY, WITH A PEDIGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 11)  
 (bl)  
 By DANA DICKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ AT 9 p.m. Monday, the temperature sign on Manhattan
Mini Storage on Varick Street read 103 degrees. A few blocks west,
inside a gritty club called Don Hill's, Marlon Richards tucked in
his billowy white shirt to neaten up for a party celebrating the
first issue of Cheap Date, a magazine about punk rock and
thrift-store shopping produced largely by children of upper-crust
families.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no open bar this night, but also no cover charge,
in keeping with Cheap Date's editorial creed: ``Living with less
with style.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards, 27, the son of Keith Richards of the Rolling Stones,
is art director of the magazine. The editor is Bay Garnett, 26, a
daughter of Andy Garnett, a member of the English aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Richards' wife, Lucie de la Falaise, the daughter of
Loulou de la Falaise, the longtime Yves Saint Laurent muse,
arrived. ``I asked Marlon, `Do we have to dress cheap?''' Ms. de la
Falaise said. ``He said no.'' She wore a pretty party dress with
narrow straps.
</P>
<P>
   Richards and Ms. Garnett handed guests the canary-covered,
42-page quarterly and a matching T-shirt. The magazine, really more
of a zine, has articles like ``Give Me Barneys Any Day,'' about a
reluctant convert to thrift shopping, and a column by filmmaker
Harmony Korine in which he imagines the provenance of thrift-store
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Richards gave a warm bearhug to Rafael de Rothschild of the
banking family, who arrived with model Karen Elson. Her sheer,
brown, flowered dress came from a London thrift store, Virginia.
``We're the two most in-love people in the world,'' she said,
kissing Rothschild. Ms. Elson is featured in Cheap Date in a mock
beauty pageant picture spread.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd danced and otherwise sucked the chill from the
room, Richards stood with Alex Friedman, 27, a son of Boston
property developer Richard Friedman, who has loaned his Martha's
Vineyard compound to the Clintons for summertime visits. Alex
Friedman, who wrote an article for Cheap Date about a bartender who
coveted a thrift-store coat, had invited Richards and Ms. de la
Falaise to the family house the following day.
</P>
<P>
   Another contributor, Iris Palmer, a model and the daughter of
Sir Mark Palmer, said, ``I think it's insulting to charge a lot for
clothes.'' She pulled out the nondesigner label of her white coat
dress. ``It's all consumerism, isn't it?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Near midnight, Richards was alone in a corner, enrapt in a video
car-racing game called Super Battle. He moved to the bar, and soon
was talking to Amber Valletta, the covergirl, who had her blond
hair fluffed to resemble a 1970s Farrah Fawcett. ``You should ask
me to contribute something for the next issue,'' Ms. Valletta told
him ``I could write something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, that'd be great,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Mogg, a bassist formerly with Nancy Boy, who contributed
an article on rock bands with big hair, pondered the appeal of
penny pinching to the children of wealthy, often titled parents.
``It's like a rich slacker thing,'' said Mogg, who is from a modest
North London family. ``But they're my friends, so I can't go too
deep into it because it will sound insulting.'' He laughed. ``But
Marlon has done a good thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
