<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA MAKES BIG PUSH INTO FULL-SIZE U.S. TRUCK MARKET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toyota has launched the first import-brand attack on the U.S.
full-size truck market.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Toyota Tundra, designed to compete against the Ford
F-150, Chevrolet Silverado/GMC Sierra and Dodge Ram, went on sale
in late May, accompanied by a $40 million advertising blitz that
bills the new truck as the ``best in class.''
</P>
<P>
   With its optional 4.7-liter, 32-valve V-8 engine rated at 245
horsepower and 315 foot-pounds of torque, the Tundra is the first
import-brand truck to match at least the mid-range power of the
full-size U.S. pickups.
</P>
<P>
   The Tundra is designed and built for the U.S. market, and to
avoid the 25 percent federal tax on imported trucks, Toyota is
assembling these vehicles at a new plant near Princeton, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, whose F-series has been the best-selling vehicle in North
America for several years, can relax for now, though. Toyota isn't
going to unseat the F-series anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Tundra sells out, plant capacity is only 100,000
trucks a year. Ford sells upwards of 600,000 F-series trucks each
year. Toyota expects to sell just one-tenth as many Tundras this
model year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the arrival of the Tundra brings the Japanese auto
industry into a market it has never broached. With the industry's
reputation for quality and perfection, Toyota is going to be a
force to be reckoned with, even in this U.S.-manufacturer-dominated
market segment.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Toyota officials believe that Tundra sales will come
primarily from traditional buyers of smaller Japanese trucks, such
as the compact Toyota Tacoma, who want to move up to a bigger and
faster machine. Another expected market is first-time pickup buyers
who prefer import products.
</P>
<P>
   Cracking the Ford/GM/Dodge full-size monopoly will be tough,
primarily because current owners of these trucks are loyal
customers and are passionate about their pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota must prove itself as a capable truck builder to win over
buyers from Ford and General Motors, much in the same way Dodge has
been doing since the introduction of the current Ram model in the
mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   Dodge made a name for itself with the radical new styling of the
Ram, along with its optional, powerful V-8 and V-10 engines.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota will make a name for itself in the full-size truck market
through a combination of attributes found in the new Tundra:
pleasing, if not radical, styling; excellent performance from
either the base V-6 or optional V-8 engine; its carlike ride and
handling; and a combination of quality, durability and ruggedness.
</P>
<P>
   The Tundra comes in two- and four-wheel-drive models with either
a regular two-door cab (with no back seat) or the Access Cab model,
with four doors and a back seat that is roomy enough for three
adults. Regular-cab models have an eight-foot bed. The Access Cab's
bed is six-and-a-half-feet long. There are three trim levels: the
base Tundra, midlevel SR5 and high-end Limited.
</P>
<P>
   We tested the four-wheel-drive, V-8, SR5 Access Cab model (base
price $25,585 plus $447 transportation), which came with a list of
options that ran the pricetag up to $29,336. With all that was
included in this price, the Tundra competes head-to-head with the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The all-new V-8 engine, based on the engine used in the upscale
Lexus LS 400, is the heart of this vehicle. Along with one of the
smoothest-shifting four-speed automatic transmissions on the
market, this powerplant gives the Tundra a sports car feel. Punch
the gas and this vehicle takes off, and it doesn't seem anything
like a truck. That kind of zip was lacking in Toyota's T-100
pickup, a V-6, midsize model that just didn't catch on with U.S.
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The four-wheel drive is a shift-on-the-fly system engaged by
pushbutton on the dash. There is a separate button to put the
transmission into low range for serious off-roading.
</P>
<P>
   The Tundra cab is as quiet as that of a Camry sedan, a real
accomplishment for a full-size pickup. Stepping up into the cab was
easy with the chrome-tube-based step-board on each side (a $399
dealer accessory).
</P>
<P>
   The rear doors swing out to the rear, and provide a wide opening
to the back seat. And unlike the competition, the Tundra's rear
doors have handles outside and inside like a normal door, rather
than in the door jamb.
</P>
<P>
   The V-8 engine provides enough power for a 2,000-pound payload
and for towing a trailer of up to 7,500 pounds _ also a first for
an import-brand truck.
</P>
<P>
   The base V-6 engine is a 3.4-liter, 24-valve powerplant rated at
190 horsepower and 220 foot-pounds of torque _ comparable to the
V-6 in the Ram, but slightly less powerful than the base
six-cylinder engines in the F-series and GM pickups. Still, many
buyers will choose the V-6 and find it more than adequate for their
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Standard safety features include dual front air bags (with
passenger bag cut-off switch), head rests and three-point seatbelts
in the outboard positions, an energy-absorbing steering column and
side-impact door beams. Four-wheel antilock brakes are optional,
and were not included on our test vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   A front bench seat is standard, but our vehicle came with dual
front captain's chairs ($75). A two-level center console had a
storage compartment and two large cup holders suitable for a Big
Gulp on the lower level. A pair of smaller cup holders pops out of
the dashboard in all Tundras.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard equipment includes air-conditioning, chrome
bumpers and mirrors, locking tailgate and fuel door, tilt steering
wheel, cruise control, dual power outlets plus lighter in the lower
dash, cut-pile carpeting and an AM/FM/cassette stereo with six
speakers.
</P>
<P>
   A convenience package on our vehicle ($2,050) added power
windows and door locks, sliding rear window and more. Other options
included 16-inch aluminum-alloy wheels ($630), an upgrade to a
cassette/compact-disc audio system ($100), fog lamps ($130), and a
dealer-added ``Extra Mile'' options package ($1,190) that tacked on
carpeted floor mats and custom pinstriping, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 14 miles per gallon in the city and
17 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 26.4 gallons of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   2000 Toyota Tundra SR5 Access Cab 4X4 pickup
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Full-size, four-door, five- or six-passenger, V-6
or V-8 powered, four-wheel-drive pickup, an all-new model.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: Toyota becomes the first import brand with a
full-size pickup for the U.S. market. With its 245-horsepower V-8
engine and beautiful styling, this truck is ready to take on the
big Ford, Chevy/GMC and Dodge pickups. Ride and handling are
carlike, power is awesome with the V-8, and quality and
dependability will be hallmarks of the Tundra.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: No complaints.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Ford F-150, Chevrolet Silverado/GMC Sierra,
Dodge Ram.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 14 miles per gallon city, 17 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $25,585 plus $447 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $29,336, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A-plus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
