</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-VOTE-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES IN EARLY BATTLE FOR HISPANIC VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's still early in the 2000 election race, but
already Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore are
slugging it out over an increasingly important constituency:
Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican frontrunner, made courtship of Latinos a
top priority during his visit to San Diego late last month, saying
he had won support from Hispanics in Texas and ``I intend to do
(that) here in the state of California as well.''
</P>
<P>
   A Texan who is at home with Hispanic language and culture, Bush
laces his speeches with Spanish phrases and does interviews on
Hispanic television in Spanish. By contrast, Gore, the Democratic
frontrunner, offers some Spanish sentences in his speeches but is
not as fluent as Bush in the language.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing sudden vulnerability in a reliable segment of their
voting bloc, Democrats are launching a salvo of their own. A
three-page press release put out by the Democratic National
Committee highlights what it calls ``Bush's anti-Hispanic record.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Chairman Roy Romer acknowledged in an
interview last week that Bush ``has support from the Hispanic
community greater than most Republicans have.'' But he added,
``This early in the campaign, people like excitement and new
personalities, but you've got to know what you're buying. There
might be new wrapping, but the content is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing Bush's opposition to affirmative action and statistical
sampling, a technique that would supplement actual head-counting in
the census, Romer said, ``When (Hispanic voters) get to know him
and contrast his record with the Democrats' (record), his
popularity will drop.'' Romer and other sampling proponents say use
of the technique would avoid the traditional undercount of poor
people including Hispanics and African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has won the endorsement of black entrepreneur Ward
Connerly, a University of California regent and the guiding force
behind Proposition 209, the 1996 voter-approved initiative that
barred the state from considering gender or race in contracts,
hiring or public university admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he believes in ``the spirit of no quotas and no
preferences.'' But his supporters point out that in five years as
governor, he has backed creative alternatives to affirmative
action. For instance, after federal courts banned race-conscious
admissions to the University of Texas, Bush supported legislation
to boost minority enrollment by giving automatic admission to the
top 10 percent of graduates from every Texas high school.
</P>
<P>
   On statistical sampling, Bush, like most Republicans, argues
there is no substitute for the actual counting of the population, a
position the U.S. Supreme Court upheld earlier this year. ``Gov.
Bush believes we should count every person and if cities think
they've been undercounted, we should keep counting until we get it
right,'' said Bush campaign spokesman Mindy Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore has backed sampling and the administration's
policy of ``mend it but don't end it'' regarding affirmative
action. Gore contends the administration's economic policies have
helped boost Hispanic family income and notes that Clinton has
appointed more Hispanics to high office than any other president,
particularly his Republican predecessors, George Bush and Ronald
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   By one estimate, 8 percent of Clinton's appointees have been
Hispanic, compared with 5 percent for Bush and 2 percent for
Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also has touted the administration's $547 million
``Hispanic education action plan'' to enhance the teaching of
English, improve reading skills and keep high school students from
dropping out. He also talks about his appreciation if Hispanic
culture dating to his high school days when he spent a summer in
Mexico learning Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The other Democratic contender, former New Jersey Sen. Bill
Bradley, has tried to appeal to Hispanics in a more indirect
fashion, talking about his commitment to the party's traditional
agenda of civil rights and fighting poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gore and Bradley spoke at the Unity '99 conference of
minority journalists in Seattle. Bush, however, showed up at the
convention for a 15-minute walk-though but without a speech. He
abruptly changed his schedule to make the appearance after reading
a news item saying that reporters attending the convention had
criticized him for snubbing their invitation even though he was in
the city campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Bush proved to be popular among Hispanics in his
reelection bid. Voter News Service exit polls showed he won 49
percent of their votes, but the San Antonio-based William Velasquez
Institute, a Hispanic interest group, put the figure at 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters say they aren't worried about Democratic attacks
on him. Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas notes that Bush has gone to
great lengths to distance himself from the harsh anti-immigrant
tone of former California Republican Gov. Pete Wilson, which
alienated Hispanic voters in that state. Wilson was the moving
force behind Proposition 187, a 1994 ballot initiative approved by
California voters that barred illegal immigrants from obtaining
most public services including enrollment in public schools. The
measure is stalled in the courts and has never been enforced.
</P>
<P>
   State Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa said in an interview
that Hispanics still are suspicious of the GOP because of that
measure and Proposition 209. He predicted Bush would get no more
than 25 percent of the state's Hispanic vote. ``He's smooth,
congenial and he can work a crowd, and he won't use inflammatory
rhetoric ... but at the end of the day, he can't run away from the
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties agree that the Hispanic vote will be crucial in
next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics number about 30 million _ 11 percent of the
population, 5 percent of the electorate. Most are of Mexican,
Puerto Rican and Cuban descent.
</P>
<P>
   They are a key constituency in New York, Florida, California and
Texas, states that collectively have 144 electoral votes, 54
percent of the 270 votes needed to win the White House. In
California and Texas alone, which combined have 86 electoral votes,
Hispanics are a quarter of the population.
</P>
<P>
   They make up 14 percent of California's voters and 16 percent of
Texas's voters. Last year 78 percent of California's Hispanics
voted for Democrat Gray Davis for governor. Two years earlier, 72
percent of Hispanics nationally voted for President Clinton's
reelection.
</P>
<P>
   Some political scientists say the challenge for Bush will be to
build on his good relations with Hispanics while not alienating the
more traditional conservative elements of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   John Garcia, a University of Arizona political scientist, said
that if Bush is the GOP nominee, ``he will be putting himself into
the position of speaking for Republican Party positions that could
make Hispanics uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Bush supports vouchers that would subsidize public
school students who want to attend private schools, a position
opposed by the League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC), a
non-partisan Hispanic civil rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to keep close watch on Governor Bush,'' said Rick
Dovalina, a Houston lawyer who is president of LULAC. ``He knows
the language and the culture, but that doesn't mean Gore couldn't
do well among Hispanics.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
