 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Widely separated thunderstorms will again erupt over parts of
Arizona, southern Nevada and southern California on Saturday as a
rich supply of tropical moisture from the Gulf of California
combines with solar heating to destabilize the atmosphere. Weak
steering winds aloft will again heighten the risk of flash flooding
in spots.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, clusters of showers and thunderstorms, some with
heavy rain, will develop near a slowing cool front from northern
Texas to the Tennessee and Ohio valleys as very humid air from the
Gulf of Mexico interacts with the front. A pool of warm air aloft
should discourage explosively tall storms, thereby limiting the
threat of severe weather. Nonetheless, rainfalls in excess of two
inches and flash flooding are possible. The risk of heavy rain will
extend to parts of the Middle Atlantic states, including West
Virginia, western Virginia and parts of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated to scattered thunderstorms will develop along the
Northeastern seaboard ahead of the front. A few of the storms may
contain gusty winds as momentum from fast winds aloft is mixed
toward the ground by currents of sinking air within the storms. An
area of moderate rain will exit northern New England into southeast
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   After a rather cool late spring and early summer, a heat wave
will build in the Northwestern states, with temperatures
approaching 100 degrees in parts of eastern Oregon, eastern
Washington and southern Idaho. Heat will also intensify in
California's Sacramento Valley, where readings could rise above 105
degrees.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Desert Deluge &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In just one hour, 1.05 inches of rain deluged McCarran Airport
in Las Vegas on Thursday, a little more than twice the city's
average for July. Heavier rains fell in other parts of the city,
causing serious flash flooding. This week, with humid air flowing
northward from the tropics, steering winds at altitudes near 18,000
feet have been very weak, sometimes blowing at speeds of 5 miles an
hour or less. As a result, thunderstorms that erupted in the
tropical air mass moved sluggishly, allowing them to concentrate
heavy rains over limited areas and thereby setting the stage for
flooding. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
