<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-EROTICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS EROTICA GETS MORE PUBLIC, ITS ALLURE MAY BE THREATENED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be that erotica is always a bit bizarre, particularly if
one isn't initiated into its codes of desire. For one left
unseduced, it can seem both discomforting and comical, like Zero
Mostel playing ``the chauffeur and the contessa'' with wealthy
widows in Mel Brooks' film ``The Producers.'' Erotica can make one
feel like a voyeur, observing humanity in all its desperate
nakedness, inventing extreme excitements.
</P>
<P>
   In one recently imagined erotic adventure, for example, the
homoerotic aspects of the Batman saga come to campy consummation:
Robin shaves his legs to fix his ``embarrassing bikini line,''
rejects the advances of the butler, Alfred, and lovingly fondles
the caped-crusader's costume. In another story with more solemn
ambitions, an online lesbian romance heats up as the lovers meet,
one wearing a leather collar, the other demanding that her boots be
licked.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are from ``Best American Erotica 1999,'' a book in
an annual series published by Simon &AMP; Schuster. The series editor,
Susie Bright, who has become the avatar of American erotica with
her widely published anthologies and essays, suggests that such
imaginings give us ``a portrait of the times we live in.'' And
perhaps they do, because submission and dominance, masochism and
sadism, exhibitionism and voyeurism are now familiar from fashion
ads and television shows and mainstream movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erotica'' is now a section in book stores, as routine as
``travel'' or ``child care.'' Sex columnists like Candace Bushnell
(``Sex and the City'') become minor celebrities. One writer of
lesbian erotica, Cecilia Tan, teaches erotic writing workshops.
Pornography has become the subject of university conferences,
complete with demonstrations. This past year, in a course on
pornography at Wesleyan University, one student's final project was
to have her wrists bound with rope and ask fellow students to flog
her.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the scope of recent erotic obsessions are
familiar: a confluence of political and social changes, an
insatiable quest for ever larger audiences for pop entertainment
and academic absorption in the subjects of body and gender. But the
preoccupations are also more evident because of the dissolving
boundaries between the public and the private in American life.
Erotica and porn, once so private that collections were hidden in
back rooms, have become aggressively public.
</P>
<P>
   This public status has also become explicitly political. Erotica
is now categorized not only by specialized taste but also by
gender, sexual preference and race. Some feminists may have
condemned porn with as much energy as the political right, but the
movement has also led to a celebration of women's erotic experience
in confessional magazine columns and an ever-accumulating
collection of anthologies, including an annual series,
``Herotica.'' The gay and lesbian movements have inspired special
imprints devoted to homosexual publishing, including collections
like ``Best Lesbian Erotica'' and ``Best Gay Erotica.'' There are
books of black erotica (''Dark Eros'' and ``Erotique Noir'') and
even some new categories of sexual exploration (``Queer Dharma:
Voices of Gay Buddhists''). Erotic writing is no longer merely a
matter of sexual arousal; it has become a declaration of identity.
</P>
<P>
   Erotica, of course, has always had a political resonance.
Pornography tends to be highly detailed about the sexual act, but
erotica gives context to the mechanics. Erotica incorporates
personalities, roles, atmosphere; the private realm emerges out of
a public universe.
</P>
<P>
   Modern views of erotica may even have their origin in a social
form of erotic gamesmanship known as libertinism that thrived among
the French aristocracy in the 18th century. As analyzed by Michel
Feher in a recent anthology, ``The Libertine Reader'' (Zone Books),
libertinism was based on an intricate set of doctrines (which have
some familiarity today through the stage and film versions of
Laclos' ``Liaisons Dangereuses'').
</P>
<P>
   For the libertine, desire was an irresistible natural force
pushing social liaisons toward erotic fulfillment. But social
convention had frustrated that natural impulse: the woman was
supposed to renounce physical pleasures, earning a reputation for
constancy and modesty, taking joy in her triumph over nature. If
she succeeded and if men acquiesced, then the two risked succumbing
to the illusion of romantic love.
</P>
<P>
   During the Middle Ages such love was an erotic ideal: the
high-born lady was worshiped with a near-religious fervor by her
knight. Such courtly love almost scorned fulfillment. But
libertines saw this love as a disease. So while they seemingly
respected social conventions (except for some of the more extreme
libertines, like the Marquis de Sade), they also undercut them. Lip
service was paid to public ideas of vice and virtue. But
conversation was laden with double-entendre. The lovers engaged in
an elaborate ritualistic dance, at once cynical about public
demands and deferential to them, leading to the mutually desired
consummation.
</P>
<P>
   This coded interaction may have become a model for the erotic
ideal. A dance takes place that is at once socially forbidden and
tacitly approved, at once violating manners and paying them homage.
Two potential lovers meet in their social roles, playing their
public parts; those roles are eventually shed with their clothing.
The erotic chronicle is as much about those roles as about the
ensuing nakedness; it tells of the passage from public to private.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens today, as erotic life becomes fully public? The
key tension is gone. Some of the more extreme forms of sexual
behavior once relegated to shame and secrecy, like sadomasochism,
have become integrated into public life. Coded behavior and
signals, the secret language of sexual subcultures, are now common
parlance. And little is considered forbidden or outrageous. The
dance of the libertine is over.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary erotica also takes on another role. Because of the
political edge given to it by ethnic and sexual movements, erotica
doesn't just embrace the public, it dismisses the private. Erotic
tastes become political declarations. Instead of erotica telling of
the shedding of public personas, it now tells of the adopting of
them. The erotic is found in the very act of exposure.
</P>
<P>
   For many readers, this approach is stimulating unusual demand,
but for one left unseduced, much recent erotica is painfully dull
and anxiously insistent. The ``Best American Erotica'' annual can
seem preoccupied with aggression and display: Zeus flees in
bewildered fear from a mortal woman who energetically welcomes his
attempted rape; a lesbian tries to avenge her transgendered lover's
murder by a homophobic mobster.
</P>
<P>
   In contemporary American culture the omnipresent erotic has even
spurred interest in what might be considered ``meta-porn,'' not
pornographic material but material about pornographic material, in
erotica conventions, art exhibits and films like ``Boogie Nights.''
If porn itself doesn't evoke the excitements of a private realm,
maybe porn about porn will.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now and then there are hints that this too shall
pass. For once erotica becomes fully public, all these expressions
of sexual desire begin to seem as artificial and arbitrary as a
chauffeur's cap. ``What are you wearing?'' a leering telephone
caller asks a woman in one of the annual's stories. And she
fearlessly replies: ``I am wearing a purple and green polka-dotted
clown suit, with a big yellow ruff collar and huge white pom-pom
buttons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
