<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWIE-ELEGANCE-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY DINNER WITH COLIN COWIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 11)  
 (HLW)  
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps it was because I don't have a television show
of my own or that I've never been interviewed by Charlie Rose.
Perhaps it was because being seated well at Balthazar or 44 is
beyond me. More likely it was because Damon Runyon got it right
when he wrote that ``a freeloader is a confirmed guest.''
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, I recently accepted an invitation to dine
at a new TriBeCa restaurant called City Hall, for a taping of
``Everyday Elegance With Colin Cowie,'' a cable television series
about ``life as it should be,'' shown on the Romance Classics and
American Movie Classics networks.
</P>
<P>
   Life as it should be, of course, isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Dutifully dressed in the ``casual elegant informal evening
wear'' suggested to me by fax, I walked into the private dining
room at City Hall, where Cowie, a post-Martha Stewart life style
guru with a tan, was busy rehearsing a conversation he was about to
tape with Henry Meer, the restaurant's owner and chef. I sat down
quietly, almost apologetically, in the shadows with the designer
Cynthia Rowley, another guest, whose newborn baby was at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I had to stay home a lot when I was pregnant,'' Ms.
Rowley said cheerfully. ``I'm here because right about now, I'm
willing to sit through almost anything that'll get me out of the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Settle, please!'' and ``Lock it up,'' some of the 25 crew
members were suddenly yelling. Ms. Rowley and I agreed to give each
other a big, fake smile across the table if we saw spinach in each
other's teeth. It was time to meet Cowie, the Austin Powers of
party planners, to whom clients like Demi Moore, Hugh Hefner and
Paula Abdul turn for over-the-top touches like shirtless waiters,
live elephants and swimming pools filled with flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts on entertaining say that a cardinal rule is to
spend time with your guests when they arrive, rather than fussing
behind the scenes. But the telegenic Cowie, who is the author of
``Colin Cowie Weddings'' and ``Effortless Elegance With Colin
Cowie,'' could manage giving us only a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you all met?'' he asked. With the help of the producer
who had booked us, he hurriedly introduced us to each other as if
we were his good friends: myself; Ms. Rowley; Meer; Gillian Duffy,
the culinary editor at New York magazine; and Lisa Archembault, a
marketing executive from Lenox china, which has a design contract
with Cowie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Champagne, anyone?'' he asked in his mellifluous South African
accent, before skittering off to deal with the technical details of
his dinner party, none of which involved cooking.
</P>
<P>
   In his wake, an assistant in a headset (will the headset become
the tiara of the next millennium?) asked if we'd like to hear the
menu. Then I was escorted to makeup. ``You look good,'' a makeup
woman said as she worked on my face so much that I started to feel
paranoid. ``You'll be great on TV. Just remember to take small
portions, and don't pick your teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   So, now I was camera-ready. But what does it mean to be
camera-ready at a dinner party? Dinner parties were once meant to
be seen by nobody but the people in the room. Today, we live in a
society approaching the only slightly exaggerated scenarios of
``The Truman Show'' and ``EdTV,'' in which cocktail hours and
benefit dinners are taped and broadcast on New York 1 and E! as if
they were scripted productions.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Everyday Elegance With Colin Cowie,'' being camera-ready
means not sitting down too hard on the radio transmitter in your
back pocket that runs the microphone clipped to your collar. It
means having only one conversation at a time, as conducted by
Cowie. It means knowing your basic table manners, which require
that you do not pick up your fork until your host begins eating.
And it also means knowing not to waste too much energy becoming
excited about the food until the camera is in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please reserve your comments about each course until we start
filming,'' John Heller, the director, said.
</P>
<P>
   These little strictures didn't bother me. I have decent table
manners, or at least I can play someone with decent manners on
television. The problem was the conversation. Cowie started by
asking us how we like to set our tables. When it was my turn to
answer, I muttered something about keeping my dinner table casual.
Then I clammed up, forcing the camera to focus on someone else. And
when, after a first course, Cowie focused on the topic of hors
d'oeuvres, I was totally flummoxed. I mean, movies, politics,
trendy pharmaceuticals, even literature, I could do. But hors
d'oeuvres? Ms. Duffy, a cheerful Englishwoman who has published a
book on the subject, firmly declared that a proper hors d'oeuvre
should be eaten in one bite. Suddenly, the camera was on me again.
I had to think fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``And is that something that you knew  &UR; before &LR;  you started
writing your book,'' I found myself asking brightly, ``or was it
something you discovered  &UR; after &LR;  all your research?''
</P>
<P>
   Who was this person talking? Normally, the only way you'd find
me discussing hors d'oeuvres is with a fake foreign accent. But
this was not an environment in which to indulge in any natural-born
sarcasm. This dinner conversation was meant to be an earnest
discussion of etiquette, gardening and our party plans for the
millennium. It was also about nodding appreciatively when Cowie
made pronouncements on such things as the genius of serving takeout
food at parties.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until he started virulently criticizing cell phones,
call-waiting and our high-tech society that my dinner with Colin
suddenly became surreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to learn to simplify our lives,'' Cowie said with
urgency, even as the lights glared and the camera stared and
technicians fiddled with elaborate equipment. ``We should not allow
ourselves to be controlled by all these electronic interruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Simplify? I felt as if I were hallucinating, as though I'd
wandered into the Mad Hatter's tea party.
</P>
<P>
   I was brought back to earth by a sound engineer ripping off his
headset. ``This is absurd!'' he shouted at a fellow crew member.
``I'm hearing you eating litchi nuts!''
</P>
<P>
   So much for not allowing ourselves to be controlled by
electronic interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Well, never mind. It was time for strawberries and poppy-seed
shortcake. After consuming it as telegenically as possible (small
bites), Ms. Rowley and I exchanged big, fake smiles across the
table, while Cowie vaporized about life's being an onion that you
peel to reach your soul at the center. But by then, what he was
saying didn't matter. The important thing was that there were no
poppy seeds stuck between my teeth. On that small note of personal
triumph, we said good night, and I walked home, still in makeup,
filled with good food and dark thoughts about a world in which to
be is to be on television.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen the TV dinner of the future, and it isn't Swanson's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
