<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERN-FASHIONS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEAVAGE-REVEALING, MIDRIFF-BARING OFFICE ATTIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 By JOANNE GALLUCCI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who are the young businesswomen of tomorrow? One need look no
further than the 20-something, miniskirt-clinging,
cleavage-revealing, midriff-bulging, tattoo-touting assistants and
interns of today.
</P>
<P>
   Summer has returned, along with an array of new, young workers
and casual-dress policies. But as soon as the rules of those
policies are e-mailed to employees _ no sandals, tank tops, jeans
or shorts _ it seems that every junior female worker brushes the
cobwebs from her skin-tight miniskirts and spaghetti-strap dresses
(not to mention the forbidden sandals and tank tops) and parades
them onto the office runway.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I don't believe in policing office attire.
But for us over-the-hill, 30-something bosses, the workplace is far
different than in our heyday, when cleavage was reserved for girls'
night out or for ``the'' man.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent staff meeting, a young woman passed by, wearing the
latest fashion T-shirt _ pink with a three-quarter-length V-neck _
and a miniskirt. A fashionable, 36-year-old colleague shook her
head in disbelief. ``I never dressed liked that at the office when
I was their age,'' she said. She still doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how the ultra-casual look hasn't extended to male
newcomers to the office, leaving women deprived in the ogling
department. During my 10 years in the communications profession,
known for its creative and liberal work environment, I can't recall
one inappropriately dressed young man. Khakis, loafers, long-sleeve
cotton shirts and short-sleeve golf shirts seem to epitomize
today's young male professional.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time a young man _ or any man, for that matter
_ showed up for a meeting in a muscle shirt? Maybe the young men
are less slaves to fashion _ or more concerned with establishing a
professional work environment.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be real. We all have our
less-than-professional-looking days, and we all have the occasional
urge to break the rules of dress _ especially on a 100-degree
summer day when my stockings and Brooks Brothers jacket stick like
glue and almost need to be peeled off at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, is that most of us don't give in to
the urge to be unprofessional.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a 16-year-old ``salesgirl'' in a clothing store, I
was scolded for chewing gum on the sales floor. Yet my body was
fully covered and unadorned with pierced or painted objects. If the
owner had known how lucky he was, I'm sure I would have received
the salesgirl-of-the-month award.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a TV newsroom intern in 1987, the norm was collared
blouses and tailored slacks, or skirts to the knee. A few years
later, lapel suits, scarves and collar shirts were career
favorites. T-shirts and sandals were reserved for the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Styles change, of course, and individuality should play a role
in anyone's wardrobe. Yet by the looks of it, a professional
appearance is no longer important to young professional women.
Expressing sexuality is.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, as I sat across from an Ivy League graduate 10
years my junior who was revealing cleavage as deep as the Great
Divide, I couldn't help but wonder why. A low salary or $20,000
tuition bills may be an excuse for an inadequate wardrobe, but
where was the brain that rewarded her with such a prestigious
degree?
</P>
<P>
   Call me conservative, but cut me some slack. I watch MTV and
VH-1 and have been known to party on weekends, too. I just happen
to think that peekaboo T-shirts and stretch pants that hug every
nook and cranny belong on a college campus, not in a meeting room
full of executives.
</P>
<P>
   This brings me to one all-important question. What new career
statements will be ushered in with the new millennium? Judging from
our recent track record, clothes will probably be outlawed. Then,
at least, we'll all be equals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
