r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     07-09 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING A LIFE ON A SYSTEM OF SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shelby Littlejohn is a delightful 15-year-old, excitedly looking
forward to her sophomore year at Martin High School in Arlington,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Singing in the choir for the fifth year coupled with the
possibility of joining the debate team and becoming a member of the
school's Explorer Post adds to the appeal of returning to school
next month.
</P>
<P>
   The ages-old adult-to-youngster question of, ``What do you want
to be when you grow up?'' drew an interesting response as we sat in
the shade enjoying a breezy Fourth of July weekend picnic and swap
meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past six years I've dreamed of being a police
officer,'' Shelby says. This elicits a groan from my husband, who,
after almost 24 years on the job, can think of a bazillion better
career choices.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby, a lock of dark hair held back from her face by a
butterfly clip, is undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch every reality-based police show on TV,'' she says, her
words blessedly bereft of the ``you knows'' and ``likes'' that
punctuate so many of the conversations of teen-age girls these
days. ``I can't think of a more rewarding job than serving
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the innocence of youth. Far be it for me to shatter a girl's
dream by bringing up the dark side of serving the public _ lousy
pay, lousy hours, no respect and the constant threat of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby represents what too many people have lost sight of today
_ the typical American teen-ager. Haunted by stories in the media
about murderous youth and out-of-control teens, we've lost our
perspective. America's schools are not overflowing with Kip
Kinkels, Eric Harrises and Dylan Klebolds. The vast majority of
young people handle the stresses of growing up in very normal ways.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby would be the first to tell you she's not perfect _ if she
didn't, her parents and grandparents would volunteer that
information. She's struggled with some of the challenges that
typically face teens in a highly mobile and increasingly
materialistic society.
</P>
<P>
   When her accountant father was transferred from New Jersey back
to Texas recently after being away for seven years, Shelby had
problems leaving behind her friends only to find herself plopped
down into one of the biggest high schools in the Metroplex _
Arlington's version of ``Beverly Hills 90210.'' The pressure to
look right, dress right, drive the right car and be invited to the
right parties is intense. If you aren't a conformist _ and Shelby
most definitely is not _ high school can be a booger bear.
</P>
<P>
   But make note of the key words in the above paragraphs that are
important clues as to why Shelby, despite a bump in the road every
now and then, will no doubt make it. ``Parents'' David and Melanie
Littlejohn, ``grandparents'' Ed and Kay Buie _ a family that is
there for her, the support system on which to build a successful
life.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her grandfather's protestations that he's ``too critical
of her,'' Shelby is the apple of his eye, if you'll pardon the
cliche. In fact, when I met her she was spending the day with
Grandpa as she has many days, at the Arlington Sportsman's Club.
She says she's a fair shot with a .22 rifle _ ``I'm getting pretty
consistent on my groupings'' _ and is learning her way around a
pistol, all under Grandpa's loving and watchful eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Buie is teaching Shelby what thousands of other parents and
grandparents have passed along to their young 'uns through the
years _ the feeling of accomplishment that comes from perfecting
one's skill at an individual sport. In this case, that sport just
happens to be target shooting. Being female is an asset for Shelby,
since girls generally have better eye-to-hand coordination than
boys, an important factor in accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   How about that? An American teen who's struggled with being
``different,'' finding confidence in something that's been roundly
condemned across the country as the ruination of today's youth _
guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to watch skeet matches on TV when we lived in New
Jersey and it looked interesting,'' said Shelby. ``When we moved to
Texas, I found out that Grandpa was involved in the Arlington
Sportsman's Club. I told him I wanted to see what it was all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   She found that it was about learning respect for guns and the
responsibility of gun ownership. It also provided a sense of
control that Shelby said she felt was lacking in the rest of her
life. She credits the shooting club with keeping her mind off New
Jersey and the friends she left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The move was hard, real hard,'' admits the youngster. ``I
would get lonely and depressed. Target shooting helped me not to
think about it. When I get a good grouping, I feel like, `I did
that. I'm in control. I tried and I got it right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And Shelby has developed a special bond with her grandfather,
partly through the interest they share in shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone to a couple of gun shows together and we go to
lunch after. We make a day of it,'' Shelby said. ``He's very
patient when working with me at the range.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I work with my Grandpa it's like working with my father.
We're that close.''
</P>
<P>
   Little one, you're going to be just fine.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
