<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OZONE10-COX     07-09 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZONE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NOXIOUS OZONE TO BE MONITORED IN SMOKIES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Air quality specialists are setting up an
intensified monitoring program in order to warn visitors to Great
Smoky Mountains National Park whenever levels of noxious ozone
approach unhealthful levels, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The park in eastern Tennessee and western North Carolina is
America's most popular national park, with more than 9 million
visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   However, a variety of factors, including its location and
topography, often lead to ozone pollution levels higher than those
of some of the most polluted cities in America.
</P>
<P>
   National Park Service officials, as well as city and state
officials, need better ``tools'' to forecast high ozone conditions
in the region, said Will Pendergrass, a National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration meteorologist at Oak Ridge, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The East Tennessee Ozone Study will attempt to refine
meteorological models used in the forecasts, as well as determine
where the pollutants leading to the ozone are coming from,
Pendergrass said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the study, NOAA will install 12 new air quality
monitors in the park and on state fire towers around it and tie
them into ozone monitors operated by the National Park Service and
the cities of Chattanooga, Knoxville and Johnson City, Tenn., he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The study will not cover the portion of the park in North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   National Park Service air resource specialist Jim Renfro said
the number of days when eight-hour ozone levels in the park exceed
Clean Air Act standards has been growing in recent years. Last year
there were 44.
</P>
<P>
   Among nearby cities, only Atlanta and Charlotte had more bad
ozone days.
</P>
<P>
   The highest reading last year was on Aug. 25. Coincidentally, a
hiker had to be evacuated from the park by ambulance that day
because of an asthma attack that was not alleviated by inhalants.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, there have been nine days that exceeded Clean
Air Act standards. Ozone levels in the park are usually worst in
late July and August, Renfro said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the park's mountains appear to inhibit the kind of air
movements that cause urban ozone levels typically to fluctuate
widely every day, with relatively clean nights, followed by high
levels in mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ozone levels in the park sometimes peak at midnight
and endure throughout the day, especially on mountain ridge lines.
</P>
<P>
   Black cherry, tulip poplar and blackberries are among plant
species that are showing damage from ozone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
