<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4763 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-GALLO-PROFILE-A     07-09 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GALLO-PROFILE-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FACE, NEW SHEEN, AT GALLO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday July 11)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEALDSBURG, Calif. _ Even years ago, when the giant E.&AMP;J. Gallo
Winery began its assault on the more expensive, $12-and-up wine
category, Gina Gallo was just 25 and preparing for a career in
sales with the family business. Today she is a winemaker at the
money-is-no-object Sonoma operation of the company and, perhaps
more important, the face of the new Gallo in a multimillion dollar
ad campaign aimed at giving the venerable brand a new veneer of
prestige.
</P>
<P>
   For the famously private Gallos, putting Gina front and center
is a major departure. But she is a bit out of the mold, too, a more
relaxed, less combative Gallo.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her great uncle, the winery patriarch Ernest Gallo, she
doesn't interrogate visitors for any useful information. Instead,
she speaks with passion of her deep involvement in producing
premium red wines: cabernet sauvignon, merlot, pinot noir, and
zinfandel, as well as smaller lots of Italian varietals like
barbera and sangiovese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely my first love is making the wine,'' said Ms. Gallo,
adding that she fell into winemaking by chance, after some classes
in enology at the University of California at Davis. ``When I was
in sales, I asked if I could go to U.C. Davis on the side, just to
understand what was in the wine,'' she said. ``Then I sat through
my first class and knew that was what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing faded denims and no makeup, Ms. Gallo still looks the
part of a cellar worker. But she has access to that rarest of
assets in wine-making, virtually unlimited capital. She takes
pleasure in the costly innovations the Gallos have implemented at
their winery.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever doubted that the Gallos could make good, even great,
wine if they wanted. The bigger issue was whether consumers, who
may associate the Gallo name with inexpensive jug wines like Hearty
Burgundy, would ever accept a premium varietal wine with the Gallo
label.
</P>
<P>
   Although she acknowledges that problem, Ms. Gallo said she sees
it as an advantage. ``If you have that family relationship with 65
years of history, that's attractive to people,'' she said. ``The
reason why we could put Gallo on the top of the line is because we
have that story.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, as Ernest Gallo said in a 1992 interview, ``using a
different brand would not be any fun.'' As president, Gallo, who is
90, still runs the marketing side of the winery, which is the
world's largest. His brother Julio died in an automobile accident
in 1993. Ms. Gallo, who is 32, is one of Julio's grandchildren; her
father, Robert Gallo, leads the production side. Twelve of 20
third-generation Gallos work in the business.
</P>
<P>
   The $4 million print and broadcast campaign spotlights Ms. Gallo
outside a barn-like building with a weathered wooden sign reading
``Gallo of Sonoma.'' Some wineries here in the bucolic Dry Creek
Valley of Sonoma County, north of San Francisco, still have
settings like that. Gallo's operations, however, more closely
resemble an oil refinery, with an unmarked entry road and a
security guard.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ads are a bit contrived, Ms. Gallo is, by contrast,
direct. She is quick to give credit to the other winemaker at
Gallo-Sonoma, Bob L. Bertheau, 36, for stewardship of the white
wines, primarily chardonnay and sauvignon blanc, and to Marcello
Monticelli, 52, a 30-year Gallo veteran who heads winemaking at
Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most winemakers today, who go from one promotional dinner
to another, Ms. Gallo travels little. She said she prefers to let
the wine speak for itself than to peddle it at tasting events.
Married, but with no children yet, she looks forward to a full role
in raising a family.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up herself in Modesto, the Central Valley site of
Gallo's headquarters, ``we always had to be at the dinner table at
7 o'clock no matter what, and wine was very much a part of that,''
she said. Wine is standard at her table, too, but not necessarily
her own wines. She has an encyclopedic knowledge of California
winemakers, even small ones like Screaming Eagle. Tasting their
wines gives a sense of what is possible, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Gallo, winemaking is always an adventure. ``In sales,
once I had the fundamental part down of how to sell, the excitement
for me died,'' she said. ``In winemaking, you understand it truly
is an art, and you don't ever master it. It is ever-challenging.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Gallos long disdained wine criticism, they now
court publications like Wine Spectator. Recent reviews of the
Gallo-Sonoma wines in that magazine gave them scores in the low 90s
on a 100-point scale, very competitive with other California wines
at similar prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third-party accolades are very helpful,'' Ms. Gallo said.
``It means reviewers are tasting your wine blind and saying, `This
is amazing.''' Noting with obvious pride that the winery
consistently sells out of its single-vineyard and estate-bottled
wines, she added, ``someone out there is enjoying them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
