<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4765 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-NAPA-WINE-$ADV1     07-09 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-NAPA-WINE-$ADV11-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WINE COUNTRY, CAN WHITE OR RED EVER BE GREEN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 11)  
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By ALAN KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. HELENA, Calif. _ Farmers and vintners in California's Napa
Valley have long exploited the region's combination of soil,
climate and topography to make wines that can compete with those of
the great Bordeaux estates. Shrewd marketing and a robust economy
have given premium Napa wines a romance and prestige that help lift
sales of wine produced throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Napa winemaking has proven so successful, in fact, that there is
very little land left on the valley floor to plant new vines. To
expand output, the wineries are planting on the surrounding
hillsides, arousing a backlash driven by environmental concerns
ranging from water pollution caused by soil erosion and pesticides
to the destruction of oak trees and wildlife habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by environmentalists, the Napa County Board of
Supervisors has already enacted regulations aimed at curbing
hillside vineyards, and the board's five elected members are being
pressed by constituents to make the rules even more restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers say hillsides are not only the last available land
for Napa vineyards but also the best land for producing world-class
wine grapes _ though the most expensive to develop. At the very
least, they say, the new rules would drive development costs even
higher. Planting a new hillside vineyard costs $35,000 to $40,000
an acre, on top of the price of the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to conserve habitat,'' said Chris Malan, a county
mental health counselor who leads Concerned Citizens for Napa
Hillsides, a small but politically vocal environmental group. ``We
need to protect our tree canopy. We need to not construct
infrastructure in the hillsides that causes flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   Napa County's landmark 1991 hillside ordinance permits farming
on slopes with grades as steep as 22.5 degrees, or 50 percent,
meaning the land rises one foot for every two horizontal feet. Ms.
Malan wants the county to tighten that limit to 13.5-degree grades
(up a foot for every 3.33 horizontal feet). Better still, she said,
would be a moratorium on all new vineyard development. ``This is a
very small county,'' she said. ``We have to reach the limit at some
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Napa's national reputation, the fight has attracted
attention from environmental groups across the country. They say
they will not hesitate to intervene if measures to clean up the
Napa River and protect wildlife seem inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's just a matter of saying, `We're going to do some study
and crack down on future development,' then that won't solve the
problem,'' said Bruce Hamilton, conservation director for the
Sierra Club. ``California, using federal standards, classified the
Napa River as impaired in 1987. If the state fails to act, then the
federal government could step in.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if neither acts,'' he added, ``then a private group like
the Sierra Club could,'' by going to court.
</P>
<P>
   Winemakers say county figures show that soil erosion has
declined by more than two-thirds since 1991. ``Many of us think the
current ordinance is pretty damn good and the problem is enforcing
it,'' said Dennis Groth, president of Groth Vineyards in Oakville.
</P>
<P>
   The wine growers cautiously embraced recommendations by a county
task force that recently evaluated Napa's hillside ordinance. The
task force, whose members included winemakers and environmentalists
as well as engineers and government officials, rejected proposals
like a moratorium on new vineyards and extending the rules to cover
replanting of existing vineyards grandfathered under the 1991 law.
Instead, it called for further study.
</P>
<P>
   Compliance with the law is largely voluntary; enforcement is
limited to responding to the public's complaints, according to
county officials. The number of vineyards that break the rules,
while thought to be small, is not known.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the problems that have come to light have been damaging
for the winemakers. ``When somebody violates the law, the finger
points at all of us,'' said Thomas Shelton, chief executive of
Joseph Phelps Vineyards and president of the Napa Vintners
Association. ``Enforcement of existing regulations is something we
can all agree on.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in Napa say that planting hillsides does not make economic
sense anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not growth; the issue is profit,'' said Volker
Eisele, a vintner and grape grower with 60 acres who is also an
environmental activist. ``When land values and business values
climb to such astronomical heights, there is a lot at stake.'' For
what it now costs to develop hillside vineyards, he said, ``to make
such a venture pay, you're looking at a $60 to $80 bottle price,
and I have trouble believing that you can project that kind of
price into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisele said the Napa industry should grow by increasing quality,
not quantity.
</P>
<P>
   For Stuart Smith, whose 30-acre Smith-Madrone Vineyards and
Winery lies nearly 1,000 feet above St. Helena in the Mayacamas
Range, growth is very much an issue. Smith, who is seeking county
permission to convert six and a half more acres into vineyards,
says modern agricultural techniques can minimize soil erosion and
habitat loss. And no one should underestimate nature's resilience,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a faded redwood stake, one of many he has found on
his property, that supported a grapevine more than a century ago.
The tall pine trees and scrub that now surround it are evidence of
the forest's regenerative vitality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forest wants to take back the vineyards,'' Smith said.
``It's a constant battle for us to keep the forest at bay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4766 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASLEEP-BENSON-HNS &LR;      07-09 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASLEEP-BENSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A RIDE WITH BOB,' COURTESY OF ASLEEP AT THE WHEEL &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By RICK MITCHELL
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Asleep at the Wheel's Grammy Award-winning
instrumental, String of Pars, was inspired by a particularly
well-played round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   When guitarist Ray Benson called last week after 18 holes at
Willie Nelson's Pedernales course outside Austin, he was in no mood
to write a sequel: String of Bogeys doesn't have quite the same
ring to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a string of somethings,'' Benson said. ``It was
threatening par.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when Nelson plays his own course, par is whatever he
shot that day, but that's another story.
</P>
<P>
   Asleep at the Wheel has been identified with the Austin music
scene for so long that many people assume the band was born in
Texas. Not so. Benson founded the Wheel some 30 years ago while he
was living on a farm in rural West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   An avid record collector, he'd discovered the vintage
western-swing music of Bob Wills and the Texas Playboys when he was
in high school. Other crucial formative influences included Hank
Williams, George Jones, Elvis Presley and Jerry Lee Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the band moved to San Francisco, where it landed a
national record deal. But, Benson said, the Bay-area acid-rock
audiences didn't know what to make of a bunch of long-haired
hippies playing traditional country music.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on the advice of Nelson and Doug Sahm of the Sir Douglas
Quintet, the entire band relocated to Austin in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Benson said he's never regretted the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this town. We've gone in and out of vogue several
times. At this point, we've become almost venerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the band has been with several record labels,
including three separate tenures at Columbia/Epic and two deals
with Capitol Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Record-label politics can be a real minefield,'' Benson said.
</P>
<P>
   Asleep at the Wheel also has undergone numerous personnel
changes. Benson, the only remaining original member, has had to
reinvent the Wheel several times. He estimates that at least 75
musicians have passed through the band, not counting studio sidemen
and one-night sit-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Benson points out that the current lineup _ featuring Jason
Roberts on fiddle, Cindy Cashdollar on steel guitar, Michael
Francis on sax, Chris Booher on piano and fiddle, Dave Miller on
bass and Dave Sanger on drums _ has been stable for three years,
with Booher the most recent addition.
</P>
<P>
   Through all the ups and downs, Benson has never lost sight of
his original goal, which is to keep the flame burning for his
traditional musical inspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Of those inspirations, the flame that burns the brightest is
that of Wills, the Texas band leader who helped invent western
swing by combining frontier fiddle breakdowns with blues, jazz and
swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the seminal figures of American popular music,
like Duke Ellington, Hank Williams and Elvis Presley,'' Benson
said. ``We've been lucky enough to be handed that mantle to
carry.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Asleep at the Wheel recorded a tribute to Bob Wills and
the Texas Playboys, featuring such high-profile guests as Nelson,
George Strait, Garth Brooks, Vince Gill, Dolly Parton and Merle
Haggard.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an almost total blackout on commercial country radio,
the album has sold more than 400,000 copies and is close to being
certified gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing that it didn't get more radio play,''
Benson said. ``But it influenced so many people. I've had a lot of
young country singers _ Wade Hayes, Tracy Byrd _ come up to me and
say, `You really turned my head around with that album.'''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Asleep at the Wheel will release another, even better
Wills tribute album called Ride With Bob. Highlights include
Haggard and the Squirrel Nut Zippers on St. Louis Blues; the Dixie
Chicks singing and swinging on Roly Poly; Lyle Lovett and Shawn
Colvin on Faded Love; and Manhattan Transfer harmonizing with
Nelson on Goin' Away Party.
</P>
<P>
   Other esteemed guests include Steve Wariner and Gill (Bob's
Breakdown); Don Walser (I Ain't Got Nobody); Lee Ann Womack (Heart
to Heart Talk); Reba McEntire (Right or Wrong); Clay Walker (Take
Me Back to Tulsa); Mark Chesnutt (Stay All Night); Dwight Yoakam
(San Antonio Rose); Byrd (You're From Texas); Tim McGraw (Milk Cow
Blues); and Clint Black (Bob Wills Is Still the King).
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Louisiana's McGraw, the North
Carolina-based Zippers and Manhattan's Transfer, the artists have
strong ties to Texas, Oklahoma or California _ the three states in
which Wills was based from the 1930s through the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between Bob Wills and everybody else was that
he incorporated blues and jazz,'' Benson said. ``In the racist
society of Texas in the 1930s and '40s, he imitated black blues
singers and had the highest respect for their musicianship and
intelligence. That's the key to western swing music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ride With Bob is Asleep at the Wheel's first album for the new
Nashville division of DreamWorks records. Because the participating
artists represent so many competing labels, it will be difficult
for DreamWorks to promote a hit single or video from the album.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Benson would like to sell as many copies as possible.
But his real goal is to do justice to Wills' legacy, inspiring new
generations of fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything I'd rather do than keep playing this
kind of music,'' he said. ``In the past, that hasn't always been
what audiences wanted us to do. Now they do. And I just love it.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
