<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$A     07-09 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL CONSULTING AT A HIGHER LEVEL  
 THE CEMENT CEILING?  
 A HECK OF A PARKING FEE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   (For release Sunday, July 11)  
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation supports an army of financial planners. But
regardless of whether they consult these professionals, six out of
10 Americans seek financial guidance from a far more established
source. They pray.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by Yankelovich Partners for the Lutheran Brotherhood, a
financial services organization in Minneapolis, asked a random
sample of Americans about money and spirituality, and found that 61
percent said they prayed before making major financial decisions.
Forty-six percent sought financial guidance by reading spiritual
materials, 24 percent by talking to members of the clergy and 17
percent by turning to religious television programs or Internet
sites.
</P>
<P>
   One variation in the responses gave a hint of where following
heavenly guidance could lead. Those who pray regularly were more
likely than those who don't (28 percent to 22 percent) to have lent
money in the past five years to someone in need.
</P>
<P>
   The Cement Ceiling?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the well-publicized accusations that Christian L. Curry
had to fake e-mail to make it look as if his employer, Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, harbored employees with racial bias, the
overwhelmingly white world of corporate management is genuinely
tough for minorities to break into, according to a group of 109
blacks, Hispanics and Native Americans who are already on the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   The group, all executives and professionals with master's
degrees in business, were surveyed by the Ph.D. Project, a
privately financed effort of businesses and foundations to improve
minority representation in American business.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the likelihood of being hired for corporate
positions, 73 percent of the group said MBAs from minority groups
lagged somewhat or far behind whites. For promotions and raises, 86
percent said minority candidates lagged somewhat or far behind.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bright spot. In the next five years, most of the
group expects that opportunities for new minority MBAs will not
worsen.
</P>
<P>
   A Heck of a Parking Fee
</P>
<P>
   After she helps that special someone select a Patek Philippe and
a couple of Rolexes, the woman who gives with style might also buy
him something to put them in. Perhaps a $3,600 leather and silk
watch box from Scatola del Tempo of Barzano, Italy, featured in an
advertisement in this month's Robb Report, a magazine for
well-heeled consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you park a Ferrari in the street?'' the ad asks. For the
customer who answers no, Chronotime Inc. in Livingston, N.J., the
American distributor for Scatola del Tempo, supplies retailers with
boxes ranging from a basic one-watch model, at $495, to a $10,000
burlwood box that rotates nine watches at once.
</P>
<P>
   Rotation, explained Terry Chabrowe, a partner at Chronotime, is
an important issue for collectors of fine watches. It sustains the
timekeeping functions of watches designed to be self-wound by the
motion of a wearer's wrist, and it also keeps the watches'
lubricating oils flowing. ``Those watches are designed to keep
moving all the time,'' Chabrowe said.
</P>
<P>
   A $10,000 box is pricey, he added, but the watches inside,
usually owned by men who are fascinated by delicate machinery, can
cost as much as $250,000 each. He said about half the inquiries he
receives about the boxes are from women looking for a perfect gift.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARBARA IRELAND
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
