<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEISURE-TIME-2TAKES-N     07-09 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEISURE-TIME-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO AMERICANS HAVE MORE OR LESS LEISURE TIME? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANNY SCOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a society in which the long lunch has gone the way of the
screened-in porch and free time often seems as rare as a telephone
without call waiting, it is surprisingly difficult to get a
definitive answer to the deceptively simple question of whether
Americans have more or less time on their hands than they used to.
</P>
<P>
   The research on time use yields evidence for three seemingly
contradictory answers: Americans work longer and have less leisure
time than they did 30 years ago; Americans work less and have more
leisure time; Americans work roughly as much as they used to, at
least on average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could talk statistics to you from here to midnight,'' said
Randy Ilg, an economist at the Bureau of Labor Statistics, which
has generated its own share of befuddling results. ``But one set of
statistics will give you one point of view and another set of
statistics will tell you something else.''
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the problem is that time-use researchers use
different methods and different data. They depend on the indulgence
and memories of ordinary folks (who, like everyone else, may be
feeling they could use a day off). They study different time
periods. They even have different definitions of basic concepts,
like leisure and work.
</P>
<P>
   But another part of the problem, some researchers say, may be
that they have been asking the wrong question. The question may not
be  &UR; whether &LR;  Americans are working or playing more but  &UR; which  &LR; ones
are. As it turns out, there may be more people underemployed and,
at the same time, more people overworked.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sense does it make to talk about averages if we have two
very divergent realities?'' asked Jiri Zuzanek, a sociologist at
the University of Waterloo in Ontario. Zuzanek recently edited a
special issue of the scholarly journal Society and Leisure devoted
to what some scholars call the ``time famine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a group of people who are overworked, and others
are benefiting from a greater amount of leisure, and the trends are
diverging, the average is not particularly meaningful,'' he said.
``That's where I am a little concerned that reporting averages does
not always reflect the dynamics of social change.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Americans may be working longer  &UR; and &LR;  have more leisure
time. That is, some Americans are clearly working longer hours
while others may have more leisure than past generations did. While
hard-driving baby boomers may infatuate the media, many men have
retired early and many people in their 20s and 30s have postponed
marriage and child rearing or are having fewer children.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 study by the Bureau of Labor Statistics on which Ilg was
a co-author found that the segment of employees working at least 49
hours a week rose from 13 percent in 1976 to 18.5 percent in 1993.
Among those most likely to work very long hours were professionals
and managers, who were also among the highest paid. People in
transportation and sales are also working more, although the
reasons are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got into this, I said both sides can't be
right,'' said Jerry Jacobs, a professor of sociology at the
University of Pennsylvania who set himself the task of trying to
reconcile the contradictory views about work and leisure. ``It
turns out that it is logically possible for them both to have a
kernel of truth because they are talking about different people.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from people's personal fascination with the way they use
their time, economists use the information to help assess the
economy's long-term health and growth. Sociologists use it to
trace, among other things, the changing social roles of men and
women, tracking the time they spend working outside and inside the
home.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite possible that many people have an exaggerated sense
of how long they work. The rise of couples in which each one works
has created intense time pressures in families. Many Americans also
have more opportunities than before and more knowledge of
opportunities missed. Leisure activities are increasingly complex
and organized. Meanwhile, e-mail, fax machines and beepers have
muddied the boundary between work and home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say the only way to make it work off the job is to
treat life off the job like work,'' said James T. Bond, vice
president of the Families and Work Institute, a policy research
institute in New York City that has found that the average workweek
is rising. ``You have to apply good management skills and
scheduling if you want to lead a normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   But when one tries to measure the time Americans spend at work
and leisure, all sorts of perplexing questions crop up. If a person
skips out of the office to run an errand, is that work or something
else? Is commuting work? Should the work of 16- and 17-year-olds be
counted? Are night courses work? When is shopping housework and
when is it recreation?
</P>
<P>
   The largest source of public data on work hours is the Bureau of
Labor Statistics, which regularly surveys 400,000 nonfarm
businesses for the number of hours worked by production and
nonsupervisory employees. It also surveys 50,000 randomly selected
households, conducting telephone interviews about hours worked in
the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of businesses suggests the average workweek in the
companies studied ``trended down,'' as Ilg put it, from 38.8 in the
mid-1960s to 36.1 in the mid-1970s, 34.9 in the mid-1980s and 34.6
in 1998. The household survey suggests the workweek went from 40
hours in the mid-1960s to approximately 38 in the mid-1970s to 39
in the mid-1980s to 39.3 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, other studies have suggested divergent
conclusions. F. Thomas Juster, an economist at the University of
Michigan who surveyed Americans about their use of time in the
mid-1970s and early 1980s, said he found that total work declined
for both men and women and leisure increased between the mid-1960s
and the early 1980s. He looked at not only paid work but housework,
too.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 Juliet B. Schor, an economist at Harvard, reported in
``The Overworked American: The Unexpected Decline of Leisure''
(Basic) that time on the job had risen steadily over the previous
20 years. Leisure was dwindling, she said; manufacturing employees,
for example, were working the equivalent of two months longer each
year than their counterparts in West Germany and France.
</P>
<P>
   Then John P. Robinson, a professor of sociology at the
University of Maryland, and Geoffrey Godbey, a professor of leisure
studies at Penn State University, reported the opposite in ``Time
for Life: The Surprising Ways Americans Use Their Time'' (Penn
State Press, 1997). They said men and women were working less than
they did in 1965 and had gained nearly an hour of free time a day.
</P>
<P>
   In a revised edition of the book, due out in September, they
write that further studies they conducted in the 1990s did not show
a continuing decline in people's hours of paid work. Nevertheless,
they said, free time continued to increase, in large part because
the amount of time spent on eating and grooming declined.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Ms. Schor, Robinson and Godbey based their findings
primarily on ``time diaries'' in which people were asked to record
in detail how they spent their time over the course of a day, in
contrast to the Bureau of Labor Statistics' method of asking
employers about hours worked or asking participants to recall their
work hours from the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and others say that people exaggerate their hours when
asked to recall them from memory. The more hours they work,
Robinson says, the more they inflate. Meanwhile, critics of the
time diary method say it is biased in the other direction: busy
people are too busy to keep diaries, so the method favors the
unbusy, a charge Robinson denies.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, Ms. Schor and their critics and defenders have all
sorts of other reservations about each side's (and everyone else's)
data _ about the points in the business cycle when the data were
collected, about the representativeness of their samples, about
whether they were measuring time working or simply time at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are problems in measurement on both sides,'' said Andrew
S. Harvey, an economist who directs the time-use research program
at St. Mary's University in Halifax, Nova Scotia. ``A lot has to do
with the timing of the observations. Then there's a question of who
you're looking at. If two of you were looking at slightly different
populations, you might get different answers.''
</P>
<P>
   But many researchers also say the data are probably telling
multiple stories at once, not only those of the undeniably
time-pressed couples juggling multiple jobs and young children but
also the stories of unhappily underemployed people perpetually
searching for more work and of men in their early 60s who until
recently were retiring at a younger and younger age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing everybody agrees on is there is a time divide,''
said Robert Drago, an economist at the University of Wisconsin in
Milwaukee. ``There is a large group of people who are overworked
and there is an arguably smaller group of people who are
underworked and searching for anything to get by. The question of
whether, on average, people are working more or less is maybe not
as important as this time divide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
