<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4782 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-TALES-$ADV11-2TAK     07-09 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-TALES-$ADV11-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE ME YOUR HUDDLED MASSES, YEARNING TO BE FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, July 11)  
 (HLW)  
 By DOUGLAS COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The less you spend on your health, the healthier you
become. This is why East Africans, training barefoot on the
savanna, so routinely humiliated America's best long-distance
runners, despite millions spent on college training programs. And
if the logic here is flawed, I don't want to hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   You see, I can no longer afford my health club. I used to belong
to the Printing House Fitness and Racquet Club on Hudson Street. I
gladly paid close to $100 a month for the privilege of being
coddled into shape. I relished the steam room and the rooftop pool,
even though I never used them. I basked in the rumor that Lou Reed
and Laurie Anderson could be found _ nobody ever actually  &UR; saw &LR; 
them _ doing crunches.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, I was forced to confront a typical New York
difficulty: I could pay my health club dues, or I could pay rent.
Rent won out. I gained 20 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, I'd always known about the Carmine Recreation Center
at Clarkson Street and Seventh Avenue South, just a block away from
my rooftop health palace. I used to see it, in fact, from above, as
I trained on the latest cardiovascular equipment in front of
panoramic windows. I never imagined, however, that I might one day
wish to join.
</P>
<P>
   The Carmine Center is a public gym, you see, one of a number
operated by the city, and it costs a member all of $25 a year. I
mean, what kind of annual thing can you get for 25 bucks? Most
people spend more than that yearly on dental floss.
</P>
<P>
   It is a low point in my life when I slouch through that door at
the Carmine Center to ask about signing up. They don't take cash at
Carmine. They like checks and money orders. I don't have a check
with me; the lady behind the desk helpfully mentions that money
orders can be purchased at the nearby check-cashing center.
</P>
<P>
   It seems an appropriate ritual. Before joining this new gym, the
institutional embodiment of my fallen status, I first have to line
up with those of no fixed bank account.
</P>
<P>
   And so I slink back into Carmine, clutching my pitiful money
order. My annual fee. The man standing in front of me has
impressive tattoos. Nervous, I begin to kibitz with the skinny guy
who gets in line behind me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you belong to this place long?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it ... any good?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best,'' he says. ``It's a neighborhood place. Nothing
like it. Twenty-five bucks and you get everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything?'' I say. ``So they have, um, free weights?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything. Free weights, machines, treadmills,
Stairmasters.''
</P>
<P>
   Well now. The scales begin to fall from my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except, you want to know something?'' my wiry friend says.
``Those machines do nothing. Stick to free weights.''
</P>
<P>
   This fellow member of the Society of Carmine is thus the first
to introduce me to the Law of Perverse Returns: the less you spend,
the greater your health returns. A circuit of Cybex machines costs
thousands of dollars. Dumbbells? Maybe $25.
</P>
<P>
   I pay my dues and step into the locker room. Hm. Stainless steel
urinals. Nice touch. In fact, there's lots of unpainted steel: the
lockers, the toilet bowls. So far, the Printing House wins out in
terms of surface ornament. It's sort of St.-Tropez versus San
Quentin. Oh, and the showers at Carmine are time-controlled: you
press a button and get a few seconds of warm water.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Some further points of contrast I soon notice. The Printing
House had a towel service; the Carmine Center offers paper towels,
and a sign admonishing you not to dry with them. The Printing House
offered free toiletries: hair conditioner, deodorant and
moisturizer. Carmine has industrial-grade soap in wall dispensers.
On the locker room walls at the Printing House, I would find
notices offering brownstones for sale, time shares in Umbria,
dog-walking services. At Carmine there's a sign that says, ``If it
smells in here, maybe it's because you forgot to flush.''
</P>
<P>
   The Printing House had a spa when I belonged _ steam room,
Jacuzzi, massage rooms _ and since then, to keep up with
ever-escalating competition, it has installed a lavish
entertainment system, including Internet access, to divert patrons
riding the cardio machines. Other private clubs have taken to
offering aromatherapy, nutritionists, even cosmetic-surgery
consultations.
</P>
<P>
   Carmine laughs at such frippery. It does have cardio equipment _
stationary bikes, reclining and upright; Stairmasters; treadmills.
OK,  &UR; a &LR;  treadmill. The second one is out of service.
</P>
<P>
   The treadmill has a sign-up sheet, and the names on this sheet
are Italian, Spanish, African, Chinese. I like this. I mean, I
don't like having to sign up for the treadmill, but it gives me
pleasure that the membership is more diverse than the cast of
``Chariots of Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once every few weeks do I have to wait long to get on one
of the cardio devices. You can't be picky; if the treadmill's in
use, you may have to ride a cycle. This, however, is good for you:
it forces you to alternate muscle groups. (Once again, the
mysterious link between No Cash and Good Health.)
</P>
<P>
   The Cybex machines occupy a single room. They're pushed close
together, and the proximity breeds social interaction. One guy in
particular is really working the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' he says to me, ``you look like the guy in the Reebok
ad.''
</P>
<P>
   I've never seen this ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look like him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the extent of our conversation. He turns his attentions
to the women, one by one. They turn him away, pleasantly, then
compare notes in Spanish. He apparently doesn't speak Spanish.
Neither do I.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite place, though, is the free-weight area. This is
where the real work takes place. The heavy lifting, so to speak.
It's even less spacious than the Cybex room _ sweaty giants
pressing iron, shoulder to shoulder. It is, in fact, probably more
than a little dangerous. I keep expecting someone's hammer curl to
nail me to the wall. But these guys are clearly accomplishing just
as much _ frankly, a whole lot more _ than the pampered folks at
the Printing House. Not a body here _ mostly male, but the
occasional female _ doesn't inspire a touch of awe. I no longer
regret my decision to join. Now I want to belong.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of weeks, I begin to develop a peculiar
reverence for the Carmine Recreation Center. Communal exercise,
after all, isn't restricted to cheery Alpine health films; it
stands at the core of the ancient Greek conception of democracy. In
Plato's ``Republic,'' the question whether women ought to exercise
naked with men is given serious consideration. I begin to suspect
that Carmine is a great civic institution on the order of the New
York Public Library: a defining feature of the egalitarian society.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and by the way, I've lost 40 pounds. My former gym may have
whittled me down some, but this place has carved me like a turkey.
</P>
<P>
   When the Printing House offers a 10-day trial membership, I sign
up just to remind myself what I've been missing. Not a lot, it
turns out. One thing you can't get at Carmine is a caliper test to
check body fat. I get one at the Printing House, and the trainer
informs me that I'm down to 11 percent. Sixteen percent is the goal
for men my age; 8 percent and I'm hanging with professional
athletes. I stumble back to Carmine, in wonder.
</P>
<P>
   After running four miles on the treadmill one day, I enter the
men's locker room to hear a male voice, unconscious of itself,
slowly croon the entirety of ``Amazing Grace.'' The voice, it turns
out, belongs to a scrawny guy who's changing in a corner. But all
about him, leaning against lockers, are huge athletes who have
ceased their trash talk for a moment to lend an ear. They nod
thoughtfully. The little guy sings. And I, for a glorious moment,
feel just like a citizen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
