<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4787 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      07-09 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON WRAPS UP FIRST BIG FORAY IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, N.Y. _ Ray Goppert II, a metalworks employee here, pressed
forward at the end of an roundtable discussion on the economic
future of the Mohawk Valley to hand his five-month-old son Ray III
to First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cuddled the baby and swirled so that encircling news
photographers could take pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought the little guy today because I wanted to see if
there would be high-paying jobs around here when he's ready to go
to work,'' Goppert said later. ``Based on what I heard from Mrs.
Clinton, I just don't know if there will be the kind of jobs we
need to keep my son around here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day as Clinton wrapped up her first solo
foray into the campaign for a Senate seat from New York Friday. She
listened politely, dutifully scribbled notes but ducked specifics
on hot-button issues.
</P>
<P>
   She heard plenty of complaints about this upstate New York
region that has been largely on the sidelines during the booming
1990s, but she offered few commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious residents blamed the high costs of electrical power and
commercial air fares for discouraging businesses from relocating in
the region. They cited the flight of young workers to distant
employment, the inadequate training of high school graduates who
stay behind and the burdensome costs and regulations for old
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of showing the detailed expertise on health care that
she exhibited while campaigning Thursday, Clinton stressed that she
needs to listen and learn about New York issues as she weighs a
final decision on whether to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I love these listening sessions,'' she said,
adding that New Yorkers were bringing issues that ``I never would
have known about that if you hadn't raised it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her lone campaign promise of the day was to support the
inclusion of New York state in the Northeast Dairy Compact, a
government-backed arrangement providing subsidies that help boost
milk prices for dairy farmers. She later stopped in Utica,
Syracuse, and the state's capital, Albany, before her scheduled
return to Washington, D.C. Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Utica she suggested a jobs fair to combat the flight of young
workers to employment elsewhere. The fair, she said, could help
graduating students find work nearby, using the theme: ``Bring it
home to the Mohawk Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   She also urged congressional passage of a White House plan to
underwrite the interest on school construction bonds nationwide. In
Utica, she said, that would help authorities complete a $45 million
state-of-the-art high school planned within an industrial park
created on the site of the decommissioned Griffiss Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Looking weary on the third day of her exploratory Senate
campaign trip, Clinton pressed her audiences to explain the
economic stagnation that has left some communities along the Eire
Canal with high unemployment and vacant 19th century buildings
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have just been some reasons why upstate New York hasn't
had conditions to create the kind of jobs that the people here
deserve,'' Clinton told about 50 people gathered at the industrial
park
</P>
<P>
   F. Eugene Romano, 70, a Utica land developer, said the city's
crumbling facades look like ``a Jurassic Park for buildings'' that
scare away prospective investors. What's needed, he told Clinton,
is a government subsidy to cut the costs of demolition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a really good idea,'' Clinton replied. ``But I'm not
familiar with that, and I will have to go back and look at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also asked why electric power costs New Yorkers about 30
percent more per kilowatt hour than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little difficult to understand, given the
extraordinary hydro-power potential and opportunities for
competition that should be available,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's campaign spokesman, said that the
first lady has steadily jotted notes of what people have told her
on her upstate New York tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will follow up with them and with other experts _ and
should she decide to run for the Senate, she will take positions on
those issues in the context of a campaign,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday she is scheduled to return to the state for a
three-day tour of New York City, Westchester County and Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
