<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, June 10,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds; Adds: OHIO-PROFILE
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   SPRAWL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ (first in an occasional series) Hoping
to tap into the increasingly large suburban portion of the
electorate, Vice President Al Gore is determined to make so-called
``urban sprawl'' a major issue in the 2000 presidential campaign.
After nearly a decade of economic growth, Gore is betting that
quality of life issues such as traffic and unfettered development _
traditionally dealt with on the local level _ will resonate in a
national campaign. There is evidence to support his strategy: More
than half of the nation's governors mentioned ``sprawl'' or ``Smart
Growth'' in their inaugural speeches. Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
Gore's likely opponent in the general election, wasn't one of them.
Although Austinites are all-too-familiar with development debates,
most famously independent Texans aren't too concerned _ although
that may be changing _ and Bush has been virtually mum on the
issue. What is Bush's view on sprawl? Does the federal government
have a legitimate role to play? (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman). 50. WITH PHOTO, LOGO
</P>
<P>
   FORBES _ ATLANTA _ Steve Forbes is coming here again Friday.
There is speculation that he is going to name Rep. Bob Barr to be
his Georgia campaign chairman. (Whitt/Gordon or Hill-Morgan,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   OZONE _ WASHINGTON _ Scientists from the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, along with researchers from other
federal agencies and universities, will begin an intensive program
this month to monitor the level of ozone in the air in the region
of the Great Smoky Mountains National Park in Tennessee. The area
has been plagued with stubborn, health-threatening levels of
summertime photochemical smog for the last several years. Purpose
of the monitoring will be to develop more accurate forecasts so
susceptible people can be warned to stay away and to identify
sources, some of which may be distant pollution generators, NOAA
said. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in Washington and Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN-SYNAGOGUE _ ST. THOMAS, Virgin Islands _ One of the New
World's oldest synagogues, a crumbling structure in the U.S. Virgin
Islands held together by limestone-and-molasses mortar, is due for
a makeover. Worshipers at the Blessing and Peace and Loving Deeds
synagogue on St. Thomas say the $350,000 renovation, due to begin
in June 1999, will restore some of the building's original beauty
lost through years of decomposing plaster. The site, which dates
from 1833, is the oldest continuously used synagogue under the
American flag. Jews settled on St. Thomas beginning in 1665.
(Emling, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by noon Fri., July 9, in (i) International and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL _ A talk with the Israeli ambassador to the United States
about Israel's new government and what it means for the future of
peace in the Middle East. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-KILLINGS _ SIDNEY, Ohio _ Follow on the shooting deaths of
three teenage girls in Sidney, Ohio, and the slaying of a man in a
neighborhood five miles away. Authorities today were searching
today for Lawrence Michael Hensley, 30, in whose home the girls'
bodies were found. Officers detonated 24 Molotov cocktails found
inside Hensley's house. Sidney is about 40 miles north of Dayton.
(Elliott, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   w/OHIO-PROILE _ Who is Lawrence Michael Hensley, (Dayton Daily
News)
</P>
<P>
   BODY-RETRIEVAL _ Clayton, Ga._A father's fight to retrieve the
body of his daughter, Rachel Trois, 16, of Pennsylvania from the
Chattooga River has become an interstate squabble. South Carolina
Sen. Strom Thurmond, rescue groups, a river watch group and
commercial rafters are debating how far rescuers should go to try
to retrieve the corpse. The father says he is determined to have a
decent burial for Rachel. (Burritt, Cox News Service)
</P>
