<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOVIE STARS' COULDA BEEN A CONTENDER _ OR COULD IT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Movie Stars,'' airing at 8 p.m. CDT Sunday and Monday on WB,
is the kind of middling series whose likable characters inspire
good intentions, although not enough to overcome scripts stripped
bare of a comedy's essential element: laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the two episodes sent for review, this is one of
those underachieving sitcoms that's far less sophisticated than its
premise and press materials would have you believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movie Stars'' centers on life in a Hollywood family. Its
goals: to satirize the celebrity world and to show that its
inhabitants are just like the rest of us working stiffs. Next
week's episode, for example, deals with whether Marnette Patterson
(playing the same character she did in ``Something So Right'')
should attend the preppy rich kid's school or the arts magnet where
she'll be more in her element.
</P>
<P>
   Dad knows that the preppy school is the pipeline to Harvard and
Princeton, even though it spits out greedy robots wanting to make
their mark on ``their'' world without much regard for anyone else.
Public or private? What's a dad to do?
</P>
<P>
   Reese Hardin (Harry Hamlin) is the dad, a high-priced action
star married to Jacey Wyatt (Jennifer Grant, daughter of real-life
movie stars Dyan Cannon and the late Cary Grant), who's closing in
on her third Oscar nomination. The kicker here: Her passion is the
art of the film, his is the art of making billions on them.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in two young children, a cranky mother, the teen rebel and
Mark Benninghofen as Reese's complaining brother (he went to a
prestigious acting school but it's Reese's face and muscles that
count in Hollywood), and you've got TV's typical dysfunctional
family.
</P>
<P>
   They just happen to live in a spacious Malibu beach house and
drop names at every chance they get. Such as: ``Robin Williams is
driving the car pool today. I don't want him yelling at me in 27
wacky voices.'' Or this one: ``Call animal control. Adam Sandler's
going through the trash again.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are just two of the bombs featuring notables, like Michael
Douglas, Mel Gibson, Jennifer Lopez (she's sunbathing next door),
Drew Barrymore and Joe Pesci. (Reese tells his son to come ``save''
him at a kid's birthday party if Pesci starts talking to him.) And
that's all in the first episode.
</P>
<P>
   Another running gag is how the brothers of famous stars run in
packs. Here Joey Travolta, Don Swayze and Frank Stallone, real-life
brothers of the famous, spend time playing cards and whining about
their missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta: ``You ever see my brother with a hairpiece? It's scary
how much we look alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Swayze does a, ahem, dirty dance move.
</P>
<P>
   See? More sad than clever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movie Stars'' isn't on the fall schedule, and its chances of
survival are probably slim. In its defense, the subject of a movie
star family is one ripe with possibilities. Who knows what scripts
will come later down the line?
</P>
<P>
   On second thought ...
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
