<HEADER>
A4805 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BODIES-BOS &LR;      07-09 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BODIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGLE TOWN'S GRAVES MAY CONTAIN 350 BODIES, NATO SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ War crimes investigators are looking into
reports that as many as 350 bodies may be buried in mass graves
near Ljubenic, in what would be the biggest concentration of
corpses found since the Kosovo air war ended last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are reports that these sites contain 350 bodies,'' said
Major Jan Joosten, a spokesman for Kosovo Force, or KFOR, in
Pristina. He said Italian forces _ who patrol the western Kosovo
area that includes Ljubenic _ and the International Criminal
Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia are investigating the reports.
</P>
<P>
   The site was closed to reporters Friday. But villagers
interviewed by the Globe a week ago described two separate
massacres by Serb forces in April, killings the villagers said
claimed at least 133 lives.
</P>
<P>
   The first assault came on April 1, when three Serb soldiers
forcibly gathered 80 men from the 2,000-population village and
machine-gunned them, survivors of the attack said.
</P>
<P>
   After separating out most of the men, the soldiers ordered the
women and children to go down to the main road toward Albania, said
Elhame Haradinaj, 33, whose father was killed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   One man was executed as he walked down the village's main road
with his neighbors, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   As they headed down the road away from the village, the women
heard three series of gunfire: two short bursts and then a long,
sustained series of automatic weapon fire that lasted about five
minutes, Haradinaj said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the village, the men were lined up and asked where their
weapons were, said Sadik Jahmurati, 47.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, Haradinaj's father, Adem Haradinaj, told the
soldiers, ``You took them last summer, the Serb police took them
last summer.'' One of the three soldiers responded, ``We are not
police. We are Yugoslav soldiers,'' and pumped several bullets into
Haradinaj's chest, ``killing him in front of us,'' Jahmurati
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   When a second man stepped forward to tell the soldiers the
village ``never made any trouble,'' he, too, was shot dead in front
of his neighbors, Jahmurati said.
</P>
<P>
   As the remaining men stood mute in fear, one of the three
soldiers turned to his fellow attackers and said, ``did you know my
brother was kidnapped by the KLA?'' referring to the ethnic
Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army that had mounted an armed
insurrection against Serb rule in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, they started to execute us,'' swinging their machine
guns along the row of men, said Gani Bushati, who miraculously
survived the assault. He lifted his shirt and lowered his trousers
to display some of the 36 bullet wounds he suffered, which stitched
a horrifying, S-shaped pattern across his body.
</P>
<P>
   Eight men survived that attack by playing dead and crawled to
the woods for safety after the Serbs left.
</P>
<P>
   In a second attack on April 7, Serb forces gunned down villagers
from Ljubenic and surrounding mountain villages who were trying to
flee, said Sali Huskaj, who survived that assault.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs and villagers ``were shouting, and we saw them coming,
so we ran to escape,'' Huskaj said. Young men from Ljubenic said
they discovered 25 bodies, including 12 from one family, when they
trekked several hours into the mountains to look for missing
villagers.
</P>
<P>
   Ljubenic residents say they believe there are at least 60 bodies
in the mountains, based on the number of villagers they know are
missing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, there were remains of what appeared to be two bodies
in the courtyard of a house near the site of the reported April 1
massacre. Locals say they think the rest of the bodies were burned
inside the house.
</P>
<P>
   Two more bodies were on the mountain, but the corpses were too
fresh to be victims of a months-old attack.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Friday whether the suspected 350 corpses are from
the two reported massacres alone, or include victims of other,
nearby massacres.
</P>
<P>
   The area around western Kosovo _ especially around the city of
Pec _ is the region where the worst reported atrocities occurred.
The area was a fierce battleground between KLA and Serb forces near
the end of the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
