<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-INDIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERIOR CHIEF DEFENDS RECORD ON INDIAN TRUST FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt on Friday defended
his department's efforts to fix trust accounts created for the
benefit of American Indians, who have sued the government for
allegedly mismanaging or losing billions of dollars from the funds.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court on behalf
of more than 300,000 Indians and 2,000 tribes seeks to compel the
government to fix a century-old trust fund system set up to manage
money earned from Indian-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs, led by Elouise Cobell, a member of the Blackfeet
tribe in Montana, contend in their 1994 lawsuit the government has
failed to ensure that profits from the land were properly
distributed to the Indian owners. They say Indians may be owned
more than $10 billion in lost payments.
</P>
<P>
   But Babbitt, questioned by a lawyer for the government, said he
has instituted plans to modernize the accounting system and that
the government was not guilty of breaking its trust relationship
with the Indians and the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has conceded that some trust fund
accounts have been mismanaged in the past, Babbitt said it would be
a mistake to take responsibility for the program away from the
department's Bureau of Indian Affairs, which is overwhelmingly
staffed with Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   He added that most Indian tribes, while frustrated by the
cumbersome bureaucracy, continue to favor keeping management of the
trust funds within the Bureau of Indian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the love-hate relationship, they (the tribes) view the
Bureau of Indian Affairs as their imperfect piece of the
government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trust funds were created in the late 19th century when it
was national policy to break up reservations and parcel out tracts
of 80 or 160 acres to individual Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the land was rich in oil, timber, minerals or
agricultural products. The Bureau of Indian Affairs, acting as a
trustee for individual Indians, negotiated the sale of oil, trees,
ore or crops, and then collected the money on behalf of the
property owners. The agency was supposed to manage this task like a
trust officer at a local bank, always acting on behalf of the
landholder.
</P>
<P>
   But by the government's own admission, the bureau did not do a
good job in the past of managing the funds.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 Interior Department report showed that more than 123,000
of the 340,000 individual Indian trust fund accounts lacked a
Social Security number or taxpayer identification number. At least
46,000 accounts were being held for Indians whose whereabouts were
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   In tens of thousands of cases, trust fund documents were shoved
into unmarked boxes and stored in barns or sheds, according to the
Interior Department.
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, many of the documents were lost or
destroyed. One neglected warehouse in Albuquerque, N.M., eventually
became so rat-infested that officials entering the building in
search of trust documents needed to wear protective suits.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several billion dollars may have been lost over the
years in undervalued and uncollected lease payments and in
destroyed or lost checks for Indian beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 report conducted for the Interior Department by the
consulting firm Arthur Andersen said the Bureau of Indian Affairs
couldn't document $2.4 billion in tribal trust fund transactions.
Three years later, another report for the department by the
consulting firm Griffin &AMP; Associates warned that trust fund
problems and the class-action lawsuit ``may result in a potential
liability to the federal government so large that it is not
reasonably estimable.''
</P>
<P>
   During his testimony, Babbitt argued that the problems with the
trust funds go back decades and that he has made progress in
correcting them since he became secretary in 1993. Recently, the
Interior Department installed a $60 million computer system
designed to improve record keeping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing the best we can as fast as we can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the plaintiffs in the lawsuit contend that Babbitt has
stalled trust fund reform for years and only began to show interest
in the problem after the department was sued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babbitt spent seven years in office denying justice to Indian
account holders and covering up his role in the debacle,'' Cobell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The government was expected to rest its case after Babbitt's
testimony, with both sides predicting the trial will wrap up next
week. U.S. District Judge Royce C. Lamberth then will decide how
much money is owed to the Indians and whether the Bureau of Indian
Affairs will continue to manage the trust accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Lamberth held Babbitt and former Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin in contempt of court for failing to turn over Indian
trust funds records sought by the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
