<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV11-B     07-09 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURBS AS CLUBS AND OTHER INSIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 11, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the most striking characteristic of the modern world is
its growing specialization and interdependence. There are more
technologies, more alliances, more jurisdictions, more side effects
and unintended consequences than a generation or two ago _ in
short, more possibilities for good and ill. It is all very well to
speak of growing complexity, but a time comes when you want a
little conceptual edge.
</P>
<P>
   A leading authority on the interrelationships among these
entities _ industries, alliances, jurisdictions, etc. _ the
burden-sharing within them and the spillovers between, in something
more than a textbook sense, is Todd Sandler.
</P>
<P>
   True, Sandler literally wrote (along with Richard Cornes) the
most popular university text concerned with these topics. ``The
Theory of Externalities, Public Goods and Club Goods'' describes
the framework with which economists and others analyze public
expenditures, including those made by the mutual benefit
associations that economists in the last 30 years have taken to
calling ``clubs'' -- toll roads, public utilities, suburbs,
colleges, defense alliances, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not stopped there. In ``Global Challenges: An
Approach to Environmental, Political and Economic Problems,''
published a couple of years ago, he demonstrated how a few basic
economic concepts _ spillovers, public goods, collective action _
could be employed to analyze the underlying similarities of a host
of problems: global warming, ozone depletion, acid rain, nuclear
waste disposal, international terrorism, disease eradication,
population growth, tropical deforestation, and peace-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Sandler's newest book, with Keith Hartley _ ``The
Political Economy of NATO'' _ was published on the day the bombing
started in Serbia. It is defense economics without algebra, says a
friend, tracing the alliance's mission from mutual assured
destruction, to flexible response, to peace-keeping. With the war
all but successfully concluded, Sandler says, ``My guess now is
that we're going to return to the days of the '50s and '60s, where
you've got three or four allies doing everything, with everybody
else free-riding.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to emphasize the relevance of the approach, the United
Nations Development Program in May published a survey volume,
``Global Public Goods: International Cooperation in the 21st
Century,'' arguing that such goods are systematically
underprovided. For some years the UNDP has been the leading edge of
cosmopolitan progressive dogma _ for example, five years ago it
produced the annual ``Human Development Report,'' with its emphasis
on individual capabilities designed to contrast with the World
Bank's more traditional ``World Development Report.''
</P>
<P>
   The set-up chapter of the new report _ on ``intergenerational''
public goods, complete with a mammoth characteristics-based
taxonomy of them _ is by Sandler.
</P>
<P>
   It is all a long way from Pleasantville, the New York City
suburb where he grew up. Indeed, the Sandler story is testimony to
the extensive network of competitive educational institutions that
are unique to the United States. Sandler learned his economics at
the Binghamton campus of the State University of New York, then
taught at a series of out-back schools including Arizona State
University and the University of Wyoming before winding up
distinguished professor of economics and political science at Iowa
State University in Ames. He is a frequent visitor to universities
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the relevance (of economics). I liked being able to
use it to my advantage. I have a 10-year-old son, he sometimes
travels with me, we were in Prague, and it started to rain. I
hailed a cab, but my son said we should walk back to the subway, it
would be a lot cheaper. I said, no, cabs will be cheap here. It
came and it was very cheap, a couple of dollars for a long ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept pumping me in the hotel afterwards, how did you know
that? I said, in any city where you can ride the subway for three
cents from one end of town to the other, you can be darn sure that
taxis would have to be quite competitive to survive. Opportunity
cost and all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandler's big break came in 1981, when he spent a year in
Australia and teamed up with Richard Cornes, then at Australian
National Universit. The pair wrote five papers in four months.
``We had trememdous difficulty in getting them published at first.
That's usually the case. . .. The comments were clearly incorrect,
so we persevered. We fixed the papers to say, `one shouldn't think
this-and-such,' then we played a kind of musical chairs. We
switched them around, and on the second go, they were all accepted.
The issue had to do with how to teach the fundamental distinctions
between public and private goods that had been spelled out earlier
by Nobel laureate Paul Samuelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point it was clear to us that we had come up with such
a different way of analyzing public goods that it was going to
catch on in a big way. We managed to strip the model down to four
elements, so that the mathematics was extremely simple. We came up
with a new way of visualizing it graphically. Once you build a
theory on such a simple and elementary framework, your ability to
extend it and apply it is almost limitless. We already had these
five papers. We said let's put it into text form.'' The result is
not deep, at least by the standards of Sandler's colleagues on the
research frontier, but broad: a highly serviceable map of one of
the most important territories in economics.
</P>
<P>
   Cornes's and Sandler's text has doubled in size since it first
appeared in 1986. Much of the new material concerns the theory of
clubs, which traces its origins to an argument among economists in
the 1920s about the pricing of congested roads. In 1957, Charles
Tiebout made a powerful case for how local jurisdictions such as
suburbs could be shaped by consumers who shopped among them for the
best public services. Only after James Buchanan and Mancur Olson in
the mid-1960s published formal analyses did the study of clubs take
off. Today, it is one of the most active topics in mathematical
economics _ and a source of much policy research as well.
</P>
<P>
   Next on Sandler's agenda is a primer on economic concepts for
the intelligent layperson. ``I hope instead of buying one of Paul
Krugman's books for an airplane trip, that they will consider
buying mine,'' says Sandler. ``I do think people want to have a
sense of what has been the economic revolution in this century and
what's going to happen in economics in the coming years. I know
what my colleagues are going to say, that I'm a popularizer now.
But I still do the stuff out in infinite space.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
