<HEADLINE>
DRIVER IN TRAIN-TRUCK COLLISION RAN STOP SIGN, AUTHORITIES SAY &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By PATTY REINERT
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A tanker truck driver ran a stop sign just before
crossing into the path of the Amtrak passenger train that derailed
west of here, injuring 21 people, authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not see the stop sign but did see the train and then
tried to brake,'' said Texas Department of Public Safety spokesman
Tom Vinger. ``It was way too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinger said the truck driver, Jason David Bubela, 21, of El
Campo, would likely be charged with a misdemeanor traffic violation
_ either failure to yield for a train or disregarding a stop sign _
in connection with the accident near Eagle Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers also are investigating possible violations for failure
to keep a log book and for operating a truck with faulty brakes.
The charges are expected within the next two weeks, Vinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Bubela, a driver for Key Energy Services of Bryan-College
Station, was not seriously injured in the wreck with the eastbound
Sunset Limited, which occurred just before noon Thursday. The
company's lawyer, Jack Loftis, declined to discuss the
investigation, citing a request by the National Transportation
Safety Board. He said Bubela would not be available for an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The train, en route from Los Angeles to Orlando, Fla., was
carrying 234 passengers and crew members, 21 of whom were treated
for mostly minor injuries at Rice Medical Center in Eagle Lake,
about 65 miles west of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the injured, including engineer J.D. Woods and his
assistant engineer, Ed Guidon, spent the night in the hospital but
were released by Friday afternoon, hospital administrator David
Keith said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 50, of San Antonio, and Guidon, 34, of La Place, La.,
were pulled from the overturned engine Thursday after rescuers used
a sledgehammer to break a window.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in the front car, so they were banged up pretty
bad,'' Keith said. ``They're going to be awfully sore for a while,
but they mostly have bumps and bruises. We were concerned that
there might be internal bleeding, but we've ruled that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak officials declined to allow their employees to be
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   NTSB officials arrived in Eagle Lake on Friday to begin their
investigation of the wreck. Spokesman Keith Hollaway said
investigators had recovered the ``black box,'' which contains a
recording of the train's operations, and sent it to Washington for
review by crash experts.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Davis, a spokesman for Union Pacific, which owns the
tracks, said crews worked throughout the night to clean up about
2,000 gallons of diesel fuel spilled from the train and to replace
800 feet of rail. The tracks were reopened at 8:30 a.m. Friday, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
