<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-WAYPEOPLERUN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN RUN, BUT YOU CAN'T HIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY FRIAUF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way People Run''
</P>
<P>
   By Christopher Tilghman
</P>
<P>
   Category: Short Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $21.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Why people run is because family crises eject them from the big,
stinking cities where they have lucrative jobs and complicated
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Where people run is to the countryside. There, everything is
clean. Country people have straightened out their priorities
without even trying. Everything becomes clear: Cities stink and
lucrative jobs gut your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Tilghman says these things over and over in his
second collection of short fiction, called ``The Way People Run.''
He says it in tangled stories about people who imagine they know
each other so well they don't bother to understand one another.
Excruciating loneliness ensues. People run to the country.
</P>
<P>
   John Steinbeck said it shorter and better, in his fable of an
animal that attempts to make a homestead outside the fruitful but
dangerous garden.
</P>
<P>
   But if you like your psychological fiction stuffed full of
self-inflicted pain and suffering, and with more layers than
homemade baklava, check out ``The Way People Run.''
</P>
<P>
   About that title: The way people run is scared, mostly. And
Tilghman nails it to the wall. In ``The Late Night News,'' he
crafts an ice-cold description of the suffering that can lead
strong people to alcoholism: ``Long ago Martin had learned that
loneliness was like all other kinds of pain: endurable if you knew
it would get no worse and if you could be certain that it would
someday stop. ... It could get a lot worse, this hollowness; he was
just standing at the edge, looking into the pit, and it was a
dangerous place to be, he knew that. The liquid voices were
inviting him to jump in: You'll love it! You can't imagine how good
permanent self-pity can feel! What else do you have on your
calendar? One of these days, perhaps tonight, perhaps even this
second, he would have to make a decision; his life was in his hands
like a folded shadow; he was terrified of the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   The author builds haystacks of familial guilt that threaten to
suffocate character and reader alike. Then, faster than your best
friend can recite your failings, he scythes through the chaff to a
kernel of human truth. Consider this, from ``A Suitable Good-Bye'':
``He found pleasure in nourishing this child, and understood for
the first time those looks of supreme contentment on the faces of
mothers when their children were eating a good supper.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a fine premise, this running from the rat race to something
better. Perhaps it does bear repeating many times.
</P>
<P>
   (Book reviewer Betsy Friauf works on the Star-Telegram features
copy desk. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
