<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS REPUBLICANS ARE BEHOLDEN TO HEALTH INSURANCE INDUSTRY &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By NANCY MATHIS
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton accused congressional
Republicans Friday of being beholden to the health insurance
industry in its &UR;  &LR; efforts to kill Democrat-backed legislation that
would establish a bill of rights for patients.
</P>
<P>
   The president also moved to counter an advertising campaign by
the legislation's opponents in which they claim the Democratic bill
will drive up insurance costs. He contended Americans would be
willing to pay &UR;  &LR; the extra $1 a month to ensure quality medical care
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to put people and principle and evidence ahead of raw
political influence,'' Clinton told medical personnel at the
Harbor-UCLA Medical Center in nearby Torrance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton again pressed the issue as the Senate prepares to open
debate next week. Republican leaders have decided to allow the
Democrats to bring up their measure, but in the end likely will
offer the GOP alternative and pass it instead. The plan would
bypass individual votes on sensitive issues.
</P>
<P>
   The president said when he read of the Republican strategy, ``I
thought to myself, what kind of a weird world am I living in? This
is about whether some people live or some people die. This is not a
typical political decision. This is about life and the quality of
life and the fundamental decency of our society.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic bill would force health maintenance organizations
and other managed care companies to allow patients the right to
specialists, to emergency care, to retain the same doctor
throughout treatment, and to file lawsuits when the refusal for
services results in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican version is less expansive and less expensive, but
Democrats complain it denies patients the right to sue and excludes
100 million people.
</P>
<P>
   The president said the drive for profits at the expense of
patient care mandates that Congress act. He said horror stories of
patients denied treatment and access to specialists are not
isolated events but signs of systemic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has used his executive order to extend much of the
Democratic proposal to the government's federal employees as well
as Medicare and Medicaid patients. He said the experience so far
for federal workers is their insurance increased by $1 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said HMOs are attempting to scare healthy clients into
thinking they would pay more for coverage to cover the sick
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to ask every American if he or she wouldn't be
willing to pay something in that range on the off chance that their
healthy self might not always be that way,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents to the legislation have launched a $750,000
advertising campaign to try to sway undecided senators.
</P>
<P>
   The president maintained the Democratic plan has the support of
70 percent of the Republicans, Democrats and independents in the
country. There are more than 200 medical and consumer groups also
backing it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his address a day after completing a tour of
impoverished regions in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he headed out for a round of golf. The president
decided to stay in California, borrowing the estate of supermarket
magnate Ron Burkle, in order to watch the Women's World Cup soccer
match Saturday between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
