<P>
   RUSSIA-MIR (Moscow) _ It looks like money woes will finally kill
Mir. Not only can't Russia afford upkeep, now Kazakhstan won't
launch rockets with supplies for cosmonauts unless it gets paid. By
David Filipov. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BODIES (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ War crimes investigators
check reports that 350 bodies may be in graves near Ljubenic, the
biggest such site found since the war ended. By Susan Milligan 750
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-VOTERS (Washington) _ Are candidates targeting these
college voters, and if so, how? With an open race next year and GOP
hopefuls like Bush and Dole, are more students attracted to the GOP
or to Democrats? By Eun Lee Koh. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   SMITH-RUN (Washington) _ Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire is
likely to resign from the Republican Party next week and continue
his campaign for the White House as an independent or third-party
candidate. By Bob Hohler 500 words. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-NEWSTART (Syracuse, N.Y.) -- In the middle of her maiden
voyage across upstate New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton suddenly
began to muse that the tour was marking not only the start of a
possible Senate campaign but the start of a new life _ the first
time, after 30 years as a career woman, that she was striking out
on her own. By Fred Kaplan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHARACTER-SCHOOL (Washington) _ The Hyde Leadership Public
Charter School, based in New England, is scheduled to open in the
nation's capital in September and is looking for students. The
school values character development over ability, and effort over
achievement. By Eun Lee Koh. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANIMALS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The accident injuring horror novelist
Stephen King last month seems to have touched off a buzz about
safety belts for pets. By Vicki Croke. 775 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-STARS (Undated) _ It's never a good time for a grating sitcom
like ``Movie Stars,'' which squanders its potential on unbelievably
stale entertainment jokes. By Matthew Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-WYNONNA (Undated) _ Wynonna is back on the road with ``The
Working Mama Tour,'' a blend of the musical and the domestic. By
Steve Morse. 850 words.
</P>
