<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   JUSTICE -- Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas blasts special
interest politics in the selection of federal judges. A number of
federal judgeships are open now because of partisanship. Thomas
recounted his selection for nomination to show that Bush never made
him pass a litmus test on conservative values. He spoke to federal
judges meeting in Kansas City. By Mark Morris.
</P>
<P>
   STARJOURNAL -- Star Journal feature. About Jesse Scott,
languishing in a Grandview nursing home, aged and blind and
forgotten by the country he served. Jesse, it turns out, is one of
the last of the famed Tuskeegee airmen. By Joe Popper.
</P>
<P>
   ZOO -- Mark Reid, director of the Sedgwick County Zoo in
Wichita, calls it a ``cultural phenomenon'': Kansas has more zoos,
per capita, than practically any other state. Kansas has 12 zoos,
three times more than Missouri, which has twice the population. The
zoos cost big bucks to operate, but communities such as Clay Center
are willing to shell out for the prestige of having their own.
Among the smaller zoos, Independence has one of the finest mountain
lion exhibits in the country. By Tom Perrin.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   NONPROFIT _ Non-profit organizations are being held more
accountable under new federal regulations enacted last month. By
Diane Stafford
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ Weekly Y2k column by David Hayes and Finn Bullar
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER -- Jerry Heaster column.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   CUP --- A scene-setter for Saturday's Women's World Cup final,
which will be the biggest women-only event in sports history. By
Mechelle Voepel.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS -- Houston Astros at Kansas City, 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Dutton.
</P>
<P>
   AARON -- Advance on Hank Aaron's appearance in town Saturday by
asking young players at a local tournament what they know about
Aaron. By Chris Carter.
</P>
