<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANS-CANCER10-COX     07-09 1669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANS-CANCER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Darker skin now may turn cancerous later
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Jane Katzen was a child, a tan
signified health.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents would tell me, `You look pale. Go out in the
sun,''' Katzen says.
</P>
<P>
   And so she did. All summer long she frolicked sunscreen-free on
the Jersey shore. In high school, she used a reflector to intensify
the sun's rays. In her 20s, she and her husband sailed from Maine
to South America, and she passed much of those 18 months basting on
deck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I was not cognizant of the damage the sun could do
to my skin,'' Katzen says.
</P>
<P>
   By the age of 28, Katzen had her first skin cancer, on her left
forearm. Over the past 22 years, the Lantana registered nurse has
had more than 50 basal and squamous cell cancers removed from her
face, neck, arms, legs and back, leaving behind a landscape of
scars.
</P>
<P>
   She now checks in with her dermatologist every three months and
routinely wears long sleeves and long pants. If she has to spend
extended time in the sun, she'll don Solumbra clothing, which
protects skin from ultraviolet rays.
</P>
<P>
   And she vacations in Seattle, Denmark and Sweden _ ``places
where it's cold and wet,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But every day, whether cloudy or sun-drenched, she longs for a
tan. ``I was an addict, so I still think that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida: A melanoma capital
</P>
<P>
   Such is the long reach and firm grasp of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 1 million Americans are diagnosed with skin cancer each
year, making it the most common type of cancer in the United
States. It's estimated that almost half of Americans who live to
the age of 65 will have skin cancer at least once.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming majority of those cancers will be the highly
curable basal cell or squamous cell varieties. Basal cell
carcinoma, a slow-growing cancer, seldom spreads to other parts of
the body. Squamous cell carcinoma also rarely spreads, but it does
so more often than basal.
</P>
<P>
   What worries dermatologists most are melanomas, the most deadly
of skin cancers. Of the estimated 9,200 deaths from skin cancer
this year, 7,300 will be from melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of melanoma are at an all-time high, and the American
Cancer Society predicts that 44,200 people will be diagnosed with
melanoma this year.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, an estimated 3,000 new cases of melanoma will be
diagnosed this year, placing the Sunshine State second in the
nation, between first-place California and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   From 1950 to 1990, the national melanoma rate doubled. ``It's a
serious epidemic,'' says Ira Schlesinger, a dermatologist in Delray
Beach. ``With melanoma, all bets are off. It doesn't behave in any
predictable fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Malignant melanoma can spread to other parts of the body very
quickly, but if detected in its earliest stages and treated
properly, it's also highly cureable.
</P>
<P>
   While it's not clear why the melanoma rate has exploded, factors
include the depletion of the ozone layer _ which in a perfect world
would help protect us from ultraviolet radiation _ and the
time-delayed effects of a nation in love with the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any form of burning or tanning is a sign of sun damage,'' says
Schlesinger, who adds that 90 percent of our sun exposure occurs
before the age of 18, and incidentally.
</P>
<P>
   And the damage is more than epidermis-deep.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun's ultraviolet rays burn the skin, they alter the
DNA in skin cells, prohibiting the DNA from multiplying and
dividing in the proper manner. That opens the door to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sun exposure also breaks down the skin's collagen and elastin
(say hello to wrinkles), stimulates pigmentation (greetings,
freckles and moles) and dilates blood vessels (welcome, visible
capillaries).
</P>
<P>
   When tanned meant traveled
</P>
<P>
   To understand the origins of sun worship in this country, you
have to rewind the sundial many moons.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling flush with victory and prosperity, post-World War II
America tilted its collective face heavenward and basked in an
unprecedented age of leisure time, interstate travel and trips to
Florida beaches.
</P>
<P>
   A tan line _ once the mark of farmers, ranchers and others who
toiled outdoors _ became the coveted accessory of the heretofore
pallid middle and upper classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a tan, that showed that you had money to travel,''
Schlesinger says. ``Having a tan was seen as affluent.''
</P>
<P>
   But that affluence came at a price, a bill that did not come due
for decades. Fifty years later, a nation is tanned, rested and
ready ... for skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Fread, 69, belonged to that initial generation of sun
worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the '40s, Fread and her sister would trudge four miles
from their home in Middletown, N.J., catch a bus and then walk
another mile to reach the beach.
</P>
<P>
   There, the teen-agers donned matching swimsuits, slathered
themselves in baby oil and spent up to eight hours a day outdoors.
``We did an awful lot of laying out on the blanket in the sun,''
says Fread, a retired schoolteacher in West Palm Beach. ``We had a
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Fread's skin would burn just a little, but then everywhere the
sun touched turned to gold. ``I used to have a beautiful tan when I
was young.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Fread avoids the beach but makes regular trips to her
dermatologist's office. She's had a couple dozen pre-cancerous and
cancerous lesions removed from her face, arms and back.
Fortunately, they've all been nonmelanoma.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the high incidence of cancer in her immediate family,
Fread remains ever-vigilant. She visits her dermatologist every few
months for screenings.
</P>
<P>
   Good call, says her dermatologist, Donna Ann Zeide.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the name of the game: To get it nice and early,'' Zeide
says. ``Why should it have to come to half a nose in a gauze pad?''
</P>
<P>
   Who's still going for the burn?
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you're a candidate for this and it's chronic, there's
nothing you can do to stop it,'' says Cathy Kollman.
</P>
<P>
   Kollman speaks from ongoing experience. Within the last month,
she had her latest in a series of surgeries to remove basal and
squamous cell skin cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Kollman, 50, cut high school to go to the beach and previously
vacationed in Puerto Rico and Antigua. ``Every place I went was
always for the sun,'' she says. ``I've been paying for it ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   After her first cancer was removed from her back in her early
20s, she says her reaction was ```Oh, how am I going to go back in
the sun?'''
</P>
<P>
   It took a few more years and few more cancers for the
seriousness of the disease to sink in. Now, she never goes without
sunscreen and hat when she walks her two golden retrievers on the
beach.
</P>
<P>
   Miami dermatologist Fredric Brandt says the crystal blue
persuasion of Florida's beaches makes reaching his patients with an
anti-tan message that much harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to the beach on any weekend, and you'll see it packed
with people sunbathing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the bikinied and Speedoed resistance recruits young
adults more than any other group, dermatologists say. (Among 25- to
29-year-olds, melanoma is more common than any non-skin cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   Sun damage is cumulative, and the exposure you get now often
won't show up for decades. ``When we're young, we all think we're
invincible,'' Zeide says. ``It's hard to be good now for five, 10,
20 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   At noon on a recent Sunday, 22-year-old Ana Maia hit Riviera
Beach armed only with an SPF of 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's low, but I know the risks,'' said the West Palm Beach
bank teller. On her twice-monthly trips to the beach, she'll
occasionally leave the sunscreen at home. ``It's dangerous, but
sometimes you have those lazy times where you don't feel like
putting anything on.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of melanoma scares her, she says, but ``you never
know what life is going to bring and you want to enjoy yourself.''
For Maia, that means sun, surf and a little color on her normally
pale skin. ``You listen to all these doctors, and there's something
wrong with everything,'' says 46-year-old Ed Martin, sunning
SPF-less on Riviera Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Florida after working eight years as a mechanical
engineer in St. Croix, where he shrugged off sunscreen despite the
equatorial rays, Martin grew up on a South Carolina farm. His
parents and grandparents toiled all summer in the fields without
sun protection; SPF factors aren't a part of his heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Wrinkles? Skin cancer? ``When you get to be a certain age,
you're going to get those anyway,'' Martin says.
</P>
<P>
   Clelio Saldana, a 47-year-old heavy equipment operator, also
follows a live-and-let-fry philosophy. ``When God says it's your
turn to go, you go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a coastal tour from Key West to Charleston,
S.C., Clelio and his wife, Nancy, caught some Riviera Beach rays.
Naturally dark-skinned Clelio wasn't wearing any sunscreen, but the
fair Nancy used Coppertone 30 on her face and shoulders, and
Australia Gold Tanning Accelerator everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm going to burn like a lobster,'' said the nurse's
assistant, 31.
</P>
<P>
   Several blankets away, Randy Eichholz spreads on a tanning oil
with a single-digit SPF.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-year-old social worker from St. Louis, Eichholz is in hot
pursuit of a Florida tan. ``That way I can make all my employees
jealous.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tide may slowly be turning on the ability of tanned skin
to make people green with envy.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood, Madison Avenue and the fashion industry, which
previously set the golden-glow standard with the likes of Raquel
Welch, that memorably bronzed Bain de Soleil model and Christie
Brinkley, are casting the spotlight on whiter shades of pale.
</P>
<P>
   Many modern mannequins, musicians and actresses exemplify the
alabaster look: Nicole Kidman, Madonna, Gwyneth Paltrow, Jewel,
Cate Blanchett and Christina Ricci, to name a fair few.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully that will help all of us,'' says former sun
worshiper Katzen. ``Pale can be absolutely beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
