<HEADER>
A4834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANS-SUNSCREEN10-COX     07-09 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANS-SUNSCREEN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Risk management for tanning
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Everybody's free to wear sunscreen, but
for some bodies, it's an absolute must. If you recognize yourself
in the risk factors below, make doubly sure you slop on the
slippery stuff:
</P>
<P>
   _ Light eyes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fair skin.
</P>
<P>
   _ Light hair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family history of skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chronic sun exposure throughout life.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blistering sunburns as a child or adolescent.
</P>
<P>
   Those at high risk should start getting annual skin-cancer
screenings in their early 20s. From then on, ``check your birthday
suit on your birthday,'' says dermatologist Donna Ann Zeide.
</P>
<P>
   Sizing up skin cancer
</P>
<P>
   Not sure if that mole is something to mull over? Remember the
ABCDE's of melanoma's warning signs:
</P>
<P>
   Asymmetry _ One half of the mole does not match the other.
</P>
<P>
   Border _ The edges are ragged, notched or blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Color _ The pigmentation is not uniform, with variable degrees
of tan, brown or black. Also look out for red, white or blue moles.
</P>
<P>
   Diameter _ Diameter greater than 6 millimeters (or bigger than a
pencil eraser). Any increase in size should be of particular
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Elevation _ The mole isn't flush with the surface of the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``But none of those things really tell the whole story,'' says
Dr. Ira Schlesinger.
</P>
<P>
   When in doubt, have your dermatologist check it out.
</P>
<P>
   And don't wait for a questionable area to hurt; skin cancers
seldom cause pain.
</P>
<P>
   Here comes the sunscreen
</P>
<P>
   No need to adopt a vampire's aversion to the sun. Solar-smart
folks follow this advice:
</P>
<P>
   Wear sunscreen every day, even if you're only going from house
to car and car to office.
</P>
<P>
   The range of products is wider than ever: spray-on sunscreens;
stick sunscreens; sunscreens for acne sufferers; foundations or
moisturizers blended with sunscreens. Find a product you like and
apply it religiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no point in torturing yourself every day,'' says
dermatologist Donna Ann Zeide says. Adds Schlesinger: ``If you're
not going to use it, it's not worth anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for broad-spectrum UVA and UVB protection. The key
ingredients? Titanium dioxide, zinc oxide or Parsol 1789. And never
dip below SPF 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like using a condom with a hole in it,'' Zeide says.
``There's no point.''
</P>
<P>
   Protect the oft-neglected eyelids, earlobes and lips. Women
develop fewer skin cancers on their lips than men do because they
enjoy the physical protection of lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Cover up your kids. Children especially need sunblock _
two-thirds of sun damage happens before the age of 15. But don't
put sunscreen on babies under 6 months of age; keep them out of
direct sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents know it's good to prevent sunburn, but they don't know
it's good to prevent sun,'' Schlesinger says.
</P>
<P>
   Replace your sunscreen annually. Unopened, sunscreen has a shelf
life of up to three years. Once opened, the SPF starts breaking
down. It's a good idea to buy new products at the beginning of each
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Spray on your tan. For those who can't warm to the thought of
alabaster skin, bronzing powders and self-tanning lotions now color
cosmetic counters, and the new formulas forgo the telltale orange
tint of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   Complete all outdoor activities before 10 a.m. or start them
after 4 p.m. to avoid the sun at its strongest.
</P>
<P>
   Get to know your skin. Practice self-exams to familiarize
yourself with your own landscape. That way, you can more easily
notice mole changes such as growing, bleeding or crusting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
