<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HUNLEY-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-09 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HUNLEY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 `THE HUNLEY:' A DRAMATIC STORYFROM A FOOTNOTE IN THE CIVIL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While history may be written by the victors, the losers are
sometimes remembered with respectful affection. So here is ``The
Hunley,'' a television movie that takes its inspiration from a
fascinating footnote to the Civil War, saluting a small band of
Confederate patriots who served with honor.
</P>
<P>
   This drama, unapologetically sympathetic to the Southern cause,
comes from TNT in Atlanta, which is offering the film's premiere
Sunday night. This is no mere exercise in whistling ``Dixie.''
``The Hunley'' is built of solid storytelling and a hard-edged
central performance by Armand Assante.
</P>
<P>
   Assante, a long way from ``The Odyssey,'' plays Lt. George E.
Dixon, an engineer who is given command of the Confederacy's secret
weapon, a submarine. The vessel, called the H.L. Hunley after its
inventor, has already claimed the lives of two crews, including its
namesake. But Gen. Pierre G.T. Beauregard (Donald Sutherland),
himself an engineer, is desperate to break the Union blockade of
Charleston. He decides to give the experimental craft another try
and another commander.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon and Beauregard have suffered grave personal losses. The
grizzled Dixon's limp is a result of an injury he sustained under
Beauregard's command at Shiloh. The bullet Dixon took in the leg
might have killed him had its course not been blocked by the lucky
coin in his pocket, a parting gift from his beloved wife, who later
perished when Union forces sank a boat on which she was traveling.
</P>
<P>
   Beauregard is a widower, too; his wife died in childbirth. His
reputation is in tatters after some blunders as a commander and his
disdainful treatment by Jefferson Davis, for whom he bears a
smoldering hatred. These background details and others upon which
the drama turns are laid out naturally as the story unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland brings a tragic weariness to his smaller but pivotal
role. While his Creole accent and reddish hair dye seem to have
been applied too generously, his blue eyes clearly convey soul-deep
pain. Occasionally his words serve the drama, too, as when he tells
Dixon, ``We are both romantics in an age of barbarians.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film belongs to Assante. His character, the nearly
broken officer who must turn a ragtag bunch of misfits into a
unified unit of heroes, could easily have turned into a cliche. But
with the collaboration of the film's writer-director, John Gray,
Assante manages to blend Dixon's strength and anguish into a
believable whole.
</P>
<P>
   The other men of the Hunley never seem less than fully formed,
even though the characters must be rendered in the quick strokes of
movie shorthand. Notable among them are Alex Jennings, Christopher
Bauer and Sebastian Roche, all of whom provide moments of heartfelt
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The film surrounds its actors with atmospheric context, whether
in the belly of the cramped submarine or on the streets of
Charleston under barrage. The visual effects are nearly always in
harmony with the drama, seldom overwhelming it. Brief scenes that
combine flashbacks with moments of Dixon's fantasy are well
handled, although a garnish of mysticism near the end does mar the
film's conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   History shows that the Hunley was not able to reverse the course
of the war. But its legacy, generations of more successful
submarines, now includes one more element, a memorable film.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`THE HUNLEY'  &QL; 
8 p.m. ET Sunday on TNT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by John Gray; story by John Fasano and
Gray. Mitch Engel, producer; George Manasse, co-producer; John
Thomas, director of photography. Music by Randy Edelman. Andrew
Adelson and Tracey Alexander, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Armand Assante ( Dixon), Donald Sutherland ( Beauregard);
Alex Jennings (Alexander), Sebastian Roche (Collins), Michael
Stuhlbarg (Wicks), Michael Dolan (Becker), Christopher Bauer
(Simkins), Jack Baun (Ridgeway), Kevin Robertson (Carlson) and Jeff
Mandon (Miller). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
