<SLUG> BC-SUNBURN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
29 INMATES SUE OVER SUNBURNS &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By ED ASHER
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Twenty-nine Texas inmates claim they were forced to
sit in a prison courtyard in blistering heat for more than six
hours and suffered severe sunburns.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen of them required medical treatment, according to a
civil rights lawsuit filed in federal court in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it was reported that they had first- and
second-degree burns,'' said the inmates' attorney, Benton
Musslewhite.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks unspecified compensatory and punitive damages
against the Texas Department of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   All 29 inmates were housed in a dormitory at the Pam Lychner
State Jail Facility in Humble.
</P>
<P>
   Musslewhite said some type of altercation occurred July 7, 1997,
and guards ``ordered the inmates out into the yard into the hot sun
as punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit said they were ordered into the yard at about 11:30
a.m. ``only in their shorts, without shade, food, water or any
other care'' and forced to stay there until about 5:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The temperature that day exceeded 100 degrees and was even
higher pursuant to the heat index,'' the suit said. ``Though all
were badly sunburned, some seriously, they were not given any
medical attention until over three hours later.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit said 19 were taken to a medical facility at about 9:20
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The foregoing conduct constituted cruel and unusual
punishment,'' the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
