<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NAMES _  &LR; When Hewlett-Packard Co. decided a few months ago to spin
off its noncomputer business into a separate company, that was the
easy part. Now for the hard part: what do you call the thing? ``We
held a mock contest for the name, but it was never a serious
effort,'' said Michael Fournell, a spokesman for ``NewCo,'' which
is the informal code name given by Hewlett-Packard to the new
enterprise. ``We knew we needed an expert.'' They weren't alone.
According to Enterprise IG, a worldwide brand-consulting firm, a
record 1,456 U.S. companies adopted new names in the first half of
the year, up 52 percent from a year before. Nearly a third of the
changes stemmed from mergers, reorganizations and spin-offs. BY
DAVID LAZARUS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENERGY _  &LR; Commonwealth Energy, a new electric-service supplier
based in Orange County, is being investigated by the state Public
Utilities Commission for retroactively billing some 19,500
customers a total of $632,000. State investigators say the company
also may be misleading customers about the amount of savings
offered by the state's deregulated energy market. BY REBECCA SMITH
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DESSERT _  &LR; Major changes are in the works at Just Desserts, the
San Francisco pastry chain, including the diversification of its
pastry lines, a doubling of its baking capacity and more emphasis
on wholesale operations. But the company's shaky financial
performance in recent years raises questions about its ability to
carry out the plan. BY CAROL EMERT
</P>
