<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTORICO-FIRING-RAN     07-09 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-FIRING-RANGE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICANS PROTEST NAVY FIRING RANGE ON NEARBY ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: P.R., Fla., Nev., Wash., Alaska, Calif., Ariz., Hawaii)  (ART ADV: Photo (NYT10) was sent on July 6 to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ For more than two months, about three
dozen people have occupied the eastern tip of this small island
seven miles off the coast of Puerto Rico trespassing on property
controlled by the U.S. Navy in an act of deliberate defiance. They
have set up tents, built a chapel and walked among craters, target
boards and unexploded bombs at the Navy's live-fire range, vowing
not to leave until the military training exercises are stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting for the future of a new generation,'' said
Carlos Zenon, a 62-year-old fisherman whose group, one of four
occupying the Navy property, planned to move in chickens and goats
in the next few weeks to further populate the range.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has used Vieques for target practice since 1941, but
that arrangement is under investigation by a special federal panel
and is fueling an unprecedented uproar in Puerto Rico, uniting
political parties and environmental and religious groups, after a
civilian security guard was killed and four other people were
injured in April when an F/A-18 jet dropped two bombs one and a
half miles from its intended target.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since its acquisition by the United States
after the 1898 Spanish-American War, Puerto Rico, a self-governing
commonwealth and a U.S. military outpost in the Caribbean, is
demanding that the Navy end all military activities in Vieques and
return the land it acquired in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a special commission appointed by Gov. Pedro Rossello
concluded that the military training had caused disastrous economic
and environmental damage and that it violated the human and
constitutional rights of the 9,300 residents of Vieques. The panel
recommended that the Navy clean up and leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an expression of Puerto Ricans' unwillingness to
serve or contribute to the defense of the nation,'' Rossello said
in an interview. ``This is specifically about irreversible and
significant damage to a community of United States citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The April accident underscored the problems facing Vieques, a
51-square-mile island _ about twice the size of Manhattan _ whose
towns of Isabel Segunda and Esperanza are within a dozen miles of
the live-impact range used by the Navy about 180 days of the year.
No more than 12 percent of the ammunition fired in Vieques involves
live explosives, Navy spokesmen said, but opponents of the training
exercises have for years blamed the explosions not only for
rattling windows and making residents anxious about their safety,
but for stifling Vieques' fledging tourism, hurting the livelihood
of fishermen and leaving the small island behind the rest of Puerto
Rico in income, employment and quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Navy pilots at the range accidentally fired 263
shells tipped with depleted uranium _ a dense material used to
penetrate thick armor _ and although Nuclear Regulatory Commission
officials say the radioactivity from the uranium is very low, the
news increased health concerns here among people already reeling
from unexplained high rates of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The security guard killed in the April accident, 35-year-old
David Sanes, was the first civilian casualty since the training
exercises began, but Puerto Rico officials say there have been
close calls over the years. In 1993, the officials say, a plane
dropped five bombs, four of which detonated within Navy property
but about a mile from Isabel Segunda, Vieques' main town. In 1997,
a vehicle was hit by M-16 bullets in the municipal dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody would allow this in the United States,'' said Ruben
Reyes, a 34-year-old agronomist who lives here with his wife and
18-month-old son. ``I don't have a problem with the Navy, but it
seems illogical to me that they conduct exercises so close to
citizens. To them, we're cockroaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials say their practices have been conducted under
strict regulations to insure safety and the preservation of the
environment, and that they consider only one civilian death in
nearly 60 years of military exercises to be a safe record. The Navy
is conducting its own investigation of the April accident and has
suspended maneuvers in Vieques. President Clinton has appointed a
special federal panel to study the Navy's need for operations in
Vieques and possible alternatives. The panel's report is expected
by August.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, exercises continue in the Caribbean, 50 miles away,
where a battle group of 10,000 troops, two submarines, a dozen
destroyers and frigates and more than 20 F/A-18s and other attack
aircraft led by the carrier John F. Kennedy. Last week they
conducted air defense exercises on the high seas, simulating a
conflict in the Persian Gulf, spotting unidentified aircraft and
shooting at imaginary enemies.
</P>
<P>
   But to fully prepare for war, Navy officials on the Kennedy
said, they need Vieques, the only place where they can count on
nearly 200,000 square miles of uncongested air and sea space and
land for target and amphibious assault practice, allowing all
battle components to come together in a realistic scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only unencumbered place by air and sea next to land
targets,'' said Adm. Carlos Johnson, the battle group commander.
``There really is no other place.''
</P>
<P>
   Vieques also offers a sophisticated infrastructure, the
officials said, including an underwater training range between
Vieques and the U.S. Virgin Islands of St. Croix and St. Thomas for
submarines. The range is worth billions of dollars. A Navy
spokesman said it would be unlikely that kind of money would be
forthcoming to replicate Vieques somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Navy lost Vieques, carrier battle groups would deploy
with substandard training,'' said Capt. James Stark, commanding
officer at the Roosevelt Roads Naval Station in Ceiba, Puerto Rico,
to which the Navy range in Vieques belongs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the Navy's exercises do not question the need for
the training but they argue that Vieques has had enough of it.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 9 letter to Rossello, Clinton stressed that the small
island was ``a vital part of our national defense and regional
security readiness training.'' Vieques is the biggest training
range for the Atlantic Fleet and has provided training for the
United States and its allies since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say there are a dozen other Navy live-fire ranges _
two in Florida serve the Atlantic fleet, 10 in Nevada, Washington,
Alaska, California, Arizona and Hawaii serve the Pacific fleet _
and that some were as close to population centers as the Vieques
range. But only here does the Navy conduct large-scale exercises
involving all Navy war resources and only here has the Navy's
presence been entangled with the politics of a U.S. territory where
a small segment of its 3.8 million residents want independence and
consider the military a symbol of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to the heart of the United States control over Puerto
Rico,'' said Ruben Berrios, a senator and president of the Puerto
Rican Independence Party who is among the protesters camped out in
the practice range here. ``We see this as the great opportunity to
correct a historic injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy acquired lands and began training in Vieques and a
smaller island, Culebra, in the early 1940s, when Puerto Rico's
governors were appointed by Washington, and before the autonomous
commonwealth status was granted by the United States in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy acquired three-fourths of Vieques, about 26,000 acres,
squeezing its then 10,000 residents between restricted federal
property that includes the 800-acre live-impact area at the eastern
tip of Vieques and an ammunition storage area at the western end.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Navy training has ignited protests,
blockades by fishing boats, brawls between off-duty sailors and
local residents, and a federal lawsuit by the governor of Puerto
Rico in 1978 asserting that the shells and bombs were endangering
Vieques' residents and destroying coral reefs, sandbars, wildlife
and other natural resources. (Similar protests had led the Navy to
stop exercises in Culebra in 1975.)
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit led to a memorandum of understanding between the
government of Puerto Rico and the Navy in 1983 that committed the
Navy to promote economic development in Vieques and undertake
conservation measures to protect endangered species like sea
turtles and the brown pelican. But 16 years later, Rossello's
commission found that little of what the memo called for had been
achieved and that the Navy's presence had hampered economic growth.
The commission said that lagoons and forests have disappeared and
mountains and coastline have been disfigured. Commissioners said
there was also evidence that materials like TNT from explosives had
infiltrated potable water reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're suffering a slow death,'' said Manuela Santiago, the
mayor of Vieques and a member of the governor's commission. The
small island lags behind the rest of Puerto Rico, with 73 percent
of its population living in poverty, compared with 58 percent in
the rest of the commonwealth. Vieques residents have no airplane or
ferry service at night, no stoplights, no movie theater and no
hospital, ``not even a Burger King,'' one resident noted.
</P>
<P>
   But Vieques attracts about 4,000 tourists a year, drawn to its
pristine beaches, bioluminescent bays and slow pace. Small cruise
ships stop here and a new 155-room luxury resort is to open in
December, creating 200 jobs. The municipality is also expanding its
airport on land donated by the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Puerto Rican and white flags for peace flutter from car
antennas all over Vieques. Signs reading ``Navy Out of Vieques''
and ``Civilian sectors off limits for all military personnel and
friends'' have sprung up on streets. Navy officials have restricted
the movement of its uniformed personnel outside their property but
to avoid a confrontation, they said, have not arrested any of the
trespassing protesters. Instead, they have posted a medical team to
stand by in case any of the demonstrators accidentally sets off an
explosion in the range.
</P>
<P>
   Sanes' death led Puerto Rico's three political parties to come
together against the Navy's presence here in a rare display of
unity, joined by religious, environmental and other groups. A
Fourth of July march in front of the Roosevelt Roads Naval Station
in Cieba drew more than 12,000 people according to Navy estimates,
and up to 50,000 according to the Puerto Rican police. The Puerto
Rico Legislature recently allocated $100,000 for an epidemiological
study into Vieques' cancer rate, which is 27 percent higher than in
the rest of Puerto Rico, and the government is preparing for legal
action as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional presentation of the governor's commission report
last week, Secretary of State Norma Burgos choked back tears to
apologize on behalf of the government of Puerto Rico to the
residents of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one way or another,'' Ms. Burgos said, ``we've all been
responsible for what's happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
