<HEADER>
A4850 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-MIR-BOS &LR;      07-09 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISCAL STRESS MAY FINISH OFF MIR SPACECRAFT EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ They tried putting Mir up for sale and offering a $100
million cosmic joy ride to a shadowy British businessman. They
tried asking the Russian public to pitch in to help keep the aging
space station in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   But none of the frantic fund-raising ideas dreamed up by
officials from the Russian space agency could save the country's
beleaguered, beloved orbital craft. This spring, Russia announced
it would leave Mir unmanned beginning in August, and then discard
it early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, an untimely spat between Russia and its fellow former
Soviet neighbor Kazakhstan is threatening to finish off Mir sooner,
and more dramatically, than anyone here expected.
</P>
<P>
   Picture an out-of-control, 130-ton fireball careening toward
who-knows-where on Earth. This, Russian space officials say, is a
potential consequence of Kazakhstan's abrupt decision this week to
ban all launches at the Baikonur Cosmodrome, the chief launch site
for Russian space missions.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan, which inherited the Baikonur site when the Soviet
Union collapsed and has leased its services to Russia, announced
the ban after a Proton booster rocket carrying a Russian military
satellite exploded shortly after takeoff Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan officials said the explosion showered a desolate
region of this vast Central Asian land with toxic heptile rocket
fuel. They said the launch site would be closed until a commission
figures out the extent of the damage to the environment and
determines whether other launches will be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan Friday prevented Russia from sending a joint
Russian-Ukrainian weather satellite into orbit. But what really
worries Russian space agency officials is Wednesday's scheduled
launch of an unmanned supply ship carrying food and water for Mir's
crew _ and a new navigation system vital to the plan for a
controlled reentry into Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Russian officials said the Mir crew _ cosmonauts Viktor
Afanasyev, Sergei Avdeyev, and French astronaut Jean-Pierre
Heignere _ will have to abandon the station next Saturday if they
do not receive fresh supplies of food and equipment. Without the
navigation system to guide it, mission control will be unable to
control Mir's descent toward Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that equipment isn't delivered at a certain time, the crew
obviously won't be able to install it,'' Russian Space Agency
spokesman Sergei Gorbunov said Friday. ``The procedure of lowering
the station's orbit will be ruptured.''
</P>
<P>
   Gromov said Kazakhstan's ban would make it much more difficult
to ensure the safe return that ground control was planning. The
idea was to direct the station _ which will ignite when it reenters
the atmosphere _ over a desolate area of the ocean and let it fall
into the water. Last month, a group of 31 leading space designers
and engineers here issued a statement saying that without guidance
equipment, there was no guarantee where Mir's fiery remains would
come down.
</P>
<P>
   That does not necessarily mean anything terrible will happen.
The US space station Skylab killed a cow in Australia when it fell
to Earth in 1979. And in February, 1991, Russian ground controllers
lost control of the 40-ton Salyut-7 space station, which crashed in
the Andes Mountains but caused no injuries or damage.
</P>
<P>
   Mir, whose planned five-year lifespan was supposed to end in
1991, was supposed to finally come down this summer so that Russia
could focus its energies, and limited funds, on helping the United
States and other countries build the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian officials have recently balked at giving up on Mir,
their unique contribution to space exploration. Western
commentators may dismiss it as a busted-up space jalopy, but for
Russians, especially the engineers who worked on it, Mir is still a
source of national pride. The way they see it, nothing better
epitomizes the Russian talent for resourceful resilience in the
face of hardship than that aging hunk of junk orbiting the earth,
years past its expected lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find the financing to keep Mir in space, Russian space
officials tried to sell shares in the station to China, but that
deal fell through when Beijing decided to focus on its own space
program. Then they offered to let British entrepreneur Peter
Llewellyn take a ride on Mir for $100 million. Llewellyn, it was
later revealed, had faced swindling charges in the United States,
and he backed out of the deal, too. And an appeal by a veteran
cosmonaut for Russians to invest in their space station brought
little support.
</P>
<P>
   Money seems to be at the root of the dispute with Kazakhstan, as
well. Russian officials have been trying to get Kazakhstan to lift
its ban on rockets, such as the Soyuz that would carry the supply
ship to Mir, that do not use the toxic heptile fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan has so far refused, causing the newspaper Segodnya to
speculate, under a banner headline that read ``Cosmic Blackmail,''
that the Kazakhs were using the ban as an excuse to bring up the
issue of Russia's $300 million in late payments for the use of
Baikonur.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakhstan's Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Pavlov, who is
heading the investigation of this week's crash, seemed to confirm
that theory, criticizing Russia during a news conference Friday for
failing to pay its debts and demanding that Moscow at least pay
damages for the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
