<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING ON CISNEROS TAPES NEARS END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An acrimonious three-week hearing to determine
whether secretly taped phone conversations can be used in the trial
against former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros neared an end
Friday when lawyers agreed to wrap up next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stop the bombing now,'' U.S. District Judge Stanley
Sporkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge set Thursday for final testimony and closing arguments
on whether portions of the tapes should be played to jurors who
will hear the government's conspiracy case against Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin has hinted he may allow the tapes into evidence, but he
has voiced concern about the amount of editing on some of them and
privacy issues swirling around the release of those involving third
parties.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes, though, are the heart of Independent Counsel David
Barrett's case against Cisneros, who is accused of concealing from
the FBI $250,000 in payments to a former lover to protect his
nomination to head the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
Barrett's investigation has cost $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros and two former HUD aides, John Rosales and Sylvia
Arce-Garcia, have pleaded not guilty to the charges in a 21-count
federal indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Jones of Lubbock, Texas, who carried on an extramarital
affair with Cisneros before he joined the Clinton administration,
is the government's star witness. She told the court she began
taping Cisneros when he was being considered by President Clinton
for the HUD job.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Jones said, Cisneros had begun to reconcile with his
wife. Jones, unemployed and then living in Lubbock, feared public
scrutiny of his HUD nomination would end his pledge to pay her
$4,000 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Jones admitted buying a ``boom box'' and making duplicates of
the tapes, throwing the originals into the trash. She also said she
tampered with about 10 tapes, deleting embarrassing information and
her threats to Cisneros to expose him to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this week's testimony focused on those alterations and
her claims that her two lawyers in Lubbock, Bruce Magness and Floyd
Holder, instructed her to ``scrub'' the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers have flatly denied her allegations, prompting
Sporkin on Thursday to consider bringing her back to the stand for
a fifth day of testimony, but that now appears unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Jones sued Cisneros to force him to honor his verbal promise of
financial support. The suit was later settled out of court for
$49,000.
</P>
<P>
   Magness engineered a plan to sell the story of her love affair
with Cisneros to the news media. He said he hoped the media
strategy would pressure Cisneros to settle the lawsuit and would
fuel deals for a movie and a book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make money,'' admitted Magness, who eventually
earned less than $10,000 for representing Jones and ended up before
a federal grand jury for 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   Jones pleaded guilty to a 28-count indictment charging her with
money laundering and bank fraud for purchasing a home with
Cisneros' payments that were funneled throug a sister and
brother-in-law. Jones is serving a 3-1/2-year prison sentence at a
medical center in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said she attempted suicide, became addicted to
prescription medicine and suffered from bouts of depression after
her extramarital affair with Cisneros became public in the late
1980s when he was mayor of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   She has agreed to testify against Cisneros in exchange for a
reduction in her sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is the second Clinton Cabinet member to face trial on
charges of unethical behavior. Former Agriculture Secretary Mike
Espy was acquitted in December 1998 on charges of bribery and
accepting illegal gratuities.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was housing secretary from 1993 to 1996. He is
currently president of the Los Angeles-based, Spanish-language
network Univision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
