<P>
   (Lede story)
</P>
<P>
   ADM-EXECS-SENTENCED (Chicago) _ Mark Whitacre, a former Archer
Daniels Midland Co. executive who secretly recorded his colleagues
conspiring to fix prices of a widely used livestock feed additive,
was sentenced to 30 months in prison Friday for his participation
in the scheme. Two other executives, including the son of the
chairman of the food-processing giant, were sentenced to two years
in federal prison and fined $350,000 each. By Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Top display)
</P>
<P>
   SPICE-TRADE (Singapore) _ On a clear day, Singaporeans can see
recession-wracked Indonesia from their southern shore. From their
living room, Seah Soo Lin and his son Jeng Jye can smell the
archipelago's budding recovery. Cinnamon, pepper, nutmeg and
cloves: an aromatic bounty sits packed in a jumble of cardboard
boxes on the floor. Outside on the patio, sandalwood chips are
piled into a mound on a table. For the last 30 years, Seah's small
family-run company, Chop Wee Kiat, has traded Indonesian spices and
fragrant woods, buying in places like Timor and Sumatra and selling
to customers from Bahrain to Tokyo. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-GROCER-EXPAND (San Francisco) _ Only a month ago, Webvan
Group Inc., a Silicon Valley startup that sells groceries online,
was taking its first orders from customers. Friday it placed a
sizable order of its own, asking Bechtel, the engineering and
construction giant, to build distribution and delivery centers in
26 markets. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Bottom)
</P>
<P>
   WEBSTOCKS-QUIET-PERIOD _ The restrictions on quiet periods are
quite fuzzy. And while many companies and their underwriters
refrain from saying anything publicly during the time immediately
preceding and following initial public offerings, more companies
are saying more than they have in the past. Internet companies in
particular are eager to provide business progress reports and to
continue announcing deals. By Andy Wang.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
