u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-COMMISSION-NYT     07-09 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-COMMISSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN UNION'S PRESIDENT APPOINTS 19 NEW COMMISSIONERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Spain, Germany, China, Italy, Britain)   By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The new president of the European Union's Executive
Commission announced the appointment of 19 commissioners Friday,
promising ``a new era of change'' after the forced resignation of
the entire previous commission last spring after accusations of
corruption. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only four members are holdovers from that commission, which was
accused of cronyism and mismanagement by a panel appointed by the
elected European Parliament. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the outgoing commissioners, Martin Bangemann of Germany,
who was in charge of telecommunications, took a job last week with
Telefonica SA, a Spanish company he had been regulating. The 15
European Union ambassadors in Brussels recommended a court
challenge to his right to a $90,000 European pension. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the new commissioners is Chris Patten, a British
Conservative who supervised Britain's handover of Hong Kong to
China in 1997 with such a vigorous defense of autonomy for the
former colony that China let it be known that it would not be happy
if he were put in charge of European Union trade relations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he got the job of managing the European Union's
relations with foreign countries, including China. But Patten will
not speak for the European Union on defense and security issues.
Coordinating those will be Javier Solana of Spain, now secretary
general of NATO, who will report directly to the 15 European Union
heads of state and is not a member of the commission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The commission's new president, Romano Prodi of Italy, gave the
trade post to Pascal Lamy, a French Socialist and a career
technocrat who was chief of staff to one of the best known
commission presidents, Jacques Delors, from 1985 to 1994. Lamy
replaces Sir Leon Brittan, a British Conservative whom the French
often accused of being too close to American trade views, though
that was hardly the view in Washington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guenter Verheugen, a German Social Democrat who has been his
country's deputy foreign minister for the last nine months, will
manage the key issue of expansion. Five formerly Communist
countries and Cyprus are on the short list to join the European
Union, and talks with five other European states are also under
way. But the earliest any of them are likely to get in is several
years from now, officials say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prodi gave the job of monetary affairs, including the European
Union's new common currency, the euro, to a former finance minister
of Spain, Pedro Solbes. France did not renominate Yves-Thibault de
Silguy, the centrist Conservative who managed the introduction of
the euro at the beginning of this year. It was worth $1.17 then and
is worth about $1.02 now, though no one has accused him of being
responsible for the decline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He had to go because France gets only two commission seats and
France's Socialist government wanted to name a Socialist, Lamy, to
an important job in Brussels after former Prime Minister Edith
Cresson, a Socialist, was disgraced last March when she resigned
with the other commissioners. President Jacques Chirac, who is
conservative, decided to sacrifice de Silguy and instead nominate
Michel Barnier, a Gaullist who was France's european affairs
minister from 1995 to 1997. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prodi put Barnier in charge of regional affairs, distributing
some of the $100 billion European Union budget to the relatively
disadvantaged corners of Europe. Half of the budget goes to farm
support, and Prodi renamed Franz Fischler, an Austrian, as
commissioner for agriculture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prodi, an economics professor who has also been prime minister
of Italy, was chosen by leaders of the 15 European Union countries
to replace Jacques Santer of Luxembourg as president of the
commission, which has a five-year term and has the job of managing
the policies the leaders decide on in their innumerable and
sometimes interminable meetings in the European capitals. The
commissioners, who work in Brussels, issue bureaucratic directives
that member countries often turn around and denounce as meddling.
The European Parliament, which indirectly forced the resignation of
Santer's commission, has insisted on the right to confirm Prodi's
new one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new Parliament was elected June 13, with around 50 percent of
the voters in France and almost 75 percent of voters in England not
interested enough to cast ballots, and it will hold hearings in
early September. Loyola de Palacio, a former Agriculture minister
of Spain and one of the four women on the commission, will handle
its relations with the Parliament, as well as transport and energy,
as a vice president. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most real power remains in the hands of the 15 member countries,
which after the usual backroom deals in each capital gave Prodi
nominees to choose from. Britain, Germany, Italy and Spain, in
addition to France, have the right to two commission posts apiece.
The 10 other countries get one each. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neil Kinnock, a Labor Party leader who left domestic politics
after losing the British election in 1992 and held the transport
portfolio on the commission from 1995 until this year, is a vice
president of the commission in charge of further administrative
reforms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was appointed, I promised I would start a new era of
change,'' Prodi said. ``It's what the commission needs. It's what
the European public has asked for. This is what I intend to
deliver, starting today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
