<HEADER>
A4876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORBES10-COX     07-09 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forbes introduces Georgia presidential campaign team
 &HT;    By Richard Whitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In front of a small group of supporters in the state
Capitol, Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes announced
his Georgia political team Friday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Barr (R-Marietta) will be honorary chairman of his
Georgia campaign. Barr also will co-chair the Forbes 2000 national
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Jokingly calling himself the only Republican candidate who can
match Vice President Al Gore in charisma, the staid editor-in-chief
of Forbes magazine promised a return to conservative government if
elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have in America a victory that matters,'' Forbes
said, calling for reforms in education, Social Security retirement
and federal tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps best known for his flat tax proposals, Forbes favors
abolishing the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   He urged supporters to visit his Web site, www.forbes2000.com,
``to see all that we're proposing.'' Forbes said he will work
aggressively in Georgia and across the country to deliver his
conservative message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to end the disconnect between Washington and the
American people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has sewn up support of
many heavy hitters in the Georgia GOP, Forbes praised his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This leadership team shows the depth of support enjoyed by my
candidacy in Georgia and the rest of the South. Anyone who thinks
that Republicans coronate their nominees has never encountered the
election-hardened men and women who stand on these stairs today,''
Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia co-chairs are: Thomas J. ``Jack'' Barnette, CEO of The
American State College; businessman William B. ``Bill'' Espy; Jerry
Keen, former chairman of the Christian Coalition in Georgia; civil
rights activist Alveda Celeste King; and Carolyn Meadows, RNC
National Committee Woman from Georgia. Russell K. ``Rusty'' Paul,
former two-term chairman of the Georgia GOP, will serve as
Southeastern political director for the national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have assembled a distinguished committee of solid and
dedicated conservative Republicans to lead an aggressive
grass-roots campaign for Steve Forbes in Georgia. This team is
second to none in experience and capability,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr introduced Forbes, praising him for his boldness and
willingness to take sometimes unpopular positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will lead a new generation of conservatives,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
