<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER MINI VAN LOADED WITH EXTRAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Chrysler's still on top of the minivan game, the
company that invented these front-wheel-drive people movers in 1984
still out in front of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of good minivans on the market today, getting
there mainly by copying the front-drive formula that Chrysler
pioneered. But the DaimlerChrysler versions have managed to remain
ahead in style, performance and comfort.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler Town and Country Limited is a unique entity, a
full-boat luxury minivan that would rival any top luxury car or
sport-utility vehicle. There's nothing else like the Town and
Country, which is aimed at an upscale niche in the minivan market
that has all to itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Limited is certainly not just for schlepping the kids off to
soccer practice or trundling the sheepdog down to the park. Now,
there are people who sneer at the very notion of a minivan,
considering their image as too domesticated and boring. But I think
even these prejudiced souls might appreciate the Town and Country's
cushy panache and superior road manners.
</P>
<P>
   The Limited is a long-wheelbase version of the ubiquitous family
of Chrysler/Dodge/Plymouth minivans, and it's loaded with comfort
features, convenience extras and stereo equipment. There is leather
seating for seven in the nicely appointed interior, dual climate
control up front, dual air-conditioning front and rear, and an
overhead console with trip computer and compass.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Chrysler minivans, there are plenty of cubbies and bins
for stowage. And, of course, a plethora of cupholders. Here's a
nice touch: hooks on the back of the rear seat designed to hang
plastic grocery bags.
</P>
<P>
   If usable space is the name of the game, then the Town and
Country has it licked. All six passengers will find more than
adequate leg, head and elbow room, even in the third seat. Much
appreciated by this tall driver was the leg, head and shoulder room
behind the wheel. For cargo, the long-wheelbase model has decent
space behind the third seat, often a failing in minivans.
</P>
<P>
   The middle bucket seats and rear seat are easy to remove but
heavy to carry. If you plan on taking one out, have someone to help
tote it into the garage. Honda's new Odyssey sets the tone for
convenience with its folding rear seat that drops down to form a
flat cargo floor.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the luxury sport utility vehicles that are clogging the
landscape, the Town and Country is stable on back roads and corners
as well as most sedans. The optional 3.8-liter V-6 is strong,
although the minivan's heft takes its toll on acceleration. Freeway
cruising and hill climbing are fairly effortless, but gas mileage
is not great.
</P>
<P>
   The Town and Country is front-wheel-drive, naturally, with
full-time all-wheel drive available as an option. Standard
equipment on the Limited include traction control, load leveling
and height control, and anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the big minivan (an oxymoron?) is attractively shaped
and smoothly aerodynamic, set off with a wide grille decorated with
Chrysler's winged emblem. The test van was sharp in anthracite gray
set off with gorgeous chrome-spoked 16-inch wheels and chrome door
handles. If ever there was a way to make a bulbous baby whale look
attractive, this is probably it.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the Town and Country has sliding passenger doors on
both sides. Here Chrysler slips behind by not offering powered
sliding doors, like some competitors. Kids struggle with these
doors, otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard is very attractive and well-finished, but it did
have one unusual feature that didn't work so well. Above the main
gauge area with the speedometer, gas gauge and other major bits,
there's a separate sliver of gauge space where all the warning
lights and turn-signal indicators are located. Problem is, the
steering wheel inevitably hid some of these important items.
</P>
<P>
   Our test minivan was equipped with white-faced gauges, an odd
touch considering they are usually associated with sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   Lest there be any doubt as to the reigning minivan king, the
latest generation of Chrysler vans are masterpieces of packaging,
well-planned out to be as practical and commodious as possible,
while holding the rising competition at bay. The Town and Country
Limited puts the gild on the lily. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Town and Country Limited &QL; 
Vehicle type: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seven-passenger, four-door minivan, front-wheel drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Base price: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $33,765. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $34,470. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Engine: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3.8-liter V-6, 180 horsepower at 4,400 rpm, 240 pound-feet of
torque at 3,200 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   Transmission: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four-speed automatic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Curb weight: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4,462 pounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wheelbase: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   119.3 inches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel economy: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   17 city, 24 highway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Highs:
</P>
<P>
   Roominess. Ride and handling.
</P>
<P>
   Lows:
</P>
<P>
   Premium price. Low gas mileage. &QL; 
