<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE GOVERNOR WELL GUARDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Looking more like Robert De Niro arriving at a
premiere than the governor of Massachusetts attending to state
business, Paul Cellucci squeezed through a security checkpoint at
the Paramount movie compound with three bodyguards in tow.
</P>
<P>
   When the studio executives saw the size of Cellucci's entourage
on his spring trip _ the three bodyguards and nine others _ they
rushed to find a bigger meeting room.
</P>
<P>
   There, the three guards moved to secure the premises, like
Secret Service agents combing a foreign embassy. Luckily, the room
had only two doors and there were three of them, a pair of
Massachusetts state troopers and one California Highway Patrol
officer, all packing guns under their plainclothes jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Mission: successful. Cellucci came home unharmed from his April
journey to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Two more trade missions overseas have confirmed Cellucci as one
of the most peripatetic governors in recent history. And now some
in the halls of government are wondering if the drum-tight security
is really necessary or just a way of repaying the loyal troopers,
who often sit in an unmarked car for hours while the governor dines
in a North End restaurant, who pick him up at 7 a.m. and drive him
home 14 hours later, and who hold the elevator for him outside his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Others insist that the security detail is just one of the
trappings of office that Cellucci seems to enjoy, unlike some of
his colleagues and predecessors. The five-day Hollywood trip _
complete with Cellucci's suite at the Beverly Hills Four Seasons _
cost taxpayers more than $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the size of Cellucci's security detail and
his willingness to bring it along on faraway missions has created a
potential image problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me he's more interested in being governor than
doing the work of the governor,'' said Jim St. George, executive
director of the Tax Equity Alliance for Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, some Cellucci critics say, the governor is the
opposite of Michael S. Dukakis, who was uncomfortable with the
trappings of office. When Dukakis was governor, he had only the
thinnest of security before running for president and regularly
used public transportation, rather than a State Police driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He enjoyed the trappings less than any governor in history,''
Republican media consultant Ray Howell said of Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is more of a retail politician who lives for
interaction with the public, Howell said. ``(William F.) Weld lived
for the chess game part of the business. And Paul loves when the
Girl Scouts come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his defenders say Cellucci's desire to go among the
people necessitates greater security. Besides, they say, the real
beefing up of bodyguards began under Weld. And Cellucci, endorsed
by the State Police in the last election, has kept up the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, other governors make do with less. Governor Lincoln
Almond of Rhode Island has just one State Police driver, who also
serves as his bodyguard. The same goes for Governor Jeanne Shaheen
of New Hampshire and Governor Angus King of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd shake them if he could. He hates entourages,'' said
King's spokesman, Dennis Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cellucci press aide Jason Kauppi insists that the
governor's security detail is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the potential for a threat against him,''
Kauppi said. ``It's standard for governors across the country to
have security details, whether they are at home or traveling. Even
just a regular day here, every place the troopers take the
governor, it's their second time going there. They scout the
entrances, check with local police about the potential for protests
or threats.''
</P>
<P>
   One night, Kauppi recalled, Cellucci was leaving a campaign stop
at J. J. Foley's Cafe, a South End bar, when his car was attacked
by union picketers who supported Scott Harshbarger in the
governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was an incident Nov. 4 during Cellucci's victory
speech, when three death penalty opponents stormed the stage at the
Park Plaza. They were stopped before they reached the stage.
</P>
<P>
   But the job may not be tedious for the troopers staking out
hallways. In Hollywood, the hotel (Four Seasons, Beverly Hills) and
the stargazing (Leonardo DiCaprio et al) were top notch.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, State Police Sergeant James Hanafin _ who was one
of the Hollywood hall monitors, along with Trooper John Cahill _
found himself at the Paris Air Show, protecting Cellucci on yet
another trade mission.
</P>
<P>
   Hanafin supervises the Executive Protection Unit, which has one
female and six male troopers specially trained by the Secret
Service to guard Cellucci and Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift at
every official event and drive them to and from the State House.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Dichio _ known affectionately as Deech within the
governor's circle _ accompanied Cellucci for the entire eight-day
trade mission to Paris and Ireland, which ended last weekend.
Although no one in the governor's office wants to say that Deech is
Cellucci's favorite, he has been around the longest.
</P>
<P>
   Hanafin and Dichio did the French leg, while Dichio met up with
Trooper Stephen Howard for the Irish stretch, with backup from
police in Belfast and assistance from the US embassy in France.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the governor's press office bristle at the
suggestion that these trips are junkets for the troopers, whose
expenses are paid by the State Police. In six months, taxpayers
have already spent more than $10,000 sending Cellucci's troopers on
out-of-state and foreign trips with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State Police makes the determinations as to who and what's
needed in terms of security,'' said Cellucci spokeswoman Ilene
Hoffer. ``I shouldn't say the governor doesn't have a say. If there
were particular concerns, those would be expressed. But the final
decision-making is with the State Police, obviously in coordination
with the governor himself and sometimes with the chief of staff.''
</P>
<P>
   The troopers do not get overtime while traveling.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's staff says the travel assignements are based not
on loyalty or hard work, but on a rotation, one for domestic trips
and one for international trips, which Hanafin oversees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's whoever it falls to,'' said Kauppi. ``All the trips are
work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
