 Friday, July 9, 1999    
 Editors     
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service has filed or will file the following for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Adds: GORE-UNITY; TEXAS-COCAINE; WWI-VETERANS; AMTRAK; SUNBURN;
COMPUTING; HELPLINE; BBN-ASTROS.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Syracuse, N.Y.) _ First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton wraps up her first solo foray into the campaign for a
Senate seat from New York. Ducking ducks specifics on hot-button
issues in the Mohawk Valley, she returns to the White House with a
spiral notebook full of handwritten reminders for follow-up
research. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Also filed in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-UNITY (Seattle) _ Vice President Al Gore calls public
schools ``a national emergency'' and proposes that all schools, old
and new, be wired for Internet access. Gore addressed a conference
of minority journalists a day after Texas Gov. George Bush made an
unexpected visit to the conference. By JOANN ZUNIGA.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Torrance, Calif.) _ President Clinton urges
Congress to put partisanship aside and approve a ``bill of rights''
for patients. While praising Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott for
agreeing to bring the issue up for debate next week, the president
criticized GOP leaders for pushing a bill limiting the number of
Americans covered, for providing insufficient protections and for
weak enforcement provisions. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-COCAINE (Austin, Texas) _ Secondary school students along
the Texas-Mexico border are more likely to have tried cocaine than
their peers in the rest of the state, according to a survey by the
Texas Commission on Alcohol and Drug Abuse. Cocaine use among all
Texas secondary school students increased by 40 percent between
1988 and 1998, according to the study. By JAIME CASTILLO. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WWI-VETERAN (Houston) _ The French consul in Houston belatedly
presents the Legion of Honor medal to an American veteran of World
War I, Thomas J. Clark. When other Texas veterans received this
award last year, Clark, who is 102, was overlooked. By BOB TUTT.
</P>
<P>
   AMTRAK (Houston) _ The driver of a tanker truck that crossed
into the path of an Amtrak passenger train, derailing it and
injuring 18 people, faces potential charges for running a stop sign
as he approached the tracks, a spokesman for the Texas Department
of Public Safety says. By PATTY REINERT (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SUNBURN (Houston) _ Twenty-nine inmates at Texas jail in Humble
have filed a federal civil rights lawsuit claiming they were forced
to sit in a prison yard in blistering heat for more than six hours
and suffered severe sunburn. By ED ASHER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CONRAD-OBIT (Houston) _ The exuberant Gemini astronaut Charles
P. ``Pete'' Conrad, who was the third man to walk on the moon, dies
in California after a motorcycle accident. He was 69. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BABBITT-INDIANS (Washington) _ Testifying before a federal
judge, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt defends his department's
efforts to fix trust accounts created for the benefit of American
Indians, who have sued the government for allegedly mismanaging or
losing billions of dollars from the funds. By MARK HELM. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-HEARING (Washington) _ The acrimonious three-week
hearing to determine whether secretly taped phone conversations can
be used in the conspiracy trial against former Housing Secretary
Henry Cisneros nears an end, with lawyers agreeing to wrap up next
week. ``We can stop the bombing now,'' U.S. District Judge Stanley
Sporkin says. By GARY MARTIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTING (Undated) _ Two notebook computers perfectly
illustrate the agony and the ecstasy at both ends of the size
spectrum. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HELPLINE (Undated) _ How to deal with icon clutter on your
Windows 98 desktop. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-MIA-HAMM (Austin, Texas) _ Bill and Stephanie Hamm, parents
of a star of American soccer, head to Pasadena, Calif. On Saturday,
they'll become a part of the largest women's sports event in recent
history _ the Women's World Cup soccer championship at the Rose
Bowl. And their daughter, Mariel Margaret ``Mia'' Hamm, had a major
hand _ make that foot _ in making the World Cup a global
phenomenon. By ARTHUR GARCIA. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Interleague play returns as the
Houston Astros open a three-game weekend series against the Kansas
City Royals. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-VOTE (Washington) _ It's early in the presidential
campaign, but already Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President
Al Gore are slugging it out over a key constituency: Hispanic
voters. We explore Bush's courtship of Hispanics and wedge issues
that the Democrats are using against him to retain Hispanic
support. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   PATIENTS'-RIGHTS (Washington) _ When the Senate this week
considers regulating managed health care, the debate is expected to
focus on questions of who should decide what medical treatment is
appropriate _ and what a patient unhappy with the decision can do
about it. The debate pits Senate Republican leaders, insurers and
business groups opposing more regulation of the health industry
against Senate Democratic leaders, consumer groups and the American
Medical Association. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ With only 18 months left in his
eight-year presidency, Bill Clinton refuses to accept lame-duck
status. He is racing around the nation as though he were just
beginning his tenure rather than limping toward the end of it. With
much of his moral leadership squandered, he wants to improve his
legacy before leaving office _ if he can. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
(Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
</TEXT>
