<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Israel fears Palestinian false hopes
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Palestinian expectations following Israel's change of
government this week are dangerously high and need to be reduced to
more realistic proportions, the Israeli ambassador to the United
States said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palestinians need to understand that this is not a complete
change,'' the ambassador, Zalman Shoval, said during a visit to
Atlanta. ``It isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's new prime minister, Ehud Barak, has promised to
reinvigorate the search for peace in the Middle East. He embarked
at once on a tour of meetings with other world leaders _ scheduling
meetings with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on Friday,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Sunday and Jordan's King
Abdullah and President Clinton next week.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's vigorous peacemaking activities have made some people in
the region hopeful that peace, so long elusive, can now be quickly
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   But Shoval warned that negotiations to resolve a conflict that
stretches back 100 years, if not thousands, will be long and
difficult, and no one's hopes will be fulfilled completely.
</P>
<P>
   He worried particularly about excessively high expectations
among Palestinians _ hopes that prosperity and a state of their own
are just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians need to understand, Shoval said, that Barak will do
nothing to jeopardize Israel's security and that he will demand
that Palestinians greatly increase their compliance with previous
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The dashing of similarly inflated Palestinian expectations
following the signing of the Oslo peace agreement in 1993 may have
led to increased violence and even terrorism, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shape and limits of any Palestinian state _ a state Shoval
said he assumes will be anti-Western and anti-Israel _ have yet to
be negotiated. Shoval said, for example, that a Palestinian state
will not be able to form any military alliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to have Saddam Hussein in our back yard,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said that he wants to negotiate peace simultaneously
with the Palestinians and Syrian President Hafez Assad. But Shoval
sounded a note of caution with regard to Syria, too.
</P>
<P>
   He used Winston Churchill's description of Russia _ ``a riddle
wrapped in a mystery inside an enigma'' _ to describe Assad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what he really wants,'' Shoval said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, an agreement on the status of the Golan Heights, captured
by Israel in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, could be achieved if
Israel's water rights and security could be assured, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But assuring Israel's security in the event of an agreement
would require the long-term presence of troops from the United
States, or perhaps NATO, the ambassador said. Because even with
peace agreements, various countries in the region will still
distrust one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Middle East will continue to be a rather volatile area,''
Shoval said, ``a dangerous neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
