<SLUG> BC-TV-WOMEN'S-WORLD-CUP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALES NOT RUSHING TO WATCH WORLD CUP ON TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is it that women want anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Not from men. We'll leave that to Dr. Laura.
</P>
<P>
   From sports television.
</P>
<P>
   Here you have perhaps the best U.S. women's sports team ever
assembled _ at least since the gold medal-winning Olympic hockey
team in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   One that features some of the most intriguing personalities in
sport.
</P>
<P>
   One that's vying for a world's championship.
</P>
<P>
   One that's playing on national TV during the summertime when,
thanks to a raft of reruns on other channels, the viewing is easy.
</P>
<P>
   And still, women aren't watching Mia and Carla and Michelle and
Briana's bid for soccer's Women's World Cup in the numbers they
should.
</P>
<P>
   Viewership ratings for the games leading up to this afternoon's
final against China haven't been as high as they could be, in part,
because of the lack of interest in the team shown by women
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The seven Women's World Cup games on ESPN have drawn an average
of 1.45 percent of the households with cable (1.1 million homes),
and the 22 games on ESPN2 have averaged 0.54 percent (347,700
homes).
</P>
<P>
   Those are hardly boffo numbers, although ESPN executive vice
president Dick Glover said this week that the tournament ``has been
every bit as big an event as we had hoped and thought it would.''
Glover even called the World Cup ``a major milestone for women's
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in fact, Sunday's U.S.-Brazil match was the most-watched
soccer telecast ever on the network.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, overall, only about one-third of the World Cup viewing
audience has been women.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like women don't watch sports on TV. Two-thirds of the
viewers of figure skating events on ESPN, for example, are women.
And, as a percentage of total viewers, women watch NFL football
games as much as they've been watching the Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   So it will be interesting to see the ratings and audience
demographics for today's final, which airs locally on WFAA/Channel
8.
</P>
<P>
   On the hopeful side, the U.S. team, with players like Mia Hamm,
Carla Overbeck, Michelle Akers and Briana Scurry, has been getting
mondo publicity this past week or so, and not just through hair
products commercials. Women as well as men can't avoid the hype.
Maybe they'll tune in.
</P>
<P>
   From the skeptic's perspective, though, a soccer game in the
middle of a weekend afternoon isn't usually the kind of happening
likely to get male or female sports fans to give up a golf date or
a trip to the mall. Who really wants to sit around the living room
and watch soccer on a Saturday afternoon in July, except maybe
those of us trying to stay out of the heat? Clearly, this is a game
that would have its best chance on a weeknight in prime time, but
that isn't about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has been made of the U.S. team's ability to attract
sellout crowds for its games that have been played across the
country. Today, in Los Angeles, a crowd of 90,000 is expected.
Supporters of soccer and backers of women's sports say that's a
sign of the increased interest in both.
</P>
<P>
   Selling even 90,000 tickets to a one-time sporting event in a
big city where the event becomes a happening is an easier task,
though, than getting people to spend two or three hours at home
watching it on TV. But TV viewership is the truer measure of the
overall interest in soccer, and in women's sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazil-U.S. game last weekend was a positive sign. But if
that interest is really growing, we should see record ratings for
today's game, especially among women.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
