<SLUG> BC-CHARACTER-SCHOOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITAL TO GET SCHOOL THAT EMPHASIZES CHARACTER DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Victoria Nedd was looking for a way to keep her
12-year-old son Patrick out of gangs and away from drugs. Then in
early May, a flier arrived in her mailbox that she says had the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyde Leadership Public Charter School, based in New England,
is scheduled to open in the nation's capital in September and is
looking for students. The school values character development over
ability, and effort over achievement _a teaching style adapted from
the school's predecessors in Bath, Maine, and Woodstock, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're from the inner city, you're always hoping that
something will help your child out,'' said Nedd.
</P>
<P>
   When Nedd decided to enroll Patrick in the seventh grade at
Hyde, she was seeking smaller classes, individualized attention,
and more family involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Although she said her son has always excelled in school, Nedd
was also concerned about peer influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when someone's going to suck one of your
children into selling drugs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nedd wasn't alone. The parents and guardians of more than 140
students in the Washington area, many unhappy with the public
schools here, have chosen to send their children to Hyde. School
officials are reviewing applications throughout the summer and
expect to fill the 240 spots allotted for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three years ago, Joseph Gauld founded the Hyde School, a
private boarding school in Bath for ``students who were getting
lost in the shuffle.'' Gauld's educational approach focused more on
the student's character and effort than achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyde school curriculum, which is trademarked as Character
First, departs from traditional emphasis on grades or test scores.
Gauld believes how hard a students tries is just as important as
any test result.
</P>
<P>
   At Hyde, students receive two grades _ one for effort and the
other for achievement. Students are encouraged to help other
students with school work, and they are all required to play a
sport to foster teamwork. There is no such thing as class rank, but
an honor roll for effort is posted every week.
</P>
<P>
   Five words have adorned the school shield since its founding _
courage, integrity, leadership, curiosity, and concern _ to remind
students what they should strive for throughout their lives. And to
help them explore their abilities and goals, students are reminded
to ask themselves a list of questions: Who am I? What am I capable
of? What's holding me back? How do I get where I want to go?
</P>
<P>
   Gauld's approach has paid off _ 97 percent of the graduates from
the Bath school move on to four-year colleges, and over the years
his teaching style has garnered national attention from television
programs such as ``60 Minutes'' and ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach works because when you focus on a person's
unique potential, you gain their deepest motivation,'' Gauld said
in a phone interview from Bath.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Gauld set up a public magnet school in New Haven,
Conn., and in 1996, he founded another boarding school in
Woodstock, Conn. The school in Washington is the first public
charter school that Gauld has founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show that what is done in a private boarding school
can also be done in a public day school,'' Gauld said.
</P>
<P>
   The school in Washington is currently accepting students for
grades 7 through 9 but plans to expand each year. For the next
academic year, the school will accept up to 420 students in grades
5 through 10. The year after that, the school will take in 570
students in grades 4 through 11. By the year 2003, the school is
hoping to enroll 1,050 students in kindergarten through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Academic requirements will be similar to those at the Bath and
Woodstock schools. In addition to the usual math, science and
English courses, the curriculum will include classes in the
performing arts and athletics, as well as a community service
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Don MacMillan, headmaster of the Hyde School in Washington, said
he hopes the school's focus on character will bolster the
self-esteem and confidence of his students _ enough to keep them
out of gangs and away from drugs.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to create a school where students support, not
pressure, each other. When teens have the support of their peers,
they will be less likely to try drugs or join gangs, MacMillan
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
