<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-COMPUTERS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta's new computer system to speed up check-in
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A major technology overhaul at Delta Air Lines is
arriving at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   The airline is rolling out a new check-in computer system
designed to speed passenger processing, shrink lines and give
agents more time to focus on solving customer problems.
</P>
<P>
   Delta this week finished installing the system on concourse D at
Hartsfield International Airport and plans to have the rest of its
gates at the airport converted by this Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The systems are a key part of a sweeping $500 million upgrade of
the airline's information technology systems, some of which still
employ 20-year-old hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Executives and workers alike say check-in computers were
outdated, hindering the carrier's efforts to deal with passenger
loads.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could put the old computer in the Smithsonian,'' said
concourse D gate agent Dana Godfrey, who called the new system ``a
huge improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta put off big technology upgrades during the early '90s,
when the airline was losing money and restructuring its in-house
computer support division. The division, now a subsidiary called
Delta Technology, developed the software in the new system.
</P>
<P>
   A push to rebuild Delta's business technology was among the
first goals outlined by Chief Executive Leo Mullin when he was
hired in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The updated check-in system also uses new Hewlett-Packard PCs
and beefed-up data networks. Officials say it lays the foundation
for other changes in passenger processing still in the planning
stages.
</P>
<P>
   They include automated rebooking of passengers who miss
connecting flights, along with self-serve check-in kiosks designed
to cut down on lines at counters and gates, said Walter Taylor, a
Delta Technology vice president.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the main focus is on getting the new system up and
running at Hartsfield, Delta's primary hub.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the old system and the one being
installed is akin to the difference between DOS and Windows on a
home computer.
</P>
<P>
   The old system, like DOS, required agents to type in letter
codes to enter or retrieve information about passengers, seat
availability or the status of connecting flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could go digging for what they were looking for, but it
took time and a lot of keystrokes,'' said Chip Houck, manager of
software development for the updated system.
</P>
<P>
   The new system uses a Windows-style display that gives agents
vital information at a glance, along with point-and-click control.
</P>
<P>
   A built-in magnetic stripe reader in the keyboard allows them to
swipe tickets or e-ticket receipts to check-in passengers, rather
than enter their names and information manually.
</P>
<P>
   Seat availability is shown graphically on a ``seat map.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants an aisle seat, we can see if it's available
without typing in anything,'' said gate agent Tomeshia Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   Boarding passes are slipped through a bar-code reader, which
automatically compiles passenger counts and alerts agents to
duplicate seat assignments or other anomalies. Flight attendants
will no longer have to help collect boarding cards at the door to
the jetway, freeing them for other preflight tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Delta test-deployed the system at several smaller airports so
glitches could be detected and fixed without affecting the hub.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Stallings, a 33-year veteran passenger service coordinator
at Hartsfield, said some older agents have had predictable gripes
about switching to a new system. But he said he's become a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, we spent all our time counting and recounting boarding
passes and beating the keyboard to death,'' said Stallings. ``This
should allow for more eye-to-eye customer contact.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
