<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONRAD-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTORCYCLE CRASH INJURIES FATAL TO APOLLO ASTRONAUT CONRAD &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By MARK CARREAU
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Apollo astronaut Charles ``Pete'' Conrad, the third
human to stroll on the moon and later a force in the continuing
efforts to develop low-cost, reusable commercial rockets, has died
of injuries sustained in a California motorcycle accident. He was
69.
</P>
<P>
   A former naval aviator, Conrad logged four sometimes harrowing
spaceflights as part of NASA's Gemini and Apollo programs,
including the first command of a U.S. space station.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the best spacecraft commander I could have hoped for,''
Joe Kerwin, a former astronaut who spent 28 days with Conrad aboard
NASA's Skylab space station in 1973, said Friday. ``He was just a
great team player. He was just a heck of a good communicator and
delegator. He was a good man to work for.''
</P>
<P>
   Space agency installations lowered their flags to half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has lost one of the great aviators and explorers of
the 20th century,'' said NASA Administrator Dan Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad died late Thursday at the Ojai Valley Hospital in Ojai,
Calif., northwest of Los Angeles, while undergoing surgery for
internal injuries sustained earlier in the day, according to James
Baroni, the deputy coroner for Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   A resident of Huntington Beach, a Los Angeles suburb, the former
astronaut was riding a 1996 Harley Davidson motorcycle as he
accompanied his wife, Nancy, and friends on a trip to Monterey.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad apparently lost control of the motorcycle on a winding
segment of highway near Ojai and was thrown off it. He was taken by
ambulance to a hospital in Ojai, where doctors discovered his
injuries included internal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   During surgery, Conrad was resuscitated after experiencing
cardiac arrest but finally died while in the operating room, Baroni
said.
</P>
<P>
   The astronaut's death comes just days before the 30th
anniversary of the Apollo 11 lunar landing, the July 16-24, 1969,
mission during which Americans Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin
became the first humans to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Among those early astronauts with whom I felt a very close
kinship, Pete was one of those at the top of the list,'' Aldrin
said Friday. ``Pete squeezed the most out of every opportunity to
expand our knowledge and operating skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's death leaves nine surviving Apollo moonwalkers. Al
Shepard, the first American to fly in space and the fifth to walk
on the moon, died July 21, 1998, following treatment for leukemia.
Jim Irwin, the eighth to wander the lunar landscape, died of a
heart attack on Aug. 8, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   After a distinguished career as a Navy test pilot, Conrad was
among NASA's second group of astronauts selectees, picked in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Assignments as co-pilot of the 1965 Gemini V mission and
commander of the 1966 Gemini XI mission, in which the crews
established flight duration, altitude and rendezvous milestones,
prepared Conrad for a lunar command.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo 12 blasted off Nov. 14, 1969, demonstrating quickly that
its predecessor did not own the franchise on drama. The spacecraft
was struck by lightning as it soared into the rain clouds, throwing
its electrical systems into turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   After the equipment settled down, NASA cleared Conrad and
colleagues Alan Bean and Richard Gordon to proceed. The lunar
module Intrepid touched down in the moon's Ocean of Storms, with
Conrad and Bean aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-9 Conrad lumbered to the surface of the moon in a
display of jocular wit and competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoopee!'' he exclaimed ``That may have been a small one for
Neil, but that's a long one for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months earlier, the taller Armstrong had electrified the
world as he stepped to the moon's surface for the first time and
announced, ``That's one small step for (a) man; one giant leap for
mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Apollo 12's crew returned safely to Earth after 31 hours on the
moon and two spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad returned to Earth orbit for a final time on May 25, 1973,
commanding Joe Kerwin and Paul Weitz as the first Skylab crew. A
converted Saturn V third stage, Skylab had been launched 11 days
earlier to serve as America's first space station.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   During its ascent, however, the Skylab lost an electrical power
generating solar array and heat shielding.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's crew in a separate spacecraft mounted a suspenseful
rescue and then spent a record 28 days aboard the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the mission proved dramatic as Conrad, before
attempting to dock with the space laboratory, gingerly maneuvered
his Apollo capsule up to the jammed solar array on Skylab. With
Kerwin securing his legs, Weitz leaned from the open capsule,
attempting unsuccessfully to pull the solar array free.
</P>
<P>
   When it was clear the scheme would not work, Conrad attempted
unsuccessfully to dock. Faced with the prospect of making a quick
return to Earth and an aborted mission, the three astronauts
managed to reconfigure their docking system and linkup.
</P>
<P>
   Once safely aboard, Kerwin recalled, Conrad enjoyed regaling his
colleagues with an account of how he should have been one of the
more famous Mercury astronauts. He would have been among the elite
group had a medical expert not misjudged his psychological
suitability for long term spaceflight, Conrad told his crew mates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt he had something to prove to the medical community. He
exercised harder than anyone else and strictly observed the dietary
restrictions,'' recalled Kerwin, now the senior vice president of
Wiley Laboratories in Houston. ``The message I got was that he
would show that guy who was psychologically fit, which he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks into their Skylab stay, Conrad and Kerwin teamed up
for a spacewalk that freed the jammed solar array, providing
much-needed power to America's first home in space.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Conrad left the space agency and NASA in 1974 to pursue a career
in business, first serving as vice president for a cable television
company.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, though, he was back in aerospace, joining McDonnell
Douglas Corp. and eventually taking on responsibility for the
commercial and military aircraft sales of the Douglas Aircraft Co.
Later, McDonnell Douglas merged with the larger Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Before his retirement in 1995, Conrad served as flight manager
for the DC-X, a futuristic prototype for a reusable rocket. Conrad
supervised flight tests in the New Mexico desert for the rocket,
which garnered a cult following.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement, Conrad formed his own company, Universal Space
Lines, with the hope of opening up space to commercial users.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Conrad's survivors include three sons.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
