<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4891 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-AR     07-09 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expectations are pretty high as the second-quarter earnings
season gets into full swing this week, with reports scheduled from
Intel, Apple Computer, International Paper, Merrill Lynch, Pfizer,
Whirlpool, Weyerhaeuser and others.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts who make forecasts for the 500 companies in
the Standard &AMP; Poor's stock index are predicting the first
double-digit growth in quarterly corporate earnings since the end
of 1997. IBES International, which tracks earnings, is forecasting
10 percent overall growth, based on its compilation of analysts'
predictions, while First Call Corp., the other leading compiler of
earnings, predicts 11.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the optimism is the gentleness of the pre-announcement
season, often a rocky run-up when many companies warn investors of
profit disappointments to come. There have been 270 negative
announcements so far, according to First Call; that total is no
worse than normal. The only ``blockbuster announcement,'' said
Chuck Hill, the director of research at First Call, was Compaq
Computer's warning in June that it expected a second-quarter loss
of as much as 15 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the number of downward revisions of analysts'
earnings estimates, which commonly occur before the beginning of a
reporting season, has been smaller than normal for the second
quarter. The current First Call forecast of 11.2 percent earnings
growth, compared with the second quarter last year, is down from
13.9 percent six months ago. That is a much smaller cut than in the
first quarter of this year, when the initial 14.3 percent forecast
was slashed to 5.7 percent. A trim of four percentage points is the
norm, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   And companies that have already reported earnings, including
General Electric, Yahoo and Alcoa, have provided good news.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has led Hill to suggest that by the time all the
second-quarter reports are in, the actual jump in earnings,
compared with the second quarter of 1998, will be closer to 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the numbers is reassuring in a period when
interest rates could move higher. The Federal Reserve, which has
already raised rates once, could raise them again later this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The good earnings prospects (analysts think that the third and
fourth quarters will be even stronger) also help investors live
with the fact that prices are high for many stocks, by historical
standards. According to IBES, stocks have been too pricey for 29
consecutive weeks, the longest overvaluation streak since before
the 1987 crash.
</P>
<P>
   But remember that a lot of the punch in the earnings numbers is
not from a new surge in growth, but from a rebound from setbacks _
or even sharp losses _ in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For example, General Motors, according to IBES estimates, will
show a surge in operating earnings in the second quarter, to $2.55
a share, compared with 54 cents a share in the corresponding period
last year. (Operating earnings are adjusted to remove the impact of
write-offs and other one-time items and are therefore different
from reported earnings.)
</P>
<P>
   But the GM gain represents mostly a rebound from sales lost
during a strike that crippled production last year. Before cutting
estimates because of the strike, analysts expected GM to earn $2.27
a share in last year's second quarter. Without GM's sharp expected
gain, the overall IBES second-quarter growth forecast would drop to
8.8 percent from 10.2 percent, according to Joseph Abbott, United
States research manager at IBES.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is also expected to rebound, to operating earnings of 54
cents a share, from 33 cents in the period a year earlier, when
chip prices were being cut. Without Intel and GM, the IBES growth
forecast would be cut to 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Easy quarterly comparisons also help in the next two quarters.
GM is expected to surge again. And with oil prices 47 percent above
the average for the last two quarters of 1998, energy sector
profits, according to First Call, should jump 39 percent in the
third quarter and 77 percent in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and brokerage firms also ought to do well in the third
quarter, compared with the disastrous results during the financial
turmoil that followed the Russian ruble devaluation and bond
default last August.
</P>
<P>
   So don't get too excited about the return to double-digit profit
increases.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
