<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-NEWSTART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR HILLARY CLINTON, A NEW BEGINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ In the middle of her maiden voyage across
upstate New York this week, Hillary Rodham Clinton suddenly began
to muse that the tour was marking not only the start of a possible
Senate campaign but the start of a new life _ the first time, after
nearly 25 years in her husband's aura, that she was striking out on
her own.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters, she noted that she has been a lawyer
speaking on behalf of clients and causes, a politician's wife and
First Lady speaking on behalf of her husband and other candidates.
But, she said, ``It is a different feeling to be the person who is
in the spotlight ... speaking on my own behalf.'' This tour, she
went on, ``was the first time I had ever done it ... I loved what I
did ... I had a wonderful time.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise of this Senate race _ already expected to
one of the tightest, best-funded, and most-watched contests of 2000
_ may be the emergence of a Hillary Clinton that few have ever
before seen.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the image has begun to shift. Shedding the emotional
armor she donned during a year of White House scandal, she has
plunged into crowds like a veteran campaigner. Famously versed in
policy details, she has spent much of her time asking her audiences
for their views and ideas. (She's calling this stage of her
campaign a ``listening tour.'')
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most remarkable, this woman with a well-honed aversion
to criticism _ particularly from the press _ started the trip by
acknowledging that her critics' most politically potent complaint _
that she's a ``carpetbagger'' who has never lived or worked in the
state _ has some validity.
</P>
<P>
   At every step along the way, from Oneonta to Cooperstown to
Utica to Syracuse to Albany and several still smaller towns in
between, Mrs. Clinton has gushed about how ``excited'' she was to
be there, how avidly she wanted to hear what people had to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a really good idea,'' she said Friday, at a high-tech
center in Rome, N.Y., when one businessman suggested subsidizing
developers for the cost of demolishing dilapidated factory
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I love these listening sessions _ I never would
have known about this,'' she beamed to a dairy farmer who talked
about the need for technical help in complying with federal
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm of the crowds clearly excited her,'' said
Judith Hope, chairwoman of the New York State Democratic Party.
``We always saw the spark; now we see the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   She has parted from President Clinton's views on some matters,
though carefully. At every forum, she has referred, at one point or
another, to a bill that ``my husband'' signed or proposed. However,
Friday, she endorsed the Northeast Dairy Compact, which would raise
prices for milk products _ while her husband's administration has
proposed a different method of helping dairy farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, before coming upstate, she also lobbied against a
provision in the president's welfare bill that would take away
money from New York's teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The election still lies 16 months away, and, one of her aides
said, she will continue well into the next year doing what she has
done this week -- speaking to small groups, showing that she knows
the issues of the state and wants to learn more.
</P>
<P>
   Once the press core dwindles _ and this was already happening by
the end of the tour Friday _ she also plans to campaigning going
door to door, a classic brand of ``retail politics'' that served
her husband well when he was a state office-seeker in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The explicit strategy is to build up enough exposure and enough
of a presence so that, by the time the debates begin and the
election heats up, she will know at least as much about New York as
any politician in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Patty Timmerman, a small businesswoman who attended one
gathering, said afterward, ``I'm a registered Republican, but I
think I'll vote for her. I didn't think I would before I came
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Mrs. Clinton running neck and neck statewide with her
likely Republican opponent, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _
clearly leading in the predominantly Democratic city then trailing
in the more conservative environs upstate and in the suburbs of
Long Island and Westchester counties.
</P>
<P>
   This is why she started her ``exploratory'' campaign upstate and
why, next week, she plans to tour the suburbs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
