<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-WORKPLACE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Concrete ceiling' stops minority career women
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Breaking through the ``glass ceiling'' that separates
most women from the top jobs in corporate America is tough enough.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to crack what minority women call a ``concrete ceiling''
is even harder _ enough so that those women have become more
pessimistic about their chances for advancement, a national report
due Tuesday will suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``While white women talk about a `glass ceiling,' women of color
perceive that the barriers they encounter, which they characterize
as a `concrete ceiling,' are more dense and less easily
shattered,'' a draft of the report by New York-based Catalyst says.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the third in Catalyst's three-year study of
minority women in corporate management. The first report covered
demographics. The second, released last year, contained preliminary
findings from a survey of more than 1,700 African-American,
Asian-American and Hispanic women managers and professionals
working for American companies.
</P>
<P>
   This year's report discloses how that group of women views the
companies for which they work, in terms of work environment and
diversity efforts.
</P>
<P>
   While nearly half of the minority women surveyed think
opportunities for them have increased over the last five years, 38
percent see no change. In fact, according to the draft, minority
women are ``questioning the wisdom of continuing to pursue a career
in the corporate private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   The major barriers they see to advancement, the report says,
are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lack of an influential mentor or sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lack of networking with influential colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lack of role models of the same race within a company.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lack of high-visibility assignments.
</P>
<P>
   White women see some of the same barriers, the draft report
says, but rank them differently in order of importance than do
minority women.
</P>
<P>
   Stereotyping of women by males and exclusion from informal
networks are cited by white women as being among the biggest
barriers to advancement. Minority women rank the absence of an
influential mentor at the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   The full report by Catalyst, which works to advance women in
business, will be released in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
