u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-LUNG-SCAN-NYT &LR;      07-09 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LUNG-SCAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMAND FOR CT SCANS SURGES AFTER STUDY FINDS EARLY DETECTION OF
LUNG CANCER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Minn, N.Y.)  (rk) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After reading Friday morning about a new study by
researchers at Cornell Medical Center showing that CT scans could
provide early detection of lung cancer in smokers and former
smokers, Richard Bauer called Cornell to find out when he could
have the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I can make arrangements, I'll be on the next
plane,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Many other people had the same idea. By midmorning, the voice
mail system at Cornell's chest scanning center in Manhattan was
full and could record no more messages. A secretary said that since
8 a.m., she had done little but answer calls from patients wanting
scans.
</P>
<P>
   New York University, which participated in the study, reported a
similar flood of calls. The Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., which
announced its own study of the scans a few weeks ago, received more
than 3,000 phone calls within a few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for appointments far exceeds our capacity,'' said
Dr. Stephen Swensen, chairman of the department of radiology at the
Mayo Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The study that provoked the excitement on Friday appears in the
current issue of The Lancet journal, a British medical publication.
In it, doctors from Cornell and New York University report that new
CT scan technology allows them to detect lung cancers early enough
for many of them to be successfully treated.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, doctors have not routinely screened people for lung
cancer because X-rays could not detect tumors in time to cure them,
or significantly prolong patients' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a 67-year-old former Navy pilot who lives in Vail, Colo.,
said he had smoked off and on since he was 18, ``probably never
more than a pack a day.'' He finally quit about 10 years ago, but
always wondered whether all those years of smoking would catch up
with him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   At annual physicals, he would ask his doctor if there was some
test that could find lung cancer early enough for it to be cured.
But the doctor would just shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea how much smokers wondered why there hasn't
been a diagnostic technique,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   For smokers or former smokers who want to be tested, Swensen
said that age 50 was a reasonable time to consider having a first
scan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidence of lung cancer starts rising dramatically at
50,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers cautioned that people need to understand what
they are getting into by having a scan. In the Lancet study, CT
scans of the lungs in 1,000 patients showed abnormal nodules in
233, nearly a quarter of the patients.
</P>
<P>
   Small nodules were not biopsied or removed immediately, but
patients were given a repeat scan a few months later. Only nodules
that grew were considered cancerous and referred for surgery.
Ultimately, just 27 of the 233 patients with nodules turned out to
have cancer.
</P>
<P>
   It is a cause for concern that so many patients had nodules,
said Dr. Barnett Kramer, deputy director of the division of cancer
prevention at the National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Though the doctors who conducted the study operated only on
patients with cancer, Kramer said it was not clear whether other
medical centers would be able to tell benign nodules from malignant
ones so accurately. If they cannot, he said, some patients may
needlessly undergo risky biopsies and operations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, some will be needlessly frightened. ``One
in four people will be told there is something to worry about,'' he
said. ``At the very least, if it doesn't lead to major surgery, it
will lead to coming in much more frequently, and living with the
abnormality.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer also said that though the lead author of the study, Dr.
Claudia I. Henschke of Cornell, had suggested that CT scans could
increase lung cancer survival from 12 percent to 80 percent, that
had not been proved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real goal is to save lives, and the study design in the
Lancet isn't really able to show definitively that it saves
lives,'' Kramer said. ``The gold standard is to do a randomized
trial, and compare the death rate of those who get screened to
those who don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of those concerns, he said, it was too early to
recommend widespread use of the CT scans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want to emphasize that we're excited,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David P. Naidich, director of thoracic imaging at New York
University Medical Center and a co-author of the Lancet study,
agreed that he and his colleagues had to determine whether the CT
scans really could save lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we will affect mortality, but it remains to be
proved,'' Naidich said. Until there is proof, he added, patients
who want scans should be told they are experimental.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said that insurers now refused to cover the
procedure, which costs about $300 per scan. Naidich said he thought
it would take three to five years to convince them that it was
worthwhile. And he and Henschke said they would like to see money
from lawsuits against the tobacco industry used to cover the cost
of screening for current and former smokers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
