<HEADLINE>
GORDON EARNS POLE POSITION IN JIFFY LUBE EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ All day long, Jeff Gordon gave chase to the
perfect lap, struggling to find the perfect line around the tricky
mile oval at New Hampshire International Speedway, only to discover
his No. 24 Dupont-sponsored Chevrolet Monte Carlo was a tick off
the pace during Friday's NASCAR Winston Cup practice session.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Gordon asked his crew chief, Ray Evernham, ``about
freeing it up,'' the three-time and defending Winston Cup champion
was caught by complete surprise when his car responded with a
record-shattering hot lap of 131.171 miles per hour that landed him
on the pole position for Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300 at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys on this team did a great job today,'' Gordon said,
saluting his Rainbow Warriors after he captured his sixth Bud Pole
Award of the season. ``We were really quick most of the day, but
never got that lap I needed. We just fine-tuned, fine-tuned all day
long. I talked to these guys, especially Ray, about freeing it up
just a little bit. Man, they did, and the car was just perfect. It
was so perfect, I didn't think the lap was that good.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be plenty good.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, a three-time winner at NHIS who became the fourth driver
in track history to win four pole positions (Mark Martin, Ricky
Craven, and Ken Schrader were the others), toppled Rusty Wallace
from the provisional pole, relegating him to the outside pole
position.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte qualified third fastest with Schrader fourth
fastest.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr., making his second of five scheduled Winston
Cup appearances this season, overcame a chipped right shoulder
blade to qualify 13th, just a tick faster than his father, who
qualified 14th fastest.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, driver of the No. 2 Miller Lite Ford Taurus, was first
out in the qualifying lineup and blistered the track with a lap of
130.770 m.p.h. that easily bettered Schrader's 2-year-old
qualifying record of 129.423 m.p.h. In all, 17 drivers wound up
surpassing Schrader's qualifying record, with Gordon establishing
the new standard with his pole-winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just went through the corners so nice that I thought I
didn't drive hard enough,'' Gordon said. ``At this place, it's
knowing when to be aggressive and when to be patient in qualifying.
You've got to be aggressively patient, and I'm really thrilled
about that run.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, was Wallace, who was mindful of the rotten luck that
had befallen many a driver in their early qualifying attempts at
NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``My car handled great and I was real happy with the speed,''
Wallace said. ``I had a lot of concern going into qualifying
because if you look at the history of this racetrack, everybody who
goes out early really has a tough time qualifying. I was talking to
the crew guys and I said, `Hey, nobody's been on the racetrack
since the last practice. It's pretty cool out and the track should
be pretty consistent. I'm just gonna have confidence in the track
and go out and drive hard.' And I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace took a decidedly different approach than Gordon's
``aggressively patient'' strategy when, he said, ``I just decided
to bomb it in there in the first turn like I had been doing in
practice, because if you're timid going into Turn 1, then you're
not going to have enough speed to contend for the pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Gordon, ``I'd been pushing most of the day and expected it
to do the same thing. I drove the car in pretty deep into (Turn)
one but was trying not to get in there too hot. The car turned
really nice for me in the middle and kind of caught me by surprise.
I got back on the gas and the thing drove off hard. I said, `All
right, this thing is really hooked up,' It was just one of those
deals where it didn't feel like it was a pole-type of lap.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was good enough to be perfect. Just perfect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tim Connolly of Endicott, N.Y., captured the pole position of
the NASCAR Featherlite Modified Series portion of Saturday's
Pennzoil/Replacement Auto Parts 100 doubleheader. Connolly
qualified in 130.327 to surpass outside pole sitter Mike Ewanitsko
of North Babylon, N.Y. . . . Tom Carey of Orange, Mass., captured
the pole for the Busch North Series event with a hot lap of 123.614
m.p.h. to start ahead of Brad Leighton of Center Harbor, N.H., the
runaway Busch North points leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
