</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REBUFFING-CDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT BUFF ENOUGH? PROCESS RESCUES SCRATCHED CDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ You promised yourself you would be good to
them.
</P>
<P>
   You promised you would keep them in their cases, away from the
kids, away from the dog, away from the litter box, away from your
sports-loving friends who come over and turn your place into Animal
House mistaking them for beer coasters.
</P>
<P>
   You are a liar.
</P>
<P>
   There you are, listening to your favorite Whiskeytown CD _ which
is, of course, ``Strangers Almanac'' _ and right when you get to
the part where singer Ryan Adams cries the chorus of Losering, you
hear this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Loo, loo, loo, ser, ser, ser, ing, ing, ing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's skip city.
</P>
<P>
   Infuriated, you pull the disc out of the player and freak when
you see little scars running down its back. Looks like someone bit
it, which explains why your kid just left the room. That's $17 down
the drain.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   If the scratch isn't too bad, there's a chance the disc can be
patched up and sound as good as new.
</P>
<P>
   This is thanks to a new service called ``rebuffing.'' said Craig
Crafton, manager of CDX used CD store in Hurst, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top layer of a CD is just plastic, and rebuffing basically
shaves off a very small amount of that plastic,'' he says. ``CDs
that have light scratches and scuff marks can be cleaned up to
brand-new quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all scratches are repairable, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Data is stored in the metal layer of a CD, so if a scratch
cuts through to the metal, it's history,'' Crafton says. ``CD
machine laser beams go through the plastic to read the data on the
metal. If there's too big a mark on the metal, the beam won't read
it. But most marks aren't that serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebuffing also works for CD-ROMs, DVDs and Sony PlayStation
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything on CD can be done,'' he says. ``It's all the same
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Crafton's store performs the service for $3-$4, depending on the
amount of damage. The discs are sent to an outside company, and it
takes about a week to get your CD back.
</P>
<P>
   Other stores, such as Sound Source in North Richland Hills and
the two CD Worlds in Dallas, have purchased the rebuffing units,
which can cost up to $10,000, and are performing the surgery
on-site.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have scratched CDs, so it's been great for
them,'' says Jeff Stout, owner of Sound Source CD shops in Bedford
and North Richland Hills. ``Rather than replace them, you can
repair them. It costs less than a third for a new CD.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound Source charges $4 a disc or $3 each for three or more
while you wait.
</P>
<P>
   Local entrepreneur Dave Gebhart and Fort Worth rock singer Ezra
Boggs were two of the first North Texans to take advantage of this
new technology. A year ago, they started a company called Disc
Doctors and began working with CD shops that needed their used CDs
repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Disc Doctors now offers the service to individual customers
through the CD Warehouse in Irving. They're hoping to expand to
other CD Warehouses, including the stores in Arlington and Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kind of stumbled on this technology,'' Gebhart says.
``We hadn't heard of anyone doing it before, so we gave it a shot,
and it's taken off. Obviously, we can't work miracles. If your CD
is cracked, it's hopeless. But we are changing our technology to
get the deeper stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Some CD owners may balk at rebuffing, choosing to stick to the
old-school way of repairing their discs: with polishes and creams.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, says Craig Crafton, but be prepared to have bigger
problems down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff doesn't really repair them,'' he says. ``It
temporarily fills in the scratches, but using that ... is kind of
reverse stupidity. You put that cream on your CD, it gets in your
CD player and it messes it up. So you have a CD that works, but a
player that doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
