<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4911 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAZI-ART-AUCTION-ART-     07-09 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZI-ART-AUCTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVELAND MUSEUM WAS THE BUYER OF MOST-PRIZED ROTHSCHILD PORTRAIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Britain, Austria)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Cleveland Museum of Art emerged Friday as the buyer
of the most prized painting in Thursday's blockbuster sale of
Rothschild family treasures: a Frans Hals portrait of a stern-faced
Amsterdam merchant that commanded $12.8 million, a record for the
artist.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, a three-quarter-length portrait of Tieleman
Roosterman bedecked in black with white ruffled collar and cuffs,
will go on view in two weeks, museum officials said. The
transaction at least partly alleviates fears that important pieces
of the Rothschild collection, which had been displayed since World
War II in Austrian museums, would disappear into private hands.
</P>
<P>
   The sale at Christie's, which totaled $89.9 million, was one of
the most successful European auctions ever, doubling its
anticipated value and breaking 10 records for such categories as
illuminated manuscripts, furniture and carpets sold at auction. The
Roosterman portrait, one of three by Hals that were auctioned, sold
for more than four times the previous record price for the Dutch
master.
</P>
<P>
   The 218 lots were sold by members of the Austrian branch of the
Jewish banking family, who this year had the trove of Old Master
paintings, exquisite furnishings and prized historical scientific
instruments returned to them by the Austrian government 61 years
after they were seized by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   After the war family members reached an agreement with the
government that allowed them to leave the country with many of
their possessions provided they left others behind. Many of the
holdings were displayed in Viennese museums until the culture
minister, Elisabeth Gehrer, decided last year to return them,
calling the postwar decisions immoral.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's auction packed Christie's Great Hall for hours of
frenzied bidding, but as is frequently the case, the identity of
many of the buyers is still a matter of speculation. Visibly active
in the salesroom were many members of other branches of the
Rothschild family, notably Elie and Lilliane de Rothschild of
Paris, who were sitting with Christopher Balfour, a vice chairman
of Christie's board. Mrs. Rothschild was seen vigorously bidding on
several items, buying a few scientific instruments along with a
southern German gilt-metal clock case, circa 1550, intricately
decorated with Greek myths of Orpheus and Eurydice. Mrs. Rothschild
paid $148,105 for the items, which were expected to sell for $8,200
and to $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   She also bought a gilt bronze and steel press dating from the
second half of the 16th century that Christie's experts thought
could fetch $12,000 to $16,000. Mrs. Rothschild paid $64,000.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the English branch of the Rothschild family was a
buyer, too. Jane Rick, the director of Spencer House, one of the
grandest London town houses, which was rescued from decay by Lord
Rothschild and restored under his direction, bought a Venetian
gilt-painted copper and bronze lantern, circa 1700, for $37,649.85.
That was just above its high estimate of $32,000. She was thought
to be bidding on behalf of Lord Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   The Hals portrait of Roosterman will be reunited in Cleveland
with another portrait by the artist that the museum bought from the
Rothschilds in 1948, from the part of their collection they were
able to take with them. That work, ``Portrait of a Woman'' (whose
identity has not been established), like the one of Roosterman, was
painted around 1630.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exceptional painting, perfect for our collection,''
said Kate M. Sellers, acting director of the Cleveland Museum of
Art.
</P>
<P>
   That the museum was determined to get the painting was evident
at Christie's on Thursday night. Clovis Whitfield, a London dealer,
who was bidding on behalf of the institution, beat out four other
bidders. The previous record for the artist was set in London in
1997 when ``St. John the Evangelist'' sold at Sotheby's for $2.9
million.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other auctioned object will remain on public view,
not in Cleveland but at Versailles. The French museum paid $10.9
million for a commode made by Jean-Henri Riesener, the finest
cabinetmaker employed by Louis XVI. The price was more than two and
a half times the estimate for the piece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
