<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY-FICTIONALIZ     07-09 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY-FICTIONALIZED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WHOM THE CASH REGISTER TOLLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY G. BINGHAM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Paris Pilgrims''
</P>
<P>
   By Clancy Carlile
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   Carroll &AMP; Graf, $25
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Want to know about Ernest Hemingway?
</P>
<P>
   Then don't read ``The Paris Pilgrims.'' This novel tells more
about Hemingway's possible sex life than you ever wanted to know.
Clancy Carlile's portrait of the artist as a 23-year-old man is
full of raucous details but not much else.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem with ``The Paris Pilgrims'' is that some of
it is fact and some is fiction, and the writer doesn't say which is
which. That's bad, because Carlile takes us into Hemingway's
bedroom _ and the bedrooms of other famous writers _ and what we
see there is graphic. It's a little like senior English class meets
``Melrose Place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Paris Pilgrims'' unfolds in 1922, when young newspaperman
Hemingway moves to France with his boyish older wife, Hadley. They
encounter fellow art bohemians James Joyce, Gertrude Stein, Ezra
Pound, Sherwood Anderson, Pablo Picasso, Cole Porter and others.
</P>
<P>
   Every character Carlile puts on stage winds up in a compromising
position with another prominent character; only occasionally does
the narrative wander back to Hemingway and his wife. We only hope
the made-up parts are the distracting details, the irrelevant
characters and the bad dialogue, like this exchange between
Hemingway and Joyce:
</P>
<P>
   ``I read `Dubliners,' '' Hemingway announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah,'' Joyce said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's ever written better short stories. How old were you
when you wrote them?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway seemed slightly incredulous for a moment, even
speechless. ``Twenty!'' He seemed to be counting on his fingers.
``But I thought they only came out about five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were turned down by 22 publishers, that's why it took so
long to bring them out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No s---?''
</P>
<P>
   Carlile, author of ``Children of the Dust,'' is at his best when
he brings life to Hemingway: sweaty, ambitious, naive, charming,
hot-tempered, coarse, rough-around-the-edges life.
</P>
<P>
   We observe Hemingway shadowboxing on the Left Bank, cheering
bullfighters in Spain, struggling with his calling. Carlile's
Hemingway is a drunk, a brute, a party boy, a homophobe, bisexual,
a cheating husband, a jealous writer, obsessed, neglectful and
self-absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   It's often interesting, and there's something to learn from
Carlile about Hemingway and his brilliance _ but we can't really
learn much when the author leaves it so unclear as to what's fact
and what's fiction.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry G. Bingham recently won a National Headliners award for
feature writing. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
