<HEADER>
A4915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-09 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: MAD COW BAN ENDING
</P>
<P>
   Officials expect the European Union's ban on Britain's worldwide
beef exports stemming from a 1996 outbreak of mad cow disease to be
lifted next week. The ban was imposed after the disease swept
through British cattle herds and was linked to Creutzfeldt-Jakob
Disease, which attacks the human brain. More than four million
animals have been destroyed in an effort to stamp out the disease,
which has accounted for 40 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: MOVE AGAINST FOX HUNTING
</P>
<P>
   In a policy reversal aimed at placating its traditional
supporters, the Labor government will push for a bill to outlaw fox
hunting. ``It will be banned _ as soon as we possibly can,'' Prime
Minister Tony Blair said on BBC-TV. An anti-fox-hunting bill died
last year when the government did not allow time for Parliament to
vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: BAR ON PROTESTANTS
</P>
<P>
   The government-appointed Parades Commission ruled against the
Orange Order's plans to turn its traditional July 12 parade on
Belfast's Protestant outskirts into a demonstration next to a large
Catholic neighborhood. The commission said 20,000 Orangemen
parading to Ormeau Park in central Belfast would ``bring wholly
unnecessary disruption to community relations.''
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: TRIAL FOR EX-PREMIER
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Charles Haughey must stand trial on
charges of obstructing justice, a Dublin court ruled. Haughey, 73,
who made a rare public appearance in court but did not comment on
the case, is accused of conspiring to prevent a
government-appointed tribunal from investigating his personal
finances. The purpose of the 1997 tribunal, and another one still
in session, is to determine how Haughey came to own a yacht,
racehorses and an island while earning only a public salary.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: NEW BLOOD SCANDAL ACCUSATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Le Parisien published a 1989 memo to Health Minister Claude Evin
warning him that tracking down people who had received transfusions
contaminated with the AIDS virus could lead to suits against the
government. The author of the memo, Jean-Francois Girard, then a
public health official, said the document had been ``taken out of
context.'' About 4,400 people contracted AIDS from inadequately
tested blood in France in the 1980s, and Evin has been charged with
involuntary homicide.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: REBELS PULL OUT
</P>
<P>
   Left-wing guerrillas withdrew from a battle zone 25 miles
southeast of Bogota after the army sent as many as 1,000 soldiers
to the mountainous area following heavy fighting a day after the
rebels gained a two-week delay in the start of peace talks. An army
spokesman said at least 38 soldiers and 40 rebels from the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia were killed in the clash,
which has alarmed residents of Bogota because it took place so
close to the capital.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: PROTECTING MOTHERS' RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court refused to allow Ryan Dobson, 6, to sue his
mother, Cynthia and claim damages for a car accident that happened
only hours before he was born. The court said a suit would be
unacceptable intrusion ``into the bodily integrity'' and privacy of
women. The boy was born with cerebral palsy and the suit was
brought by his grandfather to provide money for his long-term care.
Mrs. Dobson had already reached a settlement with her insurance
company.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: POLITICAL FALLOUT IN STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   A strike by nurses in Quebec that is inconveniencing thousands
of hospital patients is also causing stress for politicians.
Premier Lucien Bouchard has had to apologize for a memo sent by his
party, the separatist Parti Quebecois, urging members to call radio
stations and write to papers criticizing the strike without
revealing their party affiliation. Handling the strike has been
difficult for Bouchard because union support is important to the
separatist cause.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SOLDIERS TO FIGHT CRIME
</P>
<P>
   The government, trying to break the grip of crime in Mexico,
took the controversial decision to deploy 5,000 soldiers to the
Federal Preventative Police, an elite force similar to the FBI that
has been slow to move into action since it was set up in December.
Officials said the officers would be used only for intelligence
work, but the move has set off a debate about using the military to
fight the kidnappings, armed robberies and narcotics crimes that
have plagued Mexico since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: HUSSEIN ACCUSES U.N.
</P>
<P>
   President Saddam Hussein accused U.N. employees of spying,
smuggling out archaeological treasures and waging germ warfare
against Iraq. He was quoted in the official press a day after Ian
Broughton, a New Zealand mine clearing expert, was forced to leave
Baghdad after being accused of burying locust eggs to destroy Iraqi
crops. A U.N. spokesman again denied the charges, and a spokesman
for New Zealand's U.N. mission called allegations that Broughton
was spying ``completely idiotic.''
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA: SECURITY COUNCIL PRAISE
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council, saying Libya had made ``significant
progress'' toward complying with its resolutions, reaffirmed its
suspension of trade sanctions and said it would lift them
permanently once Libya complied with all its demands. Diplomats
said this meant Libya must still cooperate with the trial of two
intelligence agents accused of blowing up a Pan Am airliner over
Scotland in 1988 and agree to compensate the families of the
victims if the agents are convicted. On Wednesday Britain agreed to
reopen diplomatic relations with Libya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
