<HEADER>
A4917 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-KAUFMANN-ART-     07-09 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-KAUFMANN-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAUFMANN'S STARS TRY TO REGAIN THE HEAVENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shareholders of the Kaufmann Fund must wax nostalgic as they
consider its recent performance and wonder if the fund's best days
are behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, they remember years like 1991, when the fund returned
79 percent, outperforming its small-stock growth fund peers by 20
percentage points, on average. They remember when the stock-picking
prowess of its managers, Hans Utsch and Lawrence Auriana, was so
widely celebrated that their imprimatur could ``make'' a new issue.
</P>
<P>
   But they also remember January 1998, when the fund sold short
Amazon.com. That decision, a bet that the stock's price would
decline, cost the fund $85 million when the position was closed in
January 1999. The miscalculation was all the more unnerving because
it coincided with a slide in the fund's relative performance.
</P>
<P>
   Though investors may forgive management for underperforming the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, since small-capitalization
stocks have lagged behind larger stocks the last few years, they
are no doubt frustrated by the fund's failure to capitalize on the
surge in small stocks in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   While the average small-cap growth fund tracked by Morningstar
Inc. gained 12.17 percent this year through June 30, the Kaufmann
Fund declined 0.53 percent. That weakness dragged down the fund's
three-year average annual return to 5.11 percent, little more than
half the 9.39 percent average for its category.
</P>
<P>
   Auriana, 54, attributes the poor showing to a drift in the
fund's investment style. In the aftermath of last summer's market
turmoil, he said, ``we got cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, the fund increased its investments in health care
stocks last fall to 28 percent of the portfolio, versus an average
weighting of 13.5 percent for small-cap growth stock funds, and
pared back technology stocks to 15 percent, compared with the
average of 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the health care component of the Russell 2000 small-stock
index fell 0.81 percent this year through June 30, while the
technology sector forged ahead 17.92 percent. ``We should have
stayed true to our bottom-up style'' of selecting stocks, Auriana
said.
</P>
<P>
   The other problem, in Auriana's view, was the sharp rise in
Internet stocks. Though Web stocks made up 9.3 percent of the
Russell 2000 as of June 30, as calculated by Salomon Smith Barney,
the fund owns none. But that, he said, ``we don't regret one bit.''
He added, ``We invest in profitable companies with clear business
prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged, ``shorting Internet stocks was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But some believe that the fund's troubles go beyond style drift
and Web-phobia. For one thing, said Michael Lipper, chairman of
Lipper Inc., the fund research firm, the small-stock universe that
Utsch, 62, and Auriana once mined so successfully is now filled
with analysts, making it tougher for them to maintain an edge.
</P>
<P>
   And some critics contend that the pair allowed the fund to grow
too large and unwieldy. Kaufmann's assets swelled from $40 million
in 1990 to a peak of $6 billion in 1997, before shrinking to a
still bulky $3.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time Kaufmann ranked in the top 20 percent of its
category was 1994,'' said Jeff McConnell, an analyst with
Morningstar, when assets were $1.6 billion. To deploy all its
money, Kaufmann has expanded the number of companies in which it
invests and moved away from its micro-cap emphasis. The median
market capitalization of stocks in the fund has grown to $1.96
billion _ almost six times the $327.7 million in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Auriana says size has not weighed on the fund's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Savage, editor of The No-Load Fund Analyst, notes that
Kaufmann's total expense ratio of 1.89 percent has cut into the
fund's returns. ``It wasn't an issue when the fund was doing
well,'' he said. The average total expense ratio for small-cap
funds tracked by Lipper Inc. is 1.418 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To turn things around, Lipper thinks the fund needs to
restructure its portfolio. Management could, for example, use
losses to unlock long-term gains in some health care holdings,
freeing money for more promising areas. In his view, ``the
fundamental issue is security selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Cendant, Kaufmann's largest holding at 8 percent of assets, is a
case in which stock selection has raised questions. Not only is
Cendant a large-cap stock, but critics say that holding such a big
position in the company means that Kaufmann has missed out on other
opportunities. Last year, Cendant's shares plummeted as low as
$6.50 in the wake of an accounting scandal. But the fund bought
more shares, reducing its average cost to less than $10 a share.
Cendant has since recovered, closing Friday at $20.625.
</P>
<P>
   Auriana is comfortable with the stock, saying, ``They have
strong franchises, they generate lots of free cash flow, and the
accounting problems are behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, ``in effect, we've taken Lipper's advice.''
The fund recently reduced health care to 17 percent of its assets
by taking profits in long-time holdings like Steris and Cardinal
Health. And it restored technology to 27 percent by, for example,
increasing its position in Alpha Industries, a maker of integrated
cellular-phone circuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're comfortable with how the fund is positioned now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio consists of profitable companies that he and Utsch
believe are growing faster, and selling at cheaper price-earnings
ratios, than the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a history of investing in good growth companies,''
Auriana said. ``In no way have we altered our style.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
