<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4919 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARTOONNET-COHEN1STTA     07-09 1758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTOONNET-COHEN1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One-and-only Cartoon Network President Betty Cohen is the
marketing dynamo behind cable success story of the '90s
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's one of the most powerful women in television, equal parts
creative risk taker and savvy businesswoman in a setting where
success can be as fickle as a finger on the remote and
personalities run the gamut from Ted Turner to Bugs Bunny.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on a morning in downtown Atlanta, Betty Cohen is basically
at the mercy of a ballroom full of girls.
</P>
<P>
   First she encourages them to explore options in life. Next, to
find mentors. But it's when the Car-
</P>
<P>
   toon Network president conducts an onstage interview of a
pint-size volunteer named Allison that the predictably chatty and
easily distracted ``Take Our Daughters to Work Day'' crowd becomes,
shall we say, fully engaged.
</P>
<P>
   Allison enjoys horseback riding, playing basketball and math.
But alas, she has no idea what she might want to be someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``So she's going to need our help,'' Cohen calls out to the
crowd just before being practically knocked backward by their
shouted suggestions: a veterinarian. A scorekeeper (Cohen: ``I
think she could be a sportscaster.'') Even, egads, an agent.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the whole room suddenly gets what Cohen had been
saying a few minutes earlier: ``It's an adventure, and your
adventure to pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Cohen is still smiling. And why not? She's been in
those little girls' shoes, although at the moment, the wide, quiet
streets of Racine, Wis., where she grew up, seem awfully far from
the large corner office where an efficient staffer whisks in a
belated lunch. As always, Cohen is bathed in the glow of three TVs
silently broadcasting the Cartoon Network and its major
competitors, Nickelodeon and the Disney Channel. Daffy Duck and
Scooby Doo mugs decorate a shelf behind the couch. The 42-year-old
Cohen, a chestnut-haired, bespectacled dynamo (``short and
animated'' is how TV Guide described her in an irresistible _ and
accurate _ pun), settles in for a long talk under the gaze of her
truly animated office mates.
</P>
<P>
   Ed, Edd and Eddy. Cow and Chicken. Bubbles, Blossom and
Buttercup, a.k.a. ``The Powerpuff Girls.'' And Dexter, the little
mad scientist, who was the trailblazer for original animated
programming at a network that, let's face it, could have run ``Bugs
Bunny'' ad infinitum and done quite well for itself. The
characters' pictures practically leap off her office walls in
Turner Broadcasting's Techwood complex, leaving absolutely no doubt
about what Cohen does for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people think I must get to watch cartoons all
day,'' Cohen said, midway through a typically jampacked day that
included a teleconference with Cartoon Network's Latin American
brand manager, talks with Time Warner officials from New York and a
meeting about a CNN special that would involve Turner Learning, the
educational division Cohen also heads. ``They don't understand that
it's the entertainment business.''
</P>
<P>
   As the only president the Atlanta-based Cartoon Network has ever
known, Cohen has taken one of Turner Broadcasting founder Ted
Turner's lovably loopy ideas _ a 24-hour channel devoted to
cartoons _ and in some six years turned it into a cable success
story of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   She started with a relatively skimpy 2 million subscribers
(ironically, none in metro Atlanta, where the channel wouldn't
become available for another three years). Though still in the
shadow of Nickelodeon, longtime big kid on the kids TV block, the
Cartoon Network passed the 50 million subscriber mark in May,
making it basic cable's fastest-growing channel.
</P>
<P>
   Nick's ``Rugrats'' remains the undisputed cartoon king (most
weeks, the show is among the top 15 basic cable programs; for the
week ending June 27, it had an audience of more than 3 million).
But Cartoon Network's ``Johnny Bravo'' is beginning to flex his
comically overdeveloped muscles. A Feb. 14 episode about the
pompadoured guy who fancies himself God's gift to women was watched
in 1.3 million households, the highest ever for a single episode of
a Cartoon Network show.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more impressive: Adults make up 30 percent of the
Cartoon Network's audience in 145 countries.
</P>
<P>
   This, despite Cohen's unenviable task of having to build an
identity for a channel without a human star to speak on its behalf.
But those who know Co-
</P>
<P>
   hen say that task is no problem for her. Her strength, they say,
is in marketing, a skill honed at the fledgling Lifetime and TNT
networks and brought with her to the Cartoon Network.
</P>
<P>
   Making the nascent network primary sponsor of a NASCAR Winston
Cup Series car four years ago looks particularly prescient given
auto racing's popularity now. Indeed, Jeff Gordon won the recent
race in Sonoma, Calif., but it was the unveiling of ``The Jetsons''
car that really turned heads. (They've already used cartoon
characters Scooby Doo, Tom and Jerry and the girls from the
``Powerpuff'' series.) Over in England, meanwhile, Fred Flintstone
and Barney Rubble were gorging on strawberries and cream at
Wimbledon _ the latest marketing lob from ``Smash Tennis,'' a
Cartoon Network program that works with the U.S. Tennis Association
to introduce the game to kids.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Broadcasting &AMP; Cable magazine named Cohen marketer of
the year in 1997. And industry bible Advertising Age in November
named the Cartoon Network the year's best cable TV marketer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty is dynamite!'' says Turner, who gave her eight months to
create the cartoon channel from scratch after elevating her from
general manager of TNT in February 1992. ``She has made the Cartoon
Network what it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   Exploring in her blood
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's all been about marketing. Among the Cartoon
Network's original series, ``Dexter's Laboratory'' and ``Cow and
Chicken'' have been nominated for four and two consecutive
prime-time Emmys, respectively. And NASA in 1997 named a rock on
Mars in honor of ``Space Ghost,'' the animated talk show ``host''
who regularly has visits from the likes of Willie Nelson, Michael
Stipe of R.E.M. and Ice-T.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dexter'' was the first original Cartoon Network series
greenlighted by Cohen, who liked its pacing and characters. But the
network doesn't reflect just Cohen's tastes: She knows what works
in the highly competitive, ever-changing cable TV industry and has
an almost Turneresque zeal for exploring what's out there.
</P>
<P>
   This, after all, is the same Betty Cohen who left Racine for
Stanford University sight unseen. She'd spent the previous summer
pedaling her Schwinn around her quiet hometown, sure of almost
nothing except that it was time for her to go. Suddenly, she found
herself seated in her new roommate's convertible, traversing the
exotic snarl of San Francisco and experiencing an unforgettable
rush of exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, there was all this choice,'' Cohen remembered. ``And
I thought, `I knew there was a reason I was supposed to be bored in
Racine!'''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she'd idled her youth away, you understand. The middle
of five children born to Philip and Pearle Cohen, Cohen always used
her mind to roam. At 6, she joined a six-week summer reading
program, after which Pearle was asked by the flabbergasted teacher,
``Do you know your daughter read 99 books?!''
</P>
<P>
   It stood to reason, then, that Cohen would edit her high
school's literary magazine. Less predictable was her singing role
as Bloody Mary in the school's production of ``South Pacific.''
Cohen had no singing experience, so the school's drama instructor
arranged free lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cohen suggests the experience taught her something more
important than how to stay on pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw what interested me, and he pushed me to do more,''
Cohen said of the drama teacher, her first mentor. ``He said,
`Don't just try out for this play, don't just think of yourself in
this role.'''
</P>
<P>
   It's an attitude those around her can't help but share.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worldview has changed as a result of knowing her,'' says
Jonathan Liff, the Emory epidemiologist whom Cohen married last
year. ``It's definitely expanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving on the Stanford campus, Cohen had no specific career
goal in mind, other than an interest in TV. But she seemed to have
few qualms about staring into the unknown, according to Gale Anne
Hurd, the mega-successful film producer (``Aliens,'' ``The
Terminator''), who was her freshman roommate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrived at Stanford, I was completely overwhelmed _
what did I want to major in, what to do with my life,'' said Hurd,
who remains close friends with Cohen. ``Most of the people I knew
at Stanford were frantic. But I never saw her upset or overwhelmed.
Betty seemed so calm and focused.'' Some of that was probably due
to Phil Cohen's example. A life insurance salesman, his children
knew if they wanted to attend college out of state, they'd need
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty ... sat down with her father and he said, `Don't worry
about all four years at once. We'll take it one year at a time,'''
Pearle Cohen recalled from Highland Park, Ill., where she and Phil
now live.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, some of the former World War II pilot's spirit of
adventure had to have rubbed off on Betty when, preparing to take a
business trip to Denver, he realized all the kids hadn't yet flown
on an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walked in with seven tickets to Denver and said, `Well, I
just bought an airplane!''' said Pearle Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Was it any wonder, then, that Betty Cohen spent her junior year
living and studying on a British estate? The ``Stanford in
Britain'' experience was more than adventure, however. There, Cohen
now says, she realized that her professional future lay in
television.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote papers (one, prophetically, was on children's
television) and watched through slightly disbelieving American eyes
as Parliament debated creating a fourth British TV channel. (``We
were like, what are you debating? Figure out what shows are going
to get ratings and make money!'') But it was seeing a BBC
documentary on adult literacy that sealed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a story you can write about the shame of adults who
can't read,'' said Cohen. ``And then there was this documentary
that had live, human grown-ups needing people to tell them what was
on the menu. That's something very powerful that you can do (with
TV).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
