<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARTOONNET-COHEN2NDTA     07-09 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTOONNET-COHEN2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: do (with TV).''
</P>
<P>
   Honing her skills
</P>
<P>
   After graduating Phi Beta Kappa, Cohen worked in San Francisco
for the Public Media Center, which helped political and social
causes. One day she found herself interviewing older women for a
mental health project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept asking them individually, `Is there anything you regret
about your life,''' recalled Cohen. ``And to a person, they all
said they regretted that they didn't take more chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon thereafter, Cohen moved to New York to work for the Cable
Health Network. It later became Lifetime, where, as head of
promotions, Cohen had to lure viewers to shows such as ``Working
Mothers'' _ which aired in the middle of the workday _ and tone
down the high-pitched squeals of Dr. Ruth Westheimer as she read
promos off a TelePrompTer.
</P>
<P>
   At Lifetime, Cohen recognized the power of promotions and
packaging in the young cable industry, where there was almost no
original programming. That realization grew when she became
director of on-air promotions for Nickelodeon, then an
all-children's network owned by MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``On-air promotions had to be great at MTV because, see, they
didn't have any shows. They had a bunch of commercials for records
which were called music videos,'' said Cohen. ``They were the first
network to build an identity because of their on-air promotions and
contests and their cool animated IDs. So Nickelodeon at the time
looked over at MTV and said, `Wow, you can actually attract an
audience over how you package the shows, not just with the shows
themselves.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen wasn't looking to leave when, in 1988, a former colleague
suggested she join him at TNT, the new Turner network. On her first
visit, Cohen came armed with a list of things Atlanta had to have
for her to consider relocating: a sushi bar, a late-night
bookstore, a hol-
</P>
<P>
   istic health store. But she also carried a healthy respect for
and curiosity about what Ted Turner was trying to do by building a
network around his recently acquired library of MGM films.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck me as an idea whose time had come,'' said Cohen. ``I
thought a lot of people wanted quality
</P>
<P>
   in their TV and movies, but you didn't have to
</P>
<P>
   be snobby about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen returned to her Atlanta hotel room expecting to agonize
over her decision. Instead, she once again became that teenager
bicycling through Racine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just like, `No, I think I want to do this,''' remembered
Cohen. ``It was just one of the most natural, odd things.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen quickly influenced TNT, where she headed the marketing
department that established the network's ``brand'' as something
more than a collection of old movies. She also launched TNT's
original programming and its NFL and NBA packages. Turner clearly
liked what he saw. In 1992, Cohen was plucked from her general
manager's position at TNT and asked to build the Cartoon Network,
to hone a channel largely unfamiliar to cable operators,
advertisers and viewers. Not a problem for Cohen, according to one
top Turner executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We create new networks and take programming and piece it
together to create brands and the look and feel of networks,'' said
Terry McGuirk, chairman and CEO of Turner Broadcasting. ``That is a
very specific skill to be able to excel at. Betty is very good at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, McGuirk says he loves Cohen's ``passion'' for
programming on the Cartoon Network, which got its start when Turner
acquired the 8,500-cartoon Hanna-Barbera and MGM libraries. (The
subsequent Time Warner merger in 1995 brought additional cartoons
from Warner Bros. such as ``Roadrunner.'') Cohen says not having to
buy programs gave the channel time and money to develop its own
cartoons _ and to keep raising the bar creatively. In the works for
``Dexter's Laboratory'' is a millennium-themed, hourlong special.
The newest show, ``The Powerpuff Girls,'' about three spunky
5-year-olds keeping order in seemingly bucolic Townsville, has been
hailed by everyone from young viewers to Rap Pages magazine.
</P>
<P>
   An affinity for Bugs
</P>
<P>
   Like a mother who loves all her children equally but in
different ways, Cohen seems somewhat hesitant to single out a
favorite among all the world's cartoons. And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I can always be talked into sitting down for `Bugs Bunny'
cartoons,'' she confides. ``He's such a wise guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As unofficial symbols go, he's not bad for a network that Cohen
says has a ``Bugs Bunny-irreverent, don't take yourself too
seriously'' attitude. And who better to run it all than Cohen, who,
after describing one of the channel's early attempts to create an
animated character, began bowing forward from the waist and
giggling: ``The next time I saw (``Flintstones'') creator Joe
Barbera, it was like that thing in `Wayne's World' where you go,
`We're not worthy!'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is her sense of humor _ in particular, her trademark
burbling laugh _ that comes up frequently in conversations about
Cohen. Lynn Borsuk, a Decatur lawyer who ended up introducing Cohen
to her future husband, thinks it explains her ability to get along
with nearly everyone she meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her humor is warm, and it's silly and it's got a childlike
quality to it, where so much humor today is biting and cynical and
sarcastic,'' said Borsuk, who points out that when faulty air
conditioning forced the fire department to temporarily evacuate
Cohen and Liff's wedding reception last year, the bride was among
those laughing and making sure there were photos. (``She made it
into an adventure,'' said Hurd, another guest.) ``I think that
makes a difference in how you're able to relate to people,'' Borsuk
continued.
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake about it, Cohen has to relate to a lot of
people, whether it's Turner himself, the head of Cartoon Network
Japan or even young reporters in the student bureaus created by
Turner Learning. There's also a personal life to tend to. Her
weekend plans with Liff aren't certain yet on this Friday afternoon
_ ``Sometimes Friday nights are (for) planning the weekend,'' she
admitted _ although Cohen was determined to deliver a gift basket
to a friend who'd just had a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Getting away from the job mentally may be just as tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``She takes a lot home with her,'' said Liff, who helps Cohen
relax via long walks, moviegoing and barbecuing. ``My job is to
listen, be supportive and when appropriate, try to help her forget
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not like he hadn't been warned. When Borsuk first met
Liff at the homeless shelter where all three volunteered and wanted
to set them up, ``Betty said, `If I don't meet him in the next 72
hours, it's going to be a month.''' Even then, getting through to
her wasn't easy, says Liff, who joked at the time about dating
Cohen's secretary, since at least he could talk to her. Somehow,
though, Cohen and Liff worked it out, and they spent five hours
talking on that first dinner date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never done that before, spent five hours talking
nonstop,'' said Liff, who has two teenage sons from a previous
marriage. ``Her sense of humor is wide, and her interest level in
life is high.''
</P>
<P>
   With Liff, Cohen has gone back to Racine, a place for which she
retains obvious affection, and to China. The latter trip was for
business, but, Liff says, Cohen also visited an elementary school
and the children's section of a department store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know what childhood is like, especially in a place
like China where they don't have brothers and sisters,'' because of
population control, Cohen explained recently. Still, she doesn't
forget the folks at home. Longtime friend Jonathan Shils, an
Atlanta lawyer, says Cohen's professional stature may keep growing,
but she and Liff are still available for regular weekend movie
outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``She may be dealing with the Ted Turners and (Time Warner
Chairman) Gerald Levins of the world, but she's still Betty from
Wisconsin,'' said Shils, who was sick at home in January when Cohen
showed up with homemade kugel. ``It's just a shorthand for her
character. It's very clear when she's got you as a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as it's very clear what got her here. Her ``Take Our
Daughters to Work Day'' speech done, Cohen scooted offstage to
youthful applause and a day full of meetings, presentations and
conference calls. Onstage, the moderator encouraged the girls to
write down ``ideas for Betty'' and have their parents or teachers
pass them along.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Cohen finished chatting with McGuirk and his two
young daughters and began gradually working her way to the back of
the hotel ballroom filled with Turner Broadcasting employees.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a young girl made her way out from the rows of seats,
snaked her way through the adults and proudly presented a piece of
paper on which she'd written something to the Cartoon Network
president.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's brown eyes lit up. An idea for Betty. Who knew where
this might lead?
</P>
<P>
   IN 'TOON WITH COHEN
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Name: Betty Cohen
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Age: 42
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Occupation: President, Cartoon Network Worldwide; president,
Turner Learning.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Personal: Married to Jonathan Liff; two teenage stepsons.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hobbies: Art, travel, watching movies, reading.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born for the job: ``I always used to watch `Rocky and
Bullwinkle' with my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the power of cartoons: ``They could do anything. That's why
it bothers me when people talk about them in some sort of broad
category: `All cartoons are this or that.' You would never say all
movies are one thing or another. I think cartoons do connect people
with their inner child or their adolescence. And I actually think
cartoons are more honest. They're the most truthful form of
entertainment because people's fantasies or fears can get played
out. Bugs Bunny can fall from a 10-story building and crash and
spring back. It's like everyone's wish fantasy, so you can do
things that could never possibly happen, but they're really in
touch with where people's wishes are.''
</P>
