<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WCUP-AKERS-NYT &LR;      07-09 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-AKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AKERS SAVING ON ENERGY TO GIVE IT ALL THAT SHE'S GOT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also SOC-WCUP-WOMEN, SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN) 
(rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Her father has attended every American match
in the Women's World Cup, but sometimes he is too nervous to watch.
Bob Akers could not bear to see his daughter, Michelle, take a
penalty kick against Brazil in the semifinals, so he buried his
head in his hands, she said. She didn't miss the kick, but he did.
</P>
<P>
   He is always fearful that she will be injured, and for good
reason, because Michelle adheres to the Joe Frazier school of
defense, always leading with her face. While it is the daughter who
suffers from chronic fatigue syndrome, it is the father who is
inevitably wrung out at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got this hangdog look on his face,'' Michelle said,
imitating this visage of sad exhaustion. ``He's so proud of me. He
has watched me go through so much that it kills him to think I
might be disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could be disappointed by the way Michelle Akers has
played in this tournament, and while some of her teammates now get
more attention, not one has been more vital to the American success
in reaching Saturday's championship match against China in the Rose
Bowl. Akers, the first great star of this team _ one who dominated
the inaugural Women's World Cup in 1991 with 10 goals _ can still
control a game in defensive midfield the way she once did at
forward. At 33, she is the oldest player on the team, and perhaps
the most indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the best woman that's ever played the game, period,''
said Tony DiCicco, the American coach.
</P>
<P>
   Before the tournament began, DiCicco said he would take whatever
minutes Akers could provide. From day to day, she did not know what
she would be able to give. At its worst, the chronic fatigue would
leave her unable to practice, or to play more than a half, and
cause debilitating migraine headaches, low blood pressure, memory
loss, dizziness, bouts of vomiting and a consuming feeling of
torpor.
</P>
<P>
   She struggled through the World Cup opener against Denmark and
was spent afterward. Dainis Kalnins, the team's equipment manager,
said: ``She was literally crying. I've never seen her in such
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Akers has played every minute of the quarterfinal
match against Germany and the semifinal against Brazil. While
others appeared sluggish playing two games in four days, with a
cross-country flight in between, Akers slept the entire way from
Washington D.C. to San Francisco on a charter flight and awakened
as perky as Kathie Lee Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   Renewed, Akers rescued the Americans' game against Brazil by
shutting down its star midfielder, Sissi, clearing a threatening
shot in the first half and punching home a penalty kick to secure a
2-0 victory. Surprisingly for someone with a fatigue disorder,
Akers seems to play stronger in the second half than the first. The
nervous excitement and frantic early pace of a game tend to sap her
energy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, she is wrapped in icy towels to cool her down, and
she refuels by drinking coffee to raise her blood pressure and by
eating cereal, granola bars, bananas, whatever she can force down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising my blood pressure a couple of points can make a
difference,'' Akers said. ``For some reason, in the second half,
the game changes and I don't have to expend so much energy.''
</P>
<P>
   After each game, Akers is given an intravenous line to restore
her fluids. She carries water with her constantly to keep hydrated,
and she adheres to a special diet that avoids dairy foods, to which
she is allergic. She spends much of her time resting between games,
and she has declined to secure a shoe endorsement, not wanting the
obligation of having to make personal appearances that could
distract her or leave her tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so amazing what she has to go through just to get her
body ready for a game,'' Kalnins said.
</P>
<P>
   What Akers has not been able to avoid, however, with her
muscular style of play, is injuries. She has had at least a dozen
knee surgeries, so many that she has lost count. Seven minutes into
the 1995 World Cup, she was knocked out after colliding with a
Chinese player and did not return to the lineup until the
semifinals. Against Brazil last Sunday, Akers got an egg-sized lump
on her head after a first-half collision, and later she took a kick
to the face, which has embroidered her nose with a scab and a
purplish bruise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stick my head in places where it shouldn't be, but I'm not
going to change my style,'' she said. ``That's who I am and that's
the way I play.''
</P>
<P>
   She also suffered the most bizarre injury of the 1999 World Cup.
After sitting out the North Korea game in Foxboro, Mass., Akers was
high-fiving fans as she left the field when a spectator grabbed
her, causing her to fall and wrench her right shoulder. DiCicco
said he had never before heard of anyone being injured in a
high-five accident, ``but I knew if someone was going to do it, it
would be Michelle.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers said, laughing: ``My first thought was, `Now I have to go
tell my dad that I hurt my shoulder high-fiving.' Already, he can't
sleep at night, he's so stressed out. I've already put him in the
grave six times.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers keeps going down, but popping right back up, like one of
those childhood punching toys. ``She's a warrior,'' said Carla
Overbeck, the team captain. And now she is on the verge of a second
world championship Saturday, playing before 90,000 fans, the
largest crowd to watch a women's sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been remembering those times when I was rehabbing by
myself, or feeling sick and going to practice anyway, and saying to
God, `Please give me the energy to take another step in the last
five minutes,''' Akers said. ``All this has brought me to this
place. I'm overjoyed by the opportunity to experience this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
