<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4921 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-SIDE11-COX     07-09 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-SIDE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Illusion made real, re-created playhouse is its own cosmos
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Movie director John Madden wanted to shoot parts of
``Shakespeare in Love'' in Shakespeare's Globe Theatre, but after a
tour of the $13.6 million playhouse, he pronounced it ``too clean''
and passed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, not only does the Globe gleam with white lime wash
(made using Elizabethan methods), not only is it free of ale-soaked
sawdust and drumstick bones, it has a beautifully decorated stage.
Pillars are painted to look like marble, and on the royal-blue
underside of the stage roof is a heaven of golden constellations
and gods.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Madden's) view is modern _ that Elizabethans were raucous,
sexy people always making jokes,'' says artistic director Mark
Rylance. ``But there was also a love of illusion. These theaters
were people's palaces.'' In his own, perhaps mystical,
interpretation of historical evidence, Rylance ordered the stage
painting ``because (Elizabethans) believed in muses and heavenly
influence, balanced by devils and appetites below,'' he continues.
``Some scholars feel that the stage pillars are too far forward,
but I believe they were there as important symbols, polarities of
mind and heart, moon and sun. The stage is a cosmos. It was called
the Globe for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The hygiene and pillar issues are just two of the debates still
buzzing, like stirred-up bees, around the Globe, christened in
1997. The debates stem from the scarcity of evidence about the
original Globe in rough sketches, letters and contracts. The
reference to ``This wooden `O''' in ``Henry V'' is often mentioned
as Shakespeare's salute to the Globe, but some scholars believe
that the play was written months before the Globe's 1599 opening
and actually refers to the Curtain Theatre on the Thames' north
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Excavations of the Globe's foundations _ discovered after
construction of the new Globe began in 1991 _ confirmed that it,
too, was near-circular, apparently with 20 sides. This settled the
Great Sides Debate (18 or 20?) that raged as part of a 1990 Globe
symposium at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy dates back to when actor Sam Wanamaker, trying to
find the theater's original site in 1949, was outraged to find only
a plaque on the side of a brewery. As Wanamaker labored to get the
Globe built _ construction didn't begin until 1991, a few hundred
yards closer to the river than the original site _ he was honored
with the CBE (Commander of the Order of the British Empire) at
Whitehall Palace but that didn't quell skepticism and mockery of
his dream. When the partially finished Globe presented its
``workshop season'' (with the Atlanta Shakespeare Tavern and
Georgia Shakespeare Festival among the guest troupes) in 1995, two
years after Wanamaker's death, The Times of London asked, ``Has the
great American eccentric built his adoptive country a great
folly?''
</P>
<P>
   The booming box office suggests otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't an exercise in historical copying,'' says Peter
McCurdy, the construction foreman. ``We really believe the
materials add to the character of the performance. It's a way of
getting into the minds of 400 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater required 1,000 oak trees, including a grove planted
in 1805 for ships of the royal navy. Some 10,000 wooden pegs hold
it together. Hair from horses and cows is used in the mortar. An
early 17th-century building in the Tower of London complex was used
as a model, since its three stories are believed to be similar in
proportion to the three audience galleries of the playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Bard would approve the fact that water reeds from Norfolk
are again used in the thatch, and he might not mind that fireproof
roofing is hidden beneath it. After all, it was a burning wad of
paper from a prop cannon, landing on the thatch, that brought down
the house in 1613.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
