<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4923 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-MEGACHURCH10     07-09 2060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-MEGACHURCH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long view at New Birth
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bishop Eddie Lee Long walks before a full-length mirror, pauses
to gaze at his reflection and flexes his muscles.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor of the largest church in Atlanta is wearing a black
New York Yankees cap turned backward, Air Jordan tennis shoes and
baggy shorts. Long grabs two 50-pound weights in his hands and
begins to curl them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get any bigger,'' the 46-year-old Long says
during a morning workout in a Decatur gym. ``I'm just toning.''
</P>
<P>
   Long releases the barbells with a fierce hiss of breath. As the
weights clang back into position, Long looks at his Popeye-forearms
and grins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps in the board meetings,'' he says. ``In the old days,
the deacons ran everything. So the pastor had to come into the
board meeting pretty buffed.''
</P>
<P>
   Long is calling the shots these days. His name alone carries
enough weight to make things happen. This former corporate salesman
has muscled his way to the top of the nation's religious landscape
by transforming Decatur's New Birth Missionary Baptist Church into
a Christian colossus.
</P>
<P>
   When Long became the church's pastor in 1987, it had 300
members. He was a novice preacher, so nervous that he often threw
up before delivering a sermon.
</P>
<P>
   Today, New Birth has 23,000 members, and Long has spoken before
the Georgia General Assembly and the U.S. Congress and has visited
with President Clinton in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie came at the right time, with the right message and the
right packaging,'' said the Rev. Gerald Durley, pastor of
Providence Missionary Baptist Church in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Much of New Birth's success can be tied to its broad community
involvement. The church offers programs for single women, young
men, teenagers, the homeless, prisoners, first-time offenders, drug
addicts and AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the church's appeal is linked to Long's openness
about his own struggles. He calls himself God's ``scarred leader,''
a man who was rejected by his father, fired from a promising job in
corporate America and divorced by his first wife.
</P>
<P>
   He even had to feed pigs once to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the Prodigal Son,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of Long's comeback can be seen every Sunday morning
at New Birth. Just make sure to get there early. The unassuming
brick church seats 3,500 people and is located on 15 acres of land
near Wesley Chapel Road. The church hires eight police officers to
handle the tide of traffic for its three morning services. Area
residents joke that New Birth members find salvation in the church
but lose it in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Despite New Birth's prominence, Long remains an outsider among
metro Atlanta's black preachers. His refusal to endorse the Nation
of Islam's Million Man March and his frequent criticism of the
traditional black church annoy many black pastors. He says of those
churches, ``They major in storefront buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like Jerry Falwell, only he's black,'' said the Rev.
Timothy McDonald, president of the Concerned Black Clergy. ``Have
you ever seen him in a march or a demonstration or even a
meeting?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Long defies any easy categorization. That's the way he
likes it.
</P>
<P>
   Long dresses like a middle-age hip-hopper, sporting tight muscle
shirts and gold necklaces, but his politics and theology are
conservative. He's an ordained black Baptist minister but says
Jimmy Swaggart, a white charismatic pastor, led him to his greatest
religious awakening. He is neither Democrat nor Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been accused of not knowing who I am,'' Long said,
chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   He started off as a great salesman. A business major who
graduated from North Carolina Central University in 1976, Long
displayed a knack for winning people over. Once, in 1977, when he
was a factory sales representative for Ford Motor Co., Long was
sent to work in rural Virginia, where car dealers didn't welcome
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Long's opening sales pitch went like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Look, let's just cut the crap. I'm black. You're
white. You can call me whatever you want, but I'm here to help you
make some money. And I need you to help me make some money.'''
</P>
<P>
   Such a bottom-line approach has helped him transform New Birth
over the past decade. Only a few years ago, Long obtained a $3
million business loan for New Birth to purchase 170 acres of land
near Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The land turned out to be prime real estate. A year later, New
Birth sold the land for $14 million. Long used part of that money
to pay off the loan, all of New Birth's other debts and purchase
240 acres in Conyers for a new church. That $45 million complex is
scheduled to be complete by mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he said we were going to buy some business, it happened,''
said Andre Landers, an associate minister. ``If he said we were
going to buy some land, we bought the land. Everything he said from
the pulpit came to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   But Long is more than a businessman. He likes people. He is
constantly hugging them, even strangers who sometimes cry in his
arms. He is a gifted storyteller and mimic.
</P>
<P>
   Long calls himself a ``spiritual daddy'' to literally hundreds
of young men in his church. An estimated 40 percent of the members
of New Birth are men, a rarity among black churches.
</P>
<P>
   He's their pastor, but also a benefactor and buddy. Long has
paid college tuition for some members, given his business suits to
others and plays basketball and lifts weights with his male
ministers. He's even taken some on business trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first plane ride was with the bishop,'' Landers said. ``My
first trip overseas was with the bishop. My first family vacation
was because of him. He paid for it. There are so many firsts that
he has been responsible for.'' He takes his role as spiritual daddy
at New Birth seriously, even paddling some wayward teenage boys,
brought to him by church members who trust his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say bend over, even on Sunday, they bend over,'' he
said. ``Why? Because they respect me. Because I first died for
them. There's nothing I wouldn't do for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been providing fatherly support for years. In college, he
would cook meals for kids, buy them sports equipment and take them
to baseball games. ``He's always been a giver,'' said Dennis Meeks,
a college friend.
</P>
<P>
   Long said he gives so much to kids because he lacked such
support when growing up in Charlotte. He describes himself as a
nerd whose high school counselor told him he was too dumb to go to
college. Long's friends said he was an introvert who seldom talked.
</P>
<P>
   Issues of self-esteem, however, no longer seem to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Long occasionally refers to himself in the third person. His
pulpit is ringed with bodyguards on Sunday morning because of death
threats. And he is treated like royalty at New Birth. When he
arrived at the church after a morning workout recently, he was
greeted by three staff members _ one to take his suit inside,
another to open his car door and another to open the church door
for him.
</P>
<P>
   When Long first arrived at New Birth, he had to answer to a
deacon and trustee board. That changed when he told the
congregation a ``biblical leader'' shouldn't have to answer to such
a board. For support, he had his friend, Bishop T.D. Jakes _ they
share the same tailor _ fly to Atlanta and give a sermon backing
his position.
</P>
<P>
   Long said his congregation now understands the true role of a
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pastor is called to minister to God,'' he said. ``Then God
ministers back to him the Word, and he comes before the people to
tell them what God said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't about visiting you in the hospital. It's not about
all of this other stuff we add on _ come to my house and eat
chicken, and do this and be at my beck and call.''
</P>
<P>
   `Daddy pulled back'
</P>
<P>
   Long's father, the Rev. Floyd Long, liked to be in charge. He
was a stern Baptist minister and an entrepreneur. At one point, the
elder Long not only pastored two churches but owned a gas station
and an auto body shop in Charlotte, where Eddie Long was born.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Long was known as ``the cussing preacher,'' a tough man
who asserted himself during a period when most black men were
afraid to do so in the segregated South.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was standing in line and all of a sudden a salesman
would take a white person in front of him, he would say, `No, this
is not going to happen,''' said Larry Long, Eddie Long's older
brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He built many brand-new (church) buildings,'' Eddie Long said.
``But shortly after he built them, he would get mad at the deacons
and go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Long was emotionally distant from his children. He didn't
attend Eddie Long's football games or even his high school and
seminary graduations.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy pulled back when it came to touching you and saying,
`I love you,''' Long said. ``I needed that so badly.''
</P>
<P>
   So Long relished the love showered on him by his mother, Hattie.
She transformed his childhood home into the ``Kool-Aid'' house, a
place where all the neighborhood kids gathered to bask in her
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``His sensitivity and caring came from his mother,'' Meeks said.
``His drive and motivation came from his dad.''
</P>
<P>
   `I embraced him'
</P>
<P>
   Long's drive carried him through college. He not only became the
president of his fraternity, Kappa Alpha Psi, but a radio
personality and a concert promoter for funk groups such as Kool &AMP;
the Gang.
</P>
<P>
   Long's foray into corporate America was rockier. He did well at
Ford initially but said he was eventually fired for including
personal phone calls on his expense report. Long ended up in a
labor pool in 1979 in Richmond, standing on a corner waiting for
work. One day he was sent to a factory that made hog slop.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, he joined Honeywell Inc., where he remained for
eight years. In 1987 he left to answer a call to the ministry after
graduating from the Interdenominational Theological Center in
Atlanta the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   On the day he delivered his trial sermon, he met his first wife,
Debara. They had a son, but the marriage ended after three years.
Long persisted in his ministerial call, pastoring a small church in
Cedartown that grew to 400 people. Long returned to Atlanta when
the departing minister at New Birth suggested Long take his place.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Long watched his son's progress with a mixture of envy and
respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he became ill, people would come and talk to him about
Eddie,'' Larry Long said. ``He would swell up with pride and say,
`God really has work for that boy.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Eddie Long didn't think his father loved him. He finally
worked up the courage to ask his father _ by this time in a
hospital after suffering a stroke _ why. ``He started crying,''
Long said. ``He apologized.'' The elder Long said he didn't know
how to love a son because his own father was so distant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt sorry for him,'' Long said. ``I could tell that he had
been locked up. I embraced him.'' Floyd Long died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After finding success at New Birth, Long now has found stability
in his personal life. He and his second wife, Vanessa, have three
sons, Edward, Jared and Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   He drives a black Lincoln and lives in the Hunt Valley
subdivision, an equestrian community in Lithonia where the median
price for homes is $325,000.
</P>
<P>
   In his spare time he likes to read self-help and business books,
shop at malls and people-watch.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from making pig slop to living in a community
surrounded by horse pastures. But Long attributes his success to
something he learned as a kid.
</P>
<P>
   One summer day, Long jumped into a pool, even though he couldn't
swim. He sank to the bottom, thrashing wildly, convinced he would
die.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, someone reached in, grabbed Long, and said, ``Stand up,
fool!'' Long stood and the water came only to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll fall sometimes, but the Bible tells us to just stand,''
Long said. ``When you stand up, that's when you'll find out that
you're not overwhelmed. I just kept getting up. You only drown when
you lay in the water and don't stand up. I've never forgotten
that.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
