<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4924 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAVE-ERA-ARTIFACTS11     07-09 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVE-ERA-ARTIFACTS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biggs offers gifts of history
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ga. _ For a long time, Alfonso Biggs, 95, has been the
keeper of his family's history. He doesn't just keep it, though; he
shares it, donating many of the artifacts to public places.
</P>
<P>
   A small ceremony is scheduled for today in Talbotton _ about 40
miles northeast of here, county seat for ``a hunter's paradise'' _
to mark Biggs' latest gift, to the Talbot County (Ga.) Library.
</P>
<P>
   The items he's passing on were created by his great-grand-
</P>
<P>
   mother, Phyllis McRosalynn Biggs, a talented craftswoman,
quilter, slave _ and mistress to the plantation owner, who left the
home's contents to her. This new display _ a history lesson in a
library _ includes crocheted table scarves, pillowcases and a quilt
top dyed with pokeberries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of this display is the person who made it,''
says Evelyn Owen Rowe, vice president of the library board.
``Phyllis Biggs was imprisoned and able to rise above that and use
her talents. That shows that she was a spectacular individual with
a dauntless spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she was a spiritual beacon for the family. Alfonso Biggs
says his great-grand-
</P>
<P>
   mother, born in 1814, was snatched from her birthplace in the
Congo by slave raiders around 1831 and forced into a hellish sea
voyage that lasted 60 days, before reaching Norfolk. After
repeatedly being sold, she wound up on the Talbot County
plantation, where she bore the slavemaster three sons and a
daughter, says Biggs, before dying in 1912 in Juniper.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to spread the word in his native county about his
great-grandmother's talent, Biggs last year offered the artifacts
to the Talbot library. ``He feels strongly that the items should be
in Talbot,'' says Rowe, ``because she was a slave there.''
</P>
<P>
   As these pieces go on display, they forge another link between
the present and the past. For Biggs and his family, like black
families nationwide, that past is, of course, a mix of proud
emotional riches and wrenching physical deprivation, wrapped in a
struggle to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   On this steamy Columbus afternoon, Biggs offers a meal and a
talk about his family's pride and pain, expressing the hope that
from his gifts of history, learning will rise. His voice is strong,
his gestures sure, mind sharp _ all of which makes you hope that
this is what 95 is supposed to be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgotten black slaves' struggle for freedom did not pay off
in their time,'' he says, even though ``slaves were builders,
inventors and creators. They give a legacy of music and dance to
their new homeland. They survived under the most difficult
circumstances and developed a culture that is passed from
generation to generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharing his family history with generation after generation is
Biggs' legacy. In 1991, he gave to Fort Valley State University a
huge collection of period furnishings, most dating from 1860 to
1900 and some made by slaves. The pieces include silver, glassware,
china, quilts and linen _ along with dining room and bedroom
furniture from the Talbot County home where Phyllis Biggs was a
slave.
</P>
<P>
   The generation of students now seeing the Biggs exhibit at Fort
Valley State has shown great interest in it, says Linda Hall, vice
president for university advancement, because it provides a good
sense of how the upper class lived. She says the exhibit, on view
in the Anderson House Museum, ``puts us on the tourist map.''
</P>
<P>
   Back here in Columbus, Alphonso Biggs could be on a culinary
tourist map. The one-time textile worker, who has cooked in the
homes of Presidents Franklin D. Roosevelt, Harry S. Truman and
Dwight D. Eisenhower, still has a delicious touch, as this meal _
baked pork chops, collards, corn pudding, candied yams, corn
muffins, banana pudding _ attests. ``I walk, and I have to eat,''
he explains between bites. ``I don't go to the doctor. I don't wear
glasses. I don't take medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meal (at a large table decorated with blooming lantana
that he'd grown in his lush garden and placed in a bowl of water),
Biggs brings in a big red apple, and instead of peeling it with a
knife, he uses a mechanical apple peeler, a set of cranks, wheels
and blades that efficiently does the job as he deftly cranks the
handle.
</P>
<P>
   This machine, made by a slave boy and passed down by family
members, is, like the artifacts Biggs collected and donated, a
metaphor for the unknown and unacknowledged talents that slaves
possessed. ``Slaves were the ones who made that stuff _ in master's
blacksmith shop,'' says Biggs, matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   Born Feb. 14, 1904, Biggs recalls that his aunt, Imogene Biggs,
presented the apple peeler to him in the early 1920s and told him:
``Now you have a wonderful treasure. Keep it. It's very important.
It will be a foot log across deep water. You will need a guide to
go across deep water. You will have this history. You will have
memories way after I am gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From that day, I started saving history,'' Biggs says, his
voice firm. ``And today, it has materialized, and, you know, I am
very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   He has given the accumulated history away as diligently as he
collected it because he's ``going to the grave'' and wants to be
able to determine its fate.
</P>
<P>
   That need is understandable, as black powerlessness, and the
perception of it, have been such an abundant and bitter harvest
from seeds of slavery and Jim Crow.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Biggs' family history is instructive.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, Ella and Otha Biggs, farmed on family land in
Talbot County, where, as one of 15 children, Alfonso picked cotton,
leaving for Columbus to work in various jobs, including cooking and
cotton mill work. Explaining how he left the farm with no regrets,
he chuckles as he recalls telling his father, who wanted him to
stay: ``I love picking cotton, but it makes my back hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   He talks of growing up at a time when ``education was
forbidden'' to black people, how learning was a surreptitious act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing about all of it was that everything was
forbidden to us but work. We didn't have much time to think on what
we wanted to do in life. Now, my family could raise just about
everything we needed; we were always self-sufficient. The hardest
thing for us to get was education.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he persevered, going to school when he could,
eventually earning the equivalent of a two-year degree from Mercer
University in Macon. And he has been recognized repeatedly for his
contributions to history. Among his cherished honors is his 1997
Governor's Award in the Humanities.
</P>
<P>
   He's proud, too, of a huge wooden sign _ ``THE BIGGS HOUSE'' _
at the entrance to his home, given to him five years ago by
appreciative students who have learned from his stories and
artifacts during his many school visits and lectures.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, as he prepares for another family honor _ the
unveiling in Talbotton of his great-grandmother's creations _ he
reflects on her history and the condition of black Americans in
general.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs loves quoting his great-grandmother's sad-strong
pronouncement: ``They stripped me of everything but my thoughts,
but one day I balled up my fists and held up both my arms. In my
left arm I held the idea of my freedom. In my right arm, I held on
to my religion, my art and my music.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is fond of an old saying that comes from elders in the
Congo: ``Look on the back of your hand. It will tell you where you
come from and who you are. Never go beyond the reach of your hand.
(Stay out of debt.) And any time you think you're a white man, it's
going to tell you you're a black one.''
</P>
<P>
   This lesson, he says, has remained in his consciousness
throughout his life. Touching his left hand with his right, he
says, with more wisdom than bitterness, ``Right today, I can look
right here and get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In sharing his family history, he's working hard to make sure
everyone else gets it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
