</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4926 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-THEATER11-COX     07-09 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-THEATER11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Globe a worldly stage for Bard's works
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Twilight settles over London like a cozy canopy. Along
the cobblestoned river walk on the Thames' south bank, amid the
murmuring crowd waiting to enter Shakespeare's Globe Theatre,
something's in the air. Something even beyond the anticipation of
seeing ``Julius Caesar'' on almost the same patch of ground, under
the same sky, where it premiered exactly 400 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   William Shakespeare's play baptized the original Globe. Tonight,
in the full-scale replica of that open-roofed, half-timbered,
oak-and-mortar playhouse, we may relive Sept. 21, 1599, when
``Friends, Romans, countrymen ... !'' first rang out in the
afternoon air.
</P>
<P>
   Of the view from the river walk, the Bard would recognize only
the playhouse. Modern buildings loom so close that the theater
seems a bit overwhelmed, like a chunky schoolboy wearing a quaint
brown-and-white costume in a dark, crowded pub. Construction cranes
are visible _ in this long-slumbering industrial quarter of
Southwark, the new Globe has sparked new life.
</P>
<P>
   The strains of a brass consort summon the crowd into the
theater. Most reach their seats by crossing the ``pit,'' the arena
of hard-packed earth below the stage (where ``groundlings'' can
stand and see the play for $8.50, the equivalent of the Elizabethan
penny). The foot traffic, the open air, the toting of food and
drink (ale in 16-ounce tall boys _ an amusing Americanism to
British ears) create what artistic director Mark Rylance rightly
calls ``a fairlike atmosphere.'' Patrons exclaim in wonder at the
unexpectedly beautiful painting of the stage area, so different
from theunfinished lumber of the three audience galleries that look
straight down on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see so many young faces,'' says Atlantan J.
Brien Key, a professor of history emeritus at Oglethorpe
University, gesturing at the festive, backpack-wearing pit crowd.
``It bodes well.''
</P>
<P>
   Twilight lingers at this latitude; the play begins in natural
light. Only a smokestack peeking over the thatched roof breaks the
illusion of a blue Elizabethan sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hence, home, you idle creatures!'' Brutus' officer shouts at
the groundlings. Bingo. We patrons are the citizens of Rome. A
character points to the ``trembling Tiber'' and the Thames becomes
that stream. When Caesar's party enters in a mixture of Roman,
Elizabethan and contemporary costume ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Beware the ides of March.''
</P>
<P>
   The famous words come from the pit. Surprised backpackers turn
to see, in their midst, a small figure in a toga, made visible by
the white hair fringing his pate. Suddenly, the theater is still,
actors and audience merged in a constituency of wonder, much more
intimately than one would think possible in a theater that fits
about 1,500 spectators. The Soothsayer repeats his haunting advice.
Caesar's henchmen hoist him onstage like a doll _ drawing a laugh _
then silence settles again as the emperor confronts the seer of his
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there's something in the air. The Bard's spirit. You may
scoff at the idea of friendly ghosts, but see his play in his
house, and you too will believe. You may even wonder: Why did we
ever stop building theaters this way?
</P>
<P>
   The Buddha connection
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like a metaphysical, even supernatural, response,
that would appear to be one of director Rylance's goals. Listening
to him earlier _ in an interview in his office, with a splendid
vista of the Thames and St. Paul's Cathedral _ one could understand
why Matt Wolf, London correspondent for Variety, calls the
39-year-old Rylance ``a bit of a mystic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare was so masterly _ like Buddha or Christ or some
great philosopher, so that one needs to listen very hard and repeat
his lines till their layers of meaning emerge,'' says Rylance, a
slender man with a shy, boyishly sincere way about him (qualities
that should be helpful when he plays the female half of ``Antony
and Cleopatra,'' opening July 24).
</P>
<P>
   ``This place (the Globe) has changed me,'' he continues. ``A lot
of what I did (before launching the Globe's performance program in
1997) looks like vanity to me now. When you enter Shakespeare's
space, you begin to doubt if you can `interpret' him. The audience
should interpret. The director must simply bring the words to life,
while bearing in mind: `What does this say to us now?' I use little
scenery, so that your imagination is free to paint an ideal
production, just as when you're reading the folio.''
</P>
<P>
   This approach _ at least from the evidence of ``Caesar,'' with a
mixture of mellifluous thespian types and regular, unactorish
blokes _ has a populist vigor reminiscent of the late Joseph Papp
and his New York Shakespeare Festival. That makes sense, because
Rylance spent half his life in America. Perhaps the Globe's board
considered this a useful qualification for artistic director, since
the theater was built through the vision and drive of Sam
Wanamaker, the Chicago-bred actor-producer (who died in 1993,
before seeing it completed) and already draws a healthy portion of
its audience from the States.
</P>
<P>
   Born in England, Rylance moved to Connecticut as a toddler with
his mother and private-school teacher father, and later made his
professional debut as Puck in a Wisconsin summer festival. When he
returned to England in his early 20s, Rylance formed an acting
troupe and attracted critical praise with experimental productions;
for instance, mounting ``The Tempest'' at sites sacred to various
religions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let the soft-spoken style fool you _ Rylance is no
shrinking violet,'' Wolf says. ``In fact, some thought he was a
pretentious renegade for the job. Originally the fear was that the
Globe would be some kitschy theme park. But Mark's honored the
space, taken the work seriously, with a personal vision that
addresses scholars, tourists and critics.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is borne out by box office success: Most of the
May-September repertory is sold out. (Indeed, the overall programs
of the International Shakespeare Globe Center, including
educational events and tours of the facility, draw 600,000 visitors
a year). Yet not all pundits agree on the art. Michael Billington
of The Guardian, dean of London critics, used his ``Caesar'' pan to
expose ``snickering American jocks'' in the pit and to further
opine, ``Caught halfway between academic exercise and tourist
totem, Shakespeare's Globe should urgently rethink its future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, in a city that features such distinguished bardic
directors as Trevor Nunn, Peter Hall and Deborah Warner, Rylance
must clear a very high bar if he hopes to get raves.
</P>
<P>
   In a fax from his London home, Billington added, ``I hate all
that spurious `authenticity!'''
</P>
<P>
   Never say `authentic'
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because that word had already caused similar responses,
Rylance is touchy about the word ``authentic'' and tries not to use
it at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's possible to have a truly `authentic'
theater or performance,'' Rylance says, although he takes great
pride in the fact that the Globe uses only natural sound, no
amplification, and costumes and set pieces are generally handmade
as much as possible by Elizabethan methods.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ``The Comedy of Errors'' (which won Billington's
approval soon after the ``Caesar'' review) was played mostly in
modern dress. Rylance argues that since Elizabethan dress was
contemporary for Shakespeare's audience, ``We keep the same spirit
when our men of Rome jump up from the pit dressed (in such garb as
nylon windbreakers and backward baseball caps). Then as now, these
familiar costumes are an imaginative bridge to the audience's
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rylance's Elizabethan-style use of men in women's roles was not
a major factor in ``Caesar'' (the most male of the Bard's plays),
but it will stand under a hot, bright spotlight when Rylance
himself (an acclaimed actor) plays Cleopatra.
</P>
<P>
   As to how he'll play her, he was appropriately coy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a profound understanding of women,'' says
Rylance, whose wife is on the Globe staff, ``but there is some male
and female in all of us. I do know what it is to love someone and
to fear you'll lose them. I know what it is to be an outsider. I
know what it is be perceived as a kind of whore. Shakespeare has
done the imagining for me. If I play the human being, the woman
will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken by a true mystic, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   LONDON THEATER
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's
</P>
<P>
   Globe Theatre
</P>
<P>
   Performances Tuesdays-
</P>
<P>
   Sundays through Sept. 26, rain or shine (all seats, and stage,
are covered; standing area is open to weather). $8.50 (pit) to
$42.50. Ticket information: 011-44-171-316-4703. Globe exhibition
is open 10 a.m.-
</P>
<P>
   5 p.m. in summer; guided tours available. For brochures or
information on Globe programs, write: The Globe, 21 New Globe Walk,
Bankside,
</P>
<P>
   London SE1 9DT.
</P>
