<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4927 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA-NICK11-COX     07-09 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-NICK11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Old soul' Monica in tune with herself, her audience
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monica is the teen on Nickelodeon's upcoming kids' tour who's
never really been a child.
</P>
<P>
   At least not in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   She was introduced to us as ``Miss Thang,'' which can mean
different things to different people.
</P>
<P>
   To Monica's family, the title of her 1995 debut CD was an
appropriate way to sum up the 14-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Monica was little, she would sit at the table while
Melinda (her older cousin) was struggling to do a math problem or
something,'' recalls Marilyn Best, the singer's mother. ``And she'd
say, `Oh, Melinda, that is so easy. I can't believe you don't think
you're going to get an `A' on that. That's so simple!'
</P>
<P>
   ``So we'd say, `OK, Miss Thang, you do it.' She was always `Miss
Thang' to us. It was an innocent little name.''
</P>
<P>
   But to some people, ``Miss Thang'' is an insult _ something
mothers didn't want their daughters called because it inferred they
were too grown up for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I did my first video (for `Don't Take It Personal'), I
had my hand on my hip, neck rolling, showing attitude, and that
didn't help,'' Monica says. ``I wasn't about bubble gum songs and
smiles, like you would expect someone my age to be doing. I was me.
I was singing about pain or things that were upsetting to me or
things that I deal with, and it made it hard for people to accept
me in the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice that qualification: ``In the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she knows, is an entirely different matter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 18-year-old is one of People magazine's ``50 Most
Beautiful People.'' Chanel is flying her overseas to dress her. And
Vogue magazine just named her one of the most fashionable
entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   This particular evening not included.
</P>
<P>
   Monica is dressed in a red Nike short suit, proper attire for
what will be about a six-hour-plus rehearsal starting at 10 p.m. in
a studio on the outskirts of Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first night Monica has rehearsed with her castle
backdrop in place, which she uses during what USA Today calls her
``highly engaging set'' in Nickelodeon's All That Music &AMP; More
Festival, which comes to Atlanta on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The moves her choreographer Devyne is having her go through over
and over and over again will surely translate to the Nick crowd,
and even to the Lilith Fair audience for whom she will perform this
summer (that tour visits Lakewood Amphitheatre on July 23-24).
</P>
<P>
   ``And what does that say?'' asks R&AMP;B's multi-Grammy-nominated
Me'Shell Ndegeocello, who's on her second Lilith tour. ``What other
teen singer, teen act, out here can give the kids what they want on
one tour, turn around and fit right into a tour with the Pretenders
and Sarah McLachlan? My girl ain't your average Backstreet Boy, you
know?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really appreciative of the reception I'm getting,'' says
Monica, who's signed with the modeling agency that represents Naomi
Campbell and Kate Moss. ``People are finally starting to become
comfortable with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica's music has never been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there were those persistent questions about whether
``Don't Take It Personal (Just One of Dem Days)'' was about her
menstrual cycle. But audiences took to it, and enough people bought
it to make it a No. 1 R&AMP;B single. That made her the youngest artist
ever to have a top single on that Billboard chart.
</P>
<P>
   The slower and much easier to decipher ``Before You Walk Out of
My Life'' also hit No. 1 R&AMP;B, becoming the first of her 5
million-selling singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica doesn't just sing songs, it's like she's sharing the
stories of her life,'' remarks longtime R&AMP;B vocalist Chaka Khan.
``And from a musical standpoint, you can appreciate her being able
to deliver that vocally. But when you stop and think this is a
teenager doing this, it's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's how she's always been,'' says family friend Emma Dudley,
who met Monica some 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monica had been going to choir rehearsals with her mother since
she was 2 years old. ``And when she was 7, she was doing (gospel
standards) `Precious Lord' and `Amazing Grace' like she was as old
as we were,'' says Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica was never the kind of child who would butt into an
adult's conversation, or talk back to grown people,'' adds Best, in
the living room of the modest, split-level College Park home her
only daughter lived in from birth until last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always listened,'' her mother continues. ``She wouldn't
always do what I say. But she'd listen quietly. And then not do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica has been grown since producer Dallas Austin met her when
she was 12, he says. ``She just had this presence, this `old soul'
as people say. And in addition to her voice, that's what I thought
made her special.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I was, like, `I want to be me,''' Monica adds.
</P>
<P>
   So together they came into the industry wielding almost a
complete opposite of the smiling, single-moniker teen R&AMP;B singer of
that time, Brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Brandy's debut single was about building a relationship with
someone, while Monica's ``Don't Take It Personal'' was about taking
a break from one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were different people coming from different directions, and
the rumors about us not liking each other started instantly,''
Brandy says with a slight laugh. ``And we hadn't even met. I'm
still answering questions about fights we never had and things I
didn't say.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is,'' continues Monica, ``people don't get that
we're not a group. We came together to do (the 1999 Grammy
Award-winning single) `The Boy Is Mine' because we wanted to. Not
because we had to. But people still want to ask me something about
Brandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess when they stop asking me about that, I will have
really made a breakthrough,'' she says with an expected giggle.
``But if it never happens, I'll be all right. I'll keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll have to at this particular moment. Dinner break is over,
and the pizza is long gone. Time to take her place in front of the
castle again.
</P>
<P>
   Melinda, whom Monica gave such a hard time about math, is now
her manager. She's sitting at the opposite end of the sofa where
choreographer Devyne is playfully directing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give those kids drama, girl!''
</P>
<P>
   Monica looks back, one eyebrow raised above the black sunglasses
she wears.
</P>
<P>
   Devyne knows better, the glance seems to reply.
</P>
<P>
   Monica will always give audiences Monica.
</P>
<P>
   And if they like it, fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CONCERT PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon's All That Music &AMP; More Festival
</P>
<P>
   With Monica, 98 Degrees, Tatyana Ali and others.
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. Wednesday. $31 and $41 reserved; $24 lawn general
admission. Lakewood Amphitheatre, 2002 Lakewood Way S.E.
404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   MONICA'S RECORD
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Full name: Monica Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Birthdate: Oct. 24, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Birthplace: College Park. Moved to Buckhead in November 1998.
``But I'm thinking about moving back over to the Southside,'' she
says. ``I'm too far away from home. I only want to drive over there
at certain times of the day. And there's no real soul food in
Buckhead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Making a living: The recording artist's million-selling
singles include ``Before You Walk Out of My Life,'' ``For You I
Will'' (on the ``Space Jam'' soundtrack) and ``The Boy Is Mine,''
the duet with Brandy that earned each their first Grammy Award this
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  But if the record sales stopped: ``I would go right on to a
college that accepted me and major in child psychology.'' Monica
graduated from Atlanta Country Day School with a 4.0 average. ``I'd
have a smile on my face, my head would be up and I would continue
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
