<HEADER>
A4931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-EGYPT-445&AMP;ADD-     07-09 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-EGYPT-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK'S QUEST STARTS WITH BOOST BY EGYPT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Egypt _ The new prime minister of Israel promised
Friday to ``turn every stone'' in the quest for a broader Middle
East peace. But he cautioned that it would be a few weeks before he
would be ready to make his first moves.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of a planned series of meetings with Arab leaders,
Prime Minister Ehud Barak won a powerful endorsement from President
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, who praised Barak as a friend and a ``man
of his word.'' It would only be fair, Mubarak said, to allow Barak
some time to ``reshape the situation'' after three years of tense
Arab-Israeli relations.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, at Ras el Tine Palace on the Mediterranean coast,
was suffused with an easy joviality that would have been
unimaginable under Barak's predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, whose
relations with Arab leaders were tinged with mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity, and we have to exploit it,'' Mubarak
said in hailing a ``new momentum to the peace process'' after
Barak's election. The Israeli leader, who took office this week,
said he was determined to follow in the footsteps of his mentor,
Yitzhak Rabin, in trying to cap a career of military service with a
legacy of regional peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If peace can be achieved in the Middle East, we will achieve
it,'' Barak said at a joint news conference after hours of meetings
with Mubarak Friday morning at the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   Their remarks were short on specifics, most notably on whether
Barak might be ready soon to carry out the Wye River agreement,
which, among other items, has Israel handing over an additional 10
percent of the West Bank to Palestinian control. Netanyahu accused
the Palestinians of having failed to hold up their side of the
bargain by not cracking down on terrorism. But Egypt has urged
Barak to proceed with the handover as a sign of good will.
</P>
<P>
   Barak did seem to offer a broad hint that a further troop
withdrawal might be forthcoming. ``Basically, Israel abides by its
international agreements, and we will address them as we learn them
one by one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting set off a flurry of sessions scheduled by Barak to
demonstrate his commitment to peace. He is scheduled to meet with
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, on Sunday, at Eretz Crossing
between Israel and Gaza and to travel on Tuesday to Jordan to meet
King Abdullah before heading to the United States and a meeting
with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Although Barak was not specific Friday about his plans beyond
that, the rough timetable suggested that he hoped to begin to
translate his peace pledges into action as early as the end of the
month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Barak has signaled a particular eagerness to restart talks with
Syria, whose relations with Israel remained severed throughout
Netanyahu's tenure but which Barak has suggested could be restored
in 18 months. Those hints have unnerved some Arab commentators, who
worry that an Israeli focus on Syria might mean the neglect of the
Palestinians. Their deep disputes with Israel over land, refugees
and the future of Jerusalem remain the major obstacles to any final
Arab-Israeli settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said Friday that he recognized that the quest for a
broader peace in the region should now have ``two and a half
tracks,'' a reference to parallel Israeli discussions with the
Palestinians and with Syria and with Lebanon, which Syria
dominates. ``We are determined to turn every stone in order to go
forward without jeopardizing our security and our interests,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, 57, and Mubarak, 71, are career soldiers, and their
mutual admiration was as evident in their appearance in an ornate
ballroom of the 19th-century palace as was their similar military
bearing. The two have worked together in the past, when Barak, as
chief of the Israeli military staff, was a negotiator on Rabin's
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``One difference is that I know Mr. Barak, but I didn't know
Netanyahu,'' Mubarak said when asked to compare the meeting Friday
with one in July 1996, when Netanyahu made a foray to Egypt not
long after taking office.
</P>
<P>
   With the Camp David accords of 1979, Egypt became the first Arab
country to make peace with Israel, and it has been the most active
in trying to broker a broader settlement. Barak said he had chosen
Egypt as the first stop on his tour in recognition of that status.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as long as other Arab-Israeli disputes continue to boil,
many Egyptians oppose further warming of ties. This week, a
conference in Cairo that attracted many advocates of closer ties
prompted a counterdemonstration by opposition politicians and union
leaders who burned American and Israeli flags.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mubarak showed great warmth toward Barak, his
government has deflected hints from Barak's aides that it might be
time for Cairo to make a more tangible show of good will.
</P>
<P>
   According to Egyptian and Israeli officials, former prime
minister Shimon Peres, now in Barak's Cabinet, made several
requests this week of Egyptian officials, including that they move
to revive a regional economic conference that has been moribund
since 1997. But Egyptian officials said Peres had been told that
any such gesture would be premature until real progress toward
peace could be gauged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
