<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     07-09 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WORLD CUP FINAL HAS CHINESE HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SOC-WCUP-WOMEN, SOC-WCUP-AKERS) 
(rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Ever since the American organizers took out
their indelible-ink pens and plotted the inexorable march from sea
to shining sea, there were chauvinistic and realistic expectations
that the Yanks would win this 1999 Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anybody could have predicted the sudden hysteria for this
appealing bunch of Johnettes and Paulettes and Georgettes and
Ringoettes, but there surely was the assumption that the
combination of home cooking and summer weather and loyal home
crowds would make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is reason to think the Chinese could spurt right past
the Americans Saturday afternoon in the Rose Bowl. Then, given
America's fascination with winning, what happens to all the brave
talk about marketing these charismatic athletes?
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the Chinese should win Saturday, they would merely be
recapturing command of an event they initiated.
</P>
<P>
   That's true. Like many of the items you bring back from the
mall, the Women's World Cup carries a label that says, ``Made in
China.''
</P>
<P>
   If there had not been 65,000 fans in the stadium in Guangzhou on
Nov. 30, 1991, there very likely would not be 90,000 fans in the
Rose Bowl Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese also invented pasta, even though captain Carla
Overbeck and her chef-husband, Greg, had to slip packages of pasta
(``and spices, and I carried a wheel of Parmesan cheese,'' Overbeck
recalled) with her gear back in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The American women were really pioneers back then, catching up
on a sport that was played mainly by northern European women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, we had no idea,'' Overbeck recalled this week, on a
practice field surrounded by squealing fans, and protected by a
squad of motorcycle police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had never been to a big tournament, and it wasn't even
called a World Cup,'' Overbeck added.
</P>
<P>
   Overbeck and her husband were not sure what the diet would be
like in Guangzhou, so they carried packaged foodstuff with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't let Greg cook,'' Overbeck recalled, ``so he had
to draw diagrams and point how he wanted it done. But toward the
end, they let him cook.''
</P>
<P>
   The women were glad to have a taste of home. (In this strange
hybrid land of America, Italian cuisine is home cooking.) But they
had no complaints about the ambiance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed at the White Swan Hotel, a five-star hotel,''
recalled Joy Fawcett. ``We brought peanut butter, and we got by,
just as I'm sure they're getting by over here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember it was the first time we had ever seen outdoor food
markets,'' said Michelle Akers. ``Some of the food choices were
pretty unusual. Sure, I tasted them, after taking a picture of them
first.''
</P>
<P>
   The women had enjoyed modest crowds and celebrity in college,
but 1991 was their first experience in an international tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to convince my dad to come over,'' recalled Julie Foudy.
``He came to our hotel, and there were huge banners and flower
displays, and he said, `I can't believe the magnitude of this.' It
was unfortunate the Chinese lost in the quarterfinals, but it was a
great tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans beat Norway in the finals in front of that huge
crowd of 65,000, at that point believed to be the largest ever to
see a women's sporting event in history. The Swedish organizers in
1995 had much more modest scale _ the U.S. lost in the semifinals
to Norway in front of little more than 2,000 fans _ and now the
U.S. organizers have exceeded their own grandiose dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see 65,000 in China,'' said Lauren Gregg, the
assistant coach of the American team, ``but most of them were
factory workers who were let off from work.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there is the matter of the 1999 final. The Chinese were
stung by their early loss in 1991 in front of their fans, but they
just did not have the sophisticated techniques. Today, they do.
They destroyed Norway 5-0, in the semifinal last Saturday. Their
passing is superb, their attack aggressive, their defense
coordinated, and their goalkeeping confident.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where most eyes were glazing over at talk of
women's soccer only a few weeks ago, there is a touch of midsummer
madness for this event. But would one loss to China turn the entire
experience into a pet rock or a hula hoop?
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the greatest long-standing U.S. women's team was a
volleyball team, led by willowy and talented Flo Hyman, that lived
in makeshift training camps and made grueling international swings
to prepare for the 1984 Summer Games in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, I might have predicted that women's volleyball,
with its emphasis on grace and teamwork, would become the most
popular American women's team sport. But the Americans lost the
gold-medal match to _ ah, but you guessed it _ China. And whatever
happened to women's volleyball?
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer is not going away. Some young women in the crowd
with their ``Hamm'' and ``Scurry'' shirts are going to be playing
for the U.S. in the next century. They will be competing with the
heirs to Gao and Sun in a sport that already owes a great debt to
China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
