<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-UNITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE URGES WIRING ALL SCHOOLS FOR INTERNET TO OVERCOME `DIGITAL
DIVIDE' &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JOANN ZUNIGA
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore called public schools ``a
national emergency'' Friday and proposed that all schools, old and
new, be wired for Internet access to prevent ``the digital divide''
from widening.
</P>
<P>
   Receiving a standing ovation from a convention of minority
journalists, the Democratic presidential front-runner said: ``We
have failing schools in too many places, not just urban areas. We
should recognize it for what it is _ a national emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   The same group of journalists expressed dissatisfaction on
Thursday with Republican front-runner George W. Bush. Bush had
initially declined their invitation to speak at the conference even
though he was campaigning in Seattle anyway. Then, prompted by
newspaper criticism, Bush showed up and did a brief walk-through of
the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   A recently released U.S. Commerce Department study showed a
``digital divide'' and lack of access to technology among
minorities and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the $2 billion-a-year upgrade of schools with
computer equipment and training, Gore recommended wireless
computers for older schools rather than more costly drilling of
their infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we reach every school and library? I say yes. We need to
launch an all-out crusade to stop the digital divide,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   With a majority of U.S. companies reporting a shortage of
skilled workers, Gore said investment needs to be doubled and
possible tax cuts expanded for research and development to solve
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diversity is not important merely for political reasons, but
it's a way to give access to extend economic opportunity,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   With African-American national purchasing power at $360 billion
and Hispanics at $280 billion, U.S. minorities are among the top 20
economies of the world, exceeding many countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I was appalled at the stories of advertisers not
using ethnic radio stations. Advertising discrimination is not only
wrong, it's immoral,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his previous newspaper-reporter job in Tennessee, Gore
said he realizes that less than 12 percent of newsroom staff
members are minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is deepened and strengthened when the newsroom
reflects the diversity of the community. Self-government and
dialogue is fuller, richer, more honest and healthier if it
connects with all the community,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need any phony like I-200,'' Gore said, referring to
a Washington state initiative that ended state-funded affirmative
action programs.
</P>
<P>
   In opening up the session to feedback, moderator Jean Gaddy
Wilson said, ``You can't come to a convention full of journalists
and not have tough questions thrown your way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore retorted, ``You can't come to this part of the convention
without tough questions.''
</P>
<P>
   He touched his finger to his tongue and chalked up a one in the
air as the audience applauded, catching Gore's reference to Bush's
quick walk-through of the convention's job fair Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was asked what he would do, if elected president, to stop
the assault on affirmative action in Florida and other states.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he had spoken out repeatedly in support of affirmative
action, Gore said, ``I think those who claim this is a colorblind
society are like hunters who use a duck blind to hide behind and
hope the ducks don't notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Gore and Bush, two other presidential hopefuls, former
Sen. Bill Bradley and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, also appeared at
the convention, the largest single gathering of journalists in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
