<HEADLINE>
WITH THE STARS, SPURS AND STONE COLD, TEXAS RULES THE SPORTS WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We tried to warn y'all: Don't Mess with Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But you didn't take us seriously, didja? You supposed
know-it-alls just scoffed at our slushy ice, giggled at our baggy
knickers and shrugged off our gangly Twin Towers.
</P>
<P>
   Who's laughing now, cow-chip breath? While you were busy being
dumber than a tumbleweed, our Lone Star State has blossomed into
the Multiple SuperStars State, transforming the sports world into a
private stage of Texas Triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   If y'all agree to slide into a pair of snakeskin boots, slip on
a Stetson and twang a sincere rendition of ``Deep in the Heart of
Texas'', then, and only then, might we let you peek at our Stars'
Stanley Cup, Payne Stewart's U.S. Open title or the San Antonio
Spurs' NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've forgotten, we also own the Heisman Trophy, the
only two WNBA titles, a World Boxing Association championship belt,
a pro wrestling No. 1 ranking and have four feet firmly locked
around the Women's World Cup. And, assuming they got the memo
outlining our plan for world domination, the division-leading
Rangers and division-contending Houston Astros are fixin' to play
in the World Series in October.
</P>
<P>
   Everything always has been bigger in Texas. Now, it's also
better.
</P>
<P>
   With our teams and players delivering a Texas Two-Step right on
your skeptical kissers, don't mind if we stop to pat ourselves on
the back. With the sports world gripped in a Texas state of mind,
our pride is at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, we're not quite perfect. We admit to Leon Lett's
addiction, Leon Smith's immaturity, Juan Gonzalez's pouting and
Larry Johnson's miserable existence as an $84 million ``rebellious
slave.'' But if you will bow toward where the West begins and pick
any legitimate sport this side of the X-Games, you'll find you a
tangy Texas flavor:
BASEBALL
Our two division contenders were a combined 20 games over .500
entering last night's games and produced eight All-Stars. And maybe
you've heard of a fireball pitcher from Alvin who will be inducted
into the Hall of Fame on July 25?
FOOTBALL
By breaking every collegiate rushing record and winning the Heisman
at Texas, Ricky Williams convinced New Orleans Saints coach Mike
Ditka to surrender every draft choice and right-of-first-refusal on
the Louisiana Purchase to get him. And you know we've grown up from
being only a ``football state'' when America's Team is struggling
just to remain Texas' Team.
BASKETBALL
Granted, our Mavericks are so screwed up that last year they came
out of the draft with a German teen-ager (Dirk Nowitzki) and spent
all summer trying to convince him to come to America, only to turn
around and this year come out of the draft with an American teen
(Smith), with the intent of shipping him off to Europe. But
overshadowing them is the fact that we boast the best women's team
_ the Houston Comets _ and the best active player on the planet _
Tim Duncan.
HOCKEY
It was a goal, and it is a dent. If the first Southern team to win
the title doesn't deserve the right to launch the Cup from a
second-story balcony into a pool, who does? The Cups runneth over
in Texas, where the Houston Aeros of the Internationl Hockey
League, the sport's Triple A minor-league equivalent, won the
Turner Cup with a stunning seven-game championship series victory
against Orlando.
AUTO RACING
Corpus Christi native Bobby Labonte is second in the Winston Cup
points race, Plano's Greg Ray won the IRL's Radison 200 two weeks
ago, and, after some tinkering, we're finally proud as punch of our
Texas Motor Speedway.
BOWLING
Late leader of the senior PBA's Northern California Classic is _
who else? _ Dale Eagle, from _ where else? _ Lewisville.
GOLF
Tiger Woods had the roaring gallery, Phil Mickelson had the
Major-with-the-Pager storyline, but SMU's Stewart had the biggest
heart and smallest nerves.
TENNIS
We've been known to tell a tall tale, and admittedly this is a
stretch. But Wimbledon sensation Alexandra Stevenson and first-time
champion Lindsay Davenport mastered the grass only after being
coached by Dallas' Craig Kardon, a former Fort Worth-based
instructor who helped Martina Navratilova serve-and-volley her way
into the Hall of Fame.
TRACK
In case you've already forgotten about Michael Johnson, we present
former Trimble Tech High School and TCU star Khadevis Robinson,
winner of the men's 800 meters at the USA Outdoor Championships.
PRO WRESTLING
WWF champ Stone Cold Steve Austin was a promising defensive end at
North Texas until referees kept flagging his trademark ``stunner''
move for illegal hands to the face.
CYCLING
Greg LeWho? Having pedaled past testicular cancer, Plano native
Lance Armstrong won the prologue of the Tour de France and remains
among the race leaders as they head into the mountains.
RODEO
Superman in Chaps was born in Stephenville. Seven-time all-around
champ Ty Murray recently earned $41,000 during an eight-day span of
Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association competition, shattering the
former PRCA mark for money earned in a similar time frame by
$22,000.
SOCCER
The Burn may be a ho-hum 9-9, but bet y'all didn't realize that
U.S. women's team standout Carla Overbeck went to Richardson High
School and Mia Hamm scored her goals at Wichita Falls' Notre Dame
High in '87. Hamm's becoming as popular this summer as another star
with Texas ties _ ``Austin'' Powers.
BOXING
</P>
<P>
   There are so many divisions and classifications that any state
without a champion ought to be ashamed. We got ours, newly crowned
WBA bantamweight champ Paulie Ayala, from Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Sure it's braggin,' but we can back it up. Y'all still not
convinced?
</P>
<P>
   Then go cryin' to your next president, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
