<SLUG> BC-PHONE-COSTS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES DOWN THE FOOD CHAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Sidebar to BANDWIDTH-TELECOM)  
(For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If long-distance phone service is becoming a commodity and
bandwidth is being traded at the wholesale level for pennies a
minute, some everyday telephone users may be wondering why their
phone bills are becoming more complicated and sometimes going up.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is as unfortunate for the relatively unwired as it is
welcome for the long-distance industry: You have to spend in order
to save.
</P>
<P>
   The falling cost of long-distance capacity is leading to
drastically lower per-minute rates. Some small carriers, like IDT
Corp., offer flat rates as low as 8 cents a minute for calls at any
time to anywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But many consumers who want the psychological comfort and
gold-plated service of a big-name carrier are now facing monthly
minimum charges. AT&AMP;T, for instance, recently began charging its
basic rate customers _ those who do not sign up for a special
calling plan _ a $3 monthly minimum. MCI Worldcom also charges many
of its basic rate customers a monthly minimum of up to $5. The
carriers justify the charges by explaining that they were incurring
more costs in billing and tracking low-volume customers than they
were taking in as per-minute fees.
</P>
<P>
   Regulatory changes have made bills even more complex.
Long-distance bills include a monthly charge of about $1 to cover
the cost of offering local service in poor and rural communities,
as well as a flat fee of at least $1 to cover the cost of linking
long-distance and local networks.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers were paying for these things before, but as part of
higher per-minute rates. With the Telecommunications Act of 1996,
those fees are now flat and explicit, while per-minute rates have
declined.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
