<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DEFENDS AFFIRMATIVE ACTION IN TALK TO MINORITY JOURNALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A relentlessly serious Vice President Al Gore used two
Seattle speeches Friday to defend affirmative action, call for
removal of foreign countries' trade barriers, and pledge to assure
that Americans of all backgrounds and means get access to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gore came loaded with statistics and specifics as he addressed
the UNITY '99 minority journalists conference and a Washington
Council on International Trade luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Using the tale of a Hungarian village that sounds a trumpet to
mark a 600-year-old tragedy, Gore lampooned those who claim America
is a ``colorblind'' society less than a generation after the
Supreme Court struck down school desegregation and Congress passed
civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``They use `colorblind' in the way some people use a duck
blind,'' Gore told the journalists. ``They hide behind it and hope
no one will notice.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president denounced Initiative 200, passed by
Washington voters in 1998, which struck down affirmative action
programs in hiring by public agencies and admission to state
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arrows (of racial hate) are still flying through the
air,'' he said. Gore argued that affirmative action ``ought to be
part of the arsenal'' used to remedy inequities in U.S. society.
</P>
<P>
   With 96 percent of the world's consumers living outside the
United States, America's ethnic diversity is ``a powerful economic
asset'' in the new global economy, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing inequities that remain in American society, the vice
president saw a particular gap in access to and use of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As he introduced Gore, Gov. Gary Locke cited figures that
ownership of computers in white homes far outstrips that in black
and Hispanic households.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this age of the Internet, we are in danger of leaving
people of color behind,'' Locke said. The governor warned of ``the
racial ravine now developing in the on-line world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore took up the theme. ``We need a national crusade to close
the digital divide before it gets wider,'' he said. ``We need to
have storefront computing centers and libraries where this access
is guaranteed.''
</P>
<P>
   With his bid for the White House, and interest in technology,
Gore has become Seattle's most frequent official visitor from
Washington, D.C. _ this was his third trip this year.
</P>
<P>
   Relaxed, animated and funny last month during his presidential
announcement tour, Gore Friday gave long, figure-laden answers. He
often digressed into detail.
</P>
<P>
   Locke, a politician also known as a policy wonk, defended Gore's
penchant for details and took a swing at Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's symbol-heavy visit to the state on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people want substance,'' the governor said. ``They
want a president who understands problems of the information age.
The vice president knows this stuff. He is not just touring the
state doing photo opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore sought to raise expectations for November's World Trade
Organization meeting in Seattle. He pledged that the Clinton
administration will use the WTO session to work for reductions in
agricultural tariffs and ``outright elimination of Europe's export
subsidies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity to break down foreign barriers that
have cost us jobs here at home,'' Gore declared.
</P>
<P>
   Only one incumbent vice president in the past 150 years _ George
Bush, father of the Texas governor, in 1988 _ has won election to
the White House. Gore has trailed Gov. Bush in recent polls, and as
yet has seemed unable to give a clear idea of how his presidency
would be different from President Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Gore used Friday's stopover to test themes that will set him
apart _ but not too far apart _ from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about shortcomings in public education, from use of
outdated textbooks that talk about the Soviet Union to rundown
school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you expect kids to learn the Internet if in some
schools you blow the electricity if you plug in a computer?'' Gore
asked.
</P>
<P>
   He likened today's educational challenge to that facing the
World War II generation when it came home from battle. ``After
saving Pvt. Ryan, they came home and saved public education,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush as a likely opponent, Gore has begun to talk about how
hard up America was, in the view of Democrats, when the Clinton
administration took office in 1993. It is a ploy that Republicans
used for 10 years after Jimmy Carter was driven from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the high unemployment,'' Gore intoned Friday.
``Remember the record deficits. Remember the policy paralysis.
Remember those days when the right hand didn't know what the far
right hand was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is also courting Democratic constituencies dissatisfied
with Clinton's perceived lack of support.
</P>
<P>
   At the trade luncheon, with a bevy of labor leaders on hand, he
said that labor standards and environmental protection ``are not
second class issues anymore'' in negotiating trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
   After pointed criticism at UNITY '99 over the Clinton
administration's failure to name an Asian American to the cabinet,
Gore met privately yesterday morning with Asian American
representatives. In public, he decried racial stereotyping around
the investigation of alleged leaks of U.S. missile technology to
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way some people talked about this served to increase
discrimination against Chinese Americans,'' Gore asserted. He noted
that the country has 150,000 Chinese American scientists at work in
a wide variety of fields.
</P>
<P>
   During his UNITY '99 appearance, Gore was sharply challenged by
Derrick Jackson of the National Association of Black Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of ... calling I-200 phony, which is easy to do, would
you do something that Clinton did not do, which is fight for
affirmative action in the white communities and the white
boardrooms of America?'' Jackson asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``My recollection is he did speak out,'' Gore said of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly moved on, arguing that racial barriers remain and
must be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pledge to you I will do all I can to close the opportunity
gaps,'' Gore said. ``We don't need more scapegoats or more phony
ballot propositions like I-200. We need to all examine the kinds of
attitudes that crop up in response to national problems and
national debates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
