<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY, JULY 11 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following Money
and Business articles for release Sunday, July 11, 1999:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELIMINATE: INVEST-SULLIVAN-Q&AMP;A &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE SECTION FRONT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PEROT-JUNIOR (Undated) _ Ross Perot Jr. did learn a thing or two
at his father's knee: how to think big, and how to belly up to the
public trough, for example. By Allen Myerson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BANDWIDTH-TELECOM (Undated) _ All the fuss about bandwidth
ignores one fundamental: All but the final link to your home or
office is a commodity, with rapidly falling prices. Understanding
that may force a rethinking of the telecom business and telecom
stocks. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-COSTS (Undated) _ Why your long distance company keeps
tacking new charges on your phone bill when the actual cost of
providing long distance links is falling.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-NAPA-WINE (St. Helena, Calif.) _ Farmers and vintners in
California's Napa Valley have long exploited the region's
combination of soil, climate and topography to make wines that can
compete with those of the great Bordeaux estates. Shrewd marketing
and a robust economy have propelled premium Napa wines into a $100
million-a-year business. By Alan Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GALLO-PROFILE (Healdsburg, Calif.) _ Seven years ago, when
the giant E.&AMP;J. Gallo Winery launched its first entries in the
superpremium-and-up wine category, Gina Gallo was just 25 and
preparing for a career in sales with the family business. Today
Gina is a winemaker at Gallo's money-no-object Sonoma operation,
and perhaps more importantly, the face of the new Gallo in a
multi-million dollar ad campaign aimed at taking the venerable
brand up market. By Lawrence Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-PARTNERSHIPS (Undated) _ Winemakers consider their business
more art than science, and the field is thickly populated with
headstrong entrepreneurs and family scions. In such an environment,
partnerships where neither side has the final say might appear
doomed to deadlock and collapse. By Alice Feiring.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-STOCKS (Undated) _ Six months into the euro era, some of
the assumptions about how European stock markets would behave once
the single currency arrived are looking shaky. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INSIGHT-INVEST-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Compared to many strategists six
months ago, Edward M. Kerschner, chairman of the investment policy
committee at Paine Webber Inc., was pretty optimistic about 1999.
But the gains recorded thus far have made him cautious about the
future. Last week he took some time to talk about how the stock and
bond markets are likely to move in the last six months of the 20th
century.
</P>
