</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-WOMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TO PROVIDE TOUGH TEST FOR NEWEST U.S. SPORTS STARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.) (See also SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN, SOC-WCUP-AKERS) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ When Julie Foudy attended the 1994 men's
World Cup final at the Rose Bowl, the 1999 world soccer
championship for women was five years on the horizon and was still
being planned for small stadiums on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were saying, `No, that's not what this deserves, that's not
what it is worth,''' the American co-captain said. ``When they
moved it to bigger stadiums, we were like, `Right on, this is
something we can do.' We knew we had the personalities and the
talent. We just needed to be promoted better.''
</P>
<P>
   Convinced of their own appeal beyond the grass roots soccer
community, the American players were right. Saturday's Women's
World Cup final between the United States and China will attract a
sellout crowd of about 90,000 at the Rose Bowl, which would be the
largest audience ever to watch a women's sporting event in the
United States, and, organizers believe, in the world.
</P>
<P>
   A soccer tournament that relatively few people knew existed a
month ago has commanded such legitimacy and buzz that scalpers are
seeking as much as $1,000 for a pair of tickets that would normally
sell for $110 apiece. The match will be broadcast to a national
television audience by ABC, and will provide the American women
their grandest stage on which to display their soccer skills and to
convince sponsors and promoters that there is a need for a
professional league in this country following the 2000 Summer
Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look back in 20 years, I really think we are going to
say that the Billie Jean King-Bobby Riggs tennis match, Title IX
and the 1999 Women's World Cup are the three largest pillars
supporting women's sports in this country,'' said April Heinrichs,
a star of the women's team that won the 1991 World Cup who now
coaches women's soccer at the University of Virginia. ``We've shown
that if you put enough money into women's sports, people will come
to watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, victory is by no means certain for the Americans, who
have lost two of three matches this year to China by 2-1 scores,
and are considered by many to be underdogs. With a fast,
technically skilled team that has begun to express individual
creativity and assertiveness after years of regimented, tentative
play, China has swept through its first five games, scoring 19
goals and allowing two. It beat Norway, the defending champion, by
5-0 in the semifinals, the worst defeat in its history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think China, all-around, is technically the better
side,'' Greg Brown, the Australian coach, said after his team lost,
3-1, to the Chinese. ``They have flair, they have confidence and
they play the ball all around the park.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to success for the Americans appears to rest with their
uncertain defensive back line of Carla Overbeck, Joy Fawcett, Kate
Sobrero and Brandi Chastain. The defense has provided many nervous
moments, especially in the opening minutes of matches, with
momentary lapses that leave the United States vulnerable. The
Americans surrendered a goal to Nigeria in the 2nd minute and put a
ball into their own net five minutes into a quarterfinal match
against Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think is important for the U.S. team is to improve its
defensive play,'' said Jarl Torske, an assistant coach of Norway.
``Mistakes by the back four will be punished if they do that
against the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   While the American defense is experienced, it lacks overall
speed. Sometimes it is also left vulnerable when the defenders
sprint ahead in the aggressive American attack. Pressing forward,
the defense was left open to a counterrattack by the Chinese in
losing by 2-1 in April at Giants Stadium, ending the United States'
50-game home unbeaten streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans must be particularly vigilant toward Chinese
forward Sun Wen, who is tied for the lead with seven goals in this
World Cup. Sun is equally dangerous with or without the ball, and
is adept at slipping unnoticed behind a defense, which she did in
chipping a shot over goalkeeper Briana Scurry in that April match
at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans normally use a zone defense, but coach Tony
DiCicco said he would consider marking Sun man-to-man, likely with
Overbeck, the captain, or Sobrero, a rugged one-on-one defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just have to be a goon all game long,'' Sobrero said.
``I love that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midfield, playmaker Liu Ailing organizes a Chinese attack
that wastes no motion in storming down the flanks and that
threatens both with the long ball and with touch passing.
</P>
<P>
   American midfielder Michelle Akers, who smothered Sissi of
Brazil in the semifinals, could be assigned to Liu. Kristine Lilly
and Foudy, the other American midfielders, will be charged with
maintaining possession, working the ball from side to side to
offset the clinging Chinese defense and with providing serviceable
passes to American forwards Mia Hamm, Tiffeny Milbrett and either
Cindy Parlow or Shannon MacMillan.
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said Friday that he may start MacMillan because she is
faster than Parlow, but he noted that Parlow is a better defender.
Also, placing MacMillan into the lineup at the start would deprive
the Americans of getting a second-half lift by bringing her off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are equal to the Chinese in attack, although Hamm,
the world's leading scorer with 111 international goals, has not
put the ball into the net in the last three matches. Milbrett, a
compact, explosive player, has become the team's most reliable
scorer. MacMillan has a wicked knuckleball of a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will have an edge with the home crowd and with the
experience of having won the 1991 World Cup and the 1996 Summer
Olympics. China, which finished second at the Atlanta Olympics, has
never won a major tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience is one up on them,'' Milbrett said. ``Quite
possibly, we might be a little more competitive than them. Not by
much, but I think that helps.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
