<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0312 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEROT-JUNIOR-ART-$ADV     07-09 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEROT-JUNIOR-ART-$ADV11-900(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SON RISES IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When it comes to dynasties, Gov. George W. Bush has
said that his father's idea of the perfect son was Al Gore. Ross
Perot's idea of the perfect son is Ross Perot Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Lest Ross Jr. have any doubts about what was expected of him,
his father wrote it all down. At his college graduation, Ross Sr.
presented him with ``Everything I Know About Business,'' a treatise
that later filled 62 pages in the elder Perot's autobiography.
``Avoid undertaking new projects on a grand scale,'' it advised _
at least until after completing some low-risk trials.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, Ross Jr. has become the leading real estate
developer in a state where builders can wield more power than
governors or mayors. And now he is bending some of his father's
rules as he sets out to transform a swath of downtown Dallas the
size of about 19 Manhattan blocks into office buildings,
apartments, shopping concourses and a sports arena that, he boasts,
will give this city its own Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd better go back and read the guidelines,'' the younger
Perot said with his usual purposeful frown, sitting in an office
down the hall from his father's, both of them behind locked and
guarded doors. ``You're going to get me in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Though he is in a different trade than his father,
who built a fortune with one computer services company and has now
gone public with another, Perot has proved himself his father's son
in recognizing government as the businessman's best patron.
</P>
<P>
   As his father built his first company, Electronic Data Systems,
on winning government contracts, the son has built his real estate
empire on winning all manner of government support.
</P>
<P>
   His latest project has been based on persuading Dallas voters _
usually stingy with public money _ that they should pay $125
million of the $230 million cost for his basketball team's new
arena, the anchor for a billion-dollar-plus real estate
development.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken Donald Trump 24 years to finish two buildings on
the site of Manhattan's West Side rail yards, a tract of about the
same size. In Dallas, Perot had the dirt flying just two years
after he bought the Dallas Mavericks of the National Basketball
Association in 1996 and a year after his initial downtown
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Touring the site in his black Chevrolet Suburban, his top aides
filling its three benches, Perot bounced over curbs, across
abandoned railroad tracks and past derelict grain elevators, avidly
describing everything he plans _ down to pasting corporate logos on
the overpasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some neat naming opportunities on the bridges,'' he
told his assistants. ``Tastefully done.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot has the ready ability to turn his dreams into steel,
concrete and glass. In a business usually run on other people's
money, he uses large amounts of his own, gathered from earlier real
estate investments that he made with his father.
</P>
<P>
   His successes have had a deeply personal benefit. Even four or
five years ago, questions about how much his father's money and
connections had contributed to his own progress drew pinched
responses. His father was only an investor, Perot would say, while
full, legal, decision-making authority rested with him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with less to prove, Perot can warmly describe childhood
weekends spent looking over real estate with his father. Or, for
all the unwanted attention of being a Perot, the considerable
benefits that the name carries. ``The key thing is certainly you
can go see people,'' he said. ``They'll take your phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Congenital determination, as well as money, may allow Perot to
bring the ailing center of this city a revival that has been beyond
the abilities of anyone else. To buy the Mavericks, he had to
muscle aside Thomas O. Hicks, Dallas' own leveraged-buyout king.
Even though Hicks said he could build an arena for a city
investment of just $40 million or $50 million, Perot persuaded
civic leaders to allot about three times as much. Hicks and Perot
became partners in the project, although Perot remained the
developer.
</P>
<P>
   His headstrong ways have decisively shaped his image. No other
Texas builder is so eagerly courted or publicly reviled. To those
who have opposed the arena or his other vast projects, he is a
ruthless privateer intent on raiding the public's purse.
</P>
<P>
   Early last year in Dallas, Perot and Hicks spent $2 million to
gain voter approval of arena subsidies. An opposition group calling
itself ``It's a Bad Deal'' spent just $75,000 but came within 1,700
votes of winning. The group's members continue to shadow Perot.
``This guy is the biggest welfare baby the public has ever seen,''
Sharon Boyd, the group's leader and a former member of the Dallas
Planning Commission, said months after the vote. ``What has he ever
done without public assistance? His daddy built his own company
with public assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot responds that the jobs and tax revenues produced by his
projects far exceed any public costs. And, as he coolly told other
developers last fall at the annual meeting of the Urban Land
Institute here, braving opposition is his duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of this business is politics,'' he said, in a measured
corporate monotone that contrasts with his father's buzz-saw twang.
``As real estate developers, it's our job to go in there and get
beat up.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, back at Perot Systems after two presidential
campaigns, remains a walking editorial cartoon, a rambunctious runt
with a tomahawk profile. The son, at 5 feet 11 inches, has
conventional broad-shouldered good looks _ as perfectly pressed,
meticulously slicked back and emotionally composed as if he had
rumbled loose from a marble monument to Texas deal-makers.
</P>
<P>
   The older Perot argues that a Texas habit _ calling the father
``Big'' and the son ``Little'' when they share a given name _
shouldn't apply to him and his son. ``He's Big Ross and I'm Old
Ross, and there's no better place to live than in your son's
shadow,'' he says.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In politics, however, the younger Perot, apart from favoring
free trade, stays out of his father's way. Recalling the uproar
over his 1992 donation to President Bush's re-election campaign
before his father joined the race, he has refused to back Governor
Bush's presidential campaign until his father's plans are clear.
``I've learned my lessons,'' Perot said. ``I'm staying on the
sidelines for Dad.'' (Dad, while saying he prefers business to
politics, won't rule out another race.)
</P>
<P>
   At 40, Big Ross is less exciting than his father but also less
excitable _ a reflection of the influence of his mother, Margot,
family friends say. As the oldest of five children and the only
son, one friend said, ``Ross Jr. was trained for, conditioned for
being in the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not your normal childhood. His father, an Annapolis
graduate, surrounded his son with military heroes, former prisoners
of war and astronauts. The son distinguished himself as an Air
Force fighter pilot and later as the lead pilot on the first
helicopter trip around the world. Such training is the best
business school, the elder Perot contends, saying, ``When you're
flying a fighter, you don't have time for committee meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   He needs no prompting to tell how he offered his son, then about
14 years old, 75 cents for each bush he would plant along the road
in front of the old EDS headquarters in Dallas. Just inches into
the ground, Ross Jr. struck rock. Rejecting his father's offer to
adjust the price, Ross went at the task with a pickax. Now, his
father says, ``Anytime he buys a piece of real estate, he checks to
see where the rock is.''
</P>
<P>
   And how did he rebel? Anything like George W. Bush's wild living
in earlier days? The younger Perot throws back his head and laughs
with rare abandon. ``It wasn't really part of the program in the
Perot family,'' he says. ``Rebellion was not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, friends say, he was driven to make his own mark, to
give the lie to anyone who dared say that all his advantages were
inherited.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he assumed that he would work for his father. He started
out as a land man, leasing drilling rights for his father's oil
company. He planned to become an EDS salesman, but in 1984 his
father sold the company to General Motors. He decided to turn his
family's real estate holdings into the basis of a business, the
Hillwood Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   With his father's help, he began buying thousands of acres north
of Fort Worth, counting on the city's continuing sprawl to turn
ranches and farms dotted with post oaks and mesquite into
subdivisions and shopping malls. The city, anticipating added tax
revenue and jobs, was happy to annex his land and provide services.
</P>
<P>
   Though the collapse of the Texas economy in the late 1980s
dashed the Perots' initial plans, they still had the cash to buy
thousands of additional acres from desperate sellers. But Ross
Jr.'s new plan _ to build an air cargo hub to be called Alliance
Airport _ required help from government at all levels. After a tour
in the Hillwood helicopter, Jim Wright of Fort Worth, then the
speaker of the House and a prime beneficiary of the Perots'
campaign donations, pushed a bill through Congress for a far larger
project than the Federal Aviation Administration had recommended.
Federal, state and local governments provided more than $200
million in cash and tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Local real estate experts estimate that after some early
reversals, Perot has gained hundreds of millions of dollars turning
his Fort Worth property into the Southwest's largest hub for cargo
shipments. ``Alliance was Ross' EDS,'' said Tom Luce, a Dallas
lawyer and political adviser for father and son.
</P>
<P>
   Perot raised his bet on the area when he bought the 2,500-acre
Circle T Ranch in 1993 for less than $20 million from a desperate,
bankrupt Nelson Bunker Hunt, who had once insisted that he wouldn't
part with it even for $200 million. Perot, then 34, talked of
building a whole new city there, with thousands of office workers,
golfers, shoppers and residents.
</P>
<P>
   But the ranch was in Westlake, a hamlet of 250 affluent
residents who had moved to the country to escape traffic and
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   For Perot, though, not even lines on a map are unalterable. And
so the Westlake aldermen ousted a mayor antagonistic to him and
then gave up two-thirds of the town's property, including the
Circle T. In a special Saturday meeting, the Fort Worth City
Council, eager for development, declared the land Fort Worth's.
Amid ensuing lawsuits, it was unclear just who was the Westlake
Mayor and which city or town could claim the Circle T.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Perot was turning back to Dallas. Pointing out
his office window in North Dallas at the office park where his
father had built EDS and then, in the early 1980s, tried to expand,
Perot delivered a short sermon. ``The neighborhood groups did not
want Dad to fill out the campus,'' he said, and the city sided with
the neighbors. ``That's when Dad left Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Left _ and started an exodus, to the northern suburb of Plano.
The elder Perot bought land that accommodated several newcomers,
starting with EDS. ``Then another Dallas company, Frito-Lay, then
Fina, then Dr Pepper moved to Plano,'' Ross Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, Dallas' leaders presided over one of the
nation's deadest downtowns _ so dead that even Dallas Mayor Ron
Kirk, gazing out his own office window, couldn't resist saying,
``You go on a tour of downtown and its attractions now, and you
ask, `What can we do with the other 45 minutes of the hour?'''
</P>
<P>
   Decades earlier, Perot's father had said he would never run for
public office or buy a sports team. But Ross Jr. figured that if an
airport could cause the value of the surrounding land to soar, why
not an arena?
</P>
<P>
   In early 1996, he bought a 67 percent stake in the Mavericks for
$125 million, bluntly declaring that he was in the game for the
real estate, not love of the sport. ``A lot of people look at a
basketball team as an anchor tenant for an arena,'' he said in
announcing the purchase. ``I look at an arena as the anchor tenant
for a much larger program.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, he wanted to persuade the city to pay up and the
state to let the city raise its taxes for that purpose. The Texas
Legislature, by approving a measure letting Dallas raise its car
rental and hotel taxes, allowed backers to say that the cost would
fall only on city visitors.
</P>
<P>
   When the city then balked at Perot's demand that it pay more
than half of the arena costs, he took to the air in his company's
Bell L-3 helicopter. He carried one suburban mayor after another to
view possible arena sites in their towns. He encouraged television
helicopters to follow, giving their pilots his radio frequency so
that if cameramen missed a shot, he could swoop in again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like an Air Force mission,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kirk, pressured earlier to avoid giveaways, was now under
pressure to make a deal. ``Either way, the voters were going to
scream at you,'' he recalled. ``But you didn't want to be a mayor
that let a team walk away from a city that still hasn't gotten over
losing the Cowboys 25 years ago.'' He agreed for the city to pay
$125 million and the team owners just $105 million. In January
1998, voters just barely approved the deal.
</P>
<P>
   To guide his development plans, Perot visited 25 cities from
Shanghai to Berlin and consulted with Edward P. Bass, the Bass
brother who led his family in reviving Fort Worth's downtown.
Setting his usual high-pressure deadline, Perot gave five
architecture firms only four weeks to submit designs, though most
competitions take months.
</P>
<P>
   At the deadline, the architects, gathered at a downtown business
club, all had tales of working every day and many nights. When
Perot told Ricardo Legorreta, Mexico's best-known architect, that
the competition was great fun, Legorreta grinned and answered,
``More fun for you than it is for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot's chose David M. Schwarz of Washington and Fort Worth over
Helmut Jahn and other international stars. Schwarz, whose nostalgic
designs have made him royal architect to the Bass family, proposed
an updated brick-and-glass version of a college field house. Perot
says the final design, to be revealed as soon as this week, will be
substantially different.
</P>
<P>
   The arena will be called the American Airlines Center, with the
airline's $190 million payment over 30 years going to the team
owners, not to the city. Perot has dubbed his whole project
Victory, a name he announced at a news conference where a film and
brochure compared his ambitions to those of Churchill, among
others. His design requirements include a victory balcony where
athletes can wave their trophies to crowds below.
</P>
<P>
   The balcony is far more likely to accommodate Hicks' hockey
team, the Dallas Stars, which won the Stanley Cup last month, than
Perot's Mavericks, with a record of 19 wins and 31 losses in this
year's shortened season. Perot points out that his team (20-62 the
year before) is improving.
</P>
<P>
   Perot and Hicks are on the verge of extending their partnership
to the full Victory development, with Hicks saying that he plans to
buy a 50 percent interest.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, meanwhile, Perot's plans for the Circle T have
come up against officials weary of his muscular tactics. Fidelity
Investments wanted to build a 300-acre office park for 2,700
employees but posed one condition: settlement of the feud with
Westlake, so the company would know what municipality it would be
in. With Westlake having become more receptive, Perot asked Fort
Worth to kindly drop all the Circle T claims he had once
encouraged, arguing that the city would still benefit from
development in a neighboring town.
</P>
<P>
   At that, Fort Worth's leaders reached their limits. They
demanded that Perot repay the city's legal fees and provide other
compensation. After the city blithely let some Perot-imposed
deadlines pass, Perot agreed to build a job training center and buy
water supplies from Fort Worth for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, too, expects him to do more than build his
brick-and-mortar fortune. A grateful Kirk has challenged him to
take as much responsibility for his city as the Basses of Fort
Worth have taken for theirs. ``Ross Perot, with his wealth and
experience and family,'' he said, ``can do things for Dallas that
nobody else can do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
