<HEADLINE>
NEW MEDAL FOR AN OLD, OLD SOLDIER: FRANCE HONORS 102-YEAR-OLD U.S.
VETERAN &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By BOB TUTT
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Thomas J. Clark first saw military service in 1916
when the Texas National Guard was futilely trying to catch up with
a revolutionary Mexican leader named Pancho Villa.
</P>
<P>
   When U.S. entry into World War I the next year led to his
call-up for active duty in the Army, Clark wished he could get out
of it. He couldn't, of course.
</P>
<P>
   On the battlefield in France the next year, he served honorably
but came to revile war.
</P>
<P>
   ``War really is hell,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed this anti-war sentiment to family members Friday
before Pierre Lepetit, the French consul general in Houston,
arrived to present the 102-year-old Clark with the Legion of Honor,
France's highest national award. The presentation was made at the
St. Dominique Village retirement center, where Clark, a widower,
resides.
</P>
<P>
   As a gesture of gratitude, French President Jacques Chirac has
decreed that all Allied servicemen who served on French soil during
World War I should receive this medal and the rank of chevalier,
making Clark a member of the honorary society that dates to the
days of Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac issued the decree last year with the approach of the 80th
anniversary of the Nov. 11, 1918, armistice that ended the Great
War.
</P>
<P>
   Lepetit said an estimated 2,000 American veterans are living and
thus eligible for the honor. So far, 600 have been located.
</P>
<P>
   Clark accepted his award graciously.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Thorndale in East Central Texas, he was one of the
million-plus Yanks who participated in the bloody Battle of
Meuse-Argonne in October 1918.
</P>
<P>
   Looking through letters Clark wrote home during the war, Joan
Clark of Houston, a granddaughter, found examples of how he
deplored the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated Nov. 6, 1918, which he said was written while
he took shelter in a barn, he told his mother: ``I have been on the
front for three weeks, and believe me, war is what Sherman said it
was. The sight I have seen up there will never be forgotten, and I
hope never to see it again, but if I have to, I can and will do it
like a man.''
</P>
<P>
   And in a Nov. 29, 1918, letter, he wrote, ``Whenever you hear a
man say that he had been under heavy shell fire and was not afraid,
well, you just might call him a big liar, which he is.''
</P>
<P>
   He and three brothers served in the Army in France, and all
survived. After the war, Clark remained in France for a year as a
military policeman. He recalls that year fondly.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Texas, he became a tank car dispatcher for
the Missouri Pacific Railroad. While working in Palestine, he
married Ruby Catherine Murrell.
</P>
<P>
   They had been married 66 years when she died in 1990. They had a
son, Donald, now also deceased.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter-in-law, Norma Clark, said Thomas Clark has taken
life's sorrows in stride and has never lost his sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   He demonstrated that Friday when a television photographer aimed
a bright light at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a pistol,'' Clark joked, ``I'd shoot out that
light.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
