u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT     07-09 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON SIDES WITH NEW YORK DAIRY FARMERS ON MILK-PRICE
CARTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ANTI-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton completed her first
campaign tour across New York on Friday with an embrace of the
state's dairy farmers, declaring her support for federal
legislation that would assure them higher prices but likely force
up the price of milk for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Clinton again presented herself as a New
Yorker-in-training, eager to be educated in a series of forums with
voters in the state, she had no problem offering a position on the
milk price cartel, one of the most difficult issues in New York
state politics today.
</P>
<P>
   When the director of the Oneida County Farm Bureau, Pat Van
Lieshout, asked if New York should be permitted to join the
two-year-old federally sanctioned cartel that sets a minimum price
for milk paid to its member farmers, the first lady instantly
answered yes, in a clear sign of the preparation she has done for
her possible Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In declaring her position, Mrs. Clinton appeared to put herself
at odds with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, her likely Republican opponent
in next year's Senate race, who has sought to prevent New York's
inclusion in the Northeast Interstate Dairy Compact.
</P>
<P>
   And she risked alienating downstate voters more concerned with
supermarket prices than the plight of farmers. She also, for the
third time in two weeks, appeared to deviate from a policy promoted
by her husband's administration, in this case, the Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say that I support the dairy compact,'' Mrs. Clinton
said at a forum in Utica on Friday morning. ``And I support the
inclusion of New York, Pennsylvania, and I think it's, from what I
know now, a very important step for the dairy farmers, and, I would
argue, over the long run for the entire population to have more
price stability and more fair returns on investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone works harder than dairy farmers,'' Mrs.
Clinton added. ``Dairy farmers are on call basically 24 hours a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton disclosed her position at the fourth of her
``Listening to New Yorkers'' sessions, the centerpiece of this
campaignlike swing, in which groups of people have been invited to
sit down with Mrs. Clinton in orchestrated discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Friday Mrs. Clinton continued to go to considerable lengths to
present herself as a political ingenue, as she invited lessons from
health care workers, teachers, nursing home residents, farmers and,
at a Syracuse auto plant, factory workers. ``Thank you for
explaining this to me!'' she told a farmer in Utica Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great idea!'' she told a job trainer in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, her willingness to engage in a spontaneous exchange
with a dairy farmer on the compact issue suggested more depth to
Mrs. Clinton's knowledge about New York state than might otherwise
be suggested by the forums she has organized.
</P>
<P>
   It also was one more sign of her evolution into a full-fledged
New York political candidate. Throughout this week, Mrs. Clinton _
or Hillary, as she was addressed more than once by New York voters
_ offered clear hints that she had done her New York homework,
whether it was in addressing New York reporters by their first
names or mentioning obscure statistics about the state.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Friday she said, ``If upstate New York were a
separate state, it would rank 49th in job creation, compared to all
of the other states in the entire country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton had originally considered staying in New York for
more events in Albany on Saturday, but now plans to return to
Washington on Saturday morning. She is to return to New York on
Monday, for three or four days of visits in the New York suburbs,
the part of the state where the Senate election could well end up
being determined.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast compact is scheduled to expire on Oct. 1. The
legislation before Congress would renew it and enable New York, New
Jersey, Delaware, Maryland and Pennsylvania to join the cartel.
</P>
<P>
   The dairy compact issue is one that has long roiled this
economically depressed part of New York. It has tended to divide
politicians more by region than by party; both of New York's
Democratic senators, Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Charles Schumer,
support allowing the state to enter the organization.
</P>
<P>
   But many downstate leaders, from Giuliani to Mark Green, the New
York public advocate, have argued against it, warning that it could
raise the cost of a gallon of milk in New York City from about
$2.75 to $3.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
