A4960 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-09 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL INVESTIGATORS ASK CITY TO REVAMP POLICE DEPARTMENT
PROCEDURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a lengthy investigation of the New York City
Police Department, federal prosecutors have amassed evidence of
systemwide problems in the department's handling of police
brutality complaints, and are pressing the Giuliani administration
to undertake reforms, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If the city does not agree to changes sought by the U.S.
attorney in Brooklyn, Zachary Carter, the Justice Department could
sue the city, seeking a court-ordered overhaul and possible
oversight by a federal monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who opened his investigation after the August 1997
torture of Abner Louima by two officers in a Brooklyn station
house, is now in secret talks with top Giuliani administration
officials over a possible settlement, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One hurdle is that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a staunch defender of
the Police Department, has said he would be unwilling to accept the
imposition of a federal monitor or other outside oversight of the
department, which is by far the largest in the country with 39,000
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's precise findings were not known Friday, but the Justice
Department has said that he has examined whether incidents of
excessive force by officers ``were the product of systemic
deficiencies in police operations, including possible failures in
intake and investigation, discipline and supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have charged that police officials do not aggressively
pursue allegations of brutality by officers, even in cases in which
outside investigators have found evidence to support the charges.
For example, Carter's office has looked at how the department
follows up cases referred by the Civilian Complaint Review Board,
which investigates allegations of police wrongdoing, and cases in
which the city has settled lawsuits charging officers with
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's investigation is one of at least 10 nationwide of
police and sheriff's departments by prosecutors looking for
patterns of brutality and other civil rights violations. The
actions reflect the Justice Department's use of a 1994 law that
grew out of the Rodney King beating in Los Angeles, which
authorizes federal prosecutors to seek changes in the operations of
local departments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
