<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4961 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRAWL10-COX     07-09 2452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRAWL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Absence of sprawl from Bush agenda may stunt fast pace
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the first in an occasional series on presidential
campaign issues and Gov. George W. Bush's record.
</P>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Chili's, Home Depot, Bank of America,
Macaroni Grill, Brake Check, Blockbuster _ that's one segment in
the nearly unbroken chain of restaurants, stores, subdivisions and
apartment complexes linking Austin to Round Rock. The strip is on
Interstate 35, but it could be almost anywhere in America.
</P>
<P>
   Planners and policy wonks warn that such ``urban sprawl'' is
gobbling up green space, clogging roads and homogenizing the
American landscape. But ``sprawl'' means different things to
different people.
</P>
<P>
   For Betty Riggs, an avowed hater of strip malls who works at
Kelley's Cleaners in Round Rock's historic downtown, it translates
into ``more traffic, more problems.'' But Carmen Gutierrez moved to
Round Rock from San Angelo so she could be nearer to such stores
and restaurants. Janet Bell, a ``stay-at-home mom'' who has found
her slice of suburban heaven in a Round Rock subdivision, can't
wait for La Frontera, a shopping and office development, to open
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawl is a complex issue that doesn't easily lend itself to
political pronouncements. Nevertheless, Vice President Al Gore
views I-35, and other strips like it, as a path to the White House
_ especially since his likely Republican opponent, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, doesn't view it as an issue at all.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the Democratic front-runner, is betting that development
and traffic issues _ traditionally the concern of cities and states
_ will resonate with an increasingly suburban electorate in a
national campaign. After nearly a decade of unprecedented
prosperity, he thinks that quality-of-life proposals to preserve
open space and shorten commutes will find a receptive audience.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence to support his strategy: Last November, voters
across the country approved nearly 200 anti-sprawl initiatives.
Nearly half of the nation's governors _ most of them Republicans _
referred to sprawl in their inaugural or state of the state
speeches this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wasn't one of them. Austinites have been wringing their
hands over rapid growth for almost three decades, but sprawl hasn't
emerged as a statewide issue in Texas as it has in states such as
Georgia, Maryland and New Jersey. With no public clamor, Bush has
been virtually silent on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's basic idea about sprawl is that it's being
driven by a desire for better education for kids. He thinks the
solution is doing something about inner-city schools,'' said Bush
campaign spokesman David Beckwith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than try to engineer where people live and work, we
should help improve schools by introducing vouchers and choice,''
Beckwith added.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bush supporters wish he'd take a closer look at the sprawl
issue. Former Indianapolis Mayor Bill Hudnut, who now works for a
Washington-based nonprofit organization that studies land use, said
he wrote a letter to Bush urging him not to let Gore seize sprawl
for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Vice President Gore is on the right track, and I
really feel strongly that it would be good if George W. would carve
out a position on the subject,'' Hudnut said. ``I think that it's
important for the Republican Party to be perceived as a party
that's concerned about quality of life, about livability issues and
about how we're going to grow as a country in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving against sprawl
</P>
<P>
   Hudnut said Bush thanked him for his input _ and declined to
comment on sprawl. In contrast, Gore plans to make ``livability'' a
centerpiece of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sprawl that has developed around our cities has
transformed easy suburbs into lonely cul-de-sacs, so distant from
commercial centers that if a family wants an affordable house, a
commuting parent often gets home too late to read a bedtime
story,'' Gore said in May while serving as host at a ``National
Town Meeting for a Sustainable America.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous studies illustrate the problem, Gore and other sprawl
critics say: Between 1983 and 1995, the distance of the average
American commute increased 36 percent, according to the U.S.
Department of Transportation, and time spent commuting went up 14
percent. The American Farmland Trust, an anti-sprawl advocacy
group, says that since 1970, development has consumed 30 million
acres of U.S. farm and ranch land _ a total area larger than
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, local planning commissions and zoning boards, not
the White House, have dealt with development. But Gore believes the
federal government has contributed to sprawl by subsidizing car
travel and the extension of infrastructure to undeveloped areas,
and that Washington should take steps to curb it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wants federal officials to encourage Smart Growth _ a term
Austin uses for its effort to direct growth away from
environmentally sensitive areas _ by spending more on mass transit
and offering tax breaks for denser development on vacant land in
central cities. He advocates federal money for cities and states to
buy land and preserve it as open space.
</P>
<P>
   Bush doesn't want ``centrally planned decisions on people's
lifestyles that override people's desires,'' Beckwith said. But
Gore insists that the federal government can help communities
manage growth without being a ``beauty commissar'' or ``national
zoning board.''
</P>
<P>
   Without federal help, anti-sprawl efforts are already gaining
steam in cities and states across the country. Last November, New
Jersey residents voted to spend $1 billion to preserve 1 million
acres _ half of the remaining open land in the state _ as open
space. In Georgia, the Legislature recently created a powerful
regional transportation agency and gave Gov. Roy Barnes
far-reaching authority to curb sprawl in the Atlanta area. In
Southern California, voters drew clear boundaries around several
rapidly growing cities between Santa Barbara and Los Angeles. From
now on, voters there will have to approve new subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, voters last year approved a $65 million bond issue to
purchase or prevent development on 15,000 acres in the Barton
Springs watershed. They also signed off on a $40 million bond issue
to buy and develop parks and greenbelts in East Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Not a hot Texas topic
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, Austin is the exception to the rule in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sturzl, who heads the Texas Municipal League, is aware
that sprawl has become a ``hot topic'' nationwide, but he hasn't
heard much discussion about it in the Lone Star State. Because
Texas is so big, its cities have always been geographically large
compared to those with similar populations in smaller Eastern
states, Sturzl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How in the world can you keep population from expanding
geographically as it grows numerically? he asked. ``I don't think
Governor Bush has had any cause to even address that issue in
Texas.'' Many Texans simply don't view ``sprawl'' as a bad word,
according to state Sen. Jeff Wentworth (R-San Antonio), and they
are suspicious of government attempts to manage growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of latent Texas opposition to that sort of
planned land use. People want to have a little green space; they
want to have their own plot of ground; they don't want to build
vertically like they have in Chicago, New York, Philadelphia and
Boston,'' Wentworth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As population increases, we're going to have what they call
'urban sprawl,' and what people actually involved in it call
'homeownership.'''
</P>
<P>
   Without a public cry in Texas for anti-sprawl measures, Bush's
record on the issue is limited. He has signed several bills
designed to promote regional planning, including a comprehensive
water bill and legislation written by Wentworth that gives counties
additional regulatory authority.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also signed measures limiting the power of Texas and
its cities to regulate development. Bush's staff helped draft a
1995 ``takings'' bill that gave landowners the right to sue cities
and the state for regulatory actions that devalue their property by
more than 25 percent. Supporters describe the bill as a private
property rights measure, but critics say it makes it more difficult
for state and local officials to manage growth. Bush also approved
legislation allowing landowners to set up ``water-quality
protection zones'' to avoid Austin's development rules, and a bill
exempting some building projects from the city's Save Our Springs
law, which limits the density of development over the portion of
the Edwards Aquifer that feeds Barton Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Even though sprawl may not rank high on Texans' list of concerns
right now, some critics say Bush has failed to show leadership on
an issue that could be crucial to Texas in the 21st century.
Between 1982 and 1992, Texas lost 489,000 acres _ an area roughly
three-fourths the size of Travis County _ of ``prime and unique''
farmland, according to the American Farmland Trust. That loss was
more than in any other state, and was 11.5 percent of the total
loss in the United States during that period, according to the
American Farmland Trust. Emil Moncivais, San Antonio's planning
director, said his city recently adopted a master plan in an effort
to avoid becoming ``one big megalopolis'' like Dallas-Fort Worth.
But he said the state has done little to promote the inner-city
development that can limit sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor hasn't said anything about it. He hasn't said we
need to take some kind of action, be proactive,'' Moncivais said.
``To tell you the truth, I think we need legislation at the state
level to give local people the ability to do what they want to do.
And that's not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Kramer, who heads the Texas chapter of the Sierra Club, said
leadership from the governor's office has been critical in states
trying to curb sprawl _ and that Bush hasn't shown any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, he has no record on it,'' Kramer said. ``He's been
very much in the corner of those who have tried to restrict the
ability of various levels of government to affect land use. That's
just not in his vocabulary, to deal with the sprawl issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From a national perspective, Bush is definitely behind the
curve on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprawl's good side
</P>
<P>
   But will Bush's position on sprawl _ or lack of one _ hurt him
in the presidential campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Not with people like Janet Bell. She and her husband Roderick
began dating when they worked together at Dell Computer Corp. in
Austin, and they shared an apartment in the city before they were
married. But when it came time to raise a family, they headed
straight for the northern suburbs. They've got three kids, a
three-bedroom house they built in 1992 for $98,000, and a minivan
in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   New houses have sprung up all around the Bells since 1992, but
Bell said she doesn't mind Round Rock's rapid growth _ and she
plans to vote for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' she said, pausing to wipe tomato sauce
from her daughter's face. ``There's more to do. It increases our
property value. All the shopping centers and everything _ we're
excited about the La Frontera.''
</P>
<P>
   Builders note that growth is inevitable in a time of economic
prosperity. They point out that new households are being created at
a rate of 1.3 million a year, and that people are migrating to
areas where they can own a home and find work. Increasingly, those
places are in the suburbs: Some studies indicate that three out of
every four new jobs are being created in so-called ``edge cities''
located on the outskirts of major cities.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, they say, the American dream for many people
still consists of a home with a back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people still look to the American dream as being a
single-family home on a decent-sized lot with a back yard and a
sidewalk out front, not living in compact development,
high-density, or up rather than out,'' said Ohio builder Charlie
Ruma, who heads the National Association of Home Builders.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson County Rep. Mike Krusee, who comes from one of the
fastest-growing counties in the country, said Gore's anti-sprawl
talk may alienate people like his constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williamson County is suburban sprawl. To say you want to stop
it is to say you don't want there to be future growth or prosperity
in Williamson County,'' Krusee said. ``Growth presents some
challenges,'' Krusee said. ``Nongrowth presents even bigger
problems. Nongrowth presents poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore insists that his goal isn't to stop growth or stamp out
suburbs, but to make them more ``livable'' by preserving green
space and relieving traffic congestion. Supporting mass transit and
denser inner-city development would give people additional choices,
not mandate a certain lifestyle, he argues.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Garreau, author of the seminal sprawl book ``Edge City,''
believes Gore has hit on an issue with ``political juice'' _
although it presents risks for both parties. It's difficult for
Republicans to criticize development that is being driven by the
free market, Garreau said. Democrats need to be careful not to fall
into traditional liberal criticisms of the suburban lifestyle _
especially since about half of Americans now live in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But Garreau believes people will respond to the right message.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a situation where you have unprecedented economic
success, and something is still dreadfully wrong, something is
still missing, and people will respond to someone who says he can
fill that void in their lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garreau argues that sprawl is like pornography _ it's hard to
define, but people know it when they see it. And most people, he
says, don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever it is they think they once had, they no longer think
they have it: identity, community, civilization, soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Riggs, who has lived in Georgetown for all of her 58 years
and worked at Kelley's Cleaners in downtown Round Rock for the past
19 of them, is the sort of person Gore is trying to reach. It used
to take her 10 minutes to get from Georgetown to Round Rock in the
morning _ now it takes up to 40. She hates the anonymity of the
chain stores at strip malls, preferring the small-town feel of
places like Kelley's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they say that your taxes are going to go down
because you're going to get this industry or Sun City, they don't.
All you get is more traffic, more problems,'' Riggs said. ``I know
things have to grow, but you get tired after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
