<HEADLINE>
INDEXES END ON HIGH NOTE FOR A 2ND CONSECUTIVE FRIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the second consecutive Friday, the stock market
finished the week with a hat trick, as all the three major indexes
reached new highs. Bond prices ended slightly lower as Ford Motor
Co. completed the biggest corporate bond issue ever.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, and its finance company, Ford Motor Credit, sold $8.6
billion in bonds, including $1.8 billion of 32-year bonds that were
priced to yield 7.529 percent, or 1.4 percentage points over the
yield on the government's 30-year bond. In a reflection of the
recent strong demand for these and other corporate bonds, which
offer higher yields than the Treasury market, government bond
prices managed to remain relatively stable ahead of and during the
record sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average finished the day at 11,193.70,
up 66.81 points, or six-tenths of one percent. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index rose 8.86 points, or six-tenths of a
percent, to 1,403.28. The Nasdaq composite index climbed 21.21
points, or eight-tenths of a percent, to 2,771.86.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, the Dow was up half a percent, hitting two new
highs. The S&AMP;P 500 rose nine-tenths of one percent, hitting two new
highs, while the Nasdaq index was up 1.9 percent, setting three new
highs.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, the price of the 30-year Treasury bond was
down 5/32, to 89 22/32. The yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, rose to 6 percent from 5.99 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year bond bounced around all day. It popped
over 6 percent as some dealers apparently were selling as a way to
hedge against losses if the Ford bond sale prompted a sell-off in
the Treasury market. It dropped below 6 percent as traders decided
that the Ford deal was going well. But then it inched back to 6
percent as the afternoon wore on.
</P>
<P>
   Both stock and bond investors will be keeping a close eye on the
barometers of economic growth and inflation that the government
will release next week. Any hint of rising inflation _ which is not
expected _ or acceleration in the pace of economic growth could
send stocks lower and interest rates higher.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday will bring the report on producer prices, which could
give some signal if the recent rise in industrial commodity prices
is affecting prices. The government's overall retail sales report
for June will also be released Wednesday. Sales in retail stores
rose sharply last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index for June comes on Thursday and
industrial production figures follow on Friday. The University of
Michigan survey on consumer sentiment will also be released Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Speaking about the lackluster day in the bond market, Thomas
Connor, the head government trader at J.P. Morgan Securities, said,
``The bond market wasn't going to get up and go because we want to
see the CPI number next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Equity investors will also begin concentrating on corporate
earnings reports as the second-quarter reporting season gears up.
It is the optimism about the outlook for earnings growth the rest
of the year that is helping bolster stocks in the face of the
quarter-point interest rate increase by the Federal Reserve at the
end of last month and the possibility of another later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   The two main compilers of corporate earnings forecasts are
predicting a double-digit increase in the profits for the 500
companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's stock index. First Call Corp.'s
forecast is an increase of 11.2 percent, compared with the second
quarter of 1998. IBES International's prediction is 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since Fed policy-makers raised their short-term interest rate
target to 5 percent on June 30, investors have been debating
whether another rate increase will be necessary to curb economic
growth and keep inflation in check.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the two-year Treasury note, which is sensitive to
Fed rate moves, finished Friday at 5.58 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
