<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rare birds, these rookies, going to Super Bowl team
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When rookie Patrick Kerney reported to Falcons
mini-camp this week, he was greeted by teammates with open arms. Or
make that open palms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys were asking me for a loan,'' Kerney, the
team's first-round draft choice, said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive end from Virginia was one of 15 rookies _ nine
draft choices and six free agents _ to take part in the three-day
mandatory camp, which ended Friday. Although not much can be judged
from noncontact drills, Atlanta coach Dan Reeves spoke favorably of
his first-year players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I think they are doing a really good job of fitting
in, working hard and trying to get ready to come in and compete,''
Reeves said. ``That's what (the rookies) have to do, and we still
got a couple of weeks left to work with them before (training)
camp.''
</P>
<P>
   All rookies have to adjust in moving from college to the pros.
The transition of going to the defending NFC champions is more
intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, playing with a team that was in the Super Bowl
last year is a dream come true,'' said tight end Reggie Kelly, a
second-round pick from Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched all these guys when I was in high school and
college, and now I'm actually up here playing with and against
them,'' Kelly said. ``It's a privilege and blessing ... I'm going
to accept the challenge and do what I can to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Rondel Menendez, a seventh-rounder from Eastern
Kentucky, said he was nervous when he began working out with the
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in awe at first, just from the fact I was with a team
that was in the Super Bowl last year,'' Menendez said. ``It was a
big surprise for me, especially since I came from such a small
school. The competition is so much greater up here. It has been an
eye-opening experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerney was surprised when he put on his practice jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird to see yourself in a new uniform,'' he said. ``I
was so used to wearing the Virginia colors the past four years. I
am a bit in awe when I think about where I started at (as a college
walk-on) and where I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerney and Kelly wasted little time impressing the veteran
players. Kerney is expected to add depth to one of the NFC's best
defensive lines. Kelly is an acclaimed blocker who will allow the
Falcons to employ more two-tight-end sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat hustles to every ball with great effort,'' second-year
linebacker Keith Brooking said. ``That's what you need on defense _
to have 11 guys go all out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the young tight end (Kelly),'' veteran linebacker
Jessie Tuggle said. ``This kid is already running routes like a
veteran. But again, it's hard to tell how good or bad anyone is
until they put on the pads.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Falcons trotted off the field after the last mini-camp
practice, it was hard to tell the veterans from rookies. Most of
the rookies still have a full head of hair, but that might not be
the case later this month when training camp begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to save everything for the right time,'' Tuggle said
with a sneaky smile. ``It's all about timing, and it's too early
right now. We'll wait until training camp to actually pull out the
rookie tricks. But they got some things in store for them, for
sure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
