<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRIVATE-DIARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS SHORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 11)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forced to Share The Inner-City Turf
</P>
<P>
   For the last several years, Richard Huber, the chief executive
of Aetna Inc., has been quietly trying to tap the business
potential of the nation's central cities, which have long been
neglected by big private insurance concerns like his. Aetna has
recruited African-American and Hispanic sales representatives to
canvass their inner-city neighborhoods for customers, not only for
managed-care plans but also for retirement accounts, another big
part of the company's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was so taken by Aetna's efforts that he
enlisted Huber as a traveling companion last week on a tour of some
of the nation's blighted urban and rural areas. Huber was honored,
but also a bit concerned that the new visibility of his efforts
would encourage other companies to compete on this virgin
territory. ``This is an attractive business opportunity, and I
don't want everyone to know about it,'' he said as Clinton met with
business leaders in the Mississippi Delta on Tuesday. ``He's
blowing my cover.''
</P>
<P>
   _JOHN M. BRODER
</P>
<P>
   He's Down but Not Out
</P>
<P>
   Few executives have mastered the art of living well as fully as
Marshall S. Cogan. But now Cogan, chairman of Foamex International
and a director and former chairman of United Auto Group, is
mastering the art of cutting back. Earlier this year, he sold his
Long Island home, in Southampton, for about $10.5 million. He is
also selling part of his modern art collection through Vivian
Horan, a New York dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Cogan, who is 62, won't give up the high life altogether. He has
been negotiating to buy another Long Island house _ John Scanlon's
sprawling historic home on Main Street in Sag Harbor, for an
estimated $2.3 million, according to a person close to the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Cogan's privately held Trace International has had poorly
performing stakes in both United Auto Group, which operates auto
dealerships, and Foamex, a manufacturer of polyurethane. Cogan once
controlled the companies, but no more. If shareholders approve
Roger S. Penske's controlling investment in United Auto Group,
Cogan will receive $750,000 a year for agreeing not to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon, best known as a public relations executive, is now a
managing director at DSFX Inc., a private investigations firm.
Neither he nor Cogan returned calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   _GERALDINE FABRIKANT
</P>
<P>
   `A Breather' From the Tycoons
</P>
<P>
   As the champagne and Oysters Rockefeller circulated at the
Museum of American Financial History in lower Manhattan on Thursday
evening, the financial historian Ron Chernow _ author of ``Titan:
The Life of John D. Rockefeller Sr.'' and guest curator for the
museum's new exhibit, ``Rockefeller Revisited'' _ confirmed that he
was at work on a new biography. But his subject may surprise his
Wall Street fans: Alexander Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Chernow, who has written tomes about the House of Morgan and the
Warburg family, said he had started a biography of Andrew Carnegie
but abandoned it after deciding that ``it was time to give the
moguls of the Gilded Age a breather.'' Besides, after wrestling to
bring so many tight-lipped tycoons to life, he said, it was
refreshing to have a subject ``who committed his every thought to
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   -DIANA B. HENRIQUES
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
