<HEADLINE>
THOME CARRIES CLEVELAND FANS' ACCOLADES INTO ALL-STAR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The honored-to-be-going platitudes tumble out in a
stream of consciousness, spoken in an accent that is equal parts
Midwestern twang and Southern drawl. The infielder with the body
built for baseball talks about childhood dreams. He clasps his
hands, places his thick forearms on his knees, and highlights the
support of family. Reminded of other invited stars, he gives
endless compliments to the company he will keep Tuesday night. He
mentions the fun and excitement surrounding midsummer classics.
</P>
<P>
   But even when Jim Thome's All-Star Game thoughts are collected
and sorted and stripped of their aw-shucks emphasis, you are still
left with one big ``Thank You'' note addressed to the fans. In a
city known for its devotion to baseball, the clean-cut Cleveland
first baseman is a fan favorite. And come All-Star time, that's
what counts.
</P>
<P>
   Thome will represent the American League for the third
consecutive time in his six-year career. His last two appearances
in the All-Star Game have been by popular demand. The 28-year-old
Thome, one of two AL nonpitchers with a batting average below .300
elected to start this year (along with DH Jose Canseco), received
an astounding 679,801 more votes than runner-up Rafael Palmeiro.
Thome can credit a large part of his success in the polls to the
people of Cuyahoga County. Despite Palmeiro's first-half
statistical superiority, fans saw something more deserving in
Thome's play.
</P>
<P>
   With his .278 batting average, 13 home runs, and 48 RBIs
(entering Friday night's game), Thome stands as the classic example
of indiscriminate fan voting. The popularity contest placed the
Cleveland star ahead of a more deserving player from Texas. There
was no doubt Palmeiro's .351 average, 20 home runs, and 73 RBIs
would earn him a spot as a reserve, and on Wednesday, AL manager
Joe Torre named him to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Indians, Palmeiro didn't have the benefit of
record-setting attendance, zealous voters, or a first-half schedule
packed with home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't answer every question the media's going to ask me
about why I'm there and why Palmeiro isn't (as a starter),'' said
Thome. ``It's life. That's the nature of the game and how things
work sometimes. I've said before that he's very deserving and
probably should start.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously got the better numbers. But as a player we
can't control what the fans do. We can't control who they pick, why
they pick them. I think obviously there were enough people who
thought highly of me as a player to put me in there. Granted, you
have career years, you have average years, and some years you're
going to have below-average years. As a player, you have to realize
that there's going to be a lot of people who talk about your
perfomance, whether you do good or whether you do bad. You can't
get caught up in that.''
</P>
<P>
   The infielder also considers reputation and fan familiarity a
factor. He points toward the 17th straight All-Star appearance and
16th consecutive start for Cal Ripken. Thome claims consistency
over several seasons, rather than exceptional numbers over the
first-half of one season, earns more votes.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans know Thome continues to struggle with back problems
this season. Two pillow-sized ice bags after games leave no doubt
the injury affects his play, especially hitting. He believes fans
account for nagging injuries as well as season-long potential.
Thome contends that the 1,364,692 voters who punched out his name
factored in his role on a team boasting the best record in baseball
and the room for improvement in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star first baseman has been a model of consistency for
Cleveland. Last season, he became the first lefthanded hitter in
franchise history to record 30 home runs in three straight seasons,
and he's only slightly behind the same pace in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, Thome's postseason play keeps voters coming
back to his name. In 1998, he had team highs in home runs (6) and
RBIs (10) in 10 playoff games. The home run total tied a
single-season playoff record set by Len Dykstra, Ken Griffey Jr.,
and Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   He set a standard with four home runs in the AL Championship
Series against eventual world champion New York. Two years ago, he
blasted two home runs in the World Series against Florida. The list
continues with his 1995 performance in Game 5 of the ALCS against
Seattle when Thome hit a two-run homer in the sixth that gave the
Tribe a win and a 3-2 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   The power comes from his broad-shouldered, 6-foot-4-inch,
225-pound frame. And a lot of hard work with hitting coach Charlie
Manuel, who has guided Thome through the Cleveland system, has
helped produce steady improvement and impressive results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very coachable,'' said Manuel. ``He'll listen and, at the
same time, he's a real hard worker. He's very strong, but he had to
do a lot of work on his approach to the ball and his swing. His
dedication to the game and the fact that he loves to hit and all
the hard work together, that's why he's successful. Sometimes I
don't think he realizes the work he did when he was in the minor
leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   With his socks pulled high in honor of his grandfather, a stocky
build inherited from German-Irish ancestory, and a family of
baseball players from Peoria, Ill., behind him, Thome walks, talks,
and displays the work ethic of a throwback player. Even his mental
approach to the game could be considered old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the fans come first and players are paid to do
whatever is best for the team. He talks about the importance of
being cordial when signing autographs. He still remembers how
delighted he was when, at age 10, he snuck into the Cubs' clubhouse
and got Dave Kingman's autograph.
</P>
<P>
   After the acquisition of Matt Williams in 1997, the player
trained as a third baseman moved to first without any protest. With
regular third baseman Travis Fryman out until September with a torn
knee ligament, Thome has worked out at third over the past week and
may start there Saturday night against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a starting first baseman on the All-Star team and he's
willing to make a move to third base for the good of the team,''
said manager Mike Hargrove. ``I think that says a lot about Jimmy's
talent to be able to do that. Second of all, it says a lot about
Jimmy's character. There's not enough good things you can say about
that. I don't know if there are many players who would do that
(switch).''
</P>
<P>
   Infield/first base coach Brian Graham also commends Thome's
``All-Star personality,'' the blend of working-class attitude and
respect for the game and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the Midwest and I think it's very family-
oriented there,'' said Thome. ``You grow up and you're really close
to your family, and I think that really helped me out. My dad was a
blue-collar worker and he had to work very hard for what he's
gotten. I think that rubbed off on me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Thome first made it to the big leagues, his father wrote
``25 DBTH'' inside his baseball cap. It was a lasting message from
father to son, reminding the young player, ``Don't believe the
hype.'' Good or bad. Never let yourself get too high or too low.
</P>
<P>
   And when you're the AL's top choice to play first base in the
All-Star Game with more than one million voters lending support,
don't lose sight of all the little things that count.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
