</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DAMAGE-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. SURVEY FINDS WIDE DESTRUCTION IN KOSOVO VILLAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., skedded earlier as KOSOVO)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Two-thirds of the houses in villages
across a wide swath of Kosovo are uninhabitable because of war
damage, mainly burning by Serbs; most of the schools are severely
damaged or destroyed; much of the water is polluted, and a large
part of the agriculture is ruined, according to a U.N. survey
released this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopes that the humanitarian situation may not be as serious as
initially feared seem to be over-optimistic,'' said the report,
issued by the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The grim assessment was based on reports on 141 of Kosovo's
roughly 2,000 villages by U.N. shelter and refugee experts,
nongovernmental organizations and NATO peacekeeping troops, all of
whom filled out standardized forms.
</P>
<P>
   Warning of a ``serious humanitarian threat,'' the U.N. report
said, ``Large pockets of peoples identified by this first sample
may be facing situations that could evolve into an emergency.'' The
report said that while preparing Kosovo's damaged homes for winter
is a fundamental objective, ``there is mounting evidence that basic
requirements still need to be provided'' to significant numbers of
people.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Rapid Village Assessment _ The First Cut,'' the report
is the first of a series of studies over the next four to six weeks
intended to plot the needs of Kosovo's people after the destruction
wrought by Serb forces and NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The report cautioned that the statistical sample was too small
to accurately reflect all of Kosovo and noted that aid agencies
would make their first visits to areas where they perceived the
greatest need. But, the report said, the results suggested a
pattern that should be verified ``with all due diligence.''
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that 102 of the villages in the survey had also
been included in a survey of 650 villages conducted up to January
1999, after some initial fighting but before the Serb drive to
evict Albanians from Kosovo had emerged in full force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comparing this data we find that these 102 assessed villages
now report a two-fold increase in severely damaged homes and a near
tripling of completely destroyed,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the village survey found that 64 percent of houses
assessed had been destroyed or severely damaged, and an additional
20 percent had sustained slight or moderate damage.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials noted in one of their periodic ``emergency
updates,'' issued Friday, that ``the level of destruction is
extremely varied.'' Some areas are barely touched, like the city of
Prizren, which was used as a collection point to push refugees
south to Albania, or the eastern area of Kosovo, where U.S. troops
are now stationed and which had a proportionately larger Serb
population and less activity by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like villages in the Drenica region, the birthplace of
the KLA, and areas around Djakovica and Pec that were KLA
strongholds or supply routes, were devastated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the report cautioned that there were no precise figures
of homes destroyed yet, it said initial estimates placed the number
of severely damaged and uninhabitable homes anywhere from a minimum
of 40,000 to 50,000 to a maximum of 90,000.
</P>
<P>
   The report added that unlike the first 12 months of the
conflict, the damage in recent months included urban areas in the
north and west. For example, the previously undamaged city of Pec
is estimated to have suffered a loss of between 40 percent and 45
percent of housing stock. Urban Djakovica and Mitrovica sustained
losses estimated at 30 percent, with new severe damage in
surrounding rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Forty percent of the water in the villages surveyed was
determined to be of poor quality because it had been polluted by
``a range of materials, including human as well as animal
corpses.'' War crimes investigators have discovered a number of
incidents in which Albanians were killed and their bodies _
sometimes eight or nine at a time _ were thrown into wells and then
covered with rocks and dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 12 percent of previously existing health facilities still
exist in those villages that were surveyed,'' the report said.
``And 60 percent of previously existing schools have been severely
damaged or destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Food could be an increasing problem as more people return.
``Food availability in villages has been dramatically reduced over
the past three months as shops were looted or destroyed and
agricultural production ground to a halt,'' the report said. It
added that wheat production was expected to be 50 percent lower
than normal, while the corn crop was estimated at 10 percent to 20
percent of its usual level. Livestock losses were estimated at 40
percent to 50 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
