<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banged-up Martin says he'll finish race behind wheel
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ NASCAR driver Mark Martin, who underwent
arthroscopic knee surgery on Wednesday, completed both of his laps
in Friday's first-round qualifying for the Jiffy Lube 300.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 40, had only the 29th-fastest qualifying speed at New
Hampshire International Speedway, failing to gain one of the first
25 starting spots for Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   If Martin doesn't have one of the top 36 speeds after today's
second round, he'll still make the field by using a provisional.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is third in points and 234 behind leader Dale
Jarrett, says he'll try to finish the race, despite having to drive
with a cast on his left wrist and a heavy brace on his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going all the way,'' Martin said. ``That's it. We're gonna
race as hard as we can race.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who has six top-five finishes in eight starts on the
1.058-mile oval, has to be helped into his No. 6 Ford. He says his
ribs are still sore from his hard crash last week in practice at
Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Busch Grand National driver Matt Kenseth will practice in
Martin's No. 6 Ford today in case a relief driver is needed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotta be put in (the car),'' Martin said. ``I can do
whatever I really need to, but I don't really need to crawl in
myself, so I'm not. The knee hurts an awful lot and I hurt my ribs
trying to drive the car with no power steering. That's just how it
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett and the pace car
</P>
<P>
   There's been some debate as to whether Jarrett should have been
black-flagged last week for passing the pace car in the final laps
of the Pepsi 400 at Daytona Beach.
</P>
<P>
   After a multicar crash with three laps left caused the race to
finish under a yellow flag, Jarrett, who won the event, drove on
the track's apron to conserve fuel. He momentarily passed the pace
car, but moved behind it before crossing the start/finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Triplett, NASCAR's director of operations, said the rule
preventing cars from passing the pace car is designed to keep
drivers from gaining an advantage under caution. Competitors could
pass the pace car to get to pit road faster or pass it to gain a
lap.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett said Jarrett gained no advantage, so he wasn't
penalized.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan gets another year
</P>
<P>
   MB2 Motorsports, owned by University of Georgia graduates Tom
Beard, Nelson Bowers and Read Morton, has extended the contract of
driver Ernie Irvan through the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan, 40, is in his second season with the team, which jumped
into Winston Cup racing in 1997. Irvan, who's 22nd in points, has
16 top-10 finishes and won three poles in 47 starts in the No. 36
Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, obviously, there are other opportunities in the
Winston Cup garage,'' Irvan said. ``You always keep your options
open. But I'm committed to these guys and our sponsor. I'm not
finished, and I think we can win some races with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Another driver for No. 58
</P>
<P>
   Fledgling Ford owner Scott Barbour introduced his third driver
this season at New Hampshire. Barbour, who started the year with
Ricky Craven behind the wheel before replacing him with Loy Allen
Jr., last month, now has veteran Hut Stricklin.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, the 1994 Daytona 500 pole winner, finished 40th in both
races he started for Barbour this season. Allen didn't qualify at
Pocono on June 20, and the team skipped the road-course event at
Sonoma, Calif., the following week.
</P>
<P>
   Stricklin, who hasn't won a race in 268 career Winston Cup
starts, failed to qualify for six races this year in the No. 90
Ford of owner Junie Donlavey, and finished 33rd in his only start
at Charlotte on May 30. He didn't qualify in Friday's first round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
