<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GM ORDERED TO PAY $4.9 BILLION IN BURN LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   General Motors was ordered to pay $4.9 billion to six people
severely burned when the fuel tank of their 1979 Chevrolet Malibu
exploded after a rear-end collision. The verdict, by a 12-person
jury in a Los Angles state court, came after a 10-week trial in
which the accident victims had argued and produced some evidence
purporting to show that General Motors had known the automobile's
design was unsafe but had not changed the design because it would
have cost about $8.59 a vehicle to do so.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS CONTINUE TO SET NEW HIGHS
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index set three new highs during the week,
ending up 21.21 points, or eight-tenths of a percent, at 2,793.07.
Also recording new highs were the Dow Jones industrial average,
which finished at 11,193.70, up 66.81 points, or six-tenths of one
percent, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which gained
8.86 points, to 1,403.28.
</P>
<P>
   THE STEADY DEClINE OF THE EURO
</P>
<P>
   Little more than six months after 11 European nations adopted
the euro as a new single currency, it has become a source of
embarrassment and anxiety. The euro has steadily declined against
the dollar from nearly $1.18 at its introduction on Jan. 4 to just
below $1.02. Despite continuous exhortations by European central
bankers about the euro's fundamental value, it now has a good
chance of dropping below the value of a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   TRASH HAULER'S LEADERS SOLD SHARES
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Waste Management Inc. sold $57.6 million of
company stock in May, eight weeks before the company said it would
miss earnings forecasts, setting off a 37 percent decline in its
share price.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN BACKS CHINA ON TRADE GROUP
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Zhu Rongji of China and Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi of Japan announced an agreement that amounted to Japan's
endorsement for China to join the World Trade Organization. China
is eager to join the group and has sought support from many of its
134 members, but its negotiations with Washington _ essentially the
arbiter of China's efforts to join _ remain at an impasse.
</P>
<P>
   CONTROVERSIAL INTERNET FEE IS KILLED
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Commerce has asked the Internet's new
governing body to eliminate a controversial $1 fee on Internet
address registrations, to open its board meetings to the public and
to draft clear restrictions on the boundaries of its authority.
</P>
<P>
   LIQUID AUDIO SURGES IN DEBUT
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Liquid Audio, which sells software that lets consumers
download music from the Internet, surged $21.5625, to $36.5625, in
their first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ALLSTATE PLANS TO ACQUIRE AN INSURER
</P>
<P>
   Allstate, which has been expanding beyond its core property and
casualty business, is acquiring American Heritage Life Investment
for $1.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   SENATOR ROTH PROPOSES TAX CUT
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, William V. Roth
Jr., R-Del., proposed reducing the lowest federal income tax rate
to 14 percent from 15 percent to give a modest break to
middle-class taxpayers. The proposal will be the centerpiece of the
$792 billion, 10-year tax-cutting bill to be taken up by the Senate
this month. It would also expand IRA and 401(k) retirement savings
and include a plan to end the marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND REDUCES ITS BANK RATE
</P>
<P>
   Thailand's central bank cut its official bank rate for the
second time in two weeks to a record low, aiming to revitalize the
nation's economic recovery by lowering borrowing costs. The
benchmark rate was cut 1.5 percentage points, to 4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 2131EDT &QL; 
