<HEADER>
A4980 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE10-COX     07-09 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon sets track record in winning Jiffy Lube pole
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Rusty Wallace set the tone in first-round
qualifying for Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300 at New Hampshire
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon finished it.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was one of 17 drivers who broke the speedway qualifying
record, covering the flat, 1.058-mile oval in 29.037 seconds, an
average speed of 131.171 mph. The lap broke Ken Schrader's
two-year-old track record of 129.423 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised with our lap,'' said Gordon, who won
his second pole at New Hampshire. ``That is the most grip I've seen
at this track in quite a while. It's nice to have the air dams and
spoilers where they're at right now, because they're really giving
us a lot of grip.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, the first driver to qualify on Friday, had the
second-fastest lap at 130.770 mph. Bobby Labonte will start third,
followed by Schrader and Kyle Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon won his series-high sixth pole of the year and his fourth
in the last eight races. Gordon, the two-time defending Winston Cup
champion, also has a series-high four victories, but he still finds
himself trailing points leader Dale Jarrett by 394 points at the
halfway point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, 27, finished a disappointing 21st in last week's Pepsi
400 at Daytona International Speedway, after barely missing a
multicar accident with only three laps left. Gordon also had five
finishes of 31st or worse in the first 16 races, which helped put
him in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of put every race behind us,'' Gordon said. ``Once a
race is over, whether it's good or bad, we move on. Right now,
we've been a little inconsistent. We've won some big races and
we're fifth in points, so we can't complain too much. But we've had
some inconsistencies that have kept us out of the points lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless Jarrett really has some problems, though, I don't see
anyone catching him.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who trails Jarrett by 177 points, might be the only
driver with any shot of catching the points leader, who will start
ninth on Sunday. Still, Labonte says he isn't counting Gordon out
of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just at the halfway point,'' Labonte said. ``We've still
got half the races left to run. If you look at (Gordon's) team,
they're probably the ones who can do it, if anyone can overcome
that many points. I'm not counting anyone out, and I'm sure they're
not counting themselves out, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dale Earnhardt Jr., who chipped his right shoulder in
a Busch Grand National race last week, will start next to his
father in the seventh row. ``Little E'' was seven one-thousandths
of a second faster than his father, qualifying 13th at 129.710 mph.
Earnhardt Jr. finished 16th in his Winston Cup debut at Concord,
N.C., on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to do was beat Dale Jr., and I didn't,''
Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt fared better than Ford owner Jack Roush, whose five
cars all failed to qualify on the first day.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
