</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez's illness supplies Chen a sudden start
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rookie pitcher Odalis Perez was scratched from his
start Friday night because of illness, so the Braves started fellow
rookie Bruce Chen, who originally was going to be skipped in the
rotation heading into the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine is still set to pitch against the Red Sox on short
rest today; same with Greg Maddux on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was told Friday morning he'd be making his first start
since being recalled from Class AAA Richmond when John Smoltz went
on the disabled list. His last start in Richmond was five days ago,
so the rest worked out perfectly, even if Friday's start didn't.
Chen was roughed up for three runs, all on home runs, and left
after four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you want to know when you pitch, so you can prepare
yourself for the team,'' Chen said. ``Since I was (going to be) in
the bullpen, I knew I had to be ready for every team.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Perez's first missed start of the year. ``I couldn't
sleep last night,'' said Perez, who has had fever and a headache.
``I want to be pitching. I don't want to be around here, not being
able to go out and do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez had gone six starts without a win, dating back to June 8
against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could use a break; he's done a lot of pitching,'' Braves
manager Bobby Cox said. ``Chen could use a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston manager Jimy Williams didn't seem too concerned either
way. ``Two lefties, you know,'' Williams said. When asked if he
still expected to see Glavine and Maddux, he quipped: ``That's my
understanding, unless they want to get sick, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko's hot bat
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko finished off the Marlins series with four hits in
his last 10 at-bats to raise his batting average to .300 for the
first time since the middle of May.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his second home run of the month Thursday after hitting
just three homers in June. He had two doubles in June. He already
has four in July.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko also has improved considerably in hitting with runners in
scoring position since the start of the season. Through May 31,
Klesko was hitting .200 with no home runs and 12 RBIs with runners
in scoring position. In the six weeks since then, he has hit .348
with two homers and 12 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been feeling good,'' Klesko said. ``I've been driving the
ball into the gaps in right-center and left-center. For a while
there I was pulling a little too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez's options
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Javy Lopez, on the disabled list with a sprained right
knee, continues to target next week's Yankees series for his
return. The Braves have the option of using him as a designated
hitter for those three games in New York and three games in
Toronto, though Lopez prefers to test his knee with some catching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to start catching,'' Lopez said. ``But if I have to DH,
that's no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez caught for the second consecutive day in the bullpen
Friday, and said afterward: ``It's good enough for me to start
playing, not 100 percent, at least 60 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg update
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg dropped by the Braves clubhouse _ as he does
usually once a homestand _ well-tanned, 15 pounds lighter and fresh
off running the Peachtree Road Race last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' Ligtenberg said. ``My wife wanted to do it, so I
did it with her. It was cool to see all the people. ...I usually
run in the offseason. Now it seems every week we're going on a long
run. It keeps me in shape and it keeps me sane.''
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg just passed the three-month mark since his April 6
elbow transplant surgery. Being away from the game has been hard on
him, but Ligtenberg said it's gotten easier the closer he gets to
throwing again.
</P>
<P>
   Ligtenberg goes to physical therapy three times a week and lifts
weights four times a week. He had originally planned to begin light
throwing this week but decided to put that off a while. He plans to
start throwing long toss in August, do some 60-foot throwing in
September and throwing off the mound in October. Afterward he'll
shut down for two months and then start throwing again in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tells me if I do that, I should be ready in March,''
said Ligtenberg, who's not promising that'll be the case. ``I did
for a while, but I've gotten away from that. If I set a timetable
and I don't get there, I'll try to rush it and do something stupid.
I feel I will be ready for Opening Day, but I realize it could take
anywhere from six to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
