<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-TAX-NYT &LR;      07-09 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SENATOR URGES INCOME TAX CUT TO BENEFIT MIDDLE CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Texas)  (th) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to give a modest break to middle-class
taxpayers as the budget surplus swells, the chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee on Friday proposed reducing the lowest federal
income tax rate to 14 percent from 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, by Sen. William Roth, R-Del., will be the
centerpiece of the $792 billion, 10-year tax-cutting bill to be
taken up by the Senate later this month. Roth said Friday that the
bill would also include expansions of the Individual Retirement
Account and 401(k) retirement savings programs, a break for married
couples and a variety of proposals for health, education and child
care.
</P>
<P>
   The senator's approach was developed to appeal both to his own
party and to moderate Democrats, who have indicated a willingness
to support a substantial tax cut this year despite the opposition
of President Clinton and liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   By focusing its benefits on the middle class, Roth's plan for a
rate reduction is less partisan and confrontational than the
proposal being developed for House Republicans by Rep. Bill Archer
of Texas, the chairman of the Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Archer would probably ask for a cut in all
income tax rates, a step that conservatives say would reward the
people who shoulder the biggest share of the tax burden but that
Democrats call a giveaway to the rich.
</P>
<P>
   The rate reduction in the Senate plan would mean a tax cut of
$450 a year for a family of four with an annual income of about
$55,000, Roth said, and $250 a year for a single person with an
income of around $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   The senator did not disclose the cost of his proposal, but
analysts said it would be at least several hundred billion dollars
in foregone revenue over the next decade. Aides said Roth would
probably propose that the reduction take effect in 2001, but was
looking at whether it could be done next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My tax cut plan, which incorporates proposals that have
significant bipartisan support, would cut taxes for millions of
Americans and address the biggest financial issues faced by
individuals and families,'' Roth said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already made it clear that he will veto any bill
that emerges from Congress this year along the lines of either
Roth's or Archer's plans.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, Barry Toiv, said Friday that any
surpluses should be used to address a variety of needs beyond a tax
cut, including shoring up Medicare and increasing spending on
health, education and the military.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has left the door open to a negotiated compromise
over taxes and spending. As a result, proposals capable of
attracting bipartisan support stand some chance of becoming law, a
calculation that was clearly behind Roth's approach.
</P>
<P>
   His plan differs in several ways from Archer's plan in the
House, which will total $864 billion over a decade. Roth is pushing
hard to increase savings and investment by expanding retirement
savings programs, which have long been his favorite tax-cutting
vehicle. But he did not include a cut in the capital gains tax, a
centerpiece of Archer's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the senator include a favorite idea of conservative
Republicans, the elimination of the tax on estates and gifts.
Archer said Friday that his plan would phase out the estate tax
over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Both plans will address the ``marriage penalty'' issue, a quirk
in the tax code that leaves many couples paying higher taxes than
they would if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   Income tax is now levied at a 15 percent rate on adjusted gross
income up to $25,750 for single people and up to $43,050 for
married couples filing jointly. Income above those levels is taxed
at higher rates, starting at 28 percent and rising to a top rate of
39.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the 15 percent rate alone, even by a single percentage
point, cuts the tax bill of all taxpayers and has the greatest
effect, relative to their tax bills, on the middle class. Cutting
all rates has a disproportionate effect on people paying the
highest tax rates, and thus allocates a greater share of the
reduction in taxes to the wealthy, who pay the most taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. McIntyre, director of Citizens for Tax Justice, a
research organization that opposes the Republican plans for large
tax cuts, said Roth's proposal was fairer to average taxpayers than
Republican alternatives like a 10 percent reduction in all income
tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre estimates that 83 percent of the benefits of Roth's
proposed rate reduction would fall to taxpayers whose incomes
ranged from $25,000 a year to $125,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he said, a cut of 10 percent in all income tax
rates would overwhelmingly benefit the wealthy, with nearly a third
going to those with the highest 1 percent of incomes, more than
$300,000 a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
