<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-KURDS-NYT &LR;      07-09 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-KURDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURD REBEL'S DEATH SENTENCE EVOKES ANOTHER REBEL'S SENTENCE IN
1925  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ In what may or may not have been an eerie
coincidence, the death sentence recently given to the Kurdish rebel
leader Abdullah Ocalan was handed down on the anniversary of the
death sentence given to Turkey's last famous Kurdish rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
   That sentence was pronounced against Sheik Said, a clan leader
and Sufi dervish, on June 29, 1925. Ocalan was sentenced exactly 74
years later.
</P>
<P>
   Before his capture, Ocalan sometimes invoked Said's legacy. Both
said they took up arms because they believed the Turkish state
threatened their people's identity. Both were dealt with as bandits
rather than political leaders. Both became objects of the
government's hatred, with leading officials believing that Kurdish
violence could be ended by hanging them.
</P>
<P>
   It did not work the first time. Kurds did not submit peaceably
after Said's execution. Instead they rose up another dozen times
over the next decade and a half.
</P>
<P>
   At his recent trial, Ocalan said: ``Now is the time to end this
conflict, or it will get much worse.'' Some Kurdish militants have
vowed to launch a new wave of violence if his death sentence is
carried out. Government officials, just as they did in 1925, doubt
Kurds have the strength to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels between Said's case and that of Ocalan are not
exact, but they are remarkable enough to have become the topic of
much conversation in Kurdish intellectual circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing that happened in 1925 is happening today,''
said Yilmaz Camlibel, an engineer of Kurdish origin who lives in
Istanbul. ``Back then they said there was no such thing as a
Kurdish question, only fanatics working with foreign powers. Today
they also deny that there is a Kurdish question, and say there is
trouble only because terrorists and foreigners are confusing some
Kurds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both in 1925 and today, the Kurdish issue brings out the
chauvinism of our leaders,'' Camlibel said. ``It gives them an
excuse to limit democracy and restrict press freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Said's rebellion broke out less than two years after the
establishment of the Turkish Republic. It was a reaction to
policies adopted by the new Turkish leader, Mustafa Kemal Ataturk,
that some Kurds found intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   Ataturk was carrying out an aggressive campaign to secularize
his new country. His curbs on the power of religion horrified the
devout sheik and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   The new government also appointed non-Kurds to many local posts
in the Kurdish region, began a campaign to change Kurdish place
names, and banned the use of the Kurdish language in schools and
courts of law.
</P>
<P>
   Historians still argue about whether Said rebelled to defend
Kurdish rights or to establish religious rule in Turkey. But one of
his manifestoes called for creation of a Kurdish state, and some of
his most fervent supporters were members of Azadi (Freedom), an
organization dedicated to Kurdish nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Said and his followers began their rebellion in February 1925.
Among the first towns they took was Lijje, now known by the Turkish
name Lice. To this day Lice is one of the most rebellious towns in
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The government quickly took emergency measures, some of which
are remarkably similar to ones imposed after the current conflict
broke out in 1984. Emergency rule was imposed. Special tribunals
with broad powers were set up to try suspected rebels and
collaborators. Offenders were punished under a loosely worded law
banning ``all reaction and rebellion,'' and ``all instigation or
encouragement thereof, or the publication of anything liable to
upset the order, social harmony or tranquillity of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point Said's rebels came close to seizing Diyarbakir, the
largest city in the Kurdish region, but they were finally defeated
by the Turkish Army. The army soon began taking reprisals on
villages and clans that had supported them, perhaps sowing the
seeds of future uprisings.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief trial, a judge told Said and 46 of his comrades:
``You have all acted on behalf of one cause, the establishment of
an independent Kurdistan. You will pay with your lives, by hanging
from the gallows of justice, for the blood that you have shed and
the families you have destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   On his way to the gallows, Said is said to have told the judge:
``I like you well, but we shall settle our accounts at the last
judgment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
