A4989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-MATCHUPS10-CO     07-09 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-MATCHUPS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Matching up China and U.S. women's soccer
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   GOALKEEPING
</P>
<P>
   Briana Scurry has had perhaps the best stretch of her career
during the World Cup. She played particularly well in the
semifinals against Brazil and has shown athleticism and composure
under pressure. Gao Hong is considered one of the best keepers in
the world, although her World Cup showing has not been airtight.
She tends to be a little flamboyant, but she also has the ability
to make the dramatic save. Both keepers were named to the FIFA
all-star team.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: United States
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   This has been the weak link of the American team, although Carla
Overbeck and Kate Sobrero in the middle and Joy Fawcett on the
right side generally have been reliable. Brandi Chastain plays the
left side. The slow U.S. foursome has been broken early in almost
every game, and the speedier Chinese will try to exploit the Yankee
D. Wen Lirong, Fan Yunjie and Bai Jie have been tough to crack for
China, which has posted two shutouts in elimination play.
ADVANTAGE: China
</P>
<P>
   MIDFIELD
</P>
<P>
   Liu Ailing, showing why she's one of the most lethal playmakers
in the world, scored two goals against Norway in the semifinal. The
Chinese also have an exciting new force in 19-year-old Pu Wei. The
U.S. team has been inconsistent at times, although Michelle Akers
demonstrated her indispensability against Brazil. She will have to
be up to the task once again. Kristine Lilly has had some moments,
but Julie Foudy has been quiet during the World Cup. ADVANTAGE:
China
</P>
<P>
   FORWARDS
</P>
<P>
   Sun Wen is the most complete and explosive player in the
tournament. She has scored seven goals and poses matchup problems
no matter the opponent. Her quickness, instincts and excellence in
the air are unmatched, and she has the perfect partner in Jin Yang.
Mia Hamm has been double- and triple-teamed repeatedly but has done
a fine job as an offensive threat. In drawing corner kicks, she has
opened chances for her teammates. She will have to do more for the
Americans to win. So will Tiffeny Milbrett, whose speed makes her
contribution vitally important. Look for super-sub Shannon
MacMillan to play a role.
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE: Even
</P>
<P>
   FINAL ANALYSIS
</P>
<P>
   These teams are not mysteries to each other, having met three
times already this year. China has won two of them to boost its
already high level of confidence and is entering the final in top
form. But the Americans might have more depth and should be able to
relax now that they've reached the finals. The pressures on the
U.S. team to get here have been immense, while China has waltzed
through its two elimination games. As in the 1996 Olympic final,
which the Americans won over China in thrilling fashion in Athens,
this one has the makings of a classic. The Yanks have shown
remarkable resiliency in holding off Germany and Brazil, but they
could be in for a long afternoon if China gets on the board early.
FINAL SCORE: China 3, United States 1
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
