<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-NOTES10-COX     07-09 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-NOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day game gives teams less time to wait, worry
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ After fidgeting most of the day while waiting
for the Olympic final match three years ago, Briana Scurry is
grateful she won't have the same problem for the World Cup
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played China in the Olympics at night, and you had a lot of
time to think about things,'' said Scurry, the U.S. goalkeeper. ``I
think the feeling is the same, but I'm glad we're playing this one
during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   A rival among many
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest games may be against China, but U.S. players
weren't ready to declare it the biggest rival they have.
</P>
<P>
   Not after scraping by Germany and Brazil in their past two
games, and having a losing (10-11-1) record against Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's our big rival now because we're playing them next,''
midfielder Michelle Akers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are five teams at the top that on any given day can beat
the other,'' said defender Carla Overbeck. ``China has become a big
rival for us, but so are the Norwegians and the Germans and the
Brazilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Just enough flash
</P>
<P>
   Chinese goalkeeper Gao Hong is known to be flamboyant _ daringly
coming off her line and dramatizing difficult saves. ``But she
doesn't do it to a point where it's annoying,'' U.S. coach Tony
DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gao's got nothing on Nigeria's Ann Chiejine, who juggles
the ball after making saves and openly taunts foiled attackers. It
didn't happen much in a 7-1 rout by the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did some things our players didn't like, at least in some
of the other games we saw,'' DiCicco said. ``We liked what she did
in our game though _ picking the ball out of the back of her own
net.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the only game in town
</P>
<P>
   Norway and Brazil will meet in today's third place game.
Together with China and the United States, they make up a World Cup
foursome that is identical to the one that played in the medal
rounds of the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping close company
</P>
<P>
   Chinese players warming up for practice stared for a while as
several dozen reporters walked along the Rose Bowl sidelines after
leaving the U.S. locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Americans, China has extremely limited player
availability to the press, allowing only one day this week with
star Sun Wen. And the Chinese coaching staff was more than upset
when its closed practice on Thursday was delayed because the
Americans were conducting lengthy media interviews near the
training field.
</P>
<P>
   A cool grand
</P>
<P>
   An extra 3,000 tickets went on sale earlier this week, raising
the official Rose Bowl capacity for the championship game to around
88,000, but the asking prices for some scalpers are still on the
rise.
</P>
<P>
   World Cup organizers said they heard that a pair of $110 tickets
are going for as much as $1,000. The online auction Web site, eBay,
has been selling $45 tickets for more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
