<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-URUGUAY-ART-NY     07-09 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-URUGUAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL DEVALUATION IS BOON FOR BORDER TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHUY, Uruguay _ The 40 percent devaluation of the Brazilian
currency, the real, has shaken stock markets across Latin America
and pushed neighboring Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay into
deepening recessions. But people are smiling in Chuy.
</P>
<P>
   After years of stagnation, the streets of Chuy (pronounced
chwee) that straddle the Brazil-Uruguay border are once again
clogged with horse-drawn carts and rusty minivans filled with
merchandise from around the world, including bountiful loads of
counterfeit watches and whisky smuggled from Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   The shopping spree began on the first rainy days after the
devaluation in January, when hordes of Argentines who were
vacationing in Punta del Este deserted the beaches and made the
two-hour drive here to buy towels and sheets. Their pesos, pegged
to the strong dollar, were suddenly golden in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The Argentines went home for winter, and the boom has slowed
somewhat. But Uruguayans from as far as Montevideo continue to
travel here to buy cheap food and clothes before filling their cars
with cheap Brazilian gasoline and oil for the trip home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a crisis on one side of the border or the other,''
said Mohamad Kassem Jamaa, 39, mayor of the Brazilian side of Chuy
and a leading retailer on both sides of town. ``When Brazil is
doing well, we are in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   In good times or bad, Chuy always goes its own multicultural
way. The FM radio station alternates tangos with sambas and bossa
novas. The typical restaurant fare includes Uruguayan steaks and
Brazilian puddings.
</P>
<P>
   The town even has its own dialect, Portunol, with words that mix
Spanish and Portuguese. ``Fuchebol'' means soccer here, and
``yeitino'' means ``opportunity'' or ``profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the exotic nature of the place is the large Arab
business sector, consisting of the offspring of Palestinian,
Lebanese and Jordanian rag traders who came here in the 1960's to
take advantage of opportunities that sprang from a wave of
hyperinflation and devaluation in Brazil. Some stores hang pictures
of Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, among their sale signs.
</P>
<P>
   Business and economics are hardly dismal sciences in Chuy _
spelled Chui on the Brazilian side of Avenida Brazil, which is
called Avenida Urugui on the Brazilian side of the narrow stone
island that marks the border. Hedging, speculating, money
laundering and smuggling are time-honored trades on both sides of
this town of 20,000 people that looks like one big strip mall in
need of a paint job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Brazil is in crisis,'' a Uruguayan retailer, Mariano
Fernandez, 51, said, ``it's a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing that Fernandez does when he wakes up in the
morning is check the newspaper for news on the Brazilian economy.
The last thing that he does at night, he said, is switch on a
Brazilian television news program for signs of financial trouble
across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez is attentive, because his business _ one shop for
spare automobile parts on the Uruguayan side and a second a few
blocks away in Brazil _ depends on which way the Brazilian currency
is fluctuating.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said he was a happy man these days, because he
anticipated last year that President Fernando Henrique Cardoso of
Brazil would devalue the real after his re-election. Fernandez
overstocked his warehouse on the Brazilian side with spare tires,
spark plugs and brake linings while cutting inventory in his
Uruguayan store.
</P>
<P>
   In the months since the devaluation, Fernandez said, his sales
have grown 50 percent, even though his Uruguayan store has almost
no customers.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is climbing, and retail sales are plummeting across
the Southern Cone, but there are jobs for virtually everyone in
Chuy. Workers laid off from stores on the Uruguayan side merely
cross the border, and no one looks at their passports or asks for
working papers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the duty-free shops on the Uruguayan side that are
licensed to sell only to foreigners compensate for their shrinking
Brazilian trade by selling their French perfumes and Chilean wines
to Uruguayans. Salesmen simply do not ask customers for passports,
and local customs officials do not seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the depressed Uruguayan stores also compensate by
illegally, but openly, exchanging currencies without paying the
authorities in Montevideo a cent in regulatory fees or taxes.
</P>
<P>
   There are no firm estimates of how much business Chuy's hundreds
of stores and kiosks do, and neither the Uruguayan nor Brazilian
governments carry out much if any monitoring. But the freewheeling
nature of Chuy has a sinister side, foreign law-enforcement
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials have expressed concern that Middle
East terrorists maintain clandestine cells in Chuy and other
freewheeling border towns to profit from smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuy is a Persian market,'' Julio Dornel, 60, who owns an
appliance store, said. ``Everything is illegal but condoned.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
