<HEADER>
A4994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-CAPITAL-ART-     07-09 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-CAPITAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME MINISTER SHOWS FAITH IN MALAYSIA'S PROSPERITY BY MOVING INTO
A PALACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUTRAJAYA, Malaysia _ Until last month, Malaysia's new capital
city was more rumor than reality. Tightly guarded, rarely
photographed and cloaked in mystery, it lurked somewhere in the
endless glade of palm-oil plantations south of Kuala Lumpur _ an
Atlantis on dry land.
</P>
<P>
   Now the new capital, Putrajaya, is suddenly open for viewing.
While it is still mostly a construction site _ with loggers hacking
orderly rows of palm trees and earth-movers churning acres of red
soil _ the little of it that has been built is raising hackles in
this politically tense country.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad moved here last month, along
with 800 civil servants. His office, a massive green-domed complex,
sits across a sparkling man-made lake from an only slightly less
massive green-domed complex, which is his official residence.
</P>
<P>
   The Brobdingnagian scale of the place has led critics to accuse
Mahathir of putting up a costly monument to himself _ and at a time
when Malaysia is still nursing its wounds from the Asian economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bigger than the White House and 10 Downing Street put
together,'' said Lim Kit Siang, an opposition leader. ``Even
without a recession, you couldn't justify a thing like this. It's
on too colossal a scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody here seems to know just how big the residence is. The
government has not issued a floor plan. Even now one can only gaze
at it shimmering in the distance. Still, with its vaulted central
dome and a succession of wings that cascade down a terraced
hillside, it looks plenty big.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir does seem a bit sensitive about the house. At a news
conference in Putrajaya Friday, he reminded reporters that much of
it will be used for public events. Otherwise, he offered a
characteristically pungent defense of Putrajaya as an investment in
Malaysia's long-term future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't build monuments,'' he said, ``we build things we can
use. It is meant for the government of the future, maybe 100 years,
300 years, 1,000 years. I wouldn't know, I won't be around by
then.''
</P>
<P>
   For now Mahathir, 73, is very much around. Despite a turbulent
year in which he battled the economic crisis, imposed draconian
controls on Malaysia's currency markets, and ousted and imprisoned
his protege and deputy, Anwar Ibrahim, the prime minister seems
determined to cling to power.
</P>
<P>
   Political oddsmakers here say Mahathir may call parliamentary
elections as early as September to capitalize on Malaysia's
improving economy and the disarray within the opposition. So its
leaders are seizing on Putrajaya as a cudgel to beat back the
resurgent prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Fadzil Noor, head of Malaysia's largest Islamic party, said that
if his party gained power, he would ``get the richest kings in the
world to buy and rent out Putrajaya.'' A senior government official
replied that this remark revealed a party lacking in ``ability to
lead the nation in the next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else one may say about Putrajaya, it is most
determinedly a city of the future. Mahathir conceived the project
in the early 1990s as a laboratory for a new form of electronic
government. In the prime minister's Huxleyan vision, paper _ and
its attendant bureaucracy _ would be replaced by the Internet and
other forms of digital communication.
</P>
<P>
   Putrajaya sits next to Cyberjaya, another new city that is
trying to lure technology companies and become Malaysia's Silicon
Valley. Both are wired with the latest in fiber-optic cable and
digital technology.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the Jayas _ the Malay word means success _ symbolize
Mahathir's 17-year campaign to transform Malaysia from a British
colonial exporter of palm oil and rubber into an Asian high-tech
powerhouse that makes semiconductors and designs computer software.
</P>
<P>
   Putrajaya also has a more mundane purpose. It will relieve
congestion in Kuala Lumpur, a cramped and rapidly growing city of
two million. While Kuala Lumpur will remain the official capital of
Malaysia, all government offices are to move 25 miles south to
Putrajaya by 2012. The total cost of the project is estimated at
$5.2 billion, of which $1.3 billion has been spent so far.
</P>
<P>
   The steep price tag has drawn fierce criticism from opposition
leaders and others. Malaysia is crawling out of its worst recession
in a generation, and many of its largest banks and companies are
insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to build Putrajaya was ambitious, but it was in
keeping with the thinking of the time,'' said K.S. Jomo, a
University of Malaya political economist. ``But the decision to
keep going after the crisis hit was incredible. It is like Marie
Antoinette saying, `Let them eat cake.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jomo said it was less apt to compare Putrajaya to Palo Alto or
some other wired suburb in Silicon Valley than to Brasilia, the
eerie modernist city built from scratch as the capital of Brazil.
``In Brasilia,'' he said, ``you had this architectural dream that
became a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   To his critics, Mahathir has fallen badly out of touch. At a
time when Malaysia ought to be reforming its economy, these critics
say, the prime minister is forging ahead with the kind of
megaproject _ remember Petronas Towers? _ that landed it in trouble
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   But even his opponents concede that people here may not be
sufficiently outraged by Putrajaya. ``If this was a country with
massive poverty, it would have more of an impact,'' said Chandra
Muzzafar, an adviser to Azizah Ismail, the wife of Anwar Ibrahim,
who has formed a new opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Mahathir does not sound like a man under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not extravagant at all,'' he said in a good-natured
tone. ``A person is extravagant if he lives beyond his means. A
billionaire spending $1 billion is not being extravagant if he has
the money. But if a person is a millionaire and spends like a
billionaire, that's being extravagant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
