The most prized painting in Christie's blockbuster sale of
treasures looted by the Nazis and returned to the Rothschild family
this year by the Austrian government -- Franz Hals' portrait of the
Amsterdam merchant Tieleman Roosterman -- was bought for a record
$12.8 million by the Cleveland Museum of Art, the museum announced
Friday. It will go on view in two weeks officials there said,
alleviating fears by art lovers that most of the precious trove of
the Rothschild's art that had for years been displayed in Austrian
State museums, would disappear into private hands. (Christie's/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
