A5003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WOMEN10-COX     07-09 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where does women's soccer go from here?
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ By almost any measure, the first Women's
World Cup soccer tournament in the United States has been a
smashing success.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the American team moved undefeated through the
opening rounds and faces archrival China in the championship today
at the Rose Bowl (3:50 p.m., ABC).
</P>
<P>
   In the stands, the U.S. team has averaged 65,000 fans per game,
and today's attendance will set a U.S. record for a women's sports
event. A sellout crowd estimated at nearly 90,000 _ bigger even
than the men's World Cup final played here in 1994 between Brazil
and Italy _ will include President Clinton and an assortment of
Hollywood celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, much of the nation seems to have fallen in love
with the wholesome, ponytailed image of the U.S. squad. Talk show
host David Letterman has taken a liking to the team, proclaiming it
``Babe City.'' Hordes of young girls have adopted the players as
picture perfect role models. And in sports bars and restaurants,
televisions have been tuned to the women's games, away from the
usual fare of men playing baseball and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   After today, these Girls of Summer will step out of the
spotlight, and the more familiar American sports will reclaim their
place. And the future of women's soccer in America remains as
uncertain as before this U.S. women's team burst onto the scene
after winning the Olympic gold medal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At the grass-roots level, soccer enthusiasts are excited about
what the success of this event will mean for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the interest in this team among young girls, I
think millions more of them will want to play soccer and follow
soccer in this country,'' says Marla Messing, president and CEO of
the World Cup organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some small way, we have all been a part of history. ...
It's been like a cultural shift and the way the tournament caught
fire, we've tipped into something. We think ... that people will
look back in 20 years and say, `That event is responsible for the
development of women's sports.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the national level, establishing a professional women's
league is a priority for American soccer officials. But they
concede that converting short-term excitement over a big event into
sustained support for a women's league in a minor sport is a very
big task.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many sports on our landscape,'' Messing said.
``People will follow the U.S. women's national team. But it is
going to be very challenging to establish a successful league.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Soccer Federation is doing a feasibility study to
determine how such a league might be structured. But unlike the
WNBA (Women's National Basketball Association), women's soccer
can't call on an established male benefactor. In its fourth season,
men's Major League Soccer continues to struggle to gain its own
foothold while losing millions of dollars each year.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions are split over whether the image of the U.S. women's
team _ which seems to embrace both that of its young female fans
and of Letterman _ will benefit the sport's future.
</P>
<P>
   Raising quite a few eyebrows was the racy dimension generated by
defender Brandi Chastain on the eve of the World Cup, when she
bared nearly everything for Gear magazine. Dipping into a catcher's
crouch and holding only a well-placed soccer ball, Chastain
combined one image of the American female with a new one of
athletic accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   The players might be the daughters of Title IX, but they clearly
want little to do with some of the feminist rhetoric espoused by
leading women's sports advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything to hide,'' Chastain said. ``I wanted to
show myself in a positive way, that a female can be a woman and a
good athlete and feel good about her body. I don't think I've hurt
women's athletics or women's rights in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   But such gestures also could lead to a perception of women's
soccer as a team sports version of figure skating or gymnastics,
the so-called ``Bambi'' sports that some males love to denounce
simply because they have a strong following among women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laugh at it,'' Chastain said. ``It doesn't change what we
do on the field as soccer players.'' Elsewhere in the world, soccer
is regarded as overwhelmingly masculine, much as the NFL and
college football are here.
</P>
<P>
   In England, the Arsenal club of London, one of the biggest and
richest in the world, is virtually alone in having established a
complete system of adult, reserve and youth teams for women. But
two years ago, Kelly Smith, one of its most promising young
players, left to play at Seton Hall University in New Jersey,
choosing to develop her skills with a college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   And the English Football Association only now is pouring
resources into the women's national team since inheriting it from
another organization in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that they're obstructing anything, but they're
just not encouraging it,'' said FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper, an
Englishman. ``You have to remember that it was only a little over
10 years ago that this thing started rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in China, some of the stars of its World Cup team have
admitted that their families were concerned about them playing the
game. Star striker Sun Wen has said that as a girl she turned heads
more for her gender than for her eye-popping talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are the champions,'' assistant coach Yang Zhongjian
said, ``then I think we will be given more support by the society.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
