<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER'S REWARDS SHOULDN'T INCLUDE A PRICE TAG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Everywhere Tisha Venturini goes these days,
parents spill their dreams to her. They tell the U.S. midfielder
how much they're looking forward to their 8-year-old daughters some
day getting college soccer scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about their sentiments that doesn't set well
with her, mainly because for Venturini and the rest of the U.S.
Women's World Cup team, soccer until just recently wasn't about
chasing some carrot. It was its own reward.
</P>
<P>
   To a woman, the U.S. players embraced the game because of how it
made them feel about themselves. The sport made them strong, imbued
them with confidence, gave them the courage to take risks, forged
their identities.
</P>
<P>
   They've played all these years for the pure love of it. Their
passion wasn't fanned by any potential payoff. They had to really
value soccer to stay with it because it certainly wasn't making
them rich.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the material sense, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that makes (the U.S. women) so popular is
... they just want to go out and play soccer as best they can and
support each other and win gold medals,'' U.S. head coach Tony
DiCicco said. ``That genuine pursuit of their visions and their
dreams and goals is what's so enticing.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Never mind David Letterman's ``Babe City'' label,
what has made the U.S. women so attractive is their joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   They seem wed to their sport for all the right reasons, unlike
so many kids coming up ``who just expect things to be handed to
them,'' said Joy Fawcett, a U.S. defender and the former women's
soccer coach at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   As Venturini has discovered, the seeds of entitlement are being
planted early.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear parents talking about getting their kids soccer
college scholarships, you cringe,'' she said. ``Things like that
were never a motivation for us. Women's soccer is so pure right
now. You hope it stays the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, you fear it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Some time between the U.S. squad's opening win over Denmark on
June 19 in East Rutherford, N.J., and its World Cup title match
today against China at the Rose Bowl, an age of innocence appears
to have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   In a society where money confers legitimacy, it probably was
inevitable that capitalism would replace a
one-for-all-and-all-for-one camaraderie as the topic on the
training table.
</P>
<P>
   You just didn't want to believe that day would arrive so soon,
less than a month after the U.S. players became the talk of every
town they passed through.
</P>
<P>
   Before the U.S. national team was drawing 2,000 people to a
practice and 90,000 to a match, its members were juggling soccer
and second jobs and stretching a $5 bill tauter than cellophane
wrap to make it cover their day's meals on the road.
</P>
<P>
   They've come a long way. But instead of embracing the moment
like any athlete at any level should _ and as they always have _
some of the U.S. team members seem to have lost their perspective.
It's like they've become mesmerized by the neon dollar signs
flashing on some distant horizon.
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a word from Venturini's vocabulary, you cringe when
you hear women who have moved a nation with their magnanimity
clamoring for the creation of a women's professional soccer league
_ and fast. It's as if they went from being perspicacious to
impertinent overnight.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder if maybe they haven't been reading too many of their
press clippings. Sure, they're as big in this country as the Spice
Girls were two summers ago. But look at the Spice Girls today.
They've been scattered to the wind, torn asunder by hubris and
their own hype.
</P>
<P>
   Is that what the U.S. team wants?
</P>
<P>
   It sounds presumptuous when defender Brandi Chastain says:
``We're demanding a pro league. You can't deny us that because you
think there's a lack of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, you wish they could have held off any talk of a better
future until after they had taken care of their unfinished business
at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't misunderstand. This is not to suggest the women are
wrong to want the same opportunities and advantages their male
counterparts enjoy. If there's a pro league in the U.S. for men, a
women's league ought not to be far behind. Some say it's an
absolute must if the U.S. women are to remain one stride ahead of
the developing programs from such countries as Brazil and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   But revolutions don't happen overnight.
</P>
<P>
   A staff of nearly 200 spent three years tirelessly laying the
groundwork for the 1999 Women's World Cup. Their stated mission of
``staging a breakthrough event for women's sports and inspiring the
next generation of female athletes'' has been accomplished largely
because of all the work done behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a huge leap from a three-week parade of pride and
patriotism to a months-long celebration of soccer and it is best
not taken blindly or brazenly.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to glance at the crowds the Los Angeles Galaxy is
drawing is to sometimes wonder if Major League Soccer wasn't an
idea before its time.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the future holds, you wish the U.S. women wouldn't lose
sight of the fact that soccer already has given them so much. They
are more confident and composed and cooperative and disciplined and
determined and worldly and wise for having participated in the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   A professional soccer career lasts but a few years. The sport
has equipped these women with skills to last them a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder if they aren't selling themselves short, angling for
professional playing jobs when they could be CEOs or senators;
difference makers in a larger arena.
</P>
<P>
   You listen to Mia Hamm say of her teammates, ``After all this is
said and done, I know all these people are going to be incredibly
successful in whatever they do,'' and it dawns on you that she gets
it.
</P>
<P>
   She understands there are goals out there that have nothing to
do with soccer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
