<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-ADVANCE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't expect high-scoring duel in U.S.-China match
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ A common score tells the story of the rivalry
between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   In all three previous meetings this year, the score has been 2-1
(China won twice), and the teams split friendlies on the East Coast
in April by grabbing winning goals in the waning moments.
</P>
<P>
   And the same score won the 1996 Olympic final for the U.S. team,
on an electric August evening in Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Based on those four results, today's World Cup championship
match between the United States and China doesn't figure to veer
far from the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any of us needs any more motivation for this
game,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   And while it might be a real treat for the estimated Rose Bowl
crowd of 88,000, for the teams it means the likelihood of 90
agonizing minutes, and possibly more, before a winner is
determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a whole lot of scoring going on,'' U.S. goalkeeper
Briana Scurry said. ``All of our games with China lately have been
tight. It's going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you throw in what they've done during the World Cup, the
margin for error could be extremely small. The U.S. defense,
although it has been soft early in some matches, has surrendered
only three goals. China has let two get by.
</P>
<P>
   However, China has been so explosive offensively that, combined
with its recent results against the U.S. team, the Americans
actually might be an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be considered the favorites,'' DiCicco said.
``They've breezed through the knockout rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   April 25 still stands out as perhaps China's soccer red-letter
day. It's not the first time the Chinese had beaten the Americans;
the U.S. leads the series 11-5-5. But that's when a 94th-minute
goal by reserve Zhang Ouying snapped the Americans' 50-match home
unbeaten streak at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team had won the same way two days earlier on a goal by
Tisha Venturini, but China's belief that it could beat any team
anywhere was cemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best team we've had in a few years,''
China coach Ma Yuanan said. ``I want the team (that played on April
25) to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Striker Sun Wen has been the scoring star of the tournament. She
shares the lead with Brazil's Sissi with seven goals and has an
excellent supporting cast. The entire Chinese lineup is very quick,
technically sound and committed. Midfielder Liu Ailing has been at
the top of her game, and goalkeeper Gao Hong has played well, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive play of the Americans is the best part of their
team,'' Ma said. ``The speed and the skill level of the two teams
is the same. But on our team, there are some players who are
stronger. There's no individual on the U.S. team who can do what
Sun Wen can do.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Americans haven't brought their best game
to the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not even close,'' reserve forward Shannon MacMillan
said. ``We know we didn't play that well against Germany, and we
hung on to beat a very good Brazil team. We know we can play
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm, who has scored two goals and two assists, hasn't been
at her best, but she and Tiffeny Milbrett have the speed and skill
to threaten China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that everything comes together for us,''
Hamm said. ``We need to be patient and not get frustrated. Our best
soccer is yet to be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
