<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-FESTIVAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODSTOCK '99 PLANNERS FINED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oneida County is seeking to levy fines of as much as
$1.5 million against the organizers of the Woodstock '99 music
festival, but the organizers and county officials say they expect
the three-day concert to begin as planned on July 23 in Rome, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The fines were levied by the county's Health Department for what
it said were several violations of the mass-gathering permit it had
issued to Woodstock's organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneida County Executive, Ralph J. Eannace Jr., said Friday
that most of the violations were not serious, but concerned late
submissions of engineering plans, parking plans and a payment to
New York State for repairs it had made to the Gov. Thomas E. Dewey
Thruway for the anticipated influx of 200,000 to 300,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But Eannace said the amount of the fines is negotiable, once the
Woodstock producers comply with the permit requirements. ``We do
not anticipate cancellation; we fully anticipate compliance with
the remaining issues and the concert going forward,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   That is a considerably more optimistic tone than that sounded
earlier in the day by an Oneida County assistant attorney, Joseph
Hobika Jr., who told The Associated Press that Woodstock organizers
must pay the fines, whatever the final amount turns out to be, by
next Thursday or face the possibility that the county would cancel
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lang, one of the producers of Woodstock '99 and its 1969
eponym, held in Bethel, N.Y., called the reported violations and
fine ``a big splash in a teacup. There's certainly no ultimatum on
anybody's part,'' he said. ``They had to make some kind of official
statement to satisfy the state regs. I expect that we will have an
agreement in the next day or two.''
</P>
<P>
   The permit, a complex set of standards for any gathering larger
than 5,000 people for more than 24 hours, became state law in 1970
specifically to prevent the chaos that enveloped Bethel after the
original Woodstock. In their effort to comply, Woodstock organizers
submitted a 4,000-page tome to local officials last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of this year's festival, which is located about 110
miles upstate from the original concert's site, say they have sold
more than 150,000 tickets so far.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
