<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISSIE'S BACK _ 'NUFF SAID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``They don't make 'em like they used to/You should have just
stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   As an opening salvo on a rock 'n' roll CD, the chorus of
``Popstar,'' the lead-off track from the Pretenders' ``Viva El
Amor!'' is as right as right can be. Chrissie Hynde is addressing a
former boyfriend whose girlfriend dreams of stardom, but she's
obviously also referring to all those who would have counted her
and her band out after years of inactivity and spotty CDs.
</P>
<P>
   And right she is. ``Viva'' is a terrific, spiky rock 'n' roll
record, a statement of purpose by a woman who was at the forefront
of the English punk/New Wave movement, attained stardom early, hit
another peak with 1984's ``Learning to Crawl,'' and then did a
long, slow fade: four CDs since, none of them more than fair.
</P>
<P>
   Lord knows how long it will be before the next Pretenders CD, so
let's savor the moment: ``Viva'' finds Hynde, 47, still roaming the
streets, still in love with the idea of being a rock star, still
with much to say about the world around her, from hope for a
romance ``(Dragway 42)'' to class distinctions ``(Nails in the
Road)'' to the ache of lost love ``(Who's Who).'' That mix of
toughness and tenderness, of holding the world at arm's length but
wanting someone to hold her and be true, has characterized her best
work, and that sense is here, all dusted off and gleaming.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, ``Viva'' explores little new territory musically.
Good thing, too, because the new wrinkle, a song in Spanish called
``Rabo de Nube,'' is horrible. Musically, ``Viva'' is classic
Pretenders: sturdy guitar, nods to both New Wave structures and
'60s Motown and Beatle-esque pop, such as on the lovely ``From the
Heart Down,'' which echoes ``Across the Universe.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes this all still work is perspective: Hynde's
continuing status as one of the coolest people on the planet. She
lusts, she loves, she hurts, she tries to negotiate the minefield
of relationships, and she kisses off boyfriends with withering
lines such as the chorus to the hard-rocking ``Baby's Breath:''
``Why did you send me roses?/Save them for someone's death/The love
you have to offer/Is only baby's breath.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a classic Pretenders moment _ something that's been in
short supply for years. For the moment, at least, we've got
Chrissie Hynde back _ and it's as if she's never been away.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
