<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HOGAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN 1953, BEN HOGAN WON THE BRITISH OPEN _ AND THE HEARTS OF
CARNOUSTIE, SCOTLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, SCOTLAND _ As Carnoustie looks forward to hosting
the British Open this week, sentiment still tugs this seaside
community of 11,000 back 46 years to Ben Hogan's victory here in
the 1953 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The staging of The Open on Carnoustie's formidable Championship
Course will be, in the words of golf commentator Peter Alliss, ``a
memorable and emotional event'' largely due to Hogan's memory.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Carnoustie, Bob Blyth's eyes glisten as he talks about
watching Hogan in 1953. Blyth was then a 25-year-old schoolteacher
from nearby Dundee. Following Hogan in the 1953 Open turned Blyth
into a lifetime fan of the legendary Texan. Blyth corresponded
regularly with Hogan until the golfer's death two years ago this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Blyth will be at The Open every day this week, but he expects
his mind to wander often back to the July of 46 summers ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hogan had such control over the ball,'' says Blyth, sitting in
the soft afternoon light in the Hogan's Alley pub across Links
Parade from the 18th green of Carnoustie's Championship Course.
``When you saw Ben Hogan hit a ball, you couldn't forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   The memory of Ben Hogan is impossible to ignore here. The course
yardage books for the 7,300-yard Championship Course mark ``Hogan's
Alley,'' on the sixth fairway where Hogan threaded his drives
between an out-of-bounds fence and fairway bunkers en route to
birdies in all four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Hogan House hotel across the street from the course.
Another big new hotel on the course opened just weeks ago has as
its main lobby decor a collection of photos of Hogan in action.
More Hogan photographs adorn the walls of the Carnoustie Golf Club
meeting room.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Scotland, Hogan is identified so strongly with Carnoustie
that you'd almost think he lived here,'' says Walter Anderson of
Perth, as he looks over golf equipment at the Golf Trap Shop on
High Street. ``Of course, he was only here for two weeks. And he
never came back.''
</P>
<P>
   The person who played the biggest role in persuading Ben Hogan
to play in his one and only British Open, his wife Valerie, said in
an interview in May that she planned to watch every minute of this
week's event on television. Valerie, concerned in 1953 that her
restless husband had run out of worlds to conquer, had joined those
who urged her reluctant husband to make the then-rare journey to
Scotland for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie's death June 30 at the Westover Hills home she and Ben
had shared stirred memories of the powerful team they made during
Hogan's heyday a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really doubt that Ben could have done what he did in golf
without Valerie,'' recalls Frank Stranahan of Palm Beach, Fla., who
in 1953 traveled on the same transatlantic flight with the Hogans
and competed in the Open as an amateur. ``Valerie was so organized,
and Ben listened to her like he did to nobody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf historians debate which of Hogan's nine major championships
between 1946 and 1953 was the greatest. But Hogan's triumph at
Carnoustie in 1953 was his most significant. Hogan joined Gene
Sarazen (later, Jack Nicklaus and Gary Player) as the only golfer
to have won all four professional major championships _ The
Masters, U.S. and British Opens and the PGA Tournament _ in a
career.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's victory at Carnoustie came after the 1953 Masters and
U.S. Open. In the 46 years since no golfer has matched Hogan's
achievement of three professional majors in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   The 1953 victory at Carnoustie added another dimension to
Hogan's public persona. He was known as the game's finest shotmaker
who then had overcome a near-fatal car/bus accident. After
Carnoustie, he was the conquering American hero, honored with a
ticker-tape parade up Broadway in New York City, another parade in
his hometown of Fort Worth and athlete-of-the-year awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Carnoustie, Ben was known as America's best golfer,
period,'' says John Derr, , longtime CBS correspondent who in 1953
was America's lone electronic media link with Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   But, Derr adds, ``the 1953 British Open made Hogan a legend.''
CAPPING A CAREER Ben Hogan didn't plan to play in the British Open
when he set his 1953 schedule. The damage to his legs from the 1949
auto accident had made Hogan a part-time player, limited to the The
Masters and U.S. Open, the Colonial at his home course in Fort
Worth and a handful of smaller events. Hogan's weakened legs
couldn't stand the PGA Tournament, then a two-week, match-play
affair held in July overlapping the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the British Open had fallen from its pre-World War
II eminence. The small purse, with first-place prize of just $850
in 1952, compared to $5,000 for Colonial and $10,000 for the U.S.
Open, wasn't enough to cover travel costs. In addition, the British
then played a smaller ball than used in the U.S. and didn't allow
Hogan and other American pros to use the newly popular
center-shafted putter.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan had his personal reason to skip Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben always thought the U.S. Open was the greatest tournament
in the world, and he was afraid that if he played in the British
Open and won it that it would detract from the importance of the
U.S. Open,'' Valerie said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Masters in April, Hogan was implored to go to Britain
by Augusta National Chairman Bobby Jones, himself a three-time
winner of the British Open. Jones said Hogan needed a win in
Britain to complete his career.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews,
governing body of the game outside of the U.S. and conductor of the
British Open, buttonholed Hogan at Augusta and told him they had
increased first-place prize to $1,400 for the 1953 event and would
allow use of the center-shafted putter.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Armour, winner of the 1931 British Open held at
Carnoustie, told Hogan that Carnoustie didn't have the blind shots
or hidden hazards that Hogan detested. Walter Hagen, another
pre-World War II British Open champion, noted that Carnoustie was
considered the toughest course in Scotland. Valerie said Hagen's
observation made an impact on her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben always felt that he did best on the toughest courses,''
Valerie explained. ``That is why he played so well in the U.S.
Open. Hagen said that only the very best players could win at
Carnoustie.''
</P>
<P>
   Temporarily setting aside the question of Britain, Hogan won the
1953 Masters with a then-record score of 274. Shortly afterward,
Ben and Valerie were in New York at dinner with a friend, Paul
Shields. After discussing Ben's planned venture into the equipment
manufacturing business, Shields suddenly said ``Ben, you should go
over and play in the British Open. It will complete your career.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan gave Shields an I've-heard-this-before look and said
``don't you know that I'd have to qualify? I'd probably go all the
way over there and not even get to play in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Valerie, who probably had more influence on her husband than all
the golf legends and organizations combined, found herself
supporting Shields' arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben had never played in the British Open, and it just seemed
like he needed a new challenge,'' Valerie said. ``I think he was
getting bored.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, Hogan won his fourth Colonial tournament. The next day,
he wired his British Open entry to the R&AMP;A. Hogan asked that it be
kept confidential until after the upcoming U.S. Open at Oakmont.
</P>
<P>
   The Ben Hogan of 1953 was in a position opposite most American
pros when considering the British Open. The schedule conflict with
the PGA wouldn't apply to Hogan because he didn't plan to play in
the American event, anyway. And by 1953, Hogan was wealthy enough
to not have to worry losing money on a trip to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan had done well enough in golf, but as he rose to
prominence, Fort Worth oilmen _ chief among them the Moncriefs _
had connected Hogan to lucrative pieces of the postwar U.S. oil
boom.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan also had received a undisclosed cash settlement from
Greyhound Lines, whose bus had crossed the center highway line and
slammed into Hogan's Cadillac near Van Horn in west Texas in
February 1949. Speculation consistently placed it in excess of
$250,000, worth roughly $1.5 million in today's money and more than
Hogan made in all his major championships combined.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie said ``money was never a consideration for the British
Open.'' TAMING A TOUGH COURSE In mid-June, Hogan won the U.S. Open
at Oakmont in Pennsylvania by a six-shot margin. By the final
round, the secret of his British Open entry was out. The news
electrified Scotland. The British knew their championship had
fallen in grandeur. Now, Hogan's pending arrival would reaffirm
Scotland's seminal place in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Blyth said the low purse had been a problem in attracting
American players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Ben Hogan was coming. ... We knew Hogan was the greatest
American player. This would make the 1953 Open special.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiosity was a factor. Alliss, then a young British pro golfer
who played in the 1953 Open and later would become familiar to
American golf viewers as a television commentator, said ``in those
days, players didn't go back and forth the way they do now. This
was before television and very few people in Britain had ever seen
Hogan.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's pending arrival generated some some skepticism in Great
Britain. Bernard Darwin, the writer who had followed golf since
before World War I, wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was said that Ben Hogan was the greatest player of his day,
but many in Britain felt that Hogan had achieved his fame on
well-groomed, inland American courses. Let him come to the great
Carnoustie, people said, and we will see what manner of golfer he
is!''
</P>
<P>
   For Scotland, Hogan had to adjust to the smaller British ball,
1.62-inch diameter versus the 1.68-inch diameter American ball.
From tee to green, the smaller ball would help Hogan. It bore into
the wind better and made the 300-yard drive, a rarity in those
steel shaft and persimmon wood days, more achievable.
</P>
<P>
   But the smaller ball rotated more times during a putt,
exaggerating the breaks in greens. By 1953 Hogan was suffering from
the first putting troubles that would dog him for the rest of his
playing days.
</P>
<P>
   Only Valerie knew in 1953 that the car accident had left her
husband with greatly reduced vision in his left eye. That not only
robbed Hogan of crucial depth perception when reading greens, but
limited his look at the putt over the ball. Fearless on the tee and
fairway, Hogan was now hesitant on the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben never really recovered from the car accident,'' Valerie
said. ``But he refused to talk about his injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Scotland's weather posed another physical concern. Doctors had
saved Hogan's life in 1949 by tying off one of the major arteries
to his leg to prevent blood clots from reaching his heart. The
surgery left him with reduced circulation and vulnerability to
cold. Hogan by 1953 escaped North Texas winters in Florida and
California. Scotland's July wind-chill, even though the term hadn't
yet been invented, would be comparable to a Texas winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got all kinds of long underwear and sweaters, as well as
heaters, to take for the trip,'' Valerie said. ``I was certain that
the cold would be a problem for Ben.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
