<SLUG> BC-TERROR-PANEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSLIMS DENOUNCE GEPHARDT FOR WITHDRAWING A NOMINEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Muslim groups said Friday that they were stunned and
betrayed by the decision of the House minority leader, Rep. Dick
Gephardt, to revoke his appointment of an American Muslim to a
congressional counterterrorism commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt decided late Thursday to withdraw his appointment of
Salam Al-Marayati, executive director of the Muslim Public Affairs
Council in Los Angeles, to the National Commission on Terrorism.
Since he made the appointment in June, Gephardt, D-Mo., had been
severely criticized by Jewish organizations that portrayed
Al-Marayati as a terrorist sympathizer cloaked in a moderate's
guise.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Friday, the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination
Committee said of the decision, ``It is shameful that
Representative Gephardt would bow to pressure from pro-Israel
groups who falsely accused Dr. Al-Marayati of being a `supporter of
terrorism.'''
</P>
<P>
   Several non-Muslim religious and political leaders who have
worked with Al-Marayati in interfaith and human rights
organizations also stood by him Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David E. Bonior, D-Mich., who had originally recommended
Al-Marayati to Gephardt to serve on the commission, said in a
statement: `` Salam Al-Marayati is a person of great integrity, who
has proven his commitment to peace and constructive dialogue. As a
member of the Los Angeles Human Relations Commission, he worked
together with a large number of groups, bringing together people of
all faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that Al-Marayati will not be serving on the National
Commission on Terrorism. It is paramount that the commission
include someone with perspective, insight and sensitivity to the
concerns of the Arab and Muslim communities in this country, as
they begin to address the serious problem of terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt sent a letter to Speaker J. Dennis Hastert Friday
formally withdrawing the nomination of Al-Marayati to the
commission, a 10-member group that has six months to review
national strategy for preventing and punishing terrorism against
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Gephardt gave for withdrawing the nomination was that
it would take longer than six months for Al-Marayati to receive the
security clearance necessary to participate on the commission.
Gephardt wrote that Al-Marayati ``is prepared to provide input'' to
the commission, and he encouraged commission members to ``listen to
the voices'' of the American Muslim community.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Marayati said Friday that the episode proved that ``there are
threats to our democracy, and one of these threats is the exclusion
and discrimination that was exposed to us by these developments.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his group, the Muslim Public Affairs Council, will hold
its own counterterrorism forum and issue a paper to contribute to
the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Of his critics, Al-Marayati said, ``Either somebody is providing
them misinformation, or they're reading it from a biased lens.''
</P>
<P>
   While many Jewish groups said they were privately applauding the
Gephardt move, not many were eager to claim victory with
celebratory media releases. Some Jewish leaders said they did not
want to be seen as having encouraged the quashing of an appointee
because of his religion or ethnicity. They said their objections
were based only on statements that Al-Marayati or his associates
had made asserting that Israel shared the blame for inciting
Palestinian terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   David Harris, executive director of the American Jewish
Committee, said that while American Muslims deserved a place at the
table, ``this table is not just any table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This table,'' Harris said, ``is one that was set up to direct
U.S. policy on terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Council on American-Islamic Relations called for Gephardt to
reinstate Al-Marayati, saying: ``Those who represent one side of
the debate cannot be allowed to establish a pro-Israel litmus-test
for any Muslim who is to be considered for government service.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
