<SLUG> BC-BODY-RETRIEVAL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will wild Chattooga give up its dead?
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAYTON, Ga. _ Taking a break from paddling his sleek black
kayak, Tom Cromartie tosses a stick into the Chattooga River at a
treacherous, fast-tumbling stretch known as Raven's Chute.
</P>
<P>
   The chunk of wood disappears into the rushing avalanche of
brownish white water, just as 16-year-old Rachel Trois did in the
cool evening of May 29.
</P>
<P>
   The stick pops up in the foaming water and floats down river.
The teen-age girl wasn't so lucky. Her body has yet to surface,
trapped by the beautiful, perilous Chattooga, made famous by the
1972 movie ``Deliverance.''
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, after five failed attempts to retrieve Rachel's
body, a plea by the victim's family for another recovery try has
erupted into a widening dispute with intensely personal and
national policy ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   Search dogs have indicated the body is trapped under eight feet
of churning water, possibly wedged against an undercut rock that
faces upstream like a gaping jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Water rushes between black, smooth-backed boulders with such
force that it blasts skyward like a fountain, marking the spot
where the relentless current hurled Rachel down and won't let the
body go. Cromartie, 27, of Gainesville, was paddling the
Chattooga's treacherous Section IV the evening Rachel slipped while
she was trying to cross the river atop submerged rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The tanned, muscular kayaker came along a half-hour after the
accident, which happened several hundred yards downriver from a
massive boulder known as ``Deliverance Rock,'' where filming of the
James Dickey novel took place. Cromartie encountered a desperate
scene, as Rachel's boyfriend, the boyfriend's father and two other
young men were frantically looking for help in the fading light.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a girl down there!'' one of the boys shouted over the
Chattooga's roar, echoing through the remote, rocky gorge that
separates northeastern Georgia from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's father, Joseph Trois, 40, of Leesport, Pa., has
traveled to the river three times. Each time, he has left with
disappointment compounding his grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty simple, I want that daughter of mine,'' he said.
``I want her out of the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to retrieve the body have set off a deepening debate
over how and when _ and even whether _ rescuers should risk their
own lives for somebody who is already dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family knows if we are able to get in there, we may be
able to get just pieces of the body,'' said Tom Ramey Jr., 38,
mayor of the Rabun County town of Tiger and a member of the
county's swift-water rescue team. ``If that is what the family
wants, I am willing to try again.''
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, Oconee County emergency preparedness director
Henry Gordon, 58, said he believes another recovery attempt should
wait for lower water levels.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers from Rabun and Oconee counties participated in the
previous efforts. ``We do not want to do anything to risk a life,''
Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   The debate touches on America's environmental policy. The
Chattooga is a National Wild and Scenic River, a designation that
protects free-flowing waterways from development and from efforts
to divert the water's flow.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial rafters and the Chattooga River Watershed Coalition
protested last month when a New Jersey-based company working for
the girl's family erected a temporary five-foot-high dam of steel
braces and plastic fabric.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service, which manages the Chattooga, signed off
on the project, which included driving spikes to hold up the dam.
That involved drilling holes in the rocky river bed.
</P>
<P>
   The dam failed when the river, rising due to rain, breached the
plastic fabric in several places.
</P>
<P>
   Even though crews removed the spikes and the rest of the dam,
the coalition's executive director, Buzz Williams, said he believes
the drilling violated the Wild and Scenic River Act because it
altered the riverbed.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three dozen people have died on the Chattooga since 1970,
bringing occasional demands by grieving survivors that rapids be
permanently altered to prevent other deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that a few holes have been drilled in the rock,''
said Williams, 48, formerly a Forest Service ranger and a river
guide. ``It's where do you draw the line? There are places that
have been set aside by this country, and they should not be altered
by the hand of man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service maintains the drilling on June 24 did not
alter the riverbed. Yet in a public meeting Tuesday in Long Creek,
S.C., district Forest Service ranger Michael Crane said he opposed
construction of another temporary dam as potentially unsafe for
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Crane's stance drew criticism from Sen. Strom Thurmond (R-S.C.),
who had asked the Forest Service to work with Portadam Inc. on its
proposal to erect an even taller temporary dam.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Trois had sought help from Thurmond's office in further
efforts to retrieve his daughter's body. South Carolina's senior
senator agreed to exert his influence.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Thursday to Forest Service Chief Michael Dombeck,
Thurmond urged the agency to consider a new proposal from the South
Carolina Forestry Commission. The state agency recommended the
river be diverted around the recovery site through large pipes, or
through hoses attached to pumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither version utilizes (a) dam to stop water flow, which is
unsafe, and virtually impossible to accomplish anyway,'' Miles
Knight, a state forestry commission official, wrote Thurmond's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest wild card is the Chattooga itself. Until a dry spell
brings down water levels, some officials believe further recovery
attempts would be as futile as previous ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to tame that river,'' said Gordon, of Oconee
County. ``You have to work with it the best you can.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
