<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPICE-TRADE-ART-2TAKE     07-09 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPICE-TRADE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ANCIENT TRADE PROPELS INDONESIA'S ECONOMY AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on top 7 suppliers of spices to U.S. by market
share is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ On a clear day, Singaporeans can see
recession-wracked Indonesia from their southern shore. From their
living room, Seah Soo Lin and his son Jeng Jye can smell the
archipelago's budding recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnamon, pepper, nutmeg and cloves: an aromatic bounty sits
packed in a jumble of cardboard boxes on the floor. Outside on the
patio, sandalwood chips are piled into a mound on a table. For the
last 30 years, Seah's small family-run company, Chop Wee Kiat, has
traded Indonesian spices and fragrant woods, buying in places like
Timor and Sumatra and selling to customers from Bahrain to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Seah, seated in short trousers under a Chinese landscape
painting, might seem unsuited to a discussion of financial market
dynamics. Chop Wee Kiat, after all, is a tiny $5-million-a-year
business in a local market estimated to amount to $1.5 billion a
year. But for small players like Chop Wee Kiat, sticking with this
ancient trade amid the latest financial storms has meant staying in
touch with modern-day economics. Growing competition from distant
suppliers and larger players, meanwhile, means relying on strengths
developed through tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays if you want to survive, you must have a good
reputation, be very active and offer good service,'' Seah, 65, said
from behind yellow-tinted bifocals. ``Experience also counts.''
</P>
<P>
   He has plenty of that. Distant relatives from Indonesia
introduced Seah to the trade back in 1969 when they needed someone
to broker the sale of cinnamon sticks from Sumatra. His depth of
experience in Indonesia makes him sanguine today about what will
emerge from the country's economic and political upheaval. ``It
won't be so different,'' he shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Economic crisis has in fact been kind to the Seahs and their
Indonesian suppliers. When the rupiah plummeted last year, prices
for Indonesian products dropped, too. That put a squeeze on
manufacturers who were borrowing in foreign currency and had to
import supplies, but it was a windfall to those whose livelihoods
sprang from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   And now the spice trade is pointing toward stability and hope
for the future in Indonesia. Agriculture has proved an unexpected
bulwark of the nation's economy, sheltering rural communities from
recession. ``The one sector that hasn't been hit is agriculture,''
said David Fernandez, a J.P. Morgan economist.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture alone _ representing less than 20 percent of the
economy _ will not be enough to pull Indonesia out of recession.
Further growth in crops will require money from banks, says Stephen
Mink at the World Bank, and Indonesia's banks are being rescued by
the government under a plan the World Bank estimates will cost the
country $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, agriculture accounts for 40 percent of Indonesian jobs,
and the sector's health has been crucial in containing the spread
of poverty. Farmers outside the densely populated main island of
Java have done so well that last year the World Bank declared the
economic crisis a largely middle-class phenomenon. Jobless
urbanites began filtering back to the countryside in search of
work.
</P>
<P>
   Now, economists say, natural resources, from palm oil and coffee
to pepper and cinnamon, are helping Indonesia claw its way slowly
back to health. Interest rates, once above 70 percent, have been
halved. Inflation has all but disappeared. And in the first three
months of this year, the economy grew from the quarter before _ not
a real recovery yet, but a hint that growth may be around the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   To know the spice trade is to know a good deal about Indonesia.
Traders have been carrying spices from these islands to the rest of
the world for thousands of years, and spices have played a huge
role in the nation's political and economic history.
</P>
<P>
   Spices lured traders from Arabia, Persia and India, who brought
with them Hinduism and later Islam. Spices supported a
seventh-century commercial empire centered on Sumatra that extended
as far as modern-day Thailand and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   Arab traders long ago introduced pepper, cloves and cardamom
from Southeast Asia to Europe, where they were treasured as
preservatives and analgesics. Visigoths once ransomed Rome for
pepper. The Arabs kept the source of their spices a secret,
however, until Marco Polo divulged the truth after returning in
1292 from his travels, which included several months on Sumatra.
</P>
<P>
   Once the word was out, Europeans started a race for the Indies,
with spices inspiring the voyages of Columbus, da Gama and
Magellan. Spices financed the expansion of shipping and sowed the
seeds of empire for Spain, Portugal and England. But it was
ultimately the Dutch who captured the true spice islands, trading
Manhattan to the English in return for a tiny island covered with
nutmeg trees.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore's warehouses brimmed with Indonesian spices as the
British port became a transshipment point and home to myriad
companies like Tai Eng Ltd., which opened for business in 1948 on
land now occupied by the Singapore Stock Exchange, according to the
founder's grandson, Raymond Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Farther inland, Seah's home office still has jalousie windows,
and the only air-conditioning comes from a couple of fans. But the
business brings in nearly $5 million a year, enough for him to
raise six children, including Jeng Jye, 32, who earned an
accounting degree at Singapore's top university and then came to
work for the family business.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's troubles threatened to uproot Chop Wee Kiat's
network of sellers, many of whom were among those
Chinese-Indonesians who fled the country when mobs turned their
rage against them. But after a week or so, Seah said, most of them
returned home. ``They go back because they can make money,'' he
said, slipping back into his native Hokkien dialect.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   With agriculture rebounding, markets for spices and other
extracts are bulging. Consider Indonesia's patchouli. Cultivated
predominantly by small farmers, the leaves of the patchouli bush
yield a pungent yellow oil that lends a soothing fragrance to
soaps, detergents and fancy perfumes. Aromatherapists say patchouli
is good for treating everything from cellulite and athlete's foot
to anxiety and snake bites.
</P>
<P>
   Before the crisis, patchouli prices were at rock bottom and
farmers had begun to dig the bushes up to plant crops they could
eat or sell. But a sharp decline in supplies led to a rebound in
prices just as the economic crisis reached its worst point. After
patchouli prices jumped, farmers responded by digging up food crops
to plant patchouli, and prices have fallen back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Adequate cultivation is no guarantee of supply, either. Early
this year, so few goods were being shipped to Indonesia that
exporters were unable to find containers to pack their products in.
Banks were in such dire straits that they were declining to issue
exporters letters of credit advanced to guarantee payments. When
Chop Wee Kiat was buying nutmeg last year, Seah said, its partner
in Indonesia had no choice but to ship the spice off and trust that
payment would come.
</P>
<P>
   Cloves are another story altogether. They are used in
Indonesia's most popular consumer item, flavored cigarettes called
kreteks. Encouraged by their success in cornering the nutmeg
market, a group of ethnic Chinese traders decided in 1990 to do the
same with cloves. When the plan failed, they enlisted President
Suharto's son, who persuaded the government to give him a monopoly
on the clove trade. Companies like Chop Wee Kiat had to settle for
cloves from Madagascar and Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
   One demand imposed by the International Monetary Fund for its
$43 billion aid package was that the clove monopoly be dismantled.
That reopened Indonesia's clove trade to Seah, but confusion has
ensued. While the monopoly could not buy cloves, traders could not
get the money from banks they needed to step in. Huge shipments of
cloves were smuggled out (to the detriment of world clove prices),
but most Indonesian farmers simply stopped bothering to pick and
dry out their clove buds, said Suhas Chougule, general manager of
Surice Trading Ltd., a Singapore spice company.
</P>
<P>
   Lower prices for farmers usually mean fatter margins for
traders, because the end market for spices is largely impervious to
the boom-and-bust crop cycle, Chougule said. ``People who use white
pepper must have white pepper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the role of small middlemen is under assault by concerns
like McCormick &AMP; Co., a $1.9 billion enterprise in the United
States that bills itself as the world's largest spice company.
McCormick's buyers were once content to deal through local trading
companies like Chop Wee Kiat. But the quest for greater consistency
in quality and price has encouraged big processors to increase
direct purchases from growers.
</P>
<P>
   And the tumult in Indonesia has made the spice trade more
volatile than ever, says Raymond Lee at Tai Eng. During the height
of Indonesia's crisis, he said, prices gyrated by as much as 30
percent in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Market prices are still determined largely by word of mouth.
``There's no securities exchange offering nutmeg futures,'' Seah
Jeng Jye said. It is not uncommon now for spice traders to enter
into their own forward contracts, buying a shipment of cinnamon in
June for delivery later or to simply stockpile a spice in the hope
that prices will improve. Communications are evolving, too, the
younger Seah said. Gone are the telex and cable; Chop Wee Kiat now
takes inquiries by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Modern ways may be coming, but spice traders hope the business
is specialized enough to require their continued existence.
Experienced spice traders can tell a bad clove bud by sight and can
price sandalwood by how it smolders. ``You need to have people who
know about the trade,'' Lee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
