<HEADER>
A5020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-PROFILE10-COX     07-09 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-PROFILE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slayings suspect previously charged for indecent exposure
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The suspect in four Sidney-area slayings Thursday
has spent much of his life bouncing between jobs, three marriages
and run-ins with the law that included sex offenses for indecent
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Michael Hensley, 30, was convicted twice in four years
for public indecency, but told investigators in one of the cases he
had exposed himself more than 25 or 30 times and wanted help to
make him stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not proud of what I've done and I'm really ashamed of
it,'' Hensley told Sidney police detectives investigating a 1995
case in which Hensley was accused of masturbating in a changing
booth in a Sidney clothes store and exposing himself to a female
clerk. ``I'm sorry, but in a weird sort of way I'm glad I did it
'cause my family has found out about the problems I was going
through and they got me help.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley told police he had received psychological counseling
frequently. He received court-ordered counseling after a 1997
public indecency conviction, and had received private counseling in
Bellefontaine and at the Dettmer Hospital, a psychological care
center in Miami County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I checked myself into Dettmer Hospital but withdrew after my
ex-wife found out about my stay and called me to rub it in,'' he
told police.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley was also convicted in 1997 of exposing himself to a
passing female motorist while driving northbound on Interstate 75,
according to Sidney Municipal Court records.
</P>
<P>
   A Wapakoneta woman told police she tried to pass Hensley's car
when he exposed himself to her, then he sped his car up with hers
until she drove through the highway median to get away from him.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley had put duct tape over his license plate but was tracked
down through a physical description the woman gave of him and his
purple car.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley initially denied being involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think someone is trying to frame you?'' a police
investigator asked him, according to police reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm not very well-liked, put it that way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley told investigators he had been exposing himself for two
years by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have a sexual disorder problem and I know I need
help,'' he told Sidney police investigators. ``Some true, honest
help. Someone that will find out why I do this, because deep down I
don't want to do this. I have a lot going for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley was fined $100 and had a five-day jail sentence
suspended for his 1995 public indecency conviction in Sidney
Municipal Court. He was fined $250 and had a 90-day jail sentence
suspended following his 1997 conviction. He told investigators he
served 16 days in Logan County Jail for an earlier indecency
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Hensley married for the third time in April, after an
eight-month marriage in 1987 and a second marriage that ended in an
acrimonious divorce and custody battle in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   His wife at the time, Jennifer C. Hensley, accused him of
abusing their then 1-year-old son. Hensley denied the charge and a
hearing before a Shelby County magistrate ended in a ruling that
there was no evidence Hensley had abused his son. The magistrate
ordered, however, that all visitations between Hensley and his son
be accompanied by another adult member of Hensley's family.
</P>
<P>
   During the fight over his son's custody, court records show
Hensley was financially strapped, often switching jobs several
times a year.
</P>
<P>
   He told Sidney police investigators during an interview over his
1997 public indecency case that his son was the most important
person in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't take me away from him and please let me get help
until my problem is solved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
