<SLUG> BC-TOURDEFRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIPOLLINI WINS 6TH STAGE OF THE TOUR DE FRANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Belgium, Italy, France, Germany, Australia, Estonia, Czech
Republic)   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAUBEUGE, France _ Tom Steels of Belgium, who had already won
two sprints in this Tour de France, badly wanted to win the sixth
stage Friday because it ended in the French town of Maubeuge, just
across the border from his home. Erik Zabel badly wanted to win
because he had finished second twice in the last three days and had
not yet won a stage. Mario Cipollini badly wanted to win because he
had won the previous two days and is insatiable, as all great
sprinters are.
</P>
<P>
   In a tumultuous finish, Steels crossed the line first, with
Cipollini second and Zabel third. But minutes later, the Belgian
was disqualified and placed 172nd because of his aggressive and
dangerous tactics. After swerving to cut off Jan Svorada, a Czech
with Lampre, Steels dug his right elbow into Cipollini a few times
just before the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   The elbows could be pardoned as a common offense, but the swerve
was too blatant a piece of interference.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Cipollini, an Italian who rides for Saeco, won for
the third consecutive day. Zabel, a German with Telekom, finished
second once again and for the 17th time this year. Jaan Kirsipuu,
an Estonian with Casino who wears the overall leader's yellow
jersey, moved up to third, with the bullied Svorada fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Steels' Mapei team appealed the disqualification and a 30-second
penalty, with the international jury announcing that a decision
would be made in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, whoever he was, finished the 171.5-kilometer
(106-mile) stage in 4 hours 11 minutes 9 seconds, an average of
40.9 kilometers an hour (25 miles an hour). Of the 176 riders left,
172 finished in the same time, with Steels placed by the rules at
the bottom of the first bunch across.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsipuu remained in the lead for a fifth day, 26 seconds ahead
of Cipollini and 38 ahead of Stuart O'Grady, an Australian with
Credit Agricole.
</P>
<P>
   Steels, who trailed at the start by 17 seconds, had hoped to win
the stage and its 20 bonus seconds and vault into the yellow jersey
before the almost home folks. But Kirsipuu won an early
intermediate sprint and its 6 bonus points to thwart Steels' plans.
No jersey, no victory _ his wife probably burned dinner, too.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, where the race is never run, this was another stage
for the sprinters: a warm sun, a rolling course of no particular
difficulty and the knowledge that their glory days in the Tour de
France rival the life span of a fruit fly.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, in the first real challenge of the race, a long time
trial will exhaust the sprinters, who are more accustomed to going
all out for 300 meters than for 56.5 kilometers (35 miles). Two
days later, the Tour enters the Alps, where sprinters are an
endangered species. Cipollini, the best of them, has already
announced that he has a long-awaited appointment for root canal
work in Italy and so must withdraw in the shadow of the first peak.
</P>
<P>
   Several stages are left, then, before the sprinters come to the
fore again after both the Alps and the Pyrenees, and they made the
most of it _ in Steels' case, too much of it _ Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a macabre way, the combat in the sprint was fitting. This
sixth stage of 20 started in the city of Amiens on the Somme River
and swiftly passed into the countryside where trench warfare was at
its most fierce, destructive and absurd in World War I. Those
rolling fields, now planted in potatoes and corn, were the staging
ground of two vast, months-long battles in 1916 and 1918. British
and Commonwealth forces suffered more than 419,000 casualties, with
20,000 men killed the first day alone in July 1916. German
casualties over all are estimated between 450,000 and 680,000.
</P>
<P>
   The land taken, lost and recaptured amounted to no more than a
few kilometers along the broad front in what was then known as
Flanders.
</P>
<P>
   Some trenches are still there in the fields, preserved for
tourists. As the riders passed through the sunny countryside
Friday, they might have noticed the statues in many villages of a
soldier, his rifle and bayonet pointing at the sky and the names of
the dead filling all sides of the huge stone on which he stood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
