<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-BILLING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA INVESTIGATING ENERGY SUPPLIER  &HT;     By REBECCA SMITH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Commonwealth Energy, a new electricity supplier
based in Orange County, is being investigated by the state Public
Utilities Commission for retroactively billing about 19,000
California customers a total of $632,000.
<P>
   The PUC said it received 159 formal complaints from customers of
the 2-year-old Tustin, Calif., company, which had customers
throughout the state. Most of the complaints concerned retroactive
billing, poor customer service and Commonwealth's failure to make
good on advertised discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth President and Chief Executive Officer Fred Bloom
said that when the state first deregulated the electricity market
last year, his company sent out some bills in error. The
retroactive billing, he said, was simply correcting those mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   However, a report prepared for the PUC by state investigator
Richard Chan said Commonwealth ``had no provision in the terms and
conditions of service ... which authorized backbilling.''
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary report, PUC investigators said Commonwealth
customers were retroactively billed for as much as seven months
worth of service and for amounts ranging from 7 cents to $2,165.
</P>
<P>
   Customer Howard Thompson from Atwater, Calif., said he wound up
paying Commonwealth higher rates than he'd been paying PG&AMP;E, once
the back-billed amount was factored in.
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth determined that it had over-billed 520 customers
and ended up refunding them a total of $1,400 in amounts ranging
from one penny to $83.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the retroactive billing problem, state
investigators said the company may have run afoul of the state
utilities code by misleading consumers in direct mail advertising
about the savings available to them.
</P>
<P>
   Various flyers for the company guaranteed savings of 2 to 25
percentoff rates charged by conventional utilities. But many
customers told PUC investigators they didn't receive such a
discount when they switched service, for the energy portion of
their bills, from companies like Pacific Gas and Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth customer Nadja Sokoloff of Whittier, Calif., told
investigators she was guaranteed savings of 10 percent but didn't
get that amount once the back-billed amount was added. She told
state investigators that Commonwealth was unresponsive to her
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commonwealth needs to change some of its practices,'' said
Bill Schulte, director of the PUC's investigative unit. ``They're
guaranteeing savings that consumers aren't actually seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth's Bloom said the investigation is without merit. He
accused the PUC of waging a ``witch hunt'' that grew out of a
previous brush the company had with state Sen. Steve Peace, D-El
Cajon (San Diego County), the former chairman of the Senate
Utilities Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a public hearing last spring, Peace and Bloom got into a
shouting match in which Peace accused Bloom of being a
``charlatan'' and Bloom accused Peace of demagoguery. It ended when
Bloom challenged Peace to settle the argument outside and Peace
declined to leave the dais.
</P>
<P>
   Once the PUC opens a formal investigation, there are several
courses of action. It can negotiate a settlement in which the
subject agrees to mend its ways and pay a fine. It can prosecute a
company and even bar it from doing business in California. Or it
can conclude its case without seeking penalties or redress.
</P>
<P>
   It will be some months before the PUC decides what action, if
any, to take against Commonwealth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
