A5027 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAMES-COMPANY-SFCHRON     07-09 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAMES-COMPANY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIN-OFFS AND STARTUPS PLAYING THE NAME GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- When Hewlett-Packard Co. decided a few months ago
to spin off its noncomputer business into a separate company, that
was the easy part.
<P>
   Now for the hard part: What do you call the thing?
</P>
<P>
   ``We held a mock contest for the name, but it was never a
serious effort,'' said Michael Fournell, a spokesman for ``NewCo,''
which is the code name given by Hewlett-Packard to the new
enterprise. ``We knew we needed an expert.''
</P>
<P>
   They weren't alone. According to Enterprise IG, a worldwide
brand-consulting firm, a record 1,456 U.S. companies adopted new
names in the first half of the year, up 52 percent from a year
before. Nearly a third of the changes stemmed from mergers,
reorganizations and spin-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for HP, and for numerous other companies in an
increasingly crowded marketplace, there are plenty of experts who
are more than ready to mesh words or syllables into the next
``Coca-Cola'' or ``Sony.''
</P>
<P>
   With trademark or usage rights to just about every word and word
combination already taken, the growing ranks of professional name
consultants are finding their services increasingly in demand as
new or revamped ventures dot the corporate landscape.
</P>
<P>
   And even when a potential name manages to overcome the legal
hurdles, there's still the matter of how it will play overseas in
today's global economy.
</P>
<P>
   A classic miscue came when General Motors Corp. introduced its
Chevrolet Nova automobile in South America. In Spanish, ``no va''
translates as ``doesn't go.'' For its part, Ford Motor Co. turned a
few heads south of the border with a snazzy &LR;   &LR; model called Fiera,
or ``ugly old woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty of finding names is the blessing and bane of
our existence,'' said George Frazier, a partner with San
Francisco's Idiom, a leading name-consulting firm. ``A naming
project can either be an unprofitable headache or it can be the
easiest thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard turned to San Francisco's Landor Associates, one
of the top players in the name game. Among other accomplishments,
Landor came up with ``Lucent Technologies,'' when AT&AMP;T Corp. spun
off its Bell Laboratories research arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation with Hewlett-Packard is very similar to AT&AMP;T,''
noted Russ Meyer, Landor's executive director of corporate
identity. ``In both cases, you have to balance future vision with
heritage of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   While neither Hewlett-Packard nor Landor is ready to spill the
beans as to the new moniker, Meyer said ``a wide range of names''
has been explored, and that the winning choice will reflect ``the
intellectual and emotional content of the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's Fournell said the new name almost certainly
will be unveiled before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   What's It Worth?
</P>
<P>
   So what does a new name cost? Although name consultants are
reluctant to discuss how much individual clients shell out, they
estimate that an easy name _ one that doesn't take too long to
concoct or research _ might run about $10,000, while a real
nightmare of a job, with literally thousands of possibilities under
consideration, could cost as much as $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   That's just for the name, mind you. Such other factors as design
of a new logo and marketing can run hundreds of thousands of
dollars more.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the tech world has fueled much of the boom in
the name-consulting field. The fast-multiplying number of Internet
firms has caused a surge in demand for anything-memorable-dot-com.
</P>
<P>
   Lexicon Branding of Sausalito, Calif., was brought in several
months ago when HomeShark, an online mortgage company in San
Francisco, discovered that its name was a potential turnoff for
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``HomeShark was a name that I'm sure was intended to be
clever,'' said Lexicon's president, David Placek. ``But it had
negative overtones. The word `HomeShark' evoked connotations of
`loan shark.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lexicon's team aimed to come up with something both positive in
tone and clearer about the company's purpose. ``We just started
pairing words and ended up with a list of 600 or 700 names,''
Placek recalled. ``In that list was iOwn.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe Names
</P>
<P>
   As newly christened iOwn's Web site now explains, the overhauled
name ``echoes the satisfaction and pride our customers feel when
they buy a new home.'' It also doesn't make customers feel like
their kneecaps are in danger if a loan payment is missed.
</P>
<P>
   Different name consultants bring different methods to the mix.
Some prefer to deluge clients with hundreds of choices, and then
work together in winnowing that number down to a short list. Others
favor serving up their single best effort in a well-orchestrated
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   While one might guess that a reasonably clever computer program
should be able to dominate the name business much as IBM's Deep
Blue blew world champion Garry Kasparov off the chess board, those
in the industry are quick to point out the limitations of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't use computers to make words, because computers have
no idea what words mean,'' said Ira Bachrach, head of NameLab Inc.
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   To underline his point, he noted that many name consultants
focus just as much on the sound of a word when devising names for
global concerns. ``You want to use sounds that are part of native
speech,'' Bachrach said, ``and there are very few sounds available
to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the sound, countered Mel Owen, a trademark attorney
with the San Francisco law firm of Owen, Wickersham &AMP; Erickson. A
greater consideration is the fact that about 3 million words and
names already have been registered with federal trademark
authorities, and that more than 12 million company names now exist
in the United States alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more and more projects, and fewer and fewer names
available,'' Owen pointed out. ``In the good old days, you could
flip open a dictionary or hold a contest. That's not possible
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``With most of the descriptive words taken,'' he added, ``people
are being forced to take more arbitrary &UR;  &LR; names, like Yahoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming Net Congestion
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Internet represents the cutting edge of corporate
naming. With millions of sites jostling for attention, and with
competition fierce for a jazzy dot-com address, the trend nowadays
is for in-your-face names that may not have a thing to do with the
company's business.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, after all, doesn't sell river tours and that hasn't
stopped it from becoming the No. 1 bookstore on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Or take the example of SportSite.com, a San Jose, Calif., online
sporting-goods retailer that was finding it hard to stand out from
the pack. As Fogdog Sports, that's no longer much a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creating new names has become a legitimate business service,''
said Lexicon's Placek, who is undeterred by speculation that only a
finite number of names are ultimately possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' he allowed, ``I'm sure mathematicians
could tell you all possible combinations, but it's huge. For our
purposes, it's practically infinite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
