<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5029 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MCENROE-CAREER-TE     07-09 1860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MCENROE-CAREER-TEX </SLUG>
 
McENROE SET TO ACCEPT TENNIS' HIGHEST HONOR 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has been portrayed as the van Gogh of tennis, the tortured
genius whose sheer artistry on the court was often overshadowed by
a chronic case of tantrums that offended the game's purists, but
delighted the masses and helped propel the tennis boom in the
mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe could be as unruly as his head of curly brown hair
and as delicate as an artist whose brush strokes evolve into
masterpieces. From the time he burst on the tennis scene in 1977,
an 18-year-old amateur from New York who made it through Wimbledon
qualifying and advanced to the semifinals, he was driven by a quest
for perfection, which often drove him and those around him to
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   In a career that spanned three decades, McEnroe made an
indelible impression on the game and helped popularize tennis
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking down the street with him in 1981, I doubt if there
were five more recognizable people in the world,'' said Peter
Fleming, McEnroe's longtime doubles partner. ``In any country,
people would react _ and they'd all react differently. The guy has
an electricity about him that not many people have.''
</P>
<P>
   And today, in Newport, the quaint seaside summer resort town in
Rhode Island, McEnroe will be inducted into the International
Tennis Hall of Fame, taking his place among the legends of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years after he became a fixture in men's tennis, it
is still a matter of conjecture whether McEnroe's volatile nature
contributed to his greatness or was an obstacle that prevented him
from being acclaimed the greatest player of all time. Other tennis
players have misbehaved _ Jimmy Connors and Ilie Nastase come to
mind _ but after having covered McEnroe for most of the past 22
years, it would be difficult to name another player in the history
of the game that has been known as much for his temperament as the
way he stroked a tennis ball.
</P>
<P>
   Although his induction has been a formality, McEnroe has said he
is honored to be taking his place among the game's legends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the biggest. I'm not the strongest. I'm not the
fastest,'' McEnroe said when chosen for the Hall of Fame earlier
this year. ``The effort and intensity and understanding of
technique and doing something adventurous, that's what I'd like to
be remembered for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought some energy to the sport, a style of play not
duplicated almost at all. I feel I was a good athlete, in some ways
underrated. I had reasonable attributes.''
</P>
<P>
   The years have mellowed him, he said, but at 40, his hair
thinning and sprinkled with gray, McEnroe is still passionate about
the game. He rails against the myopia of former politicians and
failed players who run the men's tour; he is still capable of a
tirade or two during his matches on the senior tour, although he
has said that some of these outbursts are orchestrated.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he and Connors are not speaking again after an
incident in a senior's match last year in Irving, which is
reminiscent of the days when they were on opposite sides of the
net, baying at the moon and each other.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a better example of McEnroe the temperamental genius
than the footprint he left on the venerable grasscourts of the
All-England Lawn Tennis Club? He won Wimbledon three times but is
probably equally remembered for calling chair umpire Ted James
``the pits of the world,'' during a match in 1981. In retrospect,
that pales in comparison to the multitude of outbursts that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the first year of the new men's circuit, the ATP Tour,
McEnroe was disqualified during a match against Mikael Pernfors at
the Australian Open because he did not know the code of conduct had
been made more stringent to discourage boorish behavior. Tour
officials commonly refer to that rule as ``the McEnroe rule,'' and
now it is cited as the reason the men's game lacks personalities.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways McEnroe's career has been a series of
contradictions. He is a pure serve and volleyer, but unlike the
power players of today, his game was about touch, finesse and
strategy, qualities that often eluded him when he chose to speak.
</P>
<P>
   His groundstrokes were not pulverizing; instead he ladled the
ball over the net. Yet he would also try to beat the fuzz off a
tennis ball at the slightest provocation.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe's serve did not break speed records, but it handcuffed
opponents and allowed him to get to the net. He was a tennis chess
master who saw moves on the court his opponents never dreamed
existed.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe also was always keenly aware of his surroundings. He
chastised fans, thought he could call the lines better than the
linesmen, and often had a scolding word for his opponent and the
audience. During a match in the season-end championship at Madison
Square Garden one year, McEnroe stood hands on hips, frown on face,
waiting as a substantial woman struggled to her seat after a break
between games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you lose some weight,'' McEnroe told her, loud
enough for 18,000 people to hear.
</P>
<P>
   He is a product of the 1970s, when anti-heroes were the rage.
But his ``McNasty'' persona was countered by his respect for tennis
tradition and history, and loyalty to his country. Even now in his
role as a television tennis analyst, McEnroe is an outspoken
advocate for the Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   He virtually single-handedly returned the United States to Cup
prominence. He helped the United States win five Cups, among them
the 1992 Final against Switzerland in Fort Worth, and compiled a
remarkable singles record of 41-8 in Cup play. He added another 18
victories in doubles, making him easily the most prolific Davis Cup
player.
</P>
<P>
   But the Davis Cup produced some less-than-magical moments as
well. In 1981, during a raucous Davis Cup doubles match in
Cincinnati, he almost came to blows with Guillermo Vilas and
Jose-Luis Clerc of Argentina. McEnroe and Peter Fleming struggled
to win in five sets in a marathon match that was delayed more than
30 minutes because McEnroe tore apart the indoor carpet along the
seams in a fit of anger.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, it was Connors, not McEnroe, who embarrassed the U.S.
team with his on-court behavior during the Davis Cup Final in
Sweden. The United States Tennis Association was so apprehensive
about losing financial aid from sponsors, it required players to
sign a letter saying they would conduct themselves properly.
McEnroe refused to sign, and Randy Gregson, then the USTA
president, would not allow him back on the team. McEnroe rejoined
the team in 1987 after Gregson's term had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the histrionics, McEnroe built an impressive statistical
resume. He won seven Grand Slam tournaments among 77 career singles
titles, including the U.S. Open four times and Wimbledon three. He
had another 77 doubles titles, nine of which came in Slams.
</P>
<P>
   He finished as the No. 1 player in the world for four
consecutive years beginning in 1981, totaling 170 weeks atop the
game. He also spent a record 270 weeks as the No. 1 doubles player.
While Fleming was his partner for many of his doubles victories,
the popular saying in tennis was that the best doubles team in the
world was McEnroe and anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't ask for a better partner,'' Fleming said. ``There
were several times that we disagreed, but as a whole he was a great
team player.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the reason Larry Bird, Magic Johnson and Michael
Jordan were so great is that they made the players around them
better. John was like that.''
</P>
<P>
   What tennis fans will remember more than the numbers, however,
are the battles McEnroe waged against the unholy trinity of
Connors, Bjorn Borg and Ivan Lendl. They helped define him, the
good and the bad.
</P>
<P>
   Connors was his nemesis, the seasoned player who ended McEnroe's
surprising run at Wimbledon in 1977. Their matches were like
barroom brawls with invectives and tennis balls flying. The
atmosphere was charged and fans became rowdy. The genteel sport of
tennis was never the same.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe and Borg were like fire and ice. They brought out the
best in each other. McEnroe deeply respected Borg and rarely
engaged in gamesmanship when they played. They met 14 times,
splitting their matches, but several were epics.
</P>
<P>
   The 1980 Wimbledon final is considered one of the greatest
matches in history. Borg won in five sets, but not before McEnroe
won a fourth-set tiebreaker, 18-16, fighting off four match points.
He would end Borg's run of five consecutive Wimbledon titles the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe also defeated Borg in the 1980 and '81 U.S. Open finals.
Sensing perhaps that the rivalry was becoming one-sided, the stoic
Borg walked off the court after the 1981 Open and into retirement
at the age of 25.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe did not, however, have the same success against Lendl,
an impassive baseliner from the Czech Republic, who won 21 of 35
career matches against McEnroe and dealt him the biggest defeat of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   It came at the French Open in 1984. Clay is the Achilles' heel
of most American players, McEnroe included. But he won the first
two sets and was up a break in the third of the final. A victory on
the red clay at the French Open would have probably earned McEnroe
acclaim as the best player ever.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he slowly self-destructed, and Lendl fought back to win
in five sets. McEnroe has said that it was his biggest
disappointment and the match that enabled Lendl to become the
dominant player in the game.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe would recover to win Wimbledon and defeat Lendl in the
U.S. Open final that year, but at 25, those would be the last Grand
Slam singles titles of McEnroe's career. At 5-foot-11 and 165
pounds, and more comfortable with a wood racket, he soon was being
overpowered by bigger, stronger players, and racket technology. The
era of the Stradivarius in tennis had given way to the Fender
Stratocaster.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe's decline was gradual. He remained a formidable player
during the second half of the 1980s, but his diatribes were
increasing. During the 1986 year-end championship at Madison Square
Garden in January, a fan crashed the post-match interview and asked
McEnroe a rhetorical question about how it felt to lose to a
journeyman like Brad Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, probably believing this was the most intelligent
question he had been asked in years, contemplated for a moment and
then decided that when he began losing to players like Gilbert, it
was time to quit.
</P>
<P>
   He announced he was taking a sabbatical and exited the interview
area. His next match was in August, at a tournament in Stratton
Mt., Vt. But the seven-month hiatus had not changed him. Even
worse, there were new forces to reckon with.
</P>
<P>
   During a quarterfinal match against a newcomer with long dark
hair streaked with white, McEnroe hit his first serve and watched
the return whiz past his ear at twice the speed.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe stared hard at 16-year-old Andre Agassi and turned to
look at where the ball had landed, several feet past the baseline.
He had won the point, but he knew the times, they were a changin'.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
