A5037 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-09 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONACH TAKES OVER GULFSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was confirmed this week that Frank Stronach, noted
thoroughbred owner/breeder and founder of Magna International, an
auto parts company estimated to be worth $4.4 billion, has
purchased Gulfstream Park in Florida for $95 million. On Nov. 14,
Stronach purchased Santa Anita in California for $126 million, and
he now is reported to be after Monmouth Park in New Jersey to
complete his personal version of the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach bought Gulfstream through Ventures, Inc., his
acquisition arm, from Orient Corporation. ``We are pleased to have
secured a purchaser who previously has made a substantial
investment in the future of thoroughbred racing,'' said Akihiro
Terada, representing Orient Corp., Tuesday. ``We are confident
Ventures will further strengthen Gulfsteam's ranking as Florida's
No. 1 thoroughbred track, and one of the industry's national
leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulfstream, which is easily accessible from both Fort Lauderdale
and Miami, races from early January until early March, and ranks
behind only Saratoga as the favorite vacation track for New
Englanders. Stronach is likely to move quickly to expand the
Gulfstream meeting, seeking to open earlier, taking on nearby
Calder, owned by his rival Churchill Downs. Flush with cash from
simulcasting, Churchill also has been acquiring tracks, including
Hollywood Park, which is across town from Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a municipality decides it wants to have a racetrack, then
it should allow the meet to be as long as the racetrack wants,''
said Stronach. ``It's like any other business. Only the ones who do
the best job survive, and the ones who don't will disappear. I'd
like to expand the meet, and, if anybody else wants to expand
theirs, that's fine. Let Calder expand, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach doesn't fool around. He swept into Santa Anita and
ordered a $50 million renovation project. Soon thereafter, 17
administrators were let go. Santa Anita was scheduled to host the
Breeders' Cup in 2000, but Stronach's makeover sent the Cup to
Churchill Downs. Guess who has this year's Breeders' Cup?
Gulfstream on Nov. 6, and Stronach will be in charge by then.
However, the Cup expects to stay put in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Stronach's plans for Santa Anita have been popular.
Among the discussed moves are the elimination of the track's famous
downhill turf course, and paddock gardens. ``I wouldn't say that we
are scared, but we are apprehensive, definitely,'' said Ron Ellis,
who is both a trainer and television commentator. ``It's like
somebody just threw all the pieces of the circuit up in the air,
and we're waiting for them to fall back into place.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stronach does have a backer in popular conditioner Bob
Baffert. ``Stronach wants people with fresh ideas,'' said Baffert.
``He wants to get away from the attitude that says: `This is the
way it's been done, so this is the way it's going to be done.'
We're not going to like all of his ideas, but you at least have to
give the guy a chance. I think we had gotten kind of complacent
here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yagli won't run at Ascot
</P>
<P>
   Owner Allen Paulson and trainer Bill Mott have changed their
minds, and will not run Yagli, currently the leading grass horse in
North America, in the King George VI and Queen Elizabeth Diamond
Stakes at Ascot July 24. Had they done so, it would have marked a
rare incursion into European racing by a horse based in the US.
Paulson indicated that Yagli is sound, but he and Mott decided the
6-year-old son of Jade Hunter was likely to do better in the $2
million Breeders' Cup Turf, in which he finished second last year,
if they stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   Yagli, who won the Manhattan Handicap at Belmont June 5 in his
last start, will run next in the United Nations Handicap at
Monmouth July 31, or in the Sword Dancer Handicap at Saratoga Aug.
14.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Almutawakel prepares
</P>
<P>
   Almutawakel, who won the Dubai World Cup in March, defeating
Malek, Victory Gallop, and the now-retired Silver Charm, is being
pointed toward the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic by Godolphin
Stable. Almutawakel will run next in the Juddmonte International at
York Aug. 17. The Juddmonte is on the grass, but the 4-year-old
Almutawakel, who surprised at 44-1 in the Dubai World Cup, is now
considered Godolphin's best older dirt horse . . . Reraise, who won
last year's Breeders' Cup Sprint, will be out for the year after
straining a tendon while training for the Triple Bend Handicap at
Hollywood June 27. That opened the sprint ranks up, and Mazel Trick
responded by winning the Triple Bend by five lengths in track
record time of 1:19 4/5 for seven furlongs. A son of Phone Trick,
Mazel Trick is trained by Bobby Frankel, and takes over the top
spot in the West. Yes It's True, conditioned by D. Wayne Lukas, and
Good and Tough, who won the Suffolk Breeders' Cup May 29, and is
trained by Frank Alexander, will battle for Eastern supremacy when
they meet in the $300,000 DeFrancis Dash at Laurel July 17 . . .
Jockey Bill Patin, who was suspended for five years after the
Arkansas Racing Commission determined he had carried an electrical
device while riding longshot Valhol to victory in the Arkansas
Derby in April, will not be reinstated by the Louisiana Racing
Commission, which refused to renew his license. A Louisiana native,
Patin had been riding at Evangeline Downs under a temporary
restraining order.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks and from
the Daily Racing Form was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
