<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ATTACKS GOP ON HMO BILL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gearing up for next week's Senate debate on
patients' rights to medical care and insurance, President Clinton
lambasted Republican leaders Friday for what he suggested were
cynical delaying tactics intended to defeat Democratic efforts to
establish minimum federal standards for health maintenance
organizations and insurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not for it,'' the president told a sympathetic
audience of doctors, nurses and local politicians at the
Harbor-UCLA Medical Center in the southern Los Angeles suburb of
Torrance Friday morning. ``But they know they can't afford to be
caught being against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal to guarantee that all patients have access to
emergency room care and cannot be forced to change doctors in the
middle of treatment, among other provisions, died last year after
Senate Republicans kept it from being brought up. The Republicans
argued that it would cost too much and could lead employers to drop
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   But the president insisted Friday that cost increases would be
modest, and added, ``We should err on the side of humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House scheduled Friday's small, carefully staged event
on short notice after Clinton decided to extend his four-day tour
of some of the nation's poverty areas to take in the Women's World
Cup soccer finals in Pasadena on Saturday. But the president used
the occasion to tee-off sharply on the announcement by Republican
senators that they would begin debate on patients' rights next week
with a Democratic-sponsored bill, in an apparent effort to kill it
and avoid having to defend their own bill against Democratic
amendments to strengthen it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw today an amusing article in the paper which said that
the leaders of the majority party had decided that instead of
bringing up their bill and having to deal with 20 of our
amendments, which would put people _ force them to put their
members _ on record as being against these things, they would bring
up our bill and just beat it in the hope that then there would be
no specific record of accountability,'' Clinton said, warming to
the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, `What kind of a weird world am I living
in?''' the president said, adding, ``This is about whether some
people live and some people die.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks came as debate over the issue intensified and
business and insurance groups opposed to the effort began a
$750,000 television advertising campaign intended to sway undecided
Republican senators. The most controversial, and potentially
expensive, feature of the Democratic-sponsored bill would give
patients the right to sue health plans and collect damages when
treatment is withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose effort to overhaul the health care system
collapsed spectacularly in 1994, acknowledged Friday that one of
his major goals had always been to rein in rising health care costs
by moving patients into managed care. But he said, ``The purpose of
managed care is to enhance the quality of care by making it as
affordable as possible, not to undermine quality of care by making
the people who provide managed care as profitable as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's performance was one more example of his relative
ease in defining himself in opposition to Republican proposals, and
he seemed to relish the task Friday morning, growing folksy as his
audience in the hospital's auditorium responded with occasional
shouts of, ``Tell it!'' and, ``That's right!''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was introduced by Dr. John Lewin, chief executive of the
California Medical Association, which represents 35,000 doctors in
a state that was an early leader of managed care. Lewin told a
handful of HMO horror stories, like one about a man who died of
cardiac arrest while waiting an hour for his health maintenance
organization to approve treatment because a previous call had
turned out to be a case of indigestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, these are not just isolated anecdotes,'' the
president said minutes later. ``This is a systematic problem in
American health care. And once we fix it, all the people will be
happy; the HMOs will do just fine, and they'll be happy we did. And
people will wonder what in the wide world we were doing all those
years not providing these basic protections.''
</P>
<P>
   After most of a week spent highlighting rural and urban poverty,
Clinton turned to the health care issue with a vengeance Friday,
recording his weekly Saturday radio address on the subject of
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   And after sweltering days among some of nation's poorest
citizens, he returned to the friendly embrace of a billionaire
supporter, Ron Burkle, a California supermarket magnate and
Democratic contributor.
</P>
<P>
   The president is staying at Burkle's sprawling Beverly Hills
estate, Greenacres, the former home of silent film star Harold
Lloyd. Friday afternoon Clinton played golf at the exclusive
Riviera Country Club; the White House told journalists not to
expect any photographs of the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
