<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGING HOLLYWOOD TO MARKET NONVIOLENCE  
 CALIFORNIA BAPTISTS AND HOMOSEXUALS  
 CHANGES IN CHURCH MEMBERSHIP  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After two teen-age gunmen murdered 12 classmates and a teacher
in Littleton, Colo., in April, the wave of public revulsion was big
enough to crash around Hollywood, as people sought a way to explain
such a horrible event. Society suffers when children are exposed to
so much violence on television and the movies, went the familiar
complaint.
</P>
<P>
   But what to do about that? Last month, cinema operators promised
to work harder at enforcing the R-rating, the movie designation
supposed to keep out under-17-year-olds unless they come
accompanied by an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Another suggestion, less widely heard but intriguing in that it
calls for something of a cultural shift, asked Hollywood to
``de-glorify'' violence, even to show acts of principled
nonviolence.
</P>
<P>
   This idea comes from the Rev. Ellwood E. Kieser, a Roman
Catholic priest who heads Paulist Productions, a maker of movies
about Archbishop Oscar Romero of El Salvador and Dorothy Day,
co-founder of the Catholic Worker movement. Kieser is also
president of an ecumenical organization called Humanitas, which
awards prizes for movies and television shows judged by an
independent panel to reflect human (and humane) values.
</P>
<P>
   At the organization's awards luncheon on Thursday, Kieser
discussed his idea in a speech, having previously mentioned it in
an opinion article in The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of my proposals is, let's not point fingers,'' he
said, in an interview beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he proposes these three things: one, to demonstrate the
``sickness'' that lies at the heart of violent acts; two, to show
how violence can devastate victims' families and wreak inner damage
on its perpetrators; and, finally, to show how nonviolence can work
to resolve conflict.
</P>
<P>
   One can say that Hollywood already does some of this. Kieser
credits Steven Spielberg's successful 1998 film, ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' with showing the cruelty of war and its effect on people
related to those killed in battle.
</P>
<P>
   But where does one go for movies about nonviolent conflict
resolution _ other than to ``Gandhi,'' the 1982 film by Sir Richard
Attenborough about the leader of India's independence movement?
</P>
<P>
   James Wall, senior contributing editor of the weekly magazine
The Christian Century, who frequently writes about movies, said,
``The problem is, so few films focus on people with those
personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall said he did not think a lack of movies about people with
nonviolent principles was ``an ideological choice, but a marketing
choice'' by movie-makers. In other words, if Hollywood thought the
public were interested, it would make more of those movies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kieser said, nonviolent movements have been the stuff of
great historical drama, from the civil rights movement in the 1950s
to the Solidarity movement in Poland that eventually brought down
that nation's communist government in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA BAPTISTS AND HOMOSEXUALS
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, four Baptist congregations in Northern
California were voted out of a regional organization, the American
Baptist Churches of the West, after it declared them wrong to
welcome homosexual men and women as members, without teaching that
homosexual activity is sinful.
</P>
<P>
   The four appealed the dismissals, a case that came before
authorities in the larger denomination, the American Baptist
Churches USA. Last month, the appeals by all four were denied
(although a church in Ohio, which had been dismissed from its
regional jurisdiction for a similar reason, was granted its
appeal).
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Rev. Jim Hopkins, pastor of Lakeshore Avenue
Baptist Church in Oakland, Calif., the largest of the four
congregations, said the General Board's decision to deny the appeal
was ``a very unexpected move.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said his congregation faced limited options in
responding, among which were deciding to become independent or
``trying to hang on'' by pursuing ``one or two more procedures''
within the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGES IN CHURCH MEMBERSHIP
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, it became commonplace to hear that mainline
Protestant churches lost many members each year, while evangelical
churches gained. But the 1990s have told a more complicated story,
as membership curves have seemed to flatten out or even, on
occasion, changed direction.
</P>
<P>
   For five years until 1995, for example, the Episcopal Church
reported gaining members. This year, for the first time in decades,
the Southern Baptist Convention reported a membership loss.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Presbyterian Church (USA) said it had
experienced the smallest membership loss in two decades. In 1998,
the denomination declined by 20,000 members, compared with 22,000
in 1997 and 33,000 the year before. A spokesman for the
denomination, which counts 3.6 million members, said evidence
indicated adults with young children returning to church and an
increase in baptisms of adults with no previous affiliation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
