<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5045 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-09 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Century's greatest athlete? Carl Lewis
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   It was a great idea by the cable guys to offer us their list of
the 100 greatest athletes of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since ESPN began paying tribute to its top 50 every Friday
night, it's been water-cooler fodder waiting to happen. It's been a
crescendo of touching memories and moments, with millions of
viewers seeing the list pared week by week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Red Grange galloped onto the list at No. 28. But
of course, that's ESPN's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Like tax deductions and an affinity for fruitcakes, choosing the
100 greatest athletes of the century is a matter of opinion. Your
Mickey Mantle at No. 37 might be my Hank Aaron. Your top 10 might
be my fifty-somethings.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, as the century draws to a close, it is fitting to
crown someone as the one and only best of the best. But we all have
our personal favorites, our unforgettable heroes, our one-of-a-kind
performers who were like no others.
</P>
<P>
   Who was yours? Michael Jordan? Muhammad Ali? Jesse Owens? Jim
Thorpe? Babe Didrikson Zaharias? Babe Ruth? Billie Jean King? Jim
Brown?
</P>
<P>
   All of those greats are among the candidates most often
mentioned as potential No. 1s. But that's someone else's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Here, it says something else: Carl Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Some might not consider Lewis even in the top 10, or _ pointing
to Owens _ not even the No. 1 track star of the 1900s. But much
more than merely Webster's definition of athlete should be
considered when talking about the greatest of the century. After
all, if it was athletic ability alone that determined the best of
the century, Bo Jackson and Deion Sanders probably would be in the
top 10 _ they're not even close _ and Secretariat, which ESPN rated
No. 35, would have them all beat by about 100 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the gauge must include much more than ability alone.
Here, the other factors used to come up with a No. 1 were
performance, longevity, the influence on a particular sport and the
dominance shown in the era.
</P>
<P>
   Taking all those factors into account, Lewis rates ahead of them
all.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan might have been the best performer of the century. He
certainly was dominant and defined his era. But should Jordan even
rate ahead of Didrikson Zaharias, who not only dominated as much at
the Olympic level, but probably could have hit a curveball and
definitely had a better golf game?
</P>
<P>
   With respect to Thorpe and Owens, Lewis was simply the greatest
track star of the century. Not only did he match Owens' wondrous
four-gold feat of 1936 with four golds in 1984, but he added two in
1988, two in 1992 and another in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows what would have happened in 1980, when Lewis also
made the Olympic team, but the Americans boycotted the Moscow
Games? Count 'em. That's five Olympic teams Lewis made, which takes
care of the longevity question.
</P>
<P>
   As for dominance in his era, maybe only Brown, Ruth and Rocky
Marciano could match what Lewis did.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: An Olympic long jump champion will be crowned in
Sydney, Australia, next year. But whoever that winner might be,
there's a chance he wasn't even born the last time anyone but Lewis
won the long jump gold.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the influence on sport and society. Ali and King
had it, altering so many perceptions, changing the landscape of
their sports and bringing unprecedented style and grace to the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   But more so than Lewis?
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was the outspoken spark who brought the Olympic movement
out of the 19th century and into the 21st. He brought
professionalism to the Games, appearance fees and enormous
marketing possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Would there even have been a Dream Team had Lewis not
persistently shook his fist in the faces of the staid and stuffy
Olympic leadership? Would people like Picabo Street, Tara Lipinski
and Michael Johnson be millionaires today?
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, no one demanded drug-testing more than
Lewis. No one questioned the cheating more; no one refused to
buckle under pressure as much; no one persistently called for
reform more. Lewis led the charge to bring drug-testing to sports.
Now, it is present at virtually every international event.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, all of the presumed contenders for No. 1 were
marvelous in every way, and your No. 1 might be different than
mine. It's open to interpretation. After all, most of us can only
read about or watch grainy clips of Thorpe, Jack Dempsey and the
like, which admittedly is unfair.
</P>
<P>
   But from what we know, from the gauge used here, the top five
should be Jordan at No. 5, Didrikson Zaharias at No. 4, Ali at No.
3, Ruth at No. 2 and then King Carl.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just one opinion, which is what makes this argument
ever so much fun. See you at the water cooler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
