s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPEAN-WEDDINGS-$AD     07-09 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-WEDDINGS-$ADV11-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH THIS TRIP, I THEE WED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Portugal, Spain, Italy, Bali, England, Greece)   (For release on Sunday, July 11)  
(DW) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINTRA, Portugal _ It started with a bullfight and ended with
investment bankers and fashion designers skinny-dipping in the
hotel pool.
</P>
<P>
   In between, statuesque women wrapped in pashmina shawls teetered
in Manolo Blahniks on the cobblestone streets of this coastal city
built by Portuguese kings and queens for their summer palaces.
</P>
<P>
   There were ponies with hydrangeas woven into their manes,
flamenco dancing, a series of all-night parties and bottles of
Chateau Lafite brought by members of the Rothschild family from
their own vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   Those were some of the highlights when John Josephson, 37, an
investment banker, and Carolina Zapf, 30, a dress designer, invited
220 of their nearest and dearest to cross the Atlantic Ocean to
their wedding, a five-day fandango over the Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, both New Yorkers, have no family in Portugal, nor
have they ever lived there; they wanted an exotic location, and in
this day of casual jet travel and a galloping economy, the
extravagance of going to Europe for a wedding did not seem
far-fetched. A number of guests, including the bridegroom, who
specializes in movie-industry deals, were traveling from Portugal
to Sun Valley, Idaho, for the conference of media and entertainment
chieftains given by Allen &AMP; Co., the investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to go to another wedding at the Pierre?'' said
Josephson, whose mother, Arlette Brisson, wore a James Galanos
gown, a gift from the designer, to the ceremony, and changed three
times during the 12-hour reception.
</P>
<P>
   This is the summer of the European wedding for certain New
Yorkers willing to pay a minimum of $100,000 for a multi-day
splurge for hundreds of guests. At a chateau near Paris over the
Memorial Day weekend, Nathalie Gerschel, a special events
coordinator at Christie's, wed Edward Kaplan, an executive at
Showtime Networks, before 400 friends.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Jamie Saslow, a former retail sales consultant, and
David Mitchell, an investment banker, were married in the Spanish
Synagogue in the historic Jewish Ghetto in Venice with 160 guests,
who were transported to nine events in four days, requiring two
party planners from Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Also over Fourth of July weekend, Cynthia Kaufman, who used to
work in sales at Donna Karan, and Henry Gabay, an investment
banker, were married before 350 in Istanbul, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Swid, an editor at Mirabella magazine, had to choose
between the Istanbul wedding and the one in Portugal. ``Cynthia is
one of my closest friends,'' she said. That sealed her decision to
go to Istanbul, where festivities began at an open-air nightclub on
Wednesday and peaked at the Saturday ceremony in a restored Ottoman
palace overlooking the Bosporus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't figured out why there is the European wedding
craze,'' Ms. Swid said, ``but there is. Europeans say, `Our
weddings last for days.' But there can be three-day weddings in New
York or Southampton. The difference is you're on holiday, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Polly Onet, an event planner, who last year organized a wedding
for New Yorkers in Dublin, says the economy has a lot to do with
the trend. But she added, ``I think people in high society get very
bored. In order to challenge them and make things very special and
spectacular, it takes bringing them to a completely new environment
in order to blow their minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those marrying or receiving invitations, invariably
accompanied by pages of travel instructions, belong to the loosely
interlocking worlds of charity parties, investment banking and
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these people are on the same wedding circuit,'' noted
Alexandra Kotur, an editor at Vogue, who has been to three weddings
of New Yorkers this summer in Europe. The grandest joined Valesca
Dost and Mathias Guerrand-Hermes, an heir to the French fashion
house, who lives in New York. The wedding started with more than
450 guests on May 12 in Paris and ended five days later in
Marrakech, Morocco, with guests transported by two private jets.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Lind, a fashion designer, went to the Kaufman-Gabay
wedding in Istanbul, the Gerschel-Kaplan wedding in Paris (she
designed the blue satin dresses for the bridesmaids), and plans to
attend a wedding over Labor Day weekend for Victoria Scaravilli, a
Manhattan real estate agent and Owen Colligan, an investment
banker, in Capri, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Colligan and Ms. Scaravilli were themselves at the Portugal
wedding. ``When I told my family we were getting married in Capri,
they thought we were nuts,'' Colligan said, as he ate wedding cake
at 1:30 a.m. in the Palacio de Seteais, an 18th-century
palace-turned-hotel, where the reception was held.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Princess Di over there,'' he said ``wants 12 bridesmaids.
So, I had to find 12 ushers who will go with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Katrina Pavlos, a guest in Portugal, who has been invited to
four European weddings this summer, cried out, ``Please, stop, I
can't afford it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have to go to all of them,'' said Ms. Pavlos,
26, a filmmaker, as she sipped Champagne. ``They're your friends.
But I'm broke by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Onet estimated that the weddings cost the hosts, who often
fly in their own bands and a minister or rabbi to officiate,
anywhere from $100,000 to several million. This contrasts with a
wedding at the Pierre Hotel in New York, which for 200 can run
about $125,000 and up, including flowers, photographers, tips and
taxes, said Arthur Backal, the director of catering at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Guests invited to the Portugal wedding, who paid their own air
fare and lodging, said they spent from $2,500 to $4,000, not
including a gift, numerous clothing changes (during the wedding
reception alone, many of the women changed several times, moving
from cocktail dresses to ball gowns) and, in some cases, the
expense of a nanny brought from home.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Onet said that there is an element of one-upmanship in the
weddings. ``By having an extremely over-the-top, lavish event
abroad, people want to impress, make a statement and outshine the
last party,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s jet-set wedding may have been sparked by the
well-publicized foreign ceremonies of two daughters of the
billionaire Robert Miller. In 1993, Pia Miller married Christopher
Getty in Bali, where Balinese carried the couple on thrones. Three
years later, Marie-Chantal Miller married Crown Prince Pavlos of
Greece in England before 1,100 guests; Valentino designed 27
dresses for the bridal party, and Barry Diller flew in the wedding
cake on his private plane.
</P>
<P>
   Darcy Miller, the weddings editor for Martha Stewart Weddings
magazine (not one of those Miller sisters), said, ``Since the
magazine started in 1995, we've seen so many more destination
weddings, which is going somewhere for your wedding where you do
not live and no one else lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Some couples marry abroad, Ms. Miller said, as a way of paring
down the guest list without bruising feelings. They expect the
travel expense will deter all but their closest and most affluent
friends. But they find out, she said, that people love to travel.
More than 70 percent of those invited showed up for the
Josephson-Zapf wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turn my head and a new person I didn't know was coming
arrives,'' Ms. Zapf said the day before the ceremony, wearing navy
jodhpurs and a white shirt on the terrace of her hotel. She
shrugged. ``I don't know who else is going to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to think about it,'' she said, and went off
horseback riding to relax.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The partying never stops. David Schulhof, 28, a lawyer at
Miramax Films, who attended the Gerschel-Kaplan wedding, said that
on the first night there was a cocktail party on a bateau-mouche on
the Seine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the evening we raged at different nightclubs,'' he said.
``We went to Les Bains Douches, Bar Fly and Le Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Guerrand-Hermes, whose family is French, could claim
he was returning home to be married outside Paris in mid-May, and
thus his wedding was not such an extravagance, the event was the
most lavish this season. New Yorkers were invited in droves.
</P>
<P>
   On the first night, guests were instructed to wear stiletto
heels and slicked-back hair to a flamenco-themed party. The wedding
the next day took place on an Hermes estate in Chantilly, where a
New England-style church had been constructed for the ceremony.
Then, guests were flown by private planes to Marrakech. Over the
next three days, there were a party in the gardens of Yves Saint
Laurent's home, and polo on camelback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone felt like a pasha, it was from another era,'' said
Kristina Stewart, the editor in chief of Quest magazine, who
attended. On the second-to-last night, she said she told the
bridegroom, ``If you want to outdo yourself you're going to have to
come up with a Kelly bag for every guest and a virgin sacrifice
tomorrow night.'' There were no Kelly bags, but guests were sent
home with a custom-made Hermes scarf.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Josephson-Zapf fete in Sintra was more modest.
The guests, a high quotient of Internet entrepreneurs, including
Jon Diamond, the chairman of CDNow, the online music retailer, and
David Wetherell, the chairman of the venture capital company CMGI,
which just before he flew in had paid $2.03 billion for control of
the Web search engine Alta Vista. The front-desk manager of the
converted castle where many guests stayed received daily piles of
faxes in advance with all sorts of special requests, including one
for a T1 high-speed data line. (He had no idea what it was.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet, what celebrants repeatedly praised as the charm of a
multi-day wedding in Portugal was the way busy, competitive people
let down their guard. The social angling familiar to many from
weekends in the Hamptons was largely absent. ``If you take people
out of their element, it works,'' Josephson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon R. Pennington, a marketing strategist, surveyed the
guests dancing in a garden the night before the wedding and said:
``Half these people wouldn't talk to each other if they were
sitting in the Hamptons. When you take them out of the country, in
a place they've never been to, it takes their edge off.''
</P>
<P>
   At 2:30 a.m. the following night, Bradley Lander's eyes were
barely open, but he was unwilling to call it quits. ``When are you
going to be playing in Sintra again?'' he said, and got up to
dance, missing a few steps, with a scantily clad woman who tossed
her lime-green shawl in the grass to join him.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at cocktails, another man had said, ``It's chic to say
you went to Portugal for the weekend.'' Moments before he was
joined by his date, whom he had escorted from New York, he added,
``It's a great way to impress a girl and take her on a test drive
at the same time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
