<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5059 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTI-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN     07-09 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON'S LIKELY RUN BRINGS WAVE OF GOP ANTI-HILLARY
FUND-RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Adds 5 new grafs at end, explaining `pillory Hillary'
reference in lede.)  (See also NY-MRSCLINTON) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With calls to ``pillory Hillary,'' conservative and
Republican organizations are mobilizing to raise millions of
dollars all over the country in an effort to crush Hillary Rodham
Clinton's all-but-certain Senate candidacy in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has long been an object of scorn for large numbers
of conservative groups, all the more so since she attributed the
investigation of the Monica Lewinsky scandal to a ``vast right-wing
conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now her expected bid for public office has inspired fierce
opposition and a flow of checks from conservatives in far-flung
places like Alabama and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the groups behind this effort are hoping to expand
their own donor base as well as raise money that they say they will
spend to prevent Mrs. Clinton from becoming the next senator from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take more than a village to defeat Hillary
Clinton,'' Winton Blount III, chairman of the Alabama Republican
Party, wrote in asking 10,000 donors for checks of $50 or $100, to
be spent on a Senate election more than 1,000 miles away. Other
groups are mailing similar letters.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the prospect of achieving victory for Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, or any other Republican candidate, that is inspiring the
leaders of these organizations. They say their goal is simply to
keep Mrs. Clinton out of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's less motivated by the Republican we want to win _ it's
motivated by preventing her to be elected to the United States
Senate,'' said Craig Shirley, a conservative Republican consultant
who helped organize Conservatives for Effective Leadership, a
political action committee formed here last month with the goal of
raising $10 million to pay for advertisements against Mrs. Clinton
in New York State next year.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republicans had mixed reactions to the outside efforts
against Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased to have organizations outside New York
looking to defeat Hillary Clinton,'' said Dan Allen, a spokesman
for the state party. ``We feel she is only coming up here to run
for president in 2004.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Teitelbaum, director of Giuliani's exploratory committee,
said the mayor would attend fund-raisers in Alabama later this
month for his Senate campaign, but sought to distance Giuliani from
the anti-Clinton fund-raising drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``What other groups are doing, and state parties are doing, in
respect to raising money, it's not something we're connected to,''
Teitelbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican strategist involved in the Senate race in New
York doubted that the contributions aimed at defeating Mrs. Clinton
would benefit her Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as a tremendous benefit to any candidate,''
this strategist said. ``This is what the Republicans did with Ted
Kennedy and the Democrats did with Newt Gingrich. Every
fund-raising group in the world loves a bogyman.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, the spokesman for Mrs. Clinton's exploratory
committee, declined to comment on the conservative groups' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley's PAC, raising money from across the country, was
created, its literature says, to ``educate voters about unqualified
candidates.'' But Shirley confirmed that it would devote all its
energies in the next year and a half to the effort to defeat one
candidate: Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a fund-raising standpoint, anyone on the right who
doesn't target Hillary is a fool,'' Shirley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run just one cell of the vast right-wing conspiracy,'' he
said. ``The sophistry that she was selling when she coined that
phrase was that Monica was part of some right-wing conspiracy, that
we had put her up to stalking the president. Of course, that wasn't
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Some groups started raising money against Mrs. Clinton weeks
before she began her ``listening tour'' in New York on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured that a lot of the Clinton haters would come out of
the woodwork,'' said Charles Lewis, founder and executive director
of the Center for Public Integrity, a campaign finance watchdog.
``I just thought it would take a few more weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that all the money netted by the anti-Clinton
appeals will really be spent in New York; various conservative
groups have long used President Clinton and his wife as
fund-raising targets. But whatever is spent in New York will only
add to what already appears virtually certain to be the most
expensive Senate race in history.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's supporters hope to raise $25 million for her
campaign, and her most likely Republican opponent, Giuliani, hopes
to raise an equal amount. If other organizations, like the
Democratic and Republican national committees, make good on their
promise to spend millions on issue advertisements, the race could
end up costing $100 million, political strategists say.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising strategists say that the anti-Hillary fervor of the
Republican organizations demonstrates that Mrs. Clinton has already
assumed her husband's role as a magnet for checks when her name is
cited in conservative fund-raising letters.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee mentioned Mrs. Clinton's
health care policies in recent written and telephone solicitations
for cash. ``It has been a huge success,'' said Clifford D. May, the
committee's communications director. ``There is no question that
Hillary Clinton and her policies energize the Republican activists.
She is a polarizing figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Alabama's lead, the New Hampshire Republican Party
will also ask 10,000 New Hampshire Republicans to contribute money
to defeat Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had eight years of Clinton-Gore,'' said Steve Duprey,
the party chairman. ``Why would we let yet another Clinton do it in
the United States Senate? I predict it will be one of our most
effective fund-raising letters. She is a figure that energizes the
Republican base.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nolan, a nationally syndicated radio talk show host, said
he had always assumed that Mrs. Clinton would not run, because
``she has too much to lose.'' But after it became clear in late May
that she almost certainly would run, Nolan quickly helped found
Conservatives for Effective Leadership, the PAC that Shirley also
had a hand in creating.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Nolan, whose literature calls on supporters to
help ``pillory Hillary,'' sent 40,000 letters to conservatives
around the country. In an interview, he declined to say how much
had already been raised, describing the response only as ``huge.''
His solicitation letter promised ``television commercials,
newspaper ads, voter guides, media packets ... there's nothing we
won't do to keep Hillary out of office.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount, the Alabama Republican chairman, said he had challenged
other state party leaders to raise money to spend on anti-Clinton
advertisements in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Already the Alabama letter has raised tens of thousands of
dollars, party officials said. And Blount said he planned to
deliver that money personally to Republican leaders in New York. He
also said Mrs. Clinton clearly hoped to use a Senate seat as a
launching pad to return to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just imagine four years from now _ `Hillary for President,'''
Blount wrote. ``Scary, isn't it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
