<DOCNO> NYT19990709.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-KILLINGS-10COX     07-09 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-KILLINGS-10COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slaying suspect lured girls to his house
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein and Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Just days before three teen-age Sidney girls were
killed in Thursday's bloody rampage, one of the girls told her
mother that the man now suspected of killing the girls had been
luring them to his house, offering to pay them cash to watch him
masturbate, the mother said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl L. Cai, mother of victim Sherry Kimbler, said she
believes Lawrence Michael ``Mike'' Hensley, who remained at large
Friday night, killed the girls _ in a spree that also left a man
dead and a woman critically wounded _ because he feared his sex
secrets were close to being revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had an idea that people were getting on to him,''
said Cai, 35, who lives just across from Hensley's home, where the
three girls were killed. ``I think he had it set up and planned to
kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Dean Kimpel, operations chief for the Sidney police, said
that theory ``is something we're looking at.'' Police also are
investigating the possibility Hensley, 30, is part of a Satanic
cult, Kimpel said. But authorities are not close to determining a
motive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dead girls are Sherry Kimbler, 16; Sherry's cousin Tosha L.
Barrett, also 16; and Amy Mikesell, 14, described by Cai as
Sherry's best friend. Veronica Eagy, 22, of Russells Point, was
wounded by multiple shotgun wounds but crawled out a basement
window in Hensley's residence to summon help about 5:16 p.m.
Thursday. She is in critical condition and under guard at Miami
Valley Hospital, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Roy Wildermuth, 37, was killed at his home outside Sidney
about 20 minutes after the teens' deaths were discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Wildermuth, a member of First Church of God where the Hensleys
also attended services, had been praying with Hensley immediately
before he was killed, according to the victim's pastor. The pastor,
Ben Davis, said Hensley had phoned Davis, Wildermuth and other
church members before he left home. ``He called a number of church
members trying to find someone to pray with'' before he found
Wildermuth, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Kimpel said the bodies of Sherry and Tosha were found in a
bedroom on the main floor of the home. They suffered multiple
wounds from a short-barreled shotgun, according to an arrest
warrant. A shotgun had been fired in that bedroom, Kimpel said.
</P>
<P>
   Eagy's assailant apparently left her for dead, Kimpel said. She
broke out a basement window and crawled into the yard. Two teen-age
boys saw her and ran to the nearby home of a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   The stabbed body of Amy Mikesell was not found until about 10:30
p.m., Kimpel said, and her killer apparently purposely concealed
her in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three of those girls could have been models _ pretty,
petite,'' said Sherry's uncle, Bill Richards. ``This is like a slap
in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Police hauled a truckload of potential evidence from Hensley's
home. In the garage Thursday night, they found 24 Molotov cocktails
_ empty 12-ounce beer bottles recently filled with a flammable
liquid and stuffed with rags as wicks _ Kimpel said. They were
destroyed Thursday night by a U.S. Army ordnance disposal unit.
</P>
<P>
   Kimpel said Amy may have been stabbed to death hours before the
shootings. After the shootings, Julie Hensley, the suspect's wife
since April, came home and the couple drove to Wildermuth's home,
he said. Police believe Julie Hensley was unaware of the carnage in
the Queen Street home. No charges have been filed against her.
</P>
<P>
   Wildermuth, the father of three children younger than 10, was
killed by a large handgun, according to arrest warrants. His wife
and children were not home. After the shooting, police said, Julie
Hensley went for help, and her husband drove away in her car,
leaving her behind.
</P>
<P>
   A 17-year-old neighbor and former baby sitter for the
Wildermuths said her mother overheard Julie Hensley tell police
that ``it was after he finished praying that he shot Brett.''
</P>
<P>
   Hensley has a history of public indecency convictions, and
frequently sought psychological counseling because of his history
of indecent exposure, according to Sidney police records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have a sexual disorder problem and I know I need
help,'' he told Sidney police detectives investigating an earlier
indecent exposure case. ``Some true, honest help. Someone that will
find out why I do this, because deep down I don't want to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Davis of First Church of God, where Hensley's bride is a
longtime member, said Hensley had been involved in devil worship,
but church members felt he was changing with Wildermuth's help.
</P>
<P>
   Police put out a nationwide bulletin to law enforcement
agencies, seeking Hensley's arrest. Police said Hensley is
5-foot-11 with a stocky build, a goatee, a shaved head and tattoos
on both forearms. He was last seen driving a purple, two-door
Chevrolet Cavalier bearing Ohio license ANQ-7879. Police filed
arrest warrants Friday in Shelby County Common Pleas charging
Hensley with four counts of aggravated murder. The warrants said
Hensley was last seen wearing a blue T-shirt and cap with
University of Kentucky emblems on them, blue-jean shorts and white
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Kimpel said Hensley is considered heavily armed _ with at least
a shotgun, rifle and handgun _ and dangerous. He also has been
trained in the martial arts.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Hensley's family Friday said they were in shock by
the accusations against Hensley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never think it would happen to your family,'' one Hensley
relative said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret the loss of the shooting victims and we are
sympathetic and they are in our prayers as well,'' a female family
member said.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney police had given the family no information and told them
to contact police if Hensley tries to reach them, family members
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever suspected this _ it was totally off the wall,'' a
woman who said she is ``indirectly related'' to Hensley said.
``It's very obvious he cracked, so obviously something was going
on. We may never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Cai, Sherry's mother, said someone at a Fourth of July party on
Sunday told her that Hensley was luring the girls to his home with
cash to watch him masturbate. Cai said she questioned her daughter,
who admitted Hensley paid $50 to $100 to her and other girls for
the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry pleaded with Cai not to report Hensley to police, Cai
said, because Sherry feared reprisals. Cai said she didn't report
the incident after Sherry promised never to go back to Hensley's
house. ``We talked about it the last couple of days,'' Cai said.
She said she was still debating whether to report it when the
killings occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Cai said she heard what sounded like gunshots when she came home
for lunch about 1:30 p.m. She knocked on Hensley's door about 2
p.m. and asked Hensley if he had seen Sherry. He told her Sherry
had been to his house to use the phone, but left in a gray Cadillac
with a young man known to the family. Hensley also asked Cai to
come in for a drink, she said. She refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I said was, `Where's my daughter?' And he lied,'' Cai
said. When she looked into Hensley's eyes, ``I knew he knew (that)
I knew'' about the sexual favors, Cai said.
</P>
<P>
   She said a younger cousin of Sherry's later told her that
Hensley had recently offered $400 each to the three girls to meet
at his house for unspecified purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Tosha's aunt, Brenda Stiver, said Tosha had been living with her
for several months. Stiver said Tosha recently got a job ``and was
saving every dollar to get a car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't stupid girls, but they were naive, I guess you'd
say,'' said Cai's friend Georgia Fair of Sidney. ``I think little
Sherry told Hensley that her mom knew (about the sexual favors).''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Mikesell's mother, Rita, believes the teens, who've been
friends since the Mikesells moved from Florida to Sidney six months
ago, went to Hensley's house to use the phone because Sherry
Kimbler didn't have one.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Rita Mikesell thought her daughter left one day early
to go to the four-day country concert in Fort Loramie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know fully that it was Amy till noon,'' she said.
``The lieutenant brought a picture of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Wildermuth's neighbors expressed shock at his slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody in this world that's any nicer than those
people (the Wildermuths),'' Rosie Breen said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days ago, (Brett) was out here teaching his little
5-year-old how to ride her bicycle. He said, 'Rosie, do you think
I'll ever teach her?' I said, 'Sure you will.''' She paused and
stared out at the spot in front of her home where Wildermuth had
been with his little girl. ``Well, he won't now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Mary McCarty, Jim DeBrosse, Michael Jesse, Jim
Bebbington, Scott Elliot, Ken McCall, Lisa Perry, Cathy Mong and
Christine Vasconez contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
