<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5164 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     07-09 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV014-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: THE DIRT ON OFFICE BATHROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, July 14)  
 (DW)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are a boss and you're wondering why your employees seem
to be suffering from low morale, it may not because of the low pay,
long hours or powerful electric shocks you send coursing through
their bodies every time they stand up to stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The reason might be that they're disgusted with the bathrooms.
According to a survey by Kimberly-Clark, 51 percent of employees
think their office bathroom is the sanitary equivalent of a
fish-market dumpster, only with a more offensive smell.
</P>
<P>
   The survey did not reveal what this means in terms of worker
productivity, but you've got to think the news is not good.
</P>
<P>
   A worker who is too afraid to use his or her office bathroom, no
matter how urgent the need, is a worker who is not devoting his
full attention to his work. Pressure of this sort not only leads to
mistakes, but also increases the number of sick and ``personal''
days taken off by the employee.
</P>
<P>
   An employee who is dancing around the office on one leg is an
employee who is not contributing to the company's bottom line, so
to speak. It is hard to concentrate on reports and spreadsheets
when bacteria the size of Shetland ponies are clomping about in the
company restroom down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, if not likely, that most office disgruntlement
can be directly traced back to unsanitary bathrooms. Employee
complaints including the air conditioning being set too low or too
high, inadequate work space or outdated equipment could simply be a
way of crying out for a more liberal use of Sani-Flush.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers might argue that if they keep the bathrooms too
clean, employees will spend all day in there, coming out only long
enough to collect their pay checks and scarf up more coffee and
doughnuts. Judging by the survey, there is possibly some truth to
that.
</P>
<P>
   A surprising number of American workers would like to see their
office bathrooms converted into a sort of tiled, disinfected
home-entertainment center. Of those surveyed, 7 percent said they
would like phones, stereos and CD players installed in the john.
</P>
<P>
   Although I support almost every idea workers come up with to
torment their employer-oppressors, including Take Your Dog to Work
Day, I'm not sure how comfortable I'd be visiting the office
bathroom when the guy in the stall next to me is playing, at
porcelain-cracking volume, ``Cassie Eats Cockroaches'' Acid Bath on
the company-installed boom box.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to bring a newspaper or magazine into the bathroom
with you, that's fine, but please leave your KoRn and Punk-O-Rama
CDs at home or in the car.
</P>
<P>
   Even more disturbing is the opinion of 2 percent of respondents
that saunas should be installed in company restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that interpersonal relationships in the office
environment are dicey enough these days without encouraging people
to sit naked for long periods of time in a 200-degree box.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is so stupid that it could only have come from
management. Their thinking here, I presume, is that employees can
barely tolerate occupying the same building with one another let
alone sitting naked in a 200-degree box together, so saunas would
keep workers out of the company bathrooms even more effectively
than the old method, which was simply not to clean the place for
decades at a time.
</P>
<P>
   When you think of the alternatives, a little dirt might not be
such a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
