<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY   TRIES AGAIN   TO RETURN   TO YANKEES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUG FERNANDES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ At 8:42 Friday morning, Darryl Strawberry entered
the Yankees' minor league complex in a silver Ford Expedition.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of vehicle seemed appropriate, because Friday
signaled the beginning of Strawberry's journey back into baseball.
It was his first workout at a team facility since he was arrested
April 14 on charges of cocaine possession and solicitation of a
prostitute, charges to which he pleaded no contest six weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in workout clothes, Strawberry, 37, was greeted by a
handful of reporters. For about 15 minutes, before he embarked on a
workout that was closed to reporters and the public, Strawberry
stood and talked about himself, his arrest and his feelings of
remorse.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry said his troubles this spring stemmed from
depression. Still recovering from treatment for colon cancer,
Strawberry was not among the outfielders the Yankees included on
their major league roster at the end of spring training and was
left behind in Tampa to continue working into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really psychologically went through some different changes
of being out in the heat, trying to prove myself and putting extra
pressure on myself,'' Strawberry said. ``When I didn't make the
ball club, it put more pressure on me and I really fell into a real
deep depression. I wasn't mad at anyone. I was mad at myself more
than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was during this period that he began drinking again
and ``slacked off'' on attending Alcoholics Anonymous meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a tendency to come down on athletes, but we have
people in very high positions that go through the same struggles I
do with my alcoholism,'' Strawberry said. ``I'm clean and sober
today, and that's the most important thing. I want to continue to
stay that way. I'm back on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry also used the interview to apologize to George
Steinbrenner ``for any pain and shame that I caused to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done so many great things for me,'' Strawberry said. He
said he had spoken with Steinbrenner and that the principal owner
``basically told me that I let him down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt that I had a great deal of pressure on my back,
fighting through the cancer and chemo,'' Strawberry said. ``He
realized all the things that I've been trying to overcome was a
world of pressure on me. I just told him how bad I felt as a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   In the workout itself, Strawberry did some stretching and
running, shagged fly balls and spent about 15 minutes taking
batting practice. He reportedly hit more than a dozen pitches over
the fence before heading off to the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry is under a 120-day suspension imposed by Commissioner
Bud Selig, retroactive to his arrest. That means he could be
eligible to play again for the Yankees on Aug. 12, but Selig will
review the suspension on July 22 and may lift the suspension at
that point.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre has suggested that Strawberry will
need several weeks of game action in the minor leagues before the
Yankees will even consider putting him on the roster, and there are
lingering questions about the condition of Strawberry's knees and
whether he will able to play the outfield this season.
</P>
<P>
   But that issue will be addressed later. For now, Strawberry was
happy to be back in the Yankee family. He had remained in the Tampa
area since his arrest, hitting at a batting cage and, in his words,
``trying to keep a good attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not setting any personal timetables,'' he added. ``I'll
let the team judge where I'm at physically and mentally and
everything as far as getting back.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
