<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-FEE-NYT &LR;      07-09 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MOVES TO TIGHTEN REINS   ON NEW INTERNET REGULATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Va.) 
 (DW) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Responding to growing criticism of the way the
Internet's new governing body is operating, the Department of
Commerce on Friday told the nonprofit group to eliminate a
controversial $1 fee on Internet address registrations, to open its
board meetings to the public immediately and to draft clear
restrictions on the boundaries of its authority.
</P>
<P>
   Though created as a joint venture with the federal government,
the governing body, the Internet Corp. for Assigned Names and
Numbers, or Icann, has held its meetings behind closed doors since
it was formed last year. Criticism increased this spring when Icann
began making policy decisions, including one to levy fees on
Internet address registrations to finance its $5.7 million annual
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce officials also fired a public warning shot at Network
Solutions, which has bristled at measures taken to end the
company's longtime monopoly in the lucrative business of
registering domain names, as Internet addresses are known.
</P>
<P>
   In its letter, Commerce officials insisted that the department
could and would revoke the company's right to register addresses if
it continued to refuse to recognize Icann's authority. One of
Icann's first charges from Commerce was to break up Network
Solutions' monopoly in the most popular domains _ those ending in
.com, .net and .org.
</P>
<P>
   Five companies have begun a test round of competition with
Network Solutions, but technical delays and disputes between the
company, Commerce and Icann have delayed the opening of full-scale
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions called the recommended changes for Icann a
``good first step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly see this as the Department of Commerce resetting
Icann,'' said Christopher Clough, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   As for the letter's warning to the company, he said, ``We don't
think it's an issue. We're working in negotiations with Commerce
towards an acceptable solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Esther Dyson, Icann's interim chairwoman, said the board would
give the letter serious consideration and might try to act on it
before the House Commerce Committee holds hearings on the matter
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Ms. Dyson said she found the letter encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't say we were perfect,'' she said. ``But it said we
were worth improving.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposals and warnings were detailed in a 32-page document
the Commerce Department sent to Rep. Thomas Bliley III, the
chairman of the House Commerce Committee, who last month voiced
concern about the department's handing over to Icann oversight of
the Internet's administrative functions. Bliley, R-Va., Network
Solutions' home base, also asked Commerce and Ms. Dyson to respond
to concerns about the board's closed meetings, the $1 fee and other
controversial actions.
</P>
<P>
   That inquiry, along with similar letters from consumer
advocates, including Ralph Nader, followed a lobbying campaign by
Network Solutions, which insists that Icann is overstepping its
authority and trying to put the company out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Icann should immediately open its board meetings to the
public,'' the Commerce Department letter said. ``Transparency is
critical to establishing trust in decision making. And trust is
essential for Icann's ultimate success.''
</P>
<P>
   While defending Icann's authority to levy the $1 a year fee on
every domain name registered, the Commerce Department asked that it
be eliminated, at least temporarily, saying no permanent financing
method should be adopted until a permanent 18-member board is
elected.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Icann in a tough position, having spent the nearly
$500,000 in corporate donations for its start-up. But Commerce
pledged to help Icann secure government and private funds to keep
operating until a permanent revenue source is found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Icann's top priority must be completing the work necessary to
put in place an elected board of directors on a timely basis,'' the
Commerce letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the changes are posed as recommendations, not orders,
Commerce officials retain authority over Icann through next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department has the authority to terminate its relationship
with Icann if we believe that Icann isn't acting in accordance with
the principles,'' of our agreement, said Andrew Pincus, general
counsel for the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   Many critics greeted the Commerce letters as a welcome check on
the controversial board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open board meetings are a no-brainer,'' said Jonathan
Zittrain, executive director of the Berkman Center for Internet and
Society. The letter also raised the stakes over Network Solutions'
refusal to recognize Icann. The company has balked at signing the
agreement that companies wishing to compete with it have had to
sign, saying the agreement gives Icann too much authority.
</P>
<P>
   To counter charges of over-regulation, Commerce asked Icann to
``assure all registrars and registries, through contract, that it
will restrict its policy development activities to matters that are
reasonably necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Network Solutions, the Commerce Department said that it
intends to take away the company's right to run the .com, .net and
.org registry if it fails to recognize the authority of whatever
body was appointed to administer the network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
