<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUPNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS WILL BE WATCHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ By kickoff time in today's final match for
the Women's World Cup, the Rose Bowl stands will resemble ringside
at a major prize fight because several celebrities are expected to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Already sending positive RSVPs are actors Antonio Banderas,
Melanie Griffith, Elizabeth Shue and Scott Bakula, and singer k.d.
lang. Also in attendance will be President Clinton and the First
Family.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, between the third-place and championship games,
actress-turned-singer Jennifer Lopez will sing her hit ``If You Had
My Love,'' and ``Let's Get Loud.''
</P>
<P>
   The young girls in the audience will be treated to the group
Hanson singing the U.S. national anthem. Chinese celebrity Lin Liu
will sing that country's anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Consolation prize: In case you didn't know, the third-place game
between Norway and Brazil will precede the final today at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Norway, along with the United States, has been the best team in
women's soccer since the inception of the Women's World Cup. On the
other hand, Brazil has been a quick riser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We promise to make it an entertaining game for the fans,''
Brazilian Pretinha said. ``We like to play soccer and we hope they
will like to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarl Toske, Norway's assistant coach, had his own perspective _
to paraphrase, this is a rebuilding year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are building a new team, with only six or seven players
left from our Olympic squad,'' he said. ``But we feel we proved
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Politically correct: U.S. coach Tony DiCicco, when asked if
President Clinton was visiting for purely political purposes,
demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's the intent of the President. I really
think he's a fan of this team,'' DiCicco said. ``And Chelsea has
always been a fan of this team. She sat on our bench once when we
beat Norway in Washington D.C., so I don't think there's any
political motivation here. He's just a fan, and whether there's any
outreach politically, I don't know. That's way over my head.''
</P>
<P>
   End is near: U.S. player Brandi Chastain will be sad when the
tournament is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm going to be very sad. It's hard to say goodbye to
something this wonderful and this motivating,'' she said. ``It's
hard to find motivation in things and this has been such a huge
motivation factor. It will be tough to go home and take a week off.
It will be hard to have that same motivation again knowing the
World Cup is four years away, but I think we'll use this event to
look back on.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear of the unknown: It has been pretty tough over the past few
days for the U.S. players to do any scouting of the Chinese team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't seen any of their games,'' Tisha Venturini said after
a recent practice at Pomona College. ``Haven't seen any videotape
yet, either.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes it tougher is the lack of a certain sports channel at
the U.S. hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotels we have stayed in didn't have ESPN2 (which telecast
four of China's five tournament games) except in the bar, and we
didn't want to go down there because it would be impossible to
watch with the people wanting to talk with us,'' captain Carla
Overbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Ceremony planned: Win or lose, the U.S. team will be honored in
a ceremony at the Los Angeles Convention Center on Sunday
afternoon, according to officials of the Los Angeles Sports and
Entertainment Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
