<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surprise start by Chen gets Sox swinging
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bruce Chen had only a couple hours to contemplate his
seventh major league start Friday night after he was asked to
replace an ailing Odalis Perez against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   This was one Chen would like to forget.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox hammered Chen for three home runs and hung on for a
5-4 win in front of 49,636 at Turner Field, the largest Atlanta
crowd since Mark McGwire came to town last Aug. 1 during his home
run chase.
</P>
<P>
   Chen picked up the loss in his third start for Atlanta this
season, and his first since returning to the Braves from Richmond
on Monday when John Smoltz went on the disabled list again with an
inflamed elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, playing without star shortstop Nomar Garciaparra
for the seventh consecutive game and limping in on a three-game
losing streak, evened this interleague season series at 2-2 with
two more games to play here over the weekend. If Chen wasn't
striking a batter out or walking him, he was leaving his pitches
up, and the Red Sox hitters knew exactly what to do with those. So
Chen's line looked like this: four hits allowed, three of them home
runs, five strikeouts and four walks.
</P>
<P>
   Spoiling a 3-0 Braves head start on Boston starter Bret
Saberhagen, Chen's night unraveled on a leadoff homer by Wilton
Veras in the third inning and back-to-back homers by Damon Buford
and Mike Stanley to start the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason he didn't give up the lead at that point was
Andruw Jones' diving catch in shallow center field to take a
run-scoring hit away from Saberhagen. Chen lasted only one more
batter, walking Chad Fonville on four pitches to lead off the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Fonville came around to score when Andruw Jones came up a few
feet short of another great catch, allowing Darren Lewis a triple
that gave the Red Sox their first lead, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' center field clinic continued in the fifth inning when he
caught a Troy O'Leary drive over his shoulder while crashing into
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss broke an 0-for-25 slump with a soft liner to right to
drive in Eddie Perez, who had doubled, to cut the lead to 5-4 in
the seventh. But Brian Jordan grounded out to strand runners at
first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
