<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5182 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     07-09 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOE TORRE'S   REAL NEWS   ABOUT 2001  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ When Joe Torre casually mentioned in a television
interview that he was ``not thinking about'' managing the Yankees
beyond the 2001 season, it didn't deserve the headlines it
received. The Yankee manager was merely repeating what he had first
mentioned as long ago as last October when he signed his two-year
contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   But what did deserve headlines was that Joe Torre is the first
Yankee manager in nearly three decades of George Steinbrenner's
often tyrannical regime to assume that he would still be in the
Yankee dugout after the next 2 1/2 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Now that is man-bites-dog news, if not manager-bites-owner news.
Any of Torre's 13 predecessors in the Steinbrenner regime surely
would have agreed, especially Billy Martin, who, during any of his
five tempestuous terms, never dared to assume that he would still
be in the Yankee dugout after the next 2 1/2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Or until the next time the red phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   In the tumult of those Martin years, a red telephone sat on his
desk in the manager's office at Yankee Stadium. Whenever it rang,
he would all but jump out of his chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's George,'' he would say, waving a hand at anyone who was
there. ``You better leave.''
</P>
<P>
   As his visitors walked out of the office and closed the door,
they always wondered if Billy Martin was about to leave, too.
Eventually, during the 1988 season, he left for the fifth and last
time.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a black phone on the desk in the manager's office at
Yankee Stadium. When it rings, Joe Torre is always quick to answer
it because it might be George and he knows who's the Boss. But even
when it is the principal owner, Torre doesn't appear to be alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Yankees lost, 5-2, in the first game of the Shea
Stadium segment of their six-game subway series with the Mets
Friday night, they were halfway through their fourth season without
a seriously inflammable flap between the manager and the principal
owner.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Martin and some other Yankee managers, Torre has
maintained his cool even when he knows George is annoyed with him.
He has been known to phone George first and say, ``How's your
personality today, Boss?'' and then talk out the disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   There is a mutual respect between the principal owner and Torre
that seldom existed with other Yankee managers. When Torre first
took over in 1996, he told his coaches, ``If you take his money,
you've got to take'' his, shall we say, shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   Torre is so cool, he has even cooled the principal owner a few
degrees, at least publicly.
</P>
<P>
   You haven't heard the principal owner second-guessing Torre's
strategy or psychology. Not that there has been any real reason to
grumble. Now in his fourth season, Torre has guided the Yankees to
two World Series championships, two American League East titles and
their current first-place perch.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Yankees were winning two World Series and four AL
pennants under Martin and Bob Lemon two decades ago, success never
stopped the impatient principal owner from growling.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees were losing, nobody was safe, not even Yogi
Berra. Early in the 1985 season, Yogi understandably assumed he
would be the manager for more than 16 games. He was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Until Torre arrived, life with George was like that for all the
Yankee managers, beginning with Ralph Houk, who resigned after a
fourth-place finish in 1973 rather than listen to him anymore. The
others would come and go _ Bill Virdon, Martin, Lemon, Martin
again, Dick Howser, Gene Michael, Lemon again, Michael again, Clyde
King, Martin again, Berra, Martin again, Lou Piniella, Martin
again, Piniella again, Dallas Green, Bucky Dent, Stump Merrill,
Buck Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   Over four seasons, which included the strike-shortened 1994
schedule, Showalter was the Yankee manager for 581 consecutive
games, a record for the Steinbrenner era, when managers changed
more often than batboys.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't count the 36 games Torre missed at the start of
this season while recuperating from prostate surgery, he is now
approaching Showalter's mark. But he has established one record for
a Yankee manager in the Steinbrenner regime: assuming he will still
be the manager after another 2 1/2 seasons. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
