<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-1STLD-WRITE     07-09 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL INVESTIGATORS ASK CITY TO REVAMP POLICE DEPARTMENT
PROCEDURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  
 (SUBS to add 700 wds to end of original text. New text adds details
and background on the federal investigation of the Police
Department, other federal investigations of police departments and
possible political ramifications of the New York City
investigation.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a lengthy investigation of the New York City
Police Department, federal prosecutors have amassed evidence of
systemwide problems in the department's handling of police
brutality complaints, and are pressing the Giuliani administration
to undertake reforms, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If the city does not agree to changes sought by the U.S.
attorney in Brooklyn, Zachary Carter, the Justice Department could
sue the city, seeking a court-ordered overhaul and possible
oversight by a federal monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who opened his investigation after the August 1997
torture of Abner Louima by two officers in a Brooklyn station
house, is now in secret talks with top Giuliani administration
officials over a possible settlement, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   One hurdle is that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a staunch defender of
the Police Department, has said he would be unwilling to accept the
imposition of a federal monitor or other outside oversight of the
department, which is by far the largest in the country with 39,000
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's precise findings were not known Friday, but the Justice
Department has said that he has examined whether incidents of
excessive force by officers ``were the product of systemic
deficiencies in police operations, including possible failures in
intake and investigation, discipline and supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have charged that police officials do not aggressively
pursue allegations of brutality by officers, even in cases in which
outside investigators have found evidence to support the charges.
For example, Carter's office has looked at how the department
follows up cases referred by the Civilian Complaint Review Board,
which investigates allegations of police wrongdoing, and cases in
which the city has settled lawsuits charging officers with
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's investigation is one of at least 10 nationwide of
police and sheriff's departments by prosecutors looking for
patterns of brutality and other civil rights violations. The
actions reflect the Justice Department's use of a 1994 law that
grew out of the Rodney King beating in Los Angeles, which
authorizes federal prosecutors to seek changes in the operations of
local departments.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Justice Department's Civil Rights Division and
the U.S. attorney in Los Angeles announced the most recent such
inquiry, investigating the use of force and treatment of minorities
by officers in Riverside, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has also acknowledged that it is
investigating racial profiling by New Jersey State Police troopers,
in which officers stop drivers on suspicion of criminal actions
based solely on race. And after the fatal shooting of Amadou Diallo
by officers in the Bronx, Justice officials said Mary Jo White, the
U.S. attorney in Manhattan, was examining whether certain patterns
or practices of the city's Street Crime Unit violated civil rights
laws. Both of those investigations are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   City and police officials refused to answer questions Friday
night on any talks with Carter's office. Previously, Police
Commissioner Howard Safir and the corporation counsel, Michael D.
Hess, had said they were cooperating with Carter's investigation,
which Carter has confirmed publicly. City officials have said they
provided thousands of files concerning police brutality complaints
and how the department responded to them; the training of officers;
their use of firearms, and lawsuits against the department.
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions Friday night, Carter said that under
federal rules involving such investigations, the Justice Department
must bring its findings to a city or municipal government for
possible resolution before filing a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``At this particular juncture, it would not be
constructive for me to comment on any questions about any
discussions with the city.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Carter's investigation could become a divisive political issue
in New York. If he decides to sue the city, the law requires that
he have the approval of Attorney General Janet Reno. This could
result in the Clinton Justice Department's attacking the Giuliani
administration in federal court at the same time that Hillary
Rodham Clinton is running against Giuliani for a U.S. Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how such a court battle would play out in a
campaign, but Giuliani, who has trumpeted the sharp reduction in
crime in the city as his greatest achievement, has vigorously
defended the Police Department's performance.
</P>
<P>
   As the mayor said last March: ``This Police Department, for all
its faults and imperfections, and I am acutely aware of them, is
the best in the country. In every respect. Not just in reducing
crime, but in dealing with crowd control, in dealing with
minorities, in dealing with sensitive issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He has said that he has no tolerance for officers who violate
people's rights, but he has also condemned critics who blame the
entire department for the transgressions of a few officers.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Before you can start talking about federal
micromanaging of this Police Department, there are about 200 police
departments you'd have to put ahead of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of Carter's investigation have been anxiously
awaited by people inside and outside the Police Department, critics
and supporters alike. For critics, including many black and
Hispanic New Yorkers, it is viewed as perhaps the best opportunity
yet to eradicate frequent police mistreatment of minorities and a
culture of officers who cover for the misdeeds of colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials have said they are confident that Carter
would uncover isolated problems only, certainly no pattern or
policy of officials' condoning brutality or violations of civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is completing his investigation while he prepares to
leave office next Friday to join a private law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials would not discuss Carter's findings, he
seemed likely to focus on improving the way the department follows
up on complaints of brutality committed by officers, particularly
those investigated by the Civilian Complaint Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the review board has criticized the department's
lack of response when it has substantiated allegations of brutality
and referred them to the department for further disciplinary
action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
