<SLUG> BC-GASTINEAU-JAIL-SENTENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GASTINEAU GETS 15 DAYS AFTER HARASSMENT CHARGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Gastineau, the former Jets defensive end who had
a reputation for being volatile both on and off the field, was
sentenced to 15 days in jail Friday after being arrested on charges
of violating an order of protection obtained by his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Gastineau, 42, was arrested Monday after he turned himself in at
a Queens precinct station house on charges of violating a court
order to stop harassing his estranged wife, Patricia Schorr.
</P>
<P>
   He is accused of going to his wife's apartment in the Forest
Hills neighborhood of Queens, on June 22, leaning on the intercom
buzzer from 3:30 a.m. until 6:30 a.m. and refusing to leave,
according to the Queens district attorney's office. He turned
himself in on Monday and was arrested. Ms. Schorr had obtained the
order of protection after Gastineau pleaded guilty last October to
a misdemeanor assault charge for hitting her and threatening her
with a glass cocktail table.
</P>
<P>
   But even as charges for harassment in the intercom incident are
pending, Justice Deborah Stevens Modica of the State Supreme Court
in Queens, sent Gastineau to jail Friday because his Monday arrest
violated the terms of a conditional discharge in a separate
harassment case involving another woman whom he dated before
marrying Ms. Schorr last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In view of the defendant's past transgressions, as well as the
case here, we felt it was appropriate that he serve some jail
time,'' said Richard A. Brown, the Queens district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Gastineau, who lives in the Bayside area of Queens, pleaded
guilty last year to harassing the unidentified woman on a street in
Bayside in February 1998. He was charged with hitting the
33-year-old woman and bruising her face and wrist. He was released
on the condition that he attend an anger management class and that
he stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Modica ruled Friday that his arrest in the case involving his
wife constituted a violation of those conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Gastineau played for the Jets for 10 years and accumulated a
record of 22 sacks in the 1984 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-09-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
