<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-ADVANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BRACES FOR CHINA IN CUP FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Mia Hamm said she would get to bed early
Friday. Tiffeny Milbrett, suffering from recent nightmares, hoped
she could get some rest. The coolest of them all, goalkeeper Briana
Scurry, said she would sleep like a baby.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the thoughts of the players at the end of 18 months
of build-up, all the hoopla that has surrounded the United States
women's national soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   All that is left now is China _ the only team that can spoil all
this fun.
</P>
<P>
   In front of President Clinton and more than 90,000 at the Rose
Bowl this afternoon, the Americans hope to repeat their 1996
Olympic gold medal-winning performance against the Chinese when the
two teams meet for the FIFA Women's World Cup championship at 12:50
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the third-place match, Brazil faces Norway at 10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel good about where we are as a team right now,'' said
Hamm, the world's all-time leading scorer. ``But we need to make
sure everything comes together all at once. We have to leave
everything on the field because there's nothing to play for after
(today).
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think our best soccer is ahead of us. As individuals,
we've seen some incredible performances, but collectively we know
we have to be at the top of our game to win this championship.
Anything less and it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been successful against China many times
in the past, holding an 11-5-5 edge in the series. But recent
history suggests that China could steal the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   China has been more dominant in this tournament, routing Norway,
the defending Women's World Cup champion, 5-0 in the semifinals.
And the Chinese have beaten the U.S. twice in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, meanwhile, struggled to a 3-2 victory over
Germany in the quarterfinals, and though the Americans beat Brazil
2-0 to reach the championship, they hold only a 24-21 advantage in
shots against their last two opponents. China has a 44-22 margin in
shots against its last two foes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, based on their recent games with us and the fact
they played so well against Norway, everyone has to look at them
and expect them to run away with this championship,'' said U.S.
coach Tony DiCicco. ``We have to be the underdog. They breezed
through group play, dissected the world champion and beat us two
out of three.''
</P>
<P>
   Another concern for DiCicco is the team's concentration. While
China has had little disruptions, the U.S. has captured the hearts
of America, resulting in an onslaught of media and fan support
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we kind of got caught up in the hoopla before the
quarterfinal (against Germany),'' said DiCicco. ``We talked about
how we should be turning into a laser with our concentration, not a
laser show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started to get like that, but I don't think it's a problem
anymore. This team has always said it's on a mission to win the
gold medal and world championship, and they're not going to let
distractions get in the way of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, they will have enough problems dealing with China's Sun
Wen, the leading scorer of the tournament with seven goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to give her the same amount of respect we gave to
Sissi (of Brazil),'' said defender Brandi Chastain. ``They both
have the potential to score any time they touch the ball. We have
to be extra conscious when she gets into the attacking third
because she's sneaky and tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. defender Kate Sobrero will have the dangerous task of
marking Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't scare me,'' said Sobrero. ``That's what I like.
That's what I'm best at, defending somebody. It's not the
play-making ability out of the back. I just boot it and get it away
from me. If anything, I'm excited to have this challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   More than just Sun, the key for the American team is patience.
China will likely dominate most of the possessions with quick
one-touch passes. The U.S. needs to close China's space and take
advantage of every opportunity offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the front to the back, all their players have good
quickness and speed,'' said Chastain. ``But then again, that
defines our game as well. They're proficient at the little
combination plays, but how quick they pull those off and how well
they run off the ball has a lot to do with how well we defend.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, however, it should all come down to how
well the U.S. plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``China's probably playing the best that we've seen them play in
a long time,'' said Hamm. ``But what's nice about this game is that
anything can happen. We need to go out and expect to get China's
best game, but if we go out and play our best game we're going to
be OK at the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
